EXODUS OF KOSOVAR ALBANIANS IS LARGEST IN 3 WEEKS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS for new top consisting of 9 grafs, reporting on the overnight
exodus. Picks up original material at: On Monday, many refugees(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036.) 
(jw) 
 By DAVID ROHDE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BLACE, Macedonia _ More than 10,000 ethnic Albanians fled from
Kosovo into Macedonia overnight in the largest one-day exodus in
three weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Refugees reported that Yugoslav paramilitaries, some wearing
patches identifying them as members of a gang known as Arkan's
Tigers, are moving from neighborhood to neighborhood and
systematically emptying Pristina, the Kosovo capital, and its
suburbs.
</P>
<P>
   Aid agencies crammed as many as 150 people in single tents and
requested emergency medical aid while struggling to deal with the
influx, which was continuing through the night.
</P>
<P>
   The rate of the expulsions raises the specter that Yugoslav
forces may be carrying out a final push to drive all ethnic
Albanians from Pristina, a city that once had a population of
250,000.
</P>
<P>
   The influx is also likely to raise tensions in Macedonia, which
struggles with its own ethnic splits and where the government
insists that more refugees must be evacuated to third countries,
like the Untied States. Monday night, officials of the U.N. high
commissioner for Refugees blocked an attempt by the Macedonian
government to bus 500 refugees directly from the border here to
Albania.
</P>
<P>
   One Pristina suburb, Vrjanjevac, was singled out for
particularly harsh treatment, refugees told aid workers. The suburb
is now full of refugees who fled from Drenica and Podujevo, Kosovo
Liberation Army strongholds, and they are being targeted for
retribution.
</P>
<P>
   Other neighborhoods are also experiencing terror. Armersh
Zhegrani, 23, said paramilitaries with Arkan's patches on their
uniforms separated him and seven male friends from their families.
He said two of them were killed when they failed to produce German
money that the paramilitaries demanded. ``If I didn't have 300
marks,'' he said, ``they would kill me too.''
</P>
<P>
   The paramilitary group is led by Zeljko Raznjatovic, known as
Arkan, who has been charged with war crimes in Bosnia and has been
accused of attacking ethnic Albanians in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Astrid van Genderenstort, a border monitor for the United
Nations, said a systematic pattern was emerging from refugees
arriving from Pristina, where expulsion of entire neighborhoods has
been reported for the last three to five days. ``It's door to door
again today,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, many refugees here, shivering in freezing rain,
struggled to choose their destination, under pressure to leave
their camps.
</P>
<P>
   One of them, Zelije Hajdari, 75, decided last night that she did
not care where she went as long as the half dozen grandchildren
with her made it to shelter.
</P>
<P>
   Isa Hasani, 54, said that after his group crossed the border, a
Macedonian policeman told them that if they did not get on the bus
they might be pushed back into Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   And Musa Tomgola, 59, said he was so disoriented and exhausted
that he did not know where he was going when he and his wife
climbed aboard.
</P>
<P>
   The three of them and 500 other Albanian refugees from Kosovo
were the focus of a surreal, midnight standoff Sunday when
officials from the office of the U.N. High Commissioner for
Refugees blocked an attempt by Macedonian officials to send them
directly on to Albania.
</P>
<P>
   Macedonian officials said the refugees had volunteered to go.
But some of the refugees themselves and officials of the refugee
agency said the refugees had been pressured into going or were
unaware of their intended destination. The standoff, which ended at
2:30 a.m. when the refugees were sent to a nearby camp, prompted
bitter recriminations Monday morning, and symbolized the rising
tensions here as the largest influx of refugees into Macedonia in
three weeks continued.
</P>
<P>
   For the third consecutive day, thousands of Albanians crossed
the border into Macedonia on Monday as Serbian forces continued a
new wave of mass expulsions from Pristina, Kosovo's provincial
capital, and towns across southeastern Kosovo. More than 20,000
refugees have arrived in Macedonia in the past three days, 6,000 of
them on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The new arrivals have increased the sense of uneasiness in a
small country of 2 million people where long-running tensions
between the Slav majority and Albanian minority have been
exacerbated by the arrival of more than 240,000 Albanian refugees
from Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Ethnic Macedonians, Slavs who generally sympathize with the
Serbian effort to hold onto the Kosovo province, fear that if the
influx continues, they may find themselves in the minority here.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, local Albanians _ up to one-third of the
country's population _ are angered by what human rights activists
say is the government's latest heavy-handed effort to contain the
number of Albanian refugees here by shipping some of them to
Albania.
</P>
<P>
   Arben Xhefari, a member of the country's fragile coalition
government and the leader of Macedonia's major Albanian party, said
Monday that he was still investigating what occurred Sunday night
and Monday morning, but he warned that all movements of refugees
from Macedonia must be voluntary. ``This is a principle of
international law,'' he said. ``You cannot deport the deportees
again.''
</P>
<P>
   The issue is expected to continue to arise. If the influx of
refugees continues at the same rate, refugee camps here will be
filled to capacity on Wednesday, refugee agency officials said.
</P>
<P>
   This morning, after the standoff ended, Boris Trajkovski,
Macedonia's deputy foreign minister, asked NATO countries to back
the plan to ease the pressure by offering refugees who arrived at
the border the opportunity to be sent to Albania immediately.
</P>
<P>
   But officials of the refugee agency and human rights activists
cited the procedures Sunday night as an example of how such an
approach was ripe for abuse. Benjamin Ward, a researcher for Human
Rights Watch, said that international law guaranteed refugees safe
haven and warned that frightened, exhausted refugees could be
easily pressured into allowing themselves to be sent on to Albania.
``Refugees who in some cases have been on the road for days and
weeks, who are physically exhausted and psychologically frail are
in no state to make a free choice about matters that could affect
their lives for months,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   For the refugees, the dispute causes further agony. Ms. Hajdari,
who spent 12 hours waiting on the border with her grandchildren,
said her family had spent three weeks living off bread and salt in
the woods. One of the young children with her showed signs of
severe hunger.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people were crying and screaming and it was cold,'' she
said of the scene at the border. ``I ran from the Serbs and I came
here and I didn't get anything. There has to be an open door for us
somewhere.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Western diplomats here, eager to keep Macedonia stable, played
down the dispute. American and European diplomats have generally
followed a course of trying to be supportive to the fragile
Macedonian government, arguing that attacking the Macedonians could
alienate them and further destabilize the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's kind of getting into the minutiae,'' said a
Western diplomat, referring to the dispute. ``The larger issue is
that the people are getting out of Kosovo and getting refuge.''
</P>
<P>
   Much of the mistrust of Macedonian intentions stems from an
incident in early April, shortly after the NATO bombing brought the
first wave of Kosovo Albanians over the border. On that occasion,
Macedonian police, again working in the dead of night, rousted
thousands of Albanians and shipped most to other camps across
Macedonia, and several hundred to Albania and Turkey.
</P>
<P>
   Officials of the U.N. refugee agency also accused Macedonian
police of pushing 1,000 refugees back into Kosovo under cover of
darkness on May 5, the height of the last large refugee influx.
Macedonian officials vehemently denied the charge.
</P>
<P>
   In Sunday night's incident, five buses arrived at the border
crossing here. Refugee agency officials said they initially assumed
the buses would carry some of the 3,000 to 4,000 refugees waiting
to be processed by Macedonian border guards to refugee camps in
Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
   But Macedonian police loaded the buses and told the refugee
agency the refugees had volunteered to go directly to Albania.
Because they had not been told of the plan in advance and had not
interviewed the refugees themselves, the refugee agency officials
used another vehicle to block the convoy. They also called
reporters and at one point even considered forming a human chain to
block the buses.
</P>
<P>
   Dennis McNamara, the refugee agency's special envoy to the
region, arrived at the scene and angrily accused the Macedonian
government of breaking repeated promises to keep the border open.
</P>
<P>
   After negotiations, Macedonian officials bused the 500 people to
the nearby Brazda refugee camp at 2:30 a.m. The remaining refugees,
numbering several thousand, were finally placed in a transit camp
just over the border here, said Astrid van Genderen Stort, a
refugee agency border monitor.
</P>
<P>
   Trajkovski, the Macedonian official, said all of the refugees
wanted to go to Albania and refugee agency officials agreed that
some, in fact did. He added that the plan to bus people to Albania
was first suggested by NATO countries when the overcrowded camps
were near the breaking point during the earlier influx.
</P>
<P>
   Refugee camps have been built in southern Albania to house
refugees from Macedonia, but only 260 refugees have voluntarily
gone there. Many stay in Macedonia because they have an opportunity
to move to Western Europe and the United States from here. In
Albania, they do not.
</P>
<P>
   Trajkovski complained that NATO countries were not keeping their
promise to evacuate more of the refugees and help Macedonia's
collapsing economy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
