<BODY>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK COACH HAS SUPPORT _ OF FANS
</HEADLINE>
 BKN-HAWKS-KNICKS-BOS (For use by New York Times News Service clients) 
By Bob Ryan 
c.1999 The Boston Globe 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ You know what they say. Well, maybe you don't know
what they say, so allow me to tell you.
</P>
<P>
   What they say in this business is ``Hang around long enough, and
you'll see everything.''
</P>
<P>
   That probably needs an amendment. How about, ``Hang around long
enough, and you will see something you've never seen before''?
We'll leave out the ``everything'' part.
</P>
<P>
   I've been hanging around the NBA 30 years, and Monday night I
encountered two firsts: 1. Before the game a team CEO apologized to
the media for lying; 2. A crowd at Madison Square Garden chanted
lovingly for a coach who eight days before had his immediate future
decided by a lucky bounce.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, yeah. In between, there was a basketball game. The Knicks
leveled the Atlanta Hawks by a 79-66 score. (Trust me when I say
the margin felt more like a hundred thirteen.) With that win the
Knicks completed their first four-game series sweep since 1969. And
with that win the Knicks will be meeting the Indiana Pacers for the
Eastern Conference championship in a series that will begin at 5:30
p.m. Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The game was a perfunctory exercise. The Hawks would have been
better advised to send a letter of concession. But the pre- and
postgame stuff was definitely intriguing.
</P>
<P>
   The evening began with Madison Square Garden president and
acting Knicks general manager Dave Checketts addressing the media
on the subject of published reports that before the regular season
was completed, he had interviewed Phil Jackson for the Knicks'
coaching job currently held by Jeff Van Gundy, a story Checketts
had denied when first asked about it. A day later he did
acknowledge, through a public relations spokesman, that contact
indeed had been made with Jackson through an intermediary. It was
further revealed that he also had talked with Turner Broadcasting
analyst Doc Rivers, as well as Dave Cowens, who needs no
introduction.
</P>
<P>
   Monday night he admitted half the truth. He admitted that he had
lied to both the media and, more importantly, to Van Gundy. He also
acknowledged that he had spoken to Jackson directly for two hours,
and not solely to an intermediary. So he lied twice.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did it to protect the best interests of all concerned,'' he
explained. ``It was obvious that there were people who knew about
the meeting and were looking to make us squirm. I know where those
leaks are, and we'll be careful in the future.''
</P>
<P>
   That doesn't sound very contrite to me. Yeah, I lied to you guys
and to my coach. But you gotta do what you gotta do. And, hey, this
wouldn't be a problem if someone hadn't leaked it out.
</P>
<P>
   It's not like anyone in the media should be offended. Club
officials and coaches lie or distort the truth or otherwise mislead
us and, by extension, you all the time. As Checketts said, it's in
their best interests. We're engaged in a constant cat-and-mouse
game with them. This is why no member of the media should ever get
too righteous about being lied to. It's seldom personal. It comes
with the territory.
</P>
<P>
   Part B came with about 3 1/2 minutes remaining. The Knicks were
in complete control, as they had been since the middle of the first
period. It was deep into garbage time. And then it started. ``JEFF
VAN GUNDY! JEFF VAN GUNDY!'' The capacity crowd of 19,763 was
reverently chanting the beleagured mentor's name. Many of them
arose for the proverbial Standing O.
</P>
<P>
   ``A New York first,'' observed a man who safely can be described
as a ``veteran New York scribe.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I've heard, `Joe Must Go!' and `Goodbye Allie,' but in all my
years I've never heard a crowd chanting for a New York coach.''
</P>
<P>
   No one understands the fickle nature of the crowd, or the
contextual relevance of all this, more than Van Gundy, son of a
basketball lifer who has become one himself. He wasn't going to get
carried away with this.
</P>
<P>
   `` `Jeff Van Gundy,' '' he repeated. ``I kept waiting for the
next word _ `sucks.' ''
</P>
<P>
   That said, he expressed his gratitude. ``That was nice of 'em,''
he said. ``I really appreciated it.''
</P>
<P>
   Just how much he appreciated the personal apology he got from
his boss for lying to him two days earlier is another matter. ``We
had a meeting,'' he acknowledged. ``What was said will stay between
us.''
</P>
<P>
   Pressed to explain just how it is that he has been able to
retain his sanity in the midst of some truly amazing public
scrutiny, Van Gundy took a deep breath. ``I don't know,'' he
sighed. ``If you got me behind a closed door, you'd probably say,
`This guy is a lunatic.' ''
</P>
<P>
   The truth is that there isn't a coach in the league with a
better sense of who he is _ or isn't _ than Jeff Van Gundy. He
regards himself as a very fortunate fellow just to have this job.
Think about it. In the next series he will be going up against a
certified basketball legend. He is a former Division 3 point guard
who started out coaching high school and who has done every dirty
little task a coach has to do. Every day he spends at this job is a
bonus. He always feels he's on borrowed time. In that sense, Dave
Checketts can't hurt him.
</P>
<P>
   His job security? ``It's a dead issue, a non-issue,'' he
insisted.
</P>
<P>
   ``I learned a long time ago about team sports that the most
important thing is to keep the focus on the team and nothing
else,'' he explained. ``So over the next five days the only thing
I'm worried about is preparing this team to play Indiana. It's not
about me. It's about the team. I'm going to do my best to get this
team ready.''
</P>
<P>
   I believe him. What really matters is that 12 guys wearing
Knicks uniforms believe him, too.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
