<SLUG> BC-HKN-COYOTES-REAX-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLAYERS SURPRISED, BUT SAY IT'S A CUTTHROAT JOB 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By KENT SOMERS  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Keith Tkachuk didn't want to talk about possible
candidates for the Phoenix Coyotes vacant head coaching job Monday,
or the qualities he would like to see in his new boss.
</P>
<P>
   Tkachuk liked the old boss, Jim Schoenfeld, just fine, and he
wanted to pay homage to him first.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, I just want to talk about Shoney,'' Tkachuk said
Monday from his home in the Boston area. ``Today is Shoney's day.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a day Schoenfeld could have done without, since he was
fired after two seasons with the Coyotes.
</P>
<P>
   The move surprised Tkachuk, the Coyotes' captain, who was
informed of the decision by a phone call Monday morning from
General Manager Bobby Smith.
</P>
<P>
   ``It caught me by surprise,'' Tkachuk said, ``especially when,
as a team, you made a lot of strides.''
</P>
<P>
   But people will remember this season for the step the Coyotes
didn't take. They lost in the first round of the playoffs for the
eighth straight time, including each of Schoenfeld's two seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Schoenfeld had at least two things working in his favor: a
regular season in which the team finished with 90 points, the
second highest total in franchise history, and a locker room full
of players who wanted him back.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's unfortunate he had to be the fall guy for our team not
being successful,'' said Tkachuk. ``You ask any player in that
dressing room, and they'll say Shoney is a great and approachable
guy.
</P>
<P>
   ``He helped me tremendously in becoming a better person on and
off the ice. If we weren't going well, in the locker room he was
hard on me, which helped me a lot. He would ask for your opinion .
. . listen to you and talk to you about everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Teppo Numminen, a defenseman, also was surprised by the move.
``I thought Shoney would be our coach next year,'' he said. ``But
that's not the way Bobby (Smith) thought. He wanted to change, and
that's the way it is. Bobby's in charge.''
</P>
<P>
   Tkachuk said Schoenfeld's firing was the nature of hockey, where
there is little job security.
</P>
<P>
   ``You play to be traded and are hired to be fired sometimes,''
Tkachuk said.
</P>
<P>
   Center Jeremy Roenick echoed Numminen.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a cutthroat job,'' he said. ``Players lose their jobs,
coaches lose their jobs, and GMs lose their jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of guys got along with Shoney and liked him, but
unfortunately whether you like somebody or not doesn't win hockey
games. (Schoenfeld) can take solace in the fact that he worked his
(expletive) off and did what he had to do for the Phoenix
Coyotes.''
</P>
<P>
   The Coyotes went 35-35-12 in 1997-98, Schoenfeld's first season,
but lost in the first round to Detroit, which went on to win the
Stanley Cup. This season, the Coyotes went 39-31-12 and lost in
seven games to St. Louis in the first round.
</P>
<P>
   Like Tkachuk, Roenick thought the Coyotes improved this season.
But success is coming in increments that are too small, Roenick
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we can take steps as slowly as we're taking
them,'' he said. ``We have to jump start it and move quicker.''
</P>
<P>
   Roenick said he would like to see the team hire an
offensive-minded coach with a creative mind.
</P>
<P>
   Why?
</P>
<P>
   ``Because I'm an offensive-minded guy,'' he said, ``and we need
it. Let the goaltenders do their jobs. Let the defensemen do their
jobs and the forwards do their jobs.''
</P>
<P>
   The Coyotes' new coach will be the team's third since moving to
Phoenix in 1996. But coming off another first-round loss, it's not
like Schoenfeld's firing means a dynasty is being torn apart.
</P>
<P>
   ``Losing in the first round put a damper on things,'' Roenick
said. ``Yeah, we're starting over with a new coach and a new
system. But we're professionals, and we should be able to grasp it
pretty quickly.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
