<HEADLINE>
HOLMES TO GET INJECTION FOR BACK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DON KETCHUM  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX -Once  &UR; Darren Holmes' back discomfort has been taken
care of, he'll be back in the bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   There is a strong likelihood that Holmes will receive an
epidural injection today to alleviate the pain in his lower back
that has been bothering him for about two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Diamondbacks trainer  &UR; Paul Lessard refers to it as a ``nerve
impingement.''
</P>
<P>
   Holmes had a similar problem with the New York Yankees last
season and had an epidural, but he said the pain is not nearly what
it was then.
</P>
<P>
   ``That time, I couldn't even pitch. At least now, I can throw.''
</P>
<P>
   After today, Holmes probably won't be ready to pitch until
Sunday at the earliest. By then, the club will be on another trip
that will take it to New York and Montreal. &QL; 
Honoring victims &QL; 
While the Diamondbacks were in Denver over the weekend for their
series with the Colorado Rockies, Holmes met with a few of the
students who were shot at Columbine High School on April 20. He
pitched for the Rockies for five seasons and lived near Littleton,
site of the shootings. Manager  &UR; Buck &UR; Showalter met with the
school's principal before Sunday's game.
</P>
<P>
   Holmes also gathered up a bunch of Diamondbacks caps and had his
teammates sign them.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guys on our club were concerned about them and praying for
them,'' he said. ``I thought it would be a nice gesture to show the
kids and that community that our team and the people of Arizona
have them in our thoughts.'' &QL; 
Restless soul &QL; 
Don't give right-hander  &UR; Todd Stottlemyre any coffee _ he already
is bouncing off the walls as he begins his shoulder rehabilitation.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not the most patient patient,'' Lessard said. ``The thing
we have to be careful about is that when he starts feeling good,
he's going to want to do more, like pick up a ball and throw it.''
</P>
<P>
   Stottlemyre probably won't be able to do that for about four
weeks. On Sunday, Lessard said he began range-of-motion exercises,
which gave Stottlemyre more motivation. &QL; 
Miller on a roll &QL; 
Catcher  &UR; Damian Miller, who has been battling soreness and
stiffness in his left Achilles', likely will be back in the lineup
tonight.
</P>
<P>
   He is having his best season in the majors, hitting .343 with
four homers, 20 RBIs and nine doubles.
</P>
<P>
   ``Getting to play at least four or five times a week lends
itself to consistency,'' said Miller, who usually alternates with
 &UR; Kelly Stinnett. ``You get into a groove and you fight to get to
the bat rack.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller says the Achilles' affects him more when he runs. One way
to alleviate that would be to hit the ball out of the park so he
could jog around the bases.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish it was that easy,'' Miller said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
