<SLUG> BC-BKN-MAGIC-SKILES-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ORLANDO MAY EYE SKILES  
 SUNS ASSISTANT IS CANDIDATE TO SUC CEED DALY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB YOUNG  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Almost immediately after Orlando Coach Chuck Daly
announced his retirement Monday, Suns assistant Scott Skiles
emerged as a leading candidate for the plum job that Daly leaves
vacant.
</P>
<P>
   Skiles, 35, was one of the most popular players in the Orlando
franchise's history, playing there from 1989-94. He is the club's
all-time assists leader and set an NBA record in 1990, handing out
30 assists in a game against Denver.
</P>
<P>
   NBA sources said that the Magic, anticipating that Daly might
step down, had made preliminary contact with Skiles and other
potential candidates to determine whether they have interest in the
job.
</P>
<P>
   Skiles, who still owns a home in Orlando, confirmed that he has
interest in the position but would not comment on whether he
expects to be interviewed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really don't want to say anything about it right now,''
Skiles said Monday by telephone from Indiana. ``We'll just have to
wait and see what happens.''
</P>
<P>
   Agent Keith Glass, who represented Skiles as a player and now as
a coach, said the Magic organization has kept close tabs on its
former point guard, but the club hasn't officially requested an
interview.
</P>
<P>
   ``I talk to the Magic all the time about various things, and
Scott's name always comes up in those conversations,'' Glass said.
``But there hasn't been anything official from them at this point.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, when the time is right, we'd love to talk to them
about it. The whole league is aware that he's going to be a head
coach at some point, and probably a terrific one with time. And
obviously, his name is going to come up in Orlando.
</P>
<P>
   ``Including Shaq (O'Neal) and Penny (Hardaway), I'm not sure
there has ever been a more popular player with the fans in Orlando
than Scott.''
</P>
<P>
   Skiles has spent the past two seasons as an assistant to Suns
Coach Danny Ainge and was regarded as a potential head coach even
before joining the Suns staff.
</P>
<P>
   His star began to rise when Skiles took over the Greek
professional club PAOK, a perennial European power that was
foundering, at midseason in 1997. Skiles led PAOK into the European
Cup playoffs, then turned down a lucrative contract from that club
to join the Suns.
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix General Manager Bryan Colangelo said Monday that he had
not been contacted by the Magic.
</P>
<P>
   Skiles emerged as a candidate for several NBA head coaching
positions last summer but only agreed to one formal interview _
with the Chicago Bulls. Chicago hired Tim Floyd, who had long been
rumored as the replacement for Phil Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   As a player, Skiles once teamed with Orlando stars Hardaway and
O'Neal. Skiles was traded to the Washington Bullets (now the
Wizards) because the Magic wanted to free salary-cap space to sign
forward Horace Grant and management was convinced Hardaway would
become the team's point guard.
</P>
<P>
   Hardaway started this season as the club's point guard but made
it known throughout the season that he prefers to play off the
ball. Eventually, Darrell Armstrong took over at point guard and
the Magic finished as the No. 3 seed in the Eastern Conference.
</P>
<P>
   But following a first-round elimination by the Philadelphia
76ers, speculation was that Daly, 68, might leave. Hardaway's
future also is up in the air. He has an early-termination clause in
his contract and is seeking a new seven-year, $85 million contract
from the Magic.
</P>
<P>
   Other potential candidates for the Orlando job include Turner
Sports broadcaster Doc Rivers, former Charlotte Coach Dave Cowens
and Orlando's executive vice president, Julius Erving. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
