<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBC-ASU-NCAA-PLAYOFF-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEVILS SNUBBED BY NCAA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JAVIER Morales  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, Ariz. - Arizona State baseball Coach Pat Murphy may have
wanted to scream, he may have wanted to cry.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he tried to joke about something he does not find at
all funny: another snub by the NCAA selection committee _ the third
in five years for an ASU bubble team and the fifth in 10 years for
Murphy as a coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it's best for Arizona State that I'm not around, maybe I
should not sign my new deal (with the school),'' Murphy said.
``Maybe they (the NCAA) are trying to run me out of college
baseball. I don't know.
</P>
<P>
   ``If that's their goal, if that's what is best for Arizona
State, then let's do it. I can find another job. I would probably
make a good policeman.''
</P>
<P>
   More than anything, Murphy would like to police the NCAA
selection committee, which is a nine-member panel comprised of
coaches and athletic directors.
</P>
<P>
   Two of his Notre Dame teams, each with at least 45 victories,
were not selected.
</P>
<P>
   The Sun Devils, last year's national runner-up and ranked in the
Top 10 by ``Baseball America'' for most of the season, did not make
this year's field, even though it was expanded to 64 teams. They
finished 39-21 overall.
</P>
<P>
   ASU also was not selected in 1995 (34-21 record) and 1996
(35-21). That's three snubs in the past five years for the Sun
Devils under Murphy after they made a tournament trip routine under
the late Jim Brock.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to look at who else has been left out five of the
last 10 years,'' Murphy said.
</P>
<P>
   Finishing tied for fifth in the Pac-10 and a questionable
non-conference schedule were deciding factors in ASU's exclusion,
according to selection committee chairman Dick Rockwell.
</P>
<P>
   ``ASU was a .500 team (in the Pac-10), and we didn't want to go
that deep into the conference,'' Rockwell said. ``We felt that four
teams were a fair amount from the Pac-10.''
</P>
<P>
   Stanford, USC, Arizona and UCLA made the field. The Bruins
received a bid despite having a 30-29 overall record. But they did
sweep three games from ASU and tied for third in the conference
with Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   ASU tied with Washington at 12-12 record in the conference.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona defeated ASU, 6-2, in the last game of the season,
likely sealing the fate for both teams.
</P>
<P>
   ASU's Andrew Beinbrink, who attended a somber meeting with
teammates at a Tempe sports bar to watch the selection show,
believes the telling blow was the grand slam by Arizona's Keoni
DeRenne in the eighth inning of the final game of a three-game
series last week.
</P>
<P>
   UA won two out of three games.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Murphy) told us we had to win two out of three in that series
to have a good shot,'' Beinbrink said. ``Anytime you leave it up to
the committee, you're rolling the dice.''
</P>
<P>
   Rockwell said UCLA had been a tough call.
</P>
<P>
   ``The committee was mixed on UCLA; it took an hour and a half to
decide,'' Rockwell said. ``We came to the determination that UCLA
played everybody. They played 21 teams in the top 50.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sun Devils had a 1-9 record against the top 50 teams in the
NCAA's Ratings Percentage Index, according to Rockwell. They were
swept by Florida State and Stanford. They lost a game at Cal
State-Fullertion, and they lost two of three to USC.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm being honest with you _ ASU was down a few more spots than
No. 65 (in the ratings),` Rockwell said. ``You have to go much
deeper than 65.''
</P>
<P>
   Aside from Florida State and Cal State-Fullerton, ASU's
non-conference schedule included Utah, Hawaii-Hilo, Howard, New
Mexico, Brigham Young, Oklahoma, Boston College, Grand Canyon and
Southern Utah.
</P>
<P>
   None qualified for the NCAA Tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Beinbrink said ASU's appearance in the championship game last
year should have carried some weight.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've showed that when it comes to postseason play, we play
our best baseball,'' he said. ``That shows the strength of the
program.''
</P>
<P>
   But Rockwell said, ``The selection is a year-to-year process. We
don't look at history.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-25-99 0123EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
