A9902 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-COYOTES-SUCCESSOR     05-25 0668
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-COYOTES-SUCCESSOR-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COYOTES MIGHT NOT HAVE FAR TO LOOK FOR A RE PLACEMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB MCMANAMAN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - So where do the Coyotes turn now in their search for a
new head coach?
</P>
<P>
   According to General Manager Bobby Smith, who fired Coach Jim
Schoenfeld on Monday, he probably won't look beyond a short list of
more than four to six candidates. Perhaps even fewer.
</P>
<P>
   And one of them is Coyotes assistant coach John Tortorella,
whose contract expires June 30, but who was named a ``serious
candidate'' for the job by Smith on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Definitely. I've known John for two years now, and yeah, he
will get a chance to get interviewed for the job,'' Smith said. ``.
. . John will be a serious candidate and I'll gauge his interest in
remaining with the team.''
</P>
<P>
   Tortorella, 41, is seen as a hot coaching prospect in the NHL,
with other potential job opportunities reportedly in such cities as
New York, Los Angeles, Atlanta and Vancouver.
</P>
<P>
   But he is not alone on the list of potential prospects being
considered by Smith, who just completed his third season in an NHL
front office.
</P>
<P>
   A handful of other well-known names immediately surfaced after
Schoenfeld's dismissal, among them, former NHL head coaches Mike
Keenan, Ted Nolan and Larry Robinson.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd have a great deal of interest in the job, but that's
certainly up to Bobby,'' said Keenan, who has taken three teams to
the Stanley Cup Finals _ the Philadelphia Flyers, the Chicago
Blackhawks and the New York Rangers, whom he helped guide to the
championship in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   ``He interviewed me before the job went to Jimmy . . . but I'm
familiar with some of the very important people on that hockey
club. I've worked with a few of them successfully in the past, and
for that reason, I'm ``definitely'' interested in them, their
ability and the entire team. I'd certainly like another opportunity
to coach in the NHL.''
</P>
<P>
   Keenan, fired at the All-Star break as head coach of the
Vancouver Canucks, has previously coached the Coyotes' Rick Tocchet
in Philadelphia and Jeremy Roenick in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Nolan won NHL Coach of the Year honors two seasons ago after
leading the Buffalo Sabres to a 40-30-12 record, but he was
relieved of his duties that summer in a management shake-up. He
recently interviewed with the Los Angeles Kings, however, about the
vacant head coaching position there after Robinson was fired last
month.
</P>
<P>
   Smith, a teammate of Robinson's in Montreal for several seasons,
initially said Monday that both Keenan and Nolan were not
considered serious candidates to replace Schoenfeld. However,
during a radio interview later in the day on KGME-AM (550) Smith
said, ``I haven't ruled out anybody or any type of person.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith, a 15-year NHL player who won the Calder Trophy as the
NHL's Rookie of the Year in 1979 with Minnesota, did rule out
himself as a possible replacement. ``Absolutely not,'' he said
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Smith has talked at least two to three times in the past few
weeks with Robinson, though, who had coached the Kings since
1995-96. Smith would not comment on those conversations.
</P>
<P>
   Other possible candidates include Detroit Red Wings assistants
Barry Smith and Dave Lewis. Smith was among the finalists for the
job before Schoenfeld was hired. Another possibility, though a long
shot, might be veteran NHL Coach Jacques Demers. Though currently
the GM/Coach of the Tampa Bay Lightning, word is circulating that
new ownership will replace him in both capacities. Demers, however,
has three years remaining on a deal that reportedly will pay him
$800,000 annually.
</P>
<P>
   There also was some speculation late Monday that Detroit Coach
Scotty Bowman, 65, the NHL's all-time winningest head coach, might
be interested in a change of scenery after six seasons with the Red
Wings. Bowman, however, is expected to retire this summer and it is
doubtful he would consider a short-term move to Phoenix. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
