<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-25 01:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9904 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-COYOTES-BICKLEY-A     05-25 0713
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-COYOTES-BICKLEY-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TKACHUK ALLIANCE WAS FATAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN BICKLEY  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - There was the power play that Jim Schoenfeld couldn't
fix. And the one he couldn't win.
</P>
<P>
   Take a guess which one cost him his job.
</P>
<P>
   There was the coach who catered to Keith Tkachuk and the 1-0
victory. And the owner who wants the emphasis on sizzle, scoring
and Jeremy Roenick.
</P>
<P>
   Take a guess who prevailed.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Coyotes General Manager Bobby Smith announced the
firing of his second head coach in three years. He wore a sense of
resignation, as if this were an unforeseen consequence. And he
claimed it was his call all along, a decision he didn't reach until
a disastrous meeting with Schoenfeld last week.
</P>
<P>
   In their little chat, Smith said he wanted to change the style
of Coyotes' hockey. He insisted on handing all the power-play
authority to another coach. He coyly pierced Schoenfeld's bloated
sense of stubbornness and pride, and in doing so, forced him out
the door.
</P>
<P>
   Soon, Schoenfeld saw the torpedo coming, the one he had feared
all along.
</P>
<P>
   The one fired by Richard Burke.
</P>
<P>
   Really, is this any surprise?
</P>
<P>
   It is striking how Smith still feigns bewilderment over
Schoenfeld's alleged paranoia. How all the rumors over shaky job
status and postseason edicts lived only in Schoenfeld's head. Look,
the former coach may not have been a great coach, but Schoenfeld is
a very bright man. He knew all along whom he was fighting. Knew all
along he was not the owner's guy.
</P>
<P>
   But from the moment Schoenfeld arrived in the Valley, he aligned
himself with Tkachuk. He made Roenick compromise his free-wheeling
style of play. He put all his money on one horse, and when that
horse failed to reach the second round of the playoffs, it was
over.
</P>
<P>
   Schoenfeld gambled, and Schoen feld lost.
</P>
<P>
   ``A new coach is in order if we are to improve,'' Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   There is no doubt that Tkachuk matured greatly under
Schoenfeld's wing, but two years later, the Coyotes remain
strangely disjointed. Not exactly the closest group in the NHL, and
for all the good things he accomplished, this is Schoenfeld's
greatest error. By catering to one man, he lost the rest of the
dressing room very early in his tenure. And by sitting on Roenick _
who just happens to be Burke's neighbor _ he punched his own ticket
to the television booth.
</P>
<P>
   So they're starting over, and unless Scotty Bowman suddenly
wants to coach in Arizona, there is not an abundance of big-name
coaches looking for work. And remember, the future of the Coyotes
still rests on popular opinion.
</P>
<P>
   A great option would be Mike Keenan, who is definitely
interested and vowing to play nice. He has coached Roenick and Rick
Tocchet, and both players remained fiercely loyal to the Keenan
Way. He is a brilliant bench coach. And with another stadium vote
upcoming, Keenan would be a lightning rod for interest.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm biased, but I love the guy,'' Tocchet said. ``I really
do.''
</P>
<P>
   Problem is there are too many ex-coaches on payroll, and Keenan
wouldn't come cheap. Problem is, Smith wants no part of Keenan and
officially shot him off the wish list on Tuesday. Problem is, the
successor is starting to smell preordained, a job greased for
assistant coach John Tortorella.
</P>
<P>
   ``He can be one of the best hockey minds around,'' Roenick said.
``He's got the X's and O's, the personality, the ability to kick
someone in the (expletive). He was the brains behind our
operation.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever happens, the era of Jim Schoenfeld ends with a thud.
</P>
<P>
   There was the night when he was so close, when ``his guy''
almost saved the future. The night when Tkachuk's series-clinching
goal was stopped just before crossing the goal line.
</P>
<P>
   And there was the night when the other guy became a local hero,
when Roenick insisted on playing with a shattered jaw. A night when
Schoenfeld's future was sealed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's time now for a team that's more creative, more daring,''
Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   With more Roenick and less Tkachuk. With the emphasis on one
team, not one man.
</P>
<P>
   A team the owner wants and a team the ex-coach could never
produce. &QL; 
Dan Bickley can be reached at (602) 444-8253 or at
dan.bickley(at)pni.com. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
