r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-COYOTES-SCHOENFEL     05-25 0825
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-COYOTES-SCHOENFELD-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LACK OF SCORING COSTS SCHOENFELD HIS JOB 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB MCMANAMAN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Jim Schoenfeld was half right.
</P>
<P>
   After predicting the Coyotes would win Game 7 of their playoff
series against the St. Louis Blues, and then tying the outcome to
his future as the team's head coach, Schoenfeld was fired on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The end came three weeks after the franchise suffered a
first-round exit for the eighth time in its past eight trips to the
postseason.
</P>
<P>
   Citing a clash of opinions and Schoenfeld's refusal to take a
proactive stance on suggested changes involving the coaching staff
and its style, General Manager Bobby Smith terminated the veteran
coach with one year left on his contract.
</P>
<P>
   Smith said he had been all but set to announce Schoenfeld would
be returning for a third season behind the bench. But recent
discussions with the coach about the direction the team was
heading, specifically after a lengthy meeting on Thursday, changed
everything.
</P>
<P>
   According to Smith, it hinged on Schoenfeld's apparent refusal
to alter his coaching style and philosophies, something Smith told
``The Republic'' a little more than a week ago he didn't foresee
would be any problem at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt comfortable that he could,'' said Smith, who wants to
see a more creative and daring approach on offense. ``We talked at
length about changing the cast of characters around Jim and
bringing in expertise (assistant coaching) on the power play and
the creative part of our game, and that, in a large part, was the
reason why we're not on the same page and the reason for the
disagreements we've had.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had come to the decision within the past 20 days that Jim
Schoenfeld would be the coach next year. I told him, `Let's talk
about it. Let's talk about the changes in your style, the coaching
staff and your own approach that will allow us to be successful.'
But really, we couldn't overcome that and here is where we are
today.''
</P>
<P>
   Schoenfeld, who at one point this past season was the leading
candidate to win the Jack Adams Award as the NHL's Coach of the
Year, becomes the team's third head coach to be fired since the
club's final season as the Winnipeg Jets in 1995-96.
</P>
<P>
   Schoenfeld, 45, who previously coached the Buffalo Sabres, New
Jersey Devils and Washington Capitals, compiled a 74-66-24 record
in two seasons with Phoenix. This past season, he guided the
Coyotes to a 90-point season (39-31-12), the club's second-best
regular-season finish in its 20-year history. The club also set
records for fewest goals-against (197), going 10-0-1 in the month
of November, and holding the opposition to two or fewer goals for
17 straight games, the NHL's third-longest streak since 1943-44.
</P>
<P>
   Schoenfeld, who has refused repeated interview requests by
``The'' ``Republic'' since the season ended, was informed of the
decision Monday morning by Smith. Schoenfeld couldn't be reached
for comment again on Monday, but he issued the following statement
through the team:
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a situation where three people _ myself, Bobby
Smith and (Owner) Richard Burke _ are looking at the forward
direction of the hockey club and seeing it in a different way. I am
grateful to Bobby Smith for giving me the responsibility of
coaching the team and grateful for the tremendous support I
received from the entire Coyotes staff.''
</P>
<P>
   He then added a note of praise to his players, most of whom
lobbied for his return, saying, ``A special thanks to my players
who played with all the heart and determination a coach could ask
for. Good luck and keep growing.''
</P>
<P>
   Coyotes captain Keith Tkachuk said Smith called him Monday
morning to tell him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was surprised; he caught me off guard,'' Tkachuk said.
``Usually when coaches get fired, there are rumors leading up to
it. Shoney is a great person and a great coach so I was upset when
I found out.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the year we really made great steps to become a better
hockey team. I'm going to miss him tremendously.''
</P>
<P>
   The Coyotes must pay Schoenfeld's $400,000 salary for next year,
unless he finds an NHL head coaching job elsewhere. If he takes an
assistant coaching position, a settlement would have to be
negotiated.
</P>
<P>
   Coyotes assistant John Tortorella, who spent six seasons as an
assistant coach with the Sabres and coached their farm club, the
Rochester Americans, to the American Hockey League championship in
'96, is a ``serious candidate'' for the job, Smith said. His
contract expires on June 30, but he will be granted an interview
for the job within the next two weeks, sources said.
</P>
<P>
   Tortorella also has not returned repeated messages.
</P>
<P>
   Assistant coach Gordie Roberts, who also doubles as the club's
director of player development, will be assigned to the latter role
exclusively and his contract, which also was set to expire, will be
extended. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
