<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-25 01:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9907 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  cp62 &LR;  &UR; cs58 &LR;      05-25 0850
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;  
 FASSERO'S STRUGGLES CONTINUE AS TWINS TEE OFF 
</HEADLINE>
 cp62  cs58 
 &HT;    Fassero flounders
 &HT;    Left-hander surrenders 8 runs in 21/3 innings (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TYLER KEPNER  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINNEAPOLIS _ Stan Williams stood above the spray-painted home
plate down the right-field foul line at the Metrodome Monday, and
was impressed with what he saw go by. Jeff Fassero's fastball was
live, his slider was breaking right and his splitter was just as it
should be.
</P>
<P>
   When the Mariners pitching coach came back to the dugout, he
told manager Lou Piniella that Fassero, who had dominated the
Minnesota Twins last week, was looking good.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was expecting a good game out of him, I really was,''
Piniella said. ``He threw eight shutout innings last week against
the Twins and made it look relatively easy. Today, it was a totally
different result. I don't have an explanation for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Fassero gave up eight runs in 21/3 innings Monday night as the
M's fell, 10-5, before 12,101 fans. He surrendered two home runs,
pushing his major league-leading total to 17, and nine hits, tying
him with Greg Maddux for the major league lead at 88.
</P>
<P>
   The left-hander's record dropped to 2-6.
</P>
<P>
   ``They hit it up the middle,'' Fassero said. ``If I played with
five infielders up the middle, I'd probably be better off. That's
where basically all their hits went, except for the two home runs
and the one down the line.''
</P>
<P>
   Five Minnesota singles were hit up the middle, and one went to
right-center. Torii Hunter hit a double down the right-field line,
and Ron Coomer and Chad Allen powered homers to left.
</P>
<P>
   Fassero had success last week by pitching inside, and tried the
same approach this time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went inside early and wasn't getting strikes in there,''
Fassero said. ``So we went away from that a little bit, and they
went up the middle. Give them credit. It's a game of adjustments.
(Catcher) Dan (Wilson) and I tried to make some, and it just didn't
work out the right way. You've got to give them credit for what
they did.''
</P>
<P>
   What they did, Hunter said, was make a conscious effort to not
try and pull Fassero's splitter.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were trying to go up the middle,'' said the Twins' center
fielder. ``With his splitter, we knew we had to stay on that pitch,
go up the middle or the other way. We tried to do that up there,
but he kind of dominated us.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners scored twice in the first inning off Dan Perkins,
whom they scored seven runs last week. Ken Griffey Jr. extended his
career-best hitting streak to 13 games with a double that brought
in Brian Hunter, and Edgar Martinez scored Alex Rodriguez with a
ground out.
</P>
<P>
   But Minnesota took the lead in its half of the inning, on a
single _ up the middle _ by former Mariner Brent Gates and a
two-run homer by Coomer. Three singles and a fly ball produced two
runs in the second, and Allen's three-run homer knocked Fassero out
in the third.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a stupid pitch to Coomer,'' Fassero said. ``Basically,
they were both stupid pitches. With Coomer, I got it in, just not
in deep enough. He was cheating there, and a sinker away or
something off-speed might have gotten a ground ball. Allen, we made
look stupid on a slider prior to the one he hit. I looked at the
home run (on tape), and I couldn't have put it in a better
location. It was just that he was looking for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Fassero said he's taking some comfort in knowing he's not the
only pitcher around baseball giving up home runs. What bothers him
most, he said, is that so many of the homers have come with men on
base. Of the last seven homers Fassero has allowed, only one has
been solo, and 17 runners have scored.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of them have been in situations where I'm behind in the
count, not wanting to walk a guy,'' he said. ``The sad thing about
what's happened is that middle infielders, small guys, are hitting
balls out of the park. It's not just me, it's all over the league.
I'm sure I'm leading the league, but there are quite a few guys
who've given up 13, 14, 10. Home runs are up all over the league.
The only thing you've got to do is make sure nobody's on base.
Unfortunately, that hasn't been the case.''
</P>
<P>
   Perkins won his first major league game, despite allowing a
homer in the third to former Westminster Christian (Miami) High
School teammate, Rodriguez. The rookie allowed three runs on seven
hits in 62/3 innings, and four relievers finished off the M's.
</P>
<P>
   Former Mariner Bob Wells started the ninth with two quick outs
before Rodriguez singled, his fourth time on base in five at-bats.
Griffey came up next, fell behind 0-and-2 and fouled off three
pitches. Wells threw two balls, then Griffey rocketed his 17th
homer over the high wall in right field.
</P>
<P>
   ``He just said, `Here, hit it,''' Griffey said of Wells.
</P>
<P>
   As for the hitting streak, in which he's hitting .423
(22-for-52) with six homers and 15 runs batted in, Griffey said it
doesn't matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't worry about it,'' he said. ``We lost. That's all I
really worry about.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-25-99 0133EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990525.0015 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-25 01:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9908 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NFL-LADN-(SLANG)     05-25 0807
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NFL-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NFL SUITOR BROAD WAIVES EXCLUSIVITY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(EDITORS: Today in last graf refers to Tuesday.)  
 
  
BY STEVE DILBECK 
c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ If Michael Ovitz was going for the pizazz and Eli
Broad the pragmatic in their competing proposals before the NFL
expansion committee on Monday night, Broad at least opened with a
surprise:
</P>
<P>
   His group waived the two-year exclusivity agreement Ed Roski Jr.
had obtained from the Los Angeles Coliseum Commission for
renovating the stadium and owning a Coliseum team.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to get this on the merit or we're not going to get
it,'' Broad said. ``We think we have the merit, we think we have
the best ownership group, the right political support, the right
work up to date. We said let the chips fall where they may, and we
think they ought to fall in our direction.''
</P>
<P>
   Monday marked the first time the expansion committee got a look
at Ovitz's new plans for rebuilding the Coliseum, and they came
away impressed with his proposals for the stadium and parking.
</P>
<P>
   Ovitz, who had previously wowed the team owners with his flashy
plans for a hacienda-style stadium in Carson, proposed a
68,000-seat design that is expandable to 92,000 for Super Bowls. It
includes seven parking structures that would house 27,000 spaces in
a parklike setting.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was very impressive,'' said Jerry Richardson, the Carolina
owner and head of the NFL expansion committee. ``It was
extraordinary. It's a park, the design, the architectural elements
_ it's extraordinary.''
</P>
<P>
   Ovitz, however, has had only six weeks to switch his plans from
Carson after owners selected the Coliseum as the Los Angeles
stadium site and has not had time to meet with the various agencies
that control Exposition Park for input.
</P>
<P>
   Broad stressed his group has put in more than two years on the
Coliseum site, had relationships with all the area agencies and was
the only one with a practical plan.
</P>
<P>
   Broad said he continually told owners they needed to proceed
with ``due diligence'' and not be taken in by glitz.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said I don't want to be negative, but I hope you choose a
plan that is not only dazzling, but is also feasible and will get
built,'' Broad said. ``We believe our plan is the only one you're
going to see this evening that's not only spectacular but has the
necessary approvals and will actually get built.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said what I don't want to see happen is three months from
now or six months from now, the league gets frustrated by
everything that was promised that can't happen, and you take the
whole operation to Houston or another site.
</P>
<P>
   ``They knew this was not flimflam, this was the real thing and
an honest presentation.''
</P>
<P>
   The committee did not endorse either plan Monday night, but
Richardson said it is expected to meet once or twice more before
the three-day owners meetings conclude.
</P>
<P>
   Both groups said they would give their plans to the NFL and city
of Los Angeles, regardless of whether they were selected to own the
league's 32nd franchise.
</P>
<P>
   ``That both parties addressed the parking in a substantial way,
both parties were willing to share their plans with the other if
the other was selected, which was extraordinary in my judgment, and
the exclusivity issue has been withdrawn, that's all significant,''
Richardson said.
</P>
<P>
   Broad implied Ovitz's plan was not workable, particularly the
seven parking structures, and continually stressed that it was his
group that had the necessary relationships with the involved
political groups.
</P>
<P>
   But Richardson said because of the short time Ovitz had to put
his plan together, it was not reasonable to expect he would be able
to get input from all involved.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Ovitz group has only developed this concept in the last
several weeks,'' Richardson said. ``The assumption is, they will be
given a fair hearing to whatever the ruling bodies are,
particularly if it enhances that park, that section of Los Angeles
in a significant way. And if it is done, I think it would be
extraordinary.''
</P>
<P>
   Ovitz, the former superagent with deep Hollywood connections,
believed his proposal had impressed the owners.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were asked to make a plan that included 25,000 parking
spaces and to make the Coliseum an area that would have great
potential for a positive fan experience,'' Ovitz said. ``We
delivered a plan that has in excess of 27,000 parking spaces, that
has a 60-acre park that stays there to be used by the inner city
365 days a year, less than nine football games.''
</P>
<P>
   Ovitz, however, stressed he would need public support for the
estimated $225 million needed for parking.
</P>
<P>
   Roski returned from a vacation in Nepal on Monday and did not
attend the meetings, which were originally scheduled to start
today.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-25-99 0138EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
