<HEADER>
A9912 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOC-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI     05-25 0874
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOMEN'S WORLD CUP ASPIRES FOR ATTENTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA VECSEY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   When the NBA lockout was resolved and the league's schedule
makers decided the finals would be contested in July, women's
sports and soccer fans flinched.
</P>
<P>
   Ever since 1996, when the United States was awarded the 1999
Women's World Cup, the 16-country tournament has been set for
action across the nation, from June 19 to the championship match in
Los Angeles on July 10.
</P>
<P>
   But wouldn't you know it. A basketball labor dispute messes
things up.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of an open sporting slate in which the United State's
Mia Hamm, Michelle Akers and Julie Foudy could shine, instead of
exploring subplots from top teams from China, Norway and Germany,
mainstream sports fans get another chance to satisfy their athletic
cravings from the NBA trough.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our preference is to have had the calendar to ourselves, but
when you look, you see there is hardly a time when you wouldn't
have something competing with us,'' Women's World Cup president
Marla Messing said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The Women's World Cup might catch a break, though. The way
things are going, the Indiana Pacers could be playing the San
Antonio Spurs or Portland Trail Blazers in the NBA Finals.
</P>
<P>
   Such a battle of TV mini-markets would all but ensure that NBC's
ratings for the first NBA championship in these post-Jordan days
will be in the dumper.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe NBC would like to reconsider its position.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, when the U.S. women won the gold medal at a packed
stadium in Georgia, the Summer Olympics network allotted barely 10
minutes of coverage to the dramatic match _ a foul of
triple-yellow-card proportions.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe that is part of the reason ESPN and ABC decided to lock up
the entire Women's World Cup, committing to televising all 32
matches, start to finish.
</P>
<P>
   The risk is significant for a TV venture of this sort, even with
several games relegated to ESPN2.
</P>
<P>
   Soccer watching in America rates somewhere behind Robbie Knievel
daredevil stunts and Triple Crown horse racing.
</P>
<P>
   But the point for ESPN might have been to make sure that if
indeed the American appetite for the Women's World Cup is
sufficiently whetted, the cameras will be there, rolling.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Risser, ESPN vice president of programming, said Monday,
``Our coverage of the 1999 FIFA Women's World Cup is part of our
ongoing commitment to present the biggest soccer events in the
United States to the viewers.''
</P>
<P>
   The Women's World Cup is only in its third cycle (1991 and '95
were the first two) and doesn't have the history of the men's World
Cup, which started in 1930.
</P>
<P>
   World Cup organizers are praying this is the breakthrough event
for women's soccer, if not worldwide then at least in this country.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the sporting public's awareness of the World Cup seems
vague. Messing asserted again Monday that the major thrust for
ticket sales has been through the soccer community, with single
ticket sales starting one month ago.
</P>
<P>
   That has pushed total ticket sales to about 380,000, with most
sales being at sites where the U.S. team will play.
</P>
<P>
   Just this week, World Cup organizers started advertising in
major daily newspapers in Portland, Chicago, New York, the San
Francisco Bay Area, Washington D.C., Los Angeles and Boston.
</P>
<P>
   With the campaign in those venue cities, Messing said they are
projecting ticket sales to reach 500,000. That is far below the
men's World Cup, which sold out every game. But it is enough to
help Women's World Cup organizers ensure they can call this the
largest women's sporting event.
</P>
<P>
   As for concerns that ESPN is lagging in promoting the
tournament, Messing said World Cup officials are not concerned.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think with TV, proximity to the event is crucial,'' she
said. ``I don't think they do a lot of advance promotion because
that's not what their viewers are geared for.''
</P>
<P>
   Last Saturday night, amid the NBA, baseball and hockey
highlights, ESPN's Sports Center broke the Big Three's stranglehold
on sports coverage when it broadcast highlights of U.S. national
team star Mia Hamm's record-setting goal.
</P>
<P>
   By scoring her 108th international goal, Hamm broke the world
record held by Italy's Elisabetta Vignotto.
</P>
<P>
   For anyone who has seen Hamm and the marvelous U.S. team compete
in the Olympics, during international matches or exhibition
friendlies, there is little doubt that this is one of the most
compelling sports teams ever to play _ and to do it for so long.
</P>
<P>
   Six players, including Seattle's Michelle Akers, are playing in
their third World Cup. Their skill level, tenacity and hunger are
for real.
</P>
<P>
   The Hamm highlight the other night was an advance shimmer of the
kind of excitement this World Cup could inspire _ especially in the
later rounds, when the elite teams from the United States, China,
Norway and Sweden are left to display their superlative talents.
</P>
<P>
   Now, there is just a lot of waiting and wondering to be done.
What impact the tournament will have on women's soccer on a
national and world level remains to be seen, but the test is almost
upon us.
</P>
<P>
   Laura Vecsey is a P-I columnist
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
