<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL _ (Moved in ``i'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-BELGRADE (Belgrade) _ Widespread blackouts and loss of
water are seriously disrupting the lives of people in the Yugoslav
capital. Things have gotten so bad that in the Belgrade suburb of
Zemun, even McDonald's didn't have water for coffee. By Steven
Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   INDIA-POLITICS (New Delhi) _ A look at the enigmatic Sonia
Gandhi. On Tuesday, Congress Party leaders will make a last-ditch
plea to her to return as president of party as they prepare for
elections in the fall. By Celia W. Dugger.
</P>
<P>
   UZBEK-GERM-WARFARE (Undated) _ The United States and Uzbekistan
have quietly negotiated and are expected to sign a bilateral
agreement Tuesday to provide American aid in dismantling and
decontaminating one of the former Soviet Union's largest chemical
weapons testing facilities, according to Defense Department and
Uzbek officials. By Judith Miller.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Locator map has been sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-NUKE (Washington) _ Inside the congressional report on
Chinese espionage due out on Tuesday is a first-rate spy story.
Trouble is, no one is sure what it means. By Tim Weiner.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   LOUIMA-ASSESS (New York) _ With Officer Justin Volpe pleading
guilty in the Abner Louima police brutality trial, new problems
have arisen for the remaining defendants. By David Bartsow.
</P>
<P>
   WELFARE-CHILD (Milwaukee, Wis.) _ Ten years old but going on 21,
Tremayne Franks is the neighborhood's youngest corner grocer. With
both parents missing from the scene, Tremayne, who lives with his
grandmother, briefly found a shelter working at the now-closed Fast
Deal Supermarket and in his relationship with its owner, a
Palestinian immigrant. A look at fatherless boys, strained race
relations and the plight of families dropped from the welfare
rolls. By Jason DeParle.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON _ (Moved in ``w'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   GUN-LOBBY-RIFT _ The congressional battle over gun control has
exposed deep fissures in the gun lobby. Mounting tensions between
the National Rifle Association and the nation's largest gun makers
have weakened the NRA's political clout in Washington, helping gun
control advocates score several victories in the Senate last week
with the passage of the first gun control measures since the
Republicans took control of the Congress in 1994. It could also
make it harder for the NRA to beat back similar measures in the
House. By James Dao.
</P>
