A9958 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OSTLER-COLUMN-SFCHRON     05-25 0788
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OSTLER-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DINING ALFRESCO? RECONSIDER 'FRISCO
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By SCOTT OSTLER 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &LR;   &LR;  LAST CALL: Looking for a place to take a nice quiet midnight
walk? Try North Beach, San Francisco's newest graveyard.
<P>
   Fortunately, the death might be only temporary.
</P>
<P>
   It got mighty quiet last weekend when cops shut down the
normally lively sidewalk cafe action a couple hours early and gave
notice that the change would be permanent. Panic set in among
restaurant owners and patrons.
</P>
<P>
   The cops from Central Station rolled up the sidewalk cafes at
midnight Friday and Saturday. Normally the cafes serve food until 2
a.m.
</P>
<P>
   The cops seemed to be sending a message: Serve a ravioli, go to
jail. Or something like that.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's horrible,'' says Cassitta Massimo, manager of Figaro, one
of several restaurants that feature sidewalk tables. ``They
basically killed the atmosphere of North Beach.''
</P>
<P>
   Are we looking at the Des &QL; 
Moines-ization of San Francisco?
</P>
<P>
   Will newspaper headlines scream: ``A Great City Forced to Go
Home Early''?
</P>
<P>
   Maybe not. Now the police at Central are backpedaling a bit, and
the death of North Beach cafe nightlife might be exaggerated.
</P>
<P>
   Several owners say the police came around last week with a
warning, then came back Friday and Saturday night, telling
restaurant workers and patrons there would be no liquor allowed on
the outside tables after 11:30 and the tables had to be taken
inside by midnight, or else everyone would turn into a pumpkin.
</P>
<P>
   ``If our officers told them that, the officers were wrong,''
says Lieutenant Tom Del Torre. ``We'll send our permit officer
around next week (to go over the ground rules with restaurant
owners).''
</P>
<P>
   Fourteen North Beach restaurants are licensed by the state
Alcoholic Beverage Commission to serve liquor outside until
midnight, and the outdoor food licenses, issued by the city's
Department of Public Works, have no curfew.
</P>
<P>
   So why the weekend crackdown? Well, Central is instituting a new
zero-tolerance-for-bad-stuff policy.
</P>
<P>
   While over-revved and sometimes under-aged young folks flocking
to North Beach's strip clubs and Broadway bars are a growing police
problem, it's hard to see how cracking down on 1 a.m. diners
enjoying a last cup of sidewalk gelato would ease the crime
problem.
</P>
<P>
   John Konstin, owner of John's Grill downtown, took his staff to
Calzone's in North Beach last Saturday night for their regular
decompression session, and they were informed that they'd have to
lose the booze at their sidewalk table by 11:30 and lose themselves
by midnight.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were police everywhere,'' Konstin says. ``It was like
the National Guard had been called out. The police were coming
around giving warnings. `You've got 15 minutes.'''
</P>
<P>
   Wow, and this is in the heart of the regular stomping grounds of
On-Da-Town Willie Brown. This kind of thing could hurt San
Francisco's rep as a big-time nightlife city. You can get a
sidewalk snack later than midnight at Disneyland.
</P>
<P>
   Andre Astabie, manager of Calzone's, tells me the police came
around last week to warn that there would be a weekend crackdown,
and the fine for non-cooperation could be up to $3,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``If that's the ordinance, they've never enforced it before,''
Astabie says.
</P>
<P>
   Capt. John Goldberg of Central Station says no restaurants or
customers were cited, but ``we're starting to ask for compliance
(with the midnight liquor cutoff). ... The purpose (of the outdoor
tables) is so people can enjoy a meal outside in the ambience of
North Beach. It is not an extension of the bar.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have enough problems with alcohol establishments, and if
you put the alcohol outdoors (late at night), the bar loses a
tremendous amount of control over the customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Also, as it gets later, diners have gone home, it's just the
drinkers out. And as much as this is an area for tourists and
diners, it's also a residential area.''
</P>
<P>
   The restaurant people say their late-night wine-and-diners
aren't a nuisance.
</P>
<P>
   ``On Friday and Saturday our kitchen is open 'til midnight, and
we get a fair amount of late diners from `Beach Blanket Babylon,'
'' says Chris Patterson, chef de cuisine at Tavolino (Italian for
``little table'').
</P>
<P>
   Capt. Goldberg says sidewalk noise is a problem for some
residents.
</P>
<P>
   But one North Beach insider points out that any resident who
lives close enough to a restaurant to be disturbed by midnight
diners was probably high on something when he or she bought/rented
his or her place. You don't move into the heart of North Beach for
tranquility and quiet.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone is happy, but for now, still alive on the sidewalks
of North Beach: The legal midnight snack.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
