A9959 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PEOPLESOFT-SFCHRON-UP     05-25 0754
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PEOPLESOFT-SFCHRON-UPDATE1 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Editors: Fixes `Cowan' to `Conway' throughout)   Duffield Hands Over Operation of PeopleSoft 
 &HT;       
 By Benny Evangelista 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
Former Oracle Corp. executive Craig Conway officially took over
yesterday as president and chief operating officer of PeopleSoft
Inc., the once high-flying business software firm that has stumbled
in the past year.
<P>
   Conway, 44, assumes day-to-day management of the Pleasanton firm
from founder and chief executive David Duffield, who said Conway
could succeed him in that position ``in the next six to 12
months.''
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Conway said his immediate challenge is to steer
PeopleSoft past its current troubles, including a drop in corporate
software orders and a turnover in top leadership, and to refocus on
growth markets.
</P>
<P>
   ``One strategic challenge is (to find) the single opportunity
that the company can devote itself to in order to reach the next
level,'' Conway said. ``As the old saying goes, if you go hunting
two rabbits at the same time, then probably both will get away.''
</P>
<P>
   Conway, 44, moves to PeopleSoft at a time when the second
biggest maker of business management software tries to recover from
a downturn that has caused its revenue growth to plummet from as
high as 80 percent to only 10 percent in the most recent quarter.
In January, the company announced it was laying off about 400
employees.
</P>
<P>
   Shares in PeopleSoft fell from a high of $52.13 in July 1998 to
as low as $11.50 in April. Conway's appointment was announced
before the stock market opened Monday, but PeopleSoft shares rose
only 50 cents, to $16.69.
</P>
<P>
   PeopleSoft and its major competitors, Oracle and SAP AG, have
been hurt by a slump in business software sales in Asia and Latin
America. In addition, the Y2K problem has caused many corporate
technology managers to halt new spending until after the end of the
year.
</P>
<P>
   Conway said PeopleSoft also suffered from the turnover in senior
management, especially when Chief Financial Officer Ronald Codd
resigned in January to head another company and Albert Duffield,
brother of David Duffield, retired as senior vice president of
sales and marketing.
</P>
<P>
   That left David Duffield at the top, but ``as Dave will tell
you, he's maybe world-class establishing corporate culture, but
he's not the best at managing day-to-day operations,'' Conway said.
</P>
<P>
   Conway said he did not have any immediate changes planned
because he wants to take time to inventory the company's strengths
and weaknesses.
</P>
<P>
   He said that PeopleSoft, which first rocketed to success by
selling human resource management software to the largest Fortune
500 corporations, must now focus on selling business applications
to mid-sized corporations.
</P>
<P>
   Conway spent eight years at Oracle, where he was executive vice
president for marketing. That included a period in the early 1990s
when Oracle ``stumbled very &LR;   &LR; badly,'' a situation that he said was
comparable to the one PeopleSoft is facing now.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a sense we could overcome almost any obstacle by
outselling it,'' Conway said. ``You almost get lulled into a false
sense of security. PeopleSoft has been able to go so long without
hitting any obstacles. It led a charmed existence. But nobody keeps
60 to 80 percent growth up forever.''
</P>
<P>
   Conway was most recently president and CEO of OneTouch Systems
Inc. of San Jose, which was bought by Hughes Network Systems and
the Apollo Group. Before that, he was CEO of TGV Software Inc.
</P>
<P>
   ``What attracted me was that (PeopleSoft) was a company with an
incredible franchise in the high-tech industry,'' Conway said.
``Notwithstanding the tactical issues it faces this year, there's a
huge future win here.''
</P>
<P>
   Other moves will probably include acquisitions, perhaps in the
area of software automating sales force management.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stay tuned, in fact, within the next few weeks,'' Duffield
said. PeopleSoft has already signed partnerships in the past year
with customer relationship management software leader Siebel
Systems Inc. and Vantive Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Duffield, 58, will remain chairman. ``I'll die here,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said PeopleSoft must focus more on Internet products.
</P>
<P>
   ``Overall, they have to roll out the most compelling electronic
commerce and Internet-enabled products as fast as they can and
leverage their existing user base effectively and quickly,'' said
Robert Austrian, a software analyst at NationsBanc Montgomery
Securities in San Francisco.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
