<HEADER>
A9962 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-AVALANCHE-STARS-H     05-25 0799
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-AVALANCHE-STARS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL SULLIVAN  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
DALLAS _ They tried everything _ slap shots, wristers, wraparounds
and tips _ and time and again the puck either bounced away
harmlessly or disappeared into glove or pads.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Patrick Roy was at it again Monday night, and the Dallas Stars'
inability to solve the riddle in the Colorado Avalanche goal left
the President's Trophy winners on the brink of a second straight
home defeat in the NHL Western Conference finals.
</P>
<P>
   What to do in such a dire situation?
</P>
<P>
   Try, try again.
</P>
<P>
   Shot No. 44 of a grind-it-out evening at Reunion Arena
eventually would make all the difference. It came when Joe
Nieuwendyk poked in a rebound at 11:52 of the third period, and it
proved to be the game-winner as the Stars outlasted the Avalanche
4-2 to even the series at a game apiece.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was one of those rare times when you were all alone in
front of the net,'' Nieuwendyk said. ``Our persistence paid off. I
thought we wanted it more than they did tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   Game 3 is Wednesday night at Denver's McNichols Arena. And
rather than facing a sweep, Dallas served notice that it may be
ready to make some noise in this series after all.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, Roy did his best to discourage such thinking. Through
more than 2{ periods, he stopped 41 of 43 shots, almost
single-handedly keeping his team in a game the rest of the
Avalanche didn't seem to feel all that strongly about winning.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Nieuwendyk got position in front of the net. And when
Roy couldn't handle Pat Verbeek's shot cleanly, Nieuwendyk was
there to cash in on the opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't have much choice but to keep firing the puck,'' he
said. ``Patrick's been in a bit of a zone, the last week to 10
days, and we really had to get second and third opportunities.''
</P>
<P>
   Verbeek's role in the game-winner was fitting, too. About five
minutes earlier, he battled in front of the net and coaxed a shot
past Roy, but the goal was waved off when it was determined that
Verbeek had a skate in the crease at the time.
</P>
<P>
   ``We felt we'd played a good game, but he was still tied,''
Verbeek said. ``We just dug a little deeper.''
</P>
<P>
   Colorado coach Bob Hartley could not say the same of his team.
</P>
<P>
   ``They played,'' he said of the winners. ``We didn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Other events, however, were eerily reminiscent of Game 1, as a
disallowed goal once again appeared to energize the team that lost
the argument. Two nights earlier, the Avalanche had gained momentum
when an apparent goal was waved off after some poorly placed
padding kept the puck from completely crossing the line.
</P>
<P>
   This time, it was Dallas' turn to vent some frustration.
</P>
<P>
   Not only did the Stars break through on Nieuwendyk's score, but
they added that rarity of rarities _ a power-play goal _ to provide
some insurance. Mike Modano got it on a feed from Sergei Zubov at
16:28, giving Dallas its first goal with a man advantage in seven
tries on the night, and just its sixth in 61 postseason chances.
</P>
<P>
   Chalk this one up to perseverance, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we just played desperate,'' coach Ken Hitchcock said.
``We know where we're at. If it's 0-2, we're in big trouble.
</P>
<P>
   ``We played this game as a sudden-death game, and that's why we
won it.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, it would not be easy.
</P>
<P>
   Colorado scored first when Sandis Ozolinsh poked in a rebound of
a Claude Lemieux shot at 10:32 of the opening period. It was the
earliest an opponent had scored against Dallas in 12 postseason
games, and it came on a power play, ending the Stars' run of 14
consecutive successful kills.
</P>
<P>
   The lead didn't last long. Just when Roy was looking
impenetrable, Dave Reid shook off Warren Rychel long enough to get
off a shot that beat the Avalanche goalie high and to Roy's right,
tying the game at 14:11.
</P>
<P>
   Reid was forced to take more ice time after Benoit Hogue
suffered a season-ending torn knee ligament.
</P>
<P>
   Dallas goalie Ed Belfour (19 shots, 17 saves) was by no means as
busy as Roy (45 shots, 41 saves), but Belfour had his moments. His
best came when he maintained the tie with a brilliant sliding save
on Milan Hejduk about four minutes into the second period.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars came right back at the other end as Zubov got off a
blast on a drop pass from Modano and beat Roy low and to the
goalie's right, making it 2-1 Dallas at 4:56.
</P>
<P>
   Again, though, the Stars could not extend the advantage, and
Hejduk eventually shoveled a rebound past Belfour at 14:59 to tie
the game again.
</P>
<P>
   The final 20 minutes would be almost all Stars. Dallas outshot
the Avalanche 15-1 in the period and kept plugging away until Roy
finally surrendered.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars' reward for that effort: new life as the series shifts
to Colorado.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-25-99 0311EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990525.0031 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-25 03:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9963 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-ROBERTSON-COLUMN-     05-25 0908
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ROBERTSON-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DALE ROBERTSON  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
EXACTLY half, and specifically the left half, of the Astros'
starting lineup has gone DL. While that's better than AWOL, I
guess, this is not a situation to be taken lightly.
<TEXT>
<P>
   No matter how deep you are, you don't lose your third baseman,
left fielder, shortstop and projected starting catcher and not feel
a tad nervousy _ particularly when the first two on the
aforementioned snakebit list were supposed to be the Nos. 4 and 5
hitters in the batting order.
</P>
<P>
   Cleanup man Ken Caminiti, of course, became the latest lineup
scratch after pulling a calf muscle in San Francisco on Friday
night, thereby joining Moises Alou, Ricky Gutierrez and Mitch
Meluskey on what we sportswriters call ``the shelf.'' Good thing
the Astros, still somehow clinging to the best record in the
National League, have managed to build a modest cushion for
themselves entering a period in which they figure to, tops, tread
water.
</P>
<P>
   Another good thing: Excepting reliever Doug Henry, none of their
pitchers is hurt. Yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``As thin as our pitching staff is,'' general manager Gerry
Hunsicker said, ``that would be critical, a disaster.''
</P>
<P>
   Hunsicker was the National League's Executive of the Year for
1998 mostly because of the trade that made Randy Johnson a smashing
rent-an-ace for the last two months of the season. But he deserves
at least as much credit for less flamboyantly putting together a
roster perhaps capable of withstanding the kind of blows the Astros
have incurred since Alou began the parade of calamities over the
offseason by tearing an anterior cruciate ligament when he tumbled
off an exercise treadmill.
</P>
<P>
   Best case, Alou returns in late August. Meluskey, the would-be
heir apparent to traded catcher Brad Ausmus, is lost for the year
after shoulder surgery. Cammy? He's gone for 15 days minimum and
could miss as much as a month, considering the troublesome nature
of his kind of malady, never mind the ever-fragile condition of his
ridden-hard, put-away-wet 36-year-old body.
</P>
<P>
   Shortstop Gutierrez, however, was throwing batting practice
Monday and should be taking BP himself by the end of the week,
barring any setbacks. Fortunately, there's no great need to rush
Ricky's return, thanks to Tim Bogar's excellent work in the role of
understudy.
</P>
<P>
   Bogey, in fact, seems downright disinclined to give Gutierrez
his job back, never mind Ricky's .357 average when he got plunked
on the back of his left hand April 28.
</P>
<P>
   ``We might have a decision to make there,'' Hunsicker admitted.
</P>
<P>
   It's hoped the committee assigned to cover third in Caminiti's
absence _ Monday's starter Russ Johnson, Billy Spiers and,
occasionally, Jack Howell _ can behave in a similar
finders-keepers, losers-weepers fashion.
</P>
<P>
   Although Cammy will return to the lineup when he's ready
regardless of what they accomplish as a tag team, the trio should
be up to the task of at least maintaining an even keel. Caminiti
hadn't set that sizzling a pace after all, hitting for a decent
average (.292) but struggling to drive his buddies across the
plate.
</P>
<P>
   His total of 17 RBIs pales in comparison with Jeff Bagwell's 45.
Then again, perhaps that's the problem. Baggy, who bats directly
ahead of him, has been leaving hardly any R's for Cammy to BI. He's
on a club-record-wrecking pace.
</P>
<P>
   ``Still, you worry about run production,'' Hunsicker said.
``Who's going to drive them in? We can't ask Baggy to do it by
himself. Losing Cammy on top of Alou is a blow.''
</P>
<P>
   God forbid that the Killer B's _ plus the Killer E, center
fielder Carl Everett _ should begin going down as well. Among them,
the lads on the intact right side of the lineup have accounted for
well over half of the Astros' ribbies.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're at our limit,'' manager Larry Dierker said. ``We can't
afford any more injuries.''
</P>
<P>
   Which explains why he made a beeline to second base to inspect
Richard Hidalgo, who appeared to have hurt himself on a
seventh-inning double but stayed in the game.
</P>
<P>
   Dierker sees a positive in the collective negative to date,
nonetheless. Everett and Hidalgo, Alou's replacement, are receiving
the every-day ABs they need, and he believes Caminiti will actually
profit from his latest forced respite.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had a sore ankle that wasn't healing, and his back was
bothering him,'' Dierker said. ``He didn't come out of spring
training ready to play (because of a sinus infection). Maybe he'll
come back more ready than he was the first time around.''
</P>
<P>
   Among Cammy's subs, Johnson will receive the most scrutiny.
Spiers is a proven commodity, having shared starts with Sean Berry
the past two seasons, and the 37-year-old Howell is really just a
pinch hitter who will play only when absolutely necessary.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, a fiery sort, ruffled Hunsicker's feathers when he
lashed out at the GM for sending him back to New Orleans after a
strong spring training. Thus, he's on notice.
</P>
<P>
   ``Russ complained about not getting a fair chance,'' Hunsicker
said. ``OK, now he's got one. It's put-up-or-shut-up time.''
</P>
<P>
   Against the Rockies, Johnson chose the former. He singled home
the Astros' first run, drew two walks to go with his two hits and
scored twice. With a full cast of heroes, the Astros won easily _
5-2 _ behind Shane Reynolds. For another day, at least, adversity
would prove an unworthy adversary.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-25-99 0311EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990525.0032 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-25 03:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9964 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-ROCKIES-ASTROS-HN     05-25 0780
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ROCKIES-ASTROS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOSEPH DUARTE  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
During his last three starts, Shane Reynolds suffered from a ``dead
arm.''
<TEXT>
<P>
   His right arm looked plenty lively Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   Reynolds pitched his first complete game in nearly a year and
the Astros took advantage of three errors by Lenny Harris to beat
the Colorado Rockies 5-2 before a crowd of 20,772 at the Astrodome.
</P>
<P>
   Reynolds (7-3) walked one and struck out eight for his 14th
career complete game and first since June 7, 1998, against Kansas
City.
</P>
<P>
   ``My last three starts, it seemed like I went through a dead-arm
period. I didn't have it in spring training, so it kind of caught
up with me now,'' said Reynolds, who was 1-2 with a 7.88 ERA in his
previous three starts. ``Usually, I go through it one or two times
during the course of a season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It didn't leave me with very much confidence in my fastball,
and I was throwing too many split-fingers and off-speed pitches
early in the count. I'm the type of pitcher that has to throw a
number of fastballs and let the other stuff work off the
fastballs.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, add Brian Bohanon to the growing list of lefthanders
to struggle against the Astros, who improved to a National
League-best 12-2 this season against lefthanded starters.
</P>
<P>
   Bohanon (6-2) pitched six innings, allowing five runs _ four
earned _ and seven hits in losing for the first time in six road
decisions. He walked a career-high six.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros are batting .345 against lefties.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been hitting lefthanders pretty well all year long,''
manager Larry Dierker said. ``We tend to hit the guys that throw
hard a little better than the guys that throw off-speed pitches.
</P>
<P>
   ``This guy (Bohanon) is definitely an off-speed pitcher. He uses
his fastball effectively, but he usually puts it on the corner just
out of the strike zone. He doesn't give you many fastballs to hit.
It's a (challenge) to hit a guy like that because his stuff looks
real tantalizing; you want to hit it, but it's not quite a strike.
I thought we showed good patience.''
</P>
<P>
   Bohanon, a North Shore product, was not entirely to blame.
Harris committed a club-record three errors at second base, two of
which led to runs.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros sent nine batters to the plate during a three-run
third inning, taking advantage of three hits, three walks and an
error to take a 3-1 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Craig Biggio hit a one-out double, his 21st, and scored on Russ
Johnson's RBI single. Jeff Bagwell followed with an RBI double to
put the Astros ahead. After a walk to Derek Bell, Harris couldn't
complete a double play on a grounder by Richard Hidalgo, throwing
the ball past first baseman Todd Helton as Bagwell scored.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros added two runs in the fourth when Biggio and Johnson
walked and Bell chipped in his second hit to put the Astros ahead
4-1. Harris made his second costly error when he bobbled a routine
grounder by Hidalgo, allowing Johnson to score.
</P>
<P>
   Harris tied Walt Weiss' club record for errors in a game, set in
1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never had a game like that before,'' said Harris, who had
five errors all of last season with Cincinnati and the New York
Mets. ``I went up to Brian (after the game) and told him I was
sorry that I played so bad behind him. He told me not to worry
about it, that it wasn't my fault.''
</P>
<P>
   Bell, who had been 0-for-13 hitting in the No. 4 spot in the
batting order, had two singles. Bell often has expressed his desire
to hit second in the lineup, between Biggio and Bagwell, but he
approached Dierker over the weekend and volunteered to hit cleanup
while Ken Caminiti is sidelined.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him if he needed me in the bottom of the lineup, that
was no problem,'' said Bell, who raised his average to .257. ``I'll
do whatever it takes to help the team win and put all personal
statistics in the back.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would rather start off slow and help the team win rather
than get to the playoffs and then go cold. I'm trying to pace
myself this year.''
</P>
<P>
   Neifi Perez accounted for both Colorado runs with an RBI double
in the second inning and an RBI single in the seventh.
</P>
<P>
   Reynolds said his thinking was to get ahead of hitters with
fastballs, working inside and out, and then finish with off-speed
pitches. The plan worked masterfully, as he went to his fastball
more in the late innings after showing his split-finger the first
few innings.
</P>
<P>
   Rockies manager Jim Leyland left the Astrodome impressed by
Reynolds. ``That was one of the best pitching performances I've
seen,'' Leyland said. ``That's the art of pitching you saw tonight.
That was a masterpiece.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-25-99 0311EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
