<DOCNO> NYT19990525.0033 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-25 03:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9965 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-BLINEBURY-COLUMN-     05-25 0800
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-BLINEBURY-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
FranBlinebury
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
SOMETIMES you just have to do the math. Put fresh batteries in the
calculator. Punch in the figures. Add up the numbers.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, use your head.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of suggesting that there is a glittering collection of
NBA title rings out there waiting for the Rockets to slip onto
their fingers, if only somebody could convince Hakeem Olajuwon to
retire.
</P>
<P>
   We'll get to the basketball part in a minute. For now, just stay
with me on the numbers.
</P>
<P>
   When you add up the obligations the Rockets have for next season
with the players under contract _ Olajuwon, Scottie Pippen, Brent
Price, Matt Maloney, Othella Harrington, Michael Dickerson, Bryce
Drew, Matt Bullard, Antoine Carr and Cuttino Mobley _ it accounts
for $37.849 million, and the salary cap next season is expected to
be about $32 million.
</P>
<P>
   Now before you start salivating over the prospect of slicing
Olajuwon's $14.302 million off the top, take the time to learn that
50 percent of that amount _ $7.151 million, in this case _ still
counts against the cap when a player retires before the end of his
contract.
</P>
<P>
   That still gives the Rockets a payroll of $30.698 million,
leaving hardly enough _ $1.3 million _ to go out and attract a
young, high-impact free agent. Which is just as well. Because this
summer there won't be any.
</P>
<P>
   Shareef Abdur-Rahim, Stephon Marbury, Kobe Bryant and their
peers already have re-signed for the maximum allowable under the
new contract between the players union and the league. Do you want
Penny Hardaway, a softer Pippen?
</P>
<P>
   And oh, yes, did I mention that by slipping just under the
salary cap, the Rockets also would lose the middle-class exception
of $2 million and the $1 million exception for next season? In
other words, they would actually have less money to spend on free
agents.
</P>
<P>
   By giving Olajuwon a gold watch and sending him out to pasture,
how are the Rockets going to get better? With Stanley Roberts at
center?
</P>
<P>
   The difference in the scenario that has been drawn up to make a
parallel with the retirements of Michael Jordan and John Elway is
wider than the Grand Canyon. Has anybody out there not currently
under the influence of a mind-altering drug suggested even once
that the Bulls and Broncos would become better teams without their
bell cows? We have already seen what happened to the Bulls. And is
anybody holding open a place in next year's Pro Bowl for Bubby
Brister?
</P>
<P>
   Now for the basketball.
</P>
<P>
   In the last two games of their playoff series, Shaquille O'Neal
nearly tripled up David Robinson, outscoring him 58-22 and
outrebounding him by 29-11. Shaq also kept David tied in knots with
11 fouls, limiting him to 27 minutes per game.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson followed Olajuwon into the lion's den against O'Neal
and in the head-to-head matchup came away just as maimed. No shame
in that, since Shaq is the most physically overpowering center of
his time, rivaled all-time only by Wilt Chamberlain.
</P>
<P>
   But while the Admiral was taking hits to his broadside, he was
opening up opportunities for his sidekick, Tim Duncan, to devour
the Lakers. It was Robinson who took the pounding, allowing Duncan
to have the energy to make the big shots and grab the headlines.
</P>
<P>
   When Olajuwon shot face-up jumpers from the key and fadeaways on
the baseline in Game 1 of the playoffs _ 10-for-13, 22 points _ the
Rockets had the Lakers beaten until late turnovers by Mobley and
Pippen gave the game away. If the Rockets win that game, it may be
a different story entirely.
</P>
<P>
   For the rest of the series, Olajuwon indeed struggled. He
committed some ill-advised fouls. He was frustrated trying to score
inside. But Pippen shot 0-for-7 in Game 2 and 6-for-23 in Game 4,
and the rookie Dickerson did not score a single field goal from the
second half of Game 1 until the series was all but over.
</P>
<P>
   Admittedly, Olajuwon is not the same player as in 1994 and '95
when he led the Rockets to championships. But by any reasonable
ranking, he is still among the top four big men _ with Shaq, Duncan
and Alonzo Mourning _ in the NBA. He can still be effective facing
the basket, spinning occasionally into the lane. He cannot stop
Shaq one-on-one. Nobody can. It takes a team, and that's the point.
The Rockets weren't a cohesive one very often this year. Yet they
went 31-19. They drew a bad matchup in the first round, then gave
away the first game.
</P>
<P>
   It is not a time to panic, but to improvise. In two more years
with him, they at least have a chance. If Dickerson improves, if
Pippen shows up, if Charles Barkley commits himself to getting in
shape again.
</P>
<P>
   But you don't get better without Hakeem.
</P>
<P>
   If nothing else, just do the math.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
