<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CNS-STADIUMS-CASH </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STADIUM NAME GAME GAINS STEAM, AND CASH; FANS ARE STEAMED, PERIOD 
</HEADLINE>
   For use by New York Times Syndicate/News Service clients as
desired.  
 By KEN THOMAS  
 c. 1999 Columbia News Service  
 &HT;    NEW YORK _ Whatever happened to Candlestick Park? Jack Murphy
Stadium? Or the Brendan Byrne Arena? The well-known sports venues,
in fact, are still there. But all three go by different monikers,
part of trend to bring cash to the franchises by selling out their
traditional names.
 &HT;    Candlestick Park, the home of the San Francisco Giants and
49ers, known to legions of devoted fans as ``The 'Stick,'' operates
under the drabbish banner of 3Com Park at Candlestick Point. San
Diego's Jack Murphy Stadium, named for a local sportswriter who
successfully crusaded for a professional football team, morphed
into Qualcomm Park. And the Brendan Byrne Arena in East Rutherford,
N.J., which honored the state's former governor, is called the
Continental Airlines Arena.
 &HT;    All three reaped hefty financial deals for turning over their
identities to the highest bidder.
 &HT;    Like many other aspects of professional sports, the stadiums
themselves have gone corporate and their old names have gone kaput.
Of 118 professional sports franchises in the four major team
sports, 63 now play in stadiums with corporate names, according to
the Chicago-based Team Marketing Report.
 &HT;    ``In ten years there may not be many major league facilities
left unnamed,'' said Sean Brenner, the trade publication's editor.
 &HT;    The money makes the change worth it, sports analysts say.
Multi-year deals of more than $100 million were won by seven
franchises that inked naming-rights agreements. Typically, naming
deals span about 20 years and can mean up to $5 million annually
for the biggest urban markets.
 &HT;    Many fans complain about revered personalities and club
tradition being replaced by the soulless, sterile logos of modern
techno-businesses. To these fans, stadium names should not sound
like synonyms for the title pages of corporate annual reports.
 &HT;    In New York, where both the Mets and the Yankees are eyeing the
windfall reaped by other stadiums and may soon carry corporate
labels, local fans wonder if the changes will alter the fan
experience.
 &HT;    ``People from all over the world come to Yankee Stadium,'' said
Mitchell Staub, a 23-year-old baseball fan. ``They don't want to
come to 'Yankee Yahoo Stadium.'''
 &HT;    For all the fuss, corporate influence is nothing new in stadium
names. In 1926, the Chicago Cubs named their ballpark Wrigley
Field, honoring William Wrigley Jr., the club's owner and chewing
gum magnate.
 &HT;    But most sports historians point to the Buffalo Bills' 1973 deal
with Rich Products Co. as the first example of selling a stadium
name.
 &HT;    Since then, sports analysts say, the ground rules have changed.
 &HT;    ``It used to be more about corporate philanthropy,'' said Matt
Brown, a professor of sports marketing at Ohio University. Today,
however, corporations ``don't do it unless there's a return on
their investment.''
 &HT;    For corporations like United Airlines, whose logo beams _
purists might say blasphemes _ from the roof of Chicago's
basketball and hockey arena, the deals can cement a company's
presence in a city. And, as with Boston's Fleet Center, home of the
Celtics and Bruins, exclusivity means that only Fleet Bank
automated teller machines are found inside the arena.
 &HT;    For smaller companies, such as 3Com, a northern California-based
developer of computer networks, the benefits can boost stock prices
and the company's overall profile.
 &HT;    Soon to fall will be Tiger Stadium in Detroit. When the Tigers
wrap up their season this fall, they will bid farewell to their
77-year-old ballpark where hometown fans once cheered Hall of
Famers Ty Cobb, Hank Greenberg and Al Kaline.
 &HT;    Next season the Tigers will move into the spanking new Comerica
Park, sponsored by Detroit's 150-year-old bank. Comerica, which
ponied up $66 million to attach its name to the stadium for 30
years, will be the team's ``official bank,'' supply the stadium
with four bank machines and air several television and radio spots
during Tiger telecasts.
 &HT;    ``It was a once in a 30-year opportunity,'' said spokesman Wayne
Mielke of Comerica.
 &HT;    Most fans now seem to accept the corporate names as inescapable
elements of modern sports. These same corporations wrap their
images around college football bowl games, plaster advertising on
the shirts of tennis stars and spend millions for the privilege of
advertising during the Super Bowl.
 &HT;    ``It's really becoming almost a non-issue as the trend has
continued,'' said Team Marketing Report's Brenner. ``With each new
deal comes along less and less backlash.''
 &HT;    That may be true, but fans like Matt Kreinces, a Garden City,
N.Y., lawyer, still don't like it.
 &HT;    ``I don't understand why we can't use people's names,'' he said.
 &HT;     (EDITORS: Ken Thomas is a master's degree candidate at the
Graduate School of Journalism at Columbia University. There is no
charge for use of this story, but please send a tearsheet to Prof.
Wayne Svoboda, Columbia News Service, Graduate School of
Journalism, Columbia University, 2950 Broadway, New York, N.Y.
10027)   r l
 BC-CNS-STADIUMS-CASH  
 STADIUM NAME GAME GAINS STEAM, AND CASH; FANS ARE STEAMED, PERIOD  
 For use by New York Times Syndicate/News Service clients as
desired.  
 By KEN THOMAS  
 c. 1999 Columbia News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Whatever happened to Candlestick Park? Jack Murphy
Stadium? Or the Brendan Byrne Arena? The well-known sports venues,
in fact, are still there. But all three go by different monikers,
part of trend to bring cash to the franchises by selling out their
