<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CNS-WINE-EXPERT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WINE EXPERT TEACHES NOVICES TO BE CONNOISSEURS 
</HEADLINE>
   For use by New York Times Syndicate/News Service clients as
desired.  
 By ERIK LINDEN  
 c. 1999 Columbia News Service  
 &HT;    NEW YORK _ Swishing a mouthful of Cabernet Piave, the man on a
mission to demystify wines spits and then grins. ``This is getting
weird,'' says Willie Gluckstern, a 19-year veteran of hosting wine
classes in New York City. ``This is a strange Cabernet.''
 &HT;    Dressed in an olive suit, the 6-foot-4-inch Gluckstern then asks
his four wine pouring assistants _ all charming women in their 20s
_ to hand out Peranno cheese to class members.
 &HT;    ``Cheese is the great equalizer,'' Gluckstern explains to the
group of 50 novice wine tasters participating in a class on Italian
wines at the Park Central hotel in Manhattan. ``You take the worst
crap in a glass and it tastes great with cheese.''
 &HT;    In a city where wine classes are myriad and it is hip to sniff
out the best, Gluckstern is a voice unlike any other. Gluckstern
encourages people to go beyond jug wines, to avoid overexposed
brands advertised on billboards or television, and to explore wines
from smaller vineyards.
 &HT;    Perhaps Gluckstern helped start a trend. Last year, Americans
began to abandon jug wines mass produced by the large wine
corporations in favor of smaller vintages, according to Gladys
Horiuchi of the San Francisco-based Wine Institute. ``Part of that
is the fact that consumers are becoming more knowledgeable about
wines,'' says Horiuchi.
 &HT;    It's all part of a surge in wine sales in the past two decades.
In 1997, Americans drank $16 billion worth of wine, compared with
only $6 billion in 1980.
 &HT;    Gluckstern is thrilled to see the numbers rise. And he doesn't
mind cashing in at the same time. Last summer, Gluckstern wrote
``The Wine Avenger'' (Simon and Schuster), a book filled with tips
and witty wisdom. Born in New York City, Gluckstern acquired a
taste for wine from his father, who once managed Knickerbocker
Liquors, a wine wholesaler.
 &HT;    ``He piqued my interest,'' Gluckstern says of his father. ``He
told me tales of the wine trade and about rare, long forgotten
vintages.''
 &HT;    In the early 1970s, Gluckstern wrote material for stand-up
comedians and started his ``Wines for Food'' classes, which teach
novices how to pick the right wines to accompany various foods.
These days, Gluckstern runs a Web site _ wineavenger.com _ and is
the purchasing director for the upscale wine shop Nancy's Wines in
Manhattan.
 &HT;    During the class at the Park Central Hotel, the 50 class members
spit 38 different Italian wines into blue plastic cups, and get an
earful of Gluckstern's aphorisms and rules. ``You have to spit the
wine out, please,'' he tells participants. ``I don't want to lose
you because you're drunk after an hour.''
 &HT;    Over the lively music of Italian folk singer Carlo Buttie,
Gluckstern, who is 50, sets out to debunk the myths. He tells his
audience that Chardonnay wines from California are for the most
part overrated, and that wines don't always improve with age. ``The
fact that a wine can make it to an old age,'' says Gluckstern,
``does not mean it will be a ripe old age.''
 &HT;    Many participants say that Gluckstern's teachings honed their
palettes. ``I took another class in the city and it was too
intensive,'' says Christine Fasbach, 29, as she spits out a
mouthful of Pinot Grigio. ``It was simply too involved.'' Fasbach
plans to return for classes on Germanic wines and then a class on
Champagnes.
 &HT;    ``Two things I've learned are that I like Riesling wines and
that I should pay attention to the grape the wine comes from,''
says Jennifer Teitler, 29, after attending her second class with
Gluckstern. ``And I like that Willie doesn't put on any airs.''
 &HT;    Over and over, the wine guru hammers home his message that fine
wine is not only for the elite. Expensive wines are not always the
best wines, he says, and retailers and restaurant owners jack up
prices in the name of snob appeal.
 &HT;    One of his pet peeves is the much-adored Chardonnay.
 &HT;    ``Chardonnays are a joke,'' says Gluckstern, who vilifies
American winemakers for pumping up their pallid grapes with
additives like oak chips. The wine has become a smash success only
because people have grown accustomed to the wooden oak flavor. They
also like the name. Chardonnay is easy to pronounce.
 &HT;    Not so, says Harriet Lembeck, director of the Wines and Spirits
program in Manhattan. ``I wouldn't say that most Chardonnays are
over-oaked,'' says Lembeck, who is also wine director for the New
School in Manhattan. ``You just can't make sweeping statements like
that about wine.''
 &HT;    But Willie Gluckstern does.
 &HT;    ``Those bankers, brokers and gynecologists with $85,000 wine
cellars don't know anything about wines,'' Gluckstern tells his
class at the Park Central Hotel with a smirk. ``And now you do.''
 &HT;     (EDITORS: Erik Linden is a master's degree candidate at the
Graduate School of Journalism at Columbia University. There is no
charge for use of this story, but please send a tearsheet to Prof.
Wayne Svoboda, Columbia News Service, Graduate School of
Journalism, Columbia University, 2950 Broadway, New York, N.Y.
10027)   r l
 BC-CNS-WINE-EXPERT  
 WINE EXPERT TEACHES NOVICES TO BE CONNOISSEURS  
 For use by New York Times Syndicate/News Service clients as
desired.  
 By ERIK LINDEN  
 c. 1999 Columbia News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Swishing a mouthful of Cabernet Piave, the man on a
mission to demystify wines spits and then grins. ``This is getting
weird,'' says Willie Gluckstern, a 19-year veteran of hosting wine
classes in New York City. ``This is a strange Cabernet.''
</P>
<P>
   Dressed in an olive suit, the 6-foot-4-inch Gluckstern then asks
his four wine pouring assistants _ all charming women in their 20s
_ to hand out Peranno cheese to class members.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cheese is the great equalizer,'' Gluckstern explains to the
group of 50 novice wine tasters participating in a class on Italian
wines at the Park Central hotel in Manhattan. ``You take the worst
crap in a glass and it tastes great with cheese.''
</P>
<P>
   In a city where wine classes are myriad and it is hip to sniff
out the best, Gluckstern is a voice unlike any other. Gluckstern
encourages people to go beyond jug wines, to avoid overexposed
brands advertised on billboards or television, and to explore wines
from smaller vineyards.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps Gluckstern helped start a trend. Last year, Americans
began to abandon jug wines mass produced by the large wine
corporations in favor of smaller vintages, according to Gladys
Horiuchi of the San Francisco-based Wine Institute. ``Part of that
is the fact that consumers are becoming more knowledgeable about
wines,'' says Horiuchi.
</P>
<P>
   It's all part of a surge in wine sales in the past two decades.
In 1997, Americans drank $16 billion worth of wine, compared with
only $6 billion in 1980.
</P>
<P>
   Gluckstern is thrilled to see the numbers rise. And he doesn't
mind cashing in at the same time. Last summer, Gluckstern wrote
``The Wine Avenger'' (Simon and Schuster), a book filled with tips
and witty wisdom. Born in New York City, Gluckstern acquired a
taste for wine from his father, who once managed Knickerbocker
Liquors, a wine wholesaler.
</P>
<P>
   ``He piqued my interest,'' Gluckstern says of his father. ``He
told me tales of the wine trade and about rare, long forgotten
vintages.''
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1970s, Gluckstern wrote material for stand-up
comedians and started his ``Wines for Food'' classes, which teach
novices how to pick the right wines to accompany various foods.
These days, Gluckstern runs a Web site _ wineavenger.com _ and is
the purchasing director for the upscale wine shop Nancy's Wines in
Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   During the class at the Park Central Hotel, the 50 class members
spit 38 different Italian wines into blue plastic cups, and get an
earful of Gluckstern's aphorisms and rules. ``You have to spit the
wine out, please,'' he tells participants. ``I don't want to lose
you because you're drunk after an hour.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the lively music of Italian folk singer Carlo Buttie,
Gluckstern, who is 50, sets out to debunk the myths. He tells his
audience that Chardonnay wines from California are for the most
part overrated, and that wines don't always improve with age. ``The
fact that a wine can make it to an old age,'' says Gluckstern,
``does not mean it will be a ripe old age.''
</P>
<P>
   Many participants say that Gluckstern's teachings honed their
palettes. ``I took another class in the city and it was too
intensive,'' says Christine Fasbach, 29, as she spits out a
mouthful of Pinot Grigio. ``It was simply too involved.'' Fasbach
plans to return for classes on Germanic wines and then a class on
Champagnes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two things I've learned are that I like Riesling wines and
that I should pay attention to the grape the wine comes from,''
says Jennifer Teitler, 29, after attending her second class with
Gluckstern. ``And I like that Willie doesn't put on any airs.''
</P>
<P>
   Over and over, the wine guru hammers home his message that fine
wine is not only for the elite. Expensive wines are not always the
best wines, he says, and retailers and restaurant owners jack up
prices in the name of snob appeal.
</P>
<P>
   One of his pet peeves is the much-adored Chardonnay.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chardonnays are a joke,'' says Gluckstern, who vilifies
American winemakers for pumping up their pallid grapes with
additives like oak chips. The wine has become a smash success only
because people have grown accustomed to the wooden oak flavor. They
also like the name. Chardonnay is easy to pronounce.
</P>
<P>
   Not so, says Harriet Lembeck, director of the Wines and Spirits
program in Manhattan. ``I wouldn't say that most Chardonnays are
over-oaked,'' says Lembeck, who is also wine director for the New
School in Manhattan. ``You just can't make sweeping statements like
that about wine.''
</P>
<P>
   But Willie Gluckstern does.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those bankers, brokers and gynecologists with $85,000 wine
cellars don't know anything about wines,'' Gluckstern tells his
class at the Park Central Hotel with a smirk. ``And now you do.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITORS: Erik Linden is a master's degree candidate at the
Graduate School of Journalism at Columbia University. There is no
charge for use of this story, but please send a tearsheet to Prof.
Wayne Svoboda, Columbia News Service, Graduate School of
Journalism, Columbia University, 2950 Broadway, New York, N.Y.
10027) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
