<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CNS-INSTANT-COFFEE-SALES </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOURMET BEANS CAUSE INSTANT A 'LATTE' TROUBLE 
</HEADLINE>
   For use by New York Times Syndicate/News Service clients as
desired.  
 By BRAD FOSS  
 c.1999 Columbia News Service  
 &HT;    NEW YORK _ As Americans spend more time and money sipping
gourmet and specialty coffees in European-style cafes, they are
turning their backs on the less costly, less time-consuming _ and,
some argue, less tasty _ beverage made from the same bean.
 &HT;    The heyday for instant coffee in this country _ during the late
1970s _ is over. Its percentage of total U.S. coffee consumption
dropped from 13 percent in 1991 to just 9 percent by 1996, an
overall decline of 30 percent.
 &HT;    Sales overseas, however, are percolating. While the 10 million
people who still drink freeze-dried, agglomerated and crystallized
java have become a minority in this country, the worldwide
prospects for instant coffee are excellent.
 &HT;    Despite slumping sales here, instant coffee, also known as
soluble, accounts for roughly half of all consumption worldwide,
according to the Tea and Coffee Trade Journal. For instance,
instant makes up roughly 90 percent of that slurped in England and
Russia. Some former Soviet-bloc countries have similarly high rates
of consumption, and the continents of Asia and Australia are
considered the next frontiers for instant coffee manufacturers and
distributors.
 &HT;    But while instant coffee makers seek to develop new markets,
they understand that a country's palate sometimes changes when its
economy improves. ``All of the developing countries drink soluble
coffee first,'' said Jane McCabe, editor at the Tea and Coffee
Trade Journal. ``Then they switch over to roasted ground coffee.''
 &HT;    Indeed, there is some debate about the potential life span of
instant coffee once it is introduced into any country. ``People
don't like the taste,'' McCabe said. ``Once they find roasted
ground, they stick with that.''
 &HT;    On the other hand, there is some hope within the industry that
the preference for instant might be more than a passing phase in
England, Russia and some Eastern European countries. Instant is
judged by more stringent minimum standards before it is sold in
countries other than the United States, said Susan Korry, who
trades coffee worldwide for the Rothfos Corp., a division of
Neumann Kaffee Gruppe, based in Hamburg, Germany.
 &HT;    ``They have quality products shipped in,'' she said. ``Whereas
here in the United States, we don't have that type of testing.
 &HT;    ``There are products on the shelf'' in the United States, Korry
said, ``which state that they're 100 percent coffee and they're
not. There might be a bean of coffee in it.'' By allowing goods of
inferior quality in supermarkets, she said, America has ``ruined''
a once $2 billion a year industry.
 &HT;    During the 1980s, when quality and sales started to slip,
Americans began to sample gourmet ground coffee in significant
numbers. Since 1991, the number of cafes devoted to the brew in
this country has grown from 500 to more than 7,000. The number of
occasional drinkers grew by 20 million last year, according to a
recent study by the National Coffee Association. As the
association's spokesman, Gary Goldstein, explained, ``You know,
people who will go out for a double cappuccino.''
 &HT;    Quantifying the precise effect all this has had on overall
coffee drinking habits can be misleading.. For one thing, specialty
drinks such as mochas, lattes and frappuccinos contain a
considerable amount of milk and sweeteners, which can be more of an
enticement than the coffee flavors in these concoctions.
 &HT;    And while there may be more Americans enjoying these frothy
drinks, their consumption is more restrained than that of coffee
drinkers 20 years ago, who used to polish off several cups a day,
said McCabe of the coffee trade journal. Offsetting this decline,
of course, is the fact that today's consumers are willing to pay
more than $3 for trendy specialty drinks.
 &HT;    Instant coffee may be on the decline as a traditional beverage.
But, Korry said, it is growing as an ingredient in bakery products,
candies, ice cream and capuccino vending machines nationwide.
 &HT;    Indeed, the meteoric growth of the gourmet and specialty coffees
is not a total disaster for instant coffee drinkers. Korry said
that in order to maintain a presence on supermarket shelves,
companies that sell instant coffee in this country have begun to
pay closer attention to the quality and taste of their products.
 &HT;    As Grace Torbus, president of Tonex Inc., which distributes its
instant coffee internationally and in the United States, explained,
``When people take a coffee break, they want to feel like they went
out to a fine restaurant or had a gourmet dessert.''
 &HT;     (EDITORS: Brad Foss is a master's degree candidate at the
Graduate School of Journalism at Columbia University. There is no
charge for use of this story, but please send a tearsheet to Prof.
Wayne Svoboda, Columbia News Service, Graduate School of
Journalism, Columbia University, 2950 Broadway, New York, N.Y.
10027)   r l
 BC-CNS-INSTANT-COFFEE-SALES  
 GOURMET BEANS CAUSE INSTANT A 'LATTE' TROUBLE  
 For use by New York Times Syndicate/News Service clients as
desired.  
 By BRAD FOSS  
 c.1999 Columbia News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ As Americans spend more time and money sipping
gourmet and specialty coffees in European-style cafes, they are
