<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CNS-ROMANCE-BOOKS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEAVING BOSOMS AND THROBBING LOINS: ROMANCE BOOKS ARE HOT 
</HEADLINE>
   For use by New York Times Syndicate/News Service clients as
desired.  
 By GEORGINA GUSTIN  
 c. 1999 Columbia News Service  
 &HT;    NEW YORK _ When Kathy Baker meets with her reading group, they
tear a novel apart. They look at narrative tension, plot, conflict,
resolution, and denouement. They debate whether the characters were
compelling enough, the hero was sufficiently sympathetic, and the
heroine passionate but pure.
 &HT;    Shakespeare? Joyce? Balzac?
 &HT;    Not exactly. These novels have titles like ``Lord of
Scoundrels,'' ``The Unrepentant Rake,'' ``To Tame a Warrior's
Heart'' and ``A Rogue in Texas.''
 &HT;    Welcome to the steamy, stormy world of romance book fan clubs,
where the heroines are always strong but feminine and the heroes
strapping but troubled. Baker's 15-member group, called the
Heartthrobs, gets together once a month, usually in the Waldenbooks
at the Northeast Mall in Hurst, Texas, and they always have plenty
to discuss. Like Baker, most members read an average of one romance
novel a day _ 30 every month _ and are helping to make the romance
market the fastest growing market in the country.
 &HT;    The general book market may be slumping, but romance novels are
flying off the shelves faster than the racing hearts of
passion-inflamed lovers, and now account for almost 40 percent of
the entire book market, according to the American Booksellers
Association.
 &HT;    ``Romance readers are voracious,'' said Charis McEachern, a
spokesperson for the Romance Writers of America, an 8,000-member
Texas-based industry group ``Some of them read one a day, five
times a week. A lot of romance readers run out of books.''
 &HT;    And even though most academics and literati look down their
noses at the genre, fans of romance novels say there's nothing
better than curling up at the end of the day with a steamy tale of
true love and throbbing loins. And to those that say romance novels
aren't real literature, romance readers present this simple
challenge: Read one.
 &HT;    ``A lot of people don't realize the complexities of romance,''
said Pat Rouse, a columnist for Romantic Times magazine, an
industry publication with a circulation of 150,000. ``There are a
million plots in a book.''
 &HT;    The demands of romance readers are simple, however. They expect
only two things: a happy ending and absolute monogamy between hero
and heroine. But their tastes are discriminating, and what any
romance reader wants is a good story, well told.
 &HT;    ``It's important that the characters come to life off the
pages,'' Baker said. And that they do it quickly. ``Some authors
can keep your attention, but if you wait four or five chapters for
the heroine and hero to get together, it's too long. Most people
will put the book down.''
 &HT;    Under the umbrella of ``romance fiction'' there are dozens of
sub-genres, including ``women in jeopardy,'' ``western,''
``paranormal,'' ``inspirational,'' and ``futuristic.'' And with
such an array of categories romance fiction has broadened in its
appeal.
 &HT;    ``In the 70's it was just bodice rippers with a 17-year old
virgin being chased around by a landowner,'' McEachern said. ``But
in the '90s, the books are reflecting the way women are today. They
deal with real issues like child care and taking care of elderly
parents.''
 &HT;    However, she adds, ``Unlike real life, there's a guarantee with
the author. The reader knows there will be a happy ending.''
 &HT;    But it's not just a happy ending that keeps these readers
engaged. It's the network of romance readers, which has reached
something of a cult status.
 &HT;    ``If I see someone in a store buying romance, I know we'll be
friends,'' Rouse said. ``It's not just the books you read, but the
friends you make through this common interest. There's literally no
place I can go in the country where I don't have a standing
invitation to stay with a romance fan.''
 &HT;    By sending out posters to libraries across the country, the
Romance Writers of America recently tried to dispel the stereotype
of the typical romance reader. The posters, with the caption ``Look
Who's Reading Romance,'' pictured a Harvard-educated cellular
biologist, a telephone lineman, and a superior court judge, among
others.
 &HT;    ``We wanted to show it wasn't a bunch of lonely women at home
with a lot of cats,'' McEachern said.
 &HT;     (EDITORS: Georgina Gustin is a master's degree candidate at the
Graduate School of Journalism at Columbia University. There is no
charge for use of this story, but please send a tearsheet to Prof.
Wayne Svoboda, Columbia News Service, Graduate School of
Journalism, Columbia University, 2950 Broadway, New York, N.Y.
10027)   r l
 BC-CNS-ROMANCE-BOOKS  
 HEAVING BOSOMS AND THROBBING LOINS: ROMANCE BOOKS ARE HOT  
 For use by New York Times Syndicate/News Service clients as
desired.  
 By GEORGINA GUSTIN  
 c. 1999 Columbia News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When Kathy Baker meets with her reading group, they
