<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CNS-INTERNET-WEDDINGS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FROM GOBLETS TO GARTERS TO WEDDING PROPOSALS, THE NET HAS IT 
</HEADLINE>
   For use by New York Times Syndicate/News Service clients as
desired.  
 By F. BRINLEY BRUTON  
 c. 1999 Columbia News Service  
 &HT;    NEW YORK _ Planning to get married? Planning to have a wedding?
Planning to lose your mind?
 &HT;    For the nuptially challenged who cannot spare a year to try on
lavish white gowns, nibble on reception tidbits and shop for the
perfect bridesmaid gifts, the solution can be as close as the World
Wide Web. Wedding planning may become just a little easier with the
help of the Internet, which is looking to take a chunk out of the
$32 billion-a-year wedding industry.
 &HT;    By clicking on any one of numerous sites catering to the
soon-to-be wedded, an engaged couple can accomplish just about
everything they need for their marriage except for the proposal.
 &HT;    Wait a minute, there's a site for that, too. It's called
Ungroomed.com, and it walks the uninformed, or maybe just insecure,
gentleman through the details of choosing the perfect rock _ from
color scales to carat weights and diamond cut.
 &HT;    Ungroomed.com also gives tips on proposal speeches and, for the
more adventurous bridegroom, describes how to accomplish the
ultimate in romantic proposing on a sports stadium's big-screen
scoreboard.
 &HT;    Once the lady's hand is won, bride and bridegroom to be can
click on TheKnot.com which bills itself as the ``No. 1 wedding Web
site and gift registry.'' The company offers a dress catalogue,
gift registry, money-saving strategies and wedding countdown. It
also features a column called ``Ask Carley,'' which fields
questions on problems like how to plan an overseas wedding and ways
to handle ex-spouses at the ceremony.
 &HT;    And if you think you might like to wear red to your wedding,
TheKnot's ``nonconventional page'' will advise you on how to carry
it off.
 &HT;    TheKnot aims to help couples ``make it from proposal to newlywed
life,'' said Julie Komron, senior editor.
 &HT;    The site is ``not only for the bride, it's for everyone,'' she
added. ``We help with second weddings, third weddings, gay
weddings, interfaith weddings, intercultural weddings.''
 &HT;    There are lots of other sites, all with slightly different
flavors and themes. There's the Ultimate Wedding, The Wedding
Magazine, The Wedding Garden, Way Cool Weddings, and on and on.
There are sites for religious weddings, unconventional weddings and
small weddings.
 &HT;    ``The Internet has helped me plan my wedding more than any book
out there,'' Heather Henken said.
 &HT;    Among the online features touted by Henken were the budget
planners, although she had to adjust them to account for her
expensive New York lifestyle. Some wedding sites seem to assume
that, unlike the focused Henken, engaged couples are afflicted with
a disease in which every thought has fled their heads.
 &HT;    Weddings Online advertises an ``Automatic Wedding Speech.''
Brides or grooms need only fill in the blanks to name people they
want to thank, and finish sentences such as ``The first time I knew
there was something special between us was ...''
 &HT;    To get to one of these fountain-of-all-wedding-knowledge sites,
the betrothed will probably end up stumbling through localized
companies on the Web, such as http://www.albanyweddings.com, which
tells you everything you ever wanted to know about weddings in
Albany, the capital of New York. Great if you're in Albany.
 &HT;    There are the stealthy sermonizers, like Bride and Groom
Communication Online. Billing itself as a marriage advice page, the
site mostly shares tidbits like, ``God's grace is always available
to married couples.'' But it doesn't do much on the logistics
front.
 &HT;    The most important sites for many betrothed couples are those
dealing with the experiences of other couples who have decided to
put up their own pages describing their experiences. There are
volumes of these sites, complete with baby pictures of the couple,
detailed accounts of how they met and helpful hints to others
planning their special day.
 &HT;    ``Since we met on-line we felt this Web site was a natural
extension of our relationship and our wedding celebration,'' write
Karen and Michael, a perky-looking couple in Toronto.
 &HT;    Some sites helpfully market honeymoons by including direct links
to resort hotels and other amenities. Others include massive guest
books for visitors to their sites.
 &HT;    Chat rooms also are popular for those enduring the stress of
wedding planning.
 &HT;    For bride-to-be Leigh Cole these chats offered support that she
couldn't get anywhere else.
 &HT;    ``Sometimes I would go into a chat room and ask, 'Do you guys
want to kill your brothers and sisters too?''' she said. Back came
a resounding cyber, ``You bet!''
 &HT;    Says Cole: ``It was a great way to vent.''
 &HT;     (EDITORS: F. Brinley Bruton is a master's degree candidate at
the Graduate School of Journalism at Columbia University. There is
no charge for use of this story, but please send a tearsheet to
Prof. Wayne Svoboda, Columbia News Service, Graduate School of
Journalism, Columbia University, 2950 Broadway, New York, N.Y.
10027)   r l
 BC-CNS-INTERNET-WEDDINGS  
