<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-25 10:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0085 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CNS-CRIMINALS-VICTIMS     05-25 1943
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CNS-CRIMINALS-VICTIMS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRIMINALS MEET WITH VICTIMS WHOSE LIVES THEY DAMAGED 
</HEADLINE>
   For use by New York Times Syndicate/News Service clients as
desired.  
 By BRENDAN JANUARY  
 c. 1999 Columbia News Service   On Nov. 5, 1995, Jackie Millar lay
terrified on a friend's living-room floor as Craig Sussek decided
whether to execute her with a .22-caliber handgun or a .44 Magnum.
Satisfied that the fragmentation of a .22-caliber bullet would
cause more damage, the 16-year-old bent over Millar, pointed the
gun at the back of her head and pulled the trigger.
 &HT;    Millar did not die. Six weeks after the shooting, she awoke from
a coma. Five fragments of the bullet were still embedded in her
brain, stealing her sight and permanently paralyzing her right arm
and leg.
 &HT;    For the next three years, she struggled to relearn things that
once were as natural as breathing _ how to eat, how to walk, how to
speak. She also learned to forgive. In December 1997, Millar
visited Green Bay Correctional facility in Wisconsin, not far from
where the shooting took place, where Sussek was serving an 80-year
sentence.
 &HT;    Guided by Bruce Kittle, a mediator, Millar walked into a cramped
room furnished with three chairs and a small table. Millar recalled
that Sussek was sitting down when she entered the room limping on a
cane and dragging her right side.
 &HT;    ``I wanted him to see me,'' Millar said in a telephone
interview. ``He cried and then said how sorry he was. He said there
wasn't a day that went by when he didn't think about me.''
 &HT;    Victim and assailant met that day because of a philosophy that
is gaining popularity in the penal system _ restorative justice.
The program, which puts the offender and victim in the same room,
began in Canada and was introduced to the United States in the late
1970s. The face-to-face meetings have grown. Early on, the meetings
were informal and organized by church or other groups, with the
endorsement of local courts. Today, more than 120 restorative
justice programs exist in the United States, many of them still
somewhat informal but at least one, involving the Texas Department
of Justice, an official arm of the state's criminal justice system.
Other states, including Wisconsin, are expected to follow.
 &HT;    ``Justice should be about healing,'' said Bruce Kittle, a law
professor at the University of Wisconsin in Madison. ``Our justice
system treats crime as an offense against the state, and the state
punishes the offender. The victim is often left out of the process
and the offender never truly understands the impact of their
crime.''
 &HT;    After Sussek started serving his sentence, Millar began to give
talks at schools and prisons about the reality of crime. In her
speeches, she often said that she would one day like to meet
Sussek. A woman in the audience told Millar to call Kittle, an
advocate of the restorative justice program, and a meeting was
arranged three months later.
 &HT;    At the prison meeting, Millar said she sat silently as Sussek
recounted the details that forever changed their lives. He told how
he and a friend had left Millar in a pool of blood and escaped in
her car. He described going to a fast-food restaurant and buying
food with the money in her purse. He ended by saying how he took
the car to a parking lot and set it aflame.
 &HT;    ``He was sobbing as he told it,'' said Millar. ``I wanted him to
tell exactly what he had done to me. Not so I'd know. So he'd
know.''
 &HT;    When he finished, Millar embraced him.
 &HT;    ``I needed to hug him,'' said Millar, ``to say, 'I forgive you.'
It's not so easy to say those words. But you must say them because
it helps the victim to lay it to rest. Otherwise, you're constantly
in a state of anger and bitterness.''
 &HT;    Prison officials declined to permit Sussek to speak to a
reporter.
 &HT;    To begin the process of restorative justice, a mediator
establishes a relationship between the offender and the victim.
Kittle visits prisons to explain the concept to inmates. Some ask
him to contact their victims for a meeting.
 &HT;    Many victims reject the overture. ``You have to tell the inmate
that they're not interested,'' Kittle said. ``That's awkward.''
 &HT;    Other times, Kittle spends months or even years with victims,
establishing trust and overcoming their sense of anger and
violation, before finally scheduling the first meeting.
 &HT;    Once the victim and the offender are in the same room, Kittle
says, they follow a simple outline. First, they talk about the
crime itself. For many an offender, Kittle said, this is the first
time he or she has spoken the details aloud. Second, the victim
talks about how the crime disrupted his life. Third, victim,
offender and mediator discuss together what steps can be taken for
restoration.
 &HT;    ``When people can respond to what they've done,'' Kittle said,
``it's very moving.''
 &HT;    The program impressed Dan Bertrand, warden at the Green Bay
Correctional facility, where Millar and Sussek met for the first
time. Since that meeting, she has been invited several times to
address small groups of inmates at the facility.
 &HT;    ``It's very important for the inmates to see Jackie and to
understand what crime does to people,'' Bertrand said. ``There is a
different attitude afterwards. Some of the inmates are in tears and
can barely speak. It's one of those things that keeps them from
coming back here.''
 &HT;     (EDITORS: Brendan January is a master's degree candidate at the
Graduate School of Journalism at Columbia University. There is no
charge for use of this story, but please send a tearsheet to Prof.
Wayne Svoboda, Columbia News Service, Graduate School of
Journalism, Columbia University, 2950 Broadway, New York, N.Y.
10027)   r l
 BC-CNS-CRIMINALS-VICTIMS  
 CRIMINALS MEET WITH VICTIMS WHOSE LIVES THEY DAMAGED  
 For use by New York Times Syndicate/News Service clients as
desired.  
 By BRENDAN JANUARY  
 c. 1999 Columbia News Service   On Nov. 5, 1995, Jackie Millar lay
<TEXT>
terrified on a friend's living-room floor as Craig Sussek decided
whether to execute her with a .22-caliber handgun or a .44 Magnum.
Satisfied that the fragmentation of a .22-caliber bullet would
cause more damage, the 16-year-old bent over Millar, pointed the
gun at the back of her head and pulled the trigger.
<P>
   Millar did not die. Six weeks after the shooting, she awoke from
a coma. Five fragments of the bullet were still embedded in her
brain, stealing her sight and permanently paralyzing her right arm
and leg.
</P>
<P>
   For the next three years, she struggled to relearn things that
once were as natural as breathing _ how to eat, how to walk, how to
speak. She also learned to forgive. In December 1997, Millar
visited Green Bay Correctional facility in Wisconsin, not far from
where the shooting took place, where Sussek was serving an 80-year
sentence.
</P>
<P>
   Guided by Bruce Kittle, a mediator, Millar walked into a cramped
room furnished with three chairs and a small table. Millar recalled
that Sussek was sitting down when she entered the room limping on a
cane and dragging her right side.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted him to see me,'' Millar said in a telephone
interview. ``He cried and then said how sorry he was. He said there
wasn't a day that went by when he didn't think about me.''
</P>
<P>
   Victim and assailant met that day because of a philosophy that
is gaining popularity in the penal system _ restorative justice.
The program, which puts the offender and victim in the same room,
began in Canada and was introduced to the United States in the late
1970s. The face-to-face meetings have grown. Early on, the meetings
were informal and organized by church or other groups, with the
endorsement of local courts. Today, more than 120 restorative
justice programs exist in the United States, many of them still
somewhat informal but at least one, involving the Texas Department
of Justice, an official arm of the state's criminal justice system.
Other states, including Wisconsin, are expected to follow.
</P>
<P>
   ``Justice should be about healing,'' said Bruce Kittle, a law
professor at the University of Wisconsin in Madison. ``Our justice
system treats crime as an offense against the state, and the state
punishes the offender. The victim is often left out of the process
and the offender never truly understands the impact of their
crime.''
</P>
<P>
   After Sussek started serving his sentence, Millar began to give
talks at schools and prisons about the reality of crime. In her
speeches, she often said that she would one day like to meet
Sussek. A woman in the audience told Millar to call Kittle, an
advocate of the restorative justice program, and a meeting was
arranged three months later.
</P>
<P>
   At the prison meeting, Millar said she sat silently as Sussek
recounted the details that forever changed their lives. He told how
he and a friend had left Millar in a pool of blood and escaped in
her car. He described going to a fast-food restaurant and buying
food with the money in her purse. He ended by saying how he took
the car to a parking lot and set it aflame.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was sobbing as he told it,'' said Millar. ``I wanted him to
tell exactly what he had done to me. Not so I'd know. So he'd
know.''
</P>
<P>
   When he finished, Millar embraced him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I needed to hug him,'' said Millar, ``to say, 'I forgive you.'
It's not so easy to say those words. But you must say them because
it helps the victim to lay it to rest. Otherwise, you're constantly
in a state of anger and bitterness.''
</P>
<P>
   Prison officials declined to permit Sussek to speak to a
reporter.
</P>
<P>
   To begin the process of restorative justice, a mediator
establishes a relationship between the offender and the victim.
Kittle visits prisons to explain the concept to inmates. Some ask
him to contact their victims for a meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Many victims reject the overture. ``You have to tell the inmate
that they're not interested,'' Kittle said. ``That's awkward.''
</P>
<P>
   Other times, Kittle spends months or even years with victims,
establishing trust and overcoming their sense of anger and
violation, before finally scheduling the first meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Once the victim and the offender are in the same room, Kittle
says, they follow a simple outline. First, they talk about the
crime itself. For many an offender, Kittle said, this is the first
time he or she has spoken the details aloud. Second, the victim
talks about how the crime disrupted his life. Third, victim,
offender and mediator discuss together what steps can be taken for
restoration.
</P>
<P>
   ``When people can respond to what they've done,'' Kittle said,
``it's very moving.''
</P>
<P>
   The program impressed Dan Bertrand, warden at the Green Bay
Correctional facility, where Millar and Sussek met for the first
time. Since that meeting, she has been invited several times to
address small groups of inmates at the facility.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very important for the inmates to see Jackie and to
understand what crime does to people,'' Bertrand said. ``There is a
different attitude afterwards. Some of the inmates are in tears and
can barely speak. It's one of those things that keeps them from
coming back here.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITORS: Brendan January is a master's degree candidate at the
Graduate School of Journalism at Columbia University. There is no
charge for use of this story, but please send a tearsheet to Prof.
Wayne Svoboda, Columbia News Service, Graduate School of
Journalism, Columbia University, 2950 Broadway, New York, N.Y.
10027) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
