<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-25 10:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0086 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CNS-CLINTON-ENVIRONME     05-25 3021
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CNS-CLINTON-ENVIRONMENT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GREEN HOPES HAVE BEEN TEMPERED IN CLINTON YEARS 
</HEADLINE>
   For use by New York Times Syndicate/News Service clients as
desired.  
 By NOELLA KERTES  
 c. 1999 Columbia News Service  
 &HT;    Back in 1992, the environmentalists' wish list was long and
green. But six years after Bill Clinton's election, Beltway
politics have tempered those hopes.
 &HT;    When environmentalists look back on the Clinton legacy, they see
big strides coupled with missed opportunities. The overall
direction, they say, is positive. Yet a Republican-dominated
Congress and an administration diverted by scandals and
international conflicts have kept the environmental agenda from
enjoying the prominence they had expected under Clinton.
 &HT;    ``We have been frustrated by the fact that when he makes the
environment a high priority, things happen _ positive things
happen,'' said William Meadows, president of The Wilderness
Society. ``But he doesn't seem to keep it as his highest priority.
It's always sort of fourth or fifth on his list rather than second
or third.''
 &HT;    And as Bill Clinton sets up Vice President Al Gore, who is
strongly identified with environmentalism, to succeed him, some
activists say the administration has often traded its green-tinted
glasses for more corporate-friendly lenses. While crediting the
vice president with helping shape many green-friendly policies,
environmentalists complain that, like Clinton, Gore's attention
often has been diverted to foreign policy or other issues.
 &HT;    Leaders of eight environmental advocacy organizations, including
the Environmental Defense Fund, the Sierra Club and the World
Wildlife Fund, recently wrote to Gore expressing their ``deep
disappointment'' that the administration had not pushed more to
reduce global warming pollution through reductions of fossil fuel
emissions.
 &HT;    Environmental groups also withdrew in protest from an
administration task force on food safety, accusing the
Environmental Protection Administration of inaction on curtailing
harmful pesticides.
 &HT;    Once, environmentalists were so furious with Clinton that they
held a public denunciation, the ``21 Chainsaw Salute'' following
his signature on legislation that allowed the harvesting of certain
old-growth trees. Such trees are the foundation of forest
ecosystems, in the view of environmentalists, and should be
protected.
 &HT;    Clinton also occasionally employed a split-the-difference
approach that has left neither environmentalists nor their
corporate nemeses satisfied.
 &HT;    ``The fact is the president and the vice president have to make
choices in the political environment,'' Meadows said. ``I think
they try to get things done and perhaps they're less aggressive
than we would like them to be.''
 &HT;    Despite these qualms, environmentalists have had a strong voice
in the Clinton years, and they unanimously praise him for
eco-friendly appointments such as EPA Administrator Carol Browner
and Interior Secretary Bruce Babbitt. They credit Clinton with
staving off a Republican onslaught on environmental protection
following the GOP sweep of Congress in 1994. Groups that felt shut
out of Republican policy-making, now were welcomed in White House
deliberations.
 &HT;    Administration officials point to preservation of vast areas of
western lands and regulatory crackdowns as hallmarks of the Clinton
years. But despite early efforts, the administration failed to
achieve a longstanding environmentalists' goal _ raising grazing
and mining fees on federal land, activists note.
 &HT;    ``I think he deserves the criticism but it's not so black and
white,'' said Brock Evans, executive director of the Endangered
Species Coalition, who praises Clinton for significant strides in
some areas.
 &HT;    ``I would say it's nothing short of a revolution in terms of the
Forest Service. The Northwest forests are in much better shape than
they would have been under his opponents,'' he said, citing
Clinton's three-day forest summit and the subsequent implementation
of the Northwest Forest Plan, which significantly reduced logging
in a reversal of decades-old policies.
 &HT;    Evans, on the other hand, blasts Babbitt's novel system of
negotiating with huge landowners over endangered species
protection, saying the division of land for development and for
habitat inadequately protects wildlife.
 &HT;    ``History may judge this administration as being the worst in
endangered species,'' protection, Evans said.
 &HT;    And groups pushing for restoration of Florida's Everglades were
critical of the administration for not driving a harder bargain
with sugar growers who have been ordered to pay a portion of the $8
billion pricetag to partly restore the marshlands' natural water
flow.
 &HT;    One indicator of Clinton's environmental record is evident in
the criticism from business and industry, which accuse him of
unnecessary regulatory schemes that drive industry's costs up.
 &HT;    ``EPA has enlarged its enforcement powers over the last six
years. For our industry it has been calamitous,'' said Barry
Polsky, a spokesman for the American Forest &AMP; Paper Association,
adding that regulatory action to save the Northwest spotted owl
habitat and the litigation it created had led to an 80 percent
reduction in the timber harvest in the Pacific Northwest.
 &HT;    During the last decade, he said, 13 percent of the paper
industry's capital has been spent on environmental protection, a
figure his trade association predicts will double in the next five
years, ``based on laws and regulations that are now in place or
those that we think are going to be passed.''
 &HT;    A study by the Competitive Enterprise Institute, an
anti-regulation think tank, concluded that during Clinton's first
year in office, the number of Federal Register pages announcing
government actions jumped by 7 percent, and that federal agencies
spent $17.5 billion to police their regulations in 1998.
 &HT;    ``They seem to evaluate their performance not on how clean the
environment is, but how many people they cite for violations,''
said Fred L. Smith Jr., CEI president.
 &HT;    The administration also has had to defend itself against
industry accusations that agencies have ignored science in their
zeal to implement new regulations.
 &HT;    ``We think they've abused science to scare people to get their
budgets approved or in defense of their regulations,'' said Mark
Whitenton, vice president at the National Manufactures Association,
an opponent of EPA's creeping restrictions on factory emissions.
 &HT;    Administration efforts to appease both sides sometimes have left
both disgruntled. On the dominant issue of climate change,
environmental leaders praise Clinton for raising awareness of the
earth's warming trend, but fault him for surrendering to domestic
pressures against cutting emissions of so-called greenhouse gases,
which result from the burning of fossil fuels.
 &HT;    ``We'd hoped they'd be a leader in global warming but in fact
it's all been rhetoric and very little performance,'' said Brent
Blackwelder, president of Friends of the Earth, who holds Clinton
in far greater disdain than many of his environmental colleagues.
 &HT;    Industry on the other hand, is upset that the administration
even signed the 1997 international treaty on climate change,
because it commits the United States to cutting industrial
emissions by 7 percent from 1990 levels by the year 2010, targets
that industry advocates say cannot be met without damaging the
economy. The Senate still must ratify the treaty.
 &HT;    Although some hoped-for legislative overhauls never materialized
_ such as an update of Superfund hazardous waste liability _
environmentalists heralded these actions the Clinton years:
 &HT;    _ Legislative victories on the Safe Drinking Water and Clean
Water amendments.
 &HT;    _ The California Desert Protection Act, which sets aside nearly
7 million acres of California desert, the largest tract of public
land protected outside of Alaska.
 &HT;    _ Creation of Grand Staircase-Escalante National Monument in
Utah.
 &HT;    Perhaps no international issue galvanized environmentalists like
the North American Free Trade Agreement that Clinton signed with
Mexico and Canada in 1993 despite activists' objections that it
would promote environmental degradation in border areas. The
conflict continues to play out as Clinton seeks so-called
fast-track authority to ink trade deals without congressional
oversight, a move the environmentalists abhor.
 &HT;    ``We're still on opposite sides,'' said Deborah Sease, Sierra
Club legislative director.
 &HT;     (EDITORS: Noella Kertes is a master's degree candidate at the
Graduate School of Journalism at Columbia University. There is no
charge for use of this story, but please send a tearsheet to Prof.
Wayne Svoboda, Columbia News Service, Graduate School of
Journalism, Columbia University, 2950 Broadway, New York, N.Y.
10027)   r l
 BC-CNS-CLINTON-ENVIRONMENT  
 GREEN HOPES HAVE BEEN TEMPERED IN CLINTON YEARS  
 For use by New York Times Syndicate/News Service clients as
desired.  
 By NOELLA KERTES  
 c. 1999 Columbia News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Back in 1992, the environmentalists' wish list was long and
green. But six years after Bill Clinton's election, Beltway
politics have tempered those hopes.
</P>
<P>
   When environmentalists look back on the Clinton legacy, they see
big strides coupled with missed opportunities. The overall
direction, they say, is positive. Yet a Republican-dominated
Congress and an administration diverted by scandals and
international conflicts have kept the environmental agenda from
enjoying the prominence they had expected under Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have been frustrated by the fact that when he makes the
environment a high priority, things happen _ positive things
happen,'' said William Meadows, president of The Wilderness
Society. ``But he doesn't seem to keep it as his highest priority.
It's always sort of fourth or fifth on his list rather than second
or third.''
</P>
<P>
   And as Bill Clinton sets up Vice President Al Gore, who is
strongly identified with environmentalism, to succeed him, some
activists say the administration has often traded its green-tinted
glasses for more corporate-friendly lenses. While crediting the
vice president with helping shape many green-friendly policies,
environmentalists complain that, like Clinton, Gore's attention
often has been diverted to foreign policy or other issues.
</P>
<P>
   Leaders of eight environmental advocacy organizations, including
the Environmental Defense Fund, the Sierra Club and the World
Wildlife Fund, recently wrote to Gore expressing their ``deep
disappointment'' that the administration had not pushed more to
reduce global warming pollution through reductions of fossil fuel
emissions.
</P>
<P>
   Environmental groups also withdrew in protest from an
administration task force on food safety, accusing the
Environmental Protection Administration of inaction on curtailing
harmful pesticides.
</P>
<P>
   Once, environmentalists were so furious with Clinton that they
held a public denunciation, the ``21 Chainsaw Salute'' following
his signature on legislation that allowed the harvesting of certain
old-growth trees. Such trees are the foundation of forest
ecosystems, in the view of environmentalists, and should be
protected.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also occasionally employed a split-the-difference
approach that has left neither environmentalists nor their
corporate nemeses satisfied.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact is the president and the vice president have to make
choices in the political environment,'' Meadows said. ``I think
they try to get things done and perhaps they're less aggressive
than we would like them to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite these qualms, environmentalists have had a strong voice
in the Clinton years, and they unanimously praise him for
eco-friendly appointments such as EPA Administrator Carol Browner
and Interior Secretary Bruce Babbitt. They credit Clinton with
staving off a Republican onslaught on environmental protection
following the GOP sweep of Congress in 1994. Groups that felt shut
out of Republican policy-making, now were welcomed in White House
deliberations.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials point to preservation of vast areas of
western lands and regulatory crackdowns as hallmarks of the Clinton
years. But despite early efforts, the administration failed to
achieve a longstanding environmentalists' goal _ raising grazing
and mining fees on federal land, activists note.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he deserves the criticism but it's not so black and
white,'' said Brock Evans, executive director of the Endangered
Species Coalition, who praises Clinton for significant strides in
some areas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would say it's nothing short of a revolution in terms of the
Forest Service. The Northwest forests are in much better shape than
they would have been under his opponents,'' he said, citing
Clinton's three-day forest summit and the subsequent implementation
of the Northwest Forest Plan, which significantly reduced logging
in a reversal of decades-old policies.
</P>
<P>
   Evans, on the other hand, blasts Babbitt's novel system of
negotiating with huge landowners over endangered species
protection, saying the division of land for development and for
habitat inadequately protects wildlife.
</P>
<P>
   ``History may judge this administration as being the worst in
endangered species,'' protection, Evans said.
</P>
<P>
   And groups pushing for restoration of Florida's Everglades were
critical of the administration for not driving a harder bargain
with sugar growers who have been ordered to pay a portion of the $8
billion pricetag to partly restore the marshlands' natural water
flow.
</P>
<P>
   One indicator of Clinton's environmental record is evident in
the criticism from business and industry, which accuse him of
unnecessary regulatory schemes that drive industry's costs up.
</P>
<P>
   ``EPA has enlarged its enforcement powers over the last six
years. For our industry it has been calamitous,'' said Barry
Polsky, a spokesman for the American Forest &AMP; Paper Association,
adding that regulatory action to save the Northwest spotted owl
habitat and the litigation it created had led to an 80 percent
reduction in the timber harvest in the Pacific Northwest.
</P>
<P>
   During the last decade, he said, 13 percent of the paper
industry's capital has been spent on environmental protection, a
figure his trade association predicts will double in the next five
years, ``based on laws and regulations that are now in place or
those that we think are going to be passed.''
</P>
<P>
   A study by the Competitive Enterprise Institute, an
anti-regulation think tank, concluded that during Clinton's first
year in office, the number of Federal Register pages announcing
government actions jumped by 7 percent, and that federal agencies
spent $17.5 billion to police their regulations in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``They seem to evaluate their performance not on how clean the
environment is, but how many people they cite for violations,''
said Fred L. Smith Jr., CEI president.
</P>
<P>
   The administration also has had to defend itself against
industry accusations that agencies have ignored science in their
zeal to implement new regulations.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think they've abused science to scare people to get their
budgets approved or in defense of their regulations,'' said Mark
Whitenton, vice president at the National Manufactures Association,
an opponent of EPA's creeping restrictions on factory emissions.
</P>
<P>
   Administration efforts to appease both sides sometimes have left
both disgruntled. On the dominant issue of climate change,
environmental leaders praise Clinton for raising awareness of the
earth's warming trend, but fault him for surrendering to domestic
pressures against cutting emissions of so-called greenhouse gases,
which result from the burning of fossil fuels.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd hoped they'd be a leader in global warming but in fact
it's all been rhetoric and very little performance,'' said Brent
Blackwelder, president of Friends of the Earth, who holds Clinton
in far greater disdain than many of his environmental colleagues.
</P>
<P>
   Industry on the other hand, is upset that the administration
even signed the 1997 international treaty on climate change,
because it commits the United States to cutting industrial
emissions by 7 percent from 1990 levels by the year 2010, targets
that industry advocates say cannot be met without damaging the
economy. The Senate still must ratify the treaty.
</P>
<P>
   Although some hoped-for legislative overhauls never materialized
_ such as an update of Superfund hazardous waste liability _
environmentalists heralded these actions the Clinton years:
</P>
<P>
   _ Legislative victories on the Safe Drinking Water and Clean
Water amendments.
</P>
<P>
   _ The California Desert Protection Act, which sets aside nearly
7 million acres of California desert, the largest tract of public
land protected outside of Alaska.
</P>
<P>
   _ Creation of Grand Staircase-Escalante National Monument in
Utah.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps no international issue galvanized environmentalists like
the North American Free Trade Agreement that Clinton signed with
Mexico and Canada in 1993 despite activists' objections that it
would promote environmental degradation in border areas. The
conflict continues to play out as Clinton seeks so-called
fast-track authority to ink trade deals without congressional
oversight, a move the environmentalists abhor.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're still on opposite sides,'' said Deborah Sease, Sierra
Club legislative director.
</P>
