<HEADER>
A0087 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CNS-DANCE-TANGO &LR;      05-25 2571
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CNS-DANCE-TANGO </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN TANGO, DANCE IS SENSUAL AND LIFE ITSELF IS THE ART 
</HEADLINE>
   For use by New York Times Syndicate/News Service clients as
desired.  
 By JEANINE PREZIOSO  
 c. 1999 Columbia News Service  
 &HT;    NEW YORK _ She wraps her left arm delicately around his neck,
her hand brushes the side of his cheek. He gazes at her intently
and shifts his weight toward her, firmly placing his hand just
above the small of her back. She leans forward, they raise their
arms in unison, she slips her free hand into his and they began
tracing the intricate steps of a dance shaped by four cultures
spanning three continents.
 &HT;    ``Tango is everything, everything is tango. Life is tango,''
said Carlos Funes, an elderly tango dancer.
 &HT;    Tango has been called the most sensual, complex and intellectual
of all the ballroom dances. It has its roots in Argentina in 1870,
when newly arrived immigrants from Italy, France and Spain saw the
natives dancing the ``candombe'' and added their own flavors and
flair.
 &HT;    ``The tango is more than an intricate dance,'' Jorge I. Oclander
wrote in a profile of the creator of Broadway's 1997 show ``Forever
Tango,'' Luis Bravo. ``It is a feeling, an emotion and the culture
created by the thousands of men who were forced to leave their
homes, their families, their wives and their lovers during the last
25 years of the nineteenth century by the desperate poverty of a
disintegrating Europe.''
 &HT;    Some say the dance was symbolic of the relationship between a
prostitute and her client. The upper body is held stiff. The
movement is from the waist down, only.
 &HT;    While the American idea of tango is as a passionate, mysterious
sensual dance, the Argentinean view is much different. Bravo said
tango is the dance of someone who never finds a home. And it is not
a dance of passionate love, but of lust, born in Argentinean
bordellos.
 &HT;    (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
 &HT;    ``Buenos Aires was a harbor city,'' said Kurt Klestadt, an
American who lived in Argentina for a number of years. ``Ships came
in from overseas and sailors would come in looking for a good time
when they docked.'' It was the sailors and immigrants coupled with
an African influence that gave tango its character, he said.
 &HT;    (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
 &HT;    Over the years the tango has spread from new immigrant
communities to the ballrooms of upper-class Paris and New York
venues. Some of the rougher textures of the dance have been
refined.
 &HT;    A Friday night at La Belle oque, a restaurant named one of the
most romantic places in New York with its Baroque d French wine
list, would be a rich experience without the weekly tango lesson.
But last week, 45 sleek New Yorkers, the women in short black
skirts and high heels, crowded around Tioma ``El Ruso'' Maloratsky
and his Argentinean partner, Viviana Parra, who were holding each
other inches apart as they demonstrated basic tango steps on a
small dance floor.
 &HT;    ``This is one of the only dances where the connection is in the
chest,'' Maloratsky yelled over the buzz of excited first-time
dancers trampling their partners' feet. ``The chest is closer than
anything,'' he said of the distance between partners.
 &HT;    The couples fumbled and bumped their way around the dance floor,
many of them laughing. Maloratsky told the women to balance on the
balls of their feet, leaning forward, their legs slightly behind
their body. As the man takes a step back, the woman follows with
the opposite foot, he said.
 &HT;    Men always lead. ``The best lady dancer is the one who
follows,'' Maloratsky said. ``The woman has to follow the man's
center all the time.'' To demonstrate, he darts around the dance
floor, Parra held close, her eyes to his chest, moving almost as
one.
 &HT;    She said, pointing to the door: ``You let him lead in here. Out
there, it's different.''
 &HT;    The tango came to Paris in the early 1900's. The dance made its
way to New York during World War I, when there were more than 400
tango parlors in the city. After the initial craze, tango parlors
shut down about 30 years ago. New Yorkers were re-introduced to the
dance in the late 1980's when Tango Argentino came to the City
Center with choreographer Juan Carlos Copez, who has been compared
to Fred Astaire and is in the 1998 film ``Tango.''
 &HT;    Maloratsky, 27, is Russian and learned the tango five years ago.
He said when he saw it, he had to do it. He speaks to his partner
in fluent Spanish. Americans would say she is the ideal tango
dancer _ tall, thin and elegant with long dark hair falling down
her back.
 &HT;    Parra, 28, learned the dance five years ago in Argentina. She
came to New York one year ago. She and Maloratsky teach the tango
at Carnegie Hall.
 &HT;    ``It's like in the waltz, cha-cha, salsa, merengue, you can see
very good movement,'' said Parra in a smoldering Argentinean
accent, scraping dust from the soles of her shoes, so she would not
slip. ``But you cannot see all the time the deeper feelings. With
tango the atmosphere is special. I feel that.''
 &HT;    On a recent Tuesday night at Bistro Latino, which has weekly
tango salons or milongas, tango aficionados could be found crowding
the tiny dance floor surrounded by tables. It was a special party
to celebrate ``Tango Magic'' a performance at nearby Carnegie Hall
that night.
 &HT;    The tango salon started after 1986, when the show Tango
Argentino came to New York, said Johnnie Martinez, who is married
to the owner of Steppin' Out, a dance studio that hosted one of the
first tango salons in New York. They hold a salon at Bistro Latino
every Tuesday night.
 &HT;    (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
 &HT;    Sarah LaRocca now teaches three nights a week at Steppin' Out.
She was working as an artist when she met an Argentine tango dancer
in Washington, D.C., quit her job, sold all her furniture and moved
to Argentina to learn the dance. If you ask around, said La Rocca,
you will hear many of the same stories. ``I fell in love with my
instructor,'' she said. ``It's the kind of dance that consumes
people.''
 &HT;    ``When you find the right partner, it's a very deep
connection,'' La Rocca said. ``It's a euphoric feeling and you want
more of that feeling every night. It's like an addiction.''
 &HT;    (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
 &HT;    Diane Lachtrupp owns the studio. She's been teaching the dance
for 10 years. She started to learn tango after she saw Tango
Argentino. ``I saw it and said, 'This is going to be important,' ''
said Lachtrupp. ``The emotion, the poetry of movement is not how we
live our life in America. It's relating to another person. It's
spontaneous conversation.''
 &HT;    Ralph and Phyllis Molaro started taking tango lessons with
Lachtrupp 10 years ago when Lachtrupp had just started teaching.
 &HT;    ``I saw Juan Carlos Copez do it on stage in 'Tango Argentino,'
'' Ralph Molaro, 69, said. ``I said, 'This is what I want to
learn.' ''
 &HT;    ``We used to do the American Tango,'' said his 70-year-old wife,
Phyllis, who was wearing a black sequined dress and rhinestone pin
that spelled out ``tango.'' ``It's the passion of the music, it's
so exciting, you feel every nerve in your body.
 &HT;    ``It hypnotizes you,'' she said. ``These people who dance are so
committed _ they dance every night of the week.''
 &HT;     (EDITORS: Jeanine Prezioso is a master's degree candidate at
the Graduate School of Journalism at Columbia University. There is
no charge for use of this story, but please send a tearsheet to
Prof. Wayne Svoboda, Columbia News Service, Graduate School of
Journalism, Columbia University, 2950 Broadway, New York, N.Y.
10027)   r l
 BC-CNS-DANCE-TANGO  
 IN TANGO, DANCE IS SENSUAL AND LIFE ITSELF IS THE ART  
 For use by New York Times Syndicate/News Service clients as
desired.  
 By JEANINE PREZIOSO  
 c. 1999 Columbia News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ She wraps her left arm delicately around his neck,
her hand brushes the side of his cheek. He gazes at her intently
and shifts his weight toward her, firmly placing his hand just
above the small of her back. She leans forward, they raise their
arms in unison, she slips her free hand into his and they began
tracing the intricate steps of a dance shaped by four cultures
spanning three continents.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tango is everything, everything is tango. Life is tango,''
said Carlos Funes, an elderly tango dancer.
</P>
<P>
   Tango has been called the most sensual, complex and intellectual
of all the ballroom dances. It has its roots in Argentina in 1870,
when newly arrived immigrants from Italy, France and Spain saw the
natives dancing the ``candombe'' and added their own flavors and
flair.
</P>
<P>
   ``The tango is more than an intricate dance,'' Jorge I. Oclander
wrote in a profile of the creator of Broadway's 1997 show ``Forever
Tango,'' Luis Bravo. ``It is a feeling, an emotion and the culture
created by the thousands of men who were forced to leave their
homes, their families, their wives and their lovers during the last
25 years of the nineteenth century by the desperate poverty of a
disintegrating Europe.''
</P>
<P>
   Some say the dance was symbolic of the relationship between a
prostitute and her client. The upper body is held stiff. The
movement is from the waist down, only.
</P>
<P>
   While the American idea of tango is as a passionate, mysterious
sensual dance, the Argentinean view is much different. Bravo said
tango is the dance of someone who never finds a home. And it is not
a dance of passionate love, but of lust, born in Argentinean
bordellos.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ``Buenos Aires was a harbor city,'' said Kurt Klestadt, an
American who lived in Argentina for a number of years. ``Ships came
in from overseas and sailors would come in looking for a good time
when they docked.'' It was the sailors and immigrants coupled with
an African influence that gave tango its character, he said.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Over the years the tango has spread from new immigrant
communities to the ballrooms of upper-class Paris and New York
venues. Some of the rougher textures of the dance have been
refined.
</P>
<P>
   A Friday night at La Belle poque, a restaurant named one of the
most romantic places in New York with its Baroque dnd French wine
list, would be a rich experience without the weekly tango lesson.
But last week, 45 sleek New Yorkers, the women in short black
skirts and high heels, crowded around Tioma ``El Ruso'' Maloratsky
and his Argentinean partner, Viviana Parra, who were holding each
other inches apart as they demonstrated basic tango steps on a
small dance floor.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is one of the only dances where the connection is in the
chest,'' Maloratsky yelled over the buzz of excited first-time
dancers trampling their partners' feet. ``The chest is closer than
anything,'' he said of the distance between partners.
</P>
<P>
   The couples fumbled and bumped their way around the dance floor,
many of them laughing. Maloratsky told the women to balance on the
balls of their feet, leaning forward, their legs slightly behind
their body. As the man takes a step back, the woman follows with
the opposite foot, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Men always lead. ``The best lady dancer is the one who
follows,'' Maloratsky said. ``The woman has to follow the man's
center all the time.'' To demonstrate, he darts around the dance
floor, Parra held close, her eyes to his chest, moving almost as
one.
</P>
<P>
   She said, pointing to the door: ``You let him lead in here. Out
there, it's different.''
</P>
<P>
   The tango came to Paris in the early 1900's. The dance made its
way to New York during World War I, when there were more than 400
tango parlors in the city. After the initial craze, tango parlors
shut down about 30 years ago. New Yorkers were re-introduced to the
dance in the late 1980's when Tango Argentino came to the City
Center with choreographer Juan Carlos Copez, who has been compared
to Fred Astaire and is in the 1998 film ``Tango.''
</P>
<P>
   Maloratsky, 27, is Russian and learned the tango five years ago.
He said when he saw it, he had to do it. He speaks to his partner
in fluent Spanish. Americans would say she is the ideal tango
dancer _ tall, thin and elegant with long dark hair falling down
her back.
</P>
<P>
   Parra, 28, learned the dance five years ago in Argentina. She
came to New York one year ago. She and Maloratsky teach the tango
at Carnegie Hall.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like in the waltz, cha-cha, salsa, merengue, you can see
very good movement,'' said Parra in a smoldering Argentinean
accent, scraping dust from the soles of her shoes, so she would not
slip. ``But you cannot see all the time the deeper feelings. With
tango the atmosphere is special. I feel that.''
</P>
<P>
   On a recent Tuesday night at Bistro Latino, which has weekly
tango salons or milongas, tango aficionados could be found crowding
the tiny dance floor surrounded by tables. It was a special party
to celebrate ``Tango Magic'' a performance at nearby Carnegie Hall
that night.
</P>
<P>
   The tango salon started after 1986, when the show Tango
Argentino came to New York, said Johnnie Martinez, who is married
to the owner of Steppin' Out, a dance studio that hosted one of the
first tango salons in New York. They hold a salon at Bistro Latino
every Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Sarah LaRocca now teaches three nights a week at Steppin' Out.
She was working as an artist when she met an Argentine tango dancer
in Washington, D.C., quit her job, sold all her furniture and moved
to Argentina to learn the dance. If you ask around, said La Rocca,
you will hear many of the same stories. ``I fell in love with my
instructor,'' she said. ``It's the kind of dance that consumes
people.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When you find the right partner, it's a very deep
connection,'' La Rocca said. ``It's a euphoric feeling and you want
more of that feeling every night. It's like an addiction.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Diane Lachtrupp owns the studio. She's been teaching the dance
for 10 years. She started to learn tango after she saw Tango
Argentino. ``I saw it and said, 'This is going to be important,' ''
said Lachtrupp. ``The emotion, the poetry of movement is not how we
live our life in America. It's relating to another person. It's
spontaneous conversation.''
</P>
<P>
   Ralph and Phyllis Molaro started taking tango lessons with
Lachtrupp 10 years ago when Lachtrupp had just started teaching.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw Juan Carlos Copez do it on stage in 'Tango Argentino,'
'' Ralph Molaro, 69, said. ``I said, 'This is what I want to
learn.' ''
</P>
<P>
   ``We used to do the American Tango,'' said his 70-year-old wife,
Phyllis, who was wearing a black sequined dress and rhinestone pin
that spelled out ``tango.'' ``It's the passion of the music, it's
so exciting, you feel every nerve in your body.
</P>
<P>
   ``It hypnotizes you,'' she said. ``These people who dance are so
committed _ they dance every night of the week.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITORS: Jeanine Prezioso is a master's degree candidate at
the Graduate School of Journalism at Columbia University. There is
no charge for use of this story, but please send a tearsheet to
Prof. Wayne Svoboda, Columbia News Service, Graduate School of
Journalism, Columbia University, 2950 Broadway, New York, N.Y.
10027) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
