<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-25 10:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0088 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CNS-VIOLENT-WORKERS &LR;      05-25 2420
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CNS-VIOLENT-WORKERS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORKPLACE VIOLENCE OFTEN STRIKES BEFORE EMPLOYERS ACT 
</HEADLINE>
   For use by New York Times Syndicate/News Service clients as
desired.  
 By VIOLET LAW  
 c. 1999 Columbia News Service  
 &HT;    NEW YORK _ In Amagansett, N.Y., an employee angered by a late
paycheck karate-chopped a comptroller at a medical publishing
company, breaking her jaw and all but four teeth.
 &HT;    In Research Triangle Park, N.C., a scientist threw a typewriter
at a security guard who was trying to stop him from removing
property from the office.
 &HT;    In Mesa, Ariz., a supervisor for a manufacturing company was
waiting by the printer in the human resources office, when a
production worker walked in and pointed a 9-millimeter
semiautomatic at him.
 &HT;    Luckily, that supervisor managed to knock the gun out of his
hands. The worker was subsequently charged with aggravated assault.
The company, TRW Vehicular Safety System, wasted no time hiring
Lynne McClure, a management consultant specializing in workplace
violence intervention, to conduct a workshop for the management
staff.
 &HT;    At the end of the five-day workshop, McClure recalled, the
supervisor who had been confronted with the gun walked up to her
and said, ``If we'd brought you in earlier, the incident wouldn't
have gone this far.''
 &HT;    Workplace violence is nothing new, even though more often than
not, only homicides at work make headlines. In fact, other violent
incidents, such as simple assaults, aggravated assaults _ those
involving weapons _ and rapes, are far more common.
 &HT;    According to a special report on workplace violence published
last summer by the Bureau of Justice Statistics, there were 396,000
aggravated assaults and almost 1.5 million simple assaults at work
between 1992 and 1996, compared with 1,000 homicides for the same
period. A previous report tabulated close to 880,000 assaults of
any kind between 1987 and 1992.
 &HT;    For both periods, half of the violent crimes were committed by
someone unknown to the victim and another 30 percent were committed
by acquaintances, including friends, roommates, neighbors or other
employees. Researchers have cited increased stress level and
anxiety about downsizing as the main factors that provoke employees
to act out at work.
 &HT;    ``The job insecurity is the baseline for violence,'' said
Heather O'Brien, formerly a human resource director of a global
technology company who didn't want the name of the company in print
because she doesn't work there any more.
 &HT;    During her two-decade tenure, O'Brien met countless human
resource managers from manufacturing, technology and service
industries, whose attitude toward workplace violence, for the most
part, she would characterize as complacent.
 &HT;    ``Many of them think, 'It can't happen to us,' '' she said.
 &HT;    After processing numerous worker compensation claims involving
hitting, kicking, pinching and biting among co-workers, Christine
McGovern of Ohio Casualty Group, a corporate insurance company,
started in 1997 to offer for free a violence prevention program to
help her clients.
 &HT;    ``There are a lot of businesses concerned about workplace
violence,'' said McGovern, director of the program, ``but they
haven't done anything about it, or don't know what to do about
it.''
 &HT;    Recently, McGovern said a man employed by one of her clients was
hit by a co-worker with a chair after passing over that co-worker
for a promotion. Another client reported that two employees who
filed papers together in a small cubicle ended up exchanging
insults and punches.
 &HT;    ``Non-fatal incidents like these can escalate into situations
that become dangerous,'' she said. ``But most employers are very
reactive,'' not seeing the need to prevent violence until a crisis
strikes.
 &HT;    ``We're training workers to be highly skilled in math,
computers, calibration,'' said O'Brien, summing up her observations
in the technology industry, ``but we're not giving them the
psychological training to help them identify dysfunctional or
violent behaviors.'' That's why she decided to team up with
McClure, author of ``Risky Business: Managing Employee Violence in
the Workplace'' (1996), to develop violence prevention workshops.
 &HT;    Still, most employers do not call for expert help until they
have experienced what TRW did _ a life-threatening violent
incident. But McClure, the Tempe, Arizona-based expert hired by
TRW, believes in early intervention. ``Managers can tell very early
when a person becomes violent,'' McClure said. ``People act in
small ways before they become violent.''
 &HT;    With almost 20 years of experience in violence consultation,
McClure has developed a system that identifies eight different
patterns of behaviors commonly found in people with a proclivity to
violence. The tendency to over-react to people or situations, or to
experience exaggerated mood swings, are some of the behaviors that
McClurg thinks should cause concern. She coaches managers on how to
match their observations with the patterns. Taking into account the
intensity and frequency in which an employee exhibits the
behaviors, managers should refer the employee in question for
counseling as soon as possible.
 &HT;    ``You can't wait until the violent incident occurs;'' said David
Nichols, the TRW human resource person who sought McClurg's help
after the incident. ``You have to detect the problematic behaviors
early on and deal with them.'' He said McClurg's system could help
the managers and supervisors in his company to discern between
occasional violent outbursts and significant violent behaviors,
which demand immediate action.
 &HT;    Like TRW, more and more employers have awakened to the
prevalence of workplace violence, as consultants and researchers in
violence prevention point out.
 &HT;    ``In the wake of more incidents of workplace violence and
associated concerns regarding both safety and lawsuits, it appears
that more employers are indeed developing policies and protocols,''
said Roland D. Maiuro, director of Workplace Conflict Program at
University of Washington in Seattle and editor-in-chief of the
Journal of Violence and Victims.
 &HT;    Indeed, Steven Kaufer, co-founder and consultant of the
for-profit Workplace Violence Research Institute has noticed that
most companies are now taking threats of violence more seriously
than ever. He recalled an employer anxiously calling him up for
advice after a recently fired senior manager went around handing
out bullets printed with names and death threats.
 &HT;    ``People now understand that in a workplace threats also make up
workplace violence,'' Kaufer said.
 &HT;    But McClure thinks workplace violence is only a small of a
bigger problem. ``Our whole culture is getting more violent,'' she
said, ``and it's getting reflected at work.''
 &HT;     (EDITORS: Violet Law is a master's degree candidate at the
Graduate School of Journalism at Columbia University. There is no
charge for use of this story, but please send a tearsheet to Prof.
Wayne Svoboda, Columbia News Service, Graduate School of
Journalism, Columbia University, 2950 Broadway, New York, N.Y.
10027)   r l
