<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-25 10:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0103 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BIKE-HELMET-SAFETY26-     05-25 1147
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIKE-HELMET-SAFETY26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SCIENCE/HEALTH: After life-threatening accident, teen, family
promote use of bike helmets
 &HT;    By Kevin Lamb
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ The story began with the brakes locking on Jeff
Pence's borrowed bicycle, causing it to cartwheel him through the
air and onto his head.
</P>
<P>
   It almost ended there, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody agreed he would not have made it off the ground if
he hadn't been wearing a helmet,'' Judy Pence says.
</P>
<P>
   Her son would not have spent those 12 days he'll never remember
at the Children's Medical Center, fighting for his life with a
skull fracture that sheared some brain tissue, oblivious to the
gravely whispered warnings that terrified his parents, Judy and
Don. ``I never thought our life could change so quickly,'' said
Judy, who was vacationing in Lebanon, Ohio with friends at the
time.
</P>
<P>
   He also would not have spent the next year defying doctors'
forecasts by earning straight A's in his seventh-grade program for
gifted students, playing basketball and baseball and touting the
value of bicycle safety helmets on behalf of officials in both Ohio
and Florida, where the Pences live in Naples.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of all the things we see, the head injuries are absolutely the
worst,'' says Dr. Robert Pretzlaff, an intensive-care specialist at
Children's. ``Because they leave people with everything working
except the head.''
</P>
<P>
   Bike mishaps are the most common cause of serious head injuries
to children, the Southern Medical Journal reported in March, and
kill nearly 600 a year nationally. Although researchers have
determined that 85 percent of head injuries could be prevented by
helmets, an observational study in 1995 found only one in 20
children riding a bike wore a helmet.
</P>
<P>
   So Jeff's story evolved to Judy's self-published book, which
began as a memoir for the family of four and turned into a moving
testimonial for bike helmets. A Helmet Away From Heaven is written
for adults and kids 10 and older. The book then led to a
school-oriented video called What If, narrated by Jeff and aimed at
kids 9 to 15 and their parents.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've seen them all, and this is probably the best video on the
market,'' says Jim Neary, a recently retired safety officer at
Children's. It tells everything from a child's standpoint, also.''
</P>
<P>
   Now 13, Jeff was within a month of his 12th birthday that July
afternoon in 1997. The Pences had been in Lebanon just a couple of
hours when Jeff went for a bike ride with their adult host, who
``tossed me the ugliest helmet I had ever seen, a plain white
one.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeff's mother first thought the paramedics overreacted when they
ordered the CareFlight helicopter to the rural neighborhood where
he lay on the ground, unconscious and occasionally twitching. But
as a physical therapist in a neurology practice, Pence understood
all too well the explanations she would hear at the hospital.
</P>
<P>
   The heart of his brain's speech and memory sections had been
damaged. Jeff almost certainly would have to relearn how to
communicate, and there was concern that his memory might always be
impaired. But first he had to survive.
</P>
<P>
   For three days, his brain pressure measured in the 40s. ``Normal
is well under 10,'' Pence says. His injured brain had swelled like
an injured ankle.
</P>
<P>
   The equivalent of a cast to immobilize the brain was to put Jeff
in a drug-induced coma. ``They wanted his brain to have no
stimulation so it could heal,'' Pence says. ``They didn't even want
an eyebrow to move.''
</P>
<P>
   Even after he came out of eight days in a coma, his legs would
shake spastically and his eyes would roll in different directions.
Doctors worried that even after recovering otherwise, Jeff's
spasticity and double vision would linger.
</P>
<P>
   After 12 days at Children's, Jeff was able to sit up without
being supported and stay awake for 10 minutes at a time, so he
traveled by ambulance to the nearest inpatient pediatric
rehabilitation center, Children's Hospital Medical Center in
Cincinnati. Doctors who first examined him there on a Thursday
expected him to stay three to four weeks.
</P>
<P>
   But he started walking with help on Friday and independently on
Saturday. When Pence woke up Sunday morning, she was amazed to see
Jeff reading. His eyes were as good as ever. His legs no longer
twitched from muscle contractions.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff underwent speech therapy, cognitive testing and memory
exercises. He shot baskets to regain his coordination and played
catch with a tennis ball. ``It was kind of hard to catch it,'' he
says, without his hands moving quite where he wanted them, but that
Monday he was walking backwards on a balance beam, only five days
after he had not been able to sit up by himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got lost in the tunnels of the hospital on Monday and he
said, `Mom, take a left here,' `` Pence says. ``So it wasn't long
before his memory was better than mine again.''
</P>
<P>
   By Wednesday, he would check out of the hospital and ride with
his mother back to Dayton, where people greeted him with tears in
their wide eyes.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff and his younger sister had grown up always wearing helmets
when they biked at home. ``The most important thing in this whole
process is the parent made the kid wear a helmet,'' says Neary, who
knows five or six healthy children who would be dead now if they
hadn't worn bike helmets.
</P>
<P>
   In three cases, the parents made the child wear the helmet. In
another instance, Neary knows of a father who gave in and let his
son ride without one, 15 minutes before his fatal accident.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm 36, and I remember getting a new car with seat belts when
I grew up,'' Pence says. ``In our other car, we hopped back and
forth from the front seat to the back seat. I remember lying out in
the sun with baby oil for a better tan. I remember being introduced
to this new thing called a car seat for babies.''
</P>
<P>
   She hopes people will soon look back the same way at the days
when kids didn't wear bike helmets. It's coming slowly, Neary says.
The social acceptability of helmets isn't dwindling, but it hasn't
increased much in 10 years, either. ``That's what's discouraging,''
he says.
</P>
<P>
   Pence and Neary agree the impetus has to come from parents.
That's why Pence urges school districts that buy her bike-safety
video to also show it at parents' meetings.
</P>
<P>
   ``It touches on why you wear a helmet, what it protects and that
you're not a nerd if you wear one,'' Neary says. ``We still get
100-odd children in the hospital with bike injuries every year and
maybe four or five were wearing helmets. This video does a good job
of telling children, `It's important that you wear a helmet, and
don't care what anybody else thinks about it.' ``
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Lamb writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
E-mail: kevinlamb(AT)coxohio.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
