<HEADER>
A0104 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-HARRICK-ASSIST26-     05-25 0577
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-HARRICK-ASSIST26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Two assistants survive cut under new coach
 &HT;    By Chip Towers
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATHENS, Ga. _ Michael Hunt has lived in six cities the past 11
years. And he nearly made it seven in 11, had new Georgia
basketball coach Jim Harrick decided not to retain him on his staff
one month ago.
</P>
<P>
   Such is the life of a college assistant basketball coach. While
head coaches can live for years off the income from their
guaranteed contracts, assistant coaches work on year-to-year
agreements and risk not being able to take care of their families.
</P>
<P>
   For that reason, Hunt, 38, considered giving up a promising
career in the game he loves so much.
</P>
<P>
   ``The toughest part of being an assistant coach is you have to
move to achieve your goals, which is to one day be a head coach,''
Hunt said. ``After (Ron Jirsa's firing), I wasn't sure if I could
just yank up my family and tear apart their lives again. We came to
Athens with a plan to be here a lot longer than two years. My kids
really like it here and my wife had adapted well. I wasn't sure I
could put them through that again.''
</P>
<P>
   Hunt was offered at least one coaching opportunity, a head
coaching job at North Florida Community College but turned it down.
He was also considering outside opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately for Hunt, a career change was not in order. On April
22, Harrick said he was retaining Hunt and fellow Jirsa assistant
Reggie Rankin on his new staff. They were joined later on Harrick's
staff by former San Diego State assistant James Holland and former
UCLA player Cameron Dollar.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a big relief knowing my family wouldn't have to move
and start over again,'' Hunt said.
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Waters, 55, was not so lucky. Waters, who gave up his
stable, 17-year job as South Carolina-Spartanburg's coach to join
Jirsa's staff two years ago, found himself as Georgia's odd man
out. He made a quiet campaign to succeed Jirsa as head coach and,
ultimately, has instead found himself out of a job.
</P>
<P>
   The experience has left Waters bitter and disenchanted with
coaching on the Division I level.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's cutthroat, regardless of what administrators want you to
think,'' said Waters, who has returned to college to get
re-certified as a teacher. ``They talk about graduation rates,
developing character, gender equity, all that stuff. When it comes
down to it, it's about money and winning.''
</P>
<P>
   Contributing to the angst of Georgia's assistants was the rather
awkward circumstances they found themselves in during the
transition period between coaching staffs. While they were hired by
Jirsa, their contracts ran through June, so they were obligated to
continue working for Georgia, even though Harrick had already been
hired and their future in Athens was in question.
</P>
<P>
   And Harrick left them little work to do. With little time to
ponder staff decisions and the spring recruiting period running
out, Harrick chose to handle most of the recruiting himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I explained that to them,'' Harrick said. ``I said, `Right now
you don't have a job and you're going to have to interview to get
one.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Waters' son Jason has just received a master's degree
in sports management and wants to become a basketball coach. Waters
is torn about his son's choice of vocation. ``In a way, I hope he's
spared the anguish,'' Waters said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
