<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-25 10:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0105 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-HARRICK26-COX     05-25 1410
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-HARRICK26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Pieces coming together for Georgia's Harrick
 &HT;    (EDS: Runs w/BKC-HARRICK-ASSIST)
 &HT;    By Chip Towers
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATHENS, Ga. _ Jim Harrick is still trying to find his sense of
direction.
</P>
<P>
   For the past two months, the new Georgia basketball coach's
``home'' has been Room 501 at the Georgia Center for Continuing
Education, the university's hotel and conference center. He's
scheduled to move out next month _ ``They're going to put up a
plaque in there in my memory,'' Harrick cracks _ as he and wife,
Sally, finally closed last week on a beautiful house on the west
side of town. Until a few days ago, however, he was telling people
it was on the east side.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm still finding my way around,'' Harrick says.
</P>
<P>
   That's understandable considering the first day Harrick laid
eyes on the city of Athens was the day he was announced as the
Bulldogs' new coach. Despite a longtime friendship with former
Georgia coach Hugh Durham and nearly 30 years in the college
coaching business, Harrick hadn't had cause to visit the ``Classic
City'' and didn't bother to do so before making the life-altering
decision that sent him here.
</P>
<P>
   And in the 53 days since starting his new job, Harrick has spent
little time in Athens, or any other city for that matter. Before
the spring recruiting period ended last weekend, Harrick's world
consisted of an endless stream of airport terminals, cramped
coaches' offices, gymnasiums and hotel rooms.
</P>
<P>
   It's only of late that Harrick has been able to slow down long
enough to survey his new surroundings.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been really hard, the first month or so,'' says Harrick,
who was named the Bulldogs' 19th men's basketball coach on March
31. ``Everything was so unsettled, not having a staff in place,
trying to recruit and trying set up the schedule. You try to put
your stamp on everything, which means your doing everything all by
yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   Including recruit. With Ron Jirsa's assistants still on payroll
but their futures in limbo, Harrick hit the road himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought if I was going to ask somebody to come play for me
at Georgia, they'd want to be recruited by me. So I just kind of
handled everything myself,'' Harrick says.
</P>
<P>
   That proved to be a successful formula. Despite the controversy
derived from his momentary indecision to accept the Georgia job and
having just over a month to locate, recruit and sign prospects,
Harrick managed to ink a pair of 6-foot-7 junior college
All-Americans _ Shon Coleman and Anthony Evans _ who are expected
to shore up the Bulldogs' shaky inside game.
</P>
<P>
   Recruiting is something Harrick takes very seriously and
apparently does very well.
</P>
<P>
   ``Recruiting is your lifeblood,'' he says. ``People ask you how
you're doing during the season and you say nothing a couple of wins
couldn't cure. Well, in recruiting, there's nothing a couple of
recruits couldn't cure.''
</P>
<P>
   Georgia's 1999 recruiting class has received national acclaim
and was ranked as high as ninth in the country by one recruiting
service. And Harrick insists he's not through.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're talking to our contacts in Europe, Asia and Africa,''
Harrick says, only half joking.
</P>
<P>
   Because he has been on the go since his arrival, most Georgians
have little knowledge of Harrick beyond the single-paragraph
biographies that have been offered in newspaper accounts of his
hiring.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, most people do not realize Harrick is an English
teacher by trade. He spent 10 years in the California education
system as a teacher, coach and administrator. And so it follows
that he is a voracious reader, recently switching his tastes from
non-fiction to fiction and digesting the works Robert Ludlum, Tom
Clancy, Sidney Sheldon and Bob Tannenbaum, the former New York City
district attorney and mayor of Beverly Hills who also happens to be
Harrick's personal attorney.
</P>
<P>
   Harrick and his wife Sally were high school sweethearts, have
been married 38 years and have three sons, Monte, 36, Jim, 34 and
Glenn, 30. Both Harrick and Sally graduated from Stonewall Jackson
High School in Charleston, W.Va., and have been married 38 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's really a Southerner,'' Georgia athletics director Vince
Dooley points out. ``People tend to think of him as a Californian
because he spent so much time out there, but he's not. He's a
Southerner and he speaks the language very well.''
</P>
<P>
   The third-generation grandson of Lebanese immigrants, Harrick's
father was an entrepeneur who ran a hotel in Charleston, W.Va., and
owned a restaurant, Harrick's Grill. ``We struggled a little but we
always had everything we needed,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Harrick played college basketball at the now-defunct University
of Charleston (now known as Morris Harvey). ``I was a horrible
player,'' he confesses, ``but a good student of the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Harrick's hobbies include golf, tennis and racquetball, but he
does a lot less of the latter two since entering the sixth decade
of his life.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a good guy, a fun guy to be around,'' says Durham, who's
been friends with Harrick since his early days at UCLA. ``He's a
competitor, I'm telling you. We had some hellacious racquetball
matches.''
</P>
<P>
   Durham says Harrick is also an exceptional basketball coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no reason to believe he won't be successful at
Georgia,'' the Bulldogs' all-time winningest coach says. ``He's
gotten it done at Rhode Island, UCLA and Pepperdine. He'll get it
done there.''
</P>
<P>
   Harrick has a trivia question he likes to ask basketball fans at
the many banquets and booster club functions he attends throughout
the spring and summer.
</P>
<P>
   How many Division I coaches have won national championships at
two different schools? Invariably, it stumps the panel.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a trick question,'' Harrick says with a devious grin.
``There aren't any. Never been done.''
</P>
<P>
   That fact, more than any other, can be attributed to Harrick's
presence in Athens. One day, he wants the answer to that question
to be ``Jim Harrick.'' He already won a national championship at
UCLA in 1995, and he believes he can achieve that feat at the
University of Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   Really.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got a great university, a university of the highest
quality, it's in a wonderful area, it's got the resources to help
you succeed, it's got a great recruiting base and you're competing
in the SEC,'' Harrick says.
</P>
<P>
   ``There not many coaches I know that don't want to play for all
the marbles and you have a much better chance of doing that here.''
</P>
<P>
   But coming to Georgia wasn't that simple for Harrick. In what is
now an infamous bout of indecision, Harrick had second _ then third
_ thoughts about accepting the Georgia job. The morning after a
nationally-televised press conference announcing his hiring by the
Bulldogs, Harrick told UGA President Michael Adams he had decided
instead to remain at Rhode Island. After returning to Providence
that afternoon, he changed his mind again and decided to return to
Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   Harrick now jokes about it in his banquet-room speeches _ ``not
many guys can make the people in two states mad,'' he quips _ but,
in reality, it was no laughing matter. With two months to reflect
on the situation, Harrick attributes the indecision to family ties,
professional loyalty to Rhode Island and the small window of time
Georgia gave him to make a decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``In business, or when you're hiring university presidents or
ADs, they go through a screening process, they're interviewed three
or four times and a committee decides who's hired. In athletics, in
most cases, it tends to be a 24-, 48- or 72-hour decision,''
Harrick says. ``I had a son on my staff (at Rhode Island) and my
youngest son had just moved to Providence and was building a house.
You have a feeling that you're turning your back on people and I
struggled with that.''
</P>
<P>
   At times, Harrick confesses, he still agonizes over his
decision. ``But that's subsiding each day.''
</P>
<P>
   So the real question would seem to be, why come to Georgia?
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it was the lure of the SEC, competing against the
best,'' Harrick says. ``You want to go out and recruit players to
play in the best conference and compete at the highest level and
you can do that at Georgia.''
</P>
<P>
   Now Harrick will find out if he can win there as well.
</P>
<P>
   Chip Towers writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
