<P>
   Foreign editor Rick Christie, 202-887-8316, rickd(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   Bureau chief Andy Alexander, 202-887-8334, andya(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   TEEPEN-COLUMN _ The short story, as I recollect it, was set in a
future where time travel had become possible. A fellow signed up to
tour the primeval past and, like others, was cautioned to remain on
the floating path and to touch nothing, because even the smallest
alteration in the past could have huge consequences. He made the
trip and marveled at the exotic plants and creatures of an era
beyond reckoning. He scrupulously stayed on the path, but returned
to his own time to find everything changed grotesquely, and in no
way for the better. Puzzled, he sat down, only to discover, from
the evidence on his shoe sole, that in the ancient past he had
stepped on a butterfly. (Teepen, Cox Newspapers) MOVED MONDAY.
</P>
<P>
   KLEINBERG-COLUMN _ This is a private message to the State
Department: I know you are quite tied up with that Kosovo stuff,
but I also know you have the best interests of American citizens at
heart and would want to be informed about this. Hundreds of
Americans are being kidnapped daily in foreign cities, notably in
the Mediterranean rim. MOVED MONDAY.
</P>
<P>
   SCHUETT-COLUMN _ GIBSONBURG, Ohio _ This column is for readers
without any teenagers of their own. So that no one feels left out
of the annual ``school's almost out'' frenzy, I shall generously
share my kids with you. I have 60 of them and they're all in the
8th grade. I teach English. It's not a pretty job, but somebody's
gotta' do it. (Schuett, Cox News Service). MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
