(Carter, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED SUNDAY.
</P>
<P>
   TESTDRIVE-MUSTANG _ Russ test drives the new Mustang (DeVault)
(DeVault, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: This story moved Friday 5/21 to coincide with the Mustang's
35th anniversary.
</P>
<P>
   PERSONAL FINANCE
</P>
<P>
   MONEYTALK _ Column will not move this week.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT/ARTS
</P>
<P>
   MASTERPIECE-RECREATIONS _ HOGANSVILLE, Ga. _ Van Gogh's
``Sunflowers'' really catches the afternoon light. ``Mona Lisa''
smiles enigmatically as ever. Surprised to find them in a
stripped-down storefront on a small-town Georgia Main Street
otherwise given over to antiques emporiums? These and 65 other
``masterpieces'' are here in a place that celebrates artifice, the
International Art Museum of Re-Creations. If you think the notion
of a museum with a collection of fake masterpieces is strange, it's
no less odd than how it came to be located in Hogansville, 55 miles
southwest of downtown Atlanta. (Hamilton, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED. WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE
</P>
<P>
   BIKE-HELMET-SAFETY _ DAYTON, Ohio _ The story began with the
brakes locking on Jeff Pence's borrowed bicycle, causing it to
cartwheel him through the air and onto his head. It almost ended
there, too. ``Everybody agreed he would not have made it off the
ground if he hadn't been wearing a helmet,'' Judy Pence says. Her
son would not have spent those 12 days he'll never remember in the
hospital, fighting for his life with a skull fracture that sheared
some brain tissue. ``I never thought our life could change so
quickly,'' said Judy. He also would not have spent the next year
defying doctors' forecasts by earning straight A's in his
seventh-grade program for gifted students, playing basketball and
baseball and touting the value of bicycle safety helmets on behalf
of officials in both Ohio and Florida, where the Pences live in
Naples. So Jeff's story evolved to Judy's self-published book,
which began as a memoir for the family of four and turned into a
moving testimonial for bike helmets. A Helmet Away From Heaven is
written for adults and kids 10 and older. The book then led to a
school-oriented video called What If, narrated by Jeff and aimed at
kids 9 to 15 and their parents. (Lamb, Dayton Daily News) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   ATTENTION: Florida, Ohio editors.
</P>
<P>
   BABYNAMES - The baby names of the new millennium are definitely
not Jennifer and Michael. Think Zena and Zavion. (Grantham, Palm
Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
