<TEXT>
<P>
   DISPATCHES FROM DREAMSVILLE: Childhood memories of the piney
woods
</P>
<P>
   (''Dispatches from Dreamsville'' is an occasional series in
which readers share with Cox Newspapers senior writer Joe Murray
their memories of growing up in small-town America. Back then, or
at least the way we remember it, life was like a dream.)
</P>
<P>
   By Carrie Hestand
</P>
<P>
   Special to Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   My father's family had a small farm in Louisiana, but when he
and my mother married, he went to work for a lumber company for a
dollar a day.
</P>
<P>
   We lived in a two-room cabin that could be put on a railroad
flatcar and easily moved through the Louisiana forests as my
father's job moved. I guess that would be called an employee
benefit today.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, my father's job was to cut down those beautiful long leaf
pine trees. There is no way I can fully describe those pine woods
of my childhood, how beautiful they were.
</P>
<P>
   I have to say that the lumber companies did replant the forests.
The loblolly pines we know today are beautiful, and they help save
the soil.
</P>
<P>
   They keep growing to provide a crop for the paper mills and
that's important, too, but I feel sorry for all the people who
never got to see those majestic long leaf pines that used to grow
there.
</P>
<P>
   My brothers and I and the children of the other lumber workers
had a wonderful playground there in the piney woods, and I'll
always be grateful for that experience.
</P>
<P>
   The first time I remember us being loaded on the railroad car to
move, I was barely two years old -- but I already knew how to pray.
</P>
<P>
   My two oldest brothers were old enough to go to school at that
time. They rode to school in a wagon pulled by two mules and driven
by a boy whom they had had fights with.
</P>
<P>
   You might say there was strong mutual dislike. The boy refused
to stop at our house, so my brothers would get a running start and
leap onto the back of the moving wagon.
</P>
<P>
   The mules were named Rock and Kate, but I always thought they
were called ``Rotten Cake.'' I couldn't understand why those people
would give their mules such a weird name.
</P>
<P>
   The times weren't easy, but I guess we were just too young to
know it. We thought we had a great life.
</P>
<P>
   (Mrs. Carrie Hestand is a widow, a great-grandmother and a
retired seamstress who makes her home in Gladewater, Texas.)
</P>
<P>
   (If you have a story to share, send it to ``Dispatches from
Dreamsville,'' c/o Joe Murray, Cox Newspapers, P.O. Box 151108,
Lufkin, Texas, 75915. A photo of the writer is optional. If your
article is used, you will receive $25. For other Dreamsville
stories, visit htt://www.geocities.com/SoHo/Bistro/7147.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
