<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-25 10:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0113 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RETIREMENT-HAVEN26-CO     05-25 0966
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RETIREMENT-HAVEN26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Retirement mecca status faltering
 &HT;    By Douglas Belkin
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Call the Department of Elder Affairs in
Tallahassee to inquire about retiring to Florida _ as thousands of
out-of-staters do every year _ and you're not going to hear about
sugar-sand beaches, emerald golf courses or the army of senior care
experts and institutions here to care for you if you falter.
</P>
<P>
   But you will be warned of what you might be giving up:
government benefits, four seasons, proximity to your family.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not as negative as it sounds,'' said Louise Engle, an
information resource coordinator at the department. ``We just want
to make sure people understand they may be getting some benefits
where they are now that they won't be getting here . . . and to
understand that this is a different way of life.''
</P>
<P>
   Call Arizona, Mississippi, Alabama or Texas and you'll get an
altogether different response _ a come-hither sales pitch worthy of
Dale Carnegie.
</P>
<P>
   In the world of retirement destinations, Florida is still the
800-pound gorilla, but things are changing and the Sunshine State
will likely not be the de facto choice for Baby Boomers that it was
for their parents and grandparents. In 1990, Florida landed eight
communities among the top 25 in Retirement Places Rated. In the
fifth and latest edition, due for release this week, it posted just
five. Boca Raton was the highest rated at No. 6.
</P>
<P>
   Blame decades of sprawl, comparably high crime rates and a
creeping cost of living, author David Savageau said.
</P>
<P>
   And just as importantly, blame competition. Retirees vote with
their feet. Of the 450,000 seniors aged 60 and older who moved to
Florida from 1985 to1990, 128,000 left, according to Charles
Longino's book Retirement Migration in America. Florida may be the
foremost retirement state, but along with New York, Illinois and
Michigan, it is also among the states from which the greatest
number of retirees leave. Northerners who come here and then take
off have even earned their own name: halfbacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``A halfback is someone who moves from New England or New York
or Cleveland, down to Florida, becomes disillusioned and instead of
returning home, moves halfway back to the Carolinas or Alabama,''
explains Savageau. ``Believe me, there are a lot of states that are
marketing to those seniors.''
</P>
<P>
   That marketing includes the 75,000 magazines sent out of state
to anybody who calls Arizona's Office for Senior Living. An army of
telemarketers tout Mississippi's good graces to prospective
retirees and Pennsylvania's Silver and Gold Magazine gets sent out
to 100,000 senior citizens statewide. Tennessee, South Carolina,
Georgia, Alabama, Texas and even Maine are all following suit.
</P>
<P>
   Florida's pitch? Think twice. It's really hot down here in the
summer.
</P>
<P>
   It's not as if Florida is about to be supplanted as the nation's
retirement mecca anytime soon. A list of the boons retirees have
brought here compared with the rest of the nation is laughably
lopsided. Between 1985 and 1990, the net annual retirement income
transferred here from other states was $6.5 billion, according to
Retirement Migration in America. Retirees who moved to Arizona, the
No. 2 beneficiary of retirement income, brought just a sixth of
that.
</P>
<P>
   But the financial impact could be felt down the line if the
wealthiest retirees are lured to other states. Marketing campaigns
target retirees with good insurance and money in the bank.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona, for instance, advertises in four magazines targeted to
an upscale clientele. As defined by the state's Department of
Commerce, that means seniors with an annual retirement income of at
least $40,000 and a net worth of $350,000 or higher.
</P>
<P>
   ``The census bureau predicts our (retired population) is going
to double in the next 20 years,'' said Cindy LaRue, director of
Arizona's Office of Senior Industries. ``We are just trying to make
sure that as many of those people are as affluent as possible . . .
It brings in money only if you bring in retirees who can afford to
pay their way.''
</P>
<P>
   So where are the folks with money going? To the places with more
room, less congestion and fewer, well, old people.
</P>
<P>
   ``Baby boomers don't want to see themselves as the same kind of
old person as their parents or their grandparents,'' said Susan
MacManus, a political science professor at the University of
Southern Florida in Tampa who has written extensively about
retirement trends. ``The pace (of retirees moving to Florida) will
slow down as the boomers make other choices in more remote areas.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Savageau, the most desirable retirement communities
are now in the west and a growing number are college towns.
</P>
<P>
   ``Boomers planning for retirement may be headed away from
traditional California or Florida spots their parents settled,''
Savageau said. ``The fastest growing parts of the country are now
on the western slope of the Rocky Mountains and in suburban parts
of the Desert Southwest.''
</P>
<P>
   Savageau based his ratings on six factors: cost of living,
climate, crime, available services, job prospects and leisure
living (which took into consideration such things as restaurants,
golf courses, theaters and outdoor recreational activities). Out of
100 possible points, Boca scored very well in leisure living and
services _ 95 and 92, respectively _ and very poorly on cost of
living _ 32.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, Florida still claimed the most communities of the 187
considered, Savageau said. ''And everybody is watching (those
communities) to see what to do and what not to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Douglas Belkin writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
