<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-25 10:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0115 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FLA-BISHOP-RESURFACES     05-25 1078
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLA-BISHOP-RESURFACES26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Catholic officials quiet about fallen Florida bishop's status
with Church
 &HT;    By Steve Gushee
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALMA, Mich. _ Life's journey may pass through the very gates of
hell, but, just maybe, you can go home again.
</P>
<P>
   Bishop J. Keith Symons, the former leader of the Roman Catholic
Diocese of Palm Beach who resigned in disgrace last June, was born
in Champion, Mich., in the upper peninsula 66 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   He now lives among nuns at a convent in Alma, a town of 11,000
in the center of the lower part of the state, according to Michigan
records. Symons is still a bishop and is back at work. He says
Mass, hears confessions and leads retreats.
</P>
<P>
   The bishop's path from Champion to Alma, from one small farming
community to another, has been filled with honor and disgrace,
service and suffering and, possibly, at the end, peace.
</P>
<P>
   The church, which successfully suppressed all knowledge about
Symons for nearly a year, no longer conceals his whereabouts.
</P>
<P>
   He has reentered pastoral ministry in the dioceses of Lansing
and Saginaw, but the church in Michigan restricts his ministry to
adults.
</P>
<P>
   Symons left Florida abruptly after resigning last year. When
accused, Symons admitted he had sexually abused five young men as a
young priest more than 30 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The fallen bishop, who had served the five-county diocese of
Palm Beach for nearly eight years, was quickly and quietly whisked
out of town. He left a perfunctory written word of regret to the
220,000 Roman Catholics in the diocese.
</P>
<P>
   There had been no hint of his whereabouts, his spiritual state
or his physical well-being for more than 11 months. Symons just
disappeared. Church spokesmen said he was in a treatment center but
wouldn't say where.
</P>
<P>
   Last Wednesday, he surfaced as the leader of a day of prayer
dedicated to the Virgin Mary at the St. Francis Retreat Center in
Dewitt, Mich., about 6 miles north of Lansing, the state capital.
</P>
<P>
   He has taken up residence in a small, red brick cottage owned by
the Sisters of Mercy Convent in Alma, about 50 miles north of
Lansing, according to motor vehicle records. Alma is in the Roman
Catholic Diocese of Saginaw.
</P>
<P>
   The church publicized Symons' leadership of the day of prayer at
the retreat center, which is owned by the Diocese of Lansing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't be surprised if Bishop Symons was in a position to
do something like this on some kind of basis,'' said Bishop Anthony
O'Connell, who was installed as the new bishop of the Palm Beach
Diocese in January. ``The Lord restored Peter even though he had
let the Lord down badly.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, attempts by The Palm Beach Post to learn more of Symons'
status were unsuccessful. Telephone calls last Thursday from West
Palm Beach to diocesan leaders in Lansing were not returned.
Spokesmen had little to say. The church in Michigan quickly wrapped
a protective blanket of secrecy around Symons.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Savage, the business manager of the retreat center,
acknowledged by phone that the bishop led the retreat but said he
knew no details. Savage said he would forward to Symons a request
for an interview.
</P>
<P>
   But last Friday, a reporter for The Post met even louder silence
when he showed up at the center in DeWitt. Savage was off for the
day. Retreat leaders were behind closed doors in sessions with the
faithful.
</P>
<P>
   Staff members at the center's reception area confessed to
feeling uncomfortable even talking about the center and recommended
asking questions at diocesan offices.
</P>
<P>
   Next, a visit to the convent complex 44 miles away in Alma met a
still icier reception. The reporter took the convent's ``Welcome''
sign at its word, entered the vestibule of the spacious mother
house and called, ``Hello?''
</P>
<P>
   A tall, smiling sister in a modern, dark blue habit arrived,
smiled and asked whether she could be of assistance. The reporter
asked to see Bishop Symons. The nun walked into a dining room as
the reporter followed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just a moment,'' the sister said. ``I'll see if he's
available.''
</P>
<P>
   She left the room and soon returned saying, ``The bishop is not
available.'' But she said the reporter could leave a note for the
bishop and gave him paper and pen.
</P>
<P>
   The note asked Symons to consider an opportunity to talk,
through an interview, with his former flock in Palm Beach, who
cared for him and knew nothing of his life for nearly a year.
</P>
<P>
   Then another sister appeared.
</P>
<P>
   She was agitated, accused the reporter of entering a private
home uninvited and ordered him to leave the convent. He apologized
and rose to leave, asking if he could leave the note. The first
sister took the note. The second said, ``There is no one to leave a
note for. Please leave.''
</P>
<P>
   The reporter left the convent, which includes several buildings
along a tree-lined street in a middle class neighborhood about a
half-mile from Alma's main street, which is called Superior.
</P>
<P>
   Alma is a center for farming life and has a gas refinery for the
Total company, a small Presbyterian college named after the town
and dozens of churches.
</P>
<P>
   Nancy McClintic, 42, was born in Alma. Her husband, Art, grows
sugar beets, corn and cucumbers on 1,700 acres just south of the
town that is surrounded by gentle rolling hills and vast fields of
rich soil. The McClintics are members of the Alma Wesleyan Church
and are happy to talk.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of nice people here,'' Nancy McClintic said.
``Even for a college town, it's quiet. People don't lock their
doors here. When anyone is down and out, they are here to help.''
</P>
<P>
   The priest at St. Mary's Roman Catholic Church echoed those
small-town sentiments and said he didn't know that Symons was at
the convent. Apparently few in Alma did.
</P>
<P>
   As the reporter was leaving the little town, he called the
convent to leave a telephone number Symons could use if he chose to
speak. The sister who answered told him to call the Diocese of
Lansing and hung up.
</P>
<P>
   When contacted, Michael Diebold, director of communications for
the diocese, said that Lansing's bishop had issued a statement.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bishop Carl Mengeling has given Bishop Keith Symons permission
to lead spiritual retreats for adults who seek to know and love
God,'' Diebold said.
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``And we're not taking any questions.''
</P>
<P>
   Steve Gushee writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
