</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990525.0059 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-25 10:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0116 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MASTERPIECE-RECREATIO     05-25 1016
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MASTERPIECE-RECREATIONS26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Seeing is believing: Artist's copycat creations bring
masterpiece touch to small Georgia town
 &HT;    By Doug Hamilton
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOGANSVILLE, Ga. _ Van Gogh's ``Sunflowers'' really catches the
afternoon light. ``Mona Lisa'' smiles enigmatically as ever.
</P>
<P>
   Surprised to find them here in a stripped-down storefront on a
small-town Georgia Main Street otherwise given over to antiques
emporiums? Wonder how the High Museum of Art missed out on this
blockbuster? While you're pondering these questions you should
check out Picasso's epic war polemic ``Guernica.''
</P>
<P>
   These three and 64 other ``masterpieces'' are here in a place
that celebrates artifice, the International Art Museum of
Re-Creations. If you think the notion of a museum with a collection
of faux art is strange, it's no less odd than how it came to be
located in Hogansville, 55 miles southwest of downtown Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   It's the dream-come-true of Paris-born artist, author,
photographer and gadabout Jacques Harvey, who has spent a lifetime
aping the masters.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mother still has a painting of a church I did when I was 7,
in the style of Van Gogh,'' says Harvey, 61, who estimates he's
painted more than 2,500 reproductions in 25 years.
</P>
<P>
   Harvey got the idea for the museum in 1994, from his manager's
nephew, an art student from rural France who complained that the
famous museums of Paris were too far away to visit.
</P>
<P>
   ``The original versions of these paintings are in France,
Belgium, Japan _ all over the place,'' Harvey says. ``People can
come here and learn about all these paintings, and about the
artists who painted them. It's very educational.''
</P>
<P>
   For instance, a visiting group of students from Callaway Middle
School in nearby LaGrange recently was led on a scavenger hunt
through the collection. Each was given a list of items to find,
with the ultimate goal of getting them to study the canvases
closely.
</P>
<P>
   Harvey concedes that his reproductions ``are not exactly the
same as the originals. But I would say they're 99 percent the
same.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, an art expert might be able to detect a certain
coarseness in the re-creation of Manet's ``Luncheon on the Grass,''
or notice a slight difference in the pigments used to depict
Munch's ``The Scream.'' But amateur art buffs will appreciate
Harvey's obsessive attention to detail _ the only thing missing
from these works is the original signature. ``That would be
illegal,'' notes the artist, who promises to add 33 more pieces to
the collection in the months to come.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, nobody will mistake his quaint digs _ a former used
furniture store in downtown Hogansville, population 3,750 _ for the
Louvre. In fact, Harvey had once sought a flashier home for his
collection. He says he was ``in discussions'' with Mirage Resorts
mogul Steve Wynn about showcasing the paintings at Bellagio, the
Las Vegas gambling palace. The talks didn't pan out, and Harvey
jokes that Wynn ``took my idea.'' (Bellagio boasts a museum stocked
with Cezannes, Modiglianis, Renoirs and Degas _ real ones.)
</P>
<P>
   Restaurateur and longtime friend Patrick Terrail convinced
Harvey to bring his copycat creations to Georgia. The two met in
the early 1970s, when Harvey frequented Terrail's Beverly Hills
eatery Ma Maison, a favorite haunt of Hollywood celebs. Actor Gene
Kelly, one of Terrail's business partners, asked Harvey to paint a
reproduction of a Dufy masterwork. Word of the artist's talents
spread through the Hollywood community. Soon, he was copying
Monet's ``Waterlillies'' for Lucille Ball and faking a Renoir for
Johnny Carson.
</P>
<P>
   Terrail, 57, discovered Hogansville during the 1996 Atlanta
Olympics, while working as a consultant for the liquor company
Hiram Walker. Recovering from cancer treatments, he decided the
town was ``a relaxing place to settle.''
</P>
<P>
   Terrail contacted Harvey, who resides primarily in Miami, and
suggested Hogansville as a possible site for the museum. He put his
painter pal in touch with John Jones, another former Ma Maison
patron who had relocated to Georgia. Jones owns several buildings
in downtown Hogansville and would like to see it become a popular,
antiques-anchored shopping village like Dahlonega. He offered
Harvey the storefront, rent-free.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm trying to bring people to a town that has been bypassed,
but hopefully whose time has come,'' says Jones. ``We hope the
museum will convince people with an interest in art to move here,''
he adds, optimistically.
</P>
<P>
   For Harvey, the price was right, though he still had to invest
about $400,000 of his own money to renovate the property.
</P>
<P>
   The museum opened April 3 and is supported by donations and
admission fees. To attract student and senior citizen
organizations, the museum has set its group rate at $3.50 _ a
dollar less than a single adult admission.
</P>
<P>
   Harvey continues to make a living selling art reproductions.
He's painting a Chagall and a Cezanne for a British collector who
plans to store the originals in a vault and display the copies in
his home. ``That happens a lot,'' Harvey says. ``It costs so much
to insure these multi-million dollar paintings. People want to make
sure they're safe.'' His pieces sell for $4,000-$8,000.
</P>
<P>
   Of all the artists he's copied, Harvey says Chagall is the
hardest to master. ``He paints like a child. It's hard to put
yourself in the mind of a child.''
</P>
<P>
   And the easiest? It's Picasso, Harvey's favorite painter. ``When
you look at his work, you say, `Oh that's doesn't look hard,' ''
Harvey says. ``But you have to remember how long it took for him to
come up with that style. Copying is easy. Inventing is difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   IF YOU GO
</P>
<P>
   The International Art Museum of Re-Creations is open 11 a.m.-5
p.m. Wednesdays-Fridays, 10 a.m.-6 p.m. Saturdays, 1-5 p.m.
Sundays. Adults, $4.50; groups, senior citizens and Hogansville,
Ga. residents, $3.50; students, $2.50; children ages 6 to 12, $1.
203 E. Main St. Hogansville, Ga. 706-637-8030.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
