<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MURRAY-COLUMN26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tall Tales and Short Stories: Ugly story with a beautiful ending
 &HT;    By Joe Murray
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox Newspapers
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here's an ugly story told by a beautiful woman . . .
</P>
<P>
   She and her husband had been married 17 years. One day it
occurred to her he no longer seemed to notice her.
</P>
<P>
   She cut her hair. He didn't notice.
</P>
<P>
   She made her hair blonde. He didn't notice.
</P>
<P>
   She decided to go on a diet. She walked two miles every day and
counted every calorie until she lost 30 pounds and looked like a
refugee from a labor camp. Still, he didn't notice.
</P>
<P>
   One thing never she never considered: perhaps he was seeing
someone else.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I had lined up 100 men, he would have been the last one I
would have thought would cheat,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   It just never occurred to her.
</P>
<P>
   Not even when he started having his nails done.
</P>
<P>
   Not even when he started wearing black brief underwear.
</P>
<P>
   Not even when she happened to see their phone bill for more than
$800.
</P>
<P>
   She seldom dealt with the bills. Moreover, the mail came while
she was at work.
</P>
<P>
   When she asked him about the hundreds of dollars in long
distance calls _ most of them, she noticed, to a number somewhere
out West _ he told her it was all a mistake on the part of the
people at the phone company, that he had already talked to them and
they had corrected the bill.
</P>
<P>
   What she didn't know was that he immediately went out and got a
post office box. That's where the phone bill went from then on.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, this illicit love affair had been phone fascination from
the first.
</P>
<P>
   The way he would explain it to her _ when he was asking her for
a divorce _ is that he had accidentally dialed a wrong area code, a
woman answered, told him he had wrong number and then they hung up.
</P>
<P>
   He had stood there a long moment, all atwitter, then picked up
the phone again and punched redial.
</P>
<P>
   He knew from the first time he heard her voice she was the woman
he had always wanted.
</P>
<P>
   After they had separated, his wife would call the number herself
just out of curiosity.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the very least I expected something husky and sexy, like
Debra Winger,'' she said. ``Instead I got this awful, whiny
``Hel-lo'' that sounded like a hillbilly girl.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, she wasn't much more than a girl, just 20 years old,
but married with two children, having gotten an early start after
getting pregnant out of wedlock at 15.
</P>
<P>
   No matter. This was her husband's one true love. Nothing would
do but for them to divorce.
</P>
<P>
   So it was that they split their stuff, he took cash _ most of
which had come from her inheritance _ and she took the property.
</P>
<P>
   He gave up a good job where they lived in the East to move to
Arkansas to make about one-fourth the money he had been earning.
</P>
<P>
   All's well that ends well?
</P>
<P>
   Well, it has been for the wife he left behind.
</P>
<P>
   She met someone new in no time at all _ a man tall and handsome,
rich and powerful _ and, in no time at all, they were married.
She's everything he ever wanted, and she's never been so happy.
</P>
<P>
   As for the husband that went away, it turned out the love of his
life couldn't see spending the rest of her life with him.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, you can't live on love _ and her own husband makes a
lot more money than the he does.
</P>
<P>
   He wishes now he was back in the home he abandoned _ not that
she would ever have him back or, for that matter, that he could
afford a ticket back.
</P>
<P>
   All that money he went away with has since gone away, and he's
stone broke and broken-hearted to boot.
</P>
<P>
   She has her hair back to brown, she's wearing it long again and,
at her husband's insistence, has gained some of the weight she
lost. Everyone tells her she's never looked more lovely.
</P>
<P>
   Moral: Even an ugly story can have a beautiful ending.
</P>
<P>
   (Joe Murray, editor-publisher emeritus of the Lufkin Daily News,
is senior writer for Cox Newspapers. His mailing address is P.O.
Box 151108, Lufkin, Texas, 75915; email, jmurray(at)lcc.net;
website, www.geocities.com/SoHo/Bistro/7147.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
