<HEADLINE>
EDITORS:
</HEADLINE>
  
 Tuesday, May 25, 1999      The Hearst News Service will file these stories for Wednesday.
If you have questions, please call Tim Spence at 202-298-6920.  
    (Slugline includes the ``HNS'' tag.)
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   GUN-SUIT (San Francisco) _ San Francisco and several other
California cities are suing gun manufacturers, alleging that the
companies engage in unfair business practices and knowingly market
to criminals. By RAY DELGADO.
</P>
<P>
   ALAMO-CITY-TOURISM (San Antonio) _ As one of the nation's
premiere tourist destinations, San Antonio has found itself in an
uncomfortable predicament: keeping streets clean and safe for
tourists without trampling the rights of those who could frighten
them away. The police say they have been under pressure to keep
teens and vagrants away from tourists. By LISA SANDBERG. (Photo
available on Wieck database.)
</P>
<P>
   LIVING-WAGE (San Francisco) _ San Francisco's plan to require
employers who hold service contracts with the city to pay their
workers at least $11 an hour and provide health benefits has hit a
snag. By GREGORY LEWIS.
</P>
<P>
   GAS-ADDITIVE (Sacramento) _ The California Senate has voted to
require a warning label for gasoline that contains MTBE, the fuel
additive that supposedly reduces smog but can end up polluting the
water supply. By the San Francisco Examiner.
</P>
<P>
   DA-FUNDS (San Francisco) _ State Attorney General Bill Lockyer
denies any personal knowledge of a decision by his office to drop
an investigation into possible criminal misappropriation of funds
by the office of San Francisco District Attorney Terence Hallinan.
Lockyer recently endorsed Hallinan, a fellow Democrat, in the
district attorney's bid for re-election this fall. By SCOTT
WINOKUR.
</P>
<P>
   PRESIDIO-CLEANUP (San Francisco) _ The U.S. Army will pay $100
million over four years for an accelerated environmental cleanup of
the Presidio of San Francisco, a former Army base, to accommodate
its transformation to a self-sustaining national park. By GEORGE
RAINE.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE/FEATURES (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   GONDOLAS (Oakland, Calif.) _ In the culture wars around here,
Oakland has scored a coup. San Francisco may have a many-splendored
art scene, but Oakland has real Venetian gondolas offering romantic
cruises (with candles! antipasto! O Sole Mio!). By ROBERT SELNA.
</P>
<P>
   GOOD-POSTURE (Albany, N.Y.) _ Today's sedentary lifestyle often
aggravates many poor-posture problems. With many people spending
eight or more hours at a desk every day, typing at computers and
answering the phone, it's easier than ever to slump and
slouch.``We've become a nation of professional sitters,'' says
Janice Novak, a Minnesota-based health education consultant and
author of a new book, ``Posture, Get it Straight!'' By SYLVIA
WOODS.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CREDIT-SPREE (San Francisco) _ Consumers, beware. As the
economic boom and wild spending continue, that tiny plastic card in
your purse or wallet may be Public Enemy No. 1. Never before has it
been so easy to buy so much stuff and to fall into such deep debt.
By EDWARD IWATA.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MCKITTRICK-TRANSPLANT (San Francisco) _ What began as a day of
optimism for prospective liver-recipient Bobb McKittrick ended with
news that his cancer had spread from the bile duct, forcing
cancellation of an impending transplant. McKittrick, the 49ers'
longtime offensive line coach, would have shared the organ with a
six- year-old girl in a procedure known as a split-liver
transplant. By JOHN CRUMPACKER.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   LYNCH-COLUMN (Albany, N.Y.) _ There will be those cynical types
who'll maintain that New York Gov. George Pataki is backing Texas
Gov. George W. Bush early in the hope that Bush, overcome with
gratitude, will pick the New Yorker as a running mate. Don't bet on
it. Sure, New York has 33 electoral votes. But Pataki couldn't even
find enough room on his coattails last year for former Attorney
General Dennis Vacco and former U.S. Sen. Alfonse D'Amato. By DAN
LYNCH.
</P>
<P>
   MORSE-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ Rashad Williams has had a day
named after him here and he got a proclamation from Mayor Willie
Brown for raising $14,000 for Lance Kirklin, who was badly wounded
in the shooting at Columbine High School in Littleton, Colo. Rashad
is a 15-year-old who decided to do something about the Littleton
massacre while we adults were just talking about it. By ROB MORSE.
</P>
<P>
   SALTER-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ Every time there is another
outburst of mass adolescent violence in some quiet, white-bread
American town, child psychiatrist Herb Schreier of nearby Oakland
gets phone calls from reporters. Painstakingly, he reminds them
that _ while there is a surge in school shootings _ official
statistics do not support the existence of an epidemic of teen
crime. By STEPHANIE SALTER.
</P>
</TEXT>
