<SLUG> BC-LYNCH-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUST ANOTHER FAN OF GEORGE W. BUSH 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN LYNCH  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Well, jeez, what a yawner that turned out to be.
</P>
<P>
   For a week now, I've been nibbling on my nails. What was this
big announcement that George Pataki had scheduled? Given the
governor's penchant for lying low _ he's about as visible in this
town as Claude Rains or Chevy Chase _ why had he made such a
production about his news conference on Monday. What could he
possibly have on his mind?
</P>
<P>
   Would he take on New York Mayor Rudolph Giuliani for next year's
Republican nomination for the U.S. Senate? Would that be cool or
what? A big, bloody battle of the titans in New York's Republican
Party? Thank you, God.
</P>
<P>
   Or was he going to resign his office to take some big job
somewhere in private industry? That would leave Lt. Gov. Mary
Donahue as governor and spark a huge, deliciously vicious fight in
the party in 2002. Given Pataki's obvious disinterest in serving as
governor, that hardly seemed unlikely. Or despite the lukewarm
response to his year-long speeches to GOP organizations around the
country, was he announcing his candidacy for the Republican
presidential nomination anyway? Was he going to say, ``All right,
the hell with it. This is my chance. I'm going to let it all hang
out.''
</P>
<P>
   People do that sometimes _ even buttoned-down, uptight,
exceedingly proper Yalies like Pataki. They buy sailboats and light
out for Tahiti. They ditch their wives for cabaret singers named
Bambi. They run for president. Really, you never know.
</P>
<P>
   So I don't mind saying that I was absolutely quivery as Monday
drew near. As a political junkie _ as somebody with a ferocious,
frenzied interest in the democratic process and in the quirky
personalities that make it work _ I just couldn't wait to find out
what was on Pataki's mind.
</P>
<P>
   And what did it turn out to be? In a stunning act of political
courage, the governor announced Monday that he's backing the
front-runner for the Republican presidential nomination. Yes, the
governor says, Texas Gov. George W. Bush is his kind of guy.
</P>
<P>
   Now, there's a thrill. Next thing you know, Pataki will be
wearing brown shoes with a blue suit. Is there any limit to this
guy's flair for nonconformity?
</P>
<P>
   OK, I suppose it's possible that Bush will not end up as next
year's Republican presidential candidate. There could be some
scandal involving booze, drugs or a bevy of, ahem, debutantes. In
the end, Bush could be the guy who ends up sailing to Tahiti with
Bambi.
</P>
<P>
   Odds are, though, that Bush will be the man next year, and it's
not the biggest deal in the world that establishment Republicans
like Pataki end up endorsing him. For somebody like Pataki, an act
like that isn't exactly on a par with abandoning public service and
going on tour with Bob Dylan.
</P>
<P>
   There will, of course, be those cynical types who'll maintain
that Pataki is backing Bush early in the hope that Bush, overcome
with gratitude, will pick him as a running mate. Don't bet on it.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, New York has 33 electoral votes. But Pataki has
demonstrated that he would be unlikely to deliver them to Bush in a
presidential year. He couldn't even find enough room on his
coattails in New York last year for Attorney General Dennis Vacco
and Sen. Alfonse D'Amato, both of whom lost to Democratic
challengers.
</P>
<P>
   If Bush ends up as the GOP nominee, he's much likelier to look
to a Californian as a running mate, or to a woman. Or to
Pennsylvania Gov. Tom Ridge, who has a reasonable shot at
delivering his state's 23 electoral votes next year.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki didn't back Bush because of personal gain.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly he did it because this is his idea of excitement.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Dan Lynch is a columnist for the Albany Times Union, P.O. Box
15000, Albany, NY 12212.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
