<SLUG> BC-PRIVATE-RYAN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`PRIVATE RYAN' COMES INTO PERSPECTIVE ON VIDEO
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROB LOWMAN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ This year wasn't the first time, and _ based on
their record _ it probably won't be the last time that Academy of
Motion Picture Arts and Sciences members make a mistake when naming
the best picture. At least ``Shakespeare in Love'' was a
commendable, if lightweight, choice. It was certainly better than
some of the boring, ``prestigious'' epics that have won in the
past, but it was hardly as cinematic, moving or thought-provoking
as its chief rival, ``Saving Private Ryan.''
</P>
<P>
   Before you protest, ``Ryan,'' which comes out on video today,
isn't a perfect film, but unlike ``Shakespeare,'' it aimed higher
and succeeded _ sometimes brilliantly. The scenes of the landing at
Omaha Beach on D-Day are unmatched in film, an extraordinary
sequence that few directors could pull off, which is why Steven
Spielberg rightly won the Oscar for best director and the film
picked up four other Academy Awards.
</P>
<P>
   (If there is any consolation for losing the best picture Oscar,
``Ryan'' was last year's box-office champ, taking in more than $210
million.)
</P>
<P>
   But the film is more than just pyrotechnics and technique. If
``Ryan'' was merely an homage to the fighting men in World War II _
like numerous flag-waving combat movies have been _ then that
wouldn't be enough to make it a great film. The war drama tells the
story of a platoon led by Capt. Miller (Tom Hanks) to rescue a
family's last surviving son (Matt Damon), after his brothers had
been killed in combat. In doing so, it raises questions about
courage, sacrifice and morality that resonate throughout the film,
giving it a true poignancy.
</P>
<P>
   On the small screen, ``Ryan'' loses little of its impact. But
video viewers can distance themselves from some of the more
harrowing scenes, which were very intense on the big screen, and,
ironically, that might have offered them some perspective to
appreciate the film's exceptional qualities.
</P>
<P>
   DreamWorks has set ``Ryan'' as a rental only, though there
should be plenty of copies in the stores. No sell-through date has
been announced, and there are no plans for a DVD version at this
time.
</P>
<P>
   Just a thought: The largest segment of the voting members of the
academy are actors (about one-fourth), and an actors' film
(``Shakespeare'') won this year. Maybe they forgot that they aren't
voting for the Screen Actors Guild awards. It is, after all, the
Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
