<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CREDIT-SPREE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEST ADVICE FOR CREDIT USERS: BEWARE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By EDWARD IWATA  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ With the economic boom and wild spending
continuing, the credit card may be Public Enemy No. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Never before has it been so easy to buy so much stuff and to
fall into such deep debt. Credit card debt rose at a near-record
pace to $1.3 trillion in January, the Federal Reserve reported.
</P>
<P>
   Personal bankruptcies hit a record high of 1.4 million last
year.
</P>
<P>
   Feeding the frenzy are the nation's credit card issuers, who are
flooding mailboxes with billions of tempting offers. Consumer
groups accuse them of deceptive marketing and sales practices.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton and lawmakers hope to curb some of the
problems by requiring issuers to clearly disclose their fees and
terms to customers.
</P>
<P>
   With all the potential pitfalls out there, what's a poor shopper
to do? Here are some tips:
</P>
<P>
   _ Buyer beware.
</P>
<P>
   Many tricky marketing tactics used by respectable credit card
issuers are perfectly legal. It's up to consumers to train their
brains to study important information hidden deep in written
contracts.
</P>
<P>
   For direct mail solicitations, the fees and interest rates can
all be found in one place: a graph box on the mailing.
</P>
<P>
   ``The key is to really read all the fine print,'' said Linda
Sherry, editorial director at Consumer Action in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   _ Ignore telemarketing calls.
</P>
<P>
   Good telemarketers are well trained and use scripts to respond
to objections about buying a product. ``Telemarketers are out to
confuse you,'' Sherry said. ``Avoid buying things from them.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Teaser rates are dangerous traps.
</P>
<P>
   In a common sales ploy, credit card issuers offer introductory
teaser rates of 0 percent to 5 or 6 percent for the first few
months of a new account. Later, the rate suddenly jumps to 16 or 20
percent or more.
</P>
<P>
   Often, the full rate is a variable rate pegged to an economic
indicator or index set by the Federal Reserve, U.S. Treasury bills
or other benchmarks. The formula can confuse consumers, who are
shocked when they're hit by the big interest rate down the road.
</P>
<P>
   ``The teaser rates will be in big print,'' said Gail Hillebrand,
legal counsel at Consumers Union in San Francisco. ``Make sure you
know what the full terms will be.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Ask credit agencies to delete you from their mailing lists.
</P>
<P>
   ``It won't cut off the solicitations 100 percent, but it'll
substantially reduce the flow,'' said David Medine, associate
director for credit practices at the Federal Trade Commission in
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   _ Watch out for ``free'' checks in the mail.
</P>
<P>
   Another potent sales trick: Some credit card issuers will send
you a blank check that's really a cash advance on your new credit
card account. The credit card company hits you twice: You pay a 2
or 3 percent fee on the advance, as well as interest on the
outstanding balance.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks like a check. You fill it out like a check, and you
spend it like a check, but it's really an advance authorization on
your account,'' Hillebrand said. ``The best thing to do is tear it
up.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Trash extra credit cards.
</P>
<P>
   You don't need more than one or two for travel, emergency
purchases or big-ticket items.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just because it's being offered to you doesn't mean it's a
good idea,'' Hillebrand said.
</P>
<P>
   _ Be careful when you move your balance to another credit card
issuer.
</P>
<P>
   Hoping to find the lower interest rates, millions of people are
shopping around and transferring their credit card balances to
another credit card company or bank. The new company pays off the
old balance, then offers consumers the new, lower rate.
</P>
<P>
   Make sure you understand all of the terms of the transfer.
</P>
<P>
   Consumers often are socked by hidden fees and terms. Also, never
agree to transfer your balance over the phone. Make sure the terms
are in writing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stay alert because credit card issuers dangle a lot of carrots
in front of consumers,'' Sherry said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
