A0212 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      05-25 0743
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DISTANCE RUNNER GOES ALL THE WAY FOR LITTLETON 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROB MORSE  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Monday was Rashad Williams Day in San Francisco.
I celebrated it by going to City Hall to see the young man get a
proclamation from the mayor for raising $14,000 for Lance Kirklin,
who was badly wounded in the shooting at Columbine High School in
Littleton, Colo.
</P>
<P>
   Rashad Williams made my day, and a lot of people's days, by
deciding to do something about the Littleton massacre while we
adults were just talking about it.
</P>
<P>
   When I asked Rashad's grandmother, Minnie Burton, how the family
was going to celebrate Rashad Williams Day, she said, ``We're going
back to school.''
</P>
<P>
   No lunch at a fancy restaurant for this family. Three
generations of them are committed to work, education and doing good
for others. Rashad had to get back to Archbishop Riordan High
School to finish the school year. It's a privilege when you think
about it.
</P>
<P>
   Kirklin didn't get to finish his sophomore year at Littleton
High School. Kirklin spent a month in the Denver Health Center
recovering from multiple gunshot wounds to the chest and legs, as
well as a shotgun blast that tore up his face.
</P>
<P>
   Few expected this 16-year-old to live. But after holding a news
conference and participating in a party for the trauma unit's
doctors, donors and former patients, he went home a few days ago.
Still, he faces years of reconstructive surgery and it won't all be
covered by insurance.
</P>
<P>
   That's why Rashad, a 15-year-old a thousand miles away, decided
to run the Bay to Breakers race to raise the money to help him. So
far he has raised $14,000.
</P>
<P>
   Riordan Vice Principal Linda Nastari says kids are still
bringing nickels, dimes and quarters for the wounded kid in
Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   The school is still accepting checks made out to the Lance
Kirklin Support Fund c/o Everen Securities, at Riordan High School,
175 Phelan Ave., San Francisco, CA 94112.
</P>
<P>
   Rashad is long on action and short on talk, so when he spoke in
front of four news cameras in the mayor's office, he simply said:
``I just did it for Lance. I was just devastated and I decided to
help.''
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Willie Brown said he was happy to see the news media turn
out for a student trying to help another student, and hoped it
would be an example for all teen-agers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most times coverage (of teen-agers) is for something not so
positive,'' Brown said.
</P>
<P>
   It's true, and when Rashad's mother, Shirley Burton-Harrison,
told me two weeks ago that her son was actually doing something
about Littleton, I drove right out to Riordan High to meet the
young man.
</P>
<P>
   Like most Americans, I felt angry, depressed and frustrated
about what happened at Columbine High School. I didn't want to go
to Littleton or contribute to the media binge that seems to inspire
copycat shooters.
</P>
<P>
   Along came Rashad, a kid I hope will inspire copycats who do
good rather than evil.
</P>
<P>
   Don't call them copycats, though. Most kids are good to begin
with, and have their own ways of expressing it. They just need a
little inspiration.
</P>
<P>
   A family can be the best inspiration, and upon meeting Rashad's
family at City Hall, I understood where he gets his generous
impulses.
</P>
<P>
   When I shook hands with Mack Burton, Rashad's grandfather, he
pulled me aside to say he hopes what Rashad said about Lance to his
mother can be a motto for change.
</P>
<P>
   ``As adults,'' Burton said, ``we can make sure everybody hears,
`Mom, that could have been me. I only have my heart and my legs.'''
</P>
<P>
   Burton, a former football star for Washington High School here,
has the legs and the heart, too. Through his company, Burton
Construction Services and the Residential Builders Association, he
is teaching construction skills to dozens of the poor of all
descriptions, including homeless people and former substance
abusers.
</P>
<P>
   Burton's bright hope is his grandson Rashad, and kids like him,
are all our hopes.
</P>
<P>
   After the ceremony, life went on. Rashad Williams went back to
school. I gave his mom Lance Kirklin's e-mail address, kindly
supplied by the hospital. Rashad will send Lance a note. Maybe
these two quiet kids will communicate. Maybe they'll meet.
</P>
<P>
   You never know. Sometimes life provides good surprises.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Rob Morse is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner, P.O.
Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
