<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALAMO-CITY-TOURISM-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLICE SAY NOT ALL ARE WELCOME IN TOURIST MECCA 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDs: Photos available on Wieck database)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LISA SANDBERG  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ A city of contrasts.
</P>
<P>
   Well-heeled tourists saunter into an Alamo Plaza boutique.
</P>
<P>
   A young couple smile for a photograph in front of the Shrine of
Texas Liberty.
</P>
<P>
   Across the street, in the shadow of the Alamo Cenotaph, a
homeless woman gazes out of a Burger King window, mumbling and
giggling to herself. Three plastic bags, containing her worldly
possessions, rest at her feet.
</P>
<P>
   As one of the nation's premiere tourist destinations, San
Antonio has found itself in an uncomfortable predicament: Keeping
streets clean and safe for tourists without trampling the rights of
those who could frighten them away.
</P>
<P>
   Tattooed teen-agers slouch in front of trendy tourist shops.
</P>
<P>
   Horses pull white carriages past soiled street people.
</P>
<P>
   ``We go to the River Walk and the police run us off. They say
the backpacks scare off the tourists,'' said James Smith, a
21-year-old drifter with dirty clothes and a silver stud in his
chin. ``They tell us, `If you're out of sight, you're OK.'''
</P>
<P>
   How far the city has gone to sanitize downtown has been the
subject of hours of contentious testimony in a federal court
lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   A San Antonio police officer has said he was ordered to drive
out homeless people, teen-agers and other so-called
``undesirables.''
</P>
<P>
   Officer Onofre Serna also has said in a lawsuit filed in U.S.
District Court that the Police Department retaliated against him
because he objected to the orders.
</P>
<P>
   Serna, who in 1996 was transferred from the highly visible
bicycle patrol to squad-car duty, says the transfer was punishment
for complaining about the unit's harsh methods. He also says the
transfer violated his civil rights and laws protecting
whistleblowers.
</P>
<P>
   In recent testimony, nine officers said that between 1994 and
1996 they were ordered to snatch bandannas, baseball caps and other
personal belongings from suspected gang members; to remove homeless
people from benches and doorways; and to demand identification from
patrons of some bars.
</P>
<P>
   The city denies it ever took aim at particular categories of
people or retaliated against Serna.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't target people, we target problems,'' Mayor Howard
Peak said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they're not doing anything wrong, they shouldn't be
hassled. If a problem is created, it should be dealt with.''
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta, Chicago, New York, San Francisco and Tucson, Ariz., are
among dozens of U.S. cities that have tried to restrict the
homeless from certain downtown areas in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the outcome of the San Antonio trial, no one denies a
lot is at stake. Nearly 8 million visitors spent an estimated $1.72
billion in San Antonio in 1997, making tourism the city's second
largest industry, according to the Convention and Visitor's Bureau.
</P>
<P>
   The yearly economic impact of tourism here is estimated at $3.51
billion.
</P>
<P>
   The River Walk, with its 150 upscale restaurants, hotels and
bars, is Texas' No. 1 tourist destination.
</P>
<P>
   The flood of tourists onto the streets of San Antonio, a city of
1 million people, has been accompanied by a smaller but growing
stream of homeless people.
</P>
<P>
   Between 1997 and 1998, the city's homeless population jumped 23
percent, to 22,155 people, according to officials at the San
Antonio Metropolitan Ministry, which operates an emergency shelter.
</P>
<P>
   Interviews suggest an uneasy co-existence between those who
profit from the tourist industry and those who merely live
alongside it.
</P>
<P>
   Rosalinda Brinson, a sales clerk at a jewelry store overlooking
the River Walk called Minas de Taxco, put it this way: ``It's a
very big problem. Some people come in and they have hair on one
side but not on the other.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very scary,'' she said. ``I can take it, but the families
with the little girls, they don't want to come back to San
Antonio.''
</P>
<P>
   Greg Gallaspy, executive director of the Paseo del Rio
Association, an alliance of 150 River Walk businesses, agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``That type of stuff can be detrimental to the tourist
industry,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It can have a huge impact. Our mission statement is to
promote, protect and preserve the River Walk at all costs. We have
to do everything to ensure that that continues.''
</P>
<P>
   One of a dozen or so police officers assigned to the city's
downtown bike patrols, who spoke on condition of anonymity,
described the fine line between safe streets and civil rights that
the patrols face daily.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're told to take care of any problems,'' the officer said as
he prepared to begin his evening shift. ``It's a free country, but
it's also a tourist city. We get pressured by the city to do
certain things, to keep the city clean. Maybe some cops go too
far.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In court testimony and pretrial depositions, several patrol
members have insisted that a few years ago their orders went too
far.
</P>
<P>
   They say they were told to harass teen-agers and homeless
people, with or without probable cause suggesting laws were being
broken.
</P>
<P>
   ``Embarrassing'' is how one officer described the policy.
</P>
<P>
   Teen-agers would wait at the curb for the light to change
because they knew one false step would get them jaywalking tickets.
Another patrolman said officers were advised to follow a simple
formula: If a gang member and a tourist simultaneously jaywalked,
the gang member should be ticketed.
</P>
<P>
   Although most officers have testified that pressure to harass
evaporated after a 1996 internal shake-up brought new leadership to
the downtown patrol, Edward Pina, the president of the American
Civil Liberties Union in San Antonio, said he still frequently
reviews complaints about police treatment.
</P>
<P>
   ``The complaints have never stopped,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Deputy Police Chief Albert Ortiz said the department's mission
to serve and protect gives officers fairly wide latitude beyond
enforcing ordinances and laws.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, officers can tell a drifter to ``take a hike'' if
they suspect he is using a bus stop bench as shelter in stead of
waiting for a ride. But, Ortiz said, unless someone has lodged a
specific complaint, officers can't enforce the order.
</P>
<P>
   ``The operation of any police department is not predicated on
(law) enforcement. That's a minor part of the job,'' he said.
``Most of it is order maintenance and intervening before we feel
there's any violence.''
</P>
<P>
   At least one merchant has a tolerant view about vagrants and
teens.
</P>
<P>
   ``The city should never put tourism above its own people,'' said
Bill Barowski, owner of a Back Stage T-shirt store. ``Travelers
have been coming to San Antonio for 200 years, and there were
degenerates then, too.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
