A0229 &Cx1f; tth-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CITIZEN-KHRUSHCHEV-SP     05-25 0893
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CITIZEN-KHRUSHCHEV-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NIKITA KHRUSHCHEV'S SON TO BECOME U.S. CITIZEN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ARTHUR C. GORLICK  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The son of the man who ruled the Soviet Union and its Communist
Party at the peak of its Cold War with the United States is to
become an American citizen next month.
</P>
<P>
   Ordinarily the naturalization of a Russian emigre, even a rocket
scientist, would be less than remarkable. But Sergei Khrushchev's
father, Nikita, once stood behind the full fury of one of the
world's two great nuclear arsenals and declared ``We will bury
you'' to an American public already drilling its children for a
nuclear attack.
</P>
<P>
   And although some have since interpreted the comment as
referring to the competing economic systems of the two countries,
generations of Americans recall little but the image of the
shoe-pounding premier.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty-five years later, acknowledging his father was wrong
about which economic system would prevail, 63-year-old Sergei
Khruschev will clearly punctuate the end of competition between the
superpowers.
</P>
<P>
   Khrushchev and his wife, Valentina Golenko, are scheduled to
become citizens June 23 at the Immigration and Naturalization
Service regional headquarters in St. Albans, Vt., according to his
Seattle-based immigration lawyer, Dan Danilov.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought about this decision and I had the freedom to make
this decision,'' Khrushchev said in a telephone interview yesterday
from his home in Providence, R.I.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because I have been living here for seven years and working
for Brown University and I am planning to live here longer. If I am
living in the country, I think I have the obligation to be a
citizen, not a foreigner who came for temporary residence.''
</P>
<P>
   Khrushchev, a senior research scholar and lecturer at Brown
University's Center for Foreign Policy Development, is a rocket
engineer and computer scientist who once headed the Soviet Missile
Design Bureau.
</P>
<P>
   He received his ``green card,'' granting him permanent resident
status, in 1993, with the support of former President Nixon,
President Bush and Robert McNamara, defense secretary in the
Kennedy and Johnson administrations, as well as top officials in
the Central Intelligence Agency.
</P>
<P>
   He has published several books about his father, who ruled the
Soviet Union from 1953 until he was deposed in 1964, and about the
Cold War that kept the world under threat of nuclear conflict.
Nikita Khrushchev died in virtual isolation on Sept. 11, 1971.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am lecturing here at Brown University on the history of the
Cold War, and I will teach Soviet history and post-Soviet history
next fall at the Naval War College in Newport, R.I.,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He has lectured at universities and World Affairs Council
functions in Seattle, sometimes with David Eisenhower and his wife,
Julie Nixon Eisenhower, both children of presidents who engaged in
conflicts with Khrushchev's father.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it is important for everyone to understand that many
of the mistakes made during the Cold War that led to dangerous
conflicts were based on misconceptions and misunderstandings of the
way of thinking
</P>
<P>
   of the other side,'' Khrushchev said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even today, the White House did not think Yugoslavia would
resist after NATO began bombing. When you see the whole picture of
how and why leaders make the decisions that they do, you create a
greater chance for resolving conflict and achieving peace.''
</P>
<P>
   Khrushchev has just published in Russia the four-volume memoirs
of his father containing many documents never before published, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   He and Pennsylvania State University Press hope to have an
English-language version published here. Khrushchev's own book on
the history of the Cold War and post-Soviet Russia is to be
published next month.
</P>
<P>
   Sergei Khrushchev's varied career included being chief of the
Soviet Missile Design Bureau from 1958 to 1968 and later service as
a professor of missile guidance systems at Moscow Technical
University.
</P>
<P>
   But his life in the United States has also meant explaining his
father's famous ``We will bury you'' remark.
</P>
<P>
   ``This comment was among the things that were misunderstood and
it shows how dangerous this type of misunderstanding can be,''
Sergei Khrushchev said.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the time, he was referring to a socialist centralized
economic system, which he believed would prevail and be more
effective than a free market system,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because of the unfortunate phrasing, it was understood
incorrectly to mean a threat to the safety of the people of the
United States. He never wanted to bury anybody, but he believed in
a Soviet centralized economy. In the end, a free-market system
prevailed.''
</P>
<P>
   Khrushchev said that both he and his wife have been studying for
their citizenship exams, the final step before their
naturalization.
</P>
<P>
   ``I learned a long time ago about America, but now I have to
remember the names and some dates _ and it is good for a teacher to
know what it is like to be a student now and then,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Khrushchev's immigration lawyer, Danilov, said Khrushchev's main
hesitancy in applying for U.S. citizenship was a concern over what
his father would think.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him that Papa will never know about it,'' said Danilov,
himself a naturalized American citizen.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
