<HEADLINE>
ACLU, ACTIVISTS CHALLENGE DOOR-TO-DOOR CANVASSING BAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By THOMAS FARRAGHER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONGMEADOW, Mass. _ As dusk gathers in this well-to-do town of
elegant homes and velvet lawns, a stranger's finger on the doorbell
can signal something worse than boorish company. The visitor may be
breaking the law.
</P>
<P>
   In a decision that has landed it in federal court, officials
here have decided _ with recent voter encouragement _ to ban
door-to-door canvassing after 8 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   The case has advocates on both sides vigorously staking claims
to conflicting fundamental freedoms.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit pits Colonial-era rights of free speech, symbolized
by Revolutionary War pamphleteers, against the privacy rights of
weary suburbanites who, after fighting traffic, collecting kids,
and fixing meals, just want to be left alone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to paint a picture that Longmeadow is being high
and mighty and we don't want (canvassers) in our town,'' said Hal
Haberman, a selectman in this town of 15,500 some 90 miles west of
Boston. ``We think we're being reasonable. Eight o'clock is late
enough. I have no idea why they're making such a big deal out of
this.''
</P>
<P>
   The federal suit, filed in US District Court in Springfield in
March, is being pursued by an environmental rights group, which
claims the town's bylaw, enacted last fall and reaffirmed by Town
Meeting voters earlier this month, is baldly unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
   ``We canvass between 4 and 9 because that's when people are
home,'' said Christopher C. Bathurst, director of the Northampton
office of Clean Water Action, a nonprofit advocacy group. ``And
between 8 and 9 is our real key time. If we're stripped away that
one hour, that's a huge percentage hit.''
</P>
<P>
   Clean Water Action's case is being championed by the
Massachusetts Civil Liberties Union, which 11 years ago won a
permanent injunction against a Longmeadow bylaw that barred
political lawn signs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been down this road before with Longmeadow,'' said
attorney William C. Newman, the ACLU lawyer who is representing
Clean Water Action pro bono. Newman said there is ample court
precedent for a 9 p.m. canvass cutoff, the hour used as quitting
time by US Census Bureau canvassers.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is at issue here is not just one hour. It's the crucial
hour,'' said Newman. ``This dismissiveness of First Amendment
rights is really troubling.''
</P>
<P>
   Newman and his clients said they hope the town will reconsider
the bylaw before the case moves ahead before a federal judge.
</P>
<P>
   ``If people don't want to talk to us, all they have to say is
that they're not interested and we're gone off their step,''
Bathurst said. ``We're not there to sell them anything. They just
need to tell us to go away and we'll go away.''
</P>
<P>
   Clean Water Action, which says it has 700,000 members nationwide
and 30,000 in Massachusetts, has between five and 20 canvassers
that work their way through the state's cities and towns. They are
paid a starting salary of $300 a week, urging voters to write
elected officials on specific issues, handing out fact sheets, and
asking for at least $2 _ the minimum membership fee.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really feel bad that there has been this strain put between
our organization and the good folks of Longmeadow. And we're not
happy about that,'' said Bathurst, whose group has canvassed here
since 1986. ``On the other hand, if every town decided they were
going to have an 8 o'clock ordinance, it would shut down that
portion of our outreach operation.''
</P>
<P>
   The town's decision to enact its ``Go Away'' policy stems from
complaints to local police from residents, who said they were tired
of being pestered by evening visitors, pushing policies, peddling
candies, or asking for money.
</P>
<P>
   Longmeadow modeled its bylaw on a similar one that has been in
effect, without complaint, in Walpole. Both bylaws have been
reviewed by the state attorney general's office, which found no
blatant constitutional problems but did not formally endorse them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were surprised that one hour was such a big issue,'' said
Julia Whitlock, the town administrator. ``People felt they were
being annoyed at hours they didn't particularly appreciate.
Obviously you can't stop it, and we recognize that you have to be
reasonable.''
</P>
<P>
   Whitlock said that for a good part of the year, darkness has
overtaken dusk by 8 p.m. _ no time for unwanted callers on the
doorstep.
</P>
<P>
   Warren Pelmas, a retired businessman and a longtime resident,
agrees, noting that the advocacy group is winning no friends in
Longmeadow by fighting the wishes of townspeople.
</P>
<P>
   ``After 8 o'clock people are putting kids to bed. It's a quiet
time,'' Pelmas said. ``I just don't understand the arrogance of
Clean Water Action. The people of this town have clearly expressed
their opinion that they don't want to be solicited. And the ACLU?
Don't they have something better to do than sue a small town?''
</P>
<P>
   But one person's down time is another person's prime time. And
for Clean Water Action, concerned about emissions from nearby power
plants and Hamden County asthma rates, the time to strike is when
people are at home.
</P>
<P>
   In court papers filed with its lawsuit, the group cites a 1973
US Commerce Department study that shows significantly more people
are at home between 8 and 9 p.m. than in the hours before that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hamden County has some of the worst air quality in the
state,'' Bathurst said. ``That's really bad news for the elderly
and kids with asthma. This is a big deal out here. So what we care
about is why we're out here. We're not out there because we want to
force a free-speech issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Longmeadow town counsel David J. Martel said a citizens advocacy
group successfully challenged a series of local bylaws in state
court in 1985 that sought to cut off door-to-door solicitation at
sunset, or restrict it to daylight hours. The court ruled then,
Martel said, that it was legal up until 9 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``But this will be a clear test between 8 o'clock and 9
o'clock,'' said Martel.
</P>
<P>
   Federal rulings in Connecticut and Wisconsin, which upheld the
right to solicit until 9 p.m., are not legally binding in the
Longmeadow case.
</P>
<P>
   But they could presage a legal setback that could mean
Longmeadow taxpayers, among the state's most affluent, would have
to pay the plaintiff's legal fees and perhaps tens of thousands of
dollars in damages.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where do you draw the line in these two competing interests?
That is what this is all about,'' Martel said. ``People would
prefer not to have people knocking on their doors, but at the same
time the First Amendment recognizes the right of people to go
door-to-door. The people of Longmeadow felt they wanted to draw the
line at 8 o'clock.''
</P>
<P>
   Haberman said the bylaw has nothing to do with the exclusivity
that non-residents sometimes attach to this wealthy bedroom
community _ median income $63,200 _ settled in the 1640s by
Springfield residents.
</P>
<P>
   ``People for the most part don't want people showing up at their
houses at that hour _ and that's anywhere,'' the selectman said.
Clean Water Action ``should have said, `OK. Eight o'clock is what
this community wants.' Instead it's a little like the little kid
who says, `If you don't let me play, I'm going to take my ball and
go home.' ''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
