<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-LOVE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STRIVING FOR A CAREER AS AN AMATEUR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CLEA SIMON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
FOR THE LOVE OF IT 
Amateuring and Its Rivals 
By Wayne Booth 
University of Chicago Press, 237 pp., illustrated, $22 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Wayne Booth knows about being an expert. A professor emeritus of
English at the University of Chicago and the author of several
books on style, Booth has spent much of his 70-something years as
the ultimate judge, the one giving the final word. What he is still
learning, as his endearing new book makes clear, is how to be an
amateur.
</P>
<P>
   Being an amateur is not the same as being a beginner, and it is
more than what Booth refers to as the ``without'' definition, that
is, more than just ``lacking professional skill or ease.'' As
Booth's playful prose in ``For the Love of It'' sets out to
explain, being an amateur can and should be a lifelong pursuit,
followed with honor and affection. His career (if one may call it
that) as an amateur cellist began more than 40 years ago when, at
age 31, he, an academic, decided to learn. That's when his lifelong
love of music combined with his attachment to (and mild jealousy
of) his violinist wife and the rare opportunity of leisure time to
allow him to begin lessons. Four decades later, he and his wife
play regularly in amateur chamber-music groups, continue to take
music lessons, and ponder the meaning of such a pursuit in an
increasingly professional world.
</P>
<P>
   This book _ really a collection of essays, along with bits of
dialogue taken from rehearsals and lessons _ is, like its subject,
a work of love and whimsy. As anyone who has decided to follow an
alternate pursuit, whether it be music or sandlot league sports,
knows, ``amateuring,'' as Booth terms it, comes in for a lot of
criticism. Professionals deride the quality of amateur work; the
more single-minded scoff at what may seem a dilettantish approach.
Booth tackles both of these critics _ focusing on the second _ in
his attempt to return to the word the dignity of its etymological
root: the Latin amo, or ``I love.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I do quite literally love to play the cello _ especially when
others are playing with me,'' he writes. Alternating between the
philosophical (``what makes a good teacher?'') and the
autobiographical, as well as between styles, this book serves as a
running commentary on the nature and depth of this love, and all
the connections it has formed in his life. As quickly becomes
clear, Booth loves his wife, he loves his music, and he loves his
instrument (though he is more than willing to admit to his ``cello
booboos'' and general inadequacies), and these passions inform his
arguments with a warmth that even his excellent and clear-minded
``The Rhetoric of Fiction'' lacked.
</P>
<P>
   This happy emotion, however, is not without conflicts, and Booth
does admit to the problems caused by his multiple focuses, mixing
such deeper issues in with the light-hearted observations. What
value, he asks repeatedly and in different ways, do we put on our
pursuits and on our time? ``To celebrate playing for the love of it
risks downplaying the work we do that we love.'' Why do we chose to
divert our limited financial, temporal, and mental resources to
learn an instrument? ``In retirement my desk seems _ and I'm sure
its an illusion _ much more deeply flooded with unperformed tasks
then it did when I was teaching full time,'' he writes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why bother at any stage of life to work for some new skill or
know-how instead of dwelling comfortably with skills already
mastered? . . . Isn't anything worth doing worth doing really well
_ better than you'll ever paint or photograph or golf or play chess
or surf or row a boat or perform the role of King Lear in an
amateur production? And meanwhile, what about all those rival ways
of spending . . . time?''
</P>
<P>
   An honest man, he lays out the real price of his amateur
playing. For a dedicated music lover, he explains, time spent
practicing takes away from time spent listening. ``A radical
sacrifice is made, day after day, year after year. I no longer
spend anything like an hour a day listening to professionals and I
miss it. Is the playing worth the sacrifice?''
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, he concludes, it is. This is true in no small part
because of the social interaction his playing of chamber music
facilitates. But beyond all, he admits, it is the music that draws
him. ``This morning,'' he writes. ``reading about the usual
atrocities in the morning paper, I hear intruding the lovely
pattern of ritardando arpeggios at the end of that slow movement. .
. . Sometimes, when we have worked especially hard and then
experienced an especially good session, the hangover will run on
for weeks.'' The music, he concludes, has become part of him, and
that is worth the price.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
