<SLUG> BC-VERMONT-OUTSIDER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OUTSPOKEN AUTHOR FINDS RESISTANCE IN A VERMONT TOWN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JUDITH GAINES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NORTH BENNINGTON, Vt. _ Jamaica Kincaid, the author who writes
and sometimes speaks with a rapier, insists this story is not about
her.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's about a small town and people acting in a high-handed
way,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   And she claims it's about a problem all too common in Vermont
and other New England states: How siall, self-perpetuating cliques
run their communities by whim and happenstance, ignoring views that
don't jibe with their own.
</P>
<P>
   What touched off the current controversy was the village's
decision to deny the celebrated author a seat on its planning
commission, despite her having been the only one interested in the
job for months.
</P>
<P>
   Local leaders in this southern Vermont village, population
1,400, don't think broader issues are at stake. They question
Kincaid's motives and say they're uncomfortable with her outsider
status and prickly personality. After all, how could they work with
a woman who called the chairman of the board ``incompetent''?
</P>
<P>
   ``You can understand how they might think, if she thinks we're a
bunch of fools, how's it going to be to have her working with us?''
said John Ulrich, a second-grade teacher who heads North
Bennington's Board of Trustees.
</P>
<P>
   In April, the commission unanimously recommended and the
trustees approved the appointment of a 28-year-old native, Jonah
Thiem, instead of Kincaid, 50, who was born in Antigua.
</P>
<P>
   Kincaid's wrenching memoir, ``My Brother,'' was recently
nominated for the National Book Award. The New York Times has
described her as ``a ferociously honest woman (who operates) on her
own uncompromising terms.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Kevan Jones, who headed the five-member planning
commission when Kincaid's application was turned down, the
commissioners favored Thiem because he was employed in the county
as a social worker, belongs to a younger generation that needs to
be more involved in public affairs, and was born and raised in
North Bennington.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was the most familiar with our area,'' said Jones, 76, a
retired architect. ``He has firsthand knowledge of what people in
this community need.''
</P>
<P>
   Kincaid countered, ``I understand them perfectly well. They
don't understand me.''
</P>
<P>
   Ulrich added that Kincaid's application wasn't helped by some of
her caustic public comments, including calling Jones incompetent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was being generous in calling him incompetent,'' Kincaid
retorted.
</P>
<P>
   She said she's just exercising her democratic right to criticize
the laxness and wrongdoing she sees in the village government.
</P>
<P>
   She pointed to several questionable actions by the commission
and the board, including that her application was denied without a
hearing, and that Jones sought another applicant for the opening
after she applied, when his term of office had expired.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no question that obvious things about me also play
into this: I'm a woman, I'm black,'' Kincaid said.
</P>
<P>
   North Bennington has barely a half-dozen black families, and
Vermont has the fewest blacks of any state in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   But several trustees and commissioners insisted that neither
race nor gender figured in their decision. Some pointed to another
issue: Kincaid applied for the job after a private school for
troubled teens proposed to convert a house adjacent to her property
into a dormitory.
</P>
<P>
   ``Prior to that, she hadn't shown any interest'' in the
commission, said Ron Pembroke, a landscape contractor on the Board
of Trustees. ``It appeared that she wanted to block that.''
</P>
<P>
   Kincaid said she opposed the dormitory conversion but not for
reasons of narrow self-interest. In any case, she observed, ``What
is democracy but a practical daily exercise? It isn't just
theoretical . . . We the people, you bet!''
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Gray, a jeweler who has just resigned from the planning
commission, said Kincaid's charges ``have totally caught me by
surprise.''
</P>
<P>
   North Bennington ``is a pretty WASP-y area, without a lot of
cultural diversity,'' he said. But in his nearly four years on the
commission, he said he never saw any actions that smacked of racism
or sexism.
</P>
<P>
   Those who abuse power often fail to recognize their
shortcomings, Kincaid countered. ``It's not out of the blue at all.
It's here every day. The commission has an absence of critical
consciousness.''
</P>
<P>
   If North Bennington is run by a clique, then it's a laid-back,
artsy, well-intentioned bunch, several locals say.
</P>
<P>
   It's the sort of place that has no traffic lights, or street
numbers on houses. Folks work at Bennington College, or the local
schools, or the hospital, or one of a few small industries. Quite a
few are artists or writers. Authors Bernard Malamud and Shirley
Jackson have both lived here.
</P>
<P>
   The local hangout is Powers' Market, a friendly gourmet grocery
store selling items such as sesame noodles, pates, baked homemade
potato chips, and specialty olive oils.
</P>
<P>
   With only four paid employees, the village relies on voluntary
labor for most public tasks.
</P>
<P>
   The type of question that usually comes before the planning
commission ``is whether someone should have to take down their
Christmas lights or whether a porch extension will fit on
somebody's property,'' Ulrich said. ``It's pretty dry stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   In the last five years, there has never been more than one
candidate for any spot on the commission. So no one has really
scrutinized its selection process.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, Ulrich added, the commissioners are just
volunteers, doing the best they can. ``There's not enough action to
warrant hiring professionals.''
</P>
<P>
   This is part of what Kincaid means when she complains about
laxness and cliquish behavior. A resident who is involved in local
affairs but declined to give his name agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lethargy in North Bennington,'' he said. ``It's a
bedroom community that houses people with a higher than normal
amount of socio-economic success. They're well-intentioned people
who don't have the time or technical expertise to cope with federal
rules and fulfill their responsibilities.''
</P>
<P>
   Joseph J. Joseph, 76, a retired school superintendent, called it
``the North Bennington Syndrome.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The symptoms are: If you criticize the status quo because you
don't think the way they think or believe that due process is being
followed, you're ostracized,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In general, people who express unpopular or unfamiliar ideas are
greeted with ``a gentle type of sarcasm. It's a question of
attitude,'' Joseph said. ``In Jamaica's case, though, the behavior
was more extreme.''
</P>
<P>
   But this is a story that may end more happily than most of
Kincaid's searing, powerful books.
</P>
<P>
   When Jones and Gray stepped down from the planning commission
(both for personal reasons unconnected to the controversy, they
said), Kincaid decided to reapply.
</P>
<P>
   ``More likely than not, she'll be appointed,'' Ulrich said.
</P>
<P>
   And Kincaid has also agreed to join a group working to revise
the village master plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm glad she didn't go off in a huff and say that we're just a
bunch of hicks and good ol' boys,'' Ulrich said. ``We see that she
has a lot to offer.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
