<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AILING HMOS FORCED TO PASS ALONG HIGHER COSTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN SYRE AND CHARLES STEIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Massachusetts's big health maintenance organizations did some
serious financial bleeding in the first quarter of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Harvard Pilgrim Health Care and Fallon Community Health had big
losses; Tufts Health Plan had a modest loss; Blue Cross and Blue
Shield of Massachusetts eked out a small profit. The numbers for
1998 looked no better.
</P>
<P>
   Can the HMOs recover? The answer is probably yes. In fact, an
easy-to-follow model has already been laid out by the nation's big
investor-owned HMOs, most of which have managed to turn losses into
profits over the past year.
</P>
<P>
   There's only one problem: The steps the HMOs take to get better
are likely to leave the rest of us feeling worse.
</P>
<P>
   Nationally, HMOs began running into trouble in 1997. The problem
was not difficult to diagnose. A slowdown in medical inflation that
began a few years earlier convinced corporate America that
health-care costs had plateaued permanently. As a result, companies
dug in their heels and bargained for the lowest rates they could
get.
</P>
<P>
   The HMOs were happy to comply. They too seemed to feel they had
a handle on costs. Emboldened, they cut their rates in many parts
of the country in a bid to win market share from rivals.
</P>
<P>
   Life would have been wonderful for everyone if only medical
costs truly had stopped rising. Unfortunately they had not. Driven
by double-digit increases in the cost of prescription drugs, health
costs have moved off the plateau and started climbing a new
mountain.
</P>
<P>
   You don't need a degree in medicine or accounting to figure out
that an insurer who cuts his rates while his costs are rising is
going to lose money.
</P>
<P>
   Pacificare Health Systems, a big California HMO, lost money in
1997. United Healthcare, based in Minnesota, had a whopping loss in
the second quarter of 1998. Connecticut-based Oxford Health Plans
lost so much money in the second quarter of 1998 that the company
looked as if it might not survive.
</P>
<P>
   Fast-forward to the first quarter of 1999 and the picture is
very different. All three HMOs were profitable in the quarter, and
all three have seen their stock prices rebound smartly in the past
six weeks.
</P>
<P>
   What happened? Two things, actually. In all cases, the HMOs
raised their prices, anywhere from 7 percent to 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of these HMOs were at the point where they were not
viable,'' says Peter Zuger, a portfolio manager at State Street
Research in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   The price hikes were not a one-time event. The California Public
Employees Retirement System last week said the rates it pays HMOs
will climb 9.7 percent next year. As one of the nation's leading
purchasers of health care, Calpers tends to be a trendsetter for
the nation. In other words, the west wind is likely to blow east.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two years ago a 1 percent rate hike was unusual,'' says Susan
Connolly, an executive with William M. Mercer, a benefits
consulting firm. ``Now some companies are talking about
double-digit increases.''
</P>
<P>
   The second action the investor-owned HMOs took to restore
profitability was no more popular. They stopped serving patients in
lines of business that were losing money. United Healthcare dropped
out of the Medicare program in certain markets. Aetna, another big
HMO, withdrew from Medicare in six states, including Massachusetts.
Oxford withdrew from the Medicaid program in New York state.
Medicare is a government insurance plan for senior citizens;
Medicaid is a government plan for low-income people.
</P>
<P>
   The HMOs insisted that government _ both state and federal _ was
paying them too little to take care of people. They may be right.
In the meantime, however, several hundred thousand people around
the country have had to find new insurance providers.
</P>
<P>
   Could the same steps be taken here? It is already happening. All
of the major local HMOs have announced big rates hikes for next
year. Perhaps because this market is dominated by not-for-profit
HMOs, the companies here were slower to raise rates than their
investor-owned counterparts. That distinction won't last. Harvard
Pilgrim has announced rate increases of 8 to 10 percent for 2000;
Tufts has told customers to expect increases of 6 to 9 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Last year both Tufts and Blue Cross said they would no longer
participate in the state's Medicaid program. None of the major
players has quit the Medicare business, but such a move cannot be
ruled out, say those in the industry.
</P>
<P>
   Many will blame the HMOs for these hard-nosed tactics. After
all, weren't they supposed to hold down the cost of health care,
rather than passing it on to the rest of us?
</P>
<P>
   In theory, yes. But in practice, the rest of us have made it
clear we are not interested in living in a world in which HMOs
aggressively try to cut costs. We don't want our choice of doctors
or drugs restricted; nor do we want to see our doctors and
hospitals squeezed too hard. We want the best, even if we don't
always want to pay for it.
</P>
<P>
   As Pogo might have put it: ``We have met the enemy and he is
us.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Steven Syre and Charles Stein can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
