<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAFRICA-MANDELA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS HIS TERM ENDS, MANDELA GETS MIXED REVIEWS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KURT SHILLINGER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JOHANNESBURG _ On the day Nelson Mandela was sworn in as South
Africa's first democratically elected president, the country was in
tatters. More than 10,000 people had died in political violence
while Mandela's African National Congress and the former government
negotiated the end of apartheid.
</P>
<P>
   The economy held a flat growth rate for five years. The law
books were heavy with the statutes of the old order. The needs of
the masses were overwhelming: 12 million people had no reasonable
access to potable water; 64 percent of households did not have
electricity; the vast majority of blacks did not have adequate
health care. And the military, civil service, police and judiciary
all rested in the hands of white men.
</P>
<P>
   Five years later much has changed in South Africa, and much
remains to be changed. As Mandela prepares to step off the
political stage and into retirement after the June 2 elections, his
leadership draws as much harsh criticism as it does warm praise.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we talk about Mandela the president, we can only talk on
the symbolic, moral level,'' said Themba Sono, a University of
Pretoria professor. ``He was instrumental in averting a racial war,
but as an effective, hands-on president, he was an absolute
disaster.''
</P>
<P>
   While managing to soothe fearful whites as he led the nation's
first black majority government, Mandela largely failed to uplift
blacks. He often placed party and personal loyalties above the
national interest, and he leaves a nation no longer at war, but not
yet at peace with itself.
</P>
<P>
   But from where Mandela started there clearly is progress. Ahmed
Cathrada, Mandela's longtime comrade and fellow prisoner for 27
years, recalls what he found the day he walked into his new office
as the president's parliamentary counselor. ``Nothing. There wasn't
a scrap of paper. We had to start from scratch,'' he said in an
interview.
</P>
<P>
   The political deal ending apartheid required Mandela to form a
government jointly with the dominant opposition parties. Former
foes would share the job of creating the new dispensation. One
hundred days into his administration, in his first budget address
to parliament, Mandela defined the course: ``From the outset, the
government of national unity set itself two interrelated tasks:
reconciliation and reconstruction, nation-building and
development.''
</P>
<P>
   By either index _ reconciliation or reconstruction _ the
achievements of Mandela's government are limited.
</P>
<P>
   Race relations are no better today than in 1994. According to a
public survey conducted last month for the Independent Newspaper
Group, 44 percent of respondents agreed that ``blacks and whites
will never trust each other,'' while on 24 percent disagreed. Only
8 percent of whites said they would not be bothered if their
children married across the race line. The study found that ``when
black and white South Africans talk about unity and reconciliation
it seems they are talking about different things.'' In general
terms, blacks see reconciliation as an equal division of the
country's resources; whites simply want to stop talking about the
past.
</P>
<P>
   Mandela can rightly claim that his government brought clean
drinking water within 200 yards of the dwellings of 3 million
people. His government promised to build 1 million houses in five
years, but as of last December _ the latest that statistics are
available _ 681,000 were either finished or under construction.
Some 2.3 million more households have electricity. Compared with
any previous five-year period, those represent unprecedented
advances.
</P>
<P>
   But unemployment hovers near 40 percent. The economy is growing
at less than 2 percent. Thousands of schools are overcrowded, lack
textbooks and have no electricity; barely 53 percent of high school
seniors pass their final exams and qualify for graduation. Health
care is now free for children under age 6, but township clinics are
ill-equipped and the standard of care available to the majority
continues to decline.
</P>
<P>
   South Africa has the highest rate of rape in the world, and
other forms of violent crime continue to rise, including brazen
attacks on police stations. At the same time, police statistics
indicate that conviction rates have fallen steadily each of the
past five years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Take the gamut from land reform to education, the policies of
Mandela's government were weak,'' said Mahmood Mamdani, a professor
of African Studies at the University of Cape Town. ``They've come
with good intentions but without a proper grasp on the situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that they haven't tried. The new Gender Commission and the
Human Rights Commission are meant to be independent protectors of
civil rights, while the Employment Equity Act and the Basic
Conditions of Employment Act were designed to give the
long-oppressed more access to professional work and greater rights
on the shop floor.
</P>
<P>
   Despite these measures, however, ``there is a widening gap
between policy and delivery and with that comes rising social
tension,'' said Graeme Simpson, director of the Center for the
Study of Violence and Reconciliation in Johannesburg. ``The most
marginalized _ women, children, and black youth _ are even more
marginalized. We shouldn't be surprised that there is sustained
violence.''
</P>
<P>
   Mandela began his presidency inheriting a reluctant civil
service. Mandela's ANC, still more of a liberation movement that a
political party, lacked both the research capacity and experience
for effective policymaking. Experts hailed a national crime
prevention strategy as it looked on paper, but it has had little
impact.
</P>
<P>
   Mandela's instincts did not always serve him or the nation well.
He peopled his Cabinet with comrades from the anti-apartheid
struggle, and refused to reprimand or remove them either for
incompetence or mismanagement. ``It is part of our morality,'' he
said last fall at the White House, ``that we do not abandon our
friends.'' As a result, his foreign policy was neither consistent
nor, at times, coherent.
</P>
<P>
   His loyalty to party also led to problems. The ANC, still more
of a liberation movement that a political party, lacked both the
research capacity and experience for effective policymaking.
</P>
<P>
   During the first three years of his adminstration, Mandela made
highly symbolic gestures toward the white minority to avoid
alienating it as the majority took the reins of power. In December
1997, his tone shifted dramatically. From that point on, his
speeches, penned by Deputy President Thabo Mbeki, carried an
increasingly strident theme: Whites have an obligation to pay back
the social debt of their privilege.
</P>
<P>
   The speeches are just one way that Mandela, obsessed with
creating a smooth transition after his departure, allowed his
tenure to be shaped by those below him. Midway through his
presidency, he began relinquishing day-to-day control to Mbeki, who
is expected to win the June 2 elections.
</P>
<P>
   That ceding of power led to tensions from within, as Mbeki's
policies strayed from Mandela's priorities. As he leaves office,
Mandela is unlikely to be held to account for his contradictions
and shortfalls.
</P>
<P>
   He met South Africa's need at a delicate time.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really were looking for a monarch in 1994,'' Sono said.
``There could have been a racial holocaust in this country. It is
that that most of us would like to remember.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-25-99 1340EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
