<DOCNO> NYT19990525.0082 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-25 13:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0254 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLIPHANT-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      05-25 0803
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLIPHANT-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MENINO, CUOMO SET EXAMPLE ON RACE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By THOMAS OLIPHANT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Case closed.
</P>
<P>
   And the right way, too.
</P>
<P>
   What erupted as a demeaning spitting match nearly four months
ago between two of the better pols in America _ Housing and Urban
Development Secretary Andrew Cuomo and Boston Mayor Thomas Menino _
has been settled in a way that gives politics (as in the grease
that makes government work) a good name.
</P>
<P>
   And in the case of the politics of race, which was at the core
of the conflict, what gives this settlement a good aroma is that it
does not appear to have involved any compromise of consequence.
Instead, the deal affirmed the legitimate positions of the locals
and the feds without affecting a policy of zero tolerance for hate
and racism (in this case, in public housing projects).
</P>
<P>
   The wise guys around here have picked over the settlement's
entrails to discern winner and loser. But in the process they
missed the beneficiary of the late-blooming good will: Vice
President Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   It could not have been more obvious, but there was Mayor Menino,
the big cheese at a Boston fund-raising dinner for Gore, glowing as
best as this direct man can, introducing the vice president in the
most personal of terms, reflecting what has become (via empowerment
zones, public education reform, and other specific interactions) a
friendship.
</P>
<P>
   But however personal the mayor's early support of Gore for the
Democratic presidential nomination, don't think it would have been
possible had this avoidable mess between the mayor and the
secretary not been cleaned up quickly. As it was, there was more
than one mayoral intimate who thought Menino should do more
political bargaining before making an endorsement decision.
</P>
<P>
   Not the least among those urging the course Menino took,
however, was another big-time mayor who took the step way back last
year. Chicago's Rich Daley is Menino's soul brother on the subject
of taking charge and responsibility for the public schools in order
to be a force for higher standards and reform; they are close. And
if there is ever a Gore administration, no two mayors in the United
States will have more clout than Daley and Menino.
</P>
<P>
   For all this to happen, two pols had to come together without so
much as a wink at the hate and racism that must always be opposed
wherever they rear their heads. And this is big-time hate and
racism, what HUD investigators properly termed systematic
discrimination against nonwhite tenants in South Boston and
Charlestown that reached the moral equivalent of torture earlier in
the decade.
</P>
<P>
   Cuomo needed to deal with oversights; Menino couldn't avert his
eyes from the essential truth of the findings, not that he would.
</P>
<P>
   For HUD, the basic problem in February was context and
perspective. The initial report properly focused on horrid
incidents involving nine families, in effect providing the federal
government's factual blessing on a situation that spells civil
rights lawsuit, especially in the face of chronic and documented
official neglect and unresponsiveness. In fact, the class-action
litigation has been kicking around for three years, all but crying
out for settlement by a responsive city.
</P>
<P>
   But the report was much more limited in time than its
explosiveness acknowledged, in effect allowing an impression that
nothing had changed since the 1992-96 period that was its focus.
The report also hit what remains Boston's exposed nerve of race;
there's a lot of history here (most of it bad), but also a lot of
recent history (a lot of it good), and for all the local intensity,
the truth is that Boston isn't close to unique.
</P>
<P>
   The remedy was obvious: a follow-on study of the last three
years, another 150 interviews, and 23 more pages of report that
focused on the events of the last three years under a public
housing administrator, Sandra Henriquez, who is getting national
attention in this tough field. This one was brought to town by
Cuomo himself and unveiled with the mayor himself.
</P>
<P>
   Menino pledged diligence in carrying out HUD's 50-plus
recommendations for further changes. Cuomo stressed that Boston is
a symptom of a national problem, that its work since 1996 has been
more than promising, but that hate crimes and discrimination are
still present. No quarrel from Menino, who got a chance to reaffirm
his policy of zero tolerance.
</P>
<P>
   With different principals, this could have all gotten out of
hand and turned inflammatory. That it became something positive,
and that two days later Menino was in a hotel ballroom endorsing
Gore, is a tribute to what the original Mayor Daley (Rich's dad)
liked to call ``good government.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Thomas Oliphant is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
