<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-CHAIN-GANGS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLAN FOR MASSACHUSETTS CHAIN GANG BRINGS CONCERN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JORDANA HART  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Chain gangs of inmates, shackled ankle-to-ankle like on old
South highways, are coming to Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time in this state, a county sheriff will lock
teams of nonviolent convicts together in leg irons and send them
out to clean streets, paint curbs, and pick vegetables at farms.
</P>
<P>
   Bristol County Sheriff Thomas M. Hodgson said the inmates,
dressed in bright red jumpsuits and followed by two armed guards,
will learn teamwork and valuable life experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not punitive,'' Hodgson said. ``Right now, (inmates)
have not been able to access an opportunity to develop a work
ethic. This also gives them another benefit: Learning teamwork.
Five guys connected by a restraint means they have to learn to
cooperate with each other.''
</P>
<P>
   Hodgson's plan to introduce chain gangs next month touched off
outrage among civil liberties advocates, who said a practice that
evokes old images of Southern slavery and shame does not belong in
Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't believe it at first,'' said John Roberts, director of
the American Civil Liberties Union of Massachusetts. ``It is the
kind of thing that brings up images of an era we like to think is
gone. It is the kind of punishment that puts people in public
humiliation. I hope this doesn't spread'' to other houses of
correction.
</P>
<P>
   Joshua Rubenstein, northeast regional director for Amnesty
International, is calling state legislators, asking them to protest
or outlaw chain gangs. Southeastern Massachusetts lawmakers could
not immediately be reached.
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts will join nine other states _ most of them in the
South or West _ that use what corrections officials call ``tandem
work crews.'' Alabama was the first to resurrect chain gangs in
1995 following a 30-year nationwide hiatus.
</P>
<P>
   Hodgson says the unpaid chain gangs will give work experience to
inmates who until now were ineligible to leave the jail on
traditional prerelease work crews because they have too much time
left to serve. Participation is voluntary.
</P>
<P>
   The chain gang did not seem a popular notion with other
sheriffs, who said they plan to stick with their prerelease work
crews.
</P>
<P>
   Governor Paul Cellucci had no position on the plan.
</P>
<P>
   Hodgson said no sex offenders or inmates with serious records
would be allowed on the chain gang. He plans to have three crews of
five inmates, and hopes to send them out each day.
</P>
<P>
   Some sheriffs refused to criticize Hodgson, but also said the
topic of chain gangs had not come up in sheriff association
meetings.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my case, I see no need for it,'' said Worcester County
Sheriff John Flynn, recent past president of the Massachusetts
Sheriffs Association. ``But I don't fault (Hodgson) if he thinks
that is good. These people committed a crime and they owe society.
I am not worried about degrading inmates.''
</P>
<P>
   Flynn said he sends out up to 50 prerelease inmates in crews to
paint municipal buildings and undertake other public projects. Like
other work crews, his are made up of inmates with six months or
less left to serve, and though they are supervised, they are not in
restraints. Their incentive to flee is considered minimal since
they are near the end of their jail terms.
</P>
<P>
   The chain gang program meshes with the get-tough policies
Hodgson launched as soon as he took over as sheriff. He took away
many inmate privileges, including smoking, television, and weights.
He started charging inmates $5 for medical visits and haircuts.
Also, he increased education programs and offered weekend religious
retreats in the prison gymnasium.
</P>
<P>
   Hodgson is also considering a chain gang for the 70 women jailed
in Bristol County.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no play time anymore when you come to jail,'' he
said. ``The system basically set up inmates for failure. We told
them we would pay for everything and that they didn't have to do a
thing.''
</P>
<P>
   He acknowledged that the public may have to get used to seeing
the inmates chained together. In fact, he prefers to avoid the term
``chain gang.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't want to call them chain gangs since that relies on
old images and is associated with being cruel,'' he said. ``We are
giving them a portable restraint and are using their talents to get
more done for the community. They have to be restrained because of
the time they have left'' to serve.
</P>
</TEXT>
