<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTHOR-BLUME-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANDY BLUME: AIR APPARENT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL KENNEY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   OVER FITCHBURG, Mass. _ Randy Blume is at the controls of a
rented Piper Warrior II, and despite the fact that it's been a few
years since she's flown single-engine four-seaters, it is clear
that the air _ from a pilot's seat _ is her element.
</P>
<P>
   Blume is making this hop out to Fitchburg and back to help
promote her just-published first novel, ``Crazy in the Cockpit.''
Even with her worn leather flying jacket _ a souvenir from when she
flew 727s out of Guam for Continental _ tossed in a back seat,
Blume looks the part, with a face permanently weathered from years
of sitting in sun-drenched cockpits and eyes that instinctively
squint when she takes off her blue-tinted shades.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking into her classic David Clark headset, she reminds her
passenger, ``Keep a lookout for traffic, will you?''
</P>
<P>
   That's because the small Fitchburg airfield, nestled in a bowl
just outside of downtown, is ``uncontrolled,'' which means there is
no control tower to alert pilots to other aircraft in the vicinity.
</P>
<P>
   Then _ perhaps because the 5-foot-2 Blume, ``barely,'' she says
ruefully, has to take one hand off the controls to pull herself up
enough to look out over the rounded top edge of the instrument
panel _ another request: ``Look out, too, will you, for a place we
can land. That's always good to know in case the engine quits.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Like a good football field?'' her passenger asks.
</P>
<P>
   ``A big plowed field is better,'' Blume replies.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The exchange could have come right out of ``Crazy in the
Cockpit.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(itals) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I filled out the landing data form and passed it to Neil.
``There seem to be wild pigs on the runway,'' I said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wild pigs?'' he asked. ``What does that mean?''
</P>
<P>
   ``It means we should overfly the runway and take a look,''
Duncan said, scratching his armpit and then sniffing his hand.
</P>
<P>
   Neil assented, and I told (the air traffic controller) our
plans, then made an announcement on the PA explaining to the
passengers what we'd be doing.
</P>
<P>
   When we flew over the runway, and sure enough, there was a group
of pigs sitting on the tarmac.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bummer,'' Neil said, looking uncertain.
</P>
<P>
   ``Try buzzing them off,'' Duncan suggested.
</P>
<P>
   Neil descended to 500 feet and roared across the runway.
</P>
<P>
   The pigs didn't move.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought pigs were supposed to be smart,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are smart,'' Duncan said. ``They know precisely where to
sit to block the runway.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(unitals) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Randy Blume, 38, is a confessed teenage bookworm and the
daughter of author Judy Blume. That she wrote a novel _ even a
novel about a woman who chooses flying over law _ should come as no
big surprise.
</P>
<P>
   But that she was the young woman who chose flight school over
law school takes some explaining. ``I knew it was totally alien to
the way I was brought up,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Blume, who now lives in Cambridge, Mass., grew up in suburban
New Jersey and, after her mother divorced and remarried, Los
Alamos. Blume's father is a New York lawyer. She says that she was
probably always interested in airplanes _ ``It's what I remember
from going on vacations,'' she says. But more to the point, halfway
through high school, she discovered adventure through an Outward
Bound course. She was, Blume recalls, the petite tenderfoot who
fell over backwards when she first hitched a backpack over her
shoulders. But, she adds, ``I went from being the last person in
line with people yelling at me to catch up, (to) being the
leader.''
</P>
<P>
   Kendra, her heroine pilot in ``Crazy in the Cockpit,'' discovers
the lure of flying as an assignment for a college journalism
course. ``But I didn't go into flying to have something to write
about,'' Blume says.
</P>
<P>
   It was even more serendipitous than that. During her junior year
at Wesleyan University, in Middletown, Conn., a roommate's
boyfriend reported that he had taken flying lessons over the summer
and had ``soloed.'' On the strength of just that, Blume went up for
one lesson at Hartford's old Brainard Field.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was cool enough that I wanted to do it again,'' she says.
``I became totally obsessed. I read flying magazines tucked inside
textbooks. I wrote all my papers about flying. And I knew that I
wanted to be an airline pilot.''
</P>
<P>
   She had her private pilot's license by the time she graduated in
1983. That summer at her mother's vacation home on Martha's
Vineyard, when she was supposed to be getting ready for law school,
she was spending all her earnings on flying magazines.
</P>
<P>
   ``If that's what you want to do . . . '' she remembers her
mother saying. ``And that was all the permission I needed,'' says
the daughter. (Judy Blume did exercise some veto power over the
choice of a flying school, looking askance at flying-magazine
advertisements that featured ``come fly with me'' bikinied young
women.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL; 
(itals) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``How could this have happened?'' my mother wailed when I'd told
her I was deferring graduate school to become a professional pilot.
``I've sent you to the best schools. I took you to museums,
concerts, the theater. I kept the house filled with books. I didn't
let you watch TV or eat Twinkies. Where did I go wrong?''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(unitals)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The question of the mother-daughter relationship seems to touch
a nerve. The inevitable question: ``How much of the book is real?''
brings a carefully considered response.
</P>
<P>
   ``The flying is all true,'' she says. ``It's pretty much exactly
as it happened. It's pretty hard to make too much up in this book.
I suppose I could have, but I've flown into those towns and I've
flown those planes.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the people are composites,'' she says. ``Especially the
mother. It's very important that I say that.''
</P>
<P>
   And just as ``there are a few lines in her books that are things
that I had said,'' Blume says, recalling that Judy Blume's classic
``Blubber'' is based on an incident in school she told her mother
about, ``there are a few lines that my mother said that got into my
book.''
</P>
<P>
   But, she adds emphatically, ``the mother character is not my
mother.''
</P>
<P>
   Judy Blume, incidentally, does not like flying _ even in
commercial jets.
</P>
<P>
   Blume has flown her father, John Blume, around to legal
appointments in southern California but she has taken her mother up
only once, a spin out over San Francisco Bay. ``I think she thought
it was a mother thing to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Blume is divorced and is raising her son, Elliot, as a single
mother. ``One spring day when I was still married and living in
Beverly, I grabbed Elliot, who was 3, and took him flying with
me.''
</P>
<P>
   `` `Isn't this cool?' I asked him when we came down. `I don't
see what's so cool about it,' he said. `I have to sit in my car
seat just like in the car.' ''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
(itals) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the dream, I was flying a jet for a major airline. I was the
captain, but the first officer was telling me what to do because my
uniform hat (which had been designed for a man) kept slipping over
my eyes and I couldn't see. We were flying low, over the ocean, and
it was very dark. I was nervous because I didn't know how to land a
jet, but the first officer said we wouldn't have to worry about
landing if we just flew under the water. I didn't think the
airplane was supposed to get wet, but I pushed the control wheel
forward anyway. Just as the water started to splash over the
windshield, the phone rang.
</P>
<P>
   ``Want a charter?'' It was Dale, one of the pilots for Golden
Gate Aviation . . . where I was the senior charter pilot and,
because there weren't many charters, also a flight instructor.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(unitals) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   After two and a half years of flying for Continental Airlines,
Blume gave it up in 1989 to get pregnant. ``My obstetrician asked,
`How can you get pregnant if you're away four nights a week?' I was
flying for Continental out of Newark and was pretty senior, but it
wasn't working too well for my marriage and the airline lifestyle
was not the way I wanted to raise a child.''
</P>
<P>
   So, out of the job she loved, Blume started to write about it.
The book could have been a memoir, but publisher DK Ink wanted a
novel, and that's how it turned out.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Blume says, ``for the first time since I left, I'm really
starting to consider going back to flying. Elliot's life is stable,
he's going into second grade. I could go back to flight instructing
tomorrow, but I wouldn't make enough to pay the baby sitter. What
I'd love is to be on call for a charter company.''
</P>
<P>
   The love is still palpable as Randy Blume reminisces for a bit.
</P>
<P>
   ``My first commuter job was for East Hampton Air on Long
Island,'' she recalls. ``It was a 15-seat turboprop, and I couldn't
believe they were letting me do it.
</P>
<P>
   ``And then at Continental, I couldn't believe that they let me
take this 727, this big fun airplane.
</P>
<P>
   ``It still holds that appeal.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL; 
(itals) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The interphone rang (interrupting our cockpit waterfight), and I
picked it up.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's going on up there?'' Milli asked. I've got 21 medical
emergencies, and now Paulina is crying in the galley, saying we're
all going to die. Can I get a little reassurance, please?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything's fine,'' I said, choking back hysterics. ``I can't
imagine what she's talking about.''
</P>
<P>
   And suddenly, everything was fine. We were going to get to
Honolulu, and I was going to make it to Boston. Within a few months
I would be upgrading to first officer. . . .
</P>
<P>
   By the time Diamond Head came into sight, we'd cleaned up the
cockpit and dried off as well as we could. We all had wet sticky
hair, but we were too tired to care. . . .
</P>
<P>
   ``Are all Atoll Locals like this one?'' Neil asked as we taxied
to the gate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Atoll Locals are just like any other kind of flying,'' Duncan
said. ``Boring in the back, crazy in the cockpit.''
</P>
<P>
   (unitals) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
