<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WARSH-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO SUCH THING AS A FREE PLANE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID WARSH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Joel Klein, the assistant attorney general for antitrust who
has Microsoft Corp. on the run, earlier this month accused American
Airlines of driving upstart competitors out of business at its
Dallas-Fort Worth hub.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department accused the airline of slashing fares and
adding flights when three low-price airlines started flying from
its hometown airport, then raising prices again when they left. The
intent, said the complaint, was to preserve the artificially high
profits of a near-monopoly.
</P>
<P>
   The suit raised eyebrows. There have been few predatory pricing
complaints since the Reagan administration, when the largely
nonpartisan ``law and economics'' movement brought a new
sophistication about economic analysis to the federal bench and
bar. The suit is the first brought against an airline since the
industry was deregulated in 1978.
</P>
<P>
   Former US Solicitor General Robert Bork, who represents American
Airlines, was quick to claim that the government's case ``attempts
to revive a long-discredited, anticonsumer theory of
monopolization.''
</P>
<P>
   But those who think there is nothng new in antitrust economics
since the legendary Aaron Director taught the subject in the 1950s
and 1960s at the University of Chicago law school are in for a big
surprise.
</P>
<P>
   They probably include American Airlines.
</P>
<P>
   Take what appears to be the central tenet of the government
case. To prove a violation of the Sherman Act, government lawyers
must show that American's fares _ which matched but did not go
below its competitors' fares _ were below American's ``average
variable costs'' for the routes.
</P>
<P>
   In determining those costs, the government wants to include the
costs of the resources shifted to the new routes from other parts
of the far-flung American empire _ especially the ``ownership
costs'' of additional aircraft, in the form of their short-term
rental equivalents.
</P>
<P>
   Only by omitting such costs from its accounting formula can
American claim to be pricing at and not below average variable
cost, says the government.
</P>
<P>
   Bork opposes this ``creative redefinition.'' There is no
rent-a-plane company that would enable airlines to vary the size of
their fleet on short notice, he says. Therefore the measure of what
it would cost to lease a similar plane is without meaning.
Ownership cost is ``a figment of antitrust imagination,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Yet rental equivalence has become a familiar concept in
measurement economics during the last 30 years, employed in gauging
everything from tax liabilities to the consumer price index and the
cost of capital, to say nothing of its widespread use in contracts.
</P>
<P>
   Requiring American to impute a cost to the airplanes it shifts
around to meet increased competition is the opposite of unfair; it
is sound business practice.
</P>
<P>
   There is, after all, no such thing as a free airplane.
</P>
<P>
   The issue of ownership costs is just the beginning of American's
peril. Microeconomics has changed steadily in the past fifteen
years.
</P>
<P>
   Our understanding of networks and how they may be used to
diminish competition is greatly enhanced, thanks to increasingly
ventilated issues in telecommunications, computers, credit cards,
and now, airline hubs.
</P>
<P>
   The government's case has a long way to go. It is one thing to
assert that ownership costs are relevant in computing the cost of
flying a route. It is quite another to demonstrate that the ability
to disguise and bear such short-term costs is one of the ways a
dominant company creates barriers to entry. But that is why the
Amertican Airlines case is being so widely followed.
</P>
<P>
   It is still possible to find analysts who, like Bork, blithely
assert that true predatory pricing is virtually impossible _ that
the consumer always wins when a dominant competitor cuts prices to
drive a competitor out of business, even if he raises them back up
later. But they are growing fewer _ and older _ all the time.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(David Warsh is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
