<SLUG> BC-SOC-NOTEBOOK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LACK OF STAR POWER AFFECTS GALAXY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ Many of Major League Soccer's best-laid plans
have been marginally successful or have failed. This is to be
expected in a new league. But MLS is going to have even bigger
problems if it continues to allow situations such as the Los
Angeles Galaxy's to disintegrate.
</P>
<P>
   The Galaxy announced a crowd of 7,581 for their 1-0 victory over
the Revolution Sunday, giving the team a total of 72,000 spectators
for six home games this season. Interest has certainly decreased
since April 13, 1996, when the Galaxy attracted 69,255 for their
first game.
</P>
<P>
   Even more discouraging is that the Galaxy had 21,173 fans on the
same date a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   The Galaxy have been among the league's successful franchises.
The team bonded with the community on opening day and maintained
that bond until this year. But several mistakes were made in recent
months.
</P>
<P>
   Jettisoning captain Dan Calichman disrupted the balance of the
team. But the most costly removals have been the star Hispanic
players, which has led to an alienation from the most fervent and
numerous fans in the United States. Jorge Campos was sent to
Chicago, Eduardo Hurtado to the MetroStars, Martin Machon to Santos
Laguna of Mexico. Then Mauricio Cienfuegos, who can only be
described as beloved by Salvadorans, became a contract holdout.
</P>
<P>
   The week Cienfuegos signed, attendance increased by nearly
10,000 for the next game. But the spell was broken, momentum
disrupted, and the Galaxy's lack of success has once again
engendered apathy.
</P>
<P>
   The poor attendance Sunday occurred on an otherwise encouraging
weekend for MLS. Four of the other five games had crowds of more
than 20,000.
</P>
<P>
   But Los Angeles is a gigantic market for soccer, and it should
have big crowds. Even 20,000 as an average is grossly
underestimating the potential of the city.
</P>
<P>
   The Galaxy will need to have more of a Latin flavor to tap this
market. Mexican striker Carlos Hermosillo, who will arrive from
Necaxa next week, should help. There is no reason, though, that the
team could not have several Mexican and Central American players.
</P>
<P>
   There are some decent young players on the Galaxy roster, but
the fact is they are not going to sell tickets in great quantities.
</P>
<P>
   The formula for success is simple: Cater to the Hispanic
community and provide a soccer-specific stadium of 40,000 capacity.
Someone rich will become even richer by doing this someday _
hopefully, during the league's lifetime.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Bayern Munich favored
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bayern Munich has an advantage over Manchester United going into
Wednesday's Champions League final in Barcelona. The Bavarian club
held a comfortable lead in the German Bundesliga for much of the
season, holds a 12-point edge over Bayer Leverkusen with one match
remaining, and does not play in the Cup final until June 12.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the English Premier League race went to the final
week before Manchester United edged Arsenal for the title. Then,
United played an emotional FA Cup final, defeating Newcastle, 2-0,
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Both teams will be missing key players. But Bayern Munich has
had nearly two months to adjust to the losses of Brazilian striker
Elber and French defender Bixente Lizarazu, while Manchester United
will be without Roy Keane and Paul Scholes (suspended).
</P>
<P>
   Manchester United is rated the most profitable club in the
world, and might have the most fans world-wide. But United has won
the Champions Cup only once, when it defeated Benfica in London in
1968.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
