<SLUG> BC-JORDAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STUDENTS' LATEST CAUSE: LABOR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROBERT A. JORDAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Student activism, which subsided on college campuses with the
end of the Vietnam War and the dismantling of apartheid in South
Africa, has resurfaced. And the new causes and commitments would
make any national labor leader proud.
</P>
<P>
   In recent months, college students and graduate employees on
campuses from California to Massachusetts have been organizing,
mobilizing, and joining unions to fight for the rights of other
workers, and for their own.
</P>
<P>
   This upsurge in activism and its connection to labor is not
accidental or coincidental. Rather, it is linked to the recent
advent of such training programs as the AFL-CIO's Union Summer, a
four-week internship that puts college students on the nation's
streets and workplaces developing their skills and taking them back
to campus. So far, more than 1,700 young people have been part of
Union Summer since its beginning in 1996, and they have worked in
more than 30 cities. Results of this training and new activism have
been phenomenal.
</P>
<P>
   Seeking higher wages, better health care, more training, and
improved working conditions, about 1,700 graduate teaching
assistants at UCLA voted, by a wide margin, for representation by
the Student Association of Graduate Enployees, an affiliate union
of the United Auto Workers. The union election came after the
state's Public Employment Relations Board basically ruled that the
graduate assistants were not students, but rather real employees
with the right to organize.
</P>
<P>
   If the other UC campuses vote to become a union in upcoming
scheduled elections, more than 9,000 teaching assistants, tutors,
and readers will be represented by the UAW. They will have joined
20 other colleges and universities where graduate teaching
assistants voted for union representation in recent years. The
workers are seeking higher wages, better health care, and more
training through collective bargaining.
</P>
<P>
   Students at more than 25 institutions of higher learning _
including Harvard, Boston College, Boston University, Brown,
Georgetown, and Duke _ have held protests ranging from sit-ins to
teach-ins in an effort to highlight abuses of workers in sweatshops
that make collegiate wear, and to demand a living wage and fair
working conditions for these workers.
</P>
<P>
   They have demanded that firms that license college names not use
sweatshops overseas. The students also called for full disclosure
of the location of the factories making the items imprinted with
their school logos.
</P>
<P>
   At other institutions, students are fighting for the rights of
workers on campus. More than 350 students at Harvard held a rally
earlier this year calling for raises for many of the university's
janitors and dining hall workers. Fairfield University students
held an 11-hour sit-in as part of their quest to have the
university allow 60 janitors to join the Service Employees
International Union. Students at the six Claremont Colleges in
California held a fast to support the right of food service workers
to join a union.
</P>
<P>
   It is certainly no coincidence that Union Summer program
graduates have been among campus activists fighting for workers'
rights at many schools.
</P>
<P>
   As a graduate student from Columbia noted in a recent New York
Times article: ``One of the great untold stories in the '90s is
that Union Summer has created, from almost nothing, activism on
campus to a point where labor issues are among the leading issues
among students today.''
</P>
<P>
   AFL-CIO president John Sweeney said at a press conference
earlier this month in Washington, D.C., that he was ``proud that
many of these students have found training and inspiration through
the AFL-CIO's Union Summer.''
</P>
<P>
   Sweeney, the AFL-CIO, and other labor leaders nationwide are
seeing that Union Summer has struck a chord with students on dozens
of college and university campuses. In essence, the AFL-CIO's
program has achieved what many parents, and many colleges and
universities, could not. It has given students something to believe
in _ something to fight for. And labor's future looks as bright as
Union Summer.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Robert A. Jordan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-25-99 1355EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990525.0094 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-25 13:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0271 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOC-REVOLUTION-BOS &LR;      05-25 0421
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-REVOLUTION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REVOLUTION FOLLOWING A FAMILIAR GAME PLAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ The Revolution had little to be encouraged
about after a 1-0 loss to the Los Angeles Galaxy Sunday. They have
earned just 1 point in four games this month. And they appear to be
reverting to some of the habits that caused them to have the worst
record in Major League Soccer last year.
</P>
<P>
   The purposefulness and concentration of the defense has been
replaced by carelessness and missed assignments. They have
surrendered goals in the first 10 minutes of three of the last four
games. They have trailed for 167 of the last 180 minutes, turning
games into uphill battles.
</P>
<P>
   There has been a change in coaches and personnel, though. Maybe,
the coaching combination of Walter Zenga and assistant Giuseppe
Galderisi, plus the addition of midfielder John Harkes can prevent
the Revolution from sliding into lengthy losing streaks, as it did
the last two seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to see anybody with their head down,'' Galderisi
said. ``We have to believe in ourselves and take responsibility,
show what we have inside. It means work, not just physically, but
also mentally.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to play this game with your mind, otherwise you can
train for five or six hours a day and it won't make any difference.
I only want to see positive people here. Anyone negative can raise
their hand and leave. This is a testing time, a time for
concentration and attention.''
</P>
<P>
   The Revolution again improvised a starting lineup, their ninth
starting group in nine games. Richard Goulooze probably should not
have been in at the start, since he had missed three games with a
calf strain and was clearly unfit for this contest. Goulooze
started at right back and took the blame for not marking Steve
Jolley on a third-minute corner kick that resulted in the Galaxy's
goal. Paulo Dos Santos replaced Goulooze in the 41st minute and
energized the Revolution. Dos Santos has shown he belongs in the
lineup, or at least as a top substitute.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Burns (hamstring) is expected to return for the
Revolution's visit to the MetroStars Saturday, which should solve
the right back problem. Harkes provided a driving force in
midfield, and once his conditioning improves, he should take
control of the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Walter and I are hungry to win, and if the team is hungry,
too, we can finish in a high position in the standings,'' Galderisi
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
