<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-25 13:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0285 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FEATURE-BUDGET-ART-BO     05-25 0956
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FEATURE-BUDGET-ART-BOS </SLUG>
  
 ART ADV.: Photos with AUTHOR-BLUME, TIMBERLAND-WOMEN, RAC-HARNESS
and TRAVEL-LIGHTHOUSES are being transmitted to NYT Photo Service
subscribers.  
 For Immediate Release  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Boston Globe plans to move the following FEATURE stories for
use by NYTimes News Service clients.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; For questions about stories, contact  &UR; Frank Perrotta  &LR; at the
Boston Globe,  &UR; 617-929-2597. &LR;  For individual purchase of graphics
or photos please call 212 556-4204 or -1927.
</P>
<P>
   All stories will bear the BOS designator.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CONFLICT IN THE BALKANS &LR;   &UR; (i) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   NATO-PILOTS (Rinas, Albania) _ Lt. Matthew B. Holloway, an
Apache helicopter pilot, doesn't know what it feels like to fire
rockets at people. And as Washington and NATO remain stuck in
debate over whether to use the assault choppers, he wonders whether
he'll go home without finding out. By Lynda Gorov. 1000 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL (i) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SAFRICA-MANDELA (Johannesburg) _ He's respected worldwide, but
has Nelson Mandela delivered at home? A look at his legacy as South
Africa's historic victor in the battle against apartheid prepares
to retire. By Kurt Shillnger. 1500 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL (a) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   VERMONT-OUTSIDER (North Bennington, Vt.) _ Outspoken author
Jamaica Kincaid wants a post on the village planning commission,
but in a town not used to change, not to mention blacks, she's been
thwarted. By Judith Gaines. 1320 words.
</P>
<P>
   DONT-KNOCK (Longmeadow, Mass.) _ In a decision that has landed
it in federal court, officials in a small Massachusetts town have
decided to ban door-to-door canvassing after 8 p.m. The case has
feuding rights advocates staking claims to conflicting freedoms. By
Thomas Farragher. 1260 words.
</P>
<P>
   MA-CHAIN-GANGS (Undated) _ Chain gangs are coming to
Massachusetts. Bristol Sheriff Thomas M. Hodgson says the chain
gangs are voluntary and not punitive: In exchange, high-risk
inmates serving long sentences get ``good time'' credit. By Jordana
Hart. 800 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY (k) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   OLIPHANT-COLUMN (Boston) _ Mayors Thomas Menino and Andrew Cuomo
set an example on race. By Thomas Oliphant.
</P>
<P>
   LANGUAGE-COLUMN (Undated) -- Crispy is an easy word to hate,
especially for food editors, who see it on their plates week after
week. By Jan Freeman.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ENTERTAINMENT/ARTS (e) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   TV-RUSSIA (Undated) -- The Strizhenovs, a morning-TV duo, add a
little ``Family Ties'' to a format that is equal parts ``The Today
Show'' and ``Regis and Kathy lee.'' By David Filipov. 1250 words.
</P>
<P>
   AUTHOR-BLUME (Undated) _ Randy Blume, 38, is a confessed teenage
bookworm and the daughter of author Judy Blume. That she wrote a
novel _ even a novel about a woman who chooses flying over law _
should come as no big surprise. By Michael Kenney. PHOTO
</P>
<P>
   BOOK-LOVE (Undated) _ As Wayne Booth's playful prose in ``For
the Love of It'' sets out to explain, being an amateur can and
should be a lifelong pursuit. By Clea Simon.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TRAVEL (t) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-MOOSE (Undated) _ These days moose are a big tourist
draw, so towns and businesses are aiming to please by pointing the
way to hangouts and offering official moose tours. A state-by-state
guide. By Diane Daniel. (2 takes)
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-LIGHTHOUSES (Boston) _ For lighthouse lovers, the
overnights at Monomoy and Race Point lighthouses may be the
ultimate tour. For the less adventurous, Massachusetts also offers
simpler boat tours that pass lighthouses. By Alison Bass. 775
words. PHOTO
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-COLUMN &UR;  &LR; (Undated) _ The TIA/AAA forecast says more
Americans are likely to go to a family reunion or a casino this
year than last. By Jerry Morris.
</P>
<P>
   w/
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-NOTES (Undated) _ San Francisco has been called America's
favorite city, although a few Bostonians might quibble. By Richard
Carpenter.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-COLLINS (Noosa Heads, Queensland, Australia) _ One moment
you're sauntering along Hastings Street, peering into high-fashion
shop windows. By Bud Collins.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL (f) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   TIMBERLAND-WOMEN (Stratham, N.H.) _ The percent of women on
boards in corporate America is rising and now stands at 11 percent.
What's becoming clear is that when companies do have women on their
boards, there is a CEO or president who makes sure that it happens.
By Kimberly Blanton. 980 words. PHOTO
</P>
<P>
   ONBUSINESS-COLUMN (Undated) _ If you want to know how our HMOs
will become profitable again, you just have to look at the
country's big for-profit HMOs for a model. But you may not like the
answer. By Steven Syre and Charles Stein.
</P>
<P>
   WARSH-COLUMN (Undated) _ If you think there is nothing new in
antitrust economics since Aaron Director taught the subject in the
1950s and 1960s at the University of Chicago Law school, you're in
for a surprise. By David Warsh.
</P>
<P>
   JORDAN-COLUMN (Undated) _ It is no coincidence that Union Summer
program graduates have been among campus activists fighting for
worker rights at many universities. By Bob Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SPORTS (s) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   RAC-HARNESS (Plainville, Mass.) _ When you make a living
training and driving horses in a sport that has been on the
endangered species list for years, you live with uncertainty. By
Mark Blaudschun. 1375 words. PHOTO
</P>
<P>
   SOC-REVOLUTION (Pasadena, Calif.) -- The Revolution had have
earned just one point in four games this month and appear to be
reverting to some of the habits that caused them to have the worst
record last year. By Frank Dell'Apa.
</P>
<P>
   SOC-NOTEBOOK (Pasadenia, Calif.) -- MLS is going to have big
problems if it continues to allow situations such as the Los
Angeles Galaxy's to disintegrate. By Frank Dell'Apa.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The Boston Globe &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
