<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-25 13:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0292 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RAC-HARNESS-ART-BOS &LR;      05-25 1354
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-HARNESS-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HARNESS HOPE AT PLAINRIDGE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK BLAUDSCHUN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PLAINVILLE, Mass. _ Some of their belongings were in storage.
Others had been dropped off with relatives. Others were packed
along with the chldren, Nicole, who was 7 at the time, and Matthew,
who was 3.
</P>
<P>
   When James Hardy pulled his car onto Route 1 that day two
summers ago, Debra Hardy didn't know what was happening.
</P>
<P>
   Their life was wrapped up in boxes. The mobile home, which they
had occupied for more than a decade and was just a short jog over
the hill from Foxboro Park, was deserted.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't think we'd ever be coming back,'' Debra Hardy was
saying recently, when asked about the chaos in her life in August
1997. ``All our family were here, all our friends.''
</P>
<P>
   But when you make a living training and driving horses in a
sport that has been on the endangered species list for years, you
live with uncertainty.
</P>
<P>
   Security is getting up in the morning, knowing that you can go
down to the stable area, tend to horses you get to know like
children, and see if they are willing to run on any given evening.
And run well enough to help you feed your children and pay your
bills.
</P>
<P>
   In the final days of Foxboro Park, security is going to work and
seeing people you have known for years in their normal places,
doing their normal routine, always wondering when the plug would be
pulled.
</P>
<P>
   ``We heard stories for months, all the time,'' said James Hardy,
who is now back at home, driving horses, while Debra trains them at
the work-in-progress known as Plainridge Race Course, New England's
latest and probably last attempt to make harness racing a viable
commodity in the region. ``Some days we didn't think anything was
going to happen. But you always heard the stories. We didn't know
what to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Then finally it happened. Like a tornado that comes out of a
swirl of clouds, it was over. ``Just like that, too,'' said Paul
Vacca, the track superintendent at Plainridge. ``The state police
just came in and said the track was closed and everyone had to
leave immediately. The people in the money room just walked out and
left. The police had to come back and post guards until someone
could come in and finish counting the money. That's as fast as it
happened.''
</P>
<P>
   For Debra and James Hardy, it was more than a shock. It was an
upheaval. Where would they go, what would they do? James had come
out of trade school with a skill in masonry. But they were horse
people. That's all they had done together.
</P>
<P>
   Now it was in jeopardy.
</P>
<P>
   James looked around. What were the options? Maine? Jersey?
Upstate New York? ``We talked about it all,'' said James. ``It was
all up to the owners, Rob and Dave Silver and Tom Cummings, who
also had local ties. They stuck with us,'' said James. ``It was
tough on them. But they made the commitment.''
</P>
<P>
   So did the Hardys. The kids were taken out of school. James made
a scouting trip to Saratoga Raceway in upstate New York, which
seemed to offer the best chances. They rented an apartment, found a
school for Nicole and Matthew.
</P>
<P>
   They also kept an eye and ear on what was happening back home.
</P>
<P>
   For other drivers in the area, similiar stories were unfolding.
Some stuck with it, hoping for a revival. Others moved to different
tracks.
</P>
<P>
   The Hardys had some options. James could go back to masonry
work.
</P>
<P>
   But what about 60-year-old Robert Tisbert, still driving at
whatever track had horses to race?
</P>
<P>
   Or David Ingraham, who wanted more exposure and opportunities
than driving at Scarborough Downs in Maine offered?
</P>
<P>
   Closing a track wasn't like closing a factory.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people got hurt,'' said Hardy, trying to take the
anger out of his voice.
</P>
<P>
   With that kind of root system _ the community in the trailer
park in Foxborough was loaded with people tied to not only the
racetrack but with Foxboro Stadium, each owned by the Kraft family,
each in doubt in terms of long-range security _ any kind of rumor
of a positive nature can get legs quickly.
</P>
<P>
   Last April, the rumors swirled up and down Route 1 and
throughout the Northeast.
</P>
<P>
   A new track in Plainville, at the junction of Routes 1 and 495,
was on the drawing boards.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Piontkowski, once the head of the Massachusetts Racing
Commission and general manager at Foxboro, was trying to put a plan
together.
</P>
<P>
   ``We heard stories and kept hoping,'' said Debra Hardy.
</P>
<P>
   Hoping and wishing.
</P>
<P>
   But racing in Massachusetts is like politics, filled with hidden
agendas, relationships, and intrigue. Nothing comes easy.
</P>
<P>
   Piontkowski needed financial backing that no one seemed to
offer. Finally Lou Giuliano, president of the New England's
Horsemen's Association, stepped up, made some deals.
</P>
<P>
   Some people didn't like the way it was done, filled with
backroom deals and questionable tactics, they said. Others saw a
bigger picture, a path to open a new racetrack in New England, to
get harness racing back to Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   Even when the plans went through, building a track seemed a leap
of faith.
</P>
<P>
   ``We never thought it would get off the ground,'' said James
Hardy. ``We came back in December and there was nothing but a pile
of rocks here. I never thought in a million years this place would
go.''
</P>
<P>
   Hardy was comfortable in Saratoga. ``Nice people, lots of
friends,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But it wasn't home.
</P>
<P>
   Hardy had been through this once before, the first time Foxboro
closed, in 1986. He had to move, finding other tracks. But that was
before he had a family to worry about.
</P>
<P>
   Now he wanted more security than an apartment in Saratoga and a
nomadic existence.
</P>
<P>
   Four months after Hardy saw the ``rock pile,'' Plainridge opened
its doors for live racing. Plainridge had begun taking simulcast
betting, which has become the life support system for all but the
biggest tracks in this country, a month earlier.
</P>
<P>
   But live racing was what James Hardy wanted. It was what David
Ingraham, making a reputation for himself as one of the best
drivers in Maine, wanted as well.
</P>
<P>
   When Plainridge opened for racing on a track that the drivers
claim is user friendly, with gentle turns and a safer Euro track on
a five-eighths-of-a-mile course, the drivers and the trainers and
the owners came back.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was three hours away,'' aid Ingraham, who makes a daily
three-hour commute from Maine and routinely drives eight to 10
times on each card. ``Any time a new track opens, it's a plus for
the business.''
</P>
<P>
   Ingraham feels it will get better before it gets worse again.
Plainridge is not a finished product, looking more like a
construction site as the finishing touches are added.
</P>
<P>
   It is also a modern track. No grandstand, and a large,
comfortable simulcast theater that offers action from noon to
midnight.
</P>
<P>
   Slot machines are also a possibility in the future, which has
led to criticism that Plainridge is masquerading as a way to get
gambling into the state, with little or no interest in live racing.
</P>
<P>
   Don't tell that to James Ingraham or James and Debra Hardy, who
ware back in their trailor in Foxborough. ``I'm confident they
didn't spend all this money to close it again,'' said James Hardy.
``It's got to better. The track is nice, the facility is good.''
</P>
<P>
   The track is still in its trial stage. Racing cards are small
and limited. The track has live racing three days a week: Monday,
Tuesday, and Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Purists still say it is an operation built on a foundation of
sand _ shaky at best.
</P>
<P>
   One thing is clear, however. A new venue has risen from nothing
but faith.
</P>
<P>
   Much is at stake here. If it fails, harness racing in southern
New England will be gone _ probably forever.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody said we couldn't do it,'' said Vacca. ``But Lou just
pushed and pushed and pushed. It's miracle.''
</P>
<P>
   It's more than that.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's home,'' said James Hardy. ``This is where I'm from. This
is where I want to be.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
