<HEADER>
A0313 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-NOTES-BOS &LR;      05-25 0914
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-NOTES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAB FACTS ABOUT A FABLED CITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD P. CARPENTER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   San Francisco has been called America's favorite city, although
a few Bostonians might quibble. One thing is certain, though: The
City by the Bay is a trove of fascinating facts. A lot of them can
be found in an entertaining little book that's shaped like the
Golden Gate Bridge: ``San Francisco Secrets'' by John Snyder
(Chronicle Books, $7.95). Let's reveal just a few of those
``secrets'':
</P>
<P>
   --The south stairway of Alta Plaza Park replicates the grand
stairway of the casino at Monte Carlo.
</P>
<P>
   --Robert Stroud, the Birdman of Alcatraz, never kept birds at
that famous prison.
</P>
<P>
   --Much of the money for the construction of the largest Buddhist
temple in the United States, Buddha's Universal Temple, was raised
from fortune cookie sales.
</P>
<P>
   --As a courtesy to guests, the St. Francis Hotel has washed and
polished its coins daily since 1939.
</P>
<P>
   --Vermont Street, and not Lombard Street, is the city's
crookedest street.
</P>
<P>
   --Dislike of the name ``Frisco'' goes back a long, long time. In
1907, an Anti-Frisco Committee was formed.
</P>
<P>
   --A woman sued the city for $500,000, claiming that a cable car
accident turned her into a nymphomaniac. She was awarded $50,000. &QL; 
 &QL; 
And speaking of San Francisco: The name Ghirardelli conjures up
heavenly visions of chocolate, but Ghirardelli Square offers even
more: shops, restaurants, and entertainment. For a coupon
redeemable in the square for a discount booklet, shopping bag, and
chocolate treat, visit www.ghirardellisq.com. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Travel Trivia: You're flying at 35,000 feet. The air temperature
outside your plane is (a) 450 degrees below zero, (b) 45 degrees
below, (c) 45 degrees above, or (d) 450 degrees above. (Answer at
end of column.) &QL; 
 &QL; 
In a name: Seeing the name ``Irish Permanent,'' some first-time
visitors to Ireland assume the sign indicates a widespread chain of
hair salons. Actually, Irish Permanent is one of the largest
financial services companies in the Republic of Ireland. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Quotable: He who never leaves his country is full of prejudices.''
_ Carlo Goldoni (1707-1793). &QL; 
 &QL; 
Traveling via the movies: In case you were wondering, the planet
Tatooine depicted in ``Star Wars Episode 1: the Phantom Menace'' is
actually Tunisia. Meanwhile, the new comedy ``Notting Hill,''
starring Julia Roberts and Hugh Grant, was filmed on location in
West London. And the marvelously named ``Hideous Kinky,'' starring
Kate Winslet, was filmed in exotic Morocco. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Grand gifts: Celebrity Cruises has teamed up with Tiffany &AMP; Co. to
provide nice gifts for passengers on cruises that will greet the
arrival of the so-called millennium. All guests will receive an
exclusive millennium china box, inscribed with the ship's name and
voyage date. In addition, penthouse guests will receive a marine
chronometer, a solid brass clock framed in a solid mahogany box.
Royal Suite guests will receive Tiffany's solid brass Swing Clock.
And suite guests will receive solid brass travel clocks inscribed
with the ship's name and voyage date. For more information on the
variety of year-end cruises, see a travel agent or, on the Web,
visit www.celebrity-cruises.com. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Meanwhile, on Carnival: Among the gifts guests will receive on
year-end Carnival Cruise Line sailings is a bottle of Perrier-Jouet
Fleur de Champagne, Cuvee Belle Epoque, vintage 1995, along with
painted keepsake glasses. The 14,500 bottle-and-flute sets, with a
retail value of $2 million, are believed to constitute the
single-largest private order of its kind within the history of the
champagne industry. Carnival estimates that overall it will serve
some 50,000 bottles of champagne and sparkling wine on its 14 Fun
Ships during ``Millennium Cruises.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Britain's batty law: Sixty percent of Britain's 8,000 medieval
churches are home to bats _ and they can't legally be expelled or
even moved. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Mailbag: Mary Jane Kimball of Merrimack, N.H., passes along this
tip for cutting your waiting time in half at Walt Disney World's
new Test Track ride at Epcot: ``Tell the attendant that you want to
go as a `single.' They let you in a side door, which spares you
from the noise and racket of all the crash tests in the waiting
area and you are a fill-in for single seats. During the last week
in April, the line was usually about and hour and they kept
experiencing `technical difficulties,' but it is a fun attraction,
particularly for budding motorists.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   What's bothering various readers: 1) high prices for hotels,
cruises, and whatnot to celebrate the arrival of the year 2000 _
sometimes as much as 10 times the usual cost; and, 2) long lines at
car-rental counters in Orlando, Fla. One reader said he spent 2 1/2
hours in the Alamo line. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Meals for 40,000: Korean Air's catering service in Seoul is a busy
place, with the ability to make up to 40,000 meals a day for the 32
airlines it caters for. The service, featuring Eastern and Western
dishes, is already an award winner, and meals should taste even
better these days because Korean Air has gone nonsmoking on all
flights. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Did you guess it? 45 degrees below zero. (With thanks to
Atmosphere, the in-flight magazine of El Al Airlines, via frequent
contributor Dave Smith of El Al.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Send comments and questions to Travel Tidbits, Boston Globe,
Boston, MA 02107. Send e-mail to carpen(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
