<HEADLINE>
A TRIP FOR THE LIGHTHEADED 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALISON BASS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- It was a good thing that Paul Avellar, captain of the
Beachcomber, the small outboarder ferrying six nature lovers for an
overnight at the Monomoy Island lighthouse, spotted the fins first.
Otherwise there might have been panic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Paul knew exactly what it was: an ocean sunfish,'' says Lea
Goddard, who was leading the trip as a naturalist for the Cape Cod
Museum of Natural History. ``It's a really odd-looking animal.''
</P>
<P>
   The encounter was just the first adventure awaiting the campers
bound for the Monomoy National Wildlife Refuge on the island off
Chatham. The group, which had to hike 1.5 miles across poison ivy
and wetlands to Monomoy Point's 176-year-old lighthouse, also saw a
great horned owl, piping plovers, a family of gray seals, and what
Goddard thinks were coyote tracks.
</P>
<P>
   For lighthouse lovers, the Monomoy overnights and a similar
program at Race Point Lighthouse near Provincetown may be the
ultimate tour. But for the less adventurous, there are simpler boat
tours that pass lighthouses in Boston Harbor and along the state's
coast, offering splendid views of the mariners' best friends.
</P>
<P>
   For the Monomoy visitors, the most enjoyable part of staying at
the rustic, unstaffed lighthouse (besides the view from the top)
may have been waking to the knowledge that they were the only ones
on the island that day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I cannot think of another place where you are so close to
civilization and yet so far away,'' says Priscilla Reetz, 70, of
Brewster, who went on two overnight trips to Monomoy last year and
plans to go on two more this summer. ``Almost from the minute you
step on shore, it feels so remote. The sky seems wider, the smells
seem clearer, it's just the most wonderful feeling.''
</P>
<P>
   Reetz, however, cautions that the trip is not for everyone.
``There's no electricity, water, or phones, and we bring the food
in with us. It's rugged,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   For those who like plusher arrangements, there are alternatives.
Colonial history buffs can take day cruises this summer out to the
nation's oldest lighthouse, Boston Light, which was built in 1716
on Little Brewster Island in the Boston Harbor. The 103-foot
granite tower was blown up by the British in 1776 and rebuilt in
1873. It is the last operating lighthouse in the nation that is
staffed around the clock.
</P>
<P>
   ``We land on the island and take visitors up to the top of
Boston Light, where they have this incredible view,'' said John
Forbes, a spokesman for The Friends of the Boston Harbor, which
sponsors the cruises. ``And while you're there, leading authorities
will give you the history of the place.''
</P>
<P>
   The five-hour $25 cruises to Boston Light sail on June 13, July
11, Aug. 14, and Sept. 11. Interested parties can obtain a
reservation by calling 781-740-4290.
</P>
<P>
   For advance planners, the Friends are also organizing a boat
trip up to Gloucester Oct. 2, which will pass close by a number of
lighthouses, including Boston Light and Graves Light. Today, the
nonprofit group is taking more than 100 people on a sold-out cruise
of the harbor lighthouses with a midday stop in Plymouth.
</P>
<P>
   Cape Cod visitors can take day trips to the Monomoy Point
lighthouse and to the Race Point lighthouse. The newly renovated
Race Point site is open for overnight visits starting June 1, and
that trip is considerably less rugged than the overnights to
Monomoy, which leave from Brewster three times a week until Sept.
1. (They also go once a week on Saturdays until Oct. 1.)
</P>
<P>
   For the Race Point excursion, ``People meet us at a designated
point in Provincetown and we have a four-wheel-drive vehicle that
will take all their gear to the Race Point lighthouse,'' says Carol
Dumas, manager of public relations for the Cape Cod Museum of
Natural History.
</P>
<P>
   The Race Point lighthouse, which dates back to 1818, has
electricity and thus a refrigerator. According to Dumas, the meals
prepared by the naturalists who lead the overnights, are as good as
at Monomoy. ``I know one of the naturalist's specialties is pasta
primavera,'' Dumas says. ``He's not Wolfgang Puck,'' Spago's chef,
``but the food isn't bad.''
</P>
<P>
   The overnights to Monomoy and Race Point, which include dinner
and breakfast the next morning, cost $130 for people who aren't
museum members. Advance reservations are available by calling
508-896-3867.
</P>
</TEXT>
