<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-MESSENGER-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHEER AUDACITY DELIVERS `MESSENGER' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 
The Messenger 
By Mayra Montero, translated from the Spanish by Edith Grossman
(HarperFlamingo, $23) 
 
 By ANNE STEPHENSON  
 c.1999 Special to The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   This much we know is true: On June 12, 1920, the great tenor
Enrico Caruso was playing the role of Radames in ``Aida'' at the
Teatro Nacional in Havana when a bomb exploded during the second
act.
</P>
<P>
   Caruso was not on stage, but there was no doubt that the
violence was directed at him. Cuba's standard of living was
wretched, yet Caruso, who was 47 and beyond his prime, had
contracted to come to Cuba for $10,000 per performance, an
astonishing sum at that time. Hostility toward him had escalated
after reports of high ticket prices appeared in the Cuban press,
and he had received threats even before he reached Havana.
</P>
<P>
   In the panic that followed the explosion, Caruso, still dressed
in the rich, white robes of Radames, is said to have run out of the
theater and into the street with other performers in Egyptian
costumes. By most accounts, this surreal gathering was short-lived.
No one was seriously hurt, Caruso's tour was a success, and by the
end of June, he was on his way back to the United States.
</P>
<P>
   But what if the tenor's flight had not ended so quickly? What
if, after running from the theater, he had taken refuge in the
kitchen of a nearby hotel, where he found a beautiful young widow
who would become his lover and would bear his child nine months
after he left Havana?
</P>
<P>
   What if Caruso had disappeared with this woman for several
mysterious days after the bomb exploded _ disappeared with her into
a world of saints, superstition and flamboyant danger?
</P>
<P>
   Mayra Montero asks us to imagine this in ``The Messenger''
(HarperFlamingo, $23), a novel full of Chinese folk magic and
Afro-Caribbean religious lore, with the looming threat of Sicilian
thugs thrown in to spice up the deal. The story is amazingly busy _
even the smallest characters have their histories, their
melodramatic tales to tell _ and therefore occasionally laborious
reading. But for sheer, dogged audacity, no one could ask for more.
</P>
<P>
   The narrative is handled by two voices _ those of the aptly
named Aida Cheng and her daughter, Enriqueta. It is 1952, and the
59-year-old Aida is dying of cancer. In the spirit of final
disclosure, she agrees to tell Enriqueta the story of her affair
with Enriqueta's father, the great Caruso. Enriqueta, for her part,
diligently takes down her mother's words and searches for people
who were part of Aida's story so that she might record their
versions of it as well.
</P>
<P>
   Aida is the daughter of a Chinese man and a mulatta,
granddaughter of a Black and a Spaniard. From that frothy cultural
pool, she begins her story with a premonition: Five months before
the bomb exploded in Havana, she went to see her godfather, the
powerful ``santero'' Jose de Calazan, who rubbed her forehead with
coconut and lard, spit into the palms of her hands and prayed to
the saints. In doing these things, he foresaw the arrival of a
White man who was destined to bring misfortune to the sultry Aida.
</P>
<P>
   The man, of course, was Caruso. Aida, like a petulant child,
becomes devoted to him from the moment he rushes into the hotel
kitchen dressed as Radames. It's not easy to see why, for Montero
portrays the tenor as he truly was _ a fat, balding, spoiled man
who sweated constantly, smoked too many cigarettes and woke each
morning ``with shooting pains in his liver and the taste of gall in
his mouth.''
</P>
<P>
   Aida loves him passionately.
</P>
<P>
   ``He smelled of the soaps that Zirato brought him,'' she tells
Enriqueta, ``but his tongue had the bitter taste of the cigarettes
he smoked, a taste that stayed in my throat for a long time. Years
later, little drops of that bitterness would still fill my mouth,
but I welcomed them, tried to hold onto them: They were the little
I had left of him, what helped me most to remember.''
</P>
<P>
   Much of ``The Messenger'' involves the lovers' flight from men
who want to harm Caruso. This part of the story lags, mostly
because its otherworldliness conflicts with Montero's
almost-journalistic decision to provide details of everything that
happens. Her characterization is more accomplished _ my favorite
was not Caruso or his Aida but Enriqueta, the daughter born months
after Caruso returned to his family in America. A melancholy woman,
she hungers for knowledge of Caruso's place in her life.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mother and father were so passionately in love,'' she says,
``that perhaps, when I was conceived, they left me a little hollow,
distant with men, or fearful perhaps.''
</P>
<P>
   And yet she is her mother's daughter. ``We carry coincidences in
our blood,'' Aida tells her. ``We attract them like lightning.''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, it's the quiet coincidences of the sad Enriqueta
that bring this book to life. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-25-99 1409EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
