A0319 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-BUKOWSKI-AZR &LR;      05-25 0646
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-BUKOWSKI-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUKOWSKI: THROUGH A DRINKING GLASS CLEARLY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 
Charles Bukowski: Locked in the Arms of a Crazy Life 
By Howard Sounes (Grove Press, $26) 
 
 By CHARLES KELLY  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Charles Bukowski was a boy, his father used to beat him
with a shaving strop every time he failed at his weekly task of
mowing the yard so perfectly that he didn't miss a single blade of
grass.
</P>
<P>
   Bukowski had acne vulgaris, a disfiguring skin disease that
covered his face with pustules and left it pitted like a disgusting
moonscape. He labored for years at mind-numbing jobs _ Sears
Roebuck clerk, laborer in a railroad gang, mail sorter. Even as a
boy, he got drunk almost as often as he could.
</P>
<P>
   Despite a life beset by misery and characterized by excess,
Bukowski, who died on March 9, 1994, at the age of 73, built
himself into the one of the greatest proletarian writers the United
States has ever produced.
</P>
<P>
   His poetry and fiction are a travelogue of America's depths _
its lousy jobs, rank barrooms and scruffy rented rooms where
hell-raising, randy men and women battle for survival.
</P>
<P>
   Although a casual reader might dismiss him as sodden and
sex-crazed, his autobiographical novels ``Post Office,''
``Factotum'' and ``Women'' are considered classics, and his poetry
is world-famous. Many readers in Los Angeles, where he lived most
of his life, also knew him as the author of a column, ``Notes of a
Dirty Old Man,'' which appeared first in the radical newspaper``
Open City'' and later in the ``LA Free Press.''
</P>
<P>
   Even so, he remains an obscure cult figure for many members of
the American public, who are aware of him only because of the movie
``Barfly,'' a minor film starring Mickey Rourke and Faye Dunaway
that offered a glimpse of the life of a Bukowski-like character.
</P>
<P>
   In this biography, English writer Howard Sounes does an
admirable job of re-creating Bukowski's journey through the
underground passages of the American literary landscape.
</P>
<P>
   The book is even-handed. Bukowski is shown as a vulnerable man
and a good father who overcame great personal pain and tawdry
surroundings to succeed as a writer. But he also is depicted as a
regularly out-of-control drunk capable of hurtful and boorish
behavior.
</P>
<P>
   Bukowski often satirized and made fun of people who had been
good to him.
</P>
<P>
   In one case, he wrote a vicious column about a friend of his,
drug-troubled poet and English professor William Wantling. Wantling
died shortly afterward of a heart attack. Although Bukowski felt
guilty about the tragedy, he still tried to pressure Wantling's
widow to have sex with him _ an experience she described as
emotional rape.
</P>
<P>
   The book doesn't shrink from describing such outrages, but it
also depicts much that is in Bukowski's favor: his lack of
pretense, his ability to enjoy life under wrenching circumstances,
his fortitude in the face of loss.
</P>
<P>
   Most of all, Sounes credits Bukowski with being true to his art,
and to the simple style and the simple material he chose for his
writing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyday life was Bukowski's subject matter,'' Sounes writes,
``not heroic deeds or glamorous people, but the experience of less
successful Americans living in cheap apartments and working at
menial jobs.''
</P>
<P>
   The personal philosophy that underlies Bukowski's writing,
Sounes says, is ``a rejection of drudgery and imposed rules, of
mendacity and pretentiousness; an acceptance that human lives are
often wretched and that people are frequently cruel to each other,
but that life can also be beautiful, sexy and funny.''
</P>
<P>
   Through the blurriness of drink, Bukowski saw the world with a
clear eye. He chiseled a detailed portrait of it into his prose. In
doing so, Sounes shows, he illuminated many of the darkest corners
on the bottom side of American life. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
