<P>
   FLA-BISHOP-RESURFACES _ ALMA, Mich. _ Bishop J. Keith Symons,
the former leader of the Roman Catholic Diocese of Palm Beach,
Fla., resigned in disgrace last June after admitting to sexually
abusing five young men as a young priest more than 30 years ago.
The fallen bishop, who had served the five-county diocese of Palm
Beach for nearly eight years, was quickly and quietly whisked out
of town. He left a perfunctory written word of regret to the
220,000 Roman Catholics in the diocese. There had been no hint of
his whereabouts, his spiritual state or his physical well-being for
more than 11 months. Symons just disappeared. Church spokesmen said
he was in a treatment center but wouldn't say where. Last
Wednesday, he surfaced as the leader of a day of prayer dedicated
to the Virgin Mary at the St. Francis Retreat Center in Dewitt,
Mich., about 6 miles north of Lansing, the state capital. Attempts
by The Palm Beach Post to learn more of Symons' status were
unsuccessful. Telephone calls last Thursday from West Palm Beach to
diocesan leaders in Lansing were not returned. Spokesmen had little
to say. The church in Michigan quickly wrapped a protective blanket
of secrecy around Symons. (Gushee, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   RETIREMENT-HAVEN _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Call the Department
of Elder Affairs in Tallahassee to inquire about retiring to
Florida _ as thousands of out-of-staters do every year _ and you're
not going to hear about sugar-sand beaches, emerald golf courses or
the army of senior care experts and institutions here to care for
you if you falter. But you will be warned of what you might be
giving up: government benefits, four seasons, proximity to your
family. Call Arizona, Mississippi, Alabama or Texas and you'll get
an altogether different response _ a come-hither sales pitch worthy
of Dale Carnegie. In the world of retirement destinations, Florida
is still the 800-pound gorilla, but things are changing and the
Sunshine State will likely not be the de facto choice for Baby
Boomers that it was for their parents and grandparents. (Belkin,
Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
