<HEADLINE>
BIOGRAPHY VISITS GRANDDADDY OF FEDERAL SCANDALS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 
Tempest over Teapot Dome: The Story of Albert B. Fall 
By David H. Stratton (University of Oklahoma Press, $29.95) 
 
 By JON KAMMAN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   What, you might wonder, does an academic's biography of a New
Mexico politician who reached his zenith about 80 years ago contain
to recommend itself to a general readership? The answer: an
interesting, illuminating tale with quite an ironic punch line.
</P>
<P>
   Albert B. Fall was a self-made man and bigger-than-life figure
who sought his fortune in the Southwest and Mexico through
hard-rock mining, practicing law and accumulating political power.
A prospector by nature, the colorful and charismatic Fall found it
easier to achieve wealth (but not necessarily retain it) by serving
as attorney for and business associate of the likes of Arizona
frontiersman William C. ``Colonel Bill'' Greene, the ``Copper King
of Cananea'' whose interests spanned mining, railroads, vast
ranchlands and free spending.
</P>
<P>
   After helping guide New Mexico to statehood, Fall was chosen one
of that state's first two U.S. senators. He quickly became a crony
of the virtue-challenged senator from Ohio, Warren G. Harding. As
president in 1921, Harding tapped his poker-playing pal to serve as
secretary of the Interior.
</P>
<P>
   It turns out that during Fall's two-year tenure as guardian of
the nation's natural resources, he pocketed $404,000 from a couple
of tycoons to whom he granted leases to tap oil fields that the
government had been holding in reserve _ untouched even through
World War I _ in case they were ever needed to fuel the Navy. They
were the Teapot Dome field in Wyoming and Elk Hills and Buena Vista
Hills in California.
</P>
<P>
   Convicted of bribery, Fall in 1931 became the first American to
go to prison for a crime committed as a Cabinet member. Teapot Dome
stood as the nation's seediest scandal until Watergate came along
five decades later.
</P>
<P>
   It's way too convenient to tar Fall as a typical politico on the
take, writes David H. Stratton, the professor emeritus of history
at Washington State University who first began reconstructing
Fall's life and times for his 1955 doctoral dissertation.
</P>
<P>
   Stratton makes no apologies for Fall, but concludes that it
wasn't money that caused him to hand over oil-field rights. Rather,
it was Fall's ardent opposition to Progressive Era reforms _
primarily the budding conservationist movement and populist demands
for limits on corporate empire-building _ that made granting the
leases inevitable, Stratton insists.
</P>
<P>
   In Fall's view, the nation's resources were to be exploited for
the common good, and that meant unfettered industrialization. Such
a stance may be anathema today to Americans, and especially
Westerners, but here's the irony:
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, Congress ordered that the Elk Hills field be sold to
the highest private bidder, and that options, including sale, be
studied for Teapot Dome, Buena Vista Hills and three other
reserves. Occidental Petroleum Corp.'s purchase of Elk Hills for
$3.68 billion last year was the largest privatization of federal
property in American history.
</P>
<P>
   ``Albert Fall must have started spinning in his grave with
indignation,'' Stratton observes. ``Even as an unflinching
corporation man he had never seriously proposed the outright sale
of the naval reserves.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-25-99 1413EDT &QL; 
