   &UR; OTHER INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-NETANYAHU (Jerusalem) _ Benjamin Netanyahu, defeated in
his bid for another term as prime minister, is leaving politics to
hit the lecture circuit in the U.S. Also, political developments as
Ehud Barak, the new prime minister, talks with the Likud and Shas
parties. By Joel Greengerg.
</P>
<P>
   INDIA-GANDHI (New York) _ Declaring ``every drop of my blood
says this is my country,'' Sonia Gandhi returns as the head of the
Congress Party but leaves open the question of running for prime
minister in the fall elections. By Celia W. Dugger.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-APPOINT (Moscow) _ A reformer, Mikhail Zadornov, is put
in charge of the the ailing Russian economy. By Michael Wines.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NEW YORK &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   NY-LOUIMA-TRIAL (New York) _ Justin Volpe, one of five police
officers accused in a brutal precinct house assault on Abner
Louima, a Haitian immigrant, changes his plea to guilty and admits
that he sodomized Louima with a stick. Developing. By David
Barstow.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   And
</P>
<P>
   NY-LOUIMA-DEFENSE (New York) _ Now that Volpe has admitted his
guilt, a look at what kind of case prosecutors have against the
other four police officers. By Joseph B. Fried.
</P>
<P>
   And a related story:
</P>
<P>
   NY-POLICE-BRUTALITY (New York) _ A curtain-raiser on the U.S.
Civil Rights Commission hearings into police brutality. By Laurie
Flynn.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (``w'' code)
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-GUNS (Washington) _ There are signs that Republicans in
the House are poised to push the same gun-control measures that
passed the Senate. By Frank Bruni.
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS-OCONNOR (Washington) _ In 18 years on the Supreme Court,
Sandra Day O'Connor has often been the justice in the middle; in
Monday's 5-to-4 student harassment decision, she was the woman in
the middle as well. A look at the elusive question of whether women
on the court make a difference. By Linda Greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL GENERAL &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   NH-KING (Manchester, N.H.) _ In another sign that New Hampshire
is changing, the New Hampshire House is expected, after years of
resisting, to approve the celebration of Martin Luther King Day,
making it the last state to do so. By Carey Goldberg.
</P>
<P>
   CHARITY-REPORT (Undated) _ Charitable donations rose 11 percent
last year to a record $175 billion, while individual giving climbed
to 1.9 percent of personal income, the highest level since 1973,
according to a new report, ``Giving USA 1999.'' By Karen Arenson.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SCIENCE &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-UNIVERSE (Undated) _ NASA announces the results of a
decade-long project to measure the size and age of the universe.
Using the Hubble Space Telescope, astronomers have been seeking a
more precise value for the so-called Hubble constant, which
correlates the distance of celestial objects with the speed at
which they are moving away from us as the universe expands. By John
Noble Wilford. (1200 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-SHUTTLE (Cape Canaveral) _ Advancing Thursday's space
shuttle launch with equipment for the international space station.
By Beth Dickey. (600 words)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   DAIMLER-PERSUADER (Montreux, Switzerland) _ The power of
persuasion is a valuable commodity for corporate chiefs who want a
front-row seat in the global marketplace. Orchestrating complex
mergers across national borders and cultural divides, takes more
than management skills _ it takes the political knack to win over a
range of people, often with sharply conflicting agendas. While a
growing number of chief executives may rightly lay claim to this
blend of skills, Jurgen Schrempp, the German chief of
DaimlerChrysler may be the most accomplished example. By Youssef M.
Ibrahim.
</P>
<P>
   MCKESSON-OUTLOOK (Undated) _ McKesson HBOC Inc., the nation's
largest drug wholesaler, says it will lower fiscal year and
quarterly results further because of improperly recorded sales at
the software business it acquired in January. It did not disclose
the amount. Last month, the company restated earnings for the past
four quarters, reducing fiscal 1999 profit by 4.4 percent, because
sales from the HBO software business were counted improperly. The
stock fell 50% after the first announcement and is down 10% today.
By David J. Morrow.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ At 1:30 p.m., the Dow industrials were up 62
points. European markets were lower, with London down 1.69 percent,
and Frankfurt down 1.74 percent. In Asia, the Nikkei closed down
1.08 percent, and the Hang Seng fell 0.7 percent. At midday, the
U.S. long bond's yield was at 5.78 percent. By Kenneth N. Gilpin.
</P>
<P>
   ABC-PANASONIC (Washington) _ Panasonic and ABC announce that
Panasonic will provide the network with equipment to broadcast all
its pro football programming, including the Super Bowl, using
high-definition technology. By Joel Brinkley.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS-TRAVEL (Undated) _ The Business Travel column.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-GUANGDONG (Hong Kong) _ China will pump money into
Guangdong Enterprises (Holdings) Ltd. under a restructuring plan
for the troubled group of trading companies. The move is being seen
as attempt to mollify foreign investors angered over the collapse
of Gitic. By Mark Landler.
</P>
<P>
   OLIVETTI-TELECOM (Rome) _ Developments in Olivetti's takeover of
Telecom Italia. By John Tagliabue.
</P>
<P>
   KOREA-TELECOM (Tokyo) _ Shares of Korea Telecom begin trading
for the first time on Wednesday, in what may be the strongest sign
yet that South Korea has won back the hearts of international
investors. By Stephanie Strom.
</P>
<P>
   MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ The daily Marketplace column.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY &LR;  (``k'' code)
</P>
