<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990525.0144 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-25 14:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0363 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ROSENFELD-SHORTTAKES2     05-25 0248
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROSENFELD-SHORTTAKES26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY _ ShortTakes: A nation of griping
 &HT;    By Arnold Rosenfeld
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Impeachment, the most divisive issue of our time, was,
apparently, about the most forgettable. Most ordinary Americans
didn't see much to debate. Bill Clinton's personal conduct, most
thought, had been sordid and unworthy. They sentenced him,
reasonably, to a humiliating loss of respect
</P>
<P>
   Congress turned to new vistas of divisiveness. With Litttleton,
Colo., and Conyers, Ga., guns and the culture produced a new
debate, remarkable for its polarities. We seem incapable of arguing
except from only the most violent perspectives. Most people see
problems with both guns and the culture. They'd like to see a few
reasonable fixes, the kind any well-managed PTA could come up with
in an afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Chinese espionage is the latest topic. Faced with a problem that
seems to have occurred over 20 years and at least three
administrations, politicians cynically play the blame game.
Republican leaders more than imply Bill Clinton traded atomic
secrets for campaign bucks. That sounds remarkably like treason.
Does anyone believe it? Nah.
</P>
<P>
   In need of thoughtful solutions, we continue to be treated - and
behave - like chumps.
</P>
<P>
   Arnold Rosenfeld is editor-in-chief of the Cox Newspapers.
Email: arnold.rosenfeld(at)cox.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
