<HEADLINE>
OAKLAND LAKE COMES WITH FLAVOR OF MEDITERRANEAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROBERT SELNA  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKLAND, Calif. _ To gauge whether Oakland's long-awaited
cultural renaissance has yet arrived, you don't have to look much
further than Lake Merritt.
</P>
<P>
   Since February, the lake _ often promoted as the downtown's most
dazzling feature _ has been the site of Venetian gondola cruises.
</P>
<P>
   In a cultural harmonic convergence, a young couple docked two
gondolas at the lake right around the time Mayor Jerry Brown
announced plans to embrace arts and culture in a city long-maligned
for its gritty, post-industrial landscape.
</P>
<P>
   And while Oakland's gondoliers don't claim to recreate Venice in
the converted tidal slough that is Lake Merritt, they say the area
has a distinctly Italian feel.
</P>
<P>
   ``This environment looks very much like a lot of places in
Italy: a Mediterranean lake, a beautiful city with hills in the
background and churches in the foreground,'' said Gondola Servizio
owner April Quinn.
</P>
<P>
   Late last year, Quinn moved to Oakland with her husband Jeff
Fischer, followed by their two 40-foot, 1,300 pound, Venetian-built
gondolas. ``We very much hope to be a part of the renaissance of
Oakland,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Quinn and Fischer, a Canadian-born Italian tour guide and
trained gondolier, considered other venues for their flotilla _
which they believe to be the only Venetian-made gondolas in the
United States _ but said Oakland was the only location with night
lights and a romantic Mediterranean ambience.
</P>
<P>
   History makes it a good choice, too, they said. The Terrace
ballroom in the circa 1920 Lake Merritt Hotel was originally called
the Venetian Room, and the first bridge built across the lake was
dubbed the ``Bridge of Sighs,'' after Venice's famous 16th-century
stone bridge.
</P>
<P>
   The couple's choice may have been right on the mark: Oakland and
much of the California coast are in the heart of one of the world's
five Mediterranean climate regions.
</P>
<P>
   The only other regions with this distinction, said Roger Urban,
author of ``Oakland A Mediterranean City,'' are in central Chile,
southwestern Australia, the Cape region of South Africa and the
Mediterranean Sea basin, including parts of Italy and France.
</P>
<P>
   Oakland's parallels to the land of the Renaissance may not end
there. Another obscure, unconfirmed detail reported in the 1998 New
York Times Almanac is that more artists live in Oakland than
anywhere else in the United States _ other than Greenwich Village
in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   Whether Oakland will ultimately develop into a thriving hub for
arts and culture is yet to be seen, but the results for Fischer and
Quinn have been promising.
</P>
<P>
   Quinn said she books about four cruises on weekdays and five to
six on weekends, including romantic escapes, weddings,
anniversaries and birthdays.
</P>
<P>
   Cruises may include antipasto snacks, candles and traditional
Italian serenades by Fischer. The last boat returns at 11 p.m.
before the midnight turning off of the Necklace of Lights that
surrounds the lake.
</P>
<P>
   Fischer practiced poling (gondola rowing) for 10 years on
weekends and breaks from his tour-guide work, and received lessons
from Venice gondolier Roberto Vianello.
</P>
<P>
   He met Quinn, who is of Italian descent, on a visit to Long
Beach. While there, they saw an imitation gondola boat ride and
decided to start their business.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was tired of the vagabond life and she did not like the tour
guide stuff too much, so we decided to move here,'' Fischer said.
</P>
<P>
   They take their work as ambassadors of Venetian culture
seriously.
</P>
<P>
   Fischer commissioned one of the four Italian gondola
manufacturers to build one of his shiny black vessels and bought
the other from a long-time Venetian gondolier.
</P>
<P>
   Fischer said the boats were hand-fashioned from up to seven
kinds of wood and are festooned with gold-leaf ornaments and brass
fittings. A large, carved piece of walnut called a forcola serves
as the crutch for the lengthy oar the gondolier uses to propel the
craft. Fischer sunk eucalyptus poles in the lake's muddy bottom to
give the dock the feel of Venice and create a safe mooring.
</P>
<P>
   ``We consider this a continuation of the friendship of the
people who built our gondola and handed down the craft,'' Fischer
said.
</P>
<P>
   An Italian priest and the mayor of Venice christened the
couple's newly built gondola before it was shipped on a freighter
to Oakland early this year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
