<HEADLINE>
CALIFORNIA MOVES TO OUTLAW FUEL ADDITIVE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO, Calif. _ The California Senate has voted to require
a warning label for gasoline containing a fuel additive that
supposedly reduces smog but can end up polluting the water supply.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Gray Davis, a Democrat, has already declared that MTBE _
methyl tertiary butyl ether _ poses a significant risk to the
environment. He recently ordered the additive to be gradually
eliminated from the gasoline sold in the state by 2003.
</P>
<P>
   Until then, legislation passed Monday by the Senate would
require a warning label on every pump that supplies gasoline
containing more than 1 percent of MTBE. The measure passed with
bipartisan support, 32-3.
</P>
<P>
   A recent study by the National Research Council found that MTBE
is more effective than ethanol in reducing ozone, a major component
of smog. But the overall impact of either additive on reducing
ozone is very small, the study says.
</P>
<P>
   The Environmental Protection Agency, which requires the
additives in areas that violate ozone standards, is the last
remaining holdout in support of MTBE and other oxygenates that are
designed to cut vehicle pollutants.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past decade, MTBE has been traced from leaking
underground fuel tanks to about 10,000 wells in California,
including drinking water supplies in South Lake Tahoe, Santa Monica
and Napa. Because of its chemical properties, MTBE moves more
quickly through the water supply and stays around longer than
ordinary gasoline.
</P>
<P>
   If the warning label measure is passed by the Assembly and
signed by Davis, gas station owners would have until 60 days after
the bill passes to install the new labels. The state Air Resources
Board is working to develop a warning label.
</P>
<P>
   ``California motorists paid the tab for introducing MTBE several
years ago,'' said Assemblyman Don Perata, D-Alameda, author of the
measure. ``Now, they're being asked to subsidize its removal. It's
time for the oil companies to show consumers what they're paying
for.''
</P>
<P>
   Perata's label would read: ``Contains MTBE. The state of
California has determined that use of this chemical presents a
significant risk to the environment.''
</P>
</TEXT>
