<SLUG> BC-COMPUTER-COLUMN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NULLSOFT FACING SUIT OVER MP3 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID HOYE  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - You know you've hit the big time when:
</P>
<P>
   A) Major corporations line up to compete with you.
</P>
<P>
   B) You spend all day talking with lawyers and the media.
</P>
<P>
   C) All of the above.
</P>
<P>
   If you asked officials at Sedona, Ariz.-based Nullsoft Inc. and
San Diego-based MP3.com, they'd probably answer ``C.''
</P>
<P>
   Nullsoft (www.nullsoft.com) makes the popular WinAmp software
that allows computer users to play MP3 music files. The company
faces competition from heavy-hitter Real-Networks Inc., and is
being sued by PlayMedia Systems Inc. (www.playmediasystems.com).
</P>
<P>
   MP3.com (www.mp3.com) is one of the largest distributors of MP3
music files on the Internet. It faces competition from Web sites
such as Lycos Inc. (www.lycos.com), the popular Internet search
site, and has been named as a co-defendant in PlayMedia's lawsuit
against Nullsoft.
</P>
<P>
   In case you haven't heard of it yet, MP3 is a popular
compression technology that allows typically large audio files to
be compressed so they are easier to use on a computer or distribute
via the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Such digitized music is nice to have on your computer, as it
allows you to listen to music without tying up your CD-ROM drive
with an audio CD. You can also download MP3 music to portable
Walkman-like players, such as the Diamond Rio (www.diamondmm.com).
</P>
<P>
   MP3 users need software to make it all work. Some use separate
MP3 players and programs that create MP3 files, sometimes called
``rippers.'' Some use software suites that do everything _ create
and play MP3 files.
</P>
<P>
   For months, the MP3 player market has been dominated by
shareware programs such as WinAmp. Recently, however, RealNetworks,
the folks who brought you RealAudio and RealPlayer, has come out
with RealJukebox.
</P>
<P>
   RealJukebox functions as an audio CD player and also allows
users to ``rip'' music from audio CDs, turn songs into digital
computer files using either MP3 or RealAudio technology and then
play them in any order.
</P>
<P>
   MP3 fans have flocked to RealJukebox since it became available a
few weeks ago. The free software _ still only available in beta
form _ reportedly has been downloaded millions of times.
</P>
<P>
   Why is it so popular? Probably because RealJukebox is free and
does everything. Other programs that both create and play MP3 files
are distributed freely as shareware, but cost $10 to $70 to
register. And most of the time, the shareware programs expire after
a short trial period or are not fully functional until they are
registered.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, PlayMedia Systems Inc., a developer of technology for
distributing music over the Internet, has sued Nullsoft, alleging
copyright infringement. MP3.com also has been named in the lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   PlayMedia alleges that its playback software was used in
Nullsoft's WinAmp player. Nullsoft recently agreed to stop
distributing copies of WinAmp that contain the disputed software
code.
</P>
<P>
   MP3.com was named a co-defendant in the lawsuit because
PlayMedia says MP3.com promoted WinAmp and allowed visitors to
download copies of the software.
</P>
<P>
   PlayMedia's CEO Brian Litman was quoted by Reuters as saying,
``If, as we allege, the MP3 decoder in `WinAmp' infringed upon
PlayMedia's software, then by logical extension, MP3.com owes a
heavy debt to PlayMedia for our MP3 technology.''
</P>
<P>
   The naming of MP3.com in the lawsuit came just days after the
company said it would go public. The company plans an initial stock
offering intended to raise about $115 million.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for MP3.com declined to comment on the lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   I managed to get Nullsoft spokesman Rex Manz on the telephone
one recent afternoon. It sounded as though he'd been talking to
many other reporters.
</P>
<P>
   When it came to commenting on the lawsuit, Manz was short and to
the point: ``We deny the allegations of copyright infringement.''
</P>
<P>
   While he was on the phone, I asked Manz for his his take on
RealNetworks' jump into the MP3 market.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're encouraged because RealNetworks is a large company,''
Manz said. ``They have added credibility to the MP3 market. It
means the audience is growing.''
</P>
<P>
   Ahh, life in the big time. &QL; 
 &QL; 
GEEKSPEAK EXPLAINED &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Looking for a great reference manual to keep by the computer?
Look no further than ``The Computer Desktop Encyclopedia, Second
Edition,'' by Alan Freedman.
</P>
<P>
   The 1,067-page, soft-cover volume, published by AMACOM, covers
10,000 computer-related terms. The book is so complete that I think
anyone would be hard-pressed to find a better single-volume
reference anywhere _ whether in print or online.
</P>
<P>
   The $45 book covers computer terms, both new (USB) and old
(punch card). It covers the history of the Internet. It explains
differences between Windows 95 and Windows 98. It has an
understandable definition of the Y2K problem. It covers Macintosh,
mainframes, laptops . . . you name it.
</P>
<P>
   Still not sold? The encyclopedia also comes with a CD-ROM that
includes everything in the book. Just pop it in your computer, and
you have instant answers for reports, homework or anything else
that requires an accurate understanding of computer terms.
</P>
<P>
   The book should be arriving in major bookstores as you read
this. To purchase copies by telephone, dial 1-800-262-9699. For
more information and online ordering, check out
www.computerlanguage.com/home.html. &QL; 
WEB SITES OF THE WEEK &QL; 
- If you like collectibles, antiques, quilting, tea rooms, arts and
crafts, dolls and bears, jewelry, discovering new recipes and fun
things along those lines, you'll enjoy the Country Register at
www.countryregister.com. Operated by Valley resident Barbara Floyd,
the Register is both a Web site and a series of specialty
newspapers distributed in nearly every state. The site is full of
interesting news and tidbits, and includes a message board for
sharing your ideas.
</P>
<P>
   - They live near the ancient rock formations of Monument Valley,
and now they share information on the Internet. They are residents
of Kayenta, the first Navajo community to have its own Web site.
Find it at www.kayentatownship.com. The site offers a lot of
information about community government, news about Kayenta, photos
and links to related Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   - Confused by all the talk of deregulation in the energy
industry? Join the club. Then get on the Web and find some answers
at www.energyguide.com/energy/default.asp. The site offers
residents of deregulated areas an opportunity to compare rates and
choose the supplier that's best for them. There's also a host of
features, such as a handy glossary of energy terms and an area that
sells energy-efficient products.
</P>
<P>
   - You can't have sports without sports statistics. Trouble is,
keeping track of all the stats can be a pain, especially when
you're playing just for fun in a youth or adult league. Here's an
answer for ice hockey players: HockeyWeb. The site, at
www.HockeyWeb.com, will calculate the stats for teams in your
league, list rankings, display schedules and perform several other
tasks so you can concentrate on hockey. Rates are based on the
number of teams in your league. Check it out!
</P>
<P>
   - What's your browser's home page? Yahoo? Arizona Central? CNN?
How would you like to make your own home page using the links from
your Favorites list? A handy free utility called Bookmark Wizard,
recommended by reader David M., can be downloaded from Moon
Software at www.moonsoftware.com. The utility only works with
Internet Explorer, but promises to help users create HTML pages
using their lists of favorite Web sites. I haven't tried it, but it
looks pretty handy. As always, practice safe computing and check
for viruses before using anything you download from the Internet. &QL; 
 &QL; 
David Hoye can be reached at dhoye(at)home.net by e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
