<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-25 15:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0466 &Cx1f; tic-z
r t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TALIESIN-AZR &LR;      05-25 1031
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TALIESIN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GUIDES AT TALIESIN WEST GIVE INSIGHT TO FRANK LLOYD WRIGHT  
 (ADV: RESENDING TO FIX LEDE AND ADD IF-YOU-GO INFORMATION) 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BARBARA YOST  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SCOTTSDALE _ Let's make one thing clear: This is not Kitty Hawk,
N.C., and Frank Lloyd Wright is not one of the fathers of modern
aviation.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the misconceptions of some tourists, this Wright was one
of the great architects of the 20th century, and some rank him at
the very top. His legacy is the vision that led America away from
the European model of the 19th century, as is his ability to endure
and thrive.
</P>
<P>
   Born in 1867, Wright died at 92 after a career that spanned 70
years. Each time the architectural community tried to retire him,
he rebounded with a new idea, a new vision. He was the original
Comeback Kid.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks in part to last fall's public television series ``Frank
Lloyd'' ``Wright,'' by documentarian Ken Burns, interest has boomed
in such Wright enclaves as Taliesin West, the winter counterpart to
his summertime Taliesin in Spring Green, Wis.
</P>
<P>
   The national broadcast of Burns' program and his appearance at a
Taliesin event last fall have brought an influx of visitors to the
Scottsdale facility, where Wright lived from 1937 until his death
in 1959.
</P>
<P>
   But the boom had begun even before the documentary aired, said
Suzette Lucas, director of external affairs for Taliesin West.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've seen a 25 to 30 percent increase over the last three to
four years,'' Lucas said.
</P>
<P>
   Tours once offered only during the morning in summer have proven
surprisingly popular when offered in the afternoon. More Valley
residents are discovering the charm of the historic landmark that
sits in their backyard, while out-of-town guests continue to make
up the bulk of the center's many walking tours.
</P>
<P>
   Summer hours begin June 1.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to regular one-hour, 90-minute and three-hour tours,
two new tours are being offered this summer: Architecture
Discovery, designed for families with school-age children, and
Night Lights on the Desert.
</P>
<P>
   At peak season, Taliesin can see as many as 12,000 guests pass
through its portals in a month. Even in summer, visitors still
number around 4,500 monthly. May's totals this year are expected to
reach 9,000.
</P>
<P>
   For architecture buffs, students and professionals, Taliesin
West ``is almost a pilgrimage,'' Lucas said.
</P>
<P>
   Wright's unconventional designs were considered the foundation
of American architecture, which finally broke away from the fussy
European Victorian style of the late 19th century.
</P>
<P>
   His philosophy emphasized creating buildings and dwellings in
harmony with their surroundings. At Taliesin West, he and
apprentices enrolled at the Frank Lloyd Wright School of
Architecture carried that notion one step farther: actually
building the walls of the structures from the stone that forms the
floor of the Sonoran Desert.
</P>
<P>
   True to Wright's vision, Taliesin West's most striking
characteristic is its location at the heart of 600 acres of virgin
desert landscape. The vistas are simply breathtaking. Before
suburban development, visitors could have seen as far as 60 miles
in the distance, a guide reports.
</P>
<P>
   Though the Wright stuff necessarily varied from project to
project as befitted its environment, Taliesin West evokes the
familiar geometric Wright, with sharp angles and straight lines
executed in rich woods and textural stone.
</P>
<P>
   Contrast the structures here with Arizona State University's
Wright-designed Gammage Auditorium in Tempe, which is softer and
more curvilinear.
</P>
<P>
   Another myth your tour guide will be happy to debunk: Wright did
not design the Arizona Biltmore Resort Hotel in Phoenix. But he did
act as a consultant.
</P>
<P>
   Taliesin guides are knowledgeable and eager to discuss the man
and his work. Tours are comfortable, exploring the property indoors
and outdoors, and offer a chance to sit in Wright-designed
furniture. On hot days, tourgoers are invited to borrow an umbrella
to screen the sun and encouraged to intake ample amounts of water
before venturing out.
</P>
<P>
   The gift shop is well-stocked with Wright merchandise.
</P>
<P>
   Even visitors who arrive with just a smattering of knowledge
about Wright will leave knowing him better and with an appreciation
for the philosophy that brings Mother Nature into man-made
structures.
</P>
<P>
   Those elements are clear at Taliesin West, which your guide will
point out is not a museum but a working school of architecture that
accepts only 1 percent of applicants.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's such a beautiful setting, relating to the desert in a
civilized way,'' Lucas said.
</P>
<P>
   And she's quick to answer the question before another tourist
can ask: No, neither of the Wright brothers ever lived at Taliesin
West.
</P>
<P>
   Here, it was Frank Lloyd Wright's imagination that took flight. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
TALIESIN WEST TOURS
</P>
<P>
   ARCHITECTURE DISCOVERY: Begins June 1. For families with
school-age children. Discusses the role of math, science, color and
the patterns of nature that Wright used in his designs. 90-minute
tour. 10:30 a.m. and 3:30 p.m. daily. Cost: $12 general admission,
$8 for students 13 and older, $6 for children 4-12 and free for
children 3 and younger.
</P>
<P>
   NIGHT LIGHTS ON THE DESERT: Begins June 4. Two-hour tours of
600-acre Taliesin West. Friday nights at 7 and 7:30. Cost: $20
general admission, including refreshments.
</P>
<P>
   PANORAMA: Daily at 9 a.m., 10 a.m. and 11 a.m. Includes Cabaret
Cinema, Music Pavilion, Seminar theater and Wright's private
office. Cost: $10 general admission, $8 for seniors and students,
$3 for children 4-12. Children 3 and younger are free.
</P>
<P>
   INSIGHTS: Daily at noon, 1 p.m., 2 p.m. and 3 p.m. 90-minute
tour includes Panoroma Tour stops plus Wright's living room,
furnished with original chairs, stools and benches, and the Garden
Room. Cost: $14 general admission, $12 for seniors, students and
children 4 and older.
</P>
<P>
   BEHIND THE SCENES: 9 a.m. Monday and Thursday. Three-hour tour
that takes guests through Taliesin West, introduces them to a
Wright associate and ends with tea and refreshments in the
Fellowship dining room. Cost: $25. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
