<HEADER>
A0484 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PERU-CUISINE-ART-2TAK     05-25 0895
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PERU-CUISINE-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE TASTES OF PERU: A `SLEEPER' AWAKES 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(jt) 
 By ERIC ASIMOV   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Outdone by visions of gauchos on the pampas, outromanced by
images of Brazilian beaches and Carnival, and overwhelmed by the
familiar flavors of Mexico and the Caribbean, Peru may seem like
just an anonymous shade in the pan-Latin palette that has painted
many New York restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   But Peru has one of the great cuisines of the world. It is the
original fusion food, having absorbed influences from almost every
continent over the last 500 years and melded them with ingredients
and dishes that provide a direct link to the Incas. While it is
best known for ceviche, the marinated raw seafood dish, Peru's food
is remarkable for the diversity of its ingredients, from wonderful
fresh fish to astounding varieties of potatoes, corn and chilies,
and for preparations that encompass the world, from stir-fried beef
to pasta with shrimp.
</P>
<P>
   ``Peruvian is the single most important cuisine in Latin
America, with a repertoire of dishes maybe bigger than France,''
said Douglas Rodriguez, the chef and owner of Patria, the
pioneering nuevo Latino restaurant in New York. ``But it's an
undiscovered cuisine, there's no doubt about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Don't tell that to Nobu Matsuhisa, the chef and a co-owner of
Nobu, who fell in love with seafood soup, purple potatoes and an
unfamiliar herb called cilantro when he spent four years as a young
man cooking in Lima, the Peruvian capital. Today, the Nobu menu
includes several Peruvian specialties, like tiradito, a cross
between ceviche and sashimi in which raw white fish is gently
flavored with citrus and enlivened with chili, then served
exquisitely unadorned, the thin slices fanned out like the delicate
petals of a flower.
</P>
<P>
   ``My food is Japanese technique and Peruvian influence,''
Matsuhisa said.
</P>
<P>
   He also includes several different ceviches and anticuchos,
grilled meats served on skewers, though he makes appropriate
modifications for his sensitive clientele. ``In Peru, you use cow
hearts for anticucho, and people eat it in the street,'' he said.
``We have Kobe beef.''
</P>
<P>
   The Japanese-Peruvian hybrid is not at all shocking, not to
anybody who remembers that Peru's president, Alberto K. Fujimori,
himself of Japanese descent, traveled to Japan recently to mark 100
years of Japanese emigration to Peru.
</P>
<P>
   More surprising might be the influence on Peruvian cuisine of
Chinese laborers, Italian settlers and African slaves, all of whom
arrived in the 19th century. But even that infusion pales against
one of the great cross-cultural exchanges of all time.
</P>
<P>
   Pizarro, who conquered the Incas in the 16th century, had come
to the Andes in search of gold and jewels, but the lasting wealth
he discovered was potatoes. Peru is the ancestral home of potatoes:
they have been cultivated there for thousands of years, and even
today, markets display dozens of varieties in astounding shapes and
colors, from little round purple knobs to twisted rosy tubers to
sleek golden cylinders. The Incas also grew hundreds of varieties
of corn, grains like quinoa and barley, and of course, chili
peppers.
</P>
<P>
   To these, the Spanish added garlic and onions. They introduced
cows, pigs and goats to a culture that derived much of its meat and
protein from the cuy, or guinea pig, which is eaten to this day all
over Peru. They brought cabbage, peaches and apples.
</P>
<P>
   Not only is Peru a junction for cultural interchanges, it is
also a topographical microcosm. Nestled in the Pacific shoulder of
South America, the country encompasses a huge variety of climates
and terrains _ from mountains to jungle to temperate coastline.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's most important is the sheer quantity, quality and
variety of the regional cooking,'' said Copeland Marks, who spent
months in Peru researching his new book, ``The Exotic Kitchens of
Peru'' (M. Evans &AMP; Company). ``You have an extraordinary
geographical location, right on the Humboldt Current, where this
cold stream of water produces a gigantic amount and variety of
fish. Then you have the tropical jungle of the Amazon River, and
then the frigid high Andean plateau.''
</P>
<P>
   Peru was blessed as well with its steady stream of immigrants.
Africans brought peanuts and yams. Italians brought pasta. And the
Chinese brought soy sauce, rice and cooking techniques like stir
frying, creating a blend of cuisines known in Peru today as chifa.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't as if Peru just borrowed from Argentina and Chile,''
Marks said. ``It came from much farther away, from Asia and
Africa.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite a cosmopolitan appeal, Peruvian cuisine has not been
easily exported. Crucial ingredients like aji amarillo (yellow
peppers) and huacatay, a minty anise-like herb, are hard to find
outside of Peru. And of course, there is the basic unfamiliarity of
the food among North Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Slowly _ very slowly _ this may be changing. The Peruvian
population of New York City, about 23,000 in the 1990 census, is
expected to have doubled by the year 2000, said Frank Vardy, a
demographer expert with the New York Department of City Planning.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SHRIMP SOUP &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from ``The Exotic Kitchens of Peru,'' by Copeland Marks
(M. Evans &AMP; Company, 1999) Time: 20 minutes  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon corn oil
</P>
<P>
   { onion, thinly sliced
</P>
<P>
   4 cloves garlic, peeled and ground to a paste with 2 tablespoons
of water
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon paprika
</P>
<P>
   { cup chopped ripe tomato
</P>
<P>
   1{ pounds medium shrimp, peeled and deveined
</P>
<P>
   5 cups fish stock or bottled clam juice
</P>
<P>
   { cup cooked rice
</P>
<P>
   6 eggs (optional)
</P>
<P>
   1 cup milk
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon dried oregano
</P>
<P>
   \ cup fresh or frozen green peas
</P>
<P>
   1 ear of corn, fresh or frozen, cut into 6 rounds
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground black pepper.
</P>
<P>
   1. Place a deep wide-bottomed pan over medium-low heat. Heat
oil. Add onion, garlic paste, paprika and tomato. Saute until onion
is softened, about 3 minutes. Add shrimp, and saute until pink,
about 2 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   2. Add fish stock and rice, and bring to a boil. Carefully break
eggs, 1 at a time, into hot soup so that they remain intact. Simmer
until they solidify, about 2 minutes. Add milk, oregano, peas and
corn. Season with salt and pepper to taste. Simmer for 2 minutes to
reheat and allow flavors to blend. Serve in large bowls, with 1 egg
per person.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 6 servings.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TIRADITO &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Time: 15 minutes
</P>
<P>
   12 ounces sashimi-quality halibut or other firm white fish
fillet
</P>
<P>
   1{ teaspoons chili paste
</P>
<P>
   { teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon yuzu juice (see note) or a mixture of 1{ teaspoons
grapefruit juice and 1{ teaspoons orange juice
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon fresh lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons cilantro leaves.
</P>
<P>
   1. Slice halibut as thinly as possible into long strips. Place
strips on a large serving plate, radiating from the center to look
like flower petals.
</P>
<P>
   2. Brush chili paste on fish, and season with salt. Sprinkle on
the yuzu juice and lemon juice. Garnish with cilantro leaves, and
serve immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 servings.
</P>
<P>
   Note: Available in some Asian markets and by mail from Young
Land Trading, (718) 229-5535).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; LOMO SALTADO &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from Tino Patera, Tino's Place, Coral Gables, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Time: 40 minutes  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   4 all-purpose potatoes, peeled, halved lengthwise and thinly
sliced
</P>
<P>
   2 pounds beef loin, sliced into thin strips
</P>
<P>
   3 yellow peppers, sliced into thin strips
</P>
<P>
   3 red onions, peeled and cut into eighths
</P>
<P>
   4 tomatoes, cut in eighths
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons soy sauce
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon balsamic vinegar
</P>
<P>
   6 cups hot cooked rice.
</P>
<P>
   1. In a large nonstick skillet over medium heat, heat 2{
tablespoons vegetable oil. Add potatoes and saute until browned and
tender, about 15 minutes. Drain on paper towels, and set aside.
</P>
<P>
   2. In a large skillet over high heat, heat 2 tablespoons oil.
Add beef and quickly saute until beef is seared and browned on all
sides. Add peppers and saute until softened, about 2 to 3 minutes.
Remove pan from heat, and use a slotted spoon to transfer beef and
peppers to a plate.
</P>
<P>
   3. Return pan to medium-high heat and add 1{ tablespoons oil.
Add onions, and saute until edges are seared and they begin to
soften, about 2 minutes. Add tomatoes, and stir to combine.
Sprinkle soy sauce and balsamic vinegar over mixture, and saute
until tomatoes have softened, about 2 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   4. Add beef, peppers and sauteed potatoes, and toss gently.
Cover and simmer just until reheated, 2 to 3 minutes. Serve with
rice.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: Serves 6 to 8 portions.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PISCO SOUR &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Time: 5 minutes  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1{ teaspoons sugar
</P>
<P>
   2 ounces pisco
</P>
<P>
   1{ tablespoons lime juice
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon egg white
</P>
<P>
   Stick of sugar cane, for garnish.
</P>
<P>
   1. In a cup or small bowl, combine the sugar with 1{ teaspoons
hot water. Stir until the sugar has dissolved, to make a simple
syrup. Allow to cool before using.
</P>
<P>
   2. In the container of a blender, combine the pisco, lime juice
and simple syrup. Add 1 cup of ice, and blend until smooth, about
30 seconds. Add the egg white, and blend until foamy, about 10
seconds. Pour into a glass, and garnish with the sugar cane stick.
Serve immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 1 drink.
</P>
