<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PERU-MIAMI-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PERUVIAN CUISINE IS WINNING FANS IN MIAMI 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By JON NORDHEIMER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ It is now four decades since exiles from Castro's Cuba
first arrived in Miami, and were soon followed by a small army of
family restaurants that served up heaping mounds of steaming black
beans and rice and other Cuban staples like fried plantains and
mojo, the fragrant sour-orange marinade.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't take long for the spirit of Little Havana to spread
far beyond its downtown roots and embrace Spanish-speaking
immigrants from all over the hemisphere. They, in turn, opened
small mom-and-pop restaurants offering national dishes for each
homesick enclave.
</P>
<P>
   The result is a city where diners can sample the fare of a
different Latin nation every day for a fortnight. And, a few years
ago, it made Miami the birthplace of nuevo latino _ the exciting
fusion cuisine that is built on the zesty tropical tastes of the
New World.
</P>
<P>
   In the place where North America gets its first taste of the
cuisines of the southern hemisphere, Peruvian food has become
wildly popular with those bored with the relatively conservative
Cuban food, and other now-familiar cuisines.
</P>
<P>
   Peruvian food here is built around piquant but not fiery chilies
used as condiments for an endless variety of dishes and, unlike
most other Latin cuisines, an emphasis on seafood over meat. It
also tends to use less grease or oils.
</P>
<P>
   There are an estimated 65,000 Peruvian nationals living in South
Florida (some 750,000 nationwide), the Peruvian consulate here
said. They are faithful patrons of the 22 Peruvian restaurants in
Miami and surrounding towns in Dade County. But they are often
outnumbered by diners of other ethnic backgrounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm Cuban and I love Peruvian food,'' said Christina Beauvoir,
a Miami resident for 35 or her 44 years. Mrs. Beauvoir, an
embodiment of local multiculturalism, is married to a Haitian and
learned about Peruvian cooking through Peruvians on her husband's
soccer team.
</P>
<P>
   She had just finished lunch at El Chalan, a small restaurant in
a curb side shopping strip next door to a Colombian bakery and a
few yards from a Venezuelan restaurant. On weekends, the line to
get into El Chalan winds out the front door and down the block.
</P>
<P>
   A few tables away, Jerry Turberville, a retired businessman, who
was raised on a farm in Alabama, happily plowed through a dish
called jalea mixta, a seafood combination piled high on a wide
plate. His wife, Ernestina, a native of Lima, Peru, could not
finish a large bowl of Aguarditio de Mariscos, a medley crowded
with shrimp, mussels, clams and solid chunks of fish in a vivid
green chili and cilantro sauce.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's spicier than Cuban food, and the seafood is awesome,''
Mrs. Beauvoir said.
</P>
<P>
   But Peruvian cooking in Miami and elsewhere in this country also
suffers from a supply problem. Some purists argue that the
acclaimed quality of cuisine prepared in Lima, which is widely
regarded as the gastronomic capital of the Americas, is not
exportable because many of the fresh fruits and vegetables used in
its preparation are not available in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Imported frozen and packaged ingredients, they say, do not
adequately substitute for the taste of the real thing, and drive up
costs that endanger a kitchen's bottom line.
</P>
<P>
   Miami's Palacio de Jugos (Juice Palace) is a bustling market
crammed with stalls groaning under tropical fruits and vegetables,
many of them imported from the Caribbean, that fill the larders of
some of the city's best fusion kitchens.
</P>
<P>
   But potatoes and sweet corn from Peru, immensely more varied in
taste, texture and complexity than their American cousins, are
generally restricted as imports unless frozen or processed. The raw
products are capable of carrying disease or pests like the fruit
fly, which can threaten American crops.
</P>
<P>
   There are some 4,000 varieties of potato in Peru, and they may
be purple, black or as golden as egg yolks. Peruvian potatoes,
experts say, are starchier, more fibrous and have a richness of
taste unknown in American potatoes.
</P>
<P>
   Tino's Place, a fine dining restaurant in Coral Gables, a suburb
south of Miami, has found the challenge daunting. After struggling
to establish a following for Peruvian dishes that are pricey
compared to what is available in other sections of Dade County, the
restaurant has reverted to an Italian menu.
</P>
<P>
   ``We keep a Peruvian menu for those Peruvians who come here to
celebrate special occasions when they demand the best,'' Tino
Patera, the owner and chef, said.
</P>
<P>
   Regular patrons also know they can ask to see a Peruvian menu,
and Patera will have no problem coming up with several dishes like
corvina al ajillo con camarones (Pacific sea bass with shrimp in a
creamy garlic sauce) or several seviches, made with fish quickly
marinated in lime juice, hot peppers and herbs.
</P>
<P>
   ``You cannot do Peruvian dishes as fast food,'' said Patera's
wife, Lucy, whose mother and grandmother both operated restaurants
in Lima. ``We will not offer the Peruvian menu unless we have the
authentic ingredients.''
</P>
<P>
   Other Peruvian restaurants are not as choosy, and simply
substitute fresh domestic produce for Peruvian varieties. ``The
secret is to adopt ingredients available in this country and use
them to create a taste that is distinctly Peruvian,'' said Mario
Abieno, who owns El Chalan and recently opened a second restaurant
in Miami Beach, Chalan on the Beach.
</P>
<P>
   He substitutes Idaho potatoes, not as good or interesting as
Peruvian varieties, but still tempting when blended with his own
sauces and condiments.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
