<HEADLINE>
ARMY AGREES TO ACCELERATED CLEANUP OF OLD BASE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By GEORGE RAINE  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The U.S. Army will pay $100 million over four
years for an accelerated environmental cleanup of the Presidio of
San Francisco to accommodate the historic garrison's transformation
into a self-sustaining national park.
</P>
<P>
   The former Army base does not contain heavy industrial waste
like that found at shipyards or other military facilities, but it
does have numerous garbage landfills, buried construction debris
and other materials that would not be tolerated under today's
environmental laws.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement by the Army, the Department of the Interior and
the Presidio Trust, the board of directors governing the
transformation of the Presidio, was announced Monday by Rep. Nancy
Pelosi, D-Calif., who had steered the congressional legislation
that outlined the formula for the park's survival. By 2013 it must
generate $36 million annually through leased office and residential
space to fund its operating budget.
</P>
<P>
   The Presidio, an active military garrison for more than 200
years before it was turned over to the National Park Service in
1994, covers some 1,400 acres in the northwestern corner of San
Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Contaminated materials at the Presidio include pesticides,
metals and chemicals in soil. The landfills to be excavated include
building debris, household garbage and hazardous materials.
</P>
<P>
   The Presidio Trust will oversee the cleanup and believes 80
percent of it can be completed within seven years and the remainder
within 12 years, said Jim Meadows, the executive director of the
trust.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our primary concern is the water supply and the fact that
(contaminated material) could become part of the ground water
without cleanup,'' he said. ``The long-term potential is more of a
problem than any immediate danger.''
</P>
<P>
   The Presidio is not included on the Environmental Protection
Agency's Superfund list of sites containing hazardous waste.
</P>
<P>
   The Army had planned to conduct a cleanup over 30 years and
spend about $6 million. However, a negotiating team, headed by Mary
Murphy, a San Francisco commercial real estate lawyer and a member
of the Presidio Trust, approached the Army with a proposal to cut
the time by 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two years ago, we realized environmental cleanup was our
single largest infrastructure problem in reusing the park,'' Murphy
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``At first the Army was a little surprised at our proposal ...
but we gained a certain momentum after a point, and people became
committed to it,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Pelosi said it was the first time ever that federal agencies
have successfully developed a public-private partnership to conduct
a comprehensive environmental cleanup of a closed military base.
</P>
<P>
   ``The agreement is a symbol of how innovative ideas can be
realized in a tangible way to benefit the public good and U.S.
taxpayers,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The $100 million from the U.S. Army announced Monday is separate
from the Army's payment of $64 million for Presidio cleanup
announced in April 1995.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
