A0494 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ICECREAM-BOOK-REVIEW-     05-25 0673
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ICECREAM-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ODE TO A CONE 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By FLORENCE FABRICANT    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   A sure of Memorial Day _ along with the appearance of picnic
coolers and barbecue tools _ is usually a deluge of ice cream
books. But this year, there is only a sprink-ling on bookstore
shelves. Has it become too easy just to buy a pint of passion fruit
or chocolate-chocolate-chocolate chunk?
</P>
<P>
   For those who insist on homemade ice cream in summer, or who
still prefer it without locust-bean gum, there is ``The Ultimate
Ice Cream Book,'' by Bruce Weinstein (William Morrow &AMP; Co., $15).
The author, a food consultant, does a reasonably thorough job with
recipes, from the basic to the creative, like key lime, lavender
and a delicious fig. Does pushing the envelope with the likes of
avocado and corn make it ultimate? Not with vanilla-fudge missing.
</P>
<P>
   The introduction describes several kinds of ice-cream makers and
gives pros and cons for each. Most of the recipes yield a quart and
cannot be made in a single batch in one of those small
freezer-canister types.
</P>
<P>
   There are two kinds of ice cream: the French style, made in a
custard base, and the simpler Philadelphia style, with cream but no
eggs. The book offers hundreds of recipes, including variations.
With fresh ripe fruit like strawberries, for example, the
Philadelphia version results in a brighter taste and is quicker to
make.
</P>
<P>
   But most of the recipes are in the French style. A few make the
custard step easier by combining the eggs and a flavoring
ingredient, like figs, in a food processor, and then pouring sugar
and scalded milk or half-and-half while the machine is on. No
danger of curdling with this method, though the eggs don't cook as
thoroughly. With the shortcut, the results were just as rich and
smooth.
</P>
<P>
   The recipes for sorbets and granitas, like those for ice creams,
are in alphabetical order, each with several possible variations,
like maple cider instead of plain cider. A scoop of herb-flecked
cucumber sorbet makes a nice addition to a cold summer soup. There
are also some recipes for soda fountain drinks, ice cream toppings
and ice cream cones. But no new-wave smoothies.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Smoothie Deck,'' by Mary Corpening Barber, Sara Barber and
Lori Lyn Narlock (Chronicle Books, $12.95), is a deck of 52 cards,
50 of them with recipes for thick blender drinks made with
everything from fruit and sorbet to yogurt and tahini. Most can be
ready in a twinkling, assuming the preliminaries have been taken
care of, like freezing fruit. Several are spiked with alcohol, and
even some that are not can take a splash of something from the bar.
</P>
<P>
   The cards are handy and attractive, with photographs of frosty
drinks on one side and the recipe on the other. But they could
easily be misplaced, and there is no index. So, unless you do card
tricks, pulling out the right one could take some shuffling.
</P>
<P>
   MANGO SORBET
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from ``The Ultimate Ice Cream Book''
</P>
<P>
   Time: 15 minutes, plus chilling and freezing
</P>
<P>
   1 cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   2 ripe, {-pound mangoes, peeled, pitted and diced
</P>
<P>
   Juice of 1 lime.
</P>
<P>
   1. Combine sugar and } cup water in small saucepan, and simmer
until sugar dissolves. Remove from heat, and cool to room
temperature.
</P>
<P>
   2. Combine cooled syrup, mango and lime juice in blender or food
processor, and blend until smooth. Cover, and refrigerate until
very cold.
</P>
<P>
   3. Stir mixture, and then freeze in ice cream maker according to
manufacturer's directions. Serve at once, softly frozen, or
transfer to container and freeze at least 2 hours longer to harden.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 3 cups.
</P>
<P>
   PLANET PINEAPPLE SMOOTHIE
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from ``The Smoothie Deck''
</P>
<P>
   Time: 10 minutes, plus freezing  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1 cup light, unsweetened coconut milk
</P>
<P>
   2 cups nonfat vanilla frozen yogurt
</P>
<P>
   1 cup diced fresh pineapple, frozen
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon fresh lemon juice.
</P>
<P>
   Place ingredients in blender, and blend until smooth. Stir
mixture, and then pour into tall glasses.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 2 servings.
</P>
</TEXT>
