<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-25 16:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0512 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHAPMAN-TEXASATLARGE-     05-25 0583
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHAPMAN-TEXASATLARGE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A LIFE AMONG CATTLE HELPS HIM TEACH ABOUT THE FORT WORTH HERD,
HISTORY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ART CHAPMAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH _ For 64-year-old Tom B. Saunders IV, work has never
been a distant stranger. As a boy, he worked in the boiling heat of
the Fort Worth Stockyards; the rest of his life, he worked cattle
on his family ranch in Parker County.
</P>
<P>
   Cattle have always been an integral part of his life. His family
goes back to the trail-driving days in Texas, to the establishment
of commission houses in the Fort Worth yards, to today's everyday
ranching.
</P>
<P>
   Now, in addition to his other daily chores, Saunders is the
historian for the Fort Worth Herd _ longhorn cattle that signify
Fort Worth's 150-year history.
</P>
<P>
   Because the city of Fort Worth owns the herd, Saunders is now a
part-time city employee. It is an unusual situation for the
lifelong cattleman.
</P>
<P>
   ``Punching that clock is a strange thing to me,'' Saunders said.
``I don't even wear a watch. When the sun comes up, work starts;
when it goes down again, that's the end of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately for Saunders, his daily dress doesn't have to
change. He still wears his bluejeans tucked inside his boots. His
suspenders look fine; so does the straw hat he wears to fend off
the early summer sun.
</P>
<P>
   He probably couldn't change any of that if he wanted. And he
doesn't.
</P>
<P>
   Even Saunders' job responsibility isn't greatly different from
anything else he's ever done. He isn't on the city payroll to
wrangle horses or herd the cattle. He's there to teach the other
cowhands the history of their profession and Fort Worth's livestock
heritage.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just getting them straight,'' he said. ``I had to OK the
saddles, the chaps, their clothing. Everything they've got on
except their underwear is period.''
</P>
<P>
   Saunders is emphasizing the 1890s, when cattle drives died out
and terminal markets like Fort Worth were on the rise.
</P>
<P>
   ``It gives us a chance to talk about the Fort Worth yards and
how they were important to Fort Worth. The yards were the largest
employers in Fort Worth for years,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   His is an unlikely classroom. There are five or six cowhands
sitting around his Stockyards office or out squatting in the
pasture grasses among the cattle.
</P>
<P>
   They discuss the old times, the customs, the ethics. Saunders
teaches from lesson plans his wife, Ann _ a schoolteacher _ helped
him develop. Then the hands, some women, some men, begin to quiz
one another. They constantly test each other, Saunders said, and
they enjoy the challenge of learning.
</P>
<P>
   They will become more than cowhands when the longhorn herd moves
to the Stockyards next month. They will become ambassadors for the
city, and they will be expected to give accurate answers to
visitors' questions.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a real pleasure,'' Saunders said of the lessons.
``I'm looking forward to working with children on this project. I
want them to know that ranchers are probably the greatest
caretakers of the land. We are really growers of grass. I want them
to know we take care of our livestock and that you can't starve a
profit from a cow.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want them to know where all those hamburgers come from.''
</P>
<P>
   (Art Chapman writes a weekly column on things Texan for the Fort
Worth Star-Telegram. You can call him at (817) 390-7422, or e-mail:
Artc(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
