<HEADLINE>
OH, FOR TIME TO STAND IN LINE ALL DAY LONG
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MONICA ANDERSON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Star Wars: Episode 1 _ The Phantom Menace. Now showing at a
theater near you!''
</P>
<P>
   Duh.
</P>
<P>
   Unless you've been walking around with a crock pot on your head,
there is no way that you've missed all the ballyhoo surrounding
George Lucas' latest big-screen saga.
</P>
<P>
   Before opening night, hundreds of ``Star Wars'' fans around the
country camped outside of theaters so that they could be the first
to see this action adventure film.
</P>
<P>
   I've heard a lot of negative comments about these incredibly
patient people. The most common question centers around the single
interrogative, ``Why?'' As in, why would anyone put their life on
hold to get tickets to a movie that's showing on a minimum of two
screens at half of the theaters in the country?
</P>
<P>
   I'm going to go out on a limb here and guess that the movie will
be around for at least a few weeks. Call me psychic.
</P>
<P>
   The can't-afford-to-miss-a-day-at-work crowd passed these folks
on their way to the office and yelled out of their car windows,
``Get a life!'' But I'm not marching with that band because I would
love to have hours and hours to while away without an itinerary or
deadline. If you've got time to burn and you can still manage to
pay your bills, then bully for you.
</P>
<P>
   My only question regarding these avid fans and their diligence
is simply, ``Isn't that loitering?''
</P>
<P>
   Don't most cities have ordinances against congregating in front
of businesses without a permit or something? I mean, like, what if
a bunch of shopaholics parked their trailer homes in front of a
mall that's under construction? Wouldn't someone raise an eyebrow?
Wouldn't security make them disperse?
</P>
<P>
   Sure, I wait for things all the time.
</P>
<P>
   I'll give a restaurant 20 to 30 minutes to seat my party of four
on a Saturday night. And long, long ago, I stood in line for two
hours to buy tickets to a concert featuring George Clinton and the
Funkadelics, but that was the ``Aqua Boogie Tour'' after all.
</P>
<P>
   So I'm not judging anybody. Live and let live.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, I made five phone calls today and each time I was put
on hold.
</P>
<P>
   Heck, with all the time I've wasted on that, I could have seen
Star Wars.
</P>
<P>
   ``May the force be with you.''
</P>
<P>
   (Monica Frazier Anderson is a wife, mother and dentist in
Arlington, Texas. You can call her at (817) 548-5564 or write in
care of the Arlington Star-Telegram at 1111 W. Abram St.,
Arlington, TX 76013. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on
the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
