<SLUG> BC-LIVING-WAGE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAN FRANCISCO'S WAGE BILL HITS A SNAG 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By GREGORY LEWIS  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ A so-called ``living wage'' measure now before
the Board of Supervisors here has hit a snag.
</P>
<P>
   The ordinance, proposed by Board President Tom Ammiano earlier
this month would require employers who hold service contracts with
the city to pay their workers at least $11 an hour and provide
health benefits or a cash equivalent to them. The mandate also
would apply to businesses that lease property from the city, such
as those on port and airport property.
</P>
<P>
   Supervisor Mabel Teng introduced a motion this week asking for
an independent economic analysis on the controversial proposal _ a
move that would delay Board action on it.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are too many unanswered questions to make an informed
decision,'' Teng said at Monday's board meeting. ``How many people
will benefit? How much it will cost us? ... We don't know where the
dollars will come from.''
</P>
<P>
   Ammiano said after the meeting, ``I think the delay stinks.'' He
charged that putting off the vote was typical of ``the disconnect
of what the public wants and what happens in city government. The
delay is colonial. The motivation behind the delay is from people
who are well-fed and well-housed.''
</P>
<P>
   Ammiano said a lot of research on the living wage issue is
available for those who want to see it, but he said some board
members don't want to vote on the issue until after the city's
November election.
</P>
<P>
   Teng questioned the adequacy of the research. ``I have not seen
numbers,'' she said, adding that she is not opposed to increasing
the wages of low-income workers. ``If Ammiano has a study, I'd like
to see it. The Living Wage Coalition said it would cost $10 million
but had no explanation. City departments say it will cost $192
million. Those are the only two I have seen, and the disparity is
great.
</P>
<P>
   ``How can the board make an informed decision, spending
taxpayers' money if we don't know the cost?'' she asked.
</P>
<P>
   Josie Mooney, president of the San Francisco Labor Council and
head of Local 790 of the Service Employees International Union,
said, ``I find it surprising that Supervisor Teng wants San
Francisco to be the last in the nation to pass living wage
(legislation). While she wants to study it, low-income people still
will make $5.75 an hour and have to work two and three jobs to pay
the rent,'' Mooney said.
</P>
<P>
   Ammiano has described his legislation as the most sweeping
effort of its kind in the nation to raise the standard of living
for thousands of working poor.
</P>
<P>
   The current minimum wage in California is $5.75 an hour. A
person working full time earning the living wage envisioned by
Ammiano would pull in $22,800 a year, $10,840 more than a minimum
wage earner.
</P>
<P>
   Ammiano wants the law to kick in next year in order to give
contract agencies enough time to adjust.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal would exempt businesses with five or fewer
employers and those with city contracts worth less than $25,000 a
year. Also exempted would be employees under age 21 who are working
in after-school or summer jobs, employees in short-term training
programs that will help them into higher-wage jobs, and disabled
workers in special federal jobs programs.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-eight jurisdictions in the United States, among them
Oakland and San Jose, have a living wage law on the books. San
Francisco's would ensure the highest pay and be the first to
include businesses that lease city property.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Willie Brown has said he would sign any reasonable
measure.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
