<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Y2K-APPLIANCES-960(2Takes)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Y2K BUG COULD KO THE VCR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JAN JARVIS and JOHN AUSTIN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ The VCR you programmed ahead of time to
record Dick Clark's New Year's countdown refuses to work.
</P>
<P>
   The microwave fails to defrost a pound of hamburger. And the
programmable thermostat has decided it doesn't matter if the
temperature is plunging to 10 below and there's snow on the ground.
The heater isn't coming on.
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to 2000. Forget food shortages, electrical outages and
rioting in the streets. It's the little things that are more likely
to get people down when the Y2K crisis calls on consumers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to tell people these are things that won't
work,'' said Karen Anderson, founder of Y2Kwomen, an organization
dedicated to promoting Y2K awareness. ``What I want to say is look
at the things around your house that you're dependent on. If the
bread machine doesn't work it's not a huge deal but if the computer
doesn't _ and that's how you make a living _ it is.''
</P>
<P>
   The problem is, most consumers won't know for sure what will
work and what won't until they turn on their computer, VCR or
appliance. And to make matters worse, the fact that the VCR works
one day doesn't mean that it will keep working.
</P>
<P>
   ``On New Year's Day we may have problems with the switch over,''
said Larry Shafer, founder of Y2Kbase, a database where consumers
can check to see if products are Y2K-compliant. ``But at other
times the date calculations might be accurate, even if the VCR
thinks it is 1900.''
</P>
<P>
   The concerns are sparked by the Y2K bug _ the computer glitch
that may incapacitate some software and computers.
</P>
<P>
   Because of a programming technique used years ago, some software
views years in a two-digit format, such as ``99'' for 1999. The
two-digit representation of 2000 will be ``00,'' which many
computers could interpret as 1900, creating the potential for
problems for date-sensitive hardware and software.
</P>
<P>
   Consumers are clearly starting to wonder what will work and what
won't.
</P>
<P>
   The Web site had 50,000 visitors during the first four weeks
that the Y2Kbase was up for consumers to check items to see if they
are Y2K-compliant.
</P>
<P>
   For consumers, cars, computers and appliances top the list of
Y2K-compliance queries.
</P>
<P>
   Although consumers are concerned about whether their cars will
work in 2000, only 17 percent of the automobile companies in the
Y2Kbase.com database provide Y2K information on their public Web
sites.
</P>
<P>
   Just how many auto components will be affected is up for debate.
</P>
<P>
   Chevrolet has found that most systems have no date-related
functionality and were found to be Y2K-compliant.
</P>
<P>
   Computer hardware and software also raise consumer questions.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the electronics companies have no listing regarding
whether they are Y2K-compliant. But some, such as Sony Electronics,
report that most of its products will function when the date
changes from 1999 to 2000. The exception: CCDF30 cameras.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the stereos won't be a problem,'' said Stuart
Schuster, president of Marvin Electronics Co. of Fort Worth.
``There's not a date clock on them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel like most of the TVs will be fine,'' Schuster said.
``Where we don't know is some of the older VCRs.''
</P>
<P>
   THe time shift function on pre-1988 VCR models might not
function, according to the Federal Trade Commission. But the fix
for VCRs is easy. Experts suggest setting the date to 1972, because
the 1972 calendar is identical to 2000's.
</P>
<P>
   Fixing an out-of-sync VCR probably won't be necessary, and even
if it's not working, it probably won't be worth fixing, said Matt
Gallandat, owner of A/V Electronics in Arlington.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there will be a modification available or that
it would be worth modifying,'' he said. ``If you have a problem, I
don't see trying to make it work.''
</P>
<P>
   Four-head VCRs now cost around $100, so if a noncompliant one
could be fixed it's probably more practical to buy a new one,
experts said.
</P>
<P>
   Cameras, camcorders, digital wristwatches and pocket electronic
organizers containing calender chips might have Y2K problems,
according to the Federal Trade Commission. Some camcorders sold
before 1988 will display the date incorrectly but function
properly.
</P>
<P>
   Personal computers that are more than seven years old and use
Windows 95 could present problems for consumers. But the newer home
computers _ say, those sold since the advent of the Pentium chip _
shouldn't catch the Y2K bug, said John Henson, operations manager
for SPI Systems in Arlington.
</P>
<P>
   A bigger problem, he said, will be the sort of outdated hardware
and customized, proprietary software packages common to businesses
such as accountants' and doctors' offices.
</P>
<P>
   MORE
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
