<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WINE-TASTINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TASTINGS: ECLECTIC PINOT 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl) 
c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Benziger Pinot Noir 1996, California. About $18.
</P>
<P>
   Appellations can be misleading. With some wines, the California
appellation _as opposed to a Napa or Sonoma County appellation, for
example _ implies that grapes from lesser-growing regions were used
in the blend. Not in this instance. This pinot was made from 16
lots of grapes from five of the finest vineyards in the state,
stretching from the Bien Nacido Ranch in the south-central region
to the Kent and Preston vineyards in the Russian River area in
Sonoma County. Each lot was vinified and aged separately, then
blended. The alcohol content, 14.1 percent, is high for a pinot
noir but the wine has more than enough fruit to balance it out. It
could probably benefit from another year in the bottle.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-25-99 1649EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990525.0173 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-25 16:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0537 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CILANTRO-ART-NYT &LR;      05-25 0783
