<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CILANTRO-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BABY CILANTRO COMES OF AGE, SUBTLY 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (editors; Recipe at end of article)  
 (bl)  
 By MARIAN BURROS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Open a box of frilly little leaves of baby cilantro, and a clean
fresh aroma wafts out. It is not at all like the smell of mature
cilantro, which can seem musty, especially to those who don't like
it. Like other micro greens, baby cilantro is much subtler than the
grown-up version. It also has a touch of pepperiness and a bit of
grassiness lacking in its older siblings.
</P>
<P>
   Baby cilantro is the latest entrant in the great New York
restaurant race to distinguish one chef's cooking from another's
with esoteric ingredients like micro greens. Such minuscule leaves
are already becoming old hat, as chefs seek out the unusual micro
herb no one has seen before. And right now, it's this baby, also
known as coriander or Chinese parsley.
</P>
<P>
   I first encountered baby cilantro at the Indian-accented
restaurant Tabla. Jean-Georges Vongerichten is using it in spring
rolls at Vong, and Wayne Nish sprinkles it over lobster in a sauce
based on Muscat Beaumes-de-Venise at March.
</P>
<P>
   It's perfect ``for people who don't like the hard-core cilantro
flavor,'' said Daniel DelVecchio, the cuisine and design developer
for Vongerichten, who uses it to garnish the spring rolls, filled
with peeky-toe crab, chilies, mayonnaise and tamarind.
</P>
<P>
   Nish said he liked to use it ``in places where fully grown
cilantro would overwhelm everything else.'' For a flavor as
delicate as lobster's, he said, ``it adds a spike of brightness.''
</P>
<P>
   March serves the lobster with polenta studded with bits of
lobster, topped with finely cut vegetables and ground dried lobster
roe. For home cooks, the lobster with the Beaumes-de-Venise sauce
is enough of a treat to garnish with baby cilantro.
</P>
<P>
   The infant herb is available by mail from Indian Rock Produce in
Quakertown, Pa.; (800) 882-0512. It costs $40 a pound, but as
little as a quarter pound can be purchased, for $10 plus shipping.
And who knows? Later this spring, it may turn up at some of New
York's Greenmarkets.
</P>
<P>
   To grow it yourself, take this advice from Margaret Falk, the
plant records manager at the New York Botanical Garden in the
Bronx. Scatter seeds in potting soil in a flat, and cover lightly
with the soil. Put the flat in a shady spot. Keep it out of the hot
sun, since cilantro prefers cool weather. You can also try growing
cilantro indoors under grow lights, placing the lights five or six
inches above the seed flats. Pick the leaves when the plants are an
inch high.
</P>
<P>
   PRINCE EDWARD ISLAND LOBSTER WITH MUSCAT BEAUMES-DE-VENISE SAUCE
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from Wayne Nish, March
</P>
<P>
   Time: 1 hour 50 minutes
</P>
<P>
   1 large bottle Muscat Beaumes-de-Venise (750 milliliters)
</P>
<P>
   1 5-inch piece thinly sliced ginger
</P>
<P>
   5 shallots, halved
</P>
<P>
   5 cloves garlic, halved
</P>
<P>
   { teaspoon ground cumin
</P>
<P>
   1 quart plus 2 tablespoons heavy cream (40 percent, if possible)
</P>
<P>
   1 cup sea salt, plus extra to season
</P>
<P>
   Juice of { lime, or to taste
</P>
<P>
   3 lobsters, 1\ to 1{ pounds each
</P>
<P>
   { pound (2 sticks) unsalted butter
</P>
<P>
   6 tablespoons baby cilantro leaves. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1. For the sauce, combine Beaumes-de-Venise, ginger, shallots
and garlic, and cook to reduce to 1 cup. Whisk in cumin and 1 quart
cream; return to heat, and reduce to 3 cups. Remove from heat, and
strain to remove solids. Season with salt and lime juice to taste,
and keep warm. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   2. In large stockpot, combine 3 quarts water with { cup sea
salt. Place over high heat, and bring to a boil. Meanwhile, fill a
large bowl with 3 quarts water and ice, and add { cup sea salt. Set
aside. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   3. Kill each lobster by placing the tip of sharp knife on top of
the head behind the eyes and striking it down with a kitchen
mallet. Twist off the tails, and break off the claws (with
knuckles) at the bodies. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   4. Add claws to pot. After 4 minutes, add tails, and continue to
boil 6 minutes longer. Using tongs or slotted spoon, transfer claws
and tails to ice water to stop the cooking. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   5. Remove meat from shells, and cut meat into bite-size pieces.
Set aside. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   6. In a small saucepan over low heat, melt butter. Add remaining
cream, and mix well. Season with sea salt to taste. Bring to a bare
simmer, and then add lobster to heat through. To serve, remove
lobster from butter-cream mixture, and place an equal portion of
lobster on each of four plates. Spoon Beaumes-de-Venise sauce
around, and garnish with baby cilantro. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 6 large appetizers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
