<HEADER>
A0539 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Y2K-APPLIANCES-2ndTak     05-25 0651
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Y2K-APPLIANCES-2ndTake-TEX </SLUG>
 
ARLINGTON, Texas: doctors' offices. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   At home and at work, digital thermostats should not be affected
by the new year if they are programmed based on the days of the
week, not the year.
</P>
<P>
   But monitored security systems with a calendar function might
run into problems with the Y2K bug. Even if the unit is
Y2K-compliant, it could malfunction if the monitoring company's
systems are noncompliant, according to the Federal Trade
Commission.
</P>
<P>
   Malfunctions of appliances and electronics might be annoying to
consumers, but if the banking system is not Y2K-compliant, minor
annoyances could turn into major headaches.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could impact things like employers' payroll processing and
insurance companies' ability to handle claims,'' Shafer said.
``Those large systems are of more concern than products people have
around their home.''
</P>
<P>
   Away from home, computerized systems such as ATMs, gasoline
pumps and credit cards could cause a consumer crisis.
</P>
<P>
   According to Exxon Co. USA, ``...the corporation could
potentially experience disruptions to some mission critical
operations or deliveries to customers as a result of year 2000
issues, particularly in the first few weeks of the year 2000. ...
The potential financial impact or liability associated with such
disruptions cannot be reasonably estimated.''
</P>
<P>
   So, even though Exxon will spend as much as $250 million in
compliance efforts, the company isn't absolutely sure that there
won't be glitches.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's definitely a good chance credit cards could have
problems,'' said Brent Rogers, director of information technology
at Vought Heritage Federal Credit Union in Grand Prairie.
</P>
<P>
   Concerns about Y2K-related scams have led the FTC to warn
consumers to be aware of suspicious phone calls during which people
are asked to disclose their credit card and bank account numbers.
The callers claim that the numbers are needed to deal with the year
2000 problem.
</P>
<P>
   Also of concern is an anticipated year-end rush to withdraw cash
from financial institutions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want people to pull out their money because they
could be endangering themselves,'' said Quay Lutrell, vice
president of marketing at Vought Heritage Federal Credit Union.
``People are definitely going to be potential targets if someone
sees them walking out with a thick lump in their pocket and they
may follow them home.''
</P>
<P>
   Financial experts suggest withdrawing enough cash for two weeks
and no more.
</P>
<P>
   ``We strongly recommend people get traveler's checks rather than
cash,'' Lutrell said. ``And they should remember that if they leave
it in their financial institutions, it is insured, but if it's in
between the mattresses, it is not insured.''
</P>
<P>
   It could be days, weeks even months before consumers see the
effects of incorrect data resulting from the Y2K bug.
</P>
<P>
   Some systems might run into problems on Feb. 29, 2000, because
computers could forget about the leap year, Anderson said. Problems
could arise if computers disagree on what day it is.
</P>
<P>
   If software is not programmed for leap year, March 3, 2000, is
the first Friday when computers will think it is Saturday. School
bells might fail to ring, and bank vaults might not open.
</P>
<P>
   The bottom line is, it won't hurt to be prepared, Anderson said.
If the alarm doesn't work it's not that much of a problem, she
said. But if the alarm, microwave, thermostat, gas pump and ATM
don't work, it all adds up.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we have a lot of things unfolding, our ability to handle
them is compromised,'' she said. ``People need to decide what kind
of impact Y2K will have if stuff doesn't work.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   FOR INFORMATION
</P>
<P>
   Y2K compliance database: www.y2kbase.com
</P>
<P>
   Free federal Y2K information hot line: (888) USA-4-Y2K
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Consumer Gateway: www.consumer.gov
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
