<SLUG> BC-WINE-TALK-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WINE TALK: LOSING A TASTE FOR THE CHEAP STUFF 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
 (bl)  
 By FRANK J. PRIAL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   For wine enthusiasts, the opening of a winery is exciting news,
especially if it's in the Napa Valley and it plans to make only
about 500 cases a year. It's the same in Europe: the biggest buzz
invariably is about the people who make the least amount of wine,
which often is the most expensive.
</P>
<P>
   But these wines are not necessarily to everyone's taste, or
budget. Every year around this time, Market Watch, a trade
publication based in New York, releases a report on what it calls
``hot brands,'' individual wines and lines of wines whose sales
performance was particularly outstanding in the last calendar year.
These are the wines that millions of Americans buy not for snob
appeal or investment potential, but because they enjoy drinking
them.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprising, Chateau Petrus from Bordeaux, which makes only
about 3,000 cases a year, and the Grace Family Vineyards in
California, which makes a mere 300 cases, are not on this list. But
E.&AMP;J. Gallo is; it makes about 75 million cases a year. So is
Sebastiani Vineyards and some companies that are probably unknown
to drinkers of premium wines, like the Wine Group, which makes
Corbett Canyon wines, and Southcorp Wines of Australia, best known
for its Lindemans label.
</P>
<P>
   The hot brands are not necessarily the biggest sellers; rather,
they are the wines that showed the biggest jumps in sales volume
from one year to the next. What makes them important is what they
tell us about wine drinking in America now and the direction in
which it is headed. And that direction is toward well-made varietal
wines _ chardonnays, merlots, cabernets _ and away from generics
like domestic burgundy.
</P>
<P>
   The hottest domestic brand in 1998, according to Market Watch,
was Vendange from Sebastiani Vineyards in Sonoma, Calif. Vendange
makes several varietal wines, and their sales jumped from 3.8
million cases in 1997 to 4.4 million last year, an increase of
almost 15 percent. Second was Turning Leaf from Gallo, up 19
percent to a bit more than 3 million cases.
</P>
<P>
   Gallo had three other brands in the top 15: Gossamer Bay, 5th,
with 1.75 million cases, a 25 percent increase; Copperidge, 6th,
with 1.7 million cases, up 13 percent, and Gallo Sonoma, 15th,
225,000 cases, also up 25 percent. Sebastiani also took 7th and
13th place with its Nathanson Creek and Talus brands.
</P>
<P>
   Rounding out the top 15 were Kendall-Jackson, 3rd; Corbett
Canyon, 4th; Clos du Bois, 8th; Meridian, 9th; Beaulieu Vineyard,
10th; Robert Mondavi Coastal, 11th; Forest Glen, 12th, and
Forestville Vineyards, 14th.
</P>
<P>
   Other imported hot brands, in addition to Lindemans, were
Rosemount Estates of Australia; three Chilean wines _ Walnut Crest,
Vina Carolina and Caliterra _ and the only brand from Europe, Ecco
Domani. Caliterra is actually a Robert Mondavi wine and Ecco
Domani, a Gallo Italian import.
</P>
<P>
   For the record, the biggest selling wine brand in the United
States in 1998 was Franzia, made by the Wine Group, which sold 19
million cases in the bag-in-a box format. But it showed only about
a 6 percent growth rate, so it did not make the hot brands list.
Similarly, Banfi Vintners Reunite brand was the largest-selling
imported wine in this country, but its growth rate did not qualify
it for the list.
</P>
<P>
   What distinguishes this year's hot brands is the fact that they
are almost all varietal wines, which is a wine named for the
particular grape from which it is principally made. Some are made
to appeal to specific age and income groups but their producers
appear to share a common conviction: that Americans who drink wine,
whatever their age, income or level of sophistication, are no
longer satisfied with what used to be known as jug wines.
</P>
<P>
   The figures bear this out. In 1990, the California wine industry
shipped 65 million cases of generic wines and 44 million cases of
varietals. In 1997, the last year for which these figures are
available, the industry shipped 52 million cases of generics and 82
million cases of varietals. In 1985, varietals accounted for 14
percent of California wine shipments; in 1997, they accounted for
61 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Chardonnay remains the most popular of all grape varieties. It
regularly outsells almost all the other varietal wines combined.
Cabernet sauvignon continues to be the leading red grape variety,
with merlot, zinfandel and pinot noir, in that order, following
well behind.
</P>
<P>
   The most popular of all varietal wines after chardonnay is white
zinfandel, which is neither white nor, in many cases, entirely
zinfandel. Sweet and slightly carbonated, white zinfandel is more
of a specialty drink than a wine but its devoted fans insist that
it goes well with many kinds of food. Its popularity is
astonishing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It appeals to so many people because it resembles what they
grew up drinking, fruit juices and colas,'' said Stanley Hock, a
spokesman for Sutter Home Winery, which claims to have invented the
pink wine and makes and ships 4 million cases of it a year.
</P>
<P>
   While sophisticated wine drinkers may dismiss these popular
wines as irrelevant to their life styles, they do so at their
peril. The production of truly fine wines will always be limited.
In many of the fine wine districts of France, Italy and the Napa
Valley, there is no space left for expansion. But the demand for
better wines continues to grow; many of the world's best wines are
already sold on allocation.
</P>
<P>
   Most hot brands are in the $6 to $10 range, but as more
consumers learn to like varietal wines, the pressure on prices will
steadily increase. Connoisseurs may not be happy, but their
grumbling is all but drowned out by the wine industry cheering:
``Let's hear it for the hot brands.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
