<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHIGELLA-EATING-WELL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PARSLEY FOUND GUILTY IN SHIGELLOSIS OUTBREAKS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Minn., Calif., Mass., Fla., Canada)  (mk) 
 By MARIAN BURROS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Parsley very often is a garnish that is left on the plate. Which
makes the discovery that parsley was responsible for seven
outbreaks of shigellosis, a food-borne illness, last summer all the
more remarkable.
</P>
<P>
   ``Parsley is one of those things you hardly ever ask about,''
said Dr. Robert Tauxe, the chief of the food-borne and diarrheal
diseases branch of the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention
in Atlanta. But scientists were able to link the outbreaks by using
Pulsenet, a sophisticated detection system that enables them to
fingerprint the DNA of bacteria. They can then compare the
fingerprints to see if the bacteria are from a common source. In
this case, they were able to then trace the parsley to a farm in
Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists at the Minnesota Department of Health used Pulsenet
to track the shigella bacteria that caused two of the outbreaks of
shigellosis, which occurred in the state. From there, the system
helped link the parsley to outbreaks in California, Massachusetts
and Florida, and Ontario and Alberta in Canada.
</P>
<P>
   The 493 confirmed and likely cases of shigellosis in this
instance were traced to restaurant foods, including chicken
sandwiches and pasta dishes, garnished with parsley.
</P>
<P>
   Shigellosis, which occurs within 12 to 24 hours and lasts three
to five days, causes fever, serious abdominal cramps, nausea and
diarrhea. In the past it has been easily treated with antibiotics,
but this strain from Mexico was more antibiotic-resistant and
required additional treatment.
</P>
<P>
   Some forms of shigella, generally found in developing countries,
can cause dysentery, which may lead to kidney failure and death.
</P>
<P>
   Between 15,000 and 20,000 cases of shigellosis are diagnosed
each year in the United States, but the Centers for Disease Control
say that like all food- borne infections, many more go undiagnosed.
</P>
<P>
   Shigella lives in human feces and usually is passed from person
to person when carriers do not wash their hands. But scientists
believe this parsley was first contaminated at the farm right after
it was harvested, when it was kept in water that had not been
chlorinated.
</P>
<P>
   And the way the parsley was handled at the restaurants was a
contributing factor. It was chopped and left at room temperature
instead of being refrigerated. Chopping releases nutrients that
feed the bacteria, but refrigeration lowers the level of the
bacteria. Parsley can be chopped in advance, after washing under
cold running water. But chopped or whole, it should be refrigerated
at all times.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
