<HEADER>
A0569 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CUSTOMS-CORRUPTION-HN     05-25 0754
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUSTOMS-CORRUPTION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CORRUPTION AT CUSTOMS CITED IN SENATE TESTIMONY 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDs: Stands for INS-ABUSE)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By GARY MARTIN  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Allegations of wrongdoing by U.S. Customs Service
officers tripled from 1996 to 1998, according to a Senate analysis
released Tuesday that ranked Miami and the Texas cities of El Paso
and McAllen as the top three sites for complaints nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   The analysis by the Senate Finance Committee agrees with a
Treasury Department inspector general's investigation and outside
audits that there was no ``systemic corruption'' within the agency.
</P>
<P>
   But the frequency and number of allegations _ which include
bribery and drug smuggling _ make clear ``that strong external
oversight'' is needed for the troubled agency, said Sen. William
Roth Jr., R-Del., the committee chairman who held the last of three
oversight hearings on Customs on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The analysis found the most common accusation against Customs
officers from 1996 to 1998 was bribery, which amounted to 8.6
percent of all complaints.
</P>
<P>
   Sexual harassment and misconduct made up 7.2 percent of the
complaints followed by disclosure of confidential information, 5.8
percent; assault, 4.5 percent; drug trafficking, 3.9 percent; and
threats, 3.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Miami was the Customs office against which the most allegations
_ 11 percent _ were made, followed by El Paso and McAllen, with 9
percent each.
</P>
<P>
   However, the analysis did not elaborate on the nature of the
complaints.
</P>
<P>
   Other cities were: Tucson, Ariz., 6 percent; Los Angeles and San
Francisco, 5 percent each; San Diego, 4 percent; Customs
headquarters in Washington and the Houston office, 3 percent each.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, accusations of criminal wrongdoing and misconduct more
than tripled to 677 in 1998 from 209 in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   The committee asked former New York state Judge Milton Mollen,
who headed the Mollen Commission that investigated corruption
within the New York Police Department between 1992 and 1994, to
review complaints against Customs.
</P>
<P>
   Mollen said Customs officers reflect society; some are dedicated
and honorable while some are weak and vulnerable.
</P>
<P>
   ``Others are just plain venal, who view public service as a
means of using their power to illegally enrich themselves,'' Mollen
said, urging the panel to create an outside monitor to work with
Customs to confront corruption.
</P>
<P>
   Customs Commissioner Raymond Kelly has implemented procedures to
better address the complaints and has hired William Keefer, a
former Justice Department official and federal prosecutor, to steer
the agency's internal affairs operations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Misconduct by Customs employees will not be tolerated under my
watch,'' Kelly told the panel.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want everyone to understand the rules as well as the
consequences of any illegal or improper activities,'' Keefer said.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Tarr, an assistant inspector general with the Treasury
Department, said their review of Customs complaints found that
internal affairs investigators failed to follow all leads and
lacked supervisory review.
</P>
<P>
   When misconduct was substantiated, ``disciplinary penalties were
inconsistently applied,'' Tarr said, and that created a fear of
reprisal among officers and employees filing complaints against
other officers.
</P>
<P>
   Vincent Parolisi, a former New York police internal affairs
officer, was hired by Customs on May 9 to help clean up the agency.
</P>
<P>
   He told the Senate panel, ``The most formidable corruption
threat facing Customs is the illegal drug trade.''
</P>
<P>
   Parolisi also said Customs reviews found that internal affairs
``is more reactionary than proactive in detecting and combating
corruption.''
</P>
<P>
   Customs has implemented new recruitment and training practices,
and has outlined new guidelines on disciplinary actions.
</P>
<P>
   The agency is working with the Immigration and Naturalization
Service to provide more supervision and control of agents working
at land ports of entry along the U.S.-Mexico border. The INS is a
Justice Department agency and Customs is part of the Treasury
Department.
</P>
<P>
   Allegations against inspectors accounted for 29 percent of all
cases, and criminal investigators were targets of 12 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Internal affairs officers referred only 53 percent of the
allegations to Customs management for review. Of those, 29 percent
of the cases reviewed by management resulted in no action, while 71
percent resulted in some sort of sanction.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
