<SLUG> BC-SIMPLE-COOKING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT'S HOT IN BACKYARDS: GRILLED SPICY SHRIMP 
</HEADLINE>
   (editors: recipe at end of article)  
 (bl)  
 By MARK BITTMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   For all the pleasures of slow smoking on a grill, speed is why
we usually most value a grill in the backyard. I constantly get
requests for a simple but unusual, fast-cooking, great-tasting
recipe for the grill, and I always recommend spicy shrimp.
</P>
<P>
   The seasonings I use are common _ garlic, lemon, olive oil,
cayenne, paprika and salt _ but that combination produces a huge
impact on the shrimp flavor. I keep the cayenne to a minimum,
because good paprika has some heat. The red of the paprika makes
the dish look hotter than it really is, giving it a certain macho
appeal. To me, the flavor is best intense but not fiery. But you
can make it incendiary if you like.
</P>
<P>
   The key is fresh paprika, not that tin you inherited from your
mother. After you buy it, taste it; if it is hot, use half a
teaspoon.
</P>
<P>
   I created the spicy paste for this dish as a marinade to hasten
the thawing of frozen shrimp, but now I rely on it whether there is
time to marinate or not. You can let the shrimp sit in it for
hours. In fact, I like to dump both shrimp and paste in a covered
plastic container, shake them together to coat the shrimp, then
carry the container to a party and grill the shrimp there. Or just
mix the two together right before cooking.
</P>
<P>
   If you don't have a grill, the recipe also works broiled. Or you
might try it in a hot, dry pan on top of the stove, but that will
cause smoke.
</P>
<P>
   Almost all shrimp are frozen before they are sold, so you don't
sacrifice quality by buying frozen shrimp and thawing them
yourself. They may even be better.
</P>
<P>
   You don't have to peel the shrimp before cooking them either,
but I think the paste has more impact if you do, and you also
perform a kindness for your guests. I don't even bother to devein
the shrimp, because I doubt one person in 10 can tell the
difference once they are cooked.
</P>
<P>
   I like easy dishes that are so good they make people go nuts and
eat more than they should, and this is one fine example.
</P>
<P>
   SPICY GRILLED SHRIMP
</P>
<P>
   Time: 20 minutes, after heating the grill
</P>
<P>
   1 large clove garlic
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon coarse salt
</P>
<P>
   { teaspoon cayenne
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon paprika
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons olive oil
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons freshly squeezed lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   1{ to 2 pounds shrimp, in the 15-to-18-a-pound range (or
smaller, if skewered), peeled, rinsed and dried
</P>
<P>
   Lemon wedges.
</P>
<P>
   1. Start a charcoal or gas grill, or preheat the broiler. Make
the fire as hot as it will get, and adjust the rack so that it is
as close to the heat source as possible.
</P>
<P>
   2. Mince the garlic with the salt; mix it with the cayenne and
paprika, then make it into a paste with the olive oil and lemon
juice. Smear the paste all over the shrimp. Grill or broil the
shrimp, 2 to 3 minutes a side, turning once. Serve immediately or
at room temperature, with lemon wedges.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 servings.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
