<SLUG> BC-STATES-BEE-PA </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;        PENNSYLVANIA WHIZ-KID ADVANCES TO NATIONAL GEOGRAPHY BEE
FINALS
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;     By Lisa Fine  
 &HT;    c. 1999 States News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON, May 25-- A Pennsylvania teen beat out 45 others and
will advance to the final rounds of this year's National Geography
Bee for a chance to win a college scholarship and trip to
Australia.
</P>
<P>
   Raji Shankar, 14, of Havertown, Pa., and nine others from states
or U.S. territories, will be quizzed Wednesday by Jeopardy! game
show host Alex Trebek. ``I read a lot,'' Shankar said. ``I am
fortunate to have parents who allowed me to travel. They didn't
make me study this or anything, I was just good at it and it took
off from there.''
</P>
<P>
   Shankar, an eighth grader at Haverford Middle School, will be
tested for her ability to locate places on maps, define geological
terms, and identify countries by a photograph, description of the
culture or an historical event.
</P>
<P>
   With poise and enthusiasm, Shankar prevailed in eight of ten
rounds of questions Tuesday. She gave the correct answers to
questions about which country lies farther north, Chad or Botswana,
(Chad), and which Japanese island is linked to Shikoku by the
world's longest suspension bridge that spans the Inland Sea.
(Honshu).
</P>
<P>
   Shankar, who represented the state last year, but did not make
it to the final rounds, said she prepared for the contest by
studying the World Atlas for a half-hour every night and reading
international news stories.
</P>
<P>
   Her mother, Raja Kumari, said her daughter is ``world-minded''
because she has visited a grandmother in India, and vacationed in
places like Australia.
</P>
<P>
   Shankar said she enjoys reading and traveling. She said she
would most like to visit the Yucatan Peninsula to see the Maya
ruins.
</P>
<P>
   The National Geographic Society, which sponsors the contest is
offering the $25,000 scholarship and Bank One Corp., is providing
the winner with a week-long trip to Australia.
</P>
<P>
   In the final round of the contest Shankar and teens from New
York, Maine, Michigan, Missouri, North Dakota, Puerto Rico,
Tennessee, Washington, Mississippi and South Carolina, will be
eliminated as soon as they answer two questions incorrectly.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
