A0595 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WINE-INTERNET-NYTR &LR;      05-25 0940
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WINE-INTERNET-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE PROVISION COULD SHORT-CIRCUIT INTERNET LIQUOR SALES 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By CARL HULSE   
 New York Times Regional Newspapers   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The provision doesn't even mention the Internet and
it amends an arcane beverage law crafted well before World War I.
</P>
<P>
   But the stilted language on ``intoxicating liquor'' that was
slipped into a juvenile crime bill is at the center of a 21st
Century congressional fight over the future of e-commerce and sales
of wine and spirits via the Web.
</P>
<P>
   America's vintners and their allies in the world of cyberspace
say a newly adopted Senate proposal that would allow disputes over
interstate alcohol shipments to be aired in federal court is an
assault on computer shopping masquerading as a crackdown on
underage drinking.
</P>
<P>
   ``This bill does nothing to stop kids from getting alcohol,''
said Rep. Mike Thompson, D-Calif., co-chair of the congressional
Wine Caucus. ``It does a lot to slow down the effort that a lot of
states are making to solve the problem of a distribution system for
small wineries.''
</P>
<P>
   Proponents of the measure argue it is nothing more than a
well-aimed effort to reduce underage drinking and resolve some
confusion over the ability of states to enforce laws already on the
books regarding liquor shipments.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only ones who need fear this are those who are conducting
their business in an unlawful manner, particularly those who are
willing to sell alcohol to our children,'' thundered Sen. Robert
Byrd, D-W.V., as he persuaded the Senate to accept his approach.
</P>
<P>
   The high-stakes, increasingly high-decibel fight pits liquor
wholesalers trying to maintain their hold on distribution against
winemakers trying to reach new markets. It matches anti-alcohol
forces against boosters of the Internet. It contrasts the days of
Prohibition with the millennium.
</P>
<P>
   Until recently, the issue had been debated mainly at the state
level as some state legislatures sought to close their borders to
liquor shipments by making such transactions a felony. Elsewhere,
state officials have negotiated direct shipment programs with the
wine industry.
</P>
<P>
   The dispute only smoldered on Capitol Hill as the subject of
public hearings and private negotiations toward a compromise. But
it burst into the open last week when Byrd attached his proposal to
the high-profile juvenile justice bill on a surprisingly lopsided
80-17 vote.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Dianne Feinstein, D-Calif., a wine industry ally, added her
own amendment, one she portrayed as a more direct attempt to curb
underage drinking. Her measure requires shipments be marked as
alcohol with recipients forced to show proof of age.
</P>
<P>
   Now the issue moves to the House, where the legislative dynamic
is quite different. California has 52 representatives there and
many are friendly to the wine industry, including key members of
the Judiciary Committee, which has jurisdiction over much of the
juvenile crime bill.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson and Wine Caucus co-chairman George Radanovich,
R-Calif., a small winemaker, already circulated a letter objecting
to the Byrd plan to Rep. Henry Hyde, R-Ill., chairman of the panel,
as well as other congressional leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Critics of the provision say it is moving rapidly because a main
trade association backing the law, the Wine and Spirits Wholesalers
of America, has hired lobbyists who are former staffers to the two
main Senate proponents _ Byrd and Sen. Orrin Hatch, R-Utah. As
Senate Judiciary Committee chairman, Hatch first proposed the
crackdown and held a hearing on the issue in March.
</P>
<P>
   But officials at the wholesalers group said a Utah court case
over beer shipments grabbed Hatch's attention before the lobbyists
were brought on board.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically this is a back-home issue for Hatch,'' said David
Dickerson, a spokesman for the group. ``His own state is having
trouble enforcing the law.''
</P>
<P>
   The wine industry has not been reluctant to call in big guns of
its own. Among the opponents it has enlisted to the shipping
measure is the Association for Interactive Media. The large
Internet association has more than 300 influential corporate
members such as Yahoo!, Citibank and The New York Times. The group
says it fears the legislation could stifle the growth of Internet
commerce.
</P>
<P>
   The wine industry has also shown its willingness to play
hardball on the issue. On the Senate floor, Feinstein sprung the
news that Mothers Against Drunk Driving was no longer backing the
push for the Byrd measure, saying the dispute was one between
competing elements of the liquor industry.
</P>
<P>
   And the wine lobby has taken aim at the advocacy group Americans
for Responsible Alcohol Access, an organization the Wine Institute
calls a ``front'' for the wholesalers. The group has helped
television stations around the nation conduct audience-grabbing
``stings'' that show teen-agers buying spirits over the Internet.
The wine industry says those transactions could not have happened
without adult involvement.
</P>
<P>
   Barry McCahill, executive director of the group, says it is no
secret that the 2-year-old organization is funded by the liquor
wholesalers. But he said that on the direct sales issue, the
interests of the alcohol distributors and the anti-youth drinking
community coincide.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are trying to change the subject and make it about me and
the industry,'' he said of the wine lobby. ``The fact of the matter
is, these guys are shipping alcohol illegally and that has been
documented time and time again.''
</P>
<P>
   (Carl Hulse is based in the New York Times Regional Newspaper
Group's Washington bureau.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
