<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-25 17:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0607 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHEF-GEOMANCY-ART-2TA     05-25 0979
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHEF-GEOMANCY-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE FATE OF MANY A RESTAURANT IS WRITTEN IN THE SAND 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (af)  
 By RICK MARIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ What does a four-star chef do before making a big
decision about his restaurant, his personal life, his career goals?
</P>
<P>
   He jots some hash marks on a piece of paper and asks a
42-year-old Frenchman named Jerome Brasset to tell him what to do.
Hire a new sous-chef, say, or open a franchise in Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   Brasset says he can divine the future through an obscure occult
practice known as geomancy. The bizarre thing is that many of New
York's finest French chefs believe him.
</P>
<P>
   At least a dozen of them are into it, including Daniel Boulud,
Francois Payard, Jean-Louis Palladin and Eric Ripert, plus many of
their partners, wives and kitchen lieutenants. Echoing the words of
his fellow devotees, Jean-Georges Vongerichten said, ``I don't make
a move without him.''
</P>
<P>
   Other chefs think it's the nuttiest thing they've ever heard.
Christian Delouvrier, of Lespinasse, merely started laughing: ``I
don't believe it! Those guys go to a fortune teller? Ha ha ha.''
</P>
<P>
   But to Vongerichten, Brasset is no laughing matter. He has been
consulting him closely on his plans to open a boutique hotel and a
restaurant (his 10th) downtown. ``I would have walked away from the
Mercer Kitchen deal if it weren't for Jerome,'' Vongerichten said.
``I never would have opened Prime in Las Vegas or Vong in Chicago
if Jerome hadn't given me the clear-sailing sign.''
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, Ripert, the chef and co-owner of Le Bernardin, was
informed by Brasset that a key employee would be leaving soon. Sure
enough, the chef at Ripert's Atlanta restaurant quit. Jean-Yves
Schillinger was having trouble with the liquor license when he
opened Destinee a year and a half ago. Brasset said the license
would go through in a month. It did. Boulud, of Daniel and Cafe
Boulud, goes so far as to call Brasset a ``supervoyant.''
</P>
<P>
   They met through Daniel's maitre d' hotel, Bruno Jamais, who has
also introduced Brasset to other members of what Jamais called
``the French mafia connection.'' Among them are Boulud's former
pastry chef, Payard, now the co-owner of his own eponymous
patisserie. ``I don't sign a deal before I ask his advice,'' Payard
said.
</P>
<P>
   Brasset's influence extends all the way up to Alain Ducasse,
whose six Michelin stars (for two restaurants) make him something
of a culinary godfather to this generation of ambitious,
entrepreneurial French chefs. Ducasse, coy about his friendship
with Brasset, does not deny there is one.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not saying yes and I'm not saying no,'' he said, through a
spokesman, when asked if he had used him professionally. ``But I
have a lot of friends who have consulted him who have been
astonished by his performance.''
</P>
<P>
   The performance takes place during Brasset's readings. At $325
each, these private 90-minute sessions purport to draw on an
ancient form of fortunetelling dating from the early Egyptians.
Originally, the subject of the reading would draw lines in the
sand, or dirt, and the geomancer would ``read'' them, barefoot so
as to be in closer contact with the earth's forces.
</P>
<P>
   In Brasset's updated version, clients draw a random number of
hash marks on paper across 16 numbered lines. Brasset counts the
marks, runs them through his geomantic formulas, then offers his
advice.
</P>
<P>
   For customers unable to arrange or afford a tete-a-tete, Brasset
has a Web site, www.geomancyonline.com, programmed to answer all
questions (in sometimes broken English). A few months ago,
Vongerichten thought he had found his dream apartment. He logged on
and asked if he should buy. The answer came back: ``Categorically
not.'' He withdrew the bid.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is Cartesian,'' Brasset said of his system, on the phone
from his vacation house on the Spanish island of Ibiza. ``Precise,
accurate and mathematically elegant.'' The $325 fee (or as little
as $25 on line) is, he maintained, ``not expensive, because if you
want to know, `Should I open a restaurant?' it is many millions of
dollars.''
</P>
<P>
   Skeptics, of course, disagree.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has no basis in fact, like any divining,'' said James
Randi, president of the James Randi Educational Foundation, which
is devoted to debunking paranormal claims. ``Getting to know
unknown knowledge _ it's been tested endlessly, and it just doesn't
work.''
</P>
<P>
   Randi, a former illusionist known as the Amazing Randi,
dismissed geomancy as yet another form of ``gobbledygook,''
``flimflam,'' ``fantasy talk.''
</P>
<P>
   Other New York chefs were shocked to hear that some of their
most eminent colleagues were in a psychic's thrall.
</P>
<P>
   Charlie Palmer, the owner of Aureole, could barely contain his
amusement. ``I'm going to get Dionne Warwick down here,'' he said,
aluding to the singer and ``Psychic Hotline'' host. ``Maybe she
could help me pick some new fabrics.''
</P>
<P>
   But no amount of scoffing seems to penetrate Brasset's Delphic
cool. ``I am never wrong,'' he said, offering, by way of example,
his warning to clients of last July's stock market mini-crash. Much
of his clientele _ businessmen, politicians, movie stars, chefs,
the rich _ seek his market wisdom. Shouldn't he play and get rich,
too?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not my job,'' he said. ``I have enough. I have one mouth,
no more.''
</P>
<P>
   One he evidently enjoys feeding well. ``He's a big foodie,''
Vongerichten said. Ariane Daguin, whose company, D'Artagnan,
supplies fois gras and high-end game to many of New York's best
restaurants, said she saw Brasset at Palladin with Ducasse during
last month's James Beard Awards. She assumed he was some kind of
``foodie parasite,'' until her reading, at the bar of Jean Georges.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``The guy told me things from my past that nobody knows,'' she
said. ``He totally described my daughter's father.'' Another
convert. ``I don't regret my 300 bucks for one second,'' she added.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone becomes an instant disciple. Sue Huffman, the
director of marketing at the French Culinary Institute, said she
``wasn't shaken'' by her reading. Brasset said he saw her ``working
with foreigners,'' a safe bet, given her job. ``Well, yeah, there's
a lot of French people down here,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   And yet Ms. Huffman spoke glowingly about the handsome
Frenchman's charisma. ``He's absolutely charming,'' she said. ``You
kind of have to tear yourself away, because you feel like you could
talk to him for hours.''
</P>
<P>
   A valuable quality, apparently. His Web site lists his New York
address as the Pierre, where he stays every other month. Brasset
said he has about 2,000 clients. That's a lot of hash marks.
</P>
<P>
   In ancient Greece, Archimedes is said to have used geomancy to
foresee the outcome of battles. In the Islamic world, it remains a
common form of fortunetelling. But its last heyday in Western
civilization was the Renaissance.
</P>
<P>
   Princes needed to know whether it was a good time to invade a
neighboring city-state. The emerging mercantile class had questions
about frankincense futures. Then, as now, it was used by men with
their minds on their money and their money on their minds.
</P>
<P>
   John M. Greer, author of ``Earth Divination, Earth Magic: A
Practical Guide to Geomancy,'' to be published by Llewellyn in
July, said geomancy was ``traditionally very good for business
decisions and practical things.''
</P>
<P>
   And the business of chefs is, more than ever, business. And yet,
as Laurent Manrique, who left Gertrude's in March to become the
executive chef at Campton Place in San Francisco, explained:
``Chefs are in a world of food and craziness. They don't always
make the best business decisions.''
</P>
<P>
   Since the gold standard to which many of them aspire is
Vongerichten and Ducasse, they figure ``if it works for Ducasse,
maybe then it works for me,'' Vongerichten said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite their vaunted Gallic rationalism, the French have a
weakness for psychic gobbledygook. Business decisions in France are
often made with the aid of an astrologer. Banks there have been
known to require handwriting samples with job applications.
</P>
<P>
   Before adopting his current vocation, Brasset was himself a
businessman, an executive at Generale des Eaux, France's largest
water company. He met his first geomancer 15 years ago, then became
one himself, full time, in 1993. His hangout was the Parisian
two-star restaurant Ledoyen, where he did readings and befriended
the maitre d'hotel, Jamais, now at Daniel.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really came to understand chefs and the pressures they work
under,'' Brasset said. ``Chefs are anguished. At night, after
service, when everything is quiet, they have questions and no one
to turn to.''
</P>
<P>
   Vongerichten agreed. ``I work with people all day long,'' he
said. ``I'm never alone, but I never really have the chance to talk
about the issues and decisions that are very important to me. These
are the things I talk to Jerome about.'' Brasset also showed him
how to ``communicate'' and ``to be more open,'' Vongerichten said.
</P>
<P>
   Strip away the pseudomathematical mumbo jumbo, and Brasset is
also a therapist, a validater of anxieties. Palladin requested a
two-and-a-half-hour session a couple of weeks ago to help him deal
with personal issues. ``A relationship just came to an end, and I
need someone to give me advice on how I can take it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Most important, to these chefs, Brasset is _ how do you say? _
there for them. As Jamais put it: ``Most of the time when you have
a question, you already have a thought. You just need to be
convinced to listen to what is in your mind.''
</P>
<P>
   And then do whatever Jerome says. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-25-99 1713EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
