  THIS IS THE STATES NEWS SERVICE BUDGET FOR MAY
25, 1999. IF YOU HAVE ANY QUESTIONS, PLEASE CALL US AT
202-628-3100.
<TEXT>
<P>
   CALIFORNIA-STUDY-TV. (For the Hollywood Reporter.) A look at a
study from the Parents Television Council (Possible.) Robin Brown
</P>
<P>
   COLORADO-DEGETTE-GUNS. Worried that the Republican majority in
the House will be less likely to approve new gun control measures
after the Memorial Day recess, Rep. Diana DeGette is leading a
Democratic drive to force an early vote this week. The Denver
Democrat on Tuesday started to collect House members' signatures on
a petition that will, if she gets 218 of them, make Republican
leaders debate gun control on the floor this week. (400 words.) By
Charles Davant
</P>
<P>
   COLORADO-ALLARD-RENO. In the wake of reports that the Justice
Department failed to stop Chinese spies from stealing nuclear
secrets from U.S. weapons labs, Sen. Wayne Allard, R-Colo., called
Tuesday for Attorney General Janet Reno to resign. He also cited
her ``failures'' in other respects. (200 words.) By Charles Davant
</P>
<P>
   COLORADO-INSURANCE-CONSUMER. Colorado Insurance Commissioner
William Kirven warned the state's federal lawmakers Tuesday that
legislation that would liberalize the financial industry would gut
the state's consumer-protection laws. (400 words.) By Charles
Davant
</P>
<P>
   MAINE-GEOGRAPHY-BEE. A Maine whiz kid beat out 45 students from
around the nation Tuesday to advance to the finals of the National
Geography Bee. He is competing for a $25,000 college scholarship
and a trip to Australia. (500 words.) By Charles Davant
</P>
<P>
   MASSACHUSETTS-MCGOVERN-HEALTH. Rep. James P. McGovern,
D-Worcester, introduced legislation Tuesday to help ease the
continuing crisis facing the home health industry. (350 words.) By
Mark D. Preston
</P>
<P>
   NEW JERSEY-CHINA-REACT. Reaction from New Jersey delegation to
Cox report on China. (400 words.) By Paul Kane
</P>
<P>
   NEW MEXICO-CHINA-LAB. China's alleged pilfering of U.S. nuclear
secrets was apparently aided by contact scientists at the Los
Alamos National Laboratory had with officials from the China
Academy of Engineering Physics, which oversees China's nuclear
weapons programs. (400 words.) By Carrie Cunningham
</P>
<P>
   OHIO-AIRMEN-BILL. U.S. airmen killed in NATO operations in the
Balkans would be memorialized if legislation introduced recently by
Rep. Steven C. LaTourette becomes law. (300 words.) By Sean Gorman
</P>
<P>
   PENNSYLVANIA-BEE. A suburban Philadelphia whiz kid could put
Pennsylvania on the map tomorrow by representing the state against
nine other teens in the final rounds of this year's National
Geography Bee. (400 words.) By Lisa Fine
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS-OSPREY. A key Senate panel approved an additional $123
million on top of the Pentagon's budget request for the V-22
Osprey.(300 words.) By Robin Brown
</P>
<P>
   WISCONSIN-MISSING-CHILDREN. Today, National Missing Child Day,
Rep. Mark Green (R-Green Bay) introduced legislation that would
make it harder for sex offenders to enjoy some of the ``privileges
of America.'' (450 words.) By Mary Shaffrey
</P>
