<HEADLINE>
KANSAS CITY STAR BUDGET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Kansas City Star plans to move the following stories for use
by clients of the NYTimes News Service for AMs and PMs of
Wednesday, May 26. If you have any questions, please call The
Star's News Desk at (816) 234-4720.
</P>
<P>
   GORE _ Sen. John Ashcroft and Missouri Gov. Carnahan must have
thought they were hearing things when Vice President Gore called
for ``faith-based'' efforts to combat social ills. The Republican
senator has been pushing for this partnership of state and church
in the past, and now he's going to again drag out his bill, stalled
by Democrats. We suspect that Democrat Carnahan was not pleased.
David Goldstein. 25.
</P>
<P>
   WATER: At the same time he was running Mayor Kay Barnes'
campaign, political consultant Pat Gray also was working for a St.
Louis firm, Environmental Management Inc., that wants to take over
Kansas City's biggest money maker, the Water Department. Since
Barnes has taken office, she's ordered an audit of the Water
Department that some see as the first step towards ``privatizing''
its operations. A draft plan of Environmental Management Inc.'s
strategy for taking over the Water Department has been obtained by
The Star. It calls for Gray to run a public campaign to convince
voters that private management of the Water Department is a good
idea. Gromer Jeffers. 40. Photo of water treatment plant; mugs of
Barnes and Gray.
</P>
<P>
   GUN: We've been robbed! Or at least cheated. Apparently two guns
that have been touted as once owned by Jesse James were actually
made after his death. Jerry Berrios. 10. Photo of guns.
</P>
<P>
   RAYTOWN: The Raytown School District announced more than a month
ago that it would enact a dress code to bring more decorum to its
graduation, but folks were still upset on Monday when it was
enforced and some people couldn't enter. Second graduation is
Tuesday night. Donald Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   OWEN (developing): Foloing the death of WWF wrestler Owen Hart,
including updating any progress in police investigation of cause.
Also, WWF says this stunt won't be performed again, but others
will. Family criticizes WWF for such stunts. Ruth Igoe. 12.
</P>
<P>
   PIPE: Far away in Alaska, when the pictures show oil-soaked
birds and a tanker leaking crude into the ocean, an environmental
disaster such as the Exxon Valdez will easily capture the national
limelight. Much closer to home, however, the potential for another
kind of petroleum disaster lurks underground, along 150,000 miles
of pipelines that transport hazardous liquids through such places
as rural Atchison. Ruptured lines can occur anywhere, from
Coffeyville, Kan., to Glasgow, Mo., to just outside the nation's
capitol in Washington. They may not get the publicity of an Exxon
Valdez, but pipeline breaks caused $54 million in property damage
last year in the U.S., and by one count spilled 7.7 million gallons
of oil and other substances. The Environmental Defense Fund calls
that the worst toll in eight years, and charges that federal
regulators don't do nearly enough to prevent incidents like the
pipeline break outside Atchison. Pipeline companies say they still
offer the safest way to transport oil, and they're doing what they
can, including the use of ``smart pigs,'' instrument-laden devices
that travel through a line to detect possible problems. John L.
Dvorak. 36. Chart.
</P>
<P>
   CHICK. The Humane Society is outraged at Olathe South and North
high schools, where science students experiment with baby chicks by
injecting them with steroids; there is no dissection and most
chicks survive, but the Humane Society says its illegal because
federal law doesn't recognize schools as a research institute;
district says state law says they are; Humane Society will provide
district with alternatives and threatens to sue if experiment
continues next year. Mhari Doyle.
</P>
<P>
   SINE. The Kansas Legislature formally adjourns for the year.
John A. Dvorak.
</P>
<P>
   KCKTRACK (sports): Plans are unveiled for the NASCAR auto racing
track in Kansas City, Kan. Jim Pedley. 20.
</P>
<P>
   MOBOAT (business) _ April numbers are in, and it's another
record month for Kansas City's floating casinos: $42.85 million
this time. Story also will advance BOAT 27. Rick Alm.
</P>
<P>
   PAYLESS (business, tentative) _ Payless Cashways could be
opening its first new store in a few years. Jennifer Mann
</P>
<P>
   ONEOK (business) _ Oneoak, the Oklahoma company that supplies
natural gas to much of Kansas, has filed a $7.5 million suite
against Kansas Pipeline Co. Steve Everly.
</P>
</TEXT>
