<HEADER>
A0662 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PARADISE-BOOK-REVIEW-     05-25 1174
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PARADISE-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`INVENTING PARADISE': ON A GREEK ODYSSEY BY LAND, SEA AND POETRY 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Production notes are at end of review)  
 (af)  
 By RICHARD EDER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Mono dyo atoma.'' Posted beside a Greek elevator, all this
means is that it would be a poor ride for more than two
individuals. For a foreign individual, though, what a grand thing
to be addressed as an atom (I and the cosmos, arm in arm). Or to be
addressed as ``Kyrios.''
</P>
<P>
   Christian or otherwise, there is a 2,000-year jolt in having
one's ``Mr.'' lofted to a declension of ``Kyrie,'' the word for God
in the Greek New Testament and the Latin Mass.
</P>
<P>
   Tug a root and the tree quivers. Despite changes, the Greek
language and the unchanged light, sea and landscape carry roots not
just of Western civilization but of all the civilizations the West
has touched as well. For centuries, visitors have found a
particular exaltation there, granted that some mainly find cheap
vacations, sunburn and wine poisoning. Here is Henry Miller's:
</P>
<P>
   ``To fall in love with it is the easiest thing in the world. It
is like falling in love with one's own divine image reflected in a
thousand dazzling facets.'' Sounds silly? Miller's hyperactive
rhetoric was a whole sluice of silliness, which he panned for
nuggets of fundamental and unsuspected sense.
</P>
<P>
   The Greek spell is real but we tend to snub experiences we
cannot explain. Talking about a gods-haunted landscape seems facile
until Miller reverses it: Greece can make a visitor feel godlike.
</P>
<P>
   The Miller quote is from ``Inventing Paradise'' by Professor
Edmund Keeley, a lifelong student of modern Greece and a translator
of its literature. ``Paradise'' is a wonderfully personal hybrid:
part history, part literary evocation, part memoir and most of all
a travel journal. The travels are by land and by book.
</P>
<P>
   Keeley's own journeying is in the background, unobtrusive but
essential, as a quietly attentive host is essential at a salon of
luminaries. The luminaries include Miller and Lawrence Durrell, and
the constellation of Greeks, mostly poets, including two Nobel
laureates, with whom they forged a remarkable personal and
intellectual comradeship beginning a few years before World War II
and continuing a few years after.
</P>
<P>
   Keeley draws extensively on their writings for his account of
those years: diaries, journals, correspondence; Durrell's
``Prospero's Cell,'' which tells of his prewar sojourn on Corfu,
and Miller's ``Colossus of Maroussi,'' a paean to Greece drawn out
of a nine-month visit with Durrell and his Greek friends. This may
seem short, but it is the gestation time for a human and, in
Miller's case, for the imaginative re-creation of a country, a
culture and his own fierce energies.
</P>
<P>
   Miller and Durrell provide a wealth of scenes and portraits.
They lie on a Corfu beach while a shepherd drives his sheep over
and around their naked bodies as if they were two inconvenient
boulders. The village mayor comes down with his three English words
to swap tall tales about an imagined China, followed by music and
dancing.
</P>
<P>
   There are explorations of the Peloponnese, feasts and
expeditions with Miller's ``colossus'' _ George Katsimbalis, patron
of the Greek literary revival and a man with a Gargantuan appetite
for food, wine and poetry _ and endless talk with the poets: George
Seferis, Odysseus Elytis, the sea captain D.I. Antoniou and others.
</P>
<P>
   There was the painter Niko Ghika, and Constantine Tsatsos, the
political battler against dictatorship who became Greece's
president decades later after the colonels shriveled and blew away.
</P>
<P>
   No dividing line, you see, between poetry and life or landscape
or national history or tradition or politics or the blinding light.
This was a revelation to the British Durrell and the American
Miller, for whom alienation and literature were synonymous.
</P>
<P>
   But I risk giving them too much space. They are Keeley's way
into his theme and provide a lot of the fun; they are only part of
it, though, and not its most memorable fun.
</P>
<P>
   As for the theme, ``Inventing Paradise'' observes that for more
than a century after Lord Byron, travelers to Greece noted little
but the remains and artifacts of its classical civilization. The
living inhabitants were bothersome, unsanitary and irrelevant.
</P>
<P>
   The extreme of post-Byronism, though the poet criticized it, was
the removal of the Elgin marbles from the Parthenon to sanitary and
imperially relevant London. It was equivalent to the barbaric
notion, to be voiced by later tourists, that France would be
perfect were it not for the French, begging the question of who put
France there and, day by day, keeps it there.
</P>
<P>
   Durrell and Miller were the first generation of those who,
literally at least, restored the marbles. (In the next generation
were the writers Patrick Leigh Fermor, Rex Warner and others
including, though he barely notes it, Keeley). They treated Greece
not as a museum but a place where some of the spirit and genius
that fill our museums and nourish our literature are found in the
speech, gestures and passions of a living people.
</P>
<P>
   It was a great discovery or invention. (The author implies both,
which is proper because what art creates is thereby created and
becomes the object of discovery.) But it did not really belong to
the foreigners; at most they were brilliant witnesses to what their
Greek comrades were doing.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the book, the author keeps returning to Seferis,
Elytis, Angelos Sikelianos, Yannis Ritsos and other poets, citing
letters, conversations and above all their poetry.
</P>
<P>
   With his commentary, this poetry, which he and Philip Sherrard
had previously translated, is the heart of the book. The lengthy
excerpts from the great poems of Seferis, in particular _
``Thrush,'' ``The King of Asini'' _ close a magical double ring.
</P>
<P>
   They bring the power of the old myths and the ancient writers to
bear, with the greatest naturalness and art, upon the dimensions of
life today, Greek specifically but not exclusively. The poetry
makes an elevated sense, in other words, of the contemporary
experience. With these contemporary implications, it also gives a
new and unexpected vitality to the classics and the myths.
</P>
<P>
   It is the same land, sea, light (Seferis draws great darkness
out of the light) that Sophocles and Homer knew, and a language of
strong kinship and many of the same properties. The gods hung out
in the same spots; they spoke the same language.
</P>
<P>
   Such gods, so nonabstract, nonholy and so inveterately attached
to human places, pleasures and passions, are available to a Greek
poet. Even their absence is a place and their silence a language.
Writing of present and past, of Miller and Seferis, of Seferis and
the gods and, occasionally, of himself and Seferis, Keeley has made
a complex and illuminating connection.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES
</P>
<P>
   `INVENTING PARADISE
</P>
<P>
   The Greek Journey, 1937-1947'
</P>
<P>
   By Edmund Keeley
</P>
<P>
   270 pages. Farrar, Straus &AMP; Giroux. $24.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
