<P>
   USCHINA _ China's two-decade effort to steal U.S. weapons
technology has positioned Beijing to develop modern mobile nuclear
warheads as good as America's, a bipartisan congressional report
said today. An ``insatiable appetite'' for U.S. technology leaves
China ready to leap from a 1950s nuclear weapons program to
sophisticated designs ``on par with our own,'' concludes the
report. The report describes a breadth of Chinese espionage that is
so threatening to U.S. interests that some members of Congress have
compared it to the theft of atomic bomb secrets by the Soviet Union
in the 1940s. The fallout could have a profound impact on the
operation of U.S. weapons labs and on U.S.-Chinese relations. The
House and Senate have called for in-depth hearings on Chinese
espionage and U.S. nuclear security. Richardson within days is
expected to announce disciplinary action against a number of Energy
Department and lab employees in connection with anti-espionage
lapses. (Carr, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   w/USCHINA-CLINTON _ The White House called the Cox Commission
report constuctive but didn't agree with all of its findings.
(Malone, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   USCHINA-EXCERPTS _ Excerpts from the Cox Commission report.
(Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   USCHINA-BUSH _ AUSTIN, Texas _ Without prompting, Gov. George W.
Bush weighed in Tuesday on the Chinese spying scandal alleged in
the Cox report. (Herman, Austin American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   SAFRICA-ELECTION _ South Africa, which many people predicted
could plunge into war before apartheid would end, has experienced a
degree of reconciliation that many people consider a miracle. But
as South Africans prepare to elect a new president to succeed
Nelson Mandela, they know that _ with unemployment and crime sky
high, the economy stagnant and education in desperate straits _
this country that is basking in the glow of one miracle is now
badly in need of a second. An overview of where the country stands
five years after the end of apartheid and a few weeks before its
second all-race elections. (Melvin, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
85. WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
