<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-25 17:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0672 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EAST-THEATER-REVIEW-A     05-25 1266
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EAST-THEATER-REVIEW-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`EAST IS EAST': PUNGENT LIFE WITH FATHER, SERVING LOVE AND CHIPS
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(Eds.: Production notes at end of review.) 
(dal) 
 By BEN BRANTLEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The smell is what you notice first, even before you've taken a
proper look at the stage from which it emanates. It's the thick
aroma of fat heated up for deep frying, mixed with fleeting
suggestions of spice, and you can't shake it out of your nostrils
for the rest of the evening.
</P>
<P>
   That odor is one of a battery of sensory invaders in the lively
production of ``East Is East,'' Ayub Khan-Din's awkward but
affectionate tale of domestic and cultural combat among the
Pakistani owner of a chips (as in fish and chips) shop in
northwestern England, his British wife and their many children.
</P>
<P>
   There's the 1970s pop music, both Anglo-American and
Pakistani-Indian, that seeps out of radios, along with the drones
of canned laughter from a television and the continuous din of
raised voices in different accents. And the divided set, half of
which is devoted to the fragrant, tidily kept diner, boggles the
eyes with its other half: a living room teeming with mixed patterns
and pervasive clutter.
</P>
<P>
   Even though you're in the distancing darkness of the audience,
you start to feel a little crowded, a little cramped, hungry for
breathing and elbow room. Very much, in fact, like the characters
in the play you're watching.
</P>
<P>
   Those familiar with the work of Scott Elliott won't be surprised
by the viscera-grabbing techniques he employs in ``East Is East,''
which opened last night at Stage 1 of City Center. As the artistic
director of the New Group, Elliott has made a specialty of serving
up steaming slices of alienated English life, in which you can
practically taste the sudsy ale as well as the characters'
disillusionment.
</P>
<P>
   Here, in the first collaboration between the New Group and the
Manhattan Theater Club, Elliott has a bigger budget and a larger
space in which to exercise his gritty theatrical magic, and he
takes full advantage of them, with sterling assistance from Derek
McLane, the set designer. If the results are less than entirely
persuasive, that has more to do with the script than with the
staging.
</P>
<P>
   This play can definitely seem forced in its big moments of
insight, but in between those revelations, the production pulls you
right into the jumbled, fretful flow of one family's daily life.
Think of a hipper, more ambivalent variation on ``Life With
Father'' or ``Cheaper by the Dozen,'' laced with social dissonance,
and you'll get the idea.
</P>
<P>
   A critical hit in London at the Royal Court Theater two years
ago, this warmhearted, bumpy work is overly shaped by the ordering
rhythms associated with the television shows its characters feast
on, right down to a climactic scene in which a plucky mother tells
off a bigwig who insults her children. The play's strength is,
instead, in its sprawl, in its sense of the cozy disorder of an
oversize, ethnically mixed and emotionally muddled family in close
quarters.
</P>
<P>
   ``East Is East,'' which has already been turned into a
low-budget film to be released here later this year, is the first
play by Khan-Din, 37, who is best known as a movie actor. It is
clearly autobiographical, though its author has, quite reasonably,
allotted his fictional family three fewer children than its
real-life prototype of 10.
</P>
<P>
   That's still more than enough to keep any director occupied, and
Elliott and his ensemble do a solid job in keeping individual
identities vivid and distinct. On one level, these characters do
bizarrely recall the classic family of Lindsay and Crouse's ``Life
With Father.''
</P>
<P>
   Once again, there's a patriarch with whims of iron and unbudging
notions of child rearing, and a mother who acts as peacemaker and
rift-healer, while ducking confrontations with the husband she
loves. That equation is skewed by Dad's status as a Pakistani
immigrant who after decades in England still clings to the
traditions of his homeland, including arranged marriages for his
children. Filial resistance leads to acts of violence that would
never have penetrated the universe of Lindsay and Crouse.
</P>
<P>
   Edward A. Hajj, an actor making his professional debut here, and
the excellent Jenny Sterlin are the mother and father, George and
Ella Khan, and they give off a reflexive air of both comfort and
annoyance with each other that sets the evening's tone. You can
sense the persistence of a love between two strangely matched souls
that continues to baffle their children, and Khan-Din wisely
refrains from overloading the script with expository details of
family history.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the show is at its best at its most relaxed, fluidly
finding the domestic rhythms and rituals of the Khan household,
where cultural paradox is taken for granted and privacy is a rare
luxury. The early morning scenes, with the boys (five of them, to
one girl) dressing themselves in the living room out of a laundry
basket, feel vivid and true. So do the moments in which the
children riff disrespectfully about their father while working in
the family restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   It's when the play stoops to explain itself that it seems
forced. Must we really be told so explicitly why the youngest
child, Sajit (Rishi Mehta), is hiding from the world in a hooded
parka he refuses to take off? Do Abdul (Dariush Kashani) and Maneer
(Amir Sajadi), the obedient sons, and Tariq (Rahul Khanna), the
rebellious one, need to face off in such blunt declarations of
principles?
</P>
<P>
   The actors playing the children, who also include Gregory J.
Qaiyum and Purva Bedi, have developed an organic synchronicity that
falters only in the play's segues into violence. The moments of
brutality don't shock as they should, partly because Hajj, a
sprightly and small man, never projects the necessary menace or
combustible anger, as though the actor were slightly afraid of the
character.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Sterlin, whose long, equine face seems perpetually tugged by
both wryness and weariness, is first-rate. Whether sharing a
cigarette with her best friend, Annie (nicely played by Christine
Child), or calling the exotic names of her children in a hoarse,
mechanical litany, Ms. Sterlin's Ella conveys equal parts affection
and irritation in every breath.
</P>
<P>
   That's what Khan-Din's play, when it's not being self-conscious,
projects, too: an instinctive sense of the family hearth as
somewhere you want to escape from and to stay in forever, the first
and the last place you want to be.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `EAST IS EAST'
</P>
<P>
   By Ayub Khan-Din; directed by Scott Elliott; sets by Derek
McLane; costumes by Mattie Ullrich; lighting by Brian MacDevitt;
sound by Red Ramona; fight director, J. Allen Suddeth; production
stage manager, Barnaby Harris; production manager, Michael R.
Moody; associate artistic director, Michael Bush; general manager,
Victoria Bailey. Presented by the Manhattan Theater Club, Lynne
Meadow, artistic director; Barry Grove, executive producer; and the
New Group, Elliott, artistic director and Claudia Catania,
executive producer. At the City Center, Stage 1, 131 West 55th
Street, Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: Edward A. Hajj (George Khan), Jenny Sterlin (Ella Khan),
Dariush Kashani (Abdul), Rahul Khanna (Tariq), Amir Sajadi
(Maneer), Gregory J. Qaiyum (Saleem), Purva Bedi (Meenah), Rishi
Mehta (Sajit), Christine Child (Auntie Annie), Sendhil Ramamurthy
(Dr. Mehta) and Ajay Mehta (Mr. Shah). &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
