<P>
   BELLSOUTH _ ATLANTA _ BellSouth CEO Duane Ackerman this week
urged the government to encourage development of broadband
networks, a call that came with his own company challenged to
accelerate its efforts to deliver high-speed lines. (Kanell,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   GRAPEVINE _Profile of media company Grapevine, which has bought
a slew of television stations around the country in the last couple
of weeks. (Haddad, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   MINDSPRING _ MindSpring annual shareholders meeting (Katz,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   HODEPOT-ENVIRONMENT _ The environmentalists are after Home Depot
again for selling old-growth lumber. This year, Rainforest Action
Network sent Chief Qwatsinas of the Nuxalk Nation to the Home Depot
on Sydney Marcus to take back lumber that was allegedly stolen from
his homeland in British Columbia. Could involve an arrest if the
Chief makes good on his shoplifting attempt. This is the same group
that scaled a crane last year at Home Depot headquarters. (Bond,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 15.
</P>
<P>
   CINNABON _ Cinnabon names Barbara Timm-Brock COO. Timm-Brock has
been a mover and shaker in the food service industry and is
chairman of the the Women In Foodservice Association. Cinnabon also
annoounces it is developing a new baker deisng concept and
launching a new franching effort, it's first since 1992. (Poole,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   CNN _ ATANTA _ CNN annnounces $50 million deal with IDG, the big
computer magazine group. IDG will invest that amount in CNN for the
right to have its local fastened to various CNN shows and Internet
content. (Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   Y2K-FAA _ The millennium bug hasn't shut down a single computer
at the Federal Aviation Administration but it has still given the
agency that regulates the country's air space a pretty rough ride
in the past several months. (Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   COXNET WHEELS PAGE
</P>
<P>
   EDS: This is the CoxNet WHEELS page for the current week. This
layout is now available.
</P>
<P>
   COXNET WHEELS 0525 _ Although Korean automaker Hyundai has
totally rebuilt its Sonata, it's possible to argue that the
front-drive sedan's most appealing and striking features are the
papers _ the window sticker and the warranty _ that come with it.
(DeVault, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) Art includes 3-column color
photograph of the 1999 Hyundai Sonata and 18-pica photo of
interior.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   AT A GLANCE _ Fact box previewing the 1999 Hyundai Sonata. Art
includes 10-pica color detail photo of nameplate.
</P>
<P>
   SHARP DRIVING _ If having it all is what a true premium luxury
car is really all about, then Mercedes-Benz's S-Class may be on a
page by itself. (Sharp, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). Includes
1-column color photograph of columnist. END OF PAGE
</P>
<P>
   SHARP-DRIVING _ A look at the Jeep Wrangler. (Sharp, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED SUNDAY.
</P>
<P>
   THE-MECHANIC _ The dangers of patch jobs on car repairs.
(Carter, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED SUNDAY.
</P>
<P>
   TESTDRIVE-MUSTANG _ Russ test drives the new Mustang (DeVault)
Note: this pairs with Friday cover story on 35th anniversary.
(DeVault, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: This story moved Friday 5/21 to coincide with the Mustang's
35th anniversary.
</P>
<P>
   MONEYTALK _ Column will not move this week.
</P>
<P>
   INSIDER-TRADING _ ATLANTA _ Executives have many reasons to sell
stock in their companies. For John R. Alm, who last month was
promoted to executive vice president and principal operating
officer of Coca-Cola Enterprises, it's to help disadvantaged and
troubled youths. (Luke, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED MONDAY.
</P>
<P>
   HOLSENDOLPH-COLUMN _Time was, back in the 1970s, Atlanta was the
banking capital of the Southeast, partly by virtue of Mills B.
Lane, the legendary chairman of Citizens and Southern Bank. The
bank, later best known as C&AMP;S, was a powerhouse that fueled much of
the economic development, and Lane's progressive style helped to
set the tone for what we called the New South. (Holsendolph,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED MONDAY.
</P>
<P>
   WALLSTREET _ ATLANTA _ The stock market model at Georgia Tech
recently registered a ``sell'' signal. That alone would be
something to think about. It becomes even more thinkable when you
consider that it's only the fourth sell signal from that model in
more than a decade, and the previous three were in 1994, 1990 and
1987. (Walker, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED MONDAY.
</P>
