<HEADER>
A0680 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GORE26-COX     05-25 0832
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GORE, IN 'BUSH COUNTRY' CITES SUCCESS OF ANTI-POVERTY PROGRAMS
 &HT;    410&AMP;add. Moving in (w) Washington and (p) politics categories.
 &HT;    By SCOTT SHEPARD
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   EDINBURG, Texas _ Vice President Al Gore brought his
presidential campaign to ``Bush country'' Tuesday, touting
administration programs that have promoted economic growth in the
poverty-ridden Rio Grande Valley.
</P>
<P>
   Gore presided over the 5th annual conference sponsored by the
White House to review its program of ``empowerment zones'' and
``economic communities,'' launched as part of a 1993 economic
recovery initiative that was adamantly opposed by congressional
Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   The program provides grants, tax incentives and bonding
authority to economically distressed inner cities and rural areas.
</P>
<P>
   ``The message (of that program) is clear _ we don't have to
become a nation of haves and have-nots, where some people do well
and others are left behind,'' Gore told the conference. ``We don't
have to be a country where cities and suburbs see each other as
enemies, protecting their boundaries like they are walls between
us.''
</P>
<P>
   The conference brought Gore and President Clinton together
publicly for the first time since the president critiqued the vice
president's campaign in remarks to the New York Times last week,
reportedly angering him.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, here largely to introduce Gore, called the vice
president a man with an ``unparalleled combination of creativity
and energy and strength and determination.'' He said Gore, more
than anyone else, had shown that creative government support could
bring new economic vitality to depressed communities.
</P>
<P>
   But with Clinton at his side, Gore inadvertently invited
comparisons of his often passionless style of campaigning to
Clinton's hallmark exuberance.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an inevitable comparison, fair or unfair,'' said Housing
and Urban Development Secretary Andrew Cuomo, who attended the
conference. ``The president is a master communicator of historic
proportions. The vice president has a different style, but he is a
very effective communicator.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore used the conference to announce two new administration
initiatives:
</P>
<P>
   _ $32 million in grants and loans to finance the cleanup and
redevelopment of old polluted industrial sites.
</P>
<P>
   _ A presidential order expanding the two-year-old Southwest
Border Regional Partnership, which has brought some 40
``empowerment zones'' and ``economic communities'' together to
tackle economic problems of the region.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton and Gore also called on Congress to fund a new round of
these zones.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   This community was chosen to host the conference, White House
officials said, because of the success of the Rio Grande Valley
Empowerment Zone: it has generated some $100 million in public and
private investment since its creation five years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The counties that make up the empowerment zone have poverty and
unemployment rates significantly higher than U.S. or Texas rates.
In Hidalgo County, where the conference was held, 41.51 percent of
the residents live in poverty, compared to 17.66 percent in Texas
and 12.65 percent of the U.S. population. Its unemployment rate is
14.33 percent, compared to 7.11 percent statewide and 6.31
nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   Prior to the conference, Gore visited the agricultural community
of Sebastian. He visited the family of Sandra Puente, who graduated
from the University of Texas at Brownsville last weekend as a
result of an empowerment zone program that helped pay her tuition.
</P>
<P>
   He later introduced her to the conference as ``an empowerment
zone success story,'' sparking a spirited round of applause.
</P>
<P>
   The conference gave Gore an opportunity to travel to the home
state of Gov. George W. Bush, the current front-runner for the
Republican presidential nomination, for a mix of official duties,
campaign fund raising and solidifying his political ties to
Hispanic voters, who are likely to be pivotal in the 2000
presidential election.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's schedule also included an appearance Tuesday night at a
Hispanic Democratic Unity rally in McAllen, an indication of the
importance Gore is placing on the Hispanic vote in his presidential
bid. Bush won an unprecedented number of Hispanic votes in his
re-election campaign last year, although estimates vary from 40
percent to 50 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's three-day trip, which began Monday in Florida and
Georgia, is expected to yield some $850,000 for his presidential
campaign following fund-raising events Wednesday in Dallas and
Houston.
</P>
<P>
   ``Politics is like fighting a way, but you shoot money instead
of bullets,'' Georgia Gov. Roy Barnes said at a private fund-raiser
for Gore in Atlanta on Monday. ``If there's not enough money, you
get overwhelmed. If you can't get money, you don't get your message
out.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
