<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Wednesday, May 26, sent to computer graphics clients of The New
York Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
(bl) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST
</P>
<P>
   Isolated severe thunderstorms will erupt over parts of eastern
New Mexico and western Texas on Wednesday as an upper-level low
pressure system from Arizona teams with the high terrain of the
region to lift moist air streaming inland from the Gulf of Mexico.
Hail and tornadoes are possible in spots.
</P>
<P>
   Moderate to locally heavy rains will douse parts of northern and
central Texas as humid Gulf air is lifted over a stationary front
spanning from west to east across the Lone Star State. Another
mechanism for lifting Gulf air will be a small-scale boundary
marking the leading edge of rain-cooled air left in the wake of
morning clusters of showers and storms.
</P>
<P>
   Variable clouds with widely separated cool showers will prevail
from the eastern Great Lakes region to the northern and central
Appalachians as a sluggish, cold low pressure system at high
altitudes drifts overhead. Showers will jump eastward from the
mountains to parts of eastern Maine, which will lie closest to the
cold core of the upper-level low. Brisk winds from the
west-southwest will average 15 to 30 mph across much of the
Northeast.
</P>
<P>
   Thunderstorms will flare over parts of the Carolinas and Georgia
as a compact but potent jet stream disturbance works in tandem with
a stalled front to lift moist air. Depending on the supply of Gulf
moisture, a few storms may approach severe levels. Large hail and
damaging winds are possible.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, isolated, potent thunderstorms will erupt over the
mountains of south-central Montana and northern Wyoming and then
move eastward. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Power of Water
</P>
<P>
   Three cars were washed away by relatively shallow flash-flood
waters at a crossing near San Angelo, Texas, on Monday. The power
of moving water should never being taken lightly _ a cube of water
measuring just one meter on each side weighs more than 2,000
pounds. Indeed, many deaths occur when motorists attempt to drive
their cars through flooded crossings and are carried rapidly away
by swift currents. The best rule to follow is to avoid driving
through any flooded areas. If this advice is not heeded and a car
stalls in flood waters, motorists should abandon their vehicles
immediately.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
