<SLUG> BC-WRESTLER-FALL-KAN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INVESTIGATION INTO FATAL FALL FOCUSES ON WRESTLER'S HARNESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RUTH E. IGOE and LYNN HORSELY  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Professional wrestler Owen Hart had performed
the stunt before.
</P>
<P>
   Before Sunday night's World Wrestling Federation show at Kemper
Arena, the 34-year-old Hart practiced again. Cables strung from a
catwalk beneath the roof seemed taut. A harness was snug.
</P>
<P>
   But about 10 minutes before Hart, nicknamed the ``Blue Blazer,''
was scheduled to descend into the ring suspended from the cable, he
suddenly plunged about 80 feet to his death.
</P>
<P>
   Police investigators said Monday that Hart appeared to have lost
his balance, a misstep that started a still-unclear chain of lethal
events leading to the first known performance-related death at the
arena.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators are zeroing in on the wrestler's body harness
attached to the cable, which did not break. The stunt harness had
been modified with a quick-release device that Hart could use to
free himself from the cable.
</P>
<P>
   Somehow, police think, that quick release may have been
activated _ either accidentally or intentionally _ as Hart fell,
sending him crashing onto the ring below.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anytime you are up there on a catwalk with ropes everywhere,
in the dark, 92 feet above the floor, things can happen,'' said
Kansas City Police Capt. Jerry Gallagher. ``When you are dealing
with triggers that can drop you from your harness, anything can
happen. Anything can fail.''
</P>
<P>
   An autopsy Monday revealed that Hart bled to death internally
from blunt chest trauma, said Jackson County Medical Examiner
Thomas Young.
</P>
<P>
   After the show, police interviewed all the people involved with
the stunt, said Sgt. Floyd Mitchell. A final report is pending.
</P>
<P>
   Hart's descent was supposed to be an added attraction for 16,340
attending the event _ called ``Over the Edge'' _ and hundreds of
thousands of fans watching on nationwide pay-per-view.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Yeaton, an event operations coordinator for the WWF's
Kansas City show, said the federation does about 300 shows a year.
Such stunts are an ``extra, extra addition,'' done about once a
month, mostly for pay-per-view shows.
</P>
<P>
   World Wrestling Federation officials, at their Stamford, Conn.,
headquarters, said Monday they are conducting their own
investigation into the accident.
</P>
<P>
   WWF officials said they did not know how many times Hart had
performed the stunt.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are all devastated. He had a wonderful career. We are
concentrating on his family,' said spokeswoman Susan Warner.
</P>
<P>
   The Occupational Safety and Health Administration also is
looking into whether it has jurisdiction to investigate, said
Lodama Delinger, the Kansas City area director.
</P>
<P>
   An OSHA inquiry would take several months. OSHA's regional
office has not, to Delinger's knowledge, investigated the WWF or
Kemper Arena before.
</P>
<P>
   City policy allows ``proven professionals (using their own
equipment) to rappel from the Kemper catwalk,'' said Alan
Schmelzle, Kemper's general manager.
</P>
<P>
   Schmelzle said three men were on the catwalk at the time of the
accident, but that no city employees were involved in rigging the
stunt, Schmelzle said.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the International Alliance of Theatrical Stage
Employees Local 31 were hired by WWF for the show, said union
steward Jay Lewis. They joined WWF personnel already familiar with
the specific event equipment and stunts.
</P>
<P>
   Schmelzle said city officials would review their stunt policy at
Kemper, but he doubted there would be any changes. A prohibition on
rappelling would eliminate such events as circus acrobat acts at
Kemper.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a situation like this, we want to make sure nothing like
this ever happens again,'' Schmelzle said. ``To the best of my
knowledge, we have never had an incident like this...''
</P>
<P>
   Schmelzle praised the quick response of the ambulance workers
and police who tried to save Hart's life. He said it was standard
practice for the city to provide emergency rescue crews at events
such as the wrestling match.
</P>
<P>
   But spokesman Don Pickard of the Metropolitan Ambulance Services
Trust said records show that Sunday was the first time MAST had
been asked to attend a WWF event. Given the extensive preparations,
heavy choreography and staging of each scene, there's rarely a need
for ambulance personnel, Pickard said.
</P>
<P>
   Pickard said Kemper arena officials had requested that a MAST
crew stand by at the event Sunday to participate in a staged injury
with Vincent McMahon, the WWF chairman. The scene was filmed away
from the main stage.
</P>
<P>
   As the two-man ambulance crew finished the filming, Hart fell,
and they were called back in. They tried to save Hart's life,
without success. When the two men arrived on the scene, two police
officers were performing CPR.
</P>
<P>
   MAST crews then spent about 15 minutes attempting to resuscitate
Hart before taking him to a hospital.
</P>
<P>
   John Sharp, executive director of MAST, said he believes MAST
should always be asked to stand by at wrestling matches.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whenever the city has an event that has an element of danger,
the city should require the promoter to require ambulances be
there,'' Sharp said. ``That would apply to everything from boxing
matches to monster trucks.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite some criticism, Schmelzle defended the wrestling
federation's decision to continue the show after the fall. He said
Hart's colleagues were deeply saddened, but their attitude was,
``The show must go on.''
</P>
<P>
   The WWF is scheduled to host another event at Kemper in August,
and Schmelzle said they are always welcome.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are extremely popular,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
