<SLUG> BC-POLLUTION-KAN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEDERAL AGENCY'S STUDY OF SUGAR CREEK POLLUTION IS INCONCLUSIVE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MANSUR  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Despite 10 years of investigation, regulators
still cannot tell whether pollution from the former Amoco refinery
in Sugar Creek poses any health risk to area residents, according
to the first federal health assessment of the site.
</P>
<P>
   ``We found nothing of an imminent concern _ that we know of,''
said Denise Jordan-Izaguirre, regional representative of the
federal Agency for Toxic Substances and Disease Registry.
</P>
<P>
   The agency will take public comment on its draft report for 30
days.
</P>
<P>
   To plug data gaps, the federal health agency has recommended
many new tests _ including a new round of air sampling in homes in
the nearby Norledge neighborhood, where pollution from the old
refinery has migrated.
</P>
<P>
   Residents expressed dismay Monday that once again they had a
report that gave them no conclusions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to know, yes or no,'' said Bud Chappell, who
initiated the federal health assessment. ``I just don't understand
this.''
</P>
<P>
   Chappell is a leader of a local group pushing for a quicker
cleanup of the former refinery site.
</P>
<P>
   New Mayor Stan Salva said he welcomed the new federal assessment
and found its recommendations understandable. But he, too, wished
for more answers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd glad we have this,'' he said, ``but I don't think it
really answers any questions. And, maybe, these are questions we
can never answer.''
</P>
<P>
   The report cemented the position of Amoco and Sugar Creek
officials: There is no reason to believe residents are at risk from
any of the old refinery's pollution.
</P>
<P>
   But to a lawyer involved in recent litigation against Amoco, the
new assessment's indefinite finding is more evidence of a lack of
government action.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's disconcerting that as the neighbors of Amoco have died or
been diagnosed with serious disease in the last 10 years, state and
federal regulators seemed at first to be asleep on the job and more
recently sleep-walking on the job,'' said Arthur A. Benson II, an
attorney for residents who own property under which Amoco's
pollution has seeped.
</P>
<P>
   Benson added that he hoped new testing conducted for litigation
against Amoco, as well as new studies of cancer rates in Sugar
Creek, would spark regulators to take more action.
</P>
<P>
   The new testing has shown high levels of pollutants in soil and
groundwater in the Norledge area, Benson said.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan-Izaguirre confirmed the new test data and said it
appeared to show that off-site pollution had moved farther than
previously thought.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Salva worries that the city's image is being unjustly
besmirched by the suspicions and prolonged investigation of the
site's pollution.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as residents of the city being safe, I feel that they
are,'' Salva said. ``I also believe that if Amoco had spent more
money (on the cleanup) we'd be further along.''
</P>
<P>
   It appears that the regulatory agencies recently have placed a
higher priority on achieving some cleanup, Salva added.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Casebolt, Amoco's site manager in Sugar Creek, said his
company thinks that neither on-site nor off-site contamination
poses a health threat to the neighborhood. ``But we're supportive
of any additional study,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Agency for Toxic Substances and Disease Registry said Monday
it would hold a public hearing in Sugar Creek on June 2 to further
explain the study.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan-Izaguirre said the site is being cleaned up under a
federal program that tends to concentrate on pollution on site, not
off site. As a result, little testing data have been collected off
site.
</P>
<P>
   The federal Superfund program ranks sites based on their
potential to contaminate persons by polluting their groundwater,
drinking water or air. But the Amoco site is handled under another
federal hazardous waste program, known as RCRA, for the Resource
Conservation and Recovery Act that created it.
</P>
<P>
   In its new health assessment, the Agency for Toxic Substances
and Disease Registry recommended that off-site soil be tested.
Residents, including Chappell, have long complained of a lack of
soil testing in their neighborhood. At one recent meeting, Chappell
argued there had been no soil testing in the residential area near
the old refinery, but state officials said he was wrong.
</P>
<P>
   The study concluded there had been no soil testing before the
tests recently completed for Benson's firm.
</P>
<P>
   The Environmental Protection Agency, the Missouri Department of
Natural Resources and Amoco plan further testing and
pollution-containing efforts this summer.
</P>
<P>
   The state will take new samples of surface water, Amoco will
sample anew its groundwater wells, and the EPA will sample basement
air quality in Norledge area homes. Similar, but less accurate,
sampling was conducted last year but was inconclusive.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan-Izaguirre expressed frustration that her agency could not
say anything more than ``indeterminate.'' But she also promised
that her agency won't give up.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is just the first cut,'' she said. ``We are in no way
walking away from this.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
