</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FCC-FM-KAN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FCC PROPOSAL PITS RADIO GIANTS AGAINST MOM-AND-POP STATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN MURPHY  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In less than two years, the Federal Communications
Commission has chased about 480 tiny, unlicensed radio stations off
the dial as ``pirates'' of the airwaves.
</P>
<P>
   But before the year is out, ex-pirates such as Rich Wenzel of
Lawrence and Michael Gonzalo Calderon of Kansas City could be back
on the air _ compliments of the FCC.
</P>
<P>
   In a little-publicized but testy conflict, the FCC is
considering whether to let thousands of small-time radio stations
set up shop in communities where big-time stations don't want them
around.
</P>
<P>
   The FCC bowed to pressure from commercial and public radio
giants to extend the public comment period on its proposal until
August. Big broadcasters are doing studies on how small stations
interfere with their reception.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, the delay could work in favor of small stations by
giving supporters more time to sway the FCC and lobby Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've heard from the money; now the consumers and the people
who don't normally come forward will have their voices heard,''
said Michael Bracy, executive director of the Low Power Radio
Coalition. ``It should be fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Bracy said low-power radio is an important outlet for many
Americans, such as musicians who can't get played on bigger
stations, youngsters trying to break into broadcasting and scores
of ordinary people who have something to say.
</P>
<P>
   Wenzel likens community radio to the town halls of America,
where views are aired on subjects as weighty as world politics and
as light as dating tips for teen-agers.
</P>
<P>
   Tim Miller, who had a show on Wenzel's station, said
``decentralizing'' the media is the issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's been a relentless move toward centralization....It's
sad,'' said Miller, chairman of the Department of Religious Studies
at the University of Kansas.
</P>
<P>
   The technology of some of the small stations can be crude. For
example, Miller said, callers to his talk show could be heard on
the air only if he held the phone to the microphone.
</P>
<P>
   Wenzel's 10-watt FM station operated out of the basement of
Liberty Hall in Lawrence for about 15 months until June. It had a
radius of about five miles. The station was on the air 12 hours a
day and had 100 disc jockeys a week, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Calderon didn't have that kind of help at his station, which he
ran by himself at his Kansas City home. When he was at work as a
bondsman, Calderon said, he would cue up compact discs and come
home at lunch to change them.
</P>
<P>
   The 60-watt, 20-mile-radius station broadcast in Spanish for the
Hispanic community before the FCC shut it down.
</P>
<P>
   ``They created a lie that I was interfering with a 100,000-watt
station,'' Calderon said. ``I was approached the wrong way: `Get
off the air, you're interfering.' I was wondering where my
government was.''
</P>
<P>
   The commission voted 4-1 on Jan. 28 to consider issuing licenses
to community stations of 1 to 1,000 watts. Normally, 6,000 watts is
a prerequisite for a license.
</P>
<P>
   ``As we traveled the country, we've talked to lots of people who
want to use the airways to speak to their communities _ churches,
elementary schools, universities, small businesses and minority
groups,'' FCC Chairman William Kennard and Commissioner Gloria
Tristani said in a statement at the time.
</P>
<P>
   But there is some concern that low-watt stations would also give
greater airway access to people who want to spread racism and hate.
The FCC can't censor points of view but does have regulations on
material that is offensive or could incite violence.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do not want to deny schools, churches and civic
organizations a voice on the airwaves, but we are not particularly
excited about giving the David Dukes of the world a platform
either,'' said Ken Johnson, a spokesman for U.S. Rep. Billy Tauzin,
a Republican from Louisiana.
</P>
<P>
   Tauzin, chairman of the House Telecommunications Commission,
would like committee hearings on the low-power radio issue.
Congress could override the FCC decision.
</P>
<P>
   The FCC set a public comment deadline of April 12, extended it
to May 12, then extended it until Aug. 2 at the request of the
National Association of Broadcasters, the Corporation for Public
Broadcasting and National Public Radio.
</P>
<P>
   The FCC had more than 13,000 inquiries last year from people and
groups interested in starting low-power radio stations. The FCC
hasn't determined how licensees will be chosen, but both
noncommercial and commercial stations may be approved, spokesman
David Fiske said.
</P>
<P>
   People like Wenzel and Calderon could be prevented from getting
licenses because they operated illegally previously, but that also
hasn't been decided, Fiske said.
</P>
<P>
   FCC Commissioner Harold W. Furchtgott-Roth said he wasn't sure
the FCC would accomplish one of its goals _ to put more minorities
and women in the radio business.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is simply no way that the commission can say these
licenses will not be awarded to whoever applies for them first...or
that these licenses will not go to the highest bidder,'' said
Furchtgott-Roth, the only commissioner opposed to the proposal.
</P>
<P>
   The National Association of Broadcasters believes the FCC
doesn't have enough data to be assured that low-watt stations won't
dilute the signals of much larger stations.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're basically saying, `Before you know what is going to
happen, don't move forward,' '' spokesman John Earnhardt said.
</P>
<P>
   Members of Congress have been taking sides. Five members of the
House wrote Kennard a letter of support in March.
</P>
<P>
   ``The tremendous public demand for microradio is demonstrated by
the proliferation of illegal radio stations, whose operators
broadcast at the risk of financial losses and, in some cases,
imprisonment,'' the lawmakers wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Tauzin, however, wrote a letter to Kennard urging caution.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a huge policy decision,'' Tauzin aide Johnson said.
``Billy told Kennard in no uncertain terms that he is not to
proceed with microstations without consulting Congress.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
