<DOCNO> NYT19990525.0209 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-25 18:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0692 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEDICAID-FRAUD-KAN-KA     05-25 1334
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDICAID-FRAUD-KAN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOVERNMENT ACCUSES MEDICAL CENTER, RELATED COMPANY OF BILKING
MEDICAID 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK MORRIS and JULIUS A. KARASH  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ The U.S. Justice Department has accused
Truman Medical Center and a related company of bilking Medicaid by
providing substandard pre-natal care to poor Kansas City women and
billing the government for more expensive services that never were
provided.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Attorney Stephen Hill said a civil lawsuit filed Monday
would expose ``more than 100'' false Medicaid claims filed since
1993 by Truman and by Hospital Hill Health Services Corp., a
non-profit company that hires the hospital's physicians.
</P>
<P>
   Each false filing could carry a $10,000 penalty, bringing
potential damages to $1 million. In addition, a jury could force
the hospital to pay interest, attorneys' fees, restitution and
triple damages for monetary losses to the government.
</P>
<P>
   Truman and Hospital Hill ``systematically chose to profit by not
providing patients the level of Medicaid treatment to which they
were entitled,'' Hill said. ``Our purpose in bringing this action
is to improve health care to the indigent in Kansas City.''
</P>
<P>
   In a prepared statement, James Youngblood, chairman of the
hospital's obstetrics and gynecology department, defended the care
the hospital and its doctors provided to pregnant women and their
babies.
</P>
<P>
   ``The clinical care administered by professionals at Truman
Medical Center is consistently high and has not been compromised,''
Youngblood said. ``Qualified and licensed providers gave
appropriate and necessary care to patients and delivered
approximately 15,000 babies over the last six years. We continue to
provide the high quality of care expected by Kansas Citians.''
</P>
<P>
   Youngblood suggested that the complexities of Medicaid billing
may have led to Hill's questions.
</P>
<P>
   ``The government's complaint appears to arise over technical
Medicaid billing and documentation issues that are subject to
interpretation,'' Youngblood said. ``This action will be referred
to our attorneys. (Hospital Hill) and Truman Medical Center deny
the allegations and will vigorously defend this action.''
</P>
<P>
   Hill said prosecutors declined to file criminal charges against
the hospital and the physicians group, reasoning that conviction
would bar the hospital from receiving further federal aid and force
it to close. About 78 percent of the hospital's revenue comes from
either Medicare, the country's health insurance program for the
elderly, or Medicaid, the indigent health care program.
</P>
<P>
   ``The forced closing of Truman would be a monumentally tragic
event,'' Hill said.
</P>
<P>
   FBI Special Agent Larry McCormick said a criminal investigation
announced two months ago of the hospital's Medicare and Medicaid
billing practices is continuing. Hill would not rule out criminal
charges being filed against individuals in the latest case.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is always the potential for individuals to be held
criminally liable,'' Hill said. ``That is still a potential here.''
</P>
<P>
   Hill said evidence in the case would show two general types of
``purposeful, sustained and intentional'' billing fraud:
</P>
<P>
   - Instances in which the hospital and the corporation received
reimbursement from Medicaid for services that either were never
provided to low-income pregnant women or were delivered in a way
that did not meet Medicaid standards.
</P>
<P>
   - Occasions in which the hospital and corporation billed for
deliveries by Medicaid-approved physicians, when the deliveries
were performed by medical students, nurses or doctors who were not
enrolled in the program.
</P>
<P>
   In the first instance, Hill accused Truman and the doctors group
of ``ripping off'' a program designed to encourage regular
pre-natal visits by pregnant women with the same physician.
</P>
<P>
   In that program, a doctor is reimbursed $550 if a pregnant woman
receives five check-ups from the same physician before she gives
birth. The idea is to give physicians an incentive to provide
regular and consistent pre-natal care for women who already are at
risk for difficult pregnancies, Hill said.
</P>
<P>
   If the woman has fewer than five visits, or meets with a
different physician each time, the physician may only be reimbursed
for $17 per appointment.
</P>
<P>
   Hill said the investigation found few instances of physicians
billing at the $17 rate, even though other evidence showed women
often met with different doctors.
</P>
<P>
   In the second allegation, Truman physicians who had been
approved as Medicaid providers allegedly signed reimbursement
paperwork showing they had delivered infants, when the deliveries
were actually performed by unsupervised medical students, nurses or
doctors who were not enrolled in the program.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't bill for a service when the truth of the matter is
someone else is providing those services,'' Hill said. ``The
defendants had a clear understanding of Medicaid policies, but
deliberately chose to ignore them.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither Hill nor McCormick would speculate as to how common
either of the billing problems noted in Kansas City are at other
public hospitals in the United States. The government, however,
estimates that 10 to 25 percent of the more than $150 billion paid
out by Medicaid each year is lost to fraud.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's action by the federal government was the second time in
little more than two months that fraud allegations have surfaced at
Truman.
</P>
<P>
   In March, Truman and Hospital Hill Health Services doctors group
agreed to pay the federal government $242,500 to settle allegations
of Medicare fraud.
</P>
<P>
   That settlement involved allegedly fraudulent billings for tests
performed on elderly and low-income patients.
</P>
<P>
   The allegations of fraud are occurring as Truman, which serves
as Kansas City's and Jackson County's public hospital system, is
straining to achieve a financial turnaround under John Bluford, who
took over as executive director and chief executive officer in
March.
</P>
<P>
   The government said the alleged wrongdoings at Truman took place
since 1993.
</P>
<P>
   The hospital system, which includes Truman Medical Center
campuses on Hospital Hill and on Lee's Summit Road, was flush with
Medicaid payments a few years ago. But Truman has been staggered by
the new financial demands of managed care and now is scrounging to
break even.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's action by the federal government is the latest
development in a years-long crusade by federal and state
governments against health-care fraud.
</P>
<P>
   Medicaid is a joint federal-state program that provides health
care for several groups of indigent persons, including low-income
pregnant women.
</P>
<P>
   According to the latest figures available, Medicaid serves about
37 million people in the United States, including about 728,000 in
Missouri and 235,000 in Kansas.
</P>
<P>
   Government regulators say they are rooting out fraud in Medicaid
and Medicare to save taxpayers money and keep those programs alive.
</P>
<P>
   But some health providers and their defenders say the crusade
has become overly zealous.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Wade, a spokesman for the American Hospital Association
in Washington, said the latest case against Truman sounded like an
exercise in ``micromanagement'' by regulators who are ``out of
touch with how patients get care.''
</P>
<P>
   He said such actions not only create confusion but also
demoralize people who work in hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   ``The government's thrust is there is some malevolent intent,
that the hospitals are out to defraud the government, and that's
not the case,'' Wade said.
</P>
<P>
   John Leifer, an Overland Park health-care consultant, said there
is a danger that people will jump to conclusions in wake of the
charges against Truman and the doctors' group.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the current atmosphere of distrust and allegations, it's
easy to convince the public of the institution's guilt before due
process has occurred,'' Leifer said. ``I hope that people withhold
judgment in this case until all the facts are in.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
