   The Atlanta Journal-Constitution story slugged USCHINA-EXCERPTS
will not move this evening.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-25-99 1804EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990525.0211 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-25 18:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0696 &Cx1f; tad-z
u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COX-SAFRICA-ELECTIONS     05-25 2929
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COX-SAFRICA-ELECTIONS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    South Africa prepares to take another step on the long walk to
freedom
 &HT;    By Don Melvin
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   JOHANNESBURG, South Africa _ In the crowds that swell through
the modern walkways of the East Gate mall on the outskirts of
Johannesburg, between the jewelry shops and the clothing stores,
between the music shops, the toy stores and the Chick-Fil-A, black
people and white people mingle freely.
</P>
<P>
   They browse the same windows, work behind the same counters, eat
at the same restaurants and share the same taxis.
</P>
<P>
   Five years after South Africa's first all-race elections
propelled the country's first black-led government to power _ and
ended the official policy of racial oppression known as apartheid _
relations between whites and blacks are more relaxed and less
fractious than almost anyone could have predicted.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've forgiven them,'' said Bennie Makololo, 34, a black man
who sells security fences in Alexandra, an area of Johannesburg.
``Black people are not angry at whites.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe that it was a miracle,'' said Danie van den Heever,
47, a white businessman who is an eighth-generation South African.
``There's a reconciliation of South Africans who are able to
communicate, to share their desires, to share their concerns.''
</P>
<P>
   Not all is rosy between the races, of course: Some white racism
lingers, and so does some black anger. But the predicted bloodbath
never came; whites with money and property were not overrun by
black mobs, as they had feared; and radicalism among both blacks
and whites has declined.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, as big a relief as that transformation has been, the
country still faces enormous challenges. Violent crime is as
pervasive as anywhere in the world. Most blacks are still very
poor, and economic power remains concentrated in the hands of the
white minority. Unemployment, which primarily affects blacks, is
estimated at 38 percent. And while schools in some white areas
would be the envy of Cobb County, the educational system in many
black areas _ which is to say, most of the country _ is in
desperate straits. Schools lack electricity, books, qualified
teachers and adequate facilities.
</P>
<P>
   On June 2, one week from today, voters will go to the polls to
choose a successor to President Nelson Mandela, the man who emerged
from 27 years in prison to become chief architect of the country's
reconciliation.
</P>
<P>
   Most will do so in the full knowledge that South Africa, a
country basking in the glow of one miracle, desperately needs yet
another. The transformation the country must make now is not
emotional but economic.
</P>
<P>
   Most political observers feel certain that the election will be
won by the African National Congress. It is, after all, the party
of Mandela _ a man who, to many black South Africans, is nothing
less than George Washington and Martin Luther King Jr. rolled into
one.
</P>
<P>
   If so, the new president will be Thabo Mbeki, a 57-year-old
British-educated economist. He is the son of Govan Mbeki, a
journalist and activist who served time in prison with Mandela.
Thabo Mbeki has been deputy president since 1996, and over the past
couple of years, as Mandela has concentrated on the overarching
message of reconciliation, Mbeki has run the country's day-to-day
affairs.
</P>
<P>
   Mandela turned out to be perfectly suited to working the miracle
of reconciliation. A former prisoner, he forgave his captors. As
president, he shared lunch with the prosecutor who succeeded in
getting him sentenced to life in prison. He paid a courtesy call to
Betsie Verwoerd, the widow of Hendrik Verwoerd, the main designer
of apartheid.
</P>
<P>
   Now, some South Africans think _ or hope, at any rate _ that
Mbeki will be better suited than Mandela to the difficult and
technical tasks of reviving the economy, reducing unemployment,
curtailing crime and reforming education. While he lacks Mandela's
instinct for the grand gesture, he earned a master's in economics
from Sussex University in England, and he is a suave and
sophisticated politician who has promoted the idea of a
continentwide ``African renaissance'' based on economic growth.
</P>
<P>
   The only question most South African election-watchers have is
whether the ANC will win the two-thirds majority in Parliament that
would allow it to amend the constitution without relying on the
votes of opposition parties.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents, aware that their chances of victory are slender at
best, have urged voters to hold the ANC parliamentary membership
below two-thirds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think a party that has too much power inevitably abuses
it,'' said veteran anti-apartheid activist Helen Suzman, a member
of the Democratic Party _ and a friend of Mandela's.
</P>
<P>
   The ANC received 62.6 percent of the vote when it won power in
the election of 1994 and formed a government of national unity with
the National Party, which was the party of apartheid, and the
Zulu-oriented Inkatha Freedom Party. The National Party withdrew
from the coalition in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   If the ANC wins again, the reason will be more than just
residual goodwill toward Mandela and gratitude toward the party
that negotiated the end of apartheid. Beyond the freedom to live,
travel, shop and use the same rest rooms as whites, some blacks in
South Africa have seen small _ but noticeable _ improvements in
their lives.
</P>
<P>
   Muriel Maseko, for example, lives in a squatter camp in Soweto,
the black township southwest of Johannesburg. Pitted roads splay
out between rows of makeshift shacks built of scraps of corrugated
iron. There is no plumbing; residents must use portable toilets the
government has placed along the roadsides every four or five
houses.
</P>
<P>
   Yet to Maseko this bit of squalor might as well be heaven.
</P>
<P>
   Before she moved here a couple of years ago and built a house
herself, Maseko, 66, was homeless. She lived in a shelter, crammed
into a single room with dozens of other people.
</P>
<P>
   Now she has four rooms, and she shares them with only two other
people _ her daughter and randdaughter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm doing quite a lot better,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Had she built before the end of apartheid, she said, her house _
and, indeed, the entire squatter camp _ could well have fallen
before government bulldozers.
</P>
<P>
   Another person who is doing better is Emma Mhlongo, a
37-year-old mother of four who lives in Ebony Park, a neighborhood
of small, cinderblock houses east of Johannesburg.
</P>
<P>
   Mhlongo lives in one of the homes _ new houses the government
has built in an effort to improve the lives of the millions of
black South Africans who are landless.
</P>
<P>
   The house is far too small for a family of six. But it's solid,
and it has running water. It's an improvement over Mhlongo's
previous circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to be in the squatter camp down the road,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   For those who used to be homeless, the right to live unmolested
in a squatter camp is a step up. For those who were already in
squatter camps, the right to own government-built houses, however
small and boxy, is a step up from that.
</P>
<P>
   According to the ANC, the government has, in the last five
years, brought running water to 3 million people, housed nearly 3
million people, connected 2 million households to electricity, and
transferred ownership of some land to 68,000 households.
</P>
<P>
   That may not seem like much in a country of 43.4 million people
where the majority remain impoverished. But it is something.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are steadily but surely starting to dent the massive
inequalities and poverty created by apartheid,'' says the ANC's
election manifesto. ``It is only by overcoming the huge
inequalities in our society that we shall be able to build a truly
non-racial democracy.''
</P>
<P>
   In recent conversations, many black South Africans expressed
strong support for the ANC, even though the tasks ahead loom large.
Five years, they said, is a brief time in the life of the country,
and the government has been operating under constraints.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our government is doing a lot for us, '' Maseko said. ``Our
government has actually done its utmost best to improve our lives.
We have plenty of privileges, but the government does not have
enough funds.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, she gets 500 rands a month _ about $83 _ as an old-age
pension, where before she got nothing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now we don't starve any more,'' she said. ``And I'm free! I've
got a home in a squatter camp!''
</P>
<P>
   John Masinga, 46, a black man who runs a roadside exhaust-system
repair stand _ nothing more, really, than himself and a beat up
wooden table sitting among the exhaust fumes along the side of a
road north of Pretoria _ said people have to be patient with the
ANC.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are some changes,'' he said. ``If it were not for the
ANC, I wouldn't be able to do this work. The government would send
some police to push me away. The ANC has done a lot, but we cannot
expect all the changes overnight. A small child cannot just be born
and on the same day walk.''
</P>
<P>
   But support for the ANC among blacks is not universal.
</P>
<P>
   ``So far, there has not been any change,'' said Jacob Letshwene,
pastor of the St. Phillip Apostolic Church in the town of Mabopane,
outside Pretoria. ``People are jobless, and the crime rate is very
high. I am totally disappointed. Unfortunately, I voted for the ANC
in 1994.''
</P>
<P>
   Letshwene, in his late 50s, strolled the dirt streets of his
town in vest, tie and snap-brim straw hat. He said he will vote
this time for the United Christian Democratic Party. That is the
party of Lucas Mangope, the former president of Bophuthatswana,
which was this area's version of the theoretically independent
homelands, or Bantustans, into which the apartheid government tried
to herd the country's blacks.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the Bantustans were not independent but had
considerable support from the apartheid government. All were
reabsorbed into South Africa upon apartheid's demise.
</P>
<P>
   Among the other parties likely to receive noticeable support are
the Inkatha Freedom Party, built around the Zulu politician
Mangosuthu Buthelezi; the New National Party, the reincarnation of
the party that once created apartheid; the Pan Africanist Congress,
a black party more radical than the ANC; the Democratic Party, a
party of white liberals that is the successor to the Progressive
Party founded by Helen Suzman, the veteran anti-apartheid
politician; and the United Democratic Movement, led, oddly enough,
by a black former member of the anti-apartheid ANC and a white
former member of the pro-apartheid National Party.
</P>
<P>
   The membership of some of those parties shows that, despite the
ethnic reconciliation that South Africa has achieved in the last
five years, this is still a society divided by tribe and race. The
Inkatha Freedom Party is largely Zulu. The United Christian
Democratic Party, with geographically limited appeal, is mostly
Tswana. The Democratic Party and the New National Party are almost
exclusively white.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone who doubts the fractured nature of South Africa should
consider this: This is a country with 11 official languages.
</P>
<P>
   And the divisions between the four racial groups imposed on the
country by the system of apartheid _ whites, Indians, coloreds and
blacks _ still persist. Those divisions, some say, will persist far
into the future.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will take a thousand years before we come together,'' said
Patrick Singh, 50, an Afro-Asian who classifies himself colored and
lives in a predominantly colored neighborhood of Johannesburg.
``The hate is still there.''
</P>
<P>
   The country may be quiet, but this is the calm before the storm,
Singh said. Sooner or later, he said, violence will sweep over
South Africa in response to white insistence on holding onto
economic power.
</P>
<P>
   The disparities in wealth between whites and blacks are very
stark.
</P>
<P>
   While many blacks live in squatter camps, or in extremely small
and modest houses, many white people in the northern suburbs of
Johannesburg, for example, drive Mercedes, work in fashionable
offices complexes, and live in posh homes in upscale First-World
neighborhoods. The northern suburbs of Johannesburg have been
reported to have the world's greatest concentration of swimming
pools outside of Beverly Hills.
</P>
<P>
   And while some whites seem free of racism _ Marian Karsden, a
22-year-old mall store manager said she will vote for the
Zulu-oriented Inkatha Freedom Party _ among others, racism and
condescension still linger.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing wrong with having black people in government,
but I don't think they value life the same as white people,'' said
Cobie Schoeman, a 45-year-old clerk who lives in Pretoria with her
young daughter. ``I could be wrong, but I don't think so.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition, sentences recently imposed in two different
criminal cases convinced many black South Africans that the justice
system remains racist.
</P>
<P>
   On March 23, Nicholas Steyn, a white man who was convicted of
shooting a six-month-old baby girl to death as her cousin carried
her across Steyn's property, received a suspended sentence. The
next day, longtime anti-apartheid activist Allan Boesak, a black
man who was convicted of diverting charitable donations for poor
children to his personal use, was sentenced to six years in prison.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, relations between blacks and whites seem, overall,
to be on the mend. But relations between blacks, who make up 75
percent of the population, and coloreds, or mixed race people, who
make up 9 percent, tend to be hostile.
</P>
<P>
   Some blacks stereotype coloreds as foul-mouthed heavy drinkers
who think they're better than blacks because they're lighter. Some
coloreds stereotype blacks as racists every bit as virulent as the
whites who used to run this country.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, a sizable number of coloreds _ many of whom speak
Afrikaans but few of whom speak speak Zulu _ plan to vote for the
New National Party next month. They say they were discriminated
against before by whites, they're being discriminated against now
by blacks, so they might as well vote for the party than can keep
order, manage the economy and quell crime.
</P>
<P>
   ``People were better off in South Africa when the National Party
was ruling, so I think I'll vote for the National Party,'' said
Denver Isaacs, a 24-year-old unemployed colored resident of
Pretoria.
</P>
<P>
   How in the world can a colored man vote for the party of
apartheid?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a good question,'' Isaacs said. ``When the National Party
was in power, it was unfair. But now that the ANC is in, it is even
more unfair.''
</P>
<P>
   Sophia Wallenstein, 70, a retired factory worker who is colored,
said she has supported the National Party all her life _ and a
return to apartheid would be better than the current chaos.
</P>
<P>
   ``That time under the National Party was 100 percent better,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Such racial divisiveness might seem discouraging. Yet, amid all
the prejudice, poverty and crime, seeds of hope are beginning to
grow.
</P>
<P>
   In Mabopane, outside Pretoria, Nomzi Mashiane, a retired nurse,
used to drive every day by a large plot of unused city-owned land
that had become a dumping ground. Mashiane had worked in nutrition,
and one day it occurred to her: This land could be used to help
unemployed people earn money growing vegetables. And the vegetables
could improve people's diets.
</P>
<P>
   Four years ago, she got permission from the city to use the land
and began to organize people in the area to sell them on the idea.
</P>
<P>
   ``They thought that I was a bit looney,'' she said. ``They
thought that this would never work _ especially in an urban area.''
</P>
<P>
   But now the land is tilled by 53 people, most of them elderly.
Rows of spinach, cabbage, beets, onions, eggplant, beans, red
peppers and carrots sprout from the fertile earth.
</P>
<P>
   The people who work the plot keep some of the food for
themselves. The rest of the food is marketed in Pretoria, and those
who work the land share the profits.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, unemployed people do need some sense of pride,''
said Mashiane, who is 63. ``And better nutrition.''
</P>
<P>
   The project is a success largely because of Mashiane's energy
and initiative, and the diligent work of the jobless people
involved. But there was another crucial ingredient.
</P>
<P>
   Mashiane approached the department of agriculture of the
Northwest Province and convinced officials to give the project a
grant of 411,000 rands _ about $67,000 _ to install an irrigation
system. Taps protrude from the ground every 20 or 25 feet, ready to
water the vegetables and keep them healthy.
</P>
<P>
   Without this government grant, which could never have happened
under apartheid, Mashiane said, the project could never have
succeeded.
</P>
<P>
   The ANC-led government of South Africa still faces problems _
huge unemployment, rising crime, schools with no electricity or
textbooks _ that would daunt the most capable leaders in the world.
</P>
<P>
   But, to some people at least, the government appears to be
trying. And the small differences it has managed to make in the
lives of at least some of its people may well be enough to ensure
that it gets a second five years to try to address those problems.
</P>
<P>
   Esther Mashubuku, a 24-year-old who now owns one of the new
government-built houses in Ebony park, said she will vote for the
ANC. Definitely.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got the house because of voting,'' she said. ``Next time
maybe I will get a car.''
</P>
<P>
   Full coverage of the upcoming South African elections:
headlines.yahoo.com/FullCoverage/World/SouthAfrica/
</P>
<P>
   Don Melvin writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution, Atlanta,
Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
