<SLUG> BC-KOREA-TELECOM-NYT </SLUG>
  
 In sign of confidence, S. Korea Telecom Shares Will Begin Trading  
(dal) 
 By STEPHANIE STROM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ One of the surest signs that South Korea has won back
the confidence of international investors will show up on Wednesday
when shares of Korea Telecom, the country's leading telephone
carrier, begin trading for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   The company plans to sell $2.5 billion worth of stock, the first
equity deal in South Korea to exceed $1 billion.
</P>
<P>
   It could have sold upward of $10 billion worth, said Alok Sama,
head of the high-technology and telecommunications group for Asia
at Morgan Stanley Dean Witter, which is underwriting the deal.
</P>
<P>
   The largest equity offering to come out of South Korea
previously was by the Korea Electric Power Co., widely known as
Kepco, which raised $655 million in March.
</P>
<P>
   Kepco and Korea Telecom are among the 11 state-owned companies
that the South Korean government selected for privatization after
the country's economic collapse in December 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Less than a year ago, Sama said, Morgan Stanley would have
encountered trouble coaxing investors into swallowing $600 million
worth of Korea Telecom stock, but times have changed. ``Korea is
the flavor of the month, flavor of the year, whatever you want to
call it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He said the offering was helped by the large quantities of
investor cash sloshing around the globe, which has pushed even the
depressed Japanese stock market to double-digit gains this year.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, shares of telephone companies have outperformed most
stock indices this year. Demand for wireless communications
capacities like mobile telephones and wireless data transmission is
huge and growing in South Korea.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts have mildly criticized the company for changing
some of its corporate accounting policies in such a way as to
improve its operating profits. But the changes Korea Telecom made
were within those allowed by local regulations and were disclosed
in the company's prospectus. In addition, although some of the
changes would not be acceptable under U.S. accounting standards,
similar practices are used by telephone carriers elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Sama took issue with the suggestion that any accounting changes
had inflated earnings, pointing to Korea Telecom's acceleration of
depreciation charges on some assets and other restructuring
charges. ``If anything, earnings have been artificially
depressed,'' he said, ``and in any case, earnings aren't what
people are looking at.''
</P>
<P>
   He said investors were more interested in what price the stock
would be as a multiple of its cash flow, which is considered by
some to be a more important measure of value.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
