<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLIVETTI-TELECOM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TELECOM ITALIA CEO AND BOARD RESIGN IN WAKE OF OLIVETTI VICTORY 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JOHN TAGLIABUE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROME _ The chief executive and board of Telecom Italia SpA
resigned Tuesday in the aftermath of their defeat against rival
Olivetti in the recent battle for control of the telecommunications
giant.
</P>
<P>
   The resignations of Franco Bernabe and the directors had been
widely expected, but Bernabe became the first top executive
casualty since the three-month brawl for control of Telecom Italia
ended last Friday, when Olivetti won 51.9 percent of the company's
shares in a tender offer.
</P>
<P>
   Bernabe, who had fought Olivetti with a range of defensive
tactics that included a widely criticized proposal of acquisition
by Deutsche Telekom, Germany's dominant carrier, said he and the
other directors would stay on as caretakers until replacements are
chosen at a shareholder meeting June 28.
</P>
<P>
   Olivetti's effort, in the largest hostile takeover ever in
Europe, succeeded when key Telecom Italia shareholders defected on
the last day of the $65 billion offer in cash and securities.
</P>
<P>
   The Telecom Italia share price seesawed Tuesday amid investor
skittishness about the company's prospects under new management.
After falling almost 3 percent Monday and sliding 2.7 percent
further at the start of trading Tuesday, Telecom Italia's shares,
which accounted for more than half the trading in Milan on Tuesday,
recovered to close up 1.7 percent, but only after heavy buying by
Italian institutional investors. The company's savings shares,
which have no voting rights, dropped for second day, closing down
2.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Olivetti's victory also hurt Deutsche Telekom shares, which fell
5.2 percent in Frankfurt on Tuesday. Deutsche Telekom's main
domestic rival, Mannesmann AG, gained almost 5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The Telecom Italia shareholders meeting in June is expected to
choose a new board to set company policy and to name new
management. Olivetti chief executive Roberto Colaninno, 55, is
likely to succeed Bernabe. The company is expected to retain the
name Telecom Italia and its shares to trade separately.
</P>
<P>
   For Colaninno, Tuesday was a day for making visits in Rome,
underscoring the deal's heavy political trappings. After meeting
Tuesday morning with aides of Italian Prime Minister Massimo
D'Alema, Colaninno talked with Industry Minister Pierluigi Bersani
and union leaders to discuss plans for the future of Telecom
Italia. The company, a former state monopoly, is facing its fourth
management turnover since it was taken public in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Bersani said after the meeting that the Italian government would
decide whether to approve the takeover before the June 28
shareholder meeting. The government holds a 3.4 percent stake in
Telecom Italia with veto rights, though approval is considered
virtually certain.
</P>
<P>
   `'We want to follow this affair in its evolution,'' Bersani told
reporters. Telecommunications, he said, was a crucial business
``not only for employees and phone users, but also for the
country's industrial prospects.''
</P>
<P>
   Bersani was evasive on the issue of job cuts. Rather than
discussing layoffs, he said, ``It's necessary to talk about
organization, which means naturally also facing significant
interventions, but such as are reached through dialogue with the
social forces and designed to make the company more efficient.''
</P>
<P>
   Olivetti has said it expects to cut nearly 20,000 jobs at
Telecom Italia.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
