<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DA-FUNDS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOCKYER DENIES ROLE IN DECISION TO DROP PROBE OF PROSECUTOR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SCOTT WINOKUR  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ State Attorney General Bill Lockyer had ``no
personal knowledge'' of a decision by his office to drop an
investigation into possible criminal misappropriation of funds by
the office of San Francisco District Attorney Terence Hallinan,
Lockyer's spokesman says.
</P>
<P>
   Lockyer recently endorsed Hallinan, a fellow Democrat, in the
district attorney's bid for re-election this fall. But Lockyer's
spokesman, Nathan Barankin, said ``political calculations'' had not
entered into the abbreviated investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Hallinan's office improperly advanced $5,000 in salary to his
cousin, assistant district attorney Michael Hallinan, and misspent
an additional $1,800 on a Christmas party, according to an
unreleased audit by the San Francisco controller's office.
</P>
<P>
   Although the money was repaid, violations of both the city's
Administrative Code and the state Penal Code may have occurred,
legal sources said.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Terence Hallinan last week acknowledged the
error in spending money for the Christmas party, but denied that
the $5,000 paid to Michael Hallinan was improper, saying that it
was unpaid salary.
</P>
<P>
   A state government source said that investigators believed
misappropriation of funds possibly had occurred, but noted that
investigators in San Francisco had received instructions from
Sacramento to drop the case.
</P>
<P>
   Barankin confirmed that investigators for the attorney general
had, in fact, looked into the matter, but their supervisors in
Sacramento determined the case didn't meet the attorney general's
standards for further investigation and possible prosecution.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the evidence we received, it was not in any way clear to
the persons who make these assessments that there was enough,''
Barankin said.
</P>
<P>
   He said the decision to drop the matter was based in part on
consultations with ``people outside'' the attorney general's office
``who are familiar with the (San Francisco) DA's office.'' He
declined to identify those people.
</P>
<P>
   ``In assessing whether to proceed with a criminal prosecution,
against a San Francisco DA or a homeless man,'' Barankin added,
``it is incumbent upon the prosecutor _ or, in this case, the
attorney general's office _ to make sure you have a chance to
win.''
</P>
<P>
   Misappropriation of public funds is a felony punishable by
removal from office and up to four years in prison.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
