<SLUG> BC-DREW26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Carey provides Broadway-style number during May sweeps
 &HT;    By Phil Kloer
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   We've seen just about everything this May sweeps.
</P>
<P>
   We've seen Carol Hathaway's sonogram of twins on ``ER'';
Wilson's face on ``Home Improvement''; pirates attacking Noah's
Ark; Jerry Springer's so-much-classier new hairstyle and glasses;
just about all there was to see of ``Cleopatra'' through her
see-through gown; Rosie O'Donnell attacking Tom (``I am the NRA'')
Selleck; and Jennifer Anniston with a Magic Marker moustache on
``Friends.''
</P>
<P>
   About the only thing we haven't seen is a big, rousing Broadway
number, the kind that used to be mandatory as a curtain-closer back
in the golden age of American musicals.
</P>
<P>
   And who better to provide a big Broadway-style number to bring
down the curtain on May sweeps than ... Drew Carey? The burr-cut,
beer-loving comic who used to call himself The Human Cartoon?
</P>
<P>
   In case you haven't been paying attention, ``The Drew Carey
Show'' has been doing more with music than any other prime-time
series except ``Ally McBeal.'' They've done lip-syncing,
choreographed dancing, and spotlighted former Eagles guiatrist Joe
Walsh. But tonight they take it all the way home with a
show-stopping version of ``Brotherhood of Man,'' the climactic
number from ``How to Succeed in Business Without Really Trying.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the episode is just teeing up the big song-and-dance
finale. Hal Linden, no stranger to the Broadway boards, guest stars
as head of the Dutch conglomerate that owns Winfred-Louder
department store. He comes to town to fire everyone and dynamite
the store, which is, of course, the perfect set-up for the song,
about an employee trying to convince a boss that there are other
values besides the bottom line.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Morse did it first (on stage and in the movie version),
and Matthew Broderick did it quite well a few years ago in a
revival, and neither has anything to worry about from Carey. His
voice is thin, his dancing lively but limited, by Broadway
standards.
</P>
<P>
   But that's not the point. The sheer guts of tackling a four and
one-half minute slab of singing and elaborate choreography is more
than most sitcoms would dare. And Carey &AMP; Co. pull it off with an
infectious exuberance as they swirl and kick from their office
cubicles out onto the store floor and then to the boardroom.
</P>
<P>
   It's a high, giddy sequence, and a perfect note on which to end
the May sweeps.
</P>
<P>
   Other finales tonight, the last night of sweeps:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Dawson's Creek'' (8 p.m. on the WB). Dad problems abound.
Dawson finds out Joey's father is dealing drugs again, and Pacey
dukes it out with his father.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Dharma &AMP; Greg'' (8 p.m. on ABC). Realizing they never really
dated, the cute couple proceed to turn back the clock and do so.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Law &AMP; Order'' (9 p.m. on NBC). Benjamin Bratt becomes the
latest member to exit the revolving door cast in tonight's two-hour
special.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Drew Carey Show.''
</P>
<P>
   9 tonight on ABC
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B+
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
