<DOCNO> NYT19990525.0227 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-25 18:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0725 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CALIF-PESTICIDES-HNS &LR;      05-25 0567
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CALIF-PESTICIDES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPORT DETAILS PESTICIDE DAMAGE IN CALIFORNIA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JANE KAY  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ More than 25 years after regulators banned DDT
for harming wildlife, pesticides continue to kill birds and fish,
interfere with their reproduction and threaten the very survival of
many species, according to a study released Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The study by advocates of pesticide controls calls for an
immediate ban on two commonly used agricultural and garden
pesticides, diazinon and chlorpyrifos, plus carbofuran, which is
used by California rice growers.
</P>
<P>
   ``A massive chemical assault on our environment is launched each
year by California's residents, farmers and official agencies, as
we apply hundreds of millions of pounds of pesticide active
ingredients in our homes and gardens, on crops, on roadsides and in
forests,'' said Susan Kegley, one of the authors and a chemist at
the San Francisco-based Pesticide Action Network.
</P>
<P>
   Neither California growers nor state pesticide regulators had
seen the report, and therefore could not comment on its assessment
of pesticide damage to wildlife.
</P>
<P>
   Of the call for a ban, California Farm Bureau Federation
spokesman Dave Kranz said, ``California farmers face the most
stringent regulations of any farmers on the planet as far as their
use of pesticides. Farmers want to do the right thing, and they are
trying to make a living and trying to maintain the environment and
live within the rules and regulations. A blanket ban would cause
difficulties.''
</P>
<P>
   In California each year, more than 100 million pounds of the
most toxic pesticides in city and farm settings are ``responsible
for the deaths of many birds, fish and smaller aquatic animals that
fish depend on for food,'' Kegley said.
</P>
<P>
   The study, ``Disrupting the Balance: Ecological Impacts of
Pesticides in California,'' says birds are hit hardest.
</P>
<P>
   In the United States, 672 million birds are exposed to
agricultural pesticides each year, and an estimated 10 percent, or
67 million, die, according to the study.
</P>
<P>
   But, it asserted, most bird deaths caused by pesticides go
undocumented, and only a small fraction are reported. Sometimes the
chemicals kill wildlife outright, leaving dramatic evidence. Other
times, the chemicals subtly damage birds' behavior and their
reproductive and nervous systems.
</P>
<P>
   ``The loss of even a few individuals from rare, endangered or
threatened species _ for example, burrowing owls, Aleutian Canada
geese or raptors like the bald eagle, Swainson's hawk and the
peregrine falcon _ pushes the entire species that much closer to
extinction,'' Kegley said.
</P>
<P>
   One environmentalist praised the study, saying it provides
important documentation in bringing the pesticide issue to the
public.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know that pesticides are both directly killing birds at
times and can completely disrupt the food chain,'' said Craig
Breon, an environmental advocate in the Santa Clara Valley Audubon
Society. He urged cooperation with farmers and state regulators
``to see that this issue is addressed appropriately.''
</P>
<P>
   The study drew its statistics and conclusions from peer-reviewed
papers published in science and wildlife journals, government
documents, compilations of pesticide studies and interviews with
regulating agencies in California and elsewhere.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-25-99 1836EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990525.0228 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-25 18:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0726 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GUN-LAWSUITS-SFCHRON &LR;      05-25 0876
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GUN-LAWSUITS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 TWO CALIFORNIA CITIES SET TO SUE TOP GUNMAKERS  &HT;     By HARRIET CHIANG 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The cities of San Francisco and Los Angeles are
expected to sue the nation's leading gun manufacturers Tuesday in a
coordinated legal assault against the firearms industry.
</P>
<P>
   The cities hope the lawsuits will force the gun industry to take
steps to keep its weapons from criminals and to add safety devices
such as trigger locks.
</P>
<P>
   Similar suits have been filed by 10 cities, including Chicago,
Miami and New Orleans, as part of a growing movement to try to hold
the firearms industry responsible for gun violence.
</P>
<P>
   But those suits have sought to hold gun companies liable on the
grounds that they are negligently selling a dangerous product. The
suits being filed by San Francisco and Los Angeles are unusual
because they rely on a sweeping consumer protection law in which
companies can be held liable for illegal, unfair or deceptive
business practices.
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco will be joined in its Superior Court suit by
Sacramento, Berkeley and San Mateo. Los Angeles will file its suit
along with Compton. Lawyers in charge of the two suits say they
expect several more cities to join the litigation.
</P>
<P>
   Both suits will be filed against at least 40 gun manufacturers,
distributors and trade associations. The gunmakers include Smith &AMP;
Wesson, Colt, Beretta and Sturm, Ruger and Co.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuits take special aim at the handful of manufacturers in
the Los Angeles area that produce the cheap handguns known as
Saturday night specials. California, which has one of the largest
handgun industries in the country, is the leading manufacturer of
Saturday night specials.
</P>
<P>
   The city lawyers say gunmakers are washing their hands of any
responsibility for their product once it is distributed. Their
attitude is, ``Once it's out our loading dock, it's not our problem
anymore,'' said Owen Clements, chief of special litigation for the
San Francisco city attorney's office, who is coordinating the gun
suit. ``We don't think that's a responsible practice.''
</P>
<P>
   The suits are not seeking specific damages, although civil
penalties and other sanctions could amount to millions of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think it will be very significant in forcing gun
manufacturers to start acting more responsibly,'' said Luis Tolley,
a spokesman for Handgun Control, the legal action arm of the Center
to Prevent Handgun Violence, which is co-counsel in the litigation.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the gun industry has won almost every court battle.
However, in February, a New York jury found several of the nation's
largest gunmakers negligent for their marketing and distribution
practices and awarded gun victims a small amount of damages.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Delfay, president of the Sporting Arms and Ammunition
Manufacturers Institute, the largest gun industry trade
association, told the New York Times that there is no proof that
the industry is supplying guns to the criminal market.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no way for a manufacturer to know a specific firearm
is going to be used in crime,'' said Delfay, whose group is among
those named as defendants. ``If there was, I'm certain all
manufacturers would sacrifice that sale in a New York minute.''
</P>
<P>
   Clements said that accusing the gunmakers of violating
California consumer laws by failing to monitor the distribution of
their product has several advantages for the plaintiffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a broad statute that reaches all sorts of conduct that
might not be technically illegal but is unfair,'' Clements said.
</P>
<P>
   The cities say guns often fall into criminal hands through
``straw purchases'' _ in which someone lawfully purchases a large
amount of weapons, then sells them to felons or people who are
underage.
</P>
<P>
   ``They (gun companies) are selling in a way that facilitates the
supply to the criminal market,'' said Carmel Sella, the special
assistant in the Los Angeles city attorney's office who is
coordinating the Southern California suit.
</P>
<P>
   Sella said in Los Angeles, 4,700 guns are confiscated in crimes
every year.
</P>
<P>
   To win their lawsuits, the California cities will not have to
prove that the gun manufacturers caused any specific injuries, an
obstacle that many gun victims have not been able to overcome.
Instead, the cities will have to prove only that the gunmakers
engaged in an unfair business practice in distributing their
weapons.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of damages, the cities would be eligible to collect
$2,500 in civil penalties for each violation. A judge would decide
what constitutes a violation subject to the $2,500 penalty.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps more significantly, the law could force the gunmakers to
give up the profits from their allegedly unfair activities.
</P>
<P>
   The suits use the same consumer law that San Francisco used to
challenge the tobacco industry in 1996. That suit was the first
complaint filed by a city against cigarette manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
   Two years later, the city took part in the $206 billion
settlement reached between the states and the nation's leading
tobacco sellers. California will receive $26 billion from the pact,
with the state's counties and four largest cities, including San
Francisco, receiving $12.5 billion over the next 25 years. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
