<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-25 18:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0730 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ENVIRONMENT-0526-COX     05-25 0434
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ENVIRONMENT-0526-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    POLLUTION IN MINORITY COMMUNITIES TARGETED
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (a) general news categories
 &HT;    By Raven Hill
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON -- Birds don't nest anymore in the trees of Eraina
Dunn's hometown of Robbins, Ill. She blames it on fumes from the
city incinerator.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you are lucky enough to see one, they are usually just
flying through, not to stay and roost,'' Dunn said Tuesday at a
symposium on pollution in minority communities.
</P>
<P>
   Sponsors of the symposium say minority communities are
disproportionately exposed to toxic waste.
</P>
<P>
   The symposium was sponsored by 14 members of the congressional
black, Hispanic and progressive caucuses, and included residents of
contaminated areas, activists and scholars.
</P>
<P>
   Participants recommended that awareness of pollution in minority
communities be increased through legislation and education. They
also discussed the need to frame the issue in terms of health, not
civil rights, and the possibility of having the General Accounting
Office do a cost-benefit analysis of industries operating in
low-income communities.
</P>
<P>
   ``Environmental justice'' is likely to be the ``issue of the
next century,'' said Rep. John Conyers, D-Mich. He cited President
Clinton's executive order that federal agencies decrease the number
of toxic sites in minority and low-income communities.
</P>
<P>
   While federal agencies have proposed ways to achieve this goal,
some activists say state governments, particularly in the South,
are not cooperating. States are not obligated to adhere to those
guidelines.
</P>
<P>
   Sherrill Marcus, a community organizer with the Southern
Organization Committee for Economic and Social Justice in Atlanta,
said residents should have input in any action involving potential
pollution sites in their community.
</P>
<P>
   ``Help people make decisions rather than react to decisions that
have already been made,'' Marcus said.
</P>
<P>
   Another issue raised during the symposium was whether tackling
pollution in minority communities hampers economic development.
Participants rejected the idea of going easy on pollution for the
promise of jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not willing to trade our health for jobs,'' said
Florence Robinson, representing the North Baton Rouge Environmental
Association in Louisiana. Communities rarely profit from
enterprises such as medical waste disposal, she said, because they
offer jobs that are ``usually subservient positions with
substandard wages.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
