<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-25 18:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0735 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLENN-AGING26-COX     05-25 0594
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLENN-AGING26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GLENN'S SPACE FLIGHT RAISES HOPES FOR TREATMENT OF BALANCE ILLS
 &HT;    By SCOTT MONTGOMERY
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ John Glenn surprised NASA researchers by promptly
regaining normal balance soon after his space shuttle mission last
October, and his quick recovery suggests older people might respond
to treatment for balance disorders, a leading scientist said
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Although the 77-year-old former Ohio senator's first wobbly
steps off the shuttle Discovery were broadcast across the globe,
Glenn felt fine just four days later, which is within the average
range for astronauts.
</P>
<P>
   And test results on Glenn's inner ear, discussed for the first
time at Tuesday's symposium on geriatric research in Washington,
confirmed that the oldest man ever in space readapted to Earth's
gravity ``at least as fast'' as younger astronauts, said chief
researcher Dr. Owen Black, who heads the Neurotology(cq) Research
Laboratory in Oregon.
</P>
<P>
   Black, who had expected Glenn to need much longer to recover his
sense of balance than the rest of the shuttle crew, was cautiously
enthusiastic about the implications of his study.
</P>
<P>
   ``In science, you have to be very careful of what you say about
one (test) subject,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But when asked if the results were significant, Black said,
``absolutely.''
</P>
<P>
   In his research into the human balance system in the inner ear,
which is funded by NASA and the National Institutes of Health,
Black and others have developed ways to evaluate damage to the
vestibular system as well as some methods for repairing the damage.
</P>
<P>
   This work is particularly important to the elderly, who often
suffer balance problems that can lead to dangerous falls. Now Black
says there's the ``potential'' that the Glenn results could mean
elderly people with balance disorders can correct their vestibular
systems through treatment.
</P>
<P>
   At the very least, Glenn proves that an elderly man's vestibular
system is capable of the kind of readaptation that's critical to
the treatment in Black's program.
</P>
<P>
   ``At least there's the potential to put (elderly people) through
our training program,'' Black said.
</P>
<P>
   Glenn flew aboard the space shuttle Discovery as a subject of
several biology experiments seeking to understand the parallels
between the effects of aging on the body, and similar effects
caused by prolonged weightlessness in space.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to monitoring Glenn's balance before and after his
space flight, crew members during the mission collected data to
study the rate at which his body absorbed protein while in zero
gravity, as well as his ability to get restful sleep.
</P>
<P>
   Both muscle atrophy and sleep disruption are features of the
aging process and prolonged space flight. Scientists hope that
studying these effects in health astronauts will lead to
discovering the mechanisms that trigger such problems, which could
then lead to methods of controlling them.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. David Liskowsky, who heads the NASA life sciences division,
said he expects results from the remaining Glenn experiments to be
revealed when NASA holds its customary flight anniversary
symposium. Although Liskowsky said nothing has been scheduled, the
anniversary is Oct. 29.
</P>
<P>
   Glenn also attended the symposium Tuesday and added to the
discussion of balance disorders by admitting that his first moments
back on Earth after nine days in space were uncomfortable.
</P>
<P>
   ``I barfed,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
