<HEADLINE>
49ERS COACH FACES TOUGH FIGHT WITH CANCER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN CRUMPACKER  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ What began as a day of optimism for prospective
liver-recipient Bobb McKittrick ended with news that his cancer had
spread from the bile duct, forcing cancellation of an impending
transplant.
</P>
<P>
   McKittrick, the longtime offensive line coach for the San
Francisco 49ers, had gone into Stanford University Medical Center
Monday afternoon expecting to receive a partial liver after a
suitable donor organ had been located that morning in Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   Making the story more compelling was that McKittrick, 63, would
have shared the organ with a 6-year-old girl in a procedure known
as a split-liver transplant.
</P>
<P>
   The girl, who is too small to accept an adult liver, was
scheduled to receive a lobe of the organ before the remainder was
given to McKittrick.
</P>
<P>
   But when exploratory surgery was performed on McKittrick Monday
evening in preparation for the transplant, doctors discovered the
cancer, initially contained in the bile duct, had spread in the
form of white dots about the size of the head of a pin. The
transplant procedure, to be performed by liver specialists Carlos
Esquivel and Kenneth Drazlan, was canceled and McKittrick instead
had a biopsy to determine the extent of the cancer.
</P>
<P>
   ``They did an exploratory (procedure) and found some pinpoint
spots. The cancer spread so they couldn't do the transplant,'' said
Teckla McKittrick, the wife of the popular assistant coach. ``They
operated on him for about three hours and did a biopsy. He'll
probably be in the hospital for three or four days and they'll
decide what to do. It's not good news.''
</P>
<P>
   McKittrick was diagnosed with cancer of the bile duct in
mid-January, when it was also determined he would need a new liver.
He started a routine of chemotherapy and radiation in February and
finished the regimen in mid-April. In the process, the 200-pound
McKittrick lost 33 pounds but had gained six back before returning
to the hospital Monday evening.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel pretty good until I do something, then I don't have any
stamina,'' he said. ``I get tired easily.''
</P>
<P>
   But not too tired to do a little coaching. After receiving news
Monday morning about the donor organ, McKittrick did what he enjoys
most. He stopped by the 49ers' Santa Clara facility and instructed
center Jeremy Newberry and tackle Tyrone Hopson on the fine art of
pass blocking.
</P>
<P>
   Teckla McKittrick was not amused at her husband's devotion to
his job.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was a little miffed I didn't come right home,'' he said
before going into the hospital.
</P>
<P>
   McKittrick had been on the national list for a liver transplant
since February. To be accepted into the transplant program, he had
to demonstrate otherwise good health and a positive attitude in
order to offset his age, which stretched the limits of most
transplant patients.
</P>
<P>
   ``At some point, my attitude was a positive factor in proceeding
with this program,'' he said. ``I'm a little older than they'd
like. Other than my illness, I'm pretty healthy.''
</P>
<P>
   Because he has already had radiation in addition to
chemotherapy, McKittrick's treatment options are now limited.
</P>
<P>
   ``Radiation is out,'' his son, Ladd McKittrick, 38, said. ``He's
already had his maximum. Some sort of chemotherapy will be
determined. That probably will be the most likely treatment.''
</P>
<P>
   McKittrick's future with the 49ers, which he joined in 1979, is
uncertain. His illness made the team shift tight ends coach Pat
Morris to the offensive line. In the last minicamp Morris was
assisted by former 49ers guard Guy McIntyre.
</P>
<P>
   McKittrick has said he'd like to coach until he's 65.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't play golf. I don't ski. I don't hunt. I don't fish. I
don't play tennis. I coach football, and I like it,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
