<HEADER>
A0744 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BELLSOUTH26-COX     05-25 0517
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BELLSOUTH26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CEO makes argument for broad use of broadband
 &HT;    By Michael E. Kanell
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ BellSouth's chief executive this week urged the
government to encourage development of broadband networks that
would reach all Americans.
</P>
<P>
   In an unusual pitch, delivered at the annual meeting of the
Southeastern Association of Regulatory Utility Commissioners, F.
Duane Ackerman called agencies like the Federal Communications
Commission to view high-speed Internet access as they would the
telephone _ a necessity.
</P>
<P>
   Ackerman told about 250 attendees in Savannah, Ga. that the rich
and the powerful are already well on their way to the new era.
</P>
<P>
   ``Business is already getting broadband,'' he said. ``In the
next year, great numbers of affluent neighborhoods will see
broadband _ with offerings from two competitors. Densely populated
areas will get broadband, (but) not so in rural areas. Nor is it
likely to happen in many poor neighborhoods.''
</P>
<P>
   Ackerman said high-speed access is a potential enhancement to
education and health care that will someday be considered routine _
at least for those who are well-off.
</P>
<P>
   Ackerman's comments came as BellSouth faces a likely challenge
from cable companies upgrading their networks to handle broadband _
a plan that will permit them to offer high-speed Internet,
television and phone service as well. Although the cable providers
have thus far upgraded only a portion of their systems, momentum
has been given a massive shove with AT&AMP;T's purchase of two huge
cable companies. The first, Tele-Communications Inc., has little
presence in Georgia. But MediaOne, whose acquisition has not become
final, is the largest cable provider in metro Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   To compete, BellSouth and other local phone companies plan to
offer digital subscriber lines (DSL), which can carry high-speed
data over already-installed copper lines. Aware that the DSL
rollout has been bumpy, BellSouth plans to add about 1,000 devices
around metro Atlanta that will double the distance the service can
operate.
</P>
<P>
   While a consumer might choose between two wires for broadband,
Ackerman said the law favors cable over phone.
</P>
<P>
   Cable companies, for example, are not required to make their
networks open to competitors or other services. Internet Service
Providers have argued in vain _ at least so far _ that cable should
be as open as the phone networks, which carry various competitors
to the local phone companies that own the lines.
</P>
<P>
   For years, cable companies have insisted that they needed a
regulatory shield to protect them from the multi-billion-dollar
phone companies. But more recently, as their upgrades continue and
consolidation makes them ever-huger, the cable companies have
become increasingly ready to have the regulatory protections ripped
down.
</P>
<P>
   Congress is currently considering legislation that would change
some of those rules.
</P>
<P>
   Michael E. Kanell writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
