<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-25 18:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0745 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GRAPEVINE-COX     05-25 0797
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRAPEVINE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Grapevine's Reilly believes in industry
 &HT;    By Charles Haddad
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ From his eighth floor office, Wendell Reilly has a
sweeping view of a landscape dotted with construction cranes.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta enclave Buckhead, rapidly growing again, is a work in
progress and so is Reilly's TV station holding company and the
industry he's investing in.
</P>
<P>
   In the past three weeks, Reilly's Grapevine Communications has
spent $250 million to buy 11 TV stations nationwide. The purchases
have more than doubled the size of the company's holdings to 18
stations and tripled its annual cash flow to $30 million.
</P>
<P>
   And Reilly, chairman and founder of Grapevine, isn't done yet.
Indeed, he's stepping up the pace. Reilly is moving from buying
stations in places like Casper, Wyo., to richer markets such as
Huntsville, Ala., where he bought the ABC affiliate last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``My original plan was to buy 12 stations,'' says Reilly. ``I'm
way past that now. And there's no set limitations on the stations
we may own.''
</P>
<P>
   Grapevine's rapid growth belies the troubled seas it is
navigating. The TV industry is in upheaval. The big networks are
demanding that their affiliates shoulder more of the cost for
producing prime time shows.
</P>
<P>
   And some of them are starting to compete with channels such as
ABC's Soap Opera network. This new channel would feature the same
soap operas as that of ABC's affiliates, giving new and unwanted
competition for a popular genre of shows.
</P>
<P>
   This competition comes as viewership continues to decline for
network television and the industry as a group must spend billions
of dollars to upgrade stations to handle digital signals.
</P>
<P>
   ``TV is not what it used to be,'' says Reilly. ``It's going
through a rough time.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Reilly believes network television remains the single
best way for advertisers to reach a mass audience. The networks and
their affiliate stations remain the single largest slices of a
greatly fragmented pie, he says.
</P>
<P>
   It was that belief that led Reilly, whose background is in
outdoor advertising, to begin investing in the TV industry. He has
taken a contrarian approach, focusing on the small to mid-sized
stations ignored by the huge media conglomerates gobbling up
stations in big cities.
</P>
<P>
   Grapevine is not alone in this strategy. Others, including Gray
Communications Systems, have also bought up stations below the
radar of the big TV holding companies.
</P>
<P>
   Reilly's first deal was in 1997, when he bought a station in
Anchorage, Alaska. Reilly didn't start out with any capital but
soon earned the interest of an investment group in Teaneck, N.J.,
called BCI Advisors.
</P>
<P>
   BCI has a 15-year history of investing in TV and radio stations.
It also specializes in backing midsized businesses.
</P>
<P>
   For Reilly, it was a natural fit. ``The company was the smart
money in TV,'' Reilly says. ``BCI understands the market, its risks
and knows how to invest wisely.''
</P>
<P>
   In his polo shirt with a PGA logo, Reilly does not look the
dealmaker. Yet this is indeed his specialty. He enjoys telling how
he clinched a deal for a station in Savannah, one of his first,
with a handshake.
</P>
<P>
   ``My investors couldn't believe it, but that handshake held for
four months,'' says Reilly. ``The owner promised me he wouldn't
change the terms or sell to someone else and he didn't.''
</P>
<P>
   With this old-fashioned charm, Reilly has targeted family-owned
stations. He lavishes owners with the attention bigger players
wouldn't bother with. ``A big company would rather pursue a group
of six stations rather than just one,'' says Reilly.
</P>
<P>
   Reilly wants to focus even more on dealmaking. That's the
driving logic behind Grapevine's recently announced acquisition of
GOCOM, a Charlotte, N.C.-based company that owns 10 stations.
</P>
<P>
   In effect, the $185 million merger will create a new company
with headquarter operations split between Charlotte and Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   From Charlotte, GOCOM will handle management of all the
stations. Entrepreneur Ric Gorman, who will become chief executive
of the new company, runs GOCOM. His specialty is managing stations.
``Ric is a builder and he invests in sales,'' says Reilly.
</P>
<P>
   What he means is that GOCOM builds up a station's sales staff,
invests in training and also spends heavily on station promotion.
</P>
<P>
   In buying GOCOM, Grapevine is also getting Terry Segal, who once
ran the TBS Superstation. He is now head of TV programming for
GOCOM.
</P>
<P>
   Reilly will remain in Atlanta with his small staff. ``I'm the
deal guy,'' says Reilly. ``I will go and find more stations.''
</P>
<P>
   Charles Haddad writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
