<HEADER>
A0746 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MINDSPRING-COX     05-25 0488
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MINDSPRING-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MindSpring aims to be No. 2 Net provider
 &HT;    By Frances Katz
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Charles Brewer, chairman and chief executive of
MindSpring Enterprises, has a simple goal for his company. After
America Online, he would like MindSpring to be the second-largest
Internet service provider in the world.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking before the annual shareholders meeting at Atlanta's
High Museum, he spoke with his usual wit and conviction about the
future of both his company and the Internet in general.
</P>
<P>
   Brewer made it clear that MindSpring is first and foremost an
Internet access provider _ that is, a very big and influential
Internet access provider.
</P>
<P>
   Brewer said the firm needed to be big to meet its goals,
including potential media partnerships, lobbying for last-mile
access in Washington and making further acquisitions that will push
the company into the coveted No. 2 position ahead of AT&AMP;T and the
Microsoft Network.
</P>
<P>
   Previously, Brewer had suggested that Microsoft might eventually
want to sell off its dial-up access service, and if that happened,
MindSpring would definitely be interested. No deals have
transpired.
</P>
<P>
   However, Jupiter Communications analyst Mark Mooridan won't rule
out the possibility. ``Microsoft's core business is not access,''
he says. ``The MSN network barely exists anymore,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Brewer expounded on what would keep his ISP in business.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest key to our strategy is superior service and
support,'' he said. ``It's a great time for us to grow. Seventy
percent of households are not connected, but they will be, and
sooner than you might think.'' He stressed the company's goal to
continue growing, but not at the expense of service and support
that is the company's hallmark.
</P>
<P>
   Industry analysts are still wondering how MindSpring will spend
the more than $500 million it raised in a stock offering this year.
Brewer outlined several ways to leverage his 1.2 million-customer
base. This includes expanding its Web hosting and business services
division, forming partnerships and alliances with e-commerce and
media partners to optimize the MindSpring homepage, and possibly
dabbling in other telecommunications offerings.
</P>
<P>
   The company is also considering ways to provide international
access for MindSpring subscribers, but right now that type of
service is unavailable.
</P>
<P>
   But even as the Internet access business evolves beyond dial-up
phone lines into cable modems and DSL high-speed phone service,
Brewer said MindSpring's core business will always be connecting
users to the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``The job we have at MindSpring, that is connecting people to
the Internet won't change,'' Brewer said. ``But it will become more
involved.''
</P>
<P>
   Frances Katz writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
