A0747 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MINDSPRING-STOCKSPLIT     05-25 0354
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MINDSPRING-STOCKSPLIT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MindSpring sets 2-for-1 stock split
 &HT;    By Frances Katz
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ MindSpring Enterprises, whose stock price has been
steadily dropping over the past few weeks, announced a 2-for-1
stock split Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Shareholders at the close of business June 11 will receive one
additional share of MindSpring common stock for each share held.
Distribution of the additional shares will take place June 25.
</P>
<P>
   MindSpring stock has fallen from a 52-week high of $133 on April
13 to its Tuesday close of $69.
</P>
<P>
   While the company's stock has surged during the last 12 months,
it has increased just 13 percent since the beginning of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   The stock dip is part of a larger Wall Street sell-off of
technology stocks, which have been in free fall over the last few
weeks. However, many companies, including Theglobe.com and
interactive advertising service DoubleClick, have seen their shares
rise after announcing stock splits.
</P>
<P>
   The split came immediately following the approval by MindSpring
shareholders at their annual meeting Tuesday of a proposal to
increase the number of outstanding shares. Currently, 30.7 million
shares of MindSpring stock are outstanding.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe the this action will help widen the distribution
and enhance the marketability of MindSpring's common stock,'' said
Chairman and Chief Executive Officer Charles Brewer.
</P>
<P>
   He also said the split will bring the price per share of
MindSpring's common stock and the company's number of shares
outstanding into a range that should generate increased interest
from current and new shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   Investors tend to snap up shares after split announcements,
hoping they'll see a rise in the stock price.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a sort of range of stock prices that we think is
ideal, and since people do like to trade in round lots, this split
makes it practical for more investors and more small investors,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Frances Katz writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
