<HEADLINE>
FAXON BREAKS WRIST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM McCABE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Brad Faxon's weekend at home was supposed to be a break from the
PGA Tour as he recharged for a tough stretch that would include the
US Open.
</P>
<P>
   What he got instead was a broken left wrist that will keep him
sidelined 6-8 weeks, which means he is out of next month's Open at
Pinehurst No. 2. Faxon, 37, fell from a ladder at his home in
Barrington, R.I., and landed on his wrist.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'll probably have a cast on for 3-4 weeks,'' said Faxon's
agent, Greg Able of Pros Inc. ``Right now, the target date (for a
return) is probably the British Open (July 15-18).''
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, Faxon was at his home course last Thursday to watch
some of the action in the NCAA East Regional golf championships. He
was coming off a couple of solid efforts (T-13 at Greensboro, T-18
at the Byron Nelson) and feeling good about his game. Even the
Ryder Cup was on his mind, though he ranks 131st in the standings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a long shot,'' he said, ``but it would mean winning twice
and playing well in the majors.''
</P>
<P>
   Faxon and fellow Rhode Islander Billy Andrade will host the CVS
Charity Classic Aug. 1-3 at Rhode Island CC. The event will feature
18 other members of the PGA and Senior PGA Tours.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
