<DOCNO> NYT19990525.0244 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-25 19:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0759 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-NFL-MEETINGS-BOS &LR;      05-25 1103
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFL-MEETINGS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SNYDER GETS TO BUY REDSKINS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Dan Snyder, a 34-year-old PR man from Washington,
received Tuesday what few people in the NFL get. He got Al Davis's
vote.
</P>
<P>
   Snyder officialy became the owner of the Washington Redskins
after his $800 million bid was approved by a unanimous 31-0 vote of
the league's owners. That ended a year-old soap opera over the
future of the franchise that began with the death of Jack Kent
Cooke and ended with his son being effectively cut out of the
team's future by his father's will.
</P>
<P>
   That will stipulated the team be sold to the highest bidder to
fund a charitable foundation, but Cooke never had any idea it would
cost his son the team because of the skyrocketing valuations of NFL
franchises in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   John Kent Cooke, who has run the Redskins' day-to-day operation
in recent years for his father, was unable to match an $800 million
offer from Howard Milstein, with whom Snyder was a minority
partner. But Milstein was unable to receive league approval and
finally withdrew his offer and is suing the league and Redskin
management, claiming the latter worked to submarine his efforts.
</P>
<P>
   Snyder continued to press his own cause, forming a new
partnership that includes Boston businessman Mort Zuckerman and
Fred Drasner, co-publisher of the New York Daily News. Together
they made their own $800 million offer and were quickly approved
both by the trustees of Cooke's estate and the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been an unbelieveable journey,'' Snyder said Tuesday.
``This has been a lifelong dream. I am a huge fan. It's that
simple.''
</P>
<P>
   It may have been simple but it wasn't cheap. The 'Skins brought
the highest price ever for an NFL team and one of the highest in
the history of professional sports, dwarfed only by the recent sale
of Manchester United's soccer team for &UR;  &LR; $1 billion. It also brought
headaches and disappointments during the long months Milstein's
group was in negotiations, especially after it successfully outbid
Cooke's $680 million offer only to see the owners make clear they
would reject his bid if he brought it forward.
</P>
<P>
   When Milstein withdrew the offer last month, Snyder said his
dream of owning his childhood team remained intact and he
immediately began forming a new group with himself as the lead
owner.
</P>
<P>
   ``To fulfill my dream, I needed to get together with some
people,'' Snyder said. ``I stayed in the hotel and made a few calls
and said I'd press on. Within a week or two after that things came
together.''
</P>
<P>
   Drasner, who was on hand with Snyder Tuesday, had been a
financial supporter of Snyder's business efforts dating back to
their first meeting 13 years ago. At that time, Snyder was trying
to start a fledgling advertising and public relations firm that
would quickly grow into Snyder Communications, a firm now listed on
the New York Stock Exchange. Drasner financially backed that effort
and Snyder's latest one as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``I backed him 13 years ago because I thought he was a winner,''
Drasner said. ``Hopefully I'll be a passive investor and just yell
and scream at him when I think he made a mistake.''
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, Davis did not think Snyder is a mistake. The Oakland
Raiders' managing general partner has in recent years abstained
from many major league votes to protect what he sees as his own
legal rights but Tuesday he joined the crowd, throwing his support
behind the NFL's youngest owner.
</P>
<P>
   Davis and his partners also heard presentations from the two
groups vying for ownership of the league's expansion franchise in
Los Angeles. Initially, each was to give a presentation to the
Expansion Committee on how it would solve expected parking problems
at a refurbished LA Coliseum, but both sides unexpectedly were
asked to make a second presentation Tuesday morning to the full
ownership.
</P>
<P>
   Hollywood movie executive Michael Ovitz presented a stadium plan
that includes 27,000 parking spaces within the Coliseum Park area
that would cost an estimated $200 million. The stadium would be
rebuilt on top of a raised parking garage. The $200 million price
tag would be on top of the estimated $300 million price of
remodeling the stadium itself.
</P>
<P>
   Ovitz also addressed a major concern of the league, which is the
apparent apathy of Los Angeles's sports fans toward the return of
NFL football to LA.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not 100 percent convinced LA will embrace NFL football,''
Ovitz said. ``I think people are pretty fed up with NFL football
(after both the Rams and Raiders abandoned southern California in
recent years). We have to bring the fans back. We have to give them
something to root for and we have to make it easy for people to
come there and feel good there. We have to relight their fire.''
</P>
<P>
   That apathy is what two spokesmen for the New Coliseum Partners,
Ovitz's competition for ownership, said is the reason why the NFL
should adopt their stadium and parking plan over Ovitz's. It is
their opinion that a more modest parking proposal, which will use
existing lots and garages as well as building a new garage to bring
total parking within three-quarters of a mile of the Coliseum to
28,500, would cost only $67.5 million, and is more in line with
what can be reasonably financed.
</P>
<P>
   They offered the league's owners three parking plans, one of
which was all underground and cost an estimated $240 million, a
second that was a combination of above and below ground for $193
million, plus the less expensive model they favor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our presentation was about certainty,'' said John Semcken,
executive vice president of New Coliseum Partners. ``I hope this
doesn't come down to who has the best parking. Our main concern is
the league will pick a plan that can't be done and will hurt
football in Los Angeles down the road.''
</P>
<P>
   Semcken declined to say specifically that his group did not
believe Ovitz could adequately finance his proposal with a $200
million cost for parking spaces, but his belief in that was clear.
</P>
<P>
   The final day of meetings will address both a proposal to move
the kickoff back to the 25-yard line and the New England Patriots'
stadium financing request. Owner Robert Kraft expects a vote will
be taken to approve a $112.5 million league-backed loan to defray
half the cost of building a new stadium in Foxborough, Mass. that
he hopes will be ready within two years.
</P>
<P>
   Passage of that loan, a first under a new NFL policy designed to
help finance a portion of new stadiums in urban centers, is not
expected to meet much opposition.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
