<SLUG> BC-BKC-TEXAS-MIHM-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UT'S CHRIS MIHM BEEFING UP TO BECOME THE BEST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE JONES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ The halls of the Moncrief-Neuhaus Athletic
Center at the south end of Royal-Memorial Stadium on the University
of Texas campus are quiet on this spring day.
</P>
<P>
   Inside the spacious Al-Rashid Strength Complex, even the
ceiling-mounted surround-sound speakers that usually fill the
weight-training facility with a cacophony of music are silent.
</P>
<P>
   This is, however, another intense workday for Longhorns center
Chris Mihm and strength-and-conditioning coach Todd Wright, whom
basketball coach Rick Barnes says is the best there is at what he
does.
</P>
<P>
   Wright prods the 7-foot Mihm through a series of exercises that
include the inclined bench press using dumbbells, the standing push
press, squats, the dumbbell lunge-walk and a series of what Wright
calls ``prehab'' exercises that are designed to prevent injury.
</P>
<P>
   Each drill, each movement is specifically tailored for the
player whom many expect to blossom next season into one of college
basketball's best. This is a scene Mihm and Wright will repeatedly
reprise over the course of the summer. Other than to take time out
this week to try out for the World University Games U.S. team, Mihm
plans to spend a major portion of the next three months working
with Wright. Tryouts for the July 3-12 games begin Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Both relish the prospect.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chris has unbelievable genetic potential,'' said Wright, who
came to Texas with Barnes last spring. ``I've never been with a
young man who has developed as fast as he has.''
</P>
<P>
   Their unabashed goal is to build college basketball's next
player of the year.
</P>
<P>
   To date, Mihm has added 12 pounds of muscle since last season.
He weighs 275 pounds and has not lost any of his agility.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I'm ready to go out and try to dominate next season,''
said Mihm, a consensus all-Big 12 selection and the Star-Telegram
conference player of the year last year as a sophomore.
</P>
<P>
   ``\RBeing national player of the year\S has been one of my goals
since I came to Texas. I've put in my dues the last two years, but
I'm still working hard every day. And when you do that, good things
come.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm ready to try to make a run at taking this team to the
Final Four and winning a national championship. If the
player-of-the-year honor comes, then that would be fantastic, a
dream come true. But it's something I definitely want to achieve.
It's something to reach for.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, it is a goal that Barnes openly encourages _ rather than
hem and haw with the common line that team goals come first, etc.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want Chris Mihm to be player of the year,'' Barnes said.
</P>
<P>
   In this case, team success might follow, rather than the other
way around.
</P>
<P>
   Mihm, forward Gabe Muoneke and point guard Ivan Wagner return.
Sophomore forward Chris Owens _ whom Barnes likens to Muoneke _
comes off a redshirt transfer season. Three highly rated freshmen
and two junior-college shooting guards will join the roster of the
defending Big 12 regular-season champions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we're going to have a fantastic team,'' Mihm said.
</P>
<P>
   With the talent influx, Barnes should be able to field a team
that can put more pressure on those who try to double- and
triple-team Mihm. But Barnes is not just depending on the addition
of some shooters with outside range. He's already training a new
perimeter player: Chris Mihm.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not just going to put Chris on the low block and say this
is where you need to play,'' Barnes said. ``That's one of the
easiest things to do to help the other team, because they can
always find him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chris is going to open his game up. We know he's effective
inside, but he's also good facing the basket. I want to see him
shoot some threes and put the ball on the floor more effectively.
The way we're working right now, he'll do that next year.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot to work on,'' Mihm said. ``But it's been a fun
change of pace.''
</P>
<P>
   Barnes showed Mihm a newspaper article that discussed possible
NBA player-of-the-year candidates. Mentioned was the consistency of
Karl Malone, the intensity of Alonzo Mourning, the versatility of
Tim Duncan.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to see Chris Mihm put all those things together,''
Barnes said.
</P>
<P>
   Mihm is 19, but there is a new look of maturity about him. The
youthful expression has transformed into that of a young man _
ready to accept the responsibility of leadership, the burden of
great expectation that comes with a declared lofty goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I pick goals some may say are far-fetched,'' Mihm said. ``But
so far, I've achieved everything I ever set for myself. If you set
them high, and reach for them, that's the only way to go to really
make yourself go anywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Mihm around the rim Among Texas center Chris Mihm's
accomplishments last season are: _ Selected /{Fort Worth
Star-Telegram/} Big 12 Player of the Year, consensus
all-conference, /{Kansas City Star/} all-improved, all-defensive
squads, NABC all-District 9, USBWA all-District 7, honorable
mention Associated Press All-American. _ Ranked fourth nationally
in rebounding (11.0), 17th in blocked shots (2.6 per game). _
Averaged 13.7 points, 11 rebounds _ 21 points and 14 rebounds in
three postseason (Big 12, NCAA) tournament games. + Achieved 19
double-doubles, 16 in the last 21 games when he averaged 14.8
points and 12.6 rebounds and Texas went 16-5.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
