<SLUG> BC-ALLMERICA-SETTLE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COURT OKS ALLMERICA SETTLEMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNNLEY BROWNING  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Putting to rest an episode in which it purportedly led customers
to buy life insurance policies they did not need, Allmerica
Financial Corp. received final court approval Tuesday for a
settlement with policyholders who had sued over deceptive sales
practices.
</P>
<P>
   The deal, which requires the Worcester, Mass. insurer to spend
up to $31 million compensating the owners of 400,000 policies
issued over a 10-year period, represents the latest action against
an insurer accused of fraudulent practices. ``They were not the
first company to get involved in this and now its over and behind
them,'' said analyst Ira L. Zuckerman of Nutmeg Securities, Inc.
</P>
<P>
   The approval, by the US District Court in Worcester, formalizes
a preliminary agreement reached in December between Allmerica and
four policyholders who had filed a class-action suit asserting that
nearly every life policy that Allmerica peddled from 1978 to
mid-1998 was sold deceptively.
</P>
<P>
   The group said Allmerica agents misleadingly encouraged
policyholders to use their old certificates to trade up to newer,
more expensive ones, and that agents wrongly promised that life
insurance premiums would diminish over time. The company originally
estimated that it sold 450,000 policies over the period, but
recently revised the figure downward.
</P>
<P>
   Allmerica's chief spokesman, Michael Buckley, denied the company
had engaged in wrongdoing but said it had decided to resolve the
matter in court ``because it was in the best interest of
policyholders, shareholders, and the company.'' Allmerica rose 5/8
Tuesday to close at 56 on the New York Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   Under the terms of the settlement, Allmerica will allow 400,000
aggrieved policyholders two options: to buy discounted life
insurance or annuities (insurance that makes payments to the holder
over time); or to present their cases to an independent referee,
who will determine compensation and benefits. The company could end
up spending more than the $31 million it has reserved for the
settlement if many policyholders choose the latter path.
</P>
<P>
   In the biggest deceptive sales practices settlement, Prudential
Insurance Co. of America, the nation's largest life insurer, will
pay up to $2 billion to compensate 8 million policyholders. Other
big life insurers, including John Hancock Mutual Life Insurance Co.
of Boston, have settled similar suits in recent years.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
