u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHINA-COX-BEIJING-ART     05-25 0575
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-COX-BEIJING-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
603-1036.)
</HEADLINE>
  
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888) CHINA DEFENDS ITS HONOR ON SPYING CHARGES  (jw) 
 By ERIK ECKHOLM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ Accusations that Chinese spies stole nuclear weapon
designs and missile technology from the United States are ``totally
groundless,'' China's Foreign Ministry said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The espionage charges are fabrications by ``people with ulterior
motives'' who hope to divert attention from NATO's bombing campaign
in Yugoslavia and the attack on the Chinese Embassy in Belgrade,
said Zhu Bangzao, the ministry spokesman, at a regularly scheduled
news conference.
</P>
<P>
   Zhu spoke hours before the official release in Washington of the
report by a congressional committee that described suspected
Chinese operations to steal some of the most advanced American
military technologies. As of late Wednesday night, there was no
further official reaction to the report. But the Chinese denials
and countercharges have been repeatedly stated over many months, as
details of the spy accusations and the committee's conclusions have
dribbled out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people in the United States stubbornly cling to a Cold
War mentality, are full of bias and hostility toward China and have
tried in all possible ways to create rumors about China,'' Zhu
said. ``Their goal is to spread the theory of a `China threat' and
divert attention from the embassy bombing.''
</P>
<P>
   Many Chinese officials and scholars say they have deeply
resented continuing reports in the American press of accusations
about China _ first that it tried to influence American elections
with bribes, then that it stole nuclear warhead designs. None of
the charges has been proved, they note.
</P>
<P>
   Few details of the allegations have been published in the
official press here, and many people seem to accept the
government's assertion that American foes of China have
orchestrated a campaign to discredit the country.
</P>
<P>
   Anger over the spy charges was among the litany of complaints
about American treachery cited by scholars and students here in
recent weeks as they tried to explain the outpouring of harsh
anti-American feelings after the May 7 bombing of the Chinese
Embassy in Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   Chinese pride has also been hurt by the suggestion that their
own scientists could not develop advanced nuclear warheads on their
own. In recent months, prominent elder scientists have been
interviewed in the official press describing China's past
achievements in developing nuclear weapons and missiles.
</P>
<P>
   China's nuclear forces are tiny compared with those of the
United States and Russia and rely on outdated, vulnerable
fixed-site missile launchers. American military analysts believe
that in the coming decade China will start deploying smaller,
advanced warheads on mobile missiles, improving their ability to
evade destruction in an enemy attack and retaliate.
</P>
<P>
   Some American intelligence officers, supported by the
congressional committee, believe that China's quest for such
improved warheads and missiles has been greatly aided by espionage.
Other intelligence officials say this is unproved.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the origins, if China deploys larger, more accurate
nuclear forces, then its ability to threaten American allies and
troops during a crisis in Asia will be enhanced, American military
experts say.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
