<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-25 19:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0773 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SPYING-POLITICS-HNS &LR;      05-25 1238
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPYING-POLITICS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHINA SPYING CONTROVERSY BECOMES AN INSTANT CAMPAIGN ISSUE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ERIC ROSENBERG  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A bipartisan House report concluding that China has
stolen many of the country's most coveted nuclear secrets became an
instant campaign issue Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans issued withering assaults on the administration's
handling of suspicions, going back to 1995, that the Chinese were
receiving classified material from American nuclear weapons
laboratories.
</P>
<P>
   The attacks indirectly targeted Vice President Al Gore, one of
President Clinton's closest advisers and the Democratic frontrunner
campaigning to replace him.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Gov. George W. Bush, the Republican frontrunner, quickly
issued a statement in response to the 700-page House report,
attacking what he called ``the administration's failed policies
toward China.''
</P>
<P>
   The spying has ``dramatically accelerated China's emergence as a
major nuclear power,'' Bush said. ``The implications are huge for
the balance of power in Asia and for the balance of power in the
rest of the world.'' Bush especially faulted the administration's
long-held stance toward China as a ``strategic partner,'' a
position that Gore has stoutly defended.
</P>
<P>
   ``China is not America's strategic partner,'' Bush said. ``China
is a competitor which does not share our values, but now,
unfortunately shares many of our nuclear secrets.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore made no reply to the GOP attacks, but his office aides
directed reporters to the White House for a response.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton, speaking in Texas, said his administration
was ``moving aggressively to tighten security'' at the nuclear
weapons labs. He added, ``We have a solemn obligation to protect
such national security information and we have to do more to do
it.'' But the president also insisted that the administration would
continue dealing with China on a range of matters because, he said,
that, too, was in the national interest.
</P>
<P>
   Energy Secretary Bill Richardson, noting the report's conclusion
that China also stole military technology during the Ronald Reagan
and George Bush administrations, said, ``It would be a mistake to
attempt to use this report for political gain.''
</P>
<P>
   However, some Republican strategists hope to use national
security and foreign policy against Gore in the current campaign,
especially if the crisis in the Kosovo, now entering its third
month, drags on.
</P>
<P>
   ``The longer that we are involved in Kosovo, the more damage
that it, coupled with Chinese espionage, will do to Al Gore,'' said
Republican pollster Frank Luntz. ``When voters come to make that
final decision of who to elect president, these things do matter.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Nancy Pelosi, D-Calif., a member of the House Intelligence
Committee, said the Clinton-Gore administration has taken steps
``to solve the security problems at the national labs.''
</P>
<P>
   But Republicans and the House report faulted the White House for
failing to react quickly to evidence of Chinese penetration of U.S.
weapons laboratories.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Hess, a political analyst with the Brookings
Institution, a nonpartisan think tank here, said that Gore, whether
he likes it or not, will have to defend the Clinton legacy as the
election nears.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gore is one of the most active vice presidents in U.S.
history,'' Hess pointed out. ``He can take partial credit for
things that have gone right in the last eight years. But he also
has to share the blame for things that went wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore has been heavily involved in foreign policy and national
security. He successfully urged Clinton to include large defense
spending boosts in his fiscal 2000 budget and has helped devise
policy on Russia, Bosnia, the Kosovo crisis and the 1994 invasion
of Haiti.
</P>
<P>
   National security last played a big role in a presidential
election in 1988, when the Cold War was still an issue. Then Vice
President George Bush, who had been CIA director and an envoy to
China, touted his foreign policy credentials and painted Democrat
Michael Dukakis as weak on defense.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, in 1980, Reagan successfully used the Iranian hostage
crisis as part of his campaign to unseat President Jimmy Carter.
Public unhappiness over the Vietnam War played a role in bringing
Richard Nixon to power in 1968 and in forcing Lyndon Johnson to
give up his quest for a second term.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, in 1964, Johnson had defeated Sen. Barry Goldwater,
R-Ariz., partly by successfully casting Goldwater as an an extreme
foreign policy hawk. And Dwight Eisenhower won the White House in
1952 in part by accusing the Democrats of losing China to communism
in 1949.
</P>
<P>
   Norman Ornstein, an analyst at the American Enterprise
Institute, another think tank here, said Republicans are searching
for viable campaign issues because they are getting ``trounced by
Democrats'' on gun control, crime, social security and the
management of the economy.
</P>
<P>
   But Ornstein said that while the China spying issue ``has the
potential to resonate with voters,'' there are ``caveats.'' For
instance, he said, if Gore isn't directly tied to the
administration's failure to halt the espionage, voters ``are likely
to discard the issue in the voting booth.''
</P>
<P>
   Hess agreed that voters aren't likely to pull a lever for the
Republican presidential nominee solely because of the spying. But
he added that the House report could become ``ongoing background
noise'' throughout the campaign that voters might connect to
scandals involving illegal Chinese contributions to the
Clinton-Gore campaign in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   According to the House report, China stole U.S. nuclear warhead
designs, advanced radar know-how and missile guidance system
blueprints dating to the late 1970s when Carter was president. The
report concludes that an ``insatiable appetite'' for U.S.
technology has allowed China to leap from a 1950s nuclear weapons
program to state-of-the-art designs ``on par with our own.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Besides Gov. Bush, other GOP presidential hopefuls and party
leaders fired their own salvos against the administration.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., said the House report underscores ``a
complete failure to effectively bring these breaches of security to
a halt. This is a disturbing report and one that is very damning to
the administration.''
</P>
<P>
   Publishing magnate Malcolm S. ``Steve'' Forbes said ``the
Clinton-Gore administration'' has ``demonstrated incompetence,
ineptitude, and insincerity on a scale never before witnessed in
the history of U.S. defense.'' Forbes also said ``the Clinton-Gore
administration'' should suspend effort to help China gain entry to
the World trade Organization.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Nicholson, the chairman of the Republican National
Committee, said he was ``sickened'' by the findings ``and appalled
that this administration's reaction was to drag its feet out of
fear of political embarrassment.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. J.C. Watts, R-Okla., the House Republican Conference
chairman, said that while the alleged spying also occurred under
Republican Presidents Reagan and George Bush, ``only the
Clinton-Gore campaign accepted millions in campaign contributions
from communist China while easing export restrictions on advanced
technology.''
</P>
<P>
   (Eric Rosenberg can be reached at 202-298-6920 and at the email
address eric(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
