<SLUG> BC-HUNGARY-FIGHTERS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HUNGARY FEELS SECURE DESPITE HOSTING US FIGHTERS, MARINES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN MILLIGAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TASZAR, Hungary _ US fighter planes will be ready for takeoff by
the weekend to battle Yugoslav forces over the nearby southern
border, officials said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Although such an attack would bring the new NATO member closer
to the war, it is safer than ever, Hungarian and US officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hungary's security has only grown with its membership in
NATO,'' Hungarian Ministry of Defense State Secretary Lajos Fodor
said as he visited the air base here. ``The fact that US Marines
are deployed here only contributes to the stability.''
</P>
<P>
   Locals are a bit more nervous about the possibility of an
assault from their soil. While polls show Hungarians support the
NATO air strikes in general, a majority are skittish about the
launch of an attack from Hungary, fearing that Hungary will become
a Serbian target.
</P>
<P>
   Residents of the border towns already can hear the booms from
NATO bombs on the Serb side of the border. They also worry about
the fate of some 400,000 ethnic Hungarians in Vojvodina, in
northern Serbia.
</P>
<P>
   So far, Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic has made no
threats against Hungary, the only NATO member on the border of the
war zone.
</P>
<P>
   An all-out assault on Hungary would be suicidal for Milosevic,
since it would amount to a direct attack on all of NATO, said
Hungarian Air Force General Istvan Nemeth.
</P>
<P>
   Security at the border has been increased since the bombing
began, Hungarian officers said. Any potential attack on Hungary
from the south would be spotted by border guards or US or Hungarian
planes, they said.
</P>
<P>
   The stationing of the F-18s in Taszar means Yugoslavia is now
bordering four nations -- Hungary, Macedonia, Albania and Bosnia --
that have NATO troops and aircraft. Two other bordering countries,
Romania and Bulgaria, are members of NATO's Partnership for Peace.
</P>
<P>
   The F-18s can be used for several purposes, including defense of
other aircraft and direct attacks, officials said. ``We'll be ready
in a few days'' to begin operations if ordered, said a Marine
pilot, who also refused to be named.
</P>
<P>
   The base at Taszar already is home to some 500 American military
personnel who are using the base for Stabilization Force (SFOR)
operations in Bosnia, a grim reminder that the West's peace-keeping
troops are still needed in Bosnia, four years after the war there
ended.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the US presence on the base has dramatically increased,
with a reported 800 Marines on base as part of the NATO war effort.
</P>
<P>
   Nemeth acknowledged that the war was not what Hungary
anticipated when it joined the military alliance.
</P>
<P>
   Frankly, I didn't expect that on Day 12 after we joined NATO, we
would have this task to contend with,'' Nemeth said. ``As a
soldier, I was hoping for a peaceful resolution.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the other hand, we know we have an obligation,'' Nemeth
said. ``That's why Hungary has authorized NATO to use its air
space.''
</P>
</TEXT>
