<SLUG> BC-STUDENTS-MENINGITIS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GROUP RECOMMENDS MENINGITIS VACCINATION FOR STUDENTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD A. KNOX  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Melanie Bean of San Diego was an 18-year-old college student
when she got meningococcal meningitis, a raging infection that
destroyed her kidneys and left her with amputations of both arms
and legs.
</P>
<P>
   Evan Bozof was a junior at Georgia Southwestern University last
spring when meningitis struck. Twenty-six days later the college
athlete was dead.
</P>
<P>
   An apparent increase in such tragedies is touching off a debate
among public health officials. Should all US college students be
vaccinated against the strains of Neisseria meningitidis that cause
most cases of meningitis in this age group?
</P>
<P>
   Authors of a study published this week say yes. Others say more
evidence is needed to avoid unintended harm from widespread use of
a vaccine that may cause serious side-effects not seen so far in
its limited use.
</P>
<P>
   The study found that students at four-year colleges in Maryland
who live in on-campus housing had more than a three-fold higher
risk of bacterial meningitis than students who live off-campus.
College students who lived off-campus did not have a higher rate of
meningitis than 18- to 22-year-olds in general.
</P>
<P>
   The results confirm studies in military recruits showing that
close proximity increases the risk of meningococcal meningitis, a
rare but often devastating infection caused by an organism that
lives in the throats of many people without causing harm.
</P>
<P>
   The currently marketed vaccine would have prevented 80 percent
of the 228 Maryland meningitis cases among college students and
three of the four fatal cases seen there between 1992 and 1997, the
researchers said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This disease is relatively uncommon,'' said Dr. Lee H.
Harrison of Johns Hopkins University and the University of
Pittsburgh, lead author of the study, which appears in this week's
Journal of the American Medical Association. ``Yet all you have to
do is see a couple of cases of young healthy people dying in a
short period of time to be convinced that _ if you've got a vaccine
that is safe, effective, and inexpensive _ it is reasonable to
immunize.''
</P>
<P>
   The study was paid for by Pasteur Merieux Connaught, which makes
a meningitis vaccine effective against four major strains of the
bacterium, along with the US Centers for Disease Control and the
state of Maryland.
</P>
<P>
   Other public health officials acknowledge growing concern about
bacterial meningitis, even though it is a relatively rare disease
that strikes about 2,600 people a year in this country, most of
them children under age 5. About 175 cases may occur annually among
US college students.
</P>
<P>
   ``There have been anecdotal observations that a lot of college
students have been getting the disease in the last few years,''
said Dr. Bela Matyas of the Massachusetts Department of Public
Health.
</P>
<P>
   ``But from a public health standpoint, an anecdotal approach is
not appropriate,'' Matyas added. ``If we go ahead and decide that
some group of people en masse should be vaccinated, we have to
demonstrate that we will significantly reduce the disease without
causing a bigger problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Matyas noted that the meningitis vaccine ``has never been used
on a large scale, so we don't know if it's a somewhat safe vaccine
or a very safe vaccine.'' Vaccines have been known to cause
unexpected side effects when used on a mass basis, such as the
cases of paralysis called Guillain-Barre syndrome that cropped up
after the ill-advised swine flu vaccine campaign in the mid-1970s.
</P>
<P>
   The American College Health Association recommends that college
students consider meningitis vaccination, which costs about $50,
and that college health services ``take a proactive role in
providing information and access to the vaccine.''
</P>
<P>
   Matyas urged that a decision about mass vaccination await the
results next year of a national study by the CDC on meningitis
among teenagers and young adults.
</P>
</TEXT>
