<HEADLINE>
WHY HIM AND NOT ME?
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Tuesday, June 1.)  
(Eds: There will be only one Susan Swartz column this week. There
will be no columns for the next two weeks.) (mk) 
 By SUSAN SWARTZ   
 Santa Rosa (Calif.) Press Democrat   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   We were talking about the difference between lust and envy over
lunch and a friend said that he no longer lusts for things but he
is envious and one thing he envies is celebrity. For example he no
longer has car lust or house lust but he does envy the famous their
access to interesting people.
</P>
<P>
   He assumes that celebrities get to surround themselves with
fascinating people of their own choosing, that if you're famous you
can ask Tom Waits and Madeleine Albright over for dinner.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, we recognize there are drawbacks to high visibility.
You can't stop at the bagel shop all sweaty from the gym. Someone
is always watching. Look at poor Julia Roberts. She's in Newsweek
magazine, of all places, waving to a crowd in London and setting
off a scandal because she didn't shave under her arms.
</P>
<P>
   People notice those dumb things when you're famous.
</P>
<P>
   But there are times you think _ oh yes, you do _ why him/her and
not me?
</P>
<P>
   We assume the famous get invited to more parties, don't worry
about money, have good teeth and someone to work on their feet. If
they stay home with a video it's a film not yet released to us
commoners.
</P>
<P>
   My friend used to occasionally hang out with Annie Lamott, the
recently famous writer, back when she was a famous drinker. That
Lamott once drank is well known to her fans, and my friend, who
also writes and once drank, envies that she's made use of both to
become famous.
</P>
<P>
   He went to a reading for her latest book and happened to run
into her in the hall. He said ``hi.'' She said ``hi'' back and he
thought of reminding her that they used to know each other from a
certain saloon but decided not to. Not because he was too gracious
to bring up those wild years but because he would have been crushed
if she would have shook her head no, she couldn't place him.
</P>
<P>
   Most famous people come from ordinary beginnings and are going
to be remembered by people who were in their science club in high
school or drank with them one rainy Friday night in Cotati. Then
they become famous and someone thinks back and says, ``Hey, I knew
that guy.'' But it doesn't necessarily work the other way around.
</P>
<P>
   A woman I know used to go out with the famous writer John Irving
back when they were in college. She now teaches literature and
creative writing and she's not surprised that good old John became
a best-selling author.
</P>
<P>
   At age 20, when they were college juniors and ran around in the
same art and writing bunch, she says he already had an agent and
had been taken under the wing of two writing teachers.
</P>
<P>
   Recently when he was reading in San Francisco she considered
going and sending a note to him backstage, but she, too, worried
that he'd pull a blank when he looked at her.
</P>
<P>
   Being a major John Irving fan, I pressed her for all details,
romantic and otherwise. She said they went out off and on for five
months. He took her to wrestling matches and once to dinner at a
New York restaurant where there was violin music and he taught her
to drink bourbon. Another time he introduced her to Cointreau which
he'd learned to drink in Spain and he loved Spain.
</P>
<P>
   She's been following his career ever since ``The World According
to Garp.'' She liked that Jenny Garp, the mother heroine, is a
nurse because she remembered that John's mother was a nurse.
</P>
<P>
   She's also followed his personal life and notes that he seems
happily married to his current wife, a Canadian woman who used to
be his publicist. Once she ran into a mutual friend who told her
Irving had become ``an incredible womanizer.'' She says, ``I may be
the only woman who didn't sleep with him.''
</P>
<P>
   She said ``he was worldly, he had confidence and he was
focused,'' so his success makes sense. But she also says had he not
become John Irving the famous writer she might not have remembered
him as anyone more than ``another guy I dated.''
</P>
<P>
   What she envies about his life is ``having enough money to just
write, travel wherever you want, live wherever you want and to be
able to say, `I think I'll do a piece for the New Yorker.' ''
</P>
<P>
   But what do we know? Maybe the famous yearn to be invisible,
snapped at by clerks, ignored by waiters, bugged on the phone by
people wanting to give them better long distance rates.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe they're like Michelle Pfeiffer who says she likes her life
but wishes she had long legs and curly hair.
</P>
<P>
   Who wants to have to worry about things like that?
</P>
<P>
   (The Press Democrat in Santa Rosa, Calif., is part of the New
York Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
