<HEADLINE>
DUPING OF LENO ONE FOR BOOKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL GOODYKOONTZ  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - NBC's Web site for the ``Tonight Show'' includes a
teaser for the popular headlines feature in which Jay Leno shows
funny mistakes in newspapers all around the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``These headlines are real,'' the teaser reads. ``Really.''
</P>
<P>
   Not really. Not this time. It seems a Valley man is having the
last laugh.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, the headline in question really ran. It just wasn't a
mistake.
</P>
<P>
   Well, that's not exactly right either. It (begin ital) was (end
ital) a mistake, but it was a mistake made on purpose, which isn't
a mistake at all.
</P>
<P>
   It's deceit. But, first, an explanation.
</P>
<P>
   For the last year or so, Mark Walters, who owns Mr. Books in
northwest Phoenix, has had this scheme.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came up with the idea to create my own display ad that had a
problem,'' Walters said, sitting behind the counter of Mr. Books.
``Our original intent was to get some exposure, a free ad _ to get
some publicity.''
</P>
<P>
   He would have the ad printed, he figured, cut it out and send it
in. Then the ``Tonight Show'' staff would see it, like it, Leno
would show it, and Mr. Books would receive a dose of national
exposure. Exposure for an erroneous ad, yes, but exposure
nonetheless. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Not just happy accident &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Yeah, right. First of all, what are the chances the staff would
pick the ad? And if someone liked it and passed it along, there
must be a waiting list of, what, 20 years or something? By the time
the ad appeared, would Walters still be alive?
</P>
<P>
   Yes. The whole thing took about two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Walters paid $200 for an ad in the ``Custom Shopper,'' a free
publication. That's where, in the latest issue, you'll find it:
</P>
<P>
   ``Be smart, reed a book.''
</P>
<P>
   Look closely, and you'll see that the important words are what
stand out _ ``Phoenix,'' ``Mr. Books,'' that kind of thing.
</P>
<P>
   This wasn't just a happy accident. Walters studied the headlines
shown on the ``Tonight Show'' with two goals in mind. One was to
make the mistake bad enough that it would be noticed. The other was
to play up those key words so that they would show up on camera.
</P>
<P>
   ``I devised it specifically to (see) what would it look like
when the ``Tonight Show'' cameraman zoomed in on it.''
</P>
<P>
   Walters tapes up signs with goofy sayings in the windows of Mr.
Books _ one played off John and Lorena Bobbitt's marital
misadventures. ``Bobbitt sale _ sausage cookbooks half-off,'' it
read.
</P>
<P>
   He took the ``reed a book'' idea from one such sign.
</P>
<P>
   ``The original was `Be smart like us _ reed a book,' '' he said.
``I had that, but I thought, `This looks too much like something
someone's trying to do.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Can't have that. So he dropped the ``like us'' and proceeded. &QL; 
 &QL; 
`Brave little bookstore' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Then there was the matter of submitting the erroneous ad.
Walters couldn't very well own up to being its author. So he
didn't. He used his mother's address and played the part of an
impartial third party. He didn't save a copy of the letter but
remembered writing that this mistake was particularly funny,
``knowing how proper bookstores think they are.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I sent it in and started taping (the show) every night,'' he
said. On May 17, the ad ran.
</P>
<P>
   He has heard from customers who saw the spot, he said, but not
from NBC. Told about the deception, Jennifer Barnett, an NBC
spokeswoman, said, ``We get about 8,000 to 10,000 headlines a week.
We go through every one of them, and we definitely get a lot that
are fake. That's not to say that sometimes one wouldn't slip
through that is a fake.''
</P>
<P>
   Apparently.
</P>
<P>
   I've always been a Letterman man myself, so someone duping Leno
doesn't bother me much. Still, doesn't Walters feel a little bad?
</P>
<P>
   ``Not at all,'' he said. ``This is America. All you want to do
is let people know your brave little bookstore is here for people
to enjoy. I just saw it as an opportunity for the little guy to do
something a little larger than life, almost.''
</P>
<P>
   Pardon me if I don't weep. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Reach Bill Goodykoontz at bill.goodykoontz(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
