<TEXT>
<P>
   The Los Angeles Daily News plans to move the following general
stories for use by NYTimes News Service clients, AMs and PMs of
Wednesday, May 26, and thereafter. For questions about stories,
contact David Brady at the Daily News, (818) 713-3470.
</P>
<P>
   ELWAY-FOOTBALL (Los Angeles) _ Billionaire Eli Broad said he has
a verbal commitment from John Elway that if the superstar retired
quarterback enters the Los Angeles football franchise competition
at all, it will be with Broad's team. The two were sequestered for
more than two hours in a Florida airport conference room Sunday
where the conversation ranged from college experiences to
investment tips, then moved to a possible deal. By Beth Barrett and
Steve Dilbeck. (Will move in the ``a'' national and ``s'' sports
news files.)
</P>
<P>
   LADYBUG-SOLUTION (Los Angeles) _ About 2 million ladybugs will
be released in an effort to battle the Australian redgum lerp
psyllids, a new eucalyptus pest theatening trees at a suburban Los
Angele parks. By David A. Baker. (Will move in the ``a'' national
and ``n'' California news files.)
</P>
<P>
   CANCER-STUDY (Los Angeles) _ A Los Angeles woman is among 1,500
people who will take part in a five-year study of two breast cancer
drugs, one of the largest ever. What's it like to risk your own
health for the sake of science? By Robert Monroe. (Will move in the
``a'' national and ``n'' California news files.)
</P>
<P>
   SMOKING-TOURISM (Browne) - Smoking bans in three states and 31
cities, including Los Angeles, have not impacted the tourism
industry based on hotel revenues, despite tobacco company claims,
according to a study. By Phillip W. Browne. (Will move in the ``a''
national and ``n'' California news files.)
</P>
<P>
   MATTHEWS-STUDIO (Los Angeles) _ Wall Street is starting to fall
in love with Matthews Studio Group. The Burbank, Calif.-based film
equipment specialist has seen its stock hit all-time highs in
recent sessions as anticipation builds over the launch of its
Internet site. By Dave McNary. (Will move in the ``f'' financial
news file.)
</P>
<P>
   SEMINIS-SEEDS (Los Angeles) _ Seminis Inc., a fruit and
vegetable seed developer, is going public in the next few weeks.
The Ventura County, Calif.-based company is expected to offer 12.5
million shares at $23 to $25. By Deborah Adamson. (Will move in the
``f'' financial news file.)
</P>
<P>
   BEST-COMPANIES (Los Angeles) _ Three Pepperdine University
business students are in search of the perfect company, traveling
the United States this summer to meet with the heads of about 50 of
the nation's top companies to determine what makes them so
successful _ and the lessons that can be drawn from them. By
Enrique Rivero. (Will move in the ``f'' financial news file.)
</P>
<P>
   UNILAB-DEAL (Los Angeles) _ Unilab Corp. announced Tuesday it
has signed a definitive agreement to merge with a division of a
private investment firm based in New York. The deal for the
Tarzana, Calif.-based lab testing company is valued at
approximately $420 million, including $145 million in debt. By Ben
Sullivan. (Will move in the ``f'' financial news file.)
</P>
