<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-COX-CLINTON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHITE HOUSE ADMITS SECURITY BREACHES IN RESPONSE TO COX REPORT 
</HEADLINE>
  (dal) 
 By JOHN M. BRODER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The White House responded in a low-key and
respectful manner on Tuesday to the release of the Cox committee
report on Chinese nuclear espionage, acknowledging that a serious
security breach exists while assuring Congress and the public that
the administration is hard at work fixing it.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton said that he shared the concerns of the
panel's nine members and offered assurances that the administration
was working to adopt many of its recommendations.
</P>
<P>
   ``First, let me say that I am particularly appreciative of the
careful and bipartisan manner in which the committee did its
work,'' said the president, speaking at an unrelated domestic
policy event in Texas. ``Like many other countries, China seeks to
acquire our sensitive information and technology. We have a solemn
obligation to protect such national security information, and we
have to do more to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   The accommodating tone of the White House reaction arises from
the gravity of the charges in the Cox committee report released on
Tuesday and signed unanimously by the panel's Republicans and
Democrats. The president's aides, who have known of the panel's
major conclusions for several months, concluded that a harsh
response would not give sufficient weight to the seriousness of the
allegations and could be politically damaging.
</P>
<P>
   In remarks to reporters and in a written response to the Cox
committee findings, administration officials stressed that many of
the suspected losses of sensitive technology took place before
Clinton entered office. They also repeated earlier assertions that
Clinton and his top advisers took swift and decisive action when
they learned of the alleged security breaches.
</P>
<P>
   The White House's written response noted that security at the
national weapons laboratories, where the most serious leakage is
suspected to have occurred, ``has been a long-term concern,
stretching back more than two decades.''
</P>
<P>
   Bill Richardson, the secretary of energy, which overseas the
weapons labs, said at a news conference on Tuesday that the Clinton
administration deserved credit for responding promptly to
accusations of espionage.
</P>
<P>
   ``This administration has acted on the problem; previous
administrations didn't act,'' Richardson said. ``Now, this is not a
partisan issue; this is a bipartisan problem that we are trying to
fix.''
</P>
<P>
   Richardson called the Cox report ``an important, valuable piece
of work,'' yet noted that he had begun moving aggressively to
improve security and counter-espionage surveillance at the national
weapons labs long before the Cox report was released.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have undertaken a total overhaul of the Department of
Energy Counterintelligence Program,'' Richardson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do take issue with one component of the Cox report,'' he
added, ``and that is, that we have taken enormously aggressive
action to deal with the problem. We are fixing the problem. I can
assure the American people that their nuclear secrets are now safe
at the labs.''
</P>
<P>
   The administration response, fashioned over weeks of
consultations among officials of the National Security Council, the
White House counsel's office, Cabinet officers and the president's
top political advisers, is in marked contrast to its handling of
myriad other investigations launched by the Republican-led
Congress.
</P>
<P>
   The White House has responded to prior inquiries with delay,
denial and legalisms. The president's defenders have tarred the
investigations as partisan and accused Republicans of dredging up
trivia to embarrass the president.
</P>
<P>
   In this case, however, the White House has sounded a more
conciliatory note, in part because the nine-member Cox committee's
four Democrats all endorsed its findings.
</P>
<P>
   The administration also does not want to turn relations between
the United States and China into a political circus that could set
back the president's policy of ``strategic partnership'' with
Beijing for years.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said he will not allow China's alleged theft of American
military secrets to derail his policy of economic and diplomatic
engagement with Beijing because it is in the United States'
interest. He said the United States had in place strict controls to
limit transfer of sensitive technology to China, a statement at
odds with many of the conclusions of the investigative committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``I strongly believe that our continuing engagement with China
has produced benefits for our national security,'' the president
said.
</P>
<P>
   A White House official, speaking on the condition of anonymity,
said that the allegations of Chinese nuclear spying were of a
different nature from last year's impeachment charges and earlier
investigations into Whitewater and other matters.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a recognition that we are dealing with serious
issues,'' the official said, ``but we view them as issues that are
longstanding ones and that require steps to deal with, and we're
taking them.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead of mounting a hostile defense, the White House is
pleading for understanding.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't think it's valuable for anyone to point fingers in a
way that detracts from work that should be done,'' the official
said.
</P>
<P>
   But the White House did not completely abandon the field to Cox
and his conclusions. Included with the White House's written
response was a sheaf of newspaper articles and opinion pieces that
set out to debunk the committee's findings and The New York Times'
reporting on them.
</P>
<P>
   Among them are two columns by Lars Erik Nelson of the New York
Daily News, who accused the Times of conducting a ``lynching'' of
Wen Ho Lee, the former Los Alamos laboratory worker suspected of
nuclear espionage. Nelson also wrote that Clinton has gotten a
``bum rap'' over alleged theft of nuclear secrets.
</P>
<P>
   The clippings also include reports from the Washington Post and
Los Angeles Times, based on interviews with administration
officials and outside intelligence specialists, that call into
question the severity of the technical losses. Other clippings
include columns defending the administration's policy of strategic
partnership with China, including one by Henry Kissinger, the
architect of American engagement with Beijing.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, seeking to tamp down the passions that debates on China
always inspire, said Tuesday that he wanted to address the problem
of possible theft of nuclear secrets without damaging relations
with the most populous nation on earth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to assure you and all the American people that I will
work very hard with the Congress to protect our national
security,'' he said in Texas, ``to implement the recommendations
and to continue our policy of engagement because both of them are
in the national interest.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
