<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-COX-COHEN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COHEN POSTPONES TRIP TO CHINA
</HEADLINE>
   (jw) 
 By ELIZABETH BECKER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Secretary of Defense William Cohen has postponed a
planned trip to China, citing tension between Washington and
Beijing, the Pentagon announced Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   On the day Congress released its report on the theft of American
nuclear secrets by the Chinese, Pentagon spokesman Kenneth Bacon
said Cohen believed that this was ``not the easiest time to visit
China.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He did have tentative plans to go in June,'' Bacon said. ``He
feels that it may be better to go later. He remains, of course,
steadfastly committed to engagement with China as a long-term
policy.''
</P>
<P>
   China temporarily broke off all military-to-military programs
with the United States after the accidental bombing by NATO of the
Chinese Embassy in Belgrade on May 7. At the time, NATO and the
United States apologized to China for the bombing, which killed
three Chinese journalists and wounded 20 other Chinese officials.
</P>
<P>
   For nearly a week, Chinese citizens held anti-NATO and
anti-American protests in Beijing and other Chinese cities,
encouraged in part by the government, which has been opposed to the
NATO air campaign since it began in March.
</P>
<P>
   NATO supreme commander, Gen. Wesley Clark, delivered his report
Tuesday on the bombing accident, saying it had been caused by
faulty maps prepared by the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The atmosphere between China and the United States has been
clouded, as well, by the release Tuesday of the report by a select
committee of Congress that says China used documents and blueprints
it stole from the United States to develop and improve its nuclear
weapons.
</P>
<P>
   Bacon said the Cox Committee report did not suggest that China
took advantage of the military-to-military exchanges in its attempt
to steal secrets.
</P>
<P>
   ``These exchanges were, although important, not the type of
exchanges that allowed any classified information to be transmitted
one way or another,'' he said. ``We were really trying to get to
know the Chinese military a little better and allow them to get to
know our military a little better so we could avoid
misunderstandings today and in the future.''
</P>
<P>
   China will consider whether to resume those exchanges next
month, according to a Pentagon official. The official said the
lines of communication between the two militaries remained open.
</P>
<P>
   The military contacts include exchanges of high-level visits by
the secretaries of defense and heads of services, ship visits at
ports in the United States and China, exchanges of information on
safety in naval and air operations to avoid incidents at sea,
exchanges of observers at joint training exercises, and sharing of
information on disaster relief.
</P>
<P>
   The United States temporarily broke off the program in May 1996
in protest Chinese missile tests near Taiwan when that country was
holding its presidential elections.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
