<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-25 19:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0784 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NH-MLK-DAY-BOS &LR;      05-25 1262
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NH-MLK-DAY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MLK DAY OBSERVANCE   BILL PASSES IN NEW HAMPSHIRE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RALPH JIMENEZ  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CONCORD, N.H. _ Next year, New Hampshire will at last join the
rest of the nation in honoring the birthday of civil rights leader
Dr. Martin Luther King Jr.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, by a surprisingly strong vote of 212 to 148, New
Hampshire lawmakers passed King Day legislation that has Governor
Jeanne Shaheen's fervent support. The bill will come before the
24-member Senate on Thursday, which is expected to pass it. Shaheen
could sign it into law early next week.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1979 when the first King holiday bill was introduced, the
conservative, 400-member House has rejected moves to honor King 11
times. Since 1993, when Arizona joined the national fold, New
Hampshire has stood alone in refusing to attach King's name to a
holiday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to congratulate the House and all of the people who
worked so hard to get this legislation passed, not just today but
for the last 20 years,'' Shaheen said in a statement issued after a
vote that many hope will help the state shed a reputation of racial
intolerance.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, at the height of the US presidential campaign, white
supremacists held a rally on the State House steps to celebrate New
Hampshire's intransigence regarding King, who was assassinated in
1968. Last month, the Ku Klux Klan chose the little town of
Washington for a midnight leaflet campaign extolling white
separatism.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, despite a trip to New Hampshire by King's widow,
Coretta Scott King, protests by school children, and appeals from
the state's civil rights leaders, clergy and governor, King Day
legislation failed in the House by just one vote.
</P>
<P>
   Many speakers in the 90 minutes of floor debate that preceded
Tuesday's vote warned that New Hampshire should not set itself
apart by rejecting the bill again.
</P>
<P>
   ``Martin Luther King said that one day he hoped that his
children would be judged not by the color of their skin but by the
content of their character,'' Representative Jane Kelley, a Hampton
Democrat told her colleagues.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, New Hampshire must be judged by the content of its
character. We must pass this legislation before us so that the ugly
stain of racism and bigotry can be cleansed from the beautiful face
of New Hampshire,'' Kelley said.
</P>
<P>
   Civil rights activists across the country Tuesday praised the
news, describing it as an important step for the entire country.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's another step toward healing, and it's welcome,'' said the
Rev. Jesse Jackson, who marched with King throughout the South in
the 1960s. ``Our better angels in New Hampshire have prevailed.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson said that for too long the state treated the holiday as
a political football rather than a moral imperative. ``They are
trying to make up for lost time,'' he said. ``But in the end, faith
and hope have prevailed.''
</P>
<P>
   The historic vote comes 25 years after Massachusetts made King's
birthday a state holiday and 16 years after a federal law gave
states the option of joining in the national celebration of King
and his message of equality and non-violence.
</P>
<P>
   Despite victory, as the House vote indicates, resistance to
honoring King remains strong in New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   Several speakers argued that King did not deserve an honor
denied US presidents George Washington and Abraham Lincoln. Others
faulted King for reports of infidelity and his opposition to the
Vietnam War.
</P>
<P>
   ``We should honor someone with the following characteristics,''
said Representative Ralph Rosen, a retired Naval officer from
Laconia. ``That person should be preeminent in the actual
achievement of civil rights. That person should be of unquestioned
moral stature and . . . that person should be completely dedicated
to our country and all of the people in it,'' Rosen argued.
</P>
<P>
   After 20 years of often acrimonious debate, the arguments for or
against a King holiday were familar to both sides. No catcalls or
boos marred the proceeding, but some speakers, among them
Representatives John Pratt and Harvey Keye, moved their colleagues
to applause _ and at times, to tears.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been more than 40 years since I joined thousands of my
countrymen in that long march through Atlanta,'' said Pratt, then
one of the young, white civil rights activists who marched in
King's funeral procession. Atlanta's City Hall flew its flags at
half-staff and its portico was draped in black crepe. On the other
side of the street, Georgia's flags, including the battle flag of
the Confederacy, flew at full-staff above the State House while
state troopers taunted the marchers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope my colleagues today will vote in this chamber to dispel
any doubt about on which side of the street this venerable building
and the people we represent stand,'' the Walpole businessman said.
</P>
<P>
   Representative Harvey Keye of Nashua is one of three blacks
serving as a legislator in a state where African-Americans make up
less than 1 percent of the population. ``I ran in an all-white ward
and won by seven votes so I can't say it's a racist place,'' Keye
said. ``Racism comes out when there is a threat and there aren't
enough of us to provide a threat,'' Keye said after Tuesday's vote.
</P>
<P>
   In his floor speech, Keye spoke of his boyhood in Birmingham,
Ala., in the days of Governor George Wallace and police
commissioner Eugene ``Bull'' Connor. ``As a little boy, I could not
walk the streets and look white people in the eye because that was
a threat to white people and I could be arrested for disorderly
conduct,'' Keye told his colleagues.
</P>
<P>
   A stint as a gang leader sent Keye first to the courts, then to
Catholic School, and finally to college. He was working as a waiter
at a country club on a night King and his fellow Southern Christian
Leadership Council leaders were having a conference.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shortly afterward, a big bomb blew a hole in the wall and it
seemed like it had been contrived by the police because about 10
minutes later they were having a press conference with King,'' Keye
recalled.
</P>
<P>
   Young, tough, and still hotheaded, Keye said he and his friends
decided to find the bombers and kill them. King talked them out of
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Martin Luther King talked to us. He talked of Mahatma Ghandi
and his philosophy of non-violence. I stayed until the wee hours of
the morning and talked not only to Martin Luther King but to the
others, and at that time, I put down my arms and became a warrior
and an ambassador for God,'' Keye said in a speech followed by a
long silence before the applause.
</P>
<P>
   Most King holiday supporters, among them Mel Bolden, a former
state representative and member of the state's human rights
commission, cited not racism, but orneriness for New Hampshire's
solitary stance.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just them being contrary Yankees,'' said Bolden, an
octogenarian artist, who is black and who has made his home in the
state since the 1960s. Shaheen's support, Bolden said, helped
overcome that legendary stubborness.
</P>
<P>
   Though past governors have backed the holiday, Shaheen ``was the
only one who really came down front for it,'' Bolden said.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of it has to do with habituation and resistance to
people trying to tell us what to do,'' said Steve Davis, a black
school administrator who helped organize the first schoolchildrens'
march on the State House in support of the holiday a decade ago.
``This is the `Live Free or Die' state. `We are who we are and you
are not going to tell us what to do,' and you have to respect
that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
