<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times plans two pages on the continuing Kosovo
crisis.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-NATO (Brussels) _ NATO ambassadors agree to nearly double
the Kosovo peacekeeping force to around 45,000. By Michael R.
Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-DIPLO (Washington) _ Diplomatic developments: German
Foreign Minister Joschka Fischer said here today that Germany was
counting on a diplomatic outcome to the war in Kosovo, with the
backing of Russia, in the next several weeks. Echoing strong
statements by the German chancellor, Gerhard Schroeder, Fischer
stressed that Germany opposed NATO forces entering Kosovo unless a
settlement was first reached with Yugoslav President Slobodan
Milosevic. By Jane Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-PENTAGON (Washington) _ Military developments: With
allied officials now describing the Serbian air defense system as
increasingly crippled, NATO warplanes bombed several targets
overnight, including the villa and compound outside Belgrade that
is a headquarters of President Slobodan Milosevic and his
leadership, according to Pentagon and NATO officials. NATO jets
also hit the Sabac engineering depot in Serbia, equivalent to the
Corps of Engineers, according to the Pentagon. By Elizabeth Becker.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-MACEDONIA (Blace, Macedonia) _ Relief officials warn of a
new crisis as thousands more refugees are expected to enter
Macedonia; they negotiate with the Macedonian government to try to
open more camps. By David Rohde.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-REFUGEES-U.S. (Boise, Idaho) _ Kosovo refugees are being
resettled in the United States but there are still so few of them
that communities and churches are fighting over them. By Diana Jean
Schemo.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-NATO-TV (Belgrade) _ The picture is grainy, the sound
poor, but if people here really want to, and if they have
electricity, they can tune into NATO TV, beamed into Serbia on
Channel 21 every evening from an American Hercules plane. By
Carlotta Gall.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-ALBANIA (Tirana) _ The transformation from Communist
outpost to a member of the European community of nations has not
been easy. Albania remains Europe's poorest country and has
suffered through one crisis after another. With its economy
demolished and many of its roads and public buildings crumbling,
the country slid into anarchy in 1997 following the collapse of a
gigantic pyramid scheme in which huge numbers of Albanians had
invested. And now there is a new crisis. Since March 24, more than
half a million Kosovo refugees have flooded in, increasing
Albania's population by 15 percent and placing enormous strain on
its resources. By Anthony DePalma.
</P>
<P>
   The following story, which was sent earlier, is now HELD; please
guard against premature release:
