<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-BLUECROSS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLUE CROSS MEMBERS TO ACCESS TO SECOND OPINION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX PHAM  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- In an effort to cultivate a more patient-friendly
persona, Blue Cross and Blue Shield of Massachusetts said Tuesday
it will let its 1.6 million members turn to an outside organization
to appeal denials of coverage by the health insurer.
</P>
<P>
   While more than 20 states currently require health maintenance
organizations to let members get a second opinion from an
independent third party, Massachusetts does not.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly it was what our customers were clamoring for,'' said
William Van Faasen, chief executive of Blue Cross. ``As health
plans look more and more alike, it's customer satisfaction that
will differentiate us.''
</P>
<P>
   The Blue Cross move was well-received by patient advocates and
state lawmakers who say it constituted a good, if incomplete, step
toward achieving a package of patients rights that is currently
under review in the State House.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an excellent step forward,'' said Representative
Harriette Chandler, a Democrat from Worcester and co-chairwoman of
the legislative joint health care committee.
</P>
<P>
   Rebecca Derby of Health Care For All, a patient advocate group
in Boston, also lauded Blue Cross, but said the health plan did not
go far enough. For one thing, the Blue Cross plan allows members to
appeal only care in which the patient and Blue Cross disagree over
whether it's ``medically necessary.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a good concept, and we commend them for trying,'' said
Derby, ``but if they get to set the rules by which patients can
appeal, that's inadequate protection for patients.''
</P>
<P>
   The Blue Cross proposal lets patients appeal coverage denials to
physicians contracted by Vital Solutions Inc., a subsidiary of
MassPRO, a company that provides managed care services to the state
Division of Medical Assistance and private health plans throughout
Massachusetts, including Blue Cross.
</P>
<P>
   Members can turn to Vital Solutions only after they exhaust Blue
Cross' internal appeals process, which takes five days on average,
according to Ron Romano, Blue Cross' consumer ombudsman. Complaints
lodged at Vital Solutions would be resolved within 10 days.
Emergency appeals would be resolved within two days.
</P>
<P>
   The cost of the review _ $300 a case _ would be shared, with
Blue Cross paying $200 and the member paying $100. Blue Cross said
it would pay the full amount for ``hardship cases,'' which would be
determined on a case-by-case basis, Romano said.
</P>
<P>
   Blue Cross processes about 150 appeals a month, the vast
majority of which are resolved in the members' favor. Only about 20
percent of those cases remain denied, Romano said.
</P>
<P>
   Harvard Pilgrim Health Care, the state's biggest HMO, said it
has for the past 10 years allowed patients whose care had been
denied coverage to turn to outside arbitration. Of the 2,600
appeals filed at Harvard Pilgrim last year, only two have reached
arbitration. The vast majority of appeals are settled before
arbitration.
</P>
<P>
   Executives at Tufts Health Plan, the state's second-largest HMO,
Tuesday said they were ``actively considering an external appeals
process.'' Sources say Tufts is close to adopting a program similar
to Blue Cross'.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-25-99 1940EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
