<DOCNO> NYT19990525.0268 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-25 19:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0796 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TANGLED-WHALE-BOS &LR;      05-25 0397
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TANGLED-WHALE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER DELAYS RIGHT WHALE RESCUE ATTEMPT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOTT ALLEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Rough seas prevented a specially trained animal rescue team from
disentangling a rare Northern right whale snarled in fishing gear
90 miles off Cape Cod Tuesday, and rescue officials said
Wednesday's weather doesn't look promising either.
</P>
<P>
   The whale, one of only about 300 right whales left in the world,
has three buoys floating near its head and fishing line wrapped
around its body and trailing behind. Although the animal appears to
be swimming normally, officials at the Center for Coastal Studies
fear the gear will interfere with the animal's feeding, possibly
killing it.
</P>
<P>
   But, unlike most whales the center has disentangled, this one is
far outside the more protected waters of Cape Cod Bay, and rescuers
must watch out for towering waves that can swamp the hard-bottomed
inflatable boat they use in rescues.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whale is traveling through some very rough seas with up to
12-foot swells. . . . Beyond 6 feet, we can't get close to the
whale,'' said Scott Landry, spokesman for the Provincetown-based
center. ``It looks like Thursday is going to be our best weather
day.''
</P>
<P>
   The crew, led by biologist Charles ``Stormy'' Mayo, plans to
employ an old-fashioned whaling technique called ``kegging,'' in
which large buoys are attached to the whale to slow the animal and
prevent it from diving.
</P>
<P>
   Once the animal tires, the team will attempt to cut the lines
from the whale using knives on long poles equipped with
adjustable-length handles. Landry said the rescuers try never to
actually touch the whales, which can weigh up to 40 tons and kill
with the flick of a tail.
</P>
<P>
   Landry said rescuers expect a complicated effort with this
particular whale because the 45-foot animal appears strong and
because they have to work around its mouth. ``Judging from how the
animal is entangled, this would likely be more than a one-day
event,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Landry said the team does have experience on its side, since
so many whales get caught in fishing gear off the New England
coast. Last summer, they disentangled one right whale in Cape Cod
Bay three times.
</P>
<P>
   ``By the third time, he was quite amenable to it. He just opened
his mouth'' and rescuers removed the rope, Landry said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
