<HEADLINE>
CELLUCCI BACKTRACKS ON GEORGES BANK EXPLORATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOTT ALLEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Gov. Paul Cellucci beat a hasty retreat from his
tentative endorsement of oil and gas exploration in the fishing
ground of Georges Bank Tuesday, sending word out through aides that
he had not intended to reverse the state's longstanding opposition
while on a trade mission to Canada.
</P>
<P>
   Cellucci created a furor among fishermen, environmentalists and
fellow politicians last week when he told reporters in Nova Scotia
that he would consider supporting oil and gas exploration on the
Canadian side of the bank, one of the world's great fishing areas.
The US government has closed its side of the bank to the oil and
gas industry until 2012.
</P>
<P>
   But Environmental Affairs Secretary Bob Durand said that
Cellucci apparently misunderstood the issue in his interview at the
Halifax Herald. Fresh from a tour of a new natural gas plant in a
less fragile area, Cellucci let his enthusiasm for the Sable Island
project carry over to Georges Bank, he explained.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the public policy realm, there's plenty of room for
misunderstanding, and sometimes that occurs, and you've got to be
willing to say that's what happened here,'' said Durand.
</P>
<P>
   ``The governor was very excited about Sable Island and extension
of the gas pipeline,'' he said, referring to a pipeline that soon
may bring gas to Massachusetts. ``It would be easy for somebody to
see how you could misconstrue the distinction'' between Sable
Island and the explosive issue of oil drilling in Georges Bank.
</P>
<P>
   Cellucci's pirouette overshadowed efforts by US Rep. William
Delahunt, a Quincy Democrat, to extend Canada's moratorium on oil
and gas drilling on Georges Bank. In Quebec last weekend, Delahunt
won unanimous support from a group of Canadian members of
Parliament for extending the moratorium until 2012.
</P>
<P>
   In part because Cellucci's remarks were so at odds with other
Massachusetts politicians, as well as the state's position, many
observers assumed he had made a mistake when he said there could be
``middle ground'' to allow oil and gas exploration on the bank. But
Cellucci aides initially defended the position, suggesting the
Georges Bank oil and gas could reduce energy costs in New England.
</P>
<P>
   However, the uproar from activists and Massachusetts members of
Congress who oppose oil and gas exploration forced Cellucci to
clarify his views.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not changing public policy . . . He is urging the
Canadian government to extend the moratorium'' on oil and gas
exploration until 2012, Durand said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
