<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-ANALYSIS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHINA TROUBLE: OUT IN THE OPEN AND IN OUR FACES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (w and i coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID M. SHRIBMAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ It has been building, quietly, subtly, for months,
even years, but after Tuesday's congressional report on Chinese
weapons espionage, the conclusion is unavoidable: The United States
is in a full-blown foreign-policy crisis with Beijing.
</P>
<P>
   The report detailing successful Chinese efforts to steal
nuclear-weapons secrets from US laboratories is an implicit
acknowledgement of the difficult relationship state of ties with
China. But it is more than that. Its release also contributes to
the air of crisis that surrounds an increasingly critical
relationship with a nation emerging, just a decade after the
collapse of the Soviet communist bloc, as America's newest
big-power rival.
</P>
<P>
   The stunning findings that China stole classified information on
every currently deployed thermonuclear warhead in the American
intercontinental ballistic missile arsenal prompted angry denials
from China. But the findings also deepened Beijing's suspicions
about Washington even as the American political establishment
adjusts to the uncomfortable notion that an era it thought over _
when world affairs were governed by great power struggles _ may be
back again.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the House committee that concluded China now possesses
stolen classified information on all of the United States' most
advanced thermonuclear weapons, along with many of the rockets
required to launch them, was one of the most devoutly bipartisan
panels on Capitol Hill. The Republicans and Democrats submitted
their findings with the extra punch of a unanimous vote.
</P>
<P>
   Concerns about US relations with China now have spilled over
from the rarefied air of diplomacy into important trade and gritty
domestic political areas.
</P>
<P>
   These frictions affect access to each nation's economic markets.
They endanger China's membership in international trade
organizations. They shape relations between the parties on Capitol
Hill. They sharpen tensions between the Republican Party's
internationalist and isolationist factions.
</P>
<P>
   They also provide ammunition about human rights for both
religious conservatives and traditional liberals. And they could
affect the contours of the next presidential election, especially
the fortunes of Vice President Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   During the 44-year tug of the Cold War between Soviet communism
and Western capitalism _ from World War II until the fall of the
Berlin Wall _ the tensions in domestic policy and foreign policy
became inextricably interwoven. The result was a red scare that
imperiled American civil liberties, an arms race that warped the
economies of both the United States and the Soviet Union and a
climate of tension that chilled domestic politics.
</P>
<P>
   Already there are troubling signs that American domestic and
diplomatic interests are again converging, all the while
heightening rather than dampening tensions with Beijing.
</P>
<P>
   The foreign policy findings in the 700-page report are matched
by domestic-policy worries that China simultaneously sought to
influence the last American presidential election. As China has
sought to bolster its presence in global affairs and to increase
its military firepower, it also has roiled American domestic
affairs by its effort to win trade concessions from the United
States that have incendiary political implications here.
</P>
<P>
   Just Tuesday, the House marked the approaching 10th anniversary
of China's Tiananmen Square crackdown with a 418-0 vote condemning
``ongoing and egregious'' human rights abuses by the Beijing
government. Only last month, American combat jets mistakenly bombed
the Chinese Embassy in Belgrade, prompting anti-US riots in the
streets of the Chinese capital and transforming the tensions
between the two nations into a domestic controversy in China as
well.
</P>
<P>
   Though the findings of the committee provided clear evidence
that the security breaches spanned three decades and four
presidencies, the report provided yet another challenge to the
Clinton administration, which has argued for a policy of engagement
with China in the face of skepticism from both the left and right.
That challenge took the form of criticism from leading Republicans
who Tuesday demanded the resignations of Attorney General Janet
Reno, who rejected FBI requests to wiretap one of the prime
suspects in the spy case, and National Security Adviser Samuel R.
``Sandy'' Berger, who has been under fire for failing to act when
he first learned of the allegations in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, there were mounting signs Tuesday that the China
espionage scandal could provide a new hurdle for Gore, who is
seeking to succeed President Clinton in next year's election.
Former Red Cross president Elizabeth H. Dole, a potential GOP
candidate, spoke of the ``failure of the Clinton-Gore
administration to deal with'' security lapses at national nuclear
laboratories, while publisher Steve Forbes attacked what he called
``the Clinton-Gore administration's national-security policy of
hear no evil, see no evil and speak no evil.''
</P>
<P>
   Texas Governor George W. Bush, another Republican contender,
said the report ``shines a glaring light on the current
administration's failed policies toward China.'' His father was
vice president and then president during 12 of the years in which
the spying supposedly occurred.
</P>
<P>
   The disclosures about the theft of nuclear weapons secrets are
shocking in their own right. Indeed, they prompt comparisons with
Soviet espionage into the development of the hydrogen bomb at
midcentury, when American scientists were forced to conclude that
in developing the H-bomb for the United States, they also were
developing the weapon for our superpower rivals.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's report found that the stolen US nuclear secrets give
China design information on thermonuclear weapons ``on a par with
our own,'' a conclusion that suggests Americans now or in the
future may be at risk of threats from weapons their own scientists
designed. And though the focus of tensions between the two nations
now is primarily over bruised feelings and sensitive domestic
issues, the real danger in the next century may not be the threat
to China relations but the threat to US national security.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
