<SLUG> BC-CANCER-STUDY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSTON CANCER CENTERS TO PARTICIPATE IN BREAST CANCER DRUG STUDY 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By LEIGH HOPPER 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Two Houston cancer centers announced Tuesday that they
are enrolling hundreds of women in a giant experiment to compare a
proven breast cancer prevention drug to one that might work even
better.
</P>
<P>
   The University of Texas M.D. Anderson Cancer Center and St.
Luke's Episcopal Hospital are among 400 centers in the United
States, Canada and Puerto Rico participating in this test _ one of
the largest breast cancer prevention studies to date.
</P>
<P>
   The Study of Tamoxifen and Raloxifene will enroll 22,000
post-menopausal women at increased risk for breast cancer to
determine if one drug is superior to the other.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tamoxifen is a medically proven intervention, but it is not
perfect,'' said Dr. Therese Bevers, principal investigator at M.D.
Anderson. ``Women who are at an increased risk of breast cancer
need options for preventing this disease with a minimum of side
effects, and STAR is a concerted effort to find one.''
</P>
<P>
   M.D. Anderson plans to enroll 400 women, and St. Luke's Texas
Cancer Center 50 to 100 women, in the National Cancer
Institute-supported study.
</P>
<P>
   Tamoxifen and raloxifene belong to a class of drugs called
SERMS, for selective estrogen receptor modulators. They work by
imitating the effects of estrogen in some parts of the body _ for
example its protective effects on bone _ while inhibiting ``bad''
effects, such as stimulating the growth of breast cancer cells.
</P>
<P>
   Tamoxifen was hailed last year as the first pill to prevent
breast cancer, after results from the Breast Cancer Prevention
Trial involving 13,388 women nationwide showed it lowered the
incidence by 49 percent.
</P>
<P>
   But tamoxifen increases a woman's chances of developing
potentially life-threatening health problems: cancer of the uterus
(endometrial cancer), blood clots in the large veins or lungs, and
possibly stroke.
</P>
<P>
   Raloxifene, approved in 1997 to build bones in osteoporosis
patients, has shown exciting potential to fight breast cancer as
well, although studies conducted so far have been too small to
provide definitive conclusions.
</P>
<P>
   In one study of 7,705 women taking raloxifene for osteoporosis,
there was a 70 percent reduction in invasive breast cancer after
two-and-a-half years. An analysis of nine trials showed that
raloxifene was associated with a 55 percent reduction in breast
cancer risk.
</P>
<P>
   Early findings suggest raloxifene doesn't increase risk of
endometrial cancer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Raloxifene may turn out to be a better drug, with fewer
adverse events,'' Bevers said.
</P>
<P>
   Judith Jordan of Magnolia, Texas, who participated in the Breast
Cancer Prevention Trial (and later learned she was taking a
placebo, not tamoxifen), plans to sign up for this experiment as
well. On the practical side, Jordan says she gets better medical
care as a human guinea pig than she does when ``left to my own
devices.''
</P>
<P>
   A stronger motivation stems from the fact that her mother,
grandmother and great-grandmother are all breast cancer survivors.
It was difficult, Jordan said, watching her loved ones struggle
with the disease.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want my daughters-in-law to go through what I went
through,'' said Jordan, 56. ``On the loftier side, I'd like to make
a difference.''
</P>
<P>
   Women who participate in STAR must be at least 35, be
post-menopausal (or have had a hysterectomy), and have an increased
risk of breast cancer. Every woman considering signing up for the
study will have her risk assessed by a computerized program that
takes into account age, family history of breast cancer, age at
first menstrual period and age of giving birth to first child, and
personal medical history.
</P>
<P>
   A special effort will be made to enroll minority women,
traditionally underrepresented in clinical drug trials. Dr. Lisa
Newman, a breast surgeon at M.D. Anderson, is interested in the
disparities in survival rates among ethnic groups.
</P>
<P>
   Many investigators believe ethnicity-related differences in
hormone metabolism may be a factor. But data in that area is
limited: in the Breast Cancer Prevention Trial, only 3 percent of
the participants were minorities, only 1.7 percent blacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before we extrapolate from the tamoxifen study, and apply the
possible benefits of hormonally active agents in chemoprevention in
all women ... we want to know all women of all ethnic backgrounds
can derive these same benefits,'' Newman said.
</P>
<P>
   Women choosing to participate in STAR will be randomly assigned
to take either tamoxifen or raloxifene in pill form daily for five
years.
</P>
<P>
   They will be monitored closely with physical exams and
mammograms. As an added incentive, participants will get free
parking.
</P>
<P>
   Tamoxifen manufacturer Zeneca Pharmaceuticals of Delaware, and
raloxifen-maker Eli Lilly and Co. of Indiana, are providing the
drugs for free. M.D. Anderson is offering financial assistance for
transportation and other miscellaneous expenses so the trial will
be accessible to women of all economic levels.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to make it as easy as possible for women who are
interested to join this study,'' Bevers said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
--------------------------------------- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For information about eligibility for the STAR trial, women may
call M.D. Anderson's ``STAR line'' at 713-792-8064, or St. Luke's
at 713-794-6777. Information is available on the Internet at
www.mdanderson.org.
</P>
<P>
   People interested in clinical trials for cancer may also call
the National Cancer Institute's hot line, 800-4-CANCER.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
