<SLUG> BC-TV-VIOLENCE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO NETWORKS CURTAIL VIOLENT PROGRAMMING 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (e and a coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DON AUCOIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It may not last, but at least for the moment the television
industry appears to have been jolted into a heightened sense of
social responsibility by the massacre one month ago at Columbine
High School in Littleton, Colo.
</P>
<P>
   The WB network decided this week to delay airing the season
finale of ``Buffy the Vampire Slayer'' because it depicted a high
school graduation that explodes into a violent confrontation. CBS,
which had earlier shelved an episode of ``Promised Land'' involving
a shooting in front of a Denver school, took the extra step last
week yanking a much-touted but bloody new drama called ``Falcone''
off its fall schedule.
</P>
<P>
   ``We screened the pilot about a week after Littleton happened,''
CBS Television president Leslie Moonves said Tuesday. ``There were
killings on the boardwalk of New York. We all cringed. At that
moment, it became a noncontender.''
</P>
<P>
   Moonves said Hollywood is buzzing with ``a lot more discussion
than ever before'' about violence. ``It's a question of being
responsible programmers, responsible citizens,'' he added. ``I'm a
big First Amendment guy, and it's very easy to hang your hat on
that, but there's a problem out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Call it the Columbine context: In the wake of the April 20
shootings that left 15 dead and staggered the nation, TV executives
are looking much more closely at the violent content of shows they
put on the air.
</P>
<P>
   Having done its part to saturate the culture with violent
images, television is now on the defensive, as some say the medium
_ along with movies and video games _ should shoulder some of the
blame for episodes of real-life violence. Others suggest network
programmers are overreacting. Pointing to the prevalence of guns
and the weakening of the family structure, they argue that the
entertainment industry is taking the fall for a broader societal
problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone's looking for a scapegoat after Columbine, and
everybody's looking for an answer,'' said Steve Grubbs, a top
executive at BBDO Inc., a New York agency that buys TV time for
advertisers. ``But there is no one single thing to blame here.
There is no one easy answer available.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, it appears that whereas once TV executives might
have rejected criticism of excessive violence in their programs,
they now are listening closely and factoring it into their
decisions _ at least for the time being.
</P>
<P>
   ``Should we be mindful of it? Absolutely,'' Jamie Tarses,
president of ABC Entertainment, said Tuesday. ``Everyone, with good
reason, is overly sensitive to it right now.''
</P>
<P>
   As they make decisions on how much violence is too much,
programmers are again feeling the heat from Washington. A bill was
recently introduced in Congress to ban TV violence completely;
though it failed to pass, it signaled renewed congressional concern
about an issue that has often pitted Capitol Hill against
Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks, President Clinton has used his bully pulpit to
cajole the entertainment industry into handling violence more
responsibly. In a recent radio address, Clinton said that ``too
many vulnerable children . . . are steeped in this culture of
violence'' that makes them more likely to commit crimes, while
``too many creators and purveyors of violence say there is nothing
they can do about it.''
</P>
<P>
   A recent poll by the National Institute on Media and the Family,
conducted before the Columbine High shootings, found that parents
were more worried about the violence their children see on
television than about sexual content of the shows.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond political and public pressure, another possible factor
motivating network executives is that they are anticipating
pressure from advertisers who don't want their products associated
with violent fare in the wake of the recent school shootings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Broadcasters can put two and two together and figure, why give
themselves a headache,'' said Leanne Jenkins, senior vice president
at Hill Holliday Connors Cosmopulos, the second largest ad agency
in New England.
</P>
<P>
   ``Advertisers are always concerned about the environment they're
putting their message in. Network programmers know they're going to
sell the advertising easier if there's less violence,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   However, Jenkins added, many advertisers will still consider a
show's viewership ratings a more important factor than the amount
of violence when choosing which programs to advertise on.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, there are questions about how lasting the TV
industry's current qualms about violence will be. While Moonves
said it is not appropriate now to air ``Falcone,'' he has not ruled
out a spot for it on CBS's midseason schedule in January. As for
the violent graduation episode of ``Buffy the Vampire Slayer,'' the
WB's decision was to delay airing it, not scrap it entirely. The
Fox network has scheduled a program for this fall called ``Harsh
Realm'' that The New York Times said includes ``as heavy a quotient
of violence as any show ever made, though Fox executives have
promised the series will tone the violence down.''
</P>
<P>
   In general, though, the Columbine High massacre seems to have
network executives thinking harder about the possible consequences
of violent imagery, especially among young people.
</P>
<P>
   Jamie Kellner, chief executive of the WB, said in yanking the
``Buffy the Vampire Slayer'' episode that his decision was ``borne
out of a deep sense of responsibility to the WB's loyal young
audience.'' Previously, the WB had also pulled a ``Buffy'' episode
involving a student who was planning a mass murder at the high
school.
</P>
<P>
   In a conference call with TV critics Tuesday, CBS's Moonves said
the current efforts to cut down on violence are similar to the
television industry's agreement to go along with the V-chip and to
affix content ratings on programs (both of which occurred amid
congressional pressure).
</P>
<P>
   Antiviolence efforts are ``something we should work very
proactively toward, as opposed to being defensive,'' Moonves said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We always try to be responsible when it comes to violence,''
he added. ``There is no question the world has become more
heightened to what has happened recently.''
</P>
<P>
   Tarses, of ABC, predicted that fallout from the Colorado
shootings will influence the topics of numerous dramas on the fall
TV schedule. ``I'm sure some of our dramas will be addressing it in
the future season,'' she said. ``There's obviously a lot to say on
this subject.''
</P>
<P>
   Though she did not link it to the Columbine High shootings,
Tarses said a new program by David Lynch, the writer-producer
behind oft-violent fare like the movie ``Blue Velvet'' and the TV
series ``Twin Peaks,'' will not be on ABC's fall schedule.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, in a move that some speculate could be linked to the
climate of concern after Columbine, even the syndicated ``Jerry
Springer Show,'' known for fistfights and general mayhem, has
lately toned down its content.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-25-99 1946EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
