<HEADER>
A0804 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-HAWKS-ANALYSIS-CO     05-25 0882
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-HAWKS-ANALYSIS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hawks analysis: Slow pace never overtaken in series
 &HT;    By Jeffrey Denberg
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Maybe Hawks fans could take solace from being swept by
the Knicks if their team had competed with more urgency. If being
held to ridicule by the New York City crowd and media had fomented
anger. If being blown out had lit a white fire that would burn with
remembrance, driving the Hawks to do better, never to allow such a
thing to happen again.
</P>
<P>
   But that's not the way it is with this bunch.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, the Hawks know they were tired and short-handed in this
series. They would have given a better account of themselves if
injured starters Alan Henderson and LaPhonso Ellis had been able to
play.
</P>
<P>
   It would be better if these Hawks dwelled on how they lost to
the Knicks and on their stoic acceptance of a winless second round.
It would be better still if they asked why they could not play one
good game in Detroit in the first round, allowing the series to be
extended and setting themselves up for the losses to New York. It
would be better still if they engaged in self-examination over
regular-season blowout losses to lottery teams Dallas, Chicago, New
Jersey and Toronto.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Lenny Wilkens long has held the view that there are better
days ahead. ``I want to wring everything out of this season,'' he
once said, ``but next season I think we're really going to be
something.''
</P>
<P>
   His optimism is rooted partly in the four late-first-round draft
picks amassed by Hawks management and a $4.4 million trade
exception that will allow them to bring in an established player.
That the team that goes to training camp in October will be
superior to the one that finished the season is a foregone
conclusion.
</P>
<P>
   But it might not be enough. The town and its hard-core fans want
a spirited team. And this is not a spirited team.
</P>
<P>
   Spirited players are out there. Guard John Starks, a fierce
competitor and a much-needed shooter, comes to mind. He is under
contract to Golden State. The Hawks also must add an effective
backup center quick enough to help at power forward for those
inevitable periods when Alan Henderson is injured. Ferocious
Charles Oakley and Olden Polynice, both free agents, would fit the
bill.
</P>
<P>
   Options for deal-making are plentiful. The Hawks have enough
talent on the roster to spend a player or two to get better. They
also can acquire one or more of the veterans they need through
sign-and-trade deals.
</P>
<P>
   With draft picks at 17, 20, 21 and 27, they will try to trade as
many as three of them because not all of their needs can be filled
with rookies available so late in the first round. And they already
have youth aplenty in Chris Crawford, Johnson, Roshown McLeod and
Ed Gray, although Gray could be traded.
</P>
<P>
   Among other decisions involving existing players, the Hawks must
determine whether Anthony Johnson can improve enough to become the
alternate point guard they require. Plainly, Mookie Blaylock needs
help. He no longer can play 35 minutes a game and remain effective.
The Hawks must have a backup who can step in for a quarter or so
when Blaylock's game falls apart. Johnson has not given evidence
that he is that player.
</P>
<P>
   One move is certain. Each team has a $2 million ``middle-class
exception'' to the salary cap, and the Hawks will extend theirs to
forward Grant Long, who probably will sign a three-year deal after
rescuing his team so often over the regular season and in the first
round.
</P>
<P>
   But as important as it is to supplement the talent pool and hold
onto their indispensible players, the Hawks must transform
themsevles intoa team with a temper. Find one or two members who
confront their mates in the locker room after half-hearted
performances, who challenge shirkers to near-physical
confrontation, who stoke emotions.
</P>
<P>
   It's not like that now. The players walk softly among each
other. What's more, the coaches and the team executives are very
careful with feelings, as though political correctness were the
most important ingredient on a sports team.
</P>
<P>
   What general manager Pete Babcock, chief of scouting Gary
Wortman and Wilkens have assembled is a team with upper-class
values. For the most part, these are rich men who dress
conservatively, keep their tattoos to the minimum, live in
expensive homes and drive prestigious cars and SUVs. Many are
responsible parents, married with families. Basketball is a job for
them, and they never put in more than the required number of hours.
.
</P>
<P>
   And with all the earnest conversation about winning, no veteran
Hawks player wants it so much that he puts hours of extra work into
his game each day, setting an example for his teammates to follow.
</P>
<P>
   So, when the club decides on its off-season moves, that might be
the place to start. The Hawks should consider adding a few players
to whom the normal 6:30 p.m. arrival time before a home game is
inadequate, who show up an hour early to shoot and work on moves,
to think about the assignment that night.
</P>
<P>
   Keep this in mind: Not one Hawks player ever has played on a
championship team.
</P>
<P>
   Jeffrey Denberg writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
