<HEADER>
A0806 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAR-DALEJR-COX     05-25 1036
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-DALEJR-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    DALE EARNHARDT JR.:The son also rises
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CONCORD, N.C. _ Countdown to E-Day'' is at four days and
counting, and Dale Earnhardt Jr. wishes he could climb under the
hood of his No. 8 Chevrolet Monte Carlo and hide.
</P>
<P>
   For months, anticipation has surrounded the preparations for his
Winston Cup debut in Sunday's Coca-Cola 600 at Lowe's Motor
Speedway. In the final week of hysteria, he seems to be drowning.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish I would have enjoyed it more,'' Earnhardt said. ``It
will be gone and past, and I'll look back and say, `Man, I just
didn't know how good I had it.' Just like you do everything else.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish I could go back to high school, because maybe I took it
too seriously. Maybe that's what I'm doing with this, maybe I'm
taking it too seriously. Maybe it's going to be a lot of fun, but I
just don't think it is.''
</P>
<P>
   It hasn't been much fun because all eyes are on Earnhardt Jr.,
the 24-year-old driver many expect to carry NASCAR into the next
millennium. He not only will be under the close scrutiny of his
father, the seven-time Winston Cup champion, but also that of his
legion of fans, who expect him to challenge two-time defending
Winston Cup champion Jeff Gordon _ starting Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anytime anybody makes a comment about the `Countdown to
E-Day,' I correct them and tell them it's a countdown to my first
qualifying attempt,'' Earnhardt Jr. said. ``Because that's what it
is. Everybody knows how difficult it is to make these races.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Earnhardt Jr., that's what most people don't seem
to understand. As a Winston Cup rookie, there are no provisionals
to fall back on if he doesn't have one of the 36 fastest laps in
this week's qualifying on the 1.5-mile oval.
</P>
<P>
   If he doesn't make the race, Earnhardt Jr. knows the price of
failure could be steep. In fact, it could be as catastrophic to his
career as Geraldo Rivera opening Al Capone's vaults.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're expecting me to be in that race,'' Earnhardt Jr. said.
``Nobody's even thought that we might miss it. Know what I'm
saying? But that ain't the way it is.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm under pressure where I have to make the race and hopefully
run good. But what if we run poorly and get blown out of the water
with this whole big promotion? I'm worried about that. Everyone
else won't admit it, but I am. You think about that trying to get
to sleep at night.''
</P>
<P>
   Earnhardt Jr. hasn't had much sleep since he signed a five-year
sponsorship deal last year with Budweiser believed to be worth
around $50 million. The 1998 Busch Grand National champion,
Earnhardt Jr. is running a full-time Busch schedule this year, as
well as five Winston Cup races in a car owned by his father. He'll
jump to Winston Cup full-time next year.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Earnhardt Jr. gave up his life, accepting the role
of can't-miss driver, product spokesman and celebrity. Notoriety
has already taken its toll.
</P>
<P>
   After winning seven races in his first full Busch campaign last
year, Earnhardt Jr. got off to an inauspicious start this year. He
finished 14th and 35th in the first two races and fell to fifth in
points. At that point, Earnhardt says, he took back his life.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't think at all at the race track,'' he said. ``There
was nowhere you could go. The truck was packed. The trailer was
full of people. The lounge was packed full of people. There was
lines standing outside the trailer. There's people crowded around
the race car. There was somebody everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to be a good spokesman for our sponsor, but if we don't
win on the race track, they ain't gonna hang around too long, no
matter how much beer we sell.''
</P>
<P>
   Earnhardt Jr. took over his schedule, trimming back the 77
promotional appearances he was supposed to make between February
and November, so he could spend more time in the race shop. He also
allowed himself a few days a month to get away from racing and
sponsors.
</P>
<P>
   Earnhardt Jr. seems like a breath of fresh air on the circuit, a
driver who won't buckle to corporate pressure and speaks what's on
his mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``When they first announced the Budweiser deal, it got kind of
crazy for a while,'' he said. ``There was a lot of things being
scheduled, and I wasn't finding out about them until the day
before. I don't think we were prepared for it. I didn't feel I had
control.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's worked out because now I'll do any damn thing they want
me to do. I know I've got three days where I can chill, hang out,
get my thoughts together and catch up on paying bills for the
house. It's taken a lot of the pressure off of me.''
</P>
<P>
   Even Jeff Burton, among the sport's most visible drivers, seems
amazed at how well Earnhardt Jr. has handled the pressure.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's out of whack, but that's sports,'' Burton said. ``It's
like that in every sport. But he hasn't been given anything. His
father's been able to help him, but his father made him earn it. I
think everybody respects him for that. Everybody in here had
somebody help them to get where they are. Nobody in here did it on
their own. And a `name' is not going to win you races.''
</P>
<P>
   Even his father, undoubtedly his biggest critic, seems
impressed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The one thing that will get him, the only thing I think that
can bother him, is the same thing that can get Jeff Gordon or
anybody else,'' Earnhardt said, ``and that's burnout from all the
pressure and the things that go along with it.''
</P>
<P>
   THE DALE EARNHARDT JR. FILE
</P>
<P>
   Hometown: Concord, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   Birthdate: Oct. 10, 1974.
</P>
<P>
   Hobbies: Water sports, computers.
</P>
<P>
   Family: Father is former NASCAR Winston Cup champion Dale
Earnhardt.
</P>
<P>
   Accomplishments: Dominated the NASCAR Busch Series
</P>
<P>
   in 1998, winning seven races and earning 16 top-fives and 22 top
10s in 31starts on his way to a championship in his rookie season.
Won six races in a 16-race stretch. Second in Busch points race
this season. Has eight top-10s in 13 starts.
</P>
<P>
   Background: Began career at age 17 in the street-stock division
at Concord Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Schlabach writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
