<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Owners meeting notebook: For price of $800 million, Redskins get
new owner
 &HT;    By Len Pasquarelli
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Bethesda, Md., businessman Daniel M. Snyder was
unanimously approved Tuesday as the new owner of the Washington
Redskins, paying a record $800 million for the franchise. Snyder
overcame his ill-fated partnership with Howard Milstein, who
withdrew his bid in April, to secure the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has been an unbelievable journey,'' said Snyder, 34, whose
partners include several members of his family along with Mort
Zuckerman and Fred Drasner, co-publishers of the New York Daily
News. ``To me, personally, this is a lifelong dream.''
</P>
<P>
   Snyder will retain general manager Charley Casserly and coach
Norv Turner at least for this season, but is expected to eventually
hire a club president to oversee day-to-day activities of the
franchise. Current owner John Kent Cooke failed in his attempts to
buy the team through the trustees appointed by his father, the late
Jack Kent Cooke.
</P>
<P>
   Deion update
</P>
<P>
   Dallas owner Jerry Jones said he is not close to a decision yet
on cornerback Deion Sanders, whose rehabilitation from toe surgery
is expected to take another four to five months. There has been
speculation that the Cowboys will consider releasing Sanders after
June 1 to gain salary cap relief. ``Whatever we do, it will be a
business decision,'' said Jones, who has a strong personal regard
for Sanders. ``But we feel he'll be able to play.'' Sanders has a
salary cap number of $8.2 million and Dallas would realize a $6.5
million rebate if he is released.The fallback guy
</P>
<P>
   Billionaire Marvin Davis, who has flirted several times with the
purchase of pro sports franchises, has signed an option for a land
tract at Hollywood Park. Apparently Davis is attempting to position
himself as an alternative to Michael Ovitz and Eli Broad, both of
whom will bid for the expansion franchise in Los Angeles. The plans
submitted by Ovitz and Broad both call for the refurbishing of the
Los Angeles Coliseum.
</P>
<P>
   Briefly
</P>
<P>
   The four-year deal Georgia offensive tackle Chris Terry signed
with Carolina on Monday is worth $2.86 million over four years. . .
The league will unveil its new instant replay technology to the
owners today. Owners will award Super Bowl XXXVII, with San Diego
expected to get the nod over Miami.
</P>
<P>
   Len Pasquarelli writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
