<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-25 19:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0809 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-OWNERS26-COX     05-25 0550
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-OWNERS26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    So many things to do in L.A.
 &HT;    By Len Pasquarelli
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ They toted scale-model facsimiles of their designs for
refurbishing the Los Angeles Coliseum into the meeting room of an
Atlanta hotel on Tuesday. Both of the groups vying for the NFL's
next expansion franchise displayed high-tech models of what the
historic but crumbling edifice might look like when revamped for
the 2002 season.
</P>
<P>
   The models featured trees one-tenth the size of Bonsais,
mini-practice fields for the new club, luxury suites for the
Hollywood gentry and tiny automobiles tooling along the streets.
Given that the new owner could turn out to be the man who provides
the most on-site parking spots, garages were of varying size and
shape.
</P>
<P>
   Conspicuously absent from both models, however, were the fans in
the stands.
</P>
<P>
   The challenge for real-estate magnate Eli Broad and
entertainment mogul Michael Ovitz, the prominent front men for the
two potential ownership groups, is to win fans back to a market
abandoned by the Rams and Raiders after the 1994 season.
</P>
<P>
   The NFL wants to be back in Los Angeles, an area that could
command the largest franchise fee in league history.
</P>
<P>
   At the league meetings in March, the owners established a Sept.
15 deadline for the city to present a viable and united plan for
returning a franchise there. Although the city of Houston has an
advantage in planning and public financing, Los Angeles is the
coveted spot.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I'm not 100 percent convinced that (the fans will embrace
the NFL again),'' Ovitz said. ``Personally, I think they're pretty
fed up. Those fans there have found other things to do.''
</P>
<P>
   John Semcken, executive vice president for the New Coliseum
Partners, a group headed by Broad and Ed Roski, termed Los Angeles
``a market that hasn't been that successful in the last two
decades,'' and some owners clearly shared that sentiment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure there are some concerns,'' Cleveland Browns president
Carmen Policy said about the nation's second-largest market.
``We've been gone from there a long time now. We not only have to
win back fans, but we also have to create new fans as well.''
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles is ``a very rare place'' because of its diversions,
New Orleans Saints owner Tom Benson said. ``But you've got 16
million people to draw from. If you can't put 70,000 people into a
stadium with that to draw from, you must not be doing things
right.''
</P>
<P>
   Broad and Ovitz cited the need to do things the right way and
creation of a fan-friendly atmosphere. The man who gets the team
might be the one who garners the most civic support _ a critical
component for Ovitz's ambitious parking plan _ and convinces league
owners he can promote their product to a younger and hipper crowd.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the prediction by Oakland Raiders owner Al Davis that
the two might have to combine their efforts, ego probably would
preclude such a marriage.
</P>
<P>
   ``It can be a great market,'' said New England Patriots owner
Bob Kraft, chairman of the finance committee. ``So we need a great
owner with great vision there.''
</P>
<P>
   Len Pasquarelli writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
