<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CINNABON-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    AFC division Cinnabon names chief operating officer
 &HT;    By Shelia M. Poole
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ AFC Enterprises' Bakery Cafe Group said Tuesday that
Barbara Timm-Brock has been named chief operating officer of
Cinnabon Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Timm-Brock was formerly chief product officer. As COO, she will
be responsible for Cinnabon's franchise operations, training,
development services, product management and licensing.
</P>
<P>
   Her appointment ``increases the bench strength of our management
team,'' said Gregg Kaplan, president of AFC's Bakery Cafe Group.
Timm-Brock has extensive experience in the restaurant industry
including stints at Olive Garden and Pizza Hut. She is also
chairman of the Women's Foodservice Forum, an executive leadership
development organization formed to increase the presence of women
in senior-level positions.
</P>
<P>
   Cinnabon, which recently moved its headquarters to Atlanta from
Seattle, has more than 360 locations and 1998 sales of $158
million. AFC Enterprises also owns Churchs Chicken, Popeyes Chicken
&AMP; Biscuits and Seattle's Best Coffee.
</P>
<P>
   Timm-Brock's appointment comes as the AFC division institutes
several changes, including launching a new franchising effort,
expanding its site portfolio, developing a new cafe design and
introducing new products.
</P>
<P>
   Wendy Yurgo, vice president of new business development, said
the company expects to have 1,000 new units, of which 75 percent
will be franchised. The company is also exploring new sites,
including kiosks for colleges and carts for arenas and stadiums.
Cinnabon plans to update its stores, using warmer colors and
improving signs and menus.
</P>
<P>
   Shelia M. Poole writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
