A0811 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CNN-COX     05-25 0444
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CNN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CNN enters alliance with IDG
 &HT;    By Charles Haddad
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ CNN News Group announced Tuesday a $50 million deal to
augment its Internet and computer content, both on air and online,
through an expanded alliance with computer publisher IDG.
</P>
<P>
   The deal calls for Atlanta-based CNN to start a new
consumer-oriented computer show using IDG content and writers. IDG
and CNN would also advertise with each other, and CNN will take an
undisclosed minority stake in IDG.net, the parent company's
Internet unit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly we are looking to expand our relationships across
multimedia platforms,'' said CNN News Group Chairman, President and
Chief Executive Tom Johnson. ``We're in a new world today and we've
got to be prepared to seize opportunities.''
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's deal is the second of its kind for Atlanta-based CNN,
which earlier struck a broad alliance to co-brand health and
medical content with Web site WebMD.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the deal, CNN will air this fall a new 30-minute
weekly computer show on the weekend that will feature IDG content
and journalists. The show will have a consumer spin, with news and
features about electronic gadgets and advances in the Internet and
home computing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Technology news, we have realized, is very important to our
viewership,'' said Rob Tolleson, CNN's vice president for business
opportunities. So is health and medical news, which is why the
company struck the earlier deal with WebMD.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson said his company, which operates five cable TV news
channels, was continually looking for other partnerships. ``We've
been presented with a number of opportunities,'' said Johnson.
``We're looking carefully at what would work best for us.''
</P>
<P>
   IDG is a Boston-based company that publishes, among other
things, the ``PC World'' and ``InfoWeek'' magazines and the
``Dummy'' series of how-to computer books.
</P>
<P>
   IDG and CNN are no strangers, with IDG providing content for the
past year to CNN's Web unit, CNN Interactive. That deal has gone so
well, both companies said, that they decided to expand it.
</P>
<P>
   The CNN TV show represents a big opportunity for IDG, which has
no presence now on television, said Laurie Morgan, president of the
company's Internet operations. IDG's biggest competitor, Ziff
Davis, started a cable TV channel last year devoted to computers
and the Internet. It's called ZDTV and is carried on some cable
systems in metro Atlanta and satellite broadcaster DirecTV.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Haddad writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
