<HEADER>
A0812 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HODEPOT-ENVIRONMENT-C     05-25 0389
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HODEPOT-ENVIRONMENT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Protest at Home Depot
 &HT;    By Patti Bond
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Environmental activists protesting the sale of wood
from old-growth forests plan to face off with Home Depot officials
at the company's annual meeting today.
</P>
<P>
   Several groups, including Greenpeace and the Sierra Club, plan
to demonstrate before the meeting. Inside, a group of shareholders
led by Trillium Asset Management will present a proposal that asks
the company to review sales of so-called old-growth wood and take
steps to stop selling it.
</P>
<P>
   Environmental groups charge that Atlanta-based Home Depot, the
world's largest retailer of building products, sells some wood
products that come from endangered forests in Indonesia, Canada and
the Amazon. The activists say it's the retailer's responsibility to
stop buying old-growth wood from logging companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Home Depot may not be using the actual chainsaw to cut down
these forests, but they're fueling the chainsaw,'' said Michael
Brune of Rainforest Action Network. On Tuesday, about a dozen
protesters representing the San Francisco-based group demonstrated
at the Home Depot on Sidney Marcus Boulevard.
</P>
<P>
   Also on Tuesday, Greenpeace installed a 10,000-square-foot mock
Home Depot logo in a quarter-acre of clear-cut land in British
Columbia. While Rainforest Action Network is focusing on the sale
of old-growth wood, Greenpeace and Sierra Club are protesting Home
Depot for allegedly buying from vendors that clear-cut forests.
</P>
<P>
   Home Depot said it's difficult to track the source of building
materials. ``Forest conservation is an important issue, and we are
working with our vendors and other environmental advisers to better
understand the source of wood and wood products,'' said Suzanne
Apple, Home Depot's vice president of community affairs and
environmental programs.
</P>
<P>
   Apple noted that the retailer works with a third-party certifier
to verify that products live up to environmentally safe claims. For
example, Home Depot sells a mahogany door made from wood that was
either taken from a fallen tree or from a dense forest that needed
to be thinned, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Patti Bond writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution, Atlanta,
Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
