<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-25 19:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0813 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-REFUGEES-U.S.-     05-25 1269
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-REFUGEES-U.S.-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FROM KOSOVO TO `POTATO CITY,' IDAHO, THE HARD WAY
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Idaho, N.J.)   (dal) 
 By DIANA JEAN SCHEMO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOISE, Idaho _ As Mirsade Bejiqi and her family flew from Fort
Dix to their new home here, she braced herself for loneliness and
isolation. Perhaps nobody would bother meeting them, a handful of
near-penniless refugees from Kosovo hurtling toward ``Potato
City,'' as she called Idaho's capital.
</P>
<P>
   How would she find her family's luggage, the 20-year-old Ms.
Bejiqi wondered? Maybe somebody would show up to meet the Bejiqis,
but how would she recognize him?
</P>
<P>
   As it turned out, Boise recognized her. Forty people showed up
at the Boise airport on Thursday night to greet her; her father,
Ajet Bejiqi, a factory worker driven out of Pristina less than two
months ago; her mother, Bukurije, and her three brothers.
</P>
<P>
   Leaders of the Islamic Community Center came out to meet them,
bringing translators, and so did the head of the local refugee
resettlement agency. Rabbi Daniel Fink of Boise's Congregation
Ahavath Beth Israel and his wife, Laura Rappaport, also a rabbi,
who led the push for the synagogue to sponsor some refugees from
Kosovo, were there. The family that was to shelter the Bejiqis for
their first two weeks here _ and chronicle the experience for a
newspaper _ welcomed them along with reporters and television
crews.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was for me, like, amazing,'' said Mirsade Bejiqi, the
eldest of the Bejiqi children and the most proficient in English.
</P>
<P>
   Overnight, it seems, the roughly 4,000 refugees who have landed
at Fort Dix, N.J., in the last few weeks have become emblems of the
Kosovo cause. Resettlement agencies across the country report the
kind of overwhelming outpouring of sympathy for victims of the
Serbian campaign against Albanians in Kosovo that eluded the 78,000
refugees from other wars and slaughters who reached the United
States last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never heard this before from people, this wanting to do
something,'' said Lisa Reeves, director of the Agency for New
Americans, which brought the Bejiqis here. ``We're very excited to
be the first city in America to settle the Kosovars.''
</P>
<P>
   Though more than 700 of the refugees had been settled with
relatives across the United States, the Bejiqis and two families
sent to Seattle and Sarasota, Fla., were the first to leave Fort
Dix to make their way on their own in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we publicly said that we'll receive some families from
Kosovo, people really did start to call,'' Ms. Reeves said. Her
agency has sponsored refugees from Bosnia, Congo, Rwanda and
Russia, and Kurds from Iraq. This year, it is bringing 165 refugees
to this city of 150,000.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the nonprofit groups that resettle refugees in the
United States, accustomed to toiling in obscurity, were astounded
by the flood of interest. Touched by the sight of families trudging
from Kosovo over the mountains to Macedonia and Albania, Americans
began showering resettlement agencies with donations, volunteers
and offers of clothing, jobs, toys and places to stay.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a certain amount of competition out there,'' said
Richard Parkins, national director of the Episcopal Migration
Ministries in New York. ``The reality right now is there will not
be a sufficient number of refugees for all of the groups that want
to be involved in the resettlement.''
</P>
<P>
   Some resettlement officials believe the public has responded so
strongly because the Albanians from Kosovo are seen as victims of a
government with which the United States is at war. Others suggest
that the interest, unlike the lesser concern for black refugees of,
say, Sudan, is racial, although Bosnians, who are also European,
never prompted the same outpouring.
</P>
<P>
   All agree that daily television coverage of Serbian atrocities
has fueled much of the reaction.
</P>
<P>
   The selective sympathy does not go unnoticed by less-cared-for
refugees of other conflicts.
</P>
<P>
   Bashkim Selace, 29, a chip maker for Micron Technology, fled to
the United States from Albania in 1988. Eager to help the Kosovo
refugees, he went to the Boise airport to translate for the Bejiqis
but could not help remembering his own landing in Boise. One man
sponsored him, putting him alone with three other Albanian
newcomers in an apartment.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was not quite a warm welcome,'' Selace said, ``even though
the guy tried. He did his best, but it wasn't anything like what
the refugees now are receiving.''
</P>
<P>
   The people Selace met in his new home knew nothing of his ordeal
to flee communism by crossing the mountains into Yugoslavia. ``Most
people didn't even know where Albania was,'' Selace recalled.
``They thought I meant Alabama.''
</P>
<P>
   Azad Abdullah, 22, fled Iraq 11 years ago, after Saddam Hussein
killed 50,000 Kurds there with mustard gas. Before coming to the
United States by way of Guam, he spent five years in Turkish
refugee camps, where he said the authorities would shoot and
sometimes kill refugees.
</P>
<P>
   In Kosovo, ``everybody knows what's going on,'' Abdullah said.
``It's a hard story, a tragedy. But I feel like we've been through
more, but we were not advertised.''
</P>
<P>
   For Boise, being among the first cities in America to embrace
its own Albanian refugee family was a milestone.
</P>
<P>
   Notwithstanding the Aryan Nation and other extremist groups
living in the mountains of Idaho, Boise's leadership wants to shed
its image as an insular, parochial place. Businesses like Micron
Technology and Hewlett-Packard have begun a campaign to broaden
people's attitudes about foreign cultures, many of which are
finding a home in Boise.
</P>
<P>
   Abdul Yunis, a Pakistani manager at Hewlett-Packard who heads
the city's Islamic Community Center, said, ``They're finding they
can create a very tolerant and welcoming environment in the
company, and recruit people from all over, but employees still have
to deal with what's out there when they walk out the door at the
end of the day.''
</P>
<P>
   Along the highways, billboards for Christianity warn motorists
that it is the only avenue to heaven. Yunis figures whoever put up
the signs had not thought about how they looked to Boise's few
thousand Muslims and Jews.
</P>
<P>
   The city is already home to 1,000 or so Bosnian refugees.
Unemployment here is low and housing is affordable. Because of low
interest rates and a first-time homebuyer's program, scores of
Bosnian refugees have bought houses for roughly the same amount
they had been paying in rent.
</P>
<P>
   Ajet Bejiqi, 45, said his first priority was to learn English
and find a job. This week, resettlement workers will test the
Bejiqis' English and help them apply for medical benefits, food
stamps and cash assistance.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, the family has been settling in, with members
of Congregation Ahavath Beth Israel taking the Bejiqis on a retreat
in the mountains over the weekend and to Ponderosa State Park.
</P>
<P>
   The family seemed grateful for the attention and warmth, but
ached for the friends they had made on their journey from Kosovo.
``I need to thank these people,'' Mirsade Bejiqi said, ``but they
are not so close to me. I love my people more than anyone in the
world.''
</P>
<P>
   Ajet Bejiqi said he had been struck by how much Boise looked
like Pristina. But as he prepared to begin a new life, the home he
lost felt more distant than ever. ``Spiritually, Kosovo is very far
away now,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Mirsade Bejiqi offered advice for other refugees expected to
follow them to Boise: ``Forget all the bad things. Start a new life
here. And whenever it's better, we'll go back.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
