A0815 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDITORIAL-TVCOPS-BOS &LR;      05-25 0369
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-TVCOPS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUSPECT JOURNALISM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Many of the media excesses that have been widely criticized
recently _ such as the sensationalized coverage of the Colorado
school shootings and the pack harassment of Monica Lewinsky _ are
best remedied by the market of free opinion rather than tight
regulations that might impinge on important First Amendment rights.
</P>
<P>
   But the Supreme Court has shown good sense in barring a
particular excess that has nothing to do with free speech or
legitimate news gathering.
</P>
<P>
   This is the practice of reporters accompanying police on raids
and bursting into private homes or apartments as the lawmen
confront, search, and sometimes arrest the inhabitants.
</P>
<P>
   Since surprise can be a key component of such raids, cameras
often capture dramatic images. Video footage from police raids has
become a staple of popular ``real life'' TV shows portraying police
at work. These shows are essentially entertainment with little news
value.
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court decision dwelt not on how the material is used
but on the distinction between public and private property. Law
enforcement personnel cannot burst into a private dwelling unless
they have a search warrant or specific circumstances require it.
News organizations can operate unfettered in public spaces but have
no right to invade private property and cannot acquire the right
secondhand from the police.
</P>
<P>
   The consequences can be oppressive. In one of the cases the
Supreme Court decided this week, a Maryland couple's home was
raided early one morning while the husband was in his undershorts
and the wife in a nightgown. The police wrestled the man to the
floor and put a gun to his head. They were seeking the couple's
son, who was not at home but turned himself in later. A Washington
Post reporter and photographer accompanied the police. The Post, to
its credit, didn't run pictures. But the court said that in the
future, the police could be held liable for inviting the media in.
</P>
<P>
   Press freedoms should be robust, but not so bloated as to
violate personal property rights and damage the press's own
credibility.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-25-99 1953EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
