A0817 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDITORIAL-SPYING-BOS &LR;      05-25 0334
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-SPYING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ASSESSING THE SPYING SCANDAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It is an unpleasant fact of life that many countries, friend and
foe alike, are continually seeking to ferret out America's
technological and nuclear secrets.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of China, the revelations and recommendations of a
House select committee investigating the theft of US nuclear
weapons information suggest that the old maxim ``better safe than
sorry'' has been woefully ignored.
</P>
<P>
   The report identifies some of the ways China procured
information; discloses a pattern of laxity in protecting it; and
leaves no doubt that the fault lies with US authorities when a
foreign country succeeds in stealing secrets of value.
</P>
<P>
   China's pursuit of nuclear weapons data, the committee found,
took a ``mosaic'' approach, combining some traditional espionage
methods with a painstaking accumulation of disparate pieces of
information from scientific exchanges and open sources. All the
diverse bits of material were then pieced together in China.
</P>
<P>
   The result was not to bestow on China a nuclear weapons
capability that the country could not have acquired on its own, the
report found, but rather to permit Beijing to modernize its small
nuclear arsenal more cheaply and ``sooner than would otherwise have
been possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Although China's espionage went undetected through the
administrations of Jimmy Carter, Ronald Reagan, and George Bush,
the Clinton administration has an obligation to explain its
dilatory response to warnings it received concerning Chinese spying
as early as 1995 and '96.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney General Janet Reno, who has displayed stunning lapses
of judgment in the past, needs to explain why she rejected FBI
requests for wiretapping authority in the investigations.
</P>
<P>
   Above all, the United States must maintain an even keel in its
crucial relationship with Beijing, avoiding a breakdown but
refusing to be treated as a patsy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-25-99 1955EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990525.0287 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-25 19:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0818 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MORALES-TEXAS-HNS &LR;      05-25 0846
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MORALES-TEXAS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONFLICTING ACCOUNTS GIVEN IN TOBACCO FEE FIGHT 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CLAY ROBISON 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Dan Morales and a former top aide have offered
conflicting accounts of why the former assistant quit the state's
anti-tobacco lawsuit after signing a contract with Morales.
</P>
<P>
   The contract is central to Texas Attorney General John Cornyn's
allegations that Morales, the former attorney general, tried to
fraudulently secure $260 million in legal fees for a friend,
Houston attorney Marc Murr, in the tobacco case.
</P>
<P>
   Morales told a national arbitration panel that set legal fees
that Will Pryor, his former top assistant, dropped out of a Jan.
31, 1997, contract with him and Murr because Pryor couldn't meet a
financial commitment to help pay for the lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   But Pryor says he quit the case because it soon became obvious
that he wouldn't have much work to do. He said he also was
concerned that his former employment with Morales could raise
questions about the potentially lucrative contract.
</P>
<P>
   ``From my perspective, it really didn't have anything to do with
financial considerations,'' Pryor said Tuesday. He said he
consulted with Morales a few times after signing the contract but
soon dropped out because ``my involvement wasn't necessary. In any
meaningful sense, I really wasn't doing anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Pryor, in a recent letter to Cornyn, said he was surprised
months later when Morales told him that Murr had signed a separate
contract. ``But what services Marc actually provided, or did not
provide, is something I have no knowledge of,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Pryor was Morales' top assistant during most of the Democrat's
first term as attorney general from 1991-94. He was an
attorney-mediator in private practice in Dallas by the time Morales
asked him to help represent the state in the tobacco suit.
</P>
<P>
   Cornyn, who succeeded Morales on Jan. 1, has accused his
predecessor of using some signatures from the contract with Pryor
and Murr to fabricate a separate contract with Murr alone that
carries the same 1997 date. Cornyn contends the fake contract was
created much later but was backdated to bolster Murr's claim for
fees.
</P>
<P>
   The Murr-Pryor contract called for the two to share a 6 percent
contingency fee; the document with Murr alone specified simply a
``reasonable fee.''
</P>
<P>
   In his letter to Cornyn, Pryor said that Morales told him and
Murr that adding them to the tobacco suit would serve as a
``helpful reminder'' to the state's five other tobacco lawyers that
Morales was in charge.
 &UR;  &LR; ``Dan was becoming increasingly apprehensive that the `trial team'
of very prominent and successful trial lawyers could successfully
be `reined in,''' Pryor recalled.
</P>
<P>
   Other lawyers have contended that Murr did little work on the
suit, while Morales has insisted that Murr played a crucial role,
often as a behind-the-scenes adviser.
</P>
<P>
   According to an affidavit recently obtained by the Chronicle,
Morales told the national arbitrators in a closed-door meeting in
New York that Pryor had to drop out because he couldn't afford to
join other outside lawyers in financing the suit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Pryor was not able to make the financial commitment in
time, so we just stuck with the individual contract for Mr. Murr,''
Morales said in the Dec. 5 meeting, where he testified on Murr's
behalf just a few weeks before leaving office.
</P>
<P>
   Each of five other outside lawyers _ a group headed by Walter
Umphrey of Beaumont _ was required to spend $2 million in up-front
costs. They said they spent more than that but were reimbursed by
tobacco companies after the suit was settled.
</P>
<P>
   Morales told the national arbitrators that Murr was prepared to
contribute $2 million but never was asked to do so.
</P>
<P>
   Pryor said Tuesday that Morales initially proposed a contract
similar to the Umphrey group's but that he told Morales early on
that he couldn't afford to put up $2 million, so the contract was
changed to reflect that.
</P>
<P>
   In an April 12 letter to Cornyn's office, which followed the
attorney general's questioning of Pryor as part of the
investigation into the Murr contract, Pryor said he realized some
weeks or months after signing the contract that ``active,
meaningful participation in the litigation was simply not to be.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``I was concerned about the appearance of impropriety
that some would perceive, once the contract became public
knowledge, because of my relationship with Dan, especially if I was
not as active or involved in the litigation as had been
contemplated.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Murr recently withdrew his claim against the state for
some $260 million in legal fees, he still is to receive $1 million
from cigarette makers under a separate, national arbitration award
entered in December. The national arbitrators awarded $3.3 billion
to the Umphrey team of five outside lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Murr's involvement is still being investigated by the
FBI, according to Cornyn. Murr has repeatedly refused comment.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
