<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-25 19:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0823 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-US-CHINA-CLINTON26-CO     05-25 0938
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-US-CHINA-CLINTON26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CLINTON PLEDGES TIGHTER NUCLEAR SECURITY, CONTINUED CHINA TIES
 &HT;    With US-CHINA.
 &HT;    By JULIA MALONE
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton, responding to a congressional
report on decades of Chinese spying at American weapons labs,
pledged Tuesday to tighten security but also urged keeping close
ties with China.
</P>
<P>
   Members of Congress said the report showed the administration
was to blame for reacting slowly to the espionage, and said the
spying could be continuing.
</P>
<P>
   After months of White House damage-control efforts in
anticipation of the House Select Committee report, the president
paused only briefly during a campaign-style event in Edinburg,
Texas, to respond to it. He welcomed most of its recommendations,
even as his aides were quietly discouraging proposals for stringent
new laws to restrict trade with China.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like many other countries, China seeks to acquire our
sensitive information and technology,'' the president said, without
acknowledging any specific security losses. ``We have a solemn
obligation to protect such national security information, and we
have to do more to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Energy Secretary Bill Richardson, whose department oversees the
national weapons laboratories, asserted at a news conference later
that lax security going back to the 1970s has been mostly
corrected.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're fixing the problem, we're addressing the concerns of the
Congress, and it's important that the American people know that
their nuclear secrets, right at this moment, now, are safe,''
Richardson said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite administration efforts to smooth over the controversy,
Republicans in Congress served notice that the issue was far from
resolved.
</P>
<P>
   House Majority Leader Dick Armey, R-Texas, called on Clinton's
national security adviser, Sandy Berger, to resign for failing to
sound the alarm bell when he first learned of stolen missile
warhead technology in April 1996. Berger has told Congress that he
did not brief the president on the problem until the next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sandy Berger has failed in his duty to the administration and
the American people, and I think he ought to accept his
responsibility,'' Armey said.
</P>
<P>
   White House spokesman Jim Kennedy said Tuesday, ``The president
has full confidence in Sandy Berger, and we would take strong
objection to anything to the contrary.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Bob Barr, R-Ga., perhaps the most outspoken critic of the
president in Congress, came close to accusing the Clinton
administration of treasonous inaction after the discoveries of
stolen secrets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Instead of responding to this information with swift
counterintelligence action and prompt public disclosure, the White
House has dragged its feet and stonewalled at every available
opportunity,'' Barr said. ``After reading this report, one is left
with the distinct impression that the Clinton administration wanted
China's espionage efforts to succeed.''
</P>
<P>
   In more measured comments, Rep. Christopher Cox, R-Calif., the
chairman of the select committee, cast doubts on claims that the
problem has been fixed. After listening to the administration's
response, Cox said on CNN that the Energy Department's top security
official, Edward Curran, had testified earlier this year that the
department would not be spy-proof until next year.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Cox report was approved unanimously by his panel,
members of Congress divided over the severity of the problem. Some
Democrats tried to spread the blame by pointing out that the spying
extended to the Republican administrations of Ronald Reagan and
George Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``Could we have done better? Absolutely,'' said Senate Minority
Leader Tom Daschle, D-S.D., adding that ``this has been around for
a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic leader said that the Clinton administration, ``in
contrast to Reagan and Bush, chose to do something about it.''
</P>
<P>
   That remark drew a rejoinder from Jim Nicholson, chairman of the
Republican National Committee, who noted that the Cox report traced
the espionage to President Jimmy Carter's Democratic administration
during the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   ``Had Senator Daschle taken the time to read the Cox Committee
Report, he'd also know that it was the Clinton administration _ not
the Carter, Reagan or Bush administrations _ that was made aware of
this breathtaking program of Communist Chinese espionage,''
Nicholson said, citing the report's finding that the spying was
first discovered and reported internally in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Among Democrats who expressed concerns about the report, Sen.
Max Cleland of Georgia, a member of the Senate Armed Services
Committee, called the revelations ``the most serious breach of our
national security in a decade'' and a ``flaw in our national
security operations'' that must be repaired quickly.
</P>
<P>
   While Clinton praised the bipartisanship of the Cox committee,
it was far from clear how far the White House would go along on the
remedies.
</P>
<P>
   White House spokesman Kennedy said that the administration
remained committed to pushing for China's stalled membership in the
World Trade Organization, and he added the president would resist
most legislation proposed by the Cox report to tighten restrictions
on exporting high technology to China.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't think it's necessary'' to pass new laws, Kennedy said
of plans for tougher regulations the sale of high-performance
computers and satellites. He said that the president had the
authority to tighten security procedures without new mandates from
Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
