   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-SPYING (Washington) _ Rep. Christopher Cox, R-Calif., the
head of a House committee investigating allegations of espionage by
China, releases a report saying that it is likely that Chinese
spies continue to infiltrate America's most coveted nuclear
secrets. By JOHN C. HENRY.
</P>
<P>
   SPYING-POLITICS (Washington) _ A House report saying China
pilfered nuclear secrets has become an issue in the presidential
campaign. Texas Gov. George W. Bush, the Republican front-runner,
cites the report in attacking the Clinton administration's ``failed
policies toward China.'' Aides to Vice President Al Gore, the
Democratic front-runner, insist that steps have been taken to plug
leaks. By ERIC ROSENBERG. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   CUSTOMS-CORRUPTION (Washington) _ Reports of bribery and other
allegations of wrongdoing by U.S. Customs Service personnel tripled
between 1996 and 1998, according to a Senate analysis that ranks
Miami and two Texas cities, El Paso and McAllen, as the top places
for complaints. By GARY MARTIN. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   IMMIGRATION-REACTION (Washington) _ We gauge reaction to Vice
President Al Gore's announcement in Texas that legal immigrants no
longer need fear that application for safety-net programs will lead
to deportation. By STEVE LASH.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CANADA-TEXAS (Austin, Texas) _ Members of the Canadian
Parliament protest at the Texas Capitol over the pending execution
of death row inmate Joseph Stanley Faulder. Faulder, 61, is
scheduled to die by lethal injection June 17 for the fatal beating
and stabbing of Inez Phillips, 75, during a July 1975 robbery. If
the execution is carried out, Faulder will become the first
Canadian executed in the United States since 1952. Canada has no
death penalty. By JAMIE STOCKWELL.
</P>
<P>
   CALIF-PESTICIDES (San Francisco) _ More than 25 years after
regulators banned DDT for harming wildlife, pesticides continue to
kill birds and fish, interfere with their reproduction and threaten
the very survival of many species, according to a study by
advocates of pesticide controls. By JANE KAY. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   MORALES-TEXAS (Austin, Texas) _ Former state Attorney General
Dan Morales and a former top aide are offering conflicting accounts
of why the former assistant quit the state's anti-tobacco lawsuit
after signing a contract with Morales. The contract is central to
allegations that Morales tried to fraudulently secure $260 million
in legal fees for a friend. By CLAY ROBISON. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   CANCER-STUDY (Houston) _ Two cancer centers here announce they
are enrolling hundreds of women in a giant experiment to compare
one proven breast cancer prevention drug to one that might work
even better. It will be one of the biggest breast cancer studies to
date. By LEIGH HOPPER. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BBN-ASTROS (Houston) _ Mike Hampton will be going for his sixth
consecutive victory against former teammate Darryl Kile as the
Houston Astros play host to the Colorado Rockies in a 7:05 p.m. CDT
game at the Astrodome. By JOSEPH DUARTE.
</P>
