<HEADLINE>
MIR TO STAY ALOFT THROUGH FEBRUARY, SAYS RUSSIAN OFFICIAL 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By MARK CARREAU 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. _ Their own deadlines seem to come and go,
and still Russia seems no more definite over what it intends to do
with its more than 13-year-old Mir space station.
</P>
<P>
   A top Russian Space Agency official said Tuesday that Mir will
remain aloft at least through February, though government funding
will cease at the end of August.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought Americans were very practical people,'' said Boris
Ostroumov, deputy director general of the Russian Space Agency.
``It simply does not make too much sense to get rid of such a
treasure.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, the Russians suggested Mir was safe only
through August, though it was hopeful that private funding sources
might come forward with money for another year or two of
operations. The deadline then was April, a date that came and went.
</P>
<P>
   Mir's fate is significant only in that the funds it takes to
keep the outpost flying, as much as $250 million or as little as
$100 million annually by various estimates, is money that is not
available to the cash-strapped Russian government to meet its
obligations to the new international space station. Russian
financial lapses have already produced a 19-month delay in the
launching of the new station's initial crew compartment, the
service module. The United States is hopeful that it can be
launched by late November.
</P>
<P>
   Mir's current crew of cosmonauts Viktor Afanasyev and Sergei
Avdeyev and French researcher Jean-Pierre Haignere is to return to
Earth in August. However, the cosmonauts could be replaced by
another crew, or the Russians could decide to leave Mir unstaffed
until it reaches a decision.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, Mir's orbit was boosted sufficiently to keep it flying
until the end of next February without further staffing, Ostroumov
said.
</P>
<P>
   The official was guarded in his comments about Russian prospects
for a private investment that would keep Mir flying. According to
news accounts in that country, Peter Llewellyn, a 51-year-old
British businessman, has agreed to pay the Russians $100 million
for an opportunity to fly to Mir. However, the reports say his
strategy is to raise the funds from others as part of a scheme to
build a hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Despite his allegiance to Mir, Ostroumov took pains Tuesday to
echo recent comments by Russian President Boris Yeltsin that his
country will keep its commitments to the new international station.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all understand that we cannot support two programs at the
same time,'' Ostroumov said. ``No matter how badly we could feel
about that, we would have to say good-bye to the Mir station.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever money will be allocated in the future, these funds
will be utilized entirely for the purpose of the international
space station,'' the Russian official said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, forecasters offered a slightly improved forecast for
the launch of the shuttle Discovery at 6:48 a.m. EDT Thursday from
Florida.
</P>
<P>
   There is a slight chance of thunderstorms near the coastal
launch complex.
</P>
<P>
   The shuttle's seven-member crew, led by commander Kent Rominger,
plans to dock with the first two components of the new
international station.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
