<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-25 20:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0843 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-LOUIMA-BOS &LR;      05-25 1239
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-LOUIMA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLICEMAN ADMITS TORTURING ARRESTED HAITIAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRED KAPLAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK -- Justin Volpe, the police officer whose torture of a
Haitian immigrant shook this city to its racially riven core two
summers ago, stood before a federal judge Tuesday, shaking a bit
himself and wiping the sweat from the brow.
</P>
<P>
   His lawyer had stirred a storm on Monday by announcing, three
weeks into his trial, that Volpe _ who had, all along, insisted on
his innocence _ would now plead guilty to his crimes and thus face
the possibility of life in federal prison.
</P>
<P>
   The switch followed an extraordinarily damaging week in which
four of Volpe's colleagues broke down the ``blue wall of silence''
and testified against him.
</P>
<P>
   And so, at 11 Tuesday morning, the burly, once-brash 27-year-old
officer described in his own words what happened in the wee hours
of Aug. 9, 1997, when he arrested Abner Louima during a brawl
outside a Brooklyn nightclub and took him back to the 70th precinct
stationhouse.
</P>
<P>
   In the middle of his prepared statement, Volpe, reading quietly,
nervously, taking frequent deep breaths, uttered the key sentence:
``While in the bathroom at the stationhouse, in the presence of
another officer, I sodomized Mr. Louima by placing a stick in his
rectum.''
</P>
<P>
   He also admitted warning Louima, ``If you tell anybody, I'll
find you and I'll kill you.''
</P>
<P>
   When news of this torture broke two years ago, it unleashed
racial tensions pent up in this multi-cultural city for over a
decade. It deeply bruised the image of the city's police department
_ which, at the time, was enjoying the public relations bonanza of
a dramatic reduction in crime. And, to a degree unmatched until
last summer's police scandal _ when four officers fired 41 bullets
at another unarmed black immigrant, Amadou Diallo _ it tarnished
Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, who had built an international reputation
as a crimefighter.
</P>
<P>
   The details of the bathroom torture _ Volpe shoving a stick up
Louima's rectum, then bashing it against his teeth, while other
officers assisted or stayed mum _ had long been known to everyone
in the courtroom.
</P>
<P>
   But as Rev. Al Sharpton, who has led many protest marches on
Louima's behalf, said after Tuesday's courtroom hearing, it was ``a
chilling experience to sit and listen to this man, in his own
words, tell the story.''
</P>
<P>
   In all, Volpe pleaded guilty to six felonies, including assault,
conspiracy, violating Louima's civil rights, and obstructing
justice. A conspiracy charge was dropped.
</P>
<P>
   At the hearing's end, Volpe, the son of a highly decorated
retired detective, said, ``If I could just let the record reflect,
I'm sorry for hurting my family'' _ but extended no apologies to
Louima.
</P>
<P>
   Then, federal marshals took Volpe to jail, where he will be held
without bail until his formal sentencing.
</P>
<P>
   The most severe of his crimes carries a maximum punishment of
life in prison. His lawyer, Marvyn Kornberg, guessed Tuesday he
would be sentenced to ``probably 30 years or more.''
</P>
<P>
   The US attorney heading the prosecution, Zachary Carter,
emphasized, ``There was no deal'' involved in the guilty plea.
</P>
<P>
   Four other policemen _ who are charged with taking part in, or
covering up, the crime _ remain on trial. The jury, which was not
in the courtroom during Volpe's confession, will resume hearing
evidence against them Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the federal courthouse in Brooklyn Tuesday, Louima's
supporters expressed a mix of exuberance and caution.
</P>
<P>
   Sharpton proclaimed, ``Because of this, we get to see what it
looks like for justice to come our way, to some degree.''
</P>
<P>
   However, the civil rights activist said full justice would not
be served until Volpe identifies the other guilty officers.
</P>
<P>
   ``How can you plead guilty to a conspiracy and not name the
co-conspirators?'' Sharpton said. ``We don't want just Volpe. We
want all these policemen to face justice.''
</P>
<P>
   In his statement, Volpe said the ``other officer'' in the
bathroom ``saw what was going on'' and ``did nothing to stop it.''
He did not name the officer, but the remark opened up the
possibility that he could be called to elaborate as a witness for
the prosecution.
</P>
<P>
   Kornberg told reporters his client cannot be compelled to
testify, on Fifth Amendment grounds _ but added that Volpe ``will
obey any subpoena he receives.'' Though the lawyer did not say so,
he can be expected to try to dangle such cooperation in exchange
for a sentence shorter than life.
</P>
<P>
   One of the other officers on trial, Charles Schwarz, 33, is
charged with holding Louima down during Volpe's assault. His
lawyer, Stephen Worth, told reporters outside the courthouse that
Schwarz would maintain his plea of innocence, saying, ``My client
was not in the bathroom.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Worth said he was ``obviously concerned'' about what
the jurors would think when they return to the courtroom and see
that Volpe is no longer sitting at the defendants' table.
</P>
<P>
   US District Court Judge Eugene Nickerson will instruct the
jurors Wednesday on how to regard Volpe's absence.
</P>
<P>
   John Patten, the lawyer for another of the defendants, Sgt.
Michael Bellomo, said he would move for a mistrial, arguing that
the jurors would conclude Volpe had pleaded guilty, which would
prejudice them against not only his own client but all those still
accused.
</P>
<P>
   Bellomo, 37, is charged with covering up Louima's beating and
conspiring in the false arrest of Patrick Antoine, another Haitian
who was arrested _ but not tortured _ along with Louima.
</P>
<P>
   The other policemen still on trial, besides Schwarz and Bellomo,
are Officers Thomas Bruder, 33, and Thomas Wiese, 35, both accused
of violating Louima's civil rights by beating him up in a patrol
car on the way to the stationhouse.
</P>
<P>
   The turning point for Volpe came last week, when four police
officers came forth and testified against him. The case-closers
were Sgt. Kenneth Wernick, who said Volpe had bragged to him about
shoving a stick up Louima's rectum, and Officer Michael Schoer, who
said Volpe had shown him the excrement-smeared stick.
</P>
<P>
   Kornberg declined to cross-examine both officers. The lawyer,
who also represents one of the officers in the Diallo case, told
reporters Tuesday, explaining Volpe's sudden guilty plea, ``There
came a point in time when the evidence became overwhelming.''
</P>
<P>
   The surprise witnesses have been hailed by many observers,
including Mayor Giuliani, for bravely tearing down the ``blue wall
of silence'' _ the informal code against snitching on a fellow
officer.
</P>
<P>
   However, Ernie Adams, head of the organization 100 Blacks in Law
Enforcement, dismissed this notion Tuesday, saying the witnesses
should have come forward more than two years ago, when the crimes
were committed.
</P>
<P>
   In his statement to the judge, Volpe said he committed his act
because he mistook Louima for a man who had punched him during the
nightclub brawl where the arrest took place. ``I was mad,'' Volpe
explained.
</P>
<P>
   It was later revealed that Louima's cousin had hit Volpe.
Louima, at the time a security officer who had no criminal record,
suffered extensive internal injuries from Volpe's assault and
underwent several surgeries. He has hired Johnnie Cochran to
represent him in a civil suit against the city. Cochran is also
representing Amadou Diallo's family in a similar suit.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
