<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-MARLO-THOMAS-$ADV30-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEMINISM'S UNLIKELY HEROINE  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MAY 30) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By PETER M. NICHOLS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Auditioning for a soap commercial, the aspiring actress Ann
Marie, played by Marlo Thomas, is told by an executive that she has
the look of ``every mother's child.'' That's enough to wipe the
well-scrubbed, firmly fixed smile off the face of a young woman
trying her hardest to be anything but.
</P>
<P>
   What, she wonders to herself, happened to sex appeal? Sex, it
seems, is the last thing the man wants associated with his product,
though later he forces his attentions on her after inviting himself
into her apartment.
</P>
<P>
   Ann was forever enmeshed in that kind of situation in ``That
Girl,'' the ABC comedy that from 1966 to 1971 ever so judiciously
entertained the notion that an unattached woman in her 20s might
have the urge and the right to lead a life of her own.
</P>
<P>
   As is apparent in nine episodes of the show now on video from
Anchor Bay, those were deep waters in 1966.
</P>
<P>
   ``If women were single, they were `Our Miss Brooks,''' Ms.
Thomas said the other day, referring to the 1950s series in which
Eve Arden played a wisecracking high school English teacher (who
rented a room in an elderly woman's house, rather than really
living on her own). ``That Girl'' was Ms. Thomas's idea.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to do a show about a young woman who lived in her own
apartment, trying to make it, not divorced from her family, but
who, like most young girls at that time and today, still was
related to her parents but not programmed by them.''
</P>
<P>
   As reasonable as that sounds, this was a show that truly had to
watch its step. ``The networks were terrified of it,'' Ms. Thomas
said. Eventually ABC bought the idea, but, she added, ``they wanted
Ann to be the daughter of someone or the secretary of someone,
ideas I didn't like.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `Isn't there a show where I can just be the somebody,
not an offshoot of the other person?'''
</P>
<P>
   In the series, Ann lives alone in New York and supports herself
with a variety of jobs while trying out for parts that with the
exception of gigs as dancing chickens and the like in commercials
always elude her. In the meantime she tries to stay on loving but
equal footing with men.
</P>
<P>
   Her fretful parents, watching from their suburban lair,
seemingly bear the burden of a nation reluctantly embarked on a
great social experiment. Ann, in fact, is very much someone's
daughter.
</P>
<P>
   Lou Marie (Lew Parker), a well-meaning father but a dithering
worrywart, is forever descending on his little girl to monitor her
affairs. Needless to say, Lou is on especially high alert when
Ann's boyfriend, Donald (Ted Bessell, who died at 57 in 1996), is
around and is practically apoplectic anytime Donald is detected
actually alone with Ann in her apartment.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest constraint was sexual,'' Ms. Thomas said. ``I got
away with the feminist view that I didn't want to get married; I
must have said that 27 times on that show. I could have a
boyfriend. I could have him home for dinner. But you couldn't have
any sexual contact. It must never appear that Donald spent the
night.''
</P>
<P>
   Kept on tenterhooks as to just how he was supposed to behave,
Donald stays every inch the cheerful, buttoned-down, fully clothed
paragon. But then this was Ann's show. For all her thoughts of
freedom, though, the leash was short. If she was to be allowed her
little foibles, she could at least stay well dressed, bouncy and
upbeat.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Thomas said that for her, some of the show's best moments
were off camera. ``The amazing thing is that the first night we
went on the air we were a huge hit with the public,'' she said.
``We got a phenomenal amount of mail. Every young girl in America
wanted to be `that girl.' They'd write in and say: `I'm 17 and
pregnant and I can't tell my parents. Where do I go?' Married women
in their 20s who were unhappy would say, `Don't marry Donald.'
Women would write and say: `My husband beats me up. Where do I
go?'''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Thomas and her assistants tried to help. ``What I kept
finding was that there was nowhere for them to go,'' she said. ``It
totally politicized me as a feminist.'' She met Gloria Steinem and
began traveling the country for the cause.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the show, of course, the real world was exploding in
political and sexual revolt. The Vietnam War worsened; the
Democratic Convention erupted in Chicago; students fell at Kent
State. But on the air, Ann Marie bore up as perkily as ever.
</P>
<P>
   ``We stuck to the life of a young woman trying to make it on her
own,'' said Ms. Thomas, who is 55 and still acts occasionally in
films. ``We were an Audrey Hepburn movie, not a Jane Fonda movie.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-25-99 2014EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
