A0852 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AVERY-FISHER-PRIZE-$A     05-25 0945
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AVERY-FISHER-PRIZE-$ADV30-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OLYMPIANS WITH LESSONS TO IMPART  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MAY 30) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By BERNARD HOLLAND   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Calliope, Euterpe and Erato looked out from the pages of the
morning newspaper not long ago. Daughters of Zeus, goddesses of the
arts, photographically rendered.
</P>
<P>
   Well, maybe not the three Muses but certainly violinists. Their
particular Zeus has passed on but left behind a patrimony now
called the Avery Fisher Prize. Women, when I was growing up, were
not known for having pockets, but those of Sarah Chang, Pamela
Frank and Nadja Salerno-Sonnenberg are now each jingling with
$50,000.
</P>
<P>
   The big news about the prestigious and financially attractive
award is that the present honorees are all female. It has not
happened before. This same-sex recognition serves the sociological
concerns of the music world, though I, for one, can't hear anything
identifiably feminine or masculine in their playing. They just
play, which is, I hope, the reason they won.
</P>
<P>
   Now that our new set of Muses have their credentials, I hope
they will get to work. There are a lot of creative types down here
looking for inspiration. The divisions of labor will not be that of
the ancient Greeks. Calliope's beat was epic verse, Erato's love
poetry. Euterpe watched over music. (Certainly Bach felt her touch
when he was working out those five-voice strettos.) The
Chang-Frank-Salerno-Sonnenberg trio is strictly musical, but each
member is a musician in her own way.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Chang will help the needy spirit from a distance. Her gifts
are at a level so removed from the rest of us that all we can do is
feel the appropriate awe and then wonder on the mysteries of
nature. The ancients would certainly have had Ms. Chang emerging
fully formed from some Botticellian scallop shell. She is 18 now
and gives the impression of having learned her scales and arpeggios
in Elysium, Valhalla or some other godly precinct.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Frank seems much closer to the ground. Her parents are
serious pianists and teachers; her wider family is of the art
world. While Ms. Chang elevates the possibilities of her instrument
beyond our reach, Ms. Frank moves more easily among us, less a star
violinist, with all the trappings that go with that status, than a
musician who happens to play the violin.
</P>
<P>
   She is busy with chamber music, and as a soloist, she has
curiosity well beyond the marketable violin repertory. Those of us
who think that music ought to come first, and the spectacle of
performing a distant second, take comfort in a Muse like this. She
is only 31, but her head is on straight and pointing in the right
direction.
</P>
<P>
   I hope that the duties of her new position will include pointing
the way for others as well, for that is what a Muse is for. What
about all those young musicians on the Upper West Side of Manhattan
copying Horowitz and Heifetz performances from old recordings and
hoping that they can one day be just as famous?
</P>
<P>
   The occasional corrective touch from an invisible hand might
help convince a lot of misguided talent among the young that music
is more than stars and personalities.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Salerno-Sonnenberg will be the most ambivalent of our Muses.
Critics love to hate her; listeners love to love her. She is indeed
Ms. Frank held up to a mirror and rendered in reverse. Part of me
hopes that Ms. Salerno-Sonnenberg will not do too much Musing.
Given the shrill competitiveness of the music business, there is
enough look-at-me musicianship to go around without inspiring any
more.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Salerno-Sonnenberg does send out a salutary message to
people like myself, critics who have long deplored the histrionic
stage manner and the running damage to composers' wishes. Her
career is thriving, and no one seems to care what we think.
</P>
<P>
   It is a good lesson for any writer who presumes to the status of
taste-maker. Critics record events experienced through personal
lenses. The public can be momentarily swayed or diverted by
published opinion, but eventually the public makes up its own mind.
</P>
<P>
   Come to think of it, Ms. Salerno-Sonnenberg is the perfect Muse
for a number of people I can think of. One of them might be the
young Canadian woman who sent along her compact disk of Mompou's
piano music not long ago. Such scrupulousness, such respect for the
letter of the printed page. Mompou said that he hated bar lines,
and experimented with their elimination. In these performances, the
bar line's steady thump resonates through item after item.
</P>
<P>
   No hot Catalan blood here, no score-scorching surges of emotion,
no sighs, no outbursts. Civility, faithfulness, self-effacement _
all the qualities that serve Ms. Frank so well _ fall totally flat
in this recording. Evidently the Muses' work is not as clear-cut as
we thought.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe another look at that photograph will help. Are those three
distinct people looking out at us, or are they Siamese triplets:
individual personalities rendered indivisible? It just might be
that all musicians need all these Muses in different dosages all
the time: a dab of unearthliness, a bit of serious study and the
occasional fling as well. The questions are as ever: how much,
when?
</P>
<P>
   That is, indeed, the puzzle of musical performance. We
pontificate about immutable values, but one piece of music will
need more Calliope and less Euterpe, and another not. Erato can
appear absolutely vulgar in one pose and just right in another. To
inspire us, our Muses are going to have to be kept busy
simultaneously: the joint effort as three-way argument. Expect some
unruliness, but there is always Zeus to come down and straighten
things out.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
