</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GUNS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Republicans promise vote on gun legislation by June
 &HT;    By Ken Foskett
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Conceding the imperative for gun control
legislation following school violence in Colorado and Georgia,
House Republican leaders on Tuesday embraced the broad outline of
new gun restrictions adopted by the Senate last week and pledged to
vote on them by mid-June.
</P>
<P>
   But the GOP leaders left themselves room to soften some of the
more restrictive provisions of the Senate bill, such as the one
allowing law enforcement officers 72 hours to conduct criminal
background checks at gun shows. They also said they would not allow
Democrats to ``stampede'' them into action this week.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate gun control legislation, part of a $1 billion
overhaul of the juvenile justice system, would require that trigger
locks or lock boxes be sold with all handguns, subject gun buyers
at gun shows to criminal background checks and ban importing large
ammunition clips.
</P>
<P>
   ``We support common-sense legislation that keeps guns out of the
hands of unsupervised children,'' said House Speaker Dennis Hastert
(R-Ill.). ``But it does not require us to rush to judgment.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats, meanwhile, accused the GOP leadership of seeking to
delay passage of the measures until after the upcoming Memorial Day
recess in order to give opponents, principally the National Rifle
Association, time to kill it. They vowed to engage in parliamentary
ploys and delaying tactics on the House floor this week until GOP
leaders brought the gun control legislation to the floor.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Republican leadership has decided to be a tool of the NRA
and the gun interests,'' charged Rep. George Miller (D-Calif.).
</P>
<P>
   The skirmishes over the gun proposals were the latest indication
of how politically sensitive the gun debate has become. Only two
weeks ago, Judiciary Chairman Henry Hyde (R-Ill.) and other key
leaders of his committee said they would not permit gun control
legislation to be amended to their juvenile crime bill.
</P>
<P>
   But on Tuesday Hyde proposed doing just that, in exactly the
same way that the Senate used its own juvenile crime bill to become
a one-stop shop for new gun control legislation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The juvenile justice bill is very important and we did not
want to weigh it down with too much controversy,'' explained Hyde.
``But because of the tempo of events and the incidents in Colorado
and Georgia, we see no real obstacle to combining the two.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats also yielded to political necessity. In a closed
meeting Tuesday morning, they reached consensus that they would not
make a concerted effort to amend the juvenile justice bill with
additional gun control measures proposed by President Clinton, such
as limiting handgun purchases to one a month and re-instating the
three-day waiting period for any handgun purchase.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats concluded that pushing those measures might jeopardize
their chances for regaining the majority in the House in the 2000
elections. Many Democrats, particularly in rural districts, blame
their votes on the Brady bill in 1993 and the assault weapons ban
in 1994 for record losses in the 1994 elections.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are perhaps 12 seats where this is an issue,'' said Rep.
Jim Moran (D-Va.). ``The leadership wants to do what is right, but
there is also concern about winning back the majority.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to backing trigger locks on hand guns and banning
large ammo clips, the House GOP juvenile bill would also ban
juveniles from purchasing rifles and shot guns from unregistered
gun dealers and require criminal background checks for anyone
seeking to buy explosives. Clinton proposed the explosives waiting
period in his crime package.
</P>
<P>
   Hastert and other GOP leaders also favor ``instant'' background
checks at gun shows, as opposed to the 72 hour time period allowed
by the Senate bill. Democratic sponsors of the provision say it's a
critical feature because most gun shows occur on the weekend, when
access to criminal records is limited. The NRA opposes the longer
waiting period for gun shows.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Foskett writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
