A0854 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YUGOSLAVIA-BOS &LR;      05-25 1011
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YUGOSLAVIA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATO UPS SIZE OF POTENTIAL KOSOVO MONITORING FORCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE E. KORNBLUT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As US officials admitted an economic embargo
against Yugoslavia was beginning to crack, top NATO leaders united
Tuesday to approve a large increase in the number of ground forces
that would protect Kosovo after the war.
</P>
<P>
   The new NATO plan, approved by the North Atlantic Council,
called for a 50,000-member peacekeeping force _ nearly double the
size of the force NATO military leaders imagined necessary before
airstrikes began 10 weeks ago. The United States would supply about
7,000-8,000 troops.
</P>
<P>
   ``This force ... will speak softly, by which I mean that it will
be friendly to everybody,'' NATO spokesman Jamie Shea said. ``But
it will have very sharp teeth _ as well as very big teeth _ if
anybody should try to oppose it carrying out its mandate or to
threaten its personnel.''
</P>
<P>
   But the decision did not address the controversial issue of
combat troops, and remained contingent upon a peace plan that
seemed increasingly elusive Tuesday amid reports that some nations
are secretly supplying fuel to Yugoslavia in defiance of a
voluntary international embargo.
</P>
<P>
   US Secretary of State Madeleine Albright said it was ``evident
that there is a shortage of oil, and that it is affecting the
ability of the military machine to move forward,'' thanks to
successful bombing raids of Yugoslav petroleum storage areas and a
decrease in shipments through the neighboring province of
Montenegro.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are concerned, however, by what we've been hearing more and
more'' about barge traffic up and down the Danube, Albright said.
</P>
<P>
   In other developments Tuesday:
</P>
<P>
   --A UN report detailed ``a significant upsurge'' in sexual
attacks against ethnic Albanian women in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   In April, the UN Population Fund sent women's health kits into
Kosovo, including in them the ``morning after'' pill for rape
victims. Tuesday, the agency said its report was the first to
confirm the numerous rumors of rape that have been circulating
since refugees began leaving Kosovo. One psychologist, Dominique
Serrano-Fitamant, said ``any resistance is met with threats of
being burned alive,'' according to the nearly three dozen women she
interviewed.
</P>
<P>
   --As many as 150,000 new refugees were said to be on their way
from Kosovo to Macedonia, where some 22,000 ethnic Albanians have
arrived in the last three days, according to aid workers for the
UN. More than 830,000 of the 2.1 million residents of Kosovo have
fled their homes since NATO airstrikes began on March 24.
</P>
<P>
   --NATO warplanes continued to knock out power supplies in the
Yugoslav capital, bombing a Belgrade power station for the fourth
night in a row. During daytime raids Tuesday, warplanes struck at
television and radio relay stations, according to Yugoslav media.
For the third time, NATO also hit a villa belonging to Yugoslav
President Slobodan Milosevic, just west of Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   --The International Committee of the Red Cross returned to
Kosovo to reopen the agency's mission, which had closed five days
after airstrikes against Yugoslavia began.
</P>
<P>
   --Humanitarian missions planning to launch airdrops of food and
medicine over Kosovo were told they would not be guaranteed
protection by NATO forces.
</P>
<P>
   A NATO spokesman, Maj. Gen. Walter Jertz, warned the groups from
South Africa and Russia that they must work out a detailed
coordination plan with NATO, whose planes soar over Kosovo as many
as 700 times per day.
</P>
<P>
   --Despite past reluctance by NATO officials to comment on the
numbers of Yugoslav casualties, French Defense Minister Alain
Richard Tuesday put the total number of Serbian military deaths and
injuries at several hundred.
</P>
<P>
   ``One can estimate the number of Serb military killed and
wounded is in the hundreds but I can't say whether it is 150 or
950,'' Richard said at a news briefing.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, diplomatic activity continued in Moscow and
Washington, as German Foreign Minister Joschka Fischer came to the
United States to meet with Albright and US Deputy Secretary of
State Strobe Talbott continued talks in Russia with special envoy
to the Balkans, Viktor Chernomyrdin, and Finnish President Martti
Ahtisaari. Chernomyrdin and Ahtisaari are planning to fly to
Belgrade to see Milosevic Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Fischer, whose country is among the most opposed to sending in
ground troops, appeared at a news briefing with Albright but kept
discussion of division within the NATO alliance at a minimum.
Instead, both focused on what they described as an increasingly
disturbing pattern of smuggling into Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Albright said the Ukraine in particular was believed to be
allowing barges to fill up with fuel oil in its ports before
shooting down the Danube to resupply Serb troops. Cyprus and
possibly Greece were also blamed for allowing smugglers to launder
money used to pay for the fuel.
</P>
<P>
   Fischer highlighted another grim development: explosive
nationalism in Macedonia, which has been severely strained by the
flow of refugees.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will have severe consequences for stability in the whole
region, especially in Macedonia,'' Fischer said. ``So I think this
aggressive nationalism, this policy of aggressive nationalism of
Mr. Milosevic, rooted in the '30s, not in the '90s, of European
politics must be stopped and will be stopped.''
</P>
<P>
   And yet the only solid military development Tuesday was that of
the top NATO policy-making body, the North Atlantic Council, which
voted to approve the increase in potential peacekeeping troops.
</P>
<P>
   Originally, NATO officials planned to send 28,000 troops to
Kosovo, following an agreement between the Yugoslav government and
the Kosovo Liberation Army to have been signed last March. Those
peace talks in Rambouillet failed, prompting the NATO airstrikes;
now, due to the explosion of violence in the region, nearly double
the number of peacekeepers will be necessary to secure both sides,
NATO officials said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
