<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-TEACHER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OUTSTANDING TEACHER YOUNGEST TO WIN STATE HONOR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DOREEN IUDICA VIGUE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Come September, David Lussier's life will change
significantly: Not only will he become a father, he'll spend the
school year spreading good news about education as the
Massachusetts Teacher of the Year.
</P>
<P>
   Lussier, 29, a social studies teacher at Andover High School,
was chosen Teacher of the Year by the state Department of Education
from among 375 candidates for his dynamism and outstanding rapport
with students, state officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Lussier is the youngest teacher to win the honor, which awards a
teacher a yearlong sabbatical to act as a goodwill ambassador for
education.
</P>
<P>
   A teacher for seven years, Lussier believes all children should
be taught to their strengths _ and all teachers should be
innovative and take risks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I started off wanting to be a great teacher of history,'' said
Lussier, of Litchfield, N.H. ``But now that I've matured, I would
rather be respected as a great teacher of students.''
</P>
<P>
   State Department of Education Commissioner David P. Driscoll
called Lussier ``dynamic as heck.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He has a way of motivating kids,'' Driscoll said. ``He's very
conscientious. He does the extra projects, puts in the extra time,
and he's very dedicated. That's what impressed us.''
</P>
<P>
   Lussier's students are equally impressed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kids find his class creative and they are more open and feel
more comfortable to say what they have to say in terms of how they
feel about something,'' said Chris Cordima, 18, a senior who has
Lussier for advanced placement US History.
</P>
<P>
   Lussier was raised in Dracut and earned a bachelor's degree in
history from the University of Massachusetts at Lowell. He received
a master's degree in art and teaching from Boston University in
1992.
</P>
<P>
   He wanted to become a teacher, Lussier said, ``because I was
always a complete history nerd in high school and I wanted to use
that somehow to make a difference.''
</P>
<P>
   He spent his first two years teaching at Quincy High School and
began at Andover High five years ago. His wife is an elementary
school teacher in New Hampshire and they are expecting their first
child in September.
</P>
<P>
   Lussier believes teachers need to go beyond the classroom,
reaching into the community to be leaders and mentors.
</P>
<P>
   His teaching philosophy, he said, begins with the notion that
teaching the student is as vital as teaching the subject. He said
more teachers should reach out to students in different ways,
sparking curiosity with non-traditional teaching methods.
</P>
<P>
   Cordima said that Lussier practices what he preaches.
</P>
<P>
   ``His style is more alternative; it's more discussions and
activities than lectures,'' Cordima said. ``He has made me more
open-minded in terms of seeing the whole issue and digging deeper.
He's shown me everying is not just surface.''
</P>
<P>
   As Teacher of the Year, Lussier will travel to schools statewide
and discuss how best to implement education reform and share
pointers with other educators about giving _ and getting _ the most
from children.
</P>
<P>
   Lussier is most anxious to highlight excellence in schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``As educators, we do have a lot of challenges and a lot of work
ahead of us, but I think it's going to be an exciting future,'' he
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
