<SLUG> BC-CHINASPY-DICKS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DICKS WARNS AGAINST POLITICIZING CHINA REPORT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MICHAEL PAULSON  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Saying that there is plenty of blame to go around
for allowing the Chinese to steal U.S. intelligence secrets, Rep.
Norm Dicks Tuesday warned Republicans against making political
mischief with the scandal.
</P>
<P>
   Dicks, D-Wash., took particular aim at Texas Gov. George W.
Bush, saying that the presidential aspirant should be careful
because some intelligence losses occurred on his father's watch.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Republicans need to be very careful, particularly George
W. Bush, whose father was a vice president for eight years and then
president when all this happened,'' Dicks said in an interview.
``People need to be fair here. This started in the late '70s, and
went through the '80s and into the '90s, and there were two Reagan
(administrations) and one Bush administration and they didn't clean
up this problem.''
</P>
<P>
   The Texas governor was one of numerous Republicans who
criticized the Clinton administration's handling of China Tuesday
after the release of a report by a bipartisan special House
committee. The report found that Chinese espionage has led to the
theft of top-secret information about every U.S. nuclear weapon.
China denied the espionage.
</P>
<P>
   Dicks, an expert on intelligence issues, was the top Democrat on
the committee, and along with the other Democrats endorsed its
findings.
</P>
<P>
   The report is likely to cause damage to two causes Dicks cares
about _ the reputation of the Clinton administration and the health
of China-U.S. relations. But Dicks said he believed it was
important to have a unanimous report to make it clear to the
administration and to Congress the importance of following the
committee's recommendations.
</P>
<P>
   Dicks, who recently gave up his post as ranking Democrat on the
House Intelligence Committee, called the Chinese espionage ``no
doubt one of the worst counterintelligence failures in the nation's
history.''
</P>
<P>
   But Dicks, who was somewhat taken aback by the media storm that
greeted the report's release, spent Tuesday in a series of
interviews attempting, he said, ``to put it in perspective and keep
the balance.''
</P>
<P>
   He appeared on the News Hour with Jim Lehrer, Crossfire and
Larry King Live, and Wednesday he is to appear on the Today Show
and on C-SPAN's Washington Journal.
</P>
<P>
   Although Dicks praised the Clinton administration's response to
the report, he also acknowledged that he helped force that response
last fall. At that time, Dicks went to see Bill Richardson, the new
energy secretary, and warned him that the House committee was
uncovering a major scandal and that Richardson would be well-served
to follow any recommendations he got to improve his department's
poor counterintelligence operation.
</P>
<P>
   ``People can rest assured that we're getting this mess cleaned
up, and Congress and the administration are working together,''
Dicks said. ``There are going to be people who want to make
political hay out of this, but I think the American people are
going to be fair.''
</P>
<P>
   Dicks noted that, contrary to the expectations of some
Republicans last year, the committee did not find any impeachable
offenses by President Clinton, nor any concerns about campaign
contributions from China. But he said the Energy Department needs
to ``sanction'' some of its employees who hindered
counterintelligence efforts.
</P>
<P>
   Dicks said he is particularly worried about the report's impact
on U.S.-China relations. Like most elected officials from
Washington state, he is a major booster of the relationship because
of China's importance as a market for the state's exports.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a positive story for U.S.-China relations, and I'm
sure a lot of the people who don't like China are going to seize on
this,'' Dicks said. ``This makes it more difficult in Congress to
make normal trade relations permanent, and to accept China into the
World Trade Organization. It's going to complicate things in the
short term.''
</P>
<P>
   Dicks noted that the report follows an incident last month in
which the U.S. bombed the Chinese Embassy in Belgrade. The U.S.
said the bombing was accidental, but China has rejected that
explanation, and Germany has called for a NATO investigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a good moment in U.S.-China relations,'' Dicks
said. ``But we need to continue to engage China and trade with
them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
