<SLUG> BC-PATRIOTS-STADIUM-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEAT SALES FOR NEW PATRIOTS STADIUM CONTINUE TO LAG 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TINA CASSIDY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The NFL is apparently comfortable with the number of
premium seats sold to date for the proposed new New England
Patriots stadium, but people involved in the project said the
facility would have fewer corporate suites than originally
publicized.
</P>
<P>
   Since announcing its premium-seating marketing effort last
month, a group of civic leaders has said the stadium would have
about 100 to 120 luxury boxes, the most expensive class of seating,
generating $15 million in annual revenue. But people close to the
NFL say the stadium in Foxborough, Mass. will probably have 80 to
100 suites, providing $10 million a year.
</P>
<P>
   Political operative Paul G. Kirk Jr. had been using the larger
figure as part of the group's sales pitch to local corporations,
whose purchase of premium seating would provide an important source
of funding to cover the costs of the $225 million facility. While
the group succeeded in persuading the Patriots and Beacon Hill
leaders that there is enough support to justify a new Foxborough
home, it apparently overestimated just how many suites would be
realistic.
</P>
<P>
   The original estimate of 6,000 club seats, a less-expensive
seating option, remains, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
   Team owner Robert Kraft, in Atlanta this week for an NFL owners
conference, has remained quiet on the specifics of his stadium plan
until he can win approval of a separate financing package from the
league. That silence, combined with the fact that legislation
authorizing the state to spend $70 million in infrastructure
improvements around the stadium was just signed on Monday, has
hampered suite sales, the league says.
</P>
<P>
   So far, sources say sales have reached about $6 million, less
than the $7.5 million that Kirk reported on Monday. Kirk could not
be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want panic, but I don't want complacency either,''
said Roger Goodell, the NFL's stadium expert who helped craft the
Foxborough deal. ``We've still got work to do. This is a positive
indication.''
</P>
<P>
   The league recently passed a rule that will help team owners
privately finance up to 50 percent of new football facilities. The
Patriots will be the first team to reap the low-cost benefits of
that mechanism.
</P>
<P>
   Owners are expected to approve the plan in a vote Wednesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-25-99 2025EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
