<DOCNO> NYT19990525.0324 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-25 20:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0864 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOREA-ENTREPRENEURS-2     05-25 0824
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOREA-ENTREPRENEURS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN SOUTH KOREA, LAYOFFS FUEL ENTERPRISE 
</HEADLINE>
  (dal) 
 By SHERYL WUDUNN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEOUL, South Korea _ For nearly two decades, Jang Chang-ik
trudged up the corporate hill, clocking long hours and following
orders from his bosses until he became one of them.
</P>
<P>
   Then last year Jang was freed from the drudgery and became an
entrepreneur. In short, he was fired.
</P>
<P>
   Jang, 45, who had been a senior manager in the accounting
department of an LG Group company, is part of a rippling wave of
Koreans and other Asians who would never have had the nerve to set
off and start their own businesses if life had gone as they had
hoped.
</P>
<P>
   But their countries were battered by the Asian economic crisis,
they lost their jobs and now they are at the vanguard of a new
entrepreneurism in Asia.
</P>
<P>
   Some economists say that is just what Asia needs to become more
flexible and boom again. And some of the forced entrepreneurs like
Jang may end up as billionaires. But in the meantime their hopes
and dreams are balanced by their disappointments, bills and
overwhelming uncertainty.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was at a loss,'' said Kim Gwi-seon, 43, Jang's wife,
recalling the days after she had heard about her husband's
dismissal. ``We felt a sense of betrayal.''
</P>
<P>
   On Jan. 1, a day after losing his old job, Jang put up his
shingle on a new steel door. He is now chairman, president, chief
executive and chief operating officer of JCI Information
Technology, his new software consulting company.
</P>
<P>
   He has not yet turned a profit, but so far business looks
bright: he has completed one project already and has 13 employees
on a payroll that will soon expand to 20. Jang dreams that his
little company will become the next-generation LG Group _ or at
least a new livelihood for the next couple of decades for him, and
perhaps for his two sons, who are now 11 and 13.
</P>
<P>
   South Korea's giant conglomerates, known as chaebol, have been
the backbone of the country's explosive growth in the last four
decades. Controlling large swaths of the country's economic output,
they employed thousands of people who toiled under authoritarian
bosses, and their muscle upstaged many mini-manufacturers in the
market.
</P>
<P>
   But those chaebol, too, began as merely the ideas of ambitious
men, who were economically broken after the war yet had the
perseverance to build, sometimes on very little education.
</P>
<P>
   Korea already has its share of small shopkeepers. And many of
the newly unemployed will be stepping down the corporate ladder
into enterprises that do not necessarily use their skills. Still,
the layoffs of middle-class white-collar workers, who are more
familiar with cram schools than with construction sites, could help
create a new cluster of smart and nimble companies that will better
enable Korea to compete in the global marketplace.
</P>
<P>
   It is far too soon to say whether the new ventures will succeed,
and for now most of the entrepreneurs have not been nearly able to
replicate the incomes and stability that they had in their old
jobs.
</P>
<P>
   South Korea's economy is rebounding this year, but as companies
dismiss workers to slim down operations, unemployment is soaring
and the society is still battling to recover from the Asian
financial crisis that began in July 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Big chaebol like Samsung Group and LG Group are slowly
restructuring, but not nearly as much as analysts would like.
Indeed, two other chaebol, Hyundai and Daewoo, which got into
trouble partly because they had borrowed too much, have actually
increased their debts. O One result is that many economists predict
that Asia's recovery will come less from the likes of Hyundai than
from people like Jang. While Asia's bankruptcies have gotten most
of the attention, newly formed corporations have outnumbered
bankruptcies for several months, with the ratio rising so far this
year to at least 8 to 1 in South Korea's biggest cities.
</P>
<P>
   Few of the unemployed are as lucky as Jang, who spent years as a
computer programmer early in his career and therefore had readily
marketable skills. And many small-time businessmen are still
struggling, so that although the number of bankruptcies has fallen,
there may be another wave as companies who have survived this far
on their savings begin to run out of money.
</P>
<P>
   ``My wife and I are constantly talking about how to cope with
the situation,'' said Chon Boon-kee, 38, the owner of two video
houses. ``For two hours every day after midnight, we go back home
and talk about this before we go to bed. If my deficit piles up,
then my money will disappear. I'll lose my shops and become
homeless and empty-handed.''
</P>
<P>
   Chon has tried to sell one of his shops, where students used to
line up before the doors opened to view videos, but no buyers have
stepped forward. He is behind in the rent on both places, and now
he draws far fewer customers than the 30 a day he needs to break
even.  &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   Still, there is creative energy percolating among the ranks of
unemployed managers.
</P>
<P>
   Kim Kwang-yong, 46, was a traffic planning manager at Asiana
Airlines before he was let go at the end of last year. ``It's been
three months since I lost my job, but I'm still in shock,'' said
Kim, in a dark blue suit as he took a break from a job retraining
class at a college in Seoul.
</P>
<P>
   Kim has not yet found a new job. But he figured that whatever he
ended up doing, he would need to know about the Internet, so he
enrolled in an Internet course and now carries around a notebook
that says: ``Forward, march on. Do not tarry.''
</P>
<P>
   He heard about his dismissal only 10 days before it took effect,
and with three children and two elderly parents to provide for, in
addition to his wife, Kim went into a spiritual crisis over his
future. After two weeks of moping around, he decided that he would
not seek another job, but instead start his own business. The
problem was what kind of business.
</P>
<P>
   First he toyed with the idea of selling charcoal that does not
smoke, but after doing a financial evaluation, he dropped the idea
because the costs were too high. Then he considered the restaurant
franchise business, scouring 30 sites throughout the country for
possible locations of a fast-food eatery that would serve chicken,
hamburgers and hot dogs.
</P>
<P>
   He drew up a detailed business plan, writing at his desk until
the wee hours before concluding that he would need about $830,000
for a good site and scratching the idea.
</P>
<P>
   Three more business plans later, Kim decided to throw in the
towel and take the free Internet course. He has not yet settled on
an idea, but he feels more comfortable with his pace, and his
ambitions have not been tempered.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to play a big role,'' he said, and then he let slip a
plan, perhaps part vengeful. ``I want to buy Asiana Airlines after
I earn a lot of money from the business.''
</P>
<P>
   But most start-ups are frail, and squeezing out a livelihood
from a tiny venture is very difficult.
</P>
<P>
   Take Kang Chang-hHee, 55, a former shoe factory owner. A few
years ago he had a factory with 13 employees, a big house with a
garden and a wife who was in the business with him. For 17 years
they ran the factory, as well as a shoe store outlet that sold 300
pairs a day.
</P>
<P>
   But in 1990 an employee lighted a match inside the factory near
some chemicals, which exploded and set the building on fire. Three
employees, who suffered third-degree burns, sued and won, virtually
forcing Kang into bankruptcy. He sold everything to pay the
compensation. He began to drink. His wife left him.
</P>
<P>
   In 1992 he pulled himself together and tried to get another shoe
business going, but in November 1997, as the South Korean economy
was tumbling, he had to close his second factory. Exhausted and
broke, Kang tried his hand at odd construction jobs, but those
disappeared as the economy skidded further. A few months later he
ended up at the Seoul railway station, a homeless beggar with no
future.
</P>
<P>
   This winter he began selling baked egg tarts, with the help of a
welfare center that gives him a room and some assistance in
starting a vending business. He went all over town to find a good
location, moving seven times as store clerks shooed him away from
their spots, until finally a shoe store owner let him set up a
stand on the sidewalk near his store.
</P>
<P>
   Now Kang has switched to selling cakes and ice cream. When he
starts earning enough money, he hopes to open a store, remarry and
get back in touch with his five brothers and sisters.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not a thing to boast about, to stay at a welfare
center,'' he said, ``so when I become more self-sufficient, then I
will contact them. Some people live very smooth lives, but mine was
not.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
