<HEADER>
A0866 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NH-KING-870&AMP;ADD-NYT &LR;      05-25 1007
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NH-KING-870&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.H.)  
 NEW HAMPSHIRE MAKES MARTIN LUTHER KING HOLIDAY UNANIMOUS
</HEADLINE>
   (jw) 
 By CAREY GOLDBERG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CONCORD, N.H. _ New Hampshire lawmakers Tuesday approved a
permanent holiday honoring the Rev. Dr. Martin Luther King Jr.,
ending years of such protracted and contrarian resistance that the
long-awaited vote prompted one civil rights advocate to exclaim:
``Free at last, free at last! Thank God almighty, free at last!''
</P>
<P>
   The holiday bill, solidly approved by the New Hampshire House of
Representatives, has already passed the Senate and is sure to be
enthusiastically signed by Gov. Jeanne Shaheen, who pushed for it.
New Hampshire will then become the 50th state to celebrate a Martin
Luther King Day each winter.
</P>
<P>
   While the vote was surely a victory for the state's civil rights
advocates, its tiny black population and the governor, it was also
a triumph for the state's schoolchildren, who for years had marched
on the State House, calling for a holiday named for the slain civil
rights leader they were taught to revere.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last 10 years, this has become a children's crusade,''
said Steve Davis, a school official who has helped organize marches
of hundreds of students.
</P>
<P>
   Some attributed the Legislature's change of heart to a changing
political dynamic in New Hampshire: Its arch-conservative image has
recently shown sign after sign of softening, from a willingness to
consider a state income tax to the Democrats' gaining control of
the state Senate for the first time in more than seven decades.
</P>
<P>
   But other proponents of the holiday said they thought it had
just taken time to combat stubbornness and adherence to tradition
in a flinty state that has only 8,000 black people in a population
of 1.2 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it takes time for good things to happen, and this was
a good thing,'' said Ann White, a retired civil servant who has
lobbied for the holiday for years. ``Especially here in New
Hampshire, it takes time.''
</P>
<P>
   Even after all these years, however, the consensus was still far
from complete. The vote in the House on Tuesday was 212-148, and
several legislators argued against the measure. Their reasons
ranged from contentions that King should not be singled out from
among a constellation of other great civil rights leaders to a
denunciation of ``mindless conformism.''
</P>
<P>
   State Rep. Ed Putnam II, R-East Hampstead, turned to House
Speaker Donna Sytek of Salem, and said, ``Madam Speaker, if you and
398 members of the House jump out that window right now, don't look
to the 400th member to jump out behind you because it's `the only
thing to do.'''
</P>
<P>
   And another Republican, state Rep. Donald White of Hudson,
argued, ``If we establish holidays to honor ideals, perhaps we
should not reserve a day for one person.''
</P>
<P>
   But it was the likes of Jane Kelley, a veteran Democratic
legislator from Hampton, who carried the day. Just as King's ``I
have a dream'' speech talked about the day when children would be
judged not by the color of their skin but by the content of their
character, she said: ``So will New Hampshire now be judged by the
content of its character. We must erase the stain of bigotry and
racism from the face of our beautiful state.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, although it has long refused to fall in line with the
other 49 states, New Hampshire has been inching toward a
full-fledged Martin Luther King Day for years.
</P>
<P>
   Congress approved a bill declaring the third Monday in January
to be Martin Luther King Day in 1983, with observance to begin in
1986. New Hampshire lawmakers voted down bills to conform through
the late 1980s, but in 1991 it approved a measure declaring that
day to be Civil Rights Day, though with no mention of King in the
title.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the mid-1990s, New Hampshire governors, first Stephen
Merrill, a Republican, and then Mrs. Shaheen, a Democrat, issued
proclamations each year turning Civil Rights Day into Martin Luther
King Day, but still the House of Representatives balked at
cementing the change. The last time the issue came up, in 1997,
holiday proponents lost by just one vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was certainly an embarrassment,'' said state Rep. James
Splaine, D-Portsmouth, who introduced the first Martin Luther King
Jr. Day bill in 1979. ``It was embarrassing for our governor when
she went elsewhere,'' Splaine added, ``and most importantly,
embarrassing for our kids when they went elsewhere.''
</P>
<P>
   In recent years there has been little concerted opposition to
the idea of a Martin Luther King Day, said Arnie Alpert, a
spokesman for the Martin Luther King Day Committee, which united
the holiday's backers.
</P>
<P>
   At public hearings, Alpert said, only members of the John Birch
Society spoke as a group against it. Otherwise, he said, opponents
were people speaking their own minds _ sometimes recalling charges
that King had been a Communist, complaining that he had undermined
the nation by opposing the Vietnam War so vehemently, or noting
that he had a criminal record.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Arthur Hilson, president of the New England chapter of
the Southern Christian Leadership Conference, was among the
spectators in the House when the bill was passed and used the words
inscribed on King's tombstone when he declared, ``Free at last!''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Hilson said the issue just ``was never ripe'' before. ``But
there are people who are beginning to see the light that this is
the right thing to do,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Though the fight for the holiday has been prolonged and
grueling, some advocates said the struggle itself had served to
raise awareness about human rights, particularly among young New
Hampshire residents. And in some ways, there could not have been a
better time to honor King's doctrine of nonviolence, said Davis,
the school official.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're bombing for the people of Kosovo and kids are bombing
their schools, and we haven't made the connection yet,'' Davis
added. ``It's about nonviolence.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
