<HEADER>
A0869 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CANNES-FILM-FEST-$ADV     05-25 0991
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANNES-FILM-FEST-$ADV30-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR FESTIVAL PROWLERS AT CANNES, POUNCING IS ALL  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MAY 30) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By JANET MASLIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CANNES, France _ After Heather Locklear, Kate Moss and a French
actress with a tattooed buttock swanned up the red-carpeted steps
to the Palais des Festivals for this year's closing night
ceremonies, the top official accolades at the Cannes International
Film Festival were awarded to two intense, painful French-language
films dealing with hard lives in lonely surroundings.
</P>
<P>
   The Palme d'Or winner, the Belgian film ``Rosetta'' by the
brothers Luc and Jean-Pierre Dardenne, offers a fierce portrait of
a young woman trying to eke out a living against impossible odds.
It is just the kind of small, profound, beautifully realized film
that will be greatly helped by the prize.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rosetta'' is as artfully spare as the year's other major
winner, Bruno Dumont's ``L'Humanite,'' is self-consciously
minimalist. Dumont's would-be painterly, philosophical film watches
a wide-eyed police investigator respond to stirrings of evil and
sexuality in a rural town, where the filmmaker regards his
characters as brutish and naked in every sense.
</P>
<P>
   The award of a best actor prize to Emmanuel Schotte of
``L'Humanite'' made for the night's biggest jolt, since Schotte's
halting, fragile manner made the performance look less like acting.
He seemed very like the man he plays.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, this was the year that Harvey Weinstein of Miramax
declared war.
</P>
<P>
   Weinstein has long been galled by this event's elitism and its
predilection for dull, irrelevant films and he thinks it's time for
a change. ``There's something wrong with Cannes, and it needs to be
fixed,'' he said angrily by telephone from the closing night party.
``The luster of the festival is completely submerged. It's losing
its place in film history. It has the potential to be so much more
than it is now, the potential to be so much more serious and less
political. I've reached the frustration point, and I'm not scared
to say so any more.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course Weinstein could be accused of sour grapes. Miramax's
version of Oscar Wilde's ``Ideal Husband'' was this year's closing
night film and Kevin Smith's ``Dogma'' was an out-of-competition
hot potato. (Miramax bought back ``Dogma'' to shield Disney, its
parent company, from possible protests against the film's views on
Catholicism.)
</P>
<P>
   But, otherwise, the usually unstoppable Miramax team was
practically AWOL. Then again, the big American studios were also
missing with the notable exception of Disney, which was attached to
films by David Lynch, Tim Robbins and Spike Lee.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel a very sentimental attachment to Cannes, but I'm tired
of begging,'' said Weinstein, who had no luck getting ``Dogma''
into the main competition, though there was room for a two and a
half hour soap opera (``Our Happy Lives'') about a group of
star-crossed French characters. ``I'm tired of fighting for obvious
choices.'' (Among Miramax's previous rejects for Cannes' main
competition are ``My Left Foot'' and ``The Crying Game.'')
</P>
<P>
   So he spent much of this year's festival stirring up producers,
directors and financiers of his acquaintance. Maybe they will be
able to offset the doldrums that are especially extreme. When the
Variety critic Todd McCarthy fired off a salvo against overlong
films of no interest to anyone but their creators, his column was
more popular than most of the movies in town.
</P>
<P>
   And if nothing changes? ``Then I won't come,'' Weinstein said.
</P>
<P>
   If that sounds like a no-prisoners stance, it's also an
indication of what an extreme sport Cannes can be from a business
standpoint. That's what it amounts to for the small club of
distributors who dominate American art-house fare.
</P>
<P>
   The best of what has been seen here will be distributed by
companies including Sony Pictures Classics, which quietly dominated
the festival with its most sure-fire hit, Pedro Almodovar's
graceful and funny ``All About My Mother,'' Chen Kaige's ``Emperor
and the Assassin'' and Takeshi Kitano's ``Kikujiro.''
</P>
<P>
   Newcomers like Artisan had Atom Egoyan's ``Felicia's Journey,''
and ``The Limey'' by Steven Soderbergh, while the newly-formed
amalagam of October, Gramercy and Polygram swooped in to acquire
the big winner, ``Rosetta.'' These companies are all headed by film
buffs who don't care only about the bottom line.
</P>
<P>
   Showing off isn't what they're here for. Tom Bernard of the Sony
Classics team whizzes around black-tie Cannes on a bicycle. His
partner Michael Barker can go serenely unnoticed in a crowd of
filmmakers desperate to get their work financed.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Ordesky, who says he ``made'' president of Fine Line
Features as if it were a law partnership and at 36 looks as if he
would have trouble buying liquor without a picture ID, favors
hiking boots. On the Riviera. In May. He thinks they bring good
luck because he had them on when Fine Line nabbed ``Shine'' at the
snowy Sundance Film Festival.
</P>
<P>
   Inside his Cannes survival kit are two kinds of batteries in
baggies _ for the pager and for the cell phone. And there is a
witch hazel wipe. (``What if Elizabeth Hurley wants to have tea
with me and I'm a sweaty mess?'')
</P>
<P>
   He also carries a map and a complete guide to every film here,
right down to where to find the sellers in a flash. And Ordesky is
known both for toting blank movie contracts and having the
wherewithal to sign them. ``It's critical!'' he explains. ``How
many good things are on the acquisitions circuit each year? So if
one comes along and you're not ready _ whose fault is that?''
</P>
<P>
   Even (italics)before(end italics) one comes along. Ordesky
already is counting on a musical for next year being shot with 100
cameras by Lars (``Breaking the Waves'') Von Trier. As Weinstein
demonstrated by throwing down the gauntlet, no need to visit the
casinos if you want to gamble in this town.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
