<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-25 20:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0870 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEACHERS-COX     05-25 1584
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEACHERS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Teachers have their say
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ With last week's incident at Heritage High School in
Conyers, Ga., the perverse late '90s trend of school shootings
reached metro Atlanta. The local violence followed the Colorado
school massacre by a month. Bo Emerson, Bill Hendrick and Lillian
Kim of The Atlanta Journal-Constitution newspapers interviewed
teachers and principals from around Atlanta, asking how the air of
violence is affecting their schools, their students and their own
lives.
</P>
<P>
   Melody Tosi
</P>
<P>
   Age: 46
</P>
<P>
   Position: Math teacher, Pope High School, East Cobb Co., Ga.
</P>
<P>
   I'm not afraid. But, on the other hand, I'm not stupid. We have
really looked at what we would do in that situation. My students
have talked about it, and we have a plan about what we would do,
how we would escape. The fact that we were thinking about it gave
everybody a comfortable feeling.
</P>
<P>
   The positive thing about all this is it has created dialogue
with our students about what's wrong. We have talked about the
outcasts, and this has made the kids more sensitive to those kids.
It's made us more aware of people.
</P>
<P>
   I'm trying to think what my biggest (discipline) problem was 25
years ago. It was probably chewing gum.
</P>
<P>
   It would be interesting for people to spend time with the
principal, to see what kinds of things he deals with. He's spending
his days checking out rumors rather than doing what he's supposed
to be doing as a principal. It's a scary time to be a principal
right now. They're on pins and needles.
</P>
<P>
   The cool thing about being a teacher is you just do your job.
</P>
<P>
   Our kids are not naive enough to think it wouldn't happen at our
school, but I don't think they are thinking about it all the time.
But I don't know. In my wildest dreams, this was not something
anybody ever thought about.
</P>
<P>
   I don't know what the solution is. I think the only solution for
this problem now is summer vacation, getting it out of the news.
I'm an educator. I shouldn't be in news stories.
</P>
<P>
   Kids were getting picked on when I was in school. It's just the
way they deal with it. You're dealing now with a total different
set of variables, and I'll be honest: The teacher now is not just a
teacher. You have to be a counselor, a psychiatrist. I'm not just
teaching quadratic equations. And I think that has to be bad.
</P>
<P>
   James Jackson
</P>
<P>
   Age: 52
</P>
<P>
   Position: Principal, Alonzo A. Crim High School, Atlanta
</P>
<P>
   I taught from '68 to '91, or 23 years. Studentwise, there's not
a whole lot of difference now.
</P>
<P>
   I'm seeing the same kinds of things among students, basically.
The same kinds of misbehavior. They still try to slip off campus,
they still want to smoke cigarettes when they get an opportunity.
We still have occasional fights. Then as now, every now and then a
student will have a weapon.
</P>
<P>
   You know what I see as the big difference? The parents were more
supportive in the early years when the students misbehaved. Now,
parents are coming in and defending student misbehavior. I think
that's a problem. The parents say those kids were right, and we
know it's wrong.
</P>
<P>
   I don't know why many of us are surprised by what we are seeing,
because the schools are a reflection of what we see in society. We
allow them to see violence and sex on TV, in the movies, and the
child is reacting to what they see around them. Years ago, we
didn't see a person get his head blown off in the movies. We are
getting what we see in society.
</P>
<P>
   Most teachers love teaching. That's why we do it; it's not the
best moneymaking venture you could have.
</P>
<P>
   But you can't find these things happening around you and not
have some apprehension about it. (School violence) could discourage
people from going into teaching.
</P>
<P>
   But if you think about what's happening in other parts of
society, it happens in post offices. A few years back, Dr. (Martin
Luther) King's mother was shot at church, sitting at the organ. To
new teachers, I would say, don't be discouraged. There have been
isolated incidents. If anything, this should give them a keener
awareness of how they should be in education, so we can help our
children.
</P>
<P>
   I'm not going to be paranoid about it. I'm going to approach my
job with the same intensity I always have. I'm going to do much
more proactive thinking than we have in the past, and look at
situations that might happen. I'm going to try to involve parents,
staff and community resources, wherever we see the need to do that.
</P>
<P>
   I would still recommend this field. We've had some tragic
incidents to occur, but there's a silent majority (of students) out
there saying, ``We want you to help us; we need you.'' And we need
to be there for them.
</P>
<P>
   Peggy Martin
</P>
<P>
   Age: 45
</P>
<P>
   Position: Assistant principal, Walton High School, East Cobb
Co., Ga.
</P>
<P>
   What I've had to do here recently is open my eyes wider, be more
visible in the halls, just try to make sure that things are the way
they're supposed to be. In the past, you could hear a rumor and
just say, ``Oh, it's a rumor, they're just kidding. But now you can
no longer do that.''
</P>
<P>
   We're forced to check out any rumor or any story, no matter how
small it might seem. And we have to do it at a greater speed.
</P>
<P>
   So the paperwork on my desk involving students being late to
class or skipping class _ that's taking a back seat in terms of
making sure students are safe. That's been going on for the last
month or so.
</P>
<P>
   We're all saying things like ``this seems like the longest
year.'' We can't wait for it to be over.
</P>
<P>
   I really don't see any general fear on the part of the students.
I personally think the kids seem to bounce back better than the
adults. Something will happen, and then they're just on to the next
thing. Breaks help. Whenever you get a weekend in there and you
come back, you start over.
</P>
<P>
   We've beefed up security measures. Doors are locked. Visitors
are checking in. At the beginning of school, our principal kept
saying we needed to work on a safety plan. He kept stressing that.
And then, after Columbine, we worked on it. We're still working on
it.
</P>
<P>
   What I believe is that we should go for smaller schools. I think
it would be better for the students and the teachers if we had a
smaller setting. The negative consequences might be that we
wouldn't be able to offer the same courses that we offer now. But
there would be advantages in terms of interactions with people.
</P>
<P>
   I'd be crazy if I said it couldn't happen here. I'm not saying
we have the climate for it to happen here. I'm just saying it could
happen anywhere. That's what we've witnessed.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Davis
</P>
<P>
   Age: 41
</P>
<P>
   Position: Government and history teacher, football coach,
McIntosh High School, Peachtree City, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   We need to put a summer between us and the events that have
happened recently.
</P>
<P>
   We used to have a water-balloon fight this time each year. (The
students) understand that's not the kind of thing they need to be
doing right now. The last thing they need to be doing is injecting
any kind of chaos on campus.
</P>
<P>
   The reason you teach is because you love kids and you love your
subject matter. If you love kids, you're going to do whatever you
have to do to make them successful, and if that means you've got to
provide some guidance and you've got to set some moral example,
then that's what you do. The only problem is you're always fighting
against a society or a pop culture that's offering lots of bad
examples.
</P>
<P>
   Ninety-five percent of the kids who go to school here do the
right thing. They study, they go off to college and become
successful citizens. It's depressing in education that we always
have to deal with the 5 percent. You spend most of your energies on
the 5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Both coaching and teaching have been rewarding to me. In
athletics you learn lessons you don't learn in the classroom:
perseverance, dedication, teamwork, loyalty, toughness, all those
coaching cliches. Sometimes I don't think we have an abundance of
these in society anymore.
</P>
<P>
   Paul McKown
</P>
<P>
   Age: 46
</P>
<P>
   Position: Government and history teacher,
</P>
<P>
   Chattahoochee High School, Alpharetta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   What happened in Columbine gave me the opportunity to have what
I call ``teachable moments.'' Rather than sitting there and giving
all I know about the Cold War, we can talk about Columbine.
</P>
<P>
   I leave it open. I ask, ``Have they had those feelings?'' We
talk about the impact this would have on them as parents.
</P>
<P>
   When I was a junior in high school, (the National Guard
shootings at) Kent State happened 70 miles from my home. It had a
big impression on me. I ask, ``What do you think your kids will
think about Columbine?''
</P>
<P>
   I try to have them draw parallels, and I draw them myself; I
draw them in ways that are more society-centered and less
self-centered. If the subject is civil rights, I try to get them to
be more accepting of people who are different than themselves, to
display tolerance.
</P>
<P>
   There has to be a recognition _ if our country is going to
continue to be successful _ that we all have a responsibility to
teach character. I get that opportunity more than, say, someone who
works in an office and interacts with adults all day. It gives me a
chance to do some character-building that maybe other adults can't.
</P>
<P>
   Bo Emerson, Bill Hendrick and Lillian Kim write for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
