<SLUG> BC-SCI-SHUTTLE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHUTTLE READY FOR THURSDAY MISSION TO START OUTFITTING SPACE
STATION
</HEADLINE>
   (dal) 
 By BETH DICKEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. _ With the first load of supplies for the
international space station packed in its cargo bay, the space
shuttle Discovery is poised for launching on Thursday, NASA's first
human space mission in six months.
</P>
<P>
   Liftoff from Florida's Kennedy Space Center is scheduled for
6:48 a.m. Five Americans, a Canadian and a Russian will embark on a
10-day mission after a string of six launching failures since
August _ the American space industry's worst stretch of ill fortune
since the explosion of the shuttle Challenger and the failure of
four other rockets in an 18-month span beginning in 1985.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the recent record, NASA officials played down concerns
about the astronauts' safety. None of the recent failures involved
rockets of the type that will launch Discovery.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no additional anxiety,'' said a Kennedy Space Center
spokesman, Bruce Buckingham. ``We feel like we have a good vehicle
on the pad. We're not superstitious at all. We focus on the
hardware, and expect that if we've done our job, the hardware will
do its job.''
</P>
<P>
   David King, director of shuttle operations at the Kennedy Space
Center, said that extra reviews and rehearsals were conducted in
Florida and Texas to maintain skill and proficiency.
</P>
<P>
   The first spacecraft to dock at the fledgling station, Discovery
will be parked for six days while the seven astronauts unload
supplies for the first live-aboard crew, two Russians and an
American, who will arrive early next year.
</P>
<P>
   The station consists of the Russian control module Zarya and the
American connecting hub Unity, which a shuttle crew put together in
Earth orbit late last year. During the visit, two astronauts will
walk in space for a day to mount parts of two construction cranes,
one made in the United States and the other in Russia, to their
respective components.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the crew will also try to repair a Russian power
storage system and an American communication system on the station.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way I see it,'' said astronaut Daniel Barry, a computer
scientist and former physician, ``we have a new house. It doesn't
have much furniture or trim yet, and we are bringing up the parts
for both the inside and the outside _ to sort of help finish out
the house.''
</P>
<P>
   Barry, 45, is scheduled to venture into space with crewmate
Tamara Jernigan, 40, early Sunday, one day after Discovery docks.
</P>
<P>
   Construction and outfitting of the $60 billion station will
require about 160 spacewalks and 86 American and Russian space
flights through 2005 _ including 24 more shuttle trips.
</P>
<P>
   Unloading more than 4,300 pounds of cargo is the Discovery
crew's top priority. The supplies include laptop computers,
cameras, canvas bags full of maintenance tools, and seven 95-gallon
bags of drinking water siphoned from the shuttle's
electricity-generating fuel cells. Water is a byproduct of power
production.
</P>
<P>
   Joining Barry and Jernigan, both civilians, on the crew are Navy
Cmdr. Kent Rominger, the mission commander; Air Force Lt. Col. Rick
Husband, Discovery's pilot; and mission specialists Ellen Ochoa of
NASA, Julie Payette of Canada and Valery Tokarev, a colonel in the
Russian Air Force.
</P>
<P>
   The five men and two women are scheduled to climb aboard
Discovery at 3:30 a.m. on Thursday, about three hours before
liftoff.
</P>
<P>
   The shuttle's scheduled launching last week was delayed after a
storm damaged fuel tank insulation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
