<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-25 20:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0877 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-USCHINA-COX     05-25 1260
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-USCHINA-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    907-page report details theft of nuclear secrets by ChinaBy
Rebecca Carr
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ For more than 20 years, China has has stolen secret
information on every nuclear weapon in the United States arsenal,
enabling Beijing to build missiles capable of reaching America,
according to a congressional report published Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Released after a five-month struggle with the White House over
what material to declassify, the 907-report on China's ``aggressive
espionage'' touched off a firestorm on Capitol Hill and will almost
certainly affect the nation's foreign policy with China.
</P>
<P>
   Members of Congress suggested a range of reactions from tighter
export controls to creating a special Senate committee to review
the House report's findings. Some went as far as to call for the
resignation of National Security Adviser Sandy Berger and Attorney
General Janet Reno.
</P>
<P>
   Responding to the report issued by a committee headed by Rep.
Christopher Cox (R-Calif.), President Clinton said his
administration is ``moving aggressively to tighten security'' at
the nation's nuclear laboratories and would work with Congress to
implement most of the recommendations of the committee.
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton also pledged to continue to work with China on a
host of other issues, including gaining membership in the World
Trade Organization.
</P>
<P>
   All told, some nine congressional committees are planning to
examine the espionage charges set forth in the report. In a show of
concern about espionage, a Senate Appropriations subcommittee
boosted spending for security and counter intelligence by 40
percent within hours of the report's release.
</P>
<P>
   China denied all wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's ridiculous,'' said Ci Bin, first secretary at the Chinese
Embassy in Washington D.C. ``He (Cox) gives the impression that
China has stolen so many things. I believe our government did not
steal secrets. The Chinese people just want to be friends with the
American people.''
</P>
<P>
   The report, which won unanimous approval from the panel's five
Republicans and four Democrats, says China's next generation of
thermonuclear weapons will ``exploit the elements of stolen U.S.
design information'' and it contends that spying is still going on.
</P>
<P>
   ``The PRC (People's Republic of China) penetration of our
national weapons laboratories almost certainly continues today,''
Cox said.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Norm Dicks (D-Wash.), the panel's ranking Democrat, said
the spying networks at four nuclear laboratories was ``a major
counterintelligence failure, one of the worst failures in the
nation's history.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though the security breaches were discovered on President
Clinton's watch, the report documents an effort by the Chinese
government to steal nuclear secrets dating back more than two
decades and two Republican Administrations to the Carter
Administration.
</P>
<P>
   The committee found that the focus of the intelligence operation
was at four nuclear laboratories: Los Alamos, Lawrence Livermore,
Oak Ridge and Sandia.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. officials first became suspicious that spying was taking
place at Los Alamos in 1992 when Notra Trulock, an intelligence
officer at the Department of Energy, detected unusual behavior at
the laboratory.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, China began a series of nuclear weapons tests
that lasted four years. Those tests opened debate in intelligence
circles over whether a new generation of nuclear warheads was in
fact based on stolen classified information from the U.S., the
report states.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. did not become ``fully aware of the magnitude of the
counter-intelligence problem at the nuclear laboratories until 1995
when officials received a classified document from China spelling
out that it had obtained U.S. design information on the Trident II
(W-88) warhead, one of the most nation's most precise and
sophisticated weapons.
</P>
<P>
   But the president was not briefed about the counterintelligence
failures until early 1998, the report states.
</P>
<P>
   And despite repeated thefts of nuclear weapons technology, the
report finds that security at the nation's nuclear weapons
laboratories remains deficient.
</P>
<P>
   But the White House is quick to point out that after being
briefed in 1998, Clinton ordered the Department of Energy to adopt
a counterintelligence plan, but that plan will not be take full
effect until next year, the report states.
</P>
<P>
   The report also finds that in the late 1990s, China stole
developmental and research technology that, once developed, could
be used for space-based weapons to attack satellites and
submarines.
</P>
<P>
   Reacting to the report's findings, Arnold Kanter, a senior
fellow at the Washington-based Forum for International Policy, said
the spy network is not surprising since espionage has has gone on
as long as there have been countries.
</P>
<P>
   The important question to ask, Kanter said, is what has China
done with its intelligence gathering? The answer: not much.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chinese nuclear capabilities are still primitive and modest,''
said Kanter, who served in the Bush Administration as
undersecretary of State for political affairs and senior director
for defense policy and arms control at the National Security
Council.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this has been going on for 20 years, the fruits of this
have not been manifested,'' said Kanter, noting that the Chinese
have two dozen nuclear warheads in comparison to the United States'
more than 6,000.
</P>
<P>
   While the threat of spying is a serious one, Kanter said, ``We
shouldn't leap to the opposite conclusion of saying, 'Oh my God,
China has become a major threat to us.' It hasn't.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to intelligence gains at the nation's nuclear
laboratories, the committee found that the Chinese government
benefited from failed launches of commercial satellites made by
American companies.
</P>
<P>
   The report documents three failed launches of commercial
satellites made by Loral Space and Communications and Hughes
Electronics Corp. since 1992.
</P>
<P>
   After their satellites crashed on Chinese soil, House
investigators allege that the companies gave the Chinese highly
classified information to help improve the reliability of their
rocket launches.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Illegally transmitted information is useful for the design
and improved reliability of future PRC ballistic missiles as
well,'' the report states.
</P>
<P>
   The committee found that lax monitoring aided the Chinese in
obtaining information. For example, security personnel were offered
prostitutes by the Chinese to look the other way. Some were found
sleeping on the job and reporting to work under the influence of
alcohol. And security details at the satellite launch sites were
insufficiently manned.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Dore, spokesperson for Hughes, said his company
cooperated fully with the House committee. ``We agree that security
has to be improved,'' Dore said. ``We contend that we followed all
the regulations at the time.''
</P>
<P>
   The report also offers 38 recommendations to improving security
at the national labs, including:
</P>
<P>
   _ The president report to congressional leaders at least every
six months on the actions being taken to respond to espionage by
China.
</P>
<P>
   _ Appropriate agencies should conduct a damage assessment of the
implications of the security breaches.
</P>
<P>
   _ Congressional committees should consider whether the
Department of Energy should continue to maintain U.S. nuclear
weapons responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   Rebecca Carr writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
