<SLUG> BC-CHINA-COX-CHUNG-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAMPAIGN-FINANCE FIGURE LINKED TO TECHNOLOGY THEFT BY CHINA 
</HEADLINE>
  (jw) 
 By JAMES RISEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A new congressional report has determined that
there is a connection between a key figure in the campaign finance
controversy and China's theft of sensitive military-related
technology from the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The report from a select House committee states that Johnny
Chung, a Chinese-American at the heart of the campaign finance
controversy, was given $300,000 by two Chinese military officials
in an apparent effort to establish one of them, the daughter of a
Chinese general, in the United States so she could acquire American
technology.
</P>
<P>
   Liu Chaoying, the daughter of the Chinese General, Liu Huaqing,
is now the vice president of China Aerospace International Holdings
and is involved in acquisition of missile and space technology for
China. She holds the rank of lieutenant colonel in the Chinese
army.
</P>
<P>
   The congressional report says that in the summer of 1996, Chung
met in Hong Kong with Ms. Liu and Gen. Ji Shengde, the director of
Chinese military intelligence. Afterward, it says, Chung received
$300,000 from Ms. Liu and Ji.
</P>
<P>
   Chung, who pleaded guilty to fraud last year in the inquiry into
Democratic Party fund-raising practices, has described his
activities and relationship with Ms. Liu to the FBI. The FBI was
able to confirm that the money had been deposited in his bank
account and traced the money back to Hong Kong and confirmed that
Chinese army officials probably served as the conduit for the
funds, the report states.
</P>
<P>
   A month after the meeting with Ms. Liu in Hong Kong, Chung
formed Marswell Investments Inc. Ms. Liu was designated as
president of the company, based in Torrance, Calif. She made two
trips to the United States, one in July 1996, and one in August
1996. During the July visit, Chung arranged for her to attend a
Democratic National Committee fund-raiser, where she met President
Clinton and executives in the import-export business, the report
said.
</P>
<P>
   Her August trip was at Chung's invitation, after he told her
that he had contacted Boeing and McDonnell Douglas regarding her
interest in purchasing aircraft parts.
</P>
<P>
   Soon after that, however, Chung's and Ms. Liu's alleged
involvement in the campaign finance scandal was reported, and she
left the United States. Marswell Investments is now dormant, the
report stated.
</P>
<P>
   ``The purpose of Colonel Liu's contacts was apparently to
establish reputable ties and financing for her acquisition of
technology such as telecommunications and aircraft parts,'' the Cox
report said.
</P>
</TEXT>
