<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANASTASIA-BALLET-ART-$ADV30-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`ANASTASIA' LIVES ON, LIKE AN OPEN QUESTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MAY 30)  
 (af)  
 Terry Trucco's most recent article for Arts and Leisure was about
the Virsky Ukrainian National Dance Company.  
 By TERRY TRUCCO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Not many story ballets are based on the lives of real
people while they are still living. Yet the ballerina Lynn Seymour
recalls that she wasn't surprised when the choreographer Kenneth
MacMillan asked her to create the role of Anna Anderson, the woman
who for years claimed to be the Grand Duchess Anastasia, a daughter
of Czar Nicholas II of Russia, in a one-act ballet, ``Anastasia,''
that he choreographed in 1967 for Berlin's Deutsche Oper Ballet.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was a fascinating woman, even if she wasn't Anastasia,''
Ms. Seymour said of Anderson, who died in 1984. ``You empathized
with her because she was trying so hard to establish who she was.
And you wondered, how could she have made all this up? At the time,
we wanted to believe her claims were true.''
</P>
<P>
   The story of the mysterious woman who thought she was Anastasia
so captivated MacMillan that in 1971 he expanded the work into a
eveninglong ballet for Britain's Royal Ballet, which performed it
in New York the following year.
</P>
<P>
   Now, on Thursday, ``Anastasia'' returns to New York in the first
of eight performances to be presented by American Ballet Theater at
the Metropolitan Opera House. Dancing the title role on opening
night and again on June 11 will be Viviana Durante, a former
principal dancer with the Royal Ballet; she performed ``Anastasia''
with the Royal when the company staged a new production in 1996 and
was coached for the part by Ms. Seymour.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from a story filled with history, emotion and drama, Ms.
Seymour said, two themes inherent in the story _ the loss of
identity and the loneliness of the outsider _ attracted MacMillan
to the tale. ``He was fascinated by this 20th-century saga with its
issues of identity and rejection,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   MacMillan, who died in 1992, liked to build ballets around real
people who confronted problems that an audience could identify
with, she added.
</P>
<P>
   MacMillan based the ballet on two books, ``I, Anastasia,''
Anderson's 1958 autobiography, and ``Nicholas and Alexandra,'' a
1967 history of the last Czar, by Robert K. Massie. ``Kenneth
didn't like traditional romantic heroines who were perfect,'' Ms.
Seymour said. ``As a child, Anastasia was a bit of a tomboy, a bit
chubby and a bit of a problem. That added to the appeal for him.''
</P>
<P>
   The ballet depicts some of the dramatic, often harshly
contrasting events that the woman who claimed she was Anastasia
might have lived through in the days before and after the Czar's
family was executed in 1918. Set to music by Tchaikovsky, the first
two acts are lyrical renderings of the idyllic, if decaying,
Imperial Russia that Anastasia might have remembered.
</P>
<P>
   There's a lavish picnic on the Imperial yacht, with Anna dressed
in a sailor suit, and a grand ball to celebrate Anastasia's coming
of age just before the Revolution. But the surreal third act (the
original one-act work), set to music by the Czech composer Bohuslav
Martinu, unfolds in an asylum, where a confused woman claiming to
be Anastasia relives the horror of the post-Revolution years while
struggling to find her identity and hang onto her sanity.
</P>
<P>
   The style of the choreography deliberately follows the tone of
the content. The Act II ballroom scene, with its formal placement
of characters, is a bow to Marius Petipa, the Imperial Ballet's
master choreographer. But Act III is Expressionist, with so much
upper body movement for Anastasia that Ms. Seymour suggested that
Ms. Durante remove her point shoes during rehearsals to feel more
connected to the ground and freer to use her arms.
</P>
<P>
   The decision to add the ballet to Ballet Theater's repertory at
this time was fairly simple, said Kevin McKenzie, the company's
artistic director. `` `Anastasia' is a wonderful vehicle for a
ballerina,'' he said, adding that many of the company's recent
ballets had emphasized men's dancing. Because almost none of the
dancers had seen the work, he invited Ms. Durante to join Ballet
Theater as a principal dancer for the season; in addition to
``Anastasia,'' her roles include ``Romeo and Juliet'' and
``Giselle.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Durante, who has not performed ``Anastasia'' in three years,
was eager to dance the part again. ``It's not just a technical
role, but an emotional role, particularly in the third act when
she's seeing ghosts,'' she said during a recent conversation before
a rehearsal. ``Is she really seeing them or is she imagining them?
That's difficult to put on stage without words.''
</P>
<P>
   The biggest challenge is to purge the part of all sentimentality
and romance. ``She's angry, and she's real, and kind of losing her
mind, and her movements can't ever be romantic, like this,'' Ms.
Durante said, striking a graceful pose, arms out, more typical of
Juliet or Giselle than Anastasia.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Durante said she felt a kinship with a character who had
experienced painful loneliness. Born in Rome, she began dancing at
7 and because of her prodigious talents was sent to London at age
10 to study at the Royal Ballet School. ``I really couldn't speak
to people at first or be understood, and that left me to kind of
live in my own world,'' she said. ``I feel I missed out on my
childhood a lot. And that has left me with a slight pain, a slight
anger, that helps me relate to Anastasia.''
</P>
<P>
   Anastasia is a grown-up role best suited for a mature dancer,
and Ms. Durante, who is 32, said she could bring more understanding
to the part now than when she danced it three years ago. Indeed,
the last few years have been a change for her. After seven years as
a principal dancer with the Royal Ballet, she took a one-year
sabbatical from the company and ballet in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``After dancing almost all my life, I was kind of rejecting
ballet,'' she said. She didn't do class, didn't do a single plie.
Instead, she took acting lessons, rested and ``had fun,'' she said.
Eventually she realized she missed being on stage, missed ``the
energy performing and an audience gives.''
</P>
<P>
   She decided to refashion her career, becoming an international
touring artist. She has since danced with the Royal and will
perform with the company again this July, but as a guest. This year
she will also dance in Brazil, Italy, Chile and Japan.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I'm doing now is fulfilling,'' she said. ``A dancer's
career is very short, and I don't want to get stuck in one place.''
</P>
<P>
   Because the role is so complex, Ms. Durante said she never tires
of dancing Anastasia. ``The more you dance it, the more you search
inside yourself to relate to this woman,'' she said. ``Her story is
a struggle toward the truth, and I think that's what we're all
looking for _ a truth in life.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
