<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-25 20:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0882 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-POLITICS-NYT &LR;      05-25 0654
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-POLITICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
APPEARANCE WITH CLINTON SHOWS HOW FAR GORE NEEDS TO GO 
</HEADLINE>
  (dal) 
 By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   EDINBURG, Texas _ President Clinton and Vice President Al Gore
crossed paths here on Tuesday, a public pairing that inadvertently
highlighted just how far the vice president had to go in matching
his mentor's political skills.
</P>
<P>
   The president, in a warmly received 19-minute introductory
speech, heaped praise on his designated heir. The vice president
followed, giving a speech about economic development in poor
neighborhoods that went on twice as long as Clinton's and was laden
with bureaucratic phrases about applications, blueprints and
empowerment.
</P>
<P>
   It was less than two weeks ago that Clinton openly told a
reporter that he had been worried about Gore's so-far-undeclared _
and unengaging _ presidential campaign and that Gore needed to
loosen up. Tuesday was their first joint appearance since, creating
a moment that invited comparisons.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Cuomo, the secretary of housing and urban development,
who is close to Gore, accompanied the president here for the Fifth
Annual White House Community Empowerment Conference and could not
help but acknowledge the gap in their communications skills.
</P>
<P>
   The president is ``a master communicator of historic
proportions,'' Cuomo said. Gore, he added, meaning to praise him,
is ``a very effective communicator.''
</P>
<P>
   The president and vice president met here at this sun-baked
border town for an event intended to promote the administration's
establishment of ``empowerment zones,'' depressed areas where tax
breaks and investment have lured businesses and helped create
thousands of jobs.
</P>
<P>
   It was also a platform for Gore to promote his candidacy, and he
was the host. Clinton stopped by on his way to a vacation in
Florida to draw press attention to the event.
</P>
<P>
   The president did all he could to give Gore center stage. The
vice president's aides announced the only official ``news'' of the
day, a clarification of a federal regulation to reassure legal
immigrants that applying for welfare would not jeopardize their
immigration status.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the conference setting was an effort to boost Gore's
standing with Hispanic voters. It was set here in the backyard of
Gov. George W. Bush, the leading contender for the Republican
presidential nomination, in a heavily Hispanic area.
</P>
<P>
   The stage was set, unusually, with the official seals of both
the president and the vice president. And Clinton spent most of his
introduction praising Gore as a full and equal partner in the
successes of the empowerment zones that the administration has
created across the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because of his unparalleled combination of creativity and
energy, experience and determination, I asked the vice president to
take the lead in turning this vision we had into reality,'' Clinton
told the audience of a few hundred people assembled from these
zones.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a challenge, as all of you have seen, that he embraced
passionately,'' Clinton said, adding that he was ``profoundly
grateful'' to Gore for leading the way.
</P>
<P>
   Gore spoke for 40 minutes. He hardly mentioned the president
but, like Clinton, he infused his speech with flowing hand
gestures, and personalized his stories, mentioning people who had
benefited from empowerment zones. He told several people's stories
at length.
</P>
<P>
   Cuomo, a confidant of Gore and his debate adviser in 1996,
visited with reporters after the speech to highlight the
empowerment zones, but the talk turned quickly to Gore's
performance. Cuomo, son of another recognized master orator, said
that while Gore's presentation had been effective, the vice
president had ``a certain amount of work to do'' in his speech and
that the subject matter was ``a very factual, technical area.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You have the material you have,'' Cuomo said. ``We all have
our own style.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
