<HEADER>
A0885 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRO     05-25 0697
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE FLEXIBLE ART OF ART CRITICISM
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: This story also moved in the ``a'' national news file)  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sometimes a critic can go both ways:
</P>
<P>
   When the Piazzoni murals in the Old Main Library _ recently
removed from the building that will become the Asian Art Museum _
were unveiled, ``critics who had raised expectations about the
panels fell silent,'' writes  &UR; Anthony Lee &LR;  in his new book,
``Painting on the Left'' (University of California; $50, $24.95
paperback).
</P>
<P>
   ``Their content was difficult to read from a distance,'' writes
the art historian, and the ``murals looked inferior'' to paintings
on display nearby. ``Piazzoni had to wait years for another mural
commission.''
</P>
<P>
   Lee is also author of a letter to the Asian Art Museum pleading
that the murals be allowed to remain. The murals ``immediately
caused great interest,'' he wrote, adding that even the great
muralist  &UR; Diego Rivera &LR;  had realized ``how important they were as
artistic and cultural statements. ... If we today think that San
Francisco holds high status as a significant cultural center, it
was precisely because of works like Piazzoni's, so many years ago,
that such a cultural project began.''
</P>
<P>
   The murals are being prepared for shipment to conservation
laboratories, but a legal suit challenging their move is under way.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; KKK'S OFFER AND PROMISE ARE SPURNED &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Can the Ku Klux Klan help out with highway cleaning? A March 4
letter from an ACLU lawyer in Baltimore to the government of Anne
Arundel County, Md., is reprinted in the latest issue of Harper's.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Dwight Sullivan &LR; , the lawyer, begins by noting that when the
KKK asked to participate in an Adopt-a-Road program, the county
responded by suspending the program.
</P>
<P>
   The KKK agrees, said the lawyer, to replace the ``Ku Klux Klan''
name on the sign with ``The Invincible Empire Realm of Maryland.''
Furthermore, he writes, ``the organization does not plan for its
members to wear robes while engaging in trash collection.''
</P>
<P>
   We talked with Sullivan last week. In response to his letter, he
said, the county changed its suspension of the program to a
permanent shutdown.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MIRREN'S SAD TALE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Helen Mirren &LR;  told the Sunday Mail of London that she is sore
that American actresses occupy their own celebrity tier.
</P>
<P>
   ``My status in Hollywood is zero,'' she said. ``I'm certainly
not on any A-list or any B-, C-, D- or E-list. I want to be
incredibly rich and famous. It would be like nirvana starring in a
big Hollywood movie. Think of the unlimited money. Of course, I
could act them off the screen. What  &UR; Demi Moore &LR;  does is not
acting.''
</P>
<P>
   MSNBC's  &UR; Jeannette Walls &LR;  says Mirren is particularly sore that
Moore,  &UR; Michelle Pfeiffer &LR; ,  &UR; Sharon Stone &LR; ,  &UR; Julia Roberts &LR;  and
 &UR; Meryl Streep &LR;  have been named as possibilities to play Jane
Tennison  &LR; in some kind of movie version of ``Prime Suspect.''
Streep has declined the role, writes Walls, saying that Mirren
plays it better than she could.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ In Belgium,  &UR; Noel Godin &LR; , the custard pie-tosser who targeted
 &UR; Bill Gates &LR;  last year, has formed a political party called TARTE
to participate in regional elections in Brussels in June. A
statement said the party promised nothing, stood for no one and was
totally irresponsible.
</P>
<P>
   _ The U.S. government has fined Harper's Bazaar $31,000 for
sending  &UR; Naomi Campbell &LR;  and  &UR; Kate Moss &LR;  to Cuba for a photo shoot
last year. The fines, levied by the Treasury, were for violating
the U.S. embargo by ``trading with the enemy,'' paying airfares and
hotel and meal expenses. The government was said by the British
newspaper the Observer to have been particularly annoyed about the
supermodels' having tea with  &UR; Fidel Castro &LR; , after which Campbell
announced that he is ``an inspiration to the world.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Prince William &LR; , 16, who wears trunks embroidered W.O.W.
(William of Wales), has been appointed co-captain of the Eton swim
team. &LR;   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd rather know the name of a celebrity's first pet than their
solution to the world's food deficit.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Elizabeth Hurley in US magazine.
</P>
</TEXT>
