<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-25 20:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0886 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ROBERT-LA-FOSSE-DANCE     05-25 0868
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROBERT-LA-FOSSE-DANCE-2TAKES-$ADV30-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A PERFORMER'S SELVES, AT 39, PREPARE THEIR FUTURES  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MAY 30) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Texas)   (af)  
 Susan Reiter is a contributing editor for Dance magazine.  
 By SUSAN REITER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ On a recent Sunday, Robert La Fosse of New York City
Ballet prepared to put on the sleek black wig, orange gloves and
cape of the evil sorcerer Von Rothbart for the final performance of
Peter Martins' ``Swan Lake.'' Monday is the company's one day off,
but his agenda was already full: he was helping to select cast
members for a coming Asian tour of ``West Side Story.''
</P>
<P>
   A few days later, the elaborate wig and makeup of Von Rothbart
packed away, La Fosse looked more like his wholesome, all-American
self in rehearsals for two of the three new ballets, collectively
called ``Duke!'' and set to Duke Ellington's music, that have their
premiere on Thursday as part of City Ballet's program celebrating
jazz. (Also on the bill is a new ballet by Martins to music by
Wynton Marsalis.)
</P>
<P>
   In one studio La Fosse put a cast of 20 through the vigorous
paces of his own new Ellington work, ``Rockin' in Rhythm,'' while
in another he took direction from Susan Stroman, whose Ellington
ballet, ``Blossom Got Kissed,'' features a central duet in which he
partners Maria Kowroski.
</P>
<P>
   A true day off is a rarity for La Fosse. During his 13 years as
a City Ballet principal dancer, the unusually versatile performer
has also appeared on stages far from Lincoln Center. His projects
have included collaborating with choreographers like Margie Gillis
and John Kelly and appearing at the downtown performance venue
Mother, where he recently performed his own interpretation of
Isadora Duncan.
</P>
<P>
   His Broadway resume includes a stint in Bob Fosse's ``Dancin',''
and 10 years ago he won a Tony Award nomination for his multiple
roles in ``Jerome Robbins' Broadway.''
</P>
<P>
   Since 1985, La Fosse has regularly combined performing and
choreographing. The Ellington work will be his seventh for City
Ballet. ``Choreography is not just making up steps,'' he said
during a recent interview at his sunny apartment near Lincoln
Center. ``There's a lot to think about _ music, costuming. I love
the research that goes into a project. I love reading biographies,
and I'm fascinated by digging in, finding out things I didn't
know.''
</P>
<P>
   His current projects have presented ample research
opportunities. He has just begun to plan his choreography for the
Metropolitan Opera's world premiere of John Harbison's ``Great
Gatsby,'' set for December. It will include a tango and a fox trot,
and he is already delighting in the prospect.
</P>
<P>
   ``The dance of that period is so identifiable,'' he said. ``I'm
getting to research and explore time periods I would have wanted to
live through. Also, it's exciting to work on a new opera; there are
no other productions people can compare it to.''
</P>
<P>
   For the Ellington piece, set to four early compositions, La
Fosse visited swing clubs and studied all the films with which
Ellington was involved. His dancers wear jazz shoes and are more
likely to thrust their hands in their pockets than to hold them in
an academically correct position.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm using the more acrobatic kind of swing dancing, with all
the wild lifts,'' he said. ``I want it to have an underground
feeling; at the time, what these dancers were doing was new and
racy.''
</P>
<P>
   He is working closely with William Ivey Long, the costume
designer for all three Ellington works (Garth Fagan is the third
choreographer), offering his own doodles for costume ideas and
asking Long to ``take the period and do your twist on it.''
</P>
<P>
   This work represents a switch from La Fosse's previous City
Ballet choreography, all of which placed considerable demands on
the dancers' classical technique. But a foray into vernacular and
social dancing represents a homecoming for him, and his inclusion
of a tap duet for the twin brothers Kurt and Kyle Froman is a nod
toward his own roots.
</P>
<P>
   Growing up in Beaumont, Texas, he began his dance studies with
acrobatics, tap and jazz, working his way to ballet. ``I did
musicals as a kid,'' he said, ``and there was always a question as
to where I would end up. When I was 17 and moved to New York, I
always thought I would end up on Broadway.''
</P>
<P>
   But the ballet world beckoned; that same year he was offered an
apprenticeship with American Ballet Theater. He spent a few busy
years in the corps, taking advantage of the company's labor lockout
to perform in ``Dancin','' and began acquiring more important roles
once Mikhail Baryshnikov became artistic director in 1980.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was trying to develop American dancers from within the
company, and pulling away from the star system, which worked to my
advantage,'' La Fosse said. His early featured parts included
Americana roles like the second sailor in Robbins' ``Fancy Free''
and the Champion Roper in Agnes De Mille's ``Rodeo'' (where his tap
background came in handy), but an important rite of passage was the
title role in Balanchine's ``Prodigal Son,'' in which he proved
himself as a performer of both technical and dramatic power.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   He remained with Ballet Theater until 1986, taking on most of
the major princely roles in the classics but also proving
especially suited to the works of Robbins and Twyla Tharp. When
Kenneth MacMillan staged his ``Romeo and Juliet'' for the company,
La Fosse was his choice for Romeo on opening night.
</P>
<P>
   Despite flourishing at Ballet Theater, he felt the need to take
a break. Contributing to his decision were burnout from the heavy
touring schedule and his growing interest in choreography. ``There
was an element of wanting to do other things besides the ballet,''
he said. ``I was scared of change, and at the time I didn't know
what I wanted.''
</P>
<P>
   While La Fosse was mulling over his options, an invitation from
Robbins at City Ballet proved irresistible: ``I thought about it
for maybe half a second, and called back the next day,'' La Fosse
said.
</P>
<P>
   A new repertory _ the vast array of works by George Balanchine
and Robbins _ opened to him, as did an increased opportunity to do
more choreographing through City Ballet's American Music Festival
and periodic Diamond Project infusions of new works. He also
choreographed for students at the School of American Ballet.
</P>
<P>
   As his choreographic reputation grew, through works that
reflected sophisticated musicality and craftsmanship, La Fosse
received invitations to create diverse dances like a ``Stars and
Stripes'' spoof for Les Ballets Trockadero de Monte Carlo and an
eveninglong ``Nutcracker,'' set in Russia, for the Wilmington-based
Russian Ballet of Delaware, and opera productions at both Lincoln
Center houses.
</P>
<P>
   But his busy schedule as a choreographer has in no way
diminished his enthusiasm for being onstage. Now 39, he has scaled
back his classical roles, but he still dons the sneakers and blue
jeans for Tony in ``West Side Story Suite'' (in which he can be
seen next week), and has continued to perform in Robbins'
``Concert'' and ``Fancy Free.'' And Von Rothbart was just the
latest addition to his repertory of meaty character roles in City
Ballet's few full-evening works, which he discusses with eager
enthusiasm.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to be able to look like a 16-year-old Tony one night
and to be an old Dr. Coppelius the next,'' he said. ``I love the
contrast. For Von Rothbart, I made a choice not to be physically
forceful, but to be an all-powerful figure who could do almost
anything with just a look.''
</P>
<P>
   With a dancer's nemesis of a 40th birthday looming, La Fosse has
found a comfortable creative balance. ``I am where I want to be,''
he said. ``I still love performing. I'm past the point of having to
figure out something else to do other than dance. I've decided I'm
going to dance as long as I can, but I won't go onstage and dance
roles beyond my means. It's also fascinating to move people around.
As a choreographer, you have total freedom; you're making other
people look good. You're in control.''
</P>
<P>
   A return to Broadway, this time as a choreographer, may be in
his future; he has been working on a musical version of the 1980
film ``Urban Cowboy.'' ``Musical theater is one of the things I
want to do, but it's been hard finding the right project,'' he
said. ``I hope to work in different venues; I don't want to
choreograph just one kind of dance. I want people to recognize my
choreography, but I want to be able to work in different periods,
different styles. There are all kinds of projects to do as a
choreographer, and it can be boring if you limit yourself. This is
all an education.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
