<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-25 20:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0892 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BEST-COMPANIES-LADN     05-25 0725
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEST-COMPANIES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLLEGE STUDENTS SET OFF ON TRIP TO LEARN FIRMS' SECERETS OF
SUCCESS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY ENRIQUE RIVERO  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MALIBU, Calif. -- Three Pepperdine University friends are
hitting the road in search of the perfect company.
</P>
<P>
   Starting today, Alissa Andress and childhood surfing buddies
Nathan Gebhard and Michael Marriner are riding into the heart of
corporate America on a three-month search for what makes America's
50 or so best companies tick.
</P>
<P>
   They'll tour the companies and sit down with various company
heads, grilling them on the corporate structure, employee benefits
and anything else that contributes toward creating a successful
business.
</P>
<P>
   They'll be traveling with ease in a recreational vehicle, hooked
up to the Internet and sending out regular missives on their
findings.
</P>
<P>
   They also intend to write a book about the trip.
</P>
<P>
   It's a way to gain insight into successful corporate structures
directly from the people who run the companies, said Andress, 23,
who graduated in April with a degree in international business.
They hope to pass on what they learn to the public and also use
those lessons when they strike out on their own business ventures.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a textbook teaching me, not a teacher, but real
people,'' Andress said. ``Also, it's an amazing opportunity. How
many 23-year-olds get to travel around the country in a RV all
summer, all paid-for? I get to write a book at 23. I can't imagine
anything more fun than that.''
</P>
<P>
   The trip is patterned on a course taught by a former Pepperdine
business professor who has since moved to another university, said
Gebhard, 22, a business administration major who just completed his
junior year.
</P>
<P>
   To finance the trip, the trio obtained sponsorship from a number
of firms, including Monster.com, an Internet job search service
that is providing a link for the trio's Web page. Other sponsors
include Internet service provider Mindspring, and computer and
software giants Sun Microsystems and Microsoft Corp.
</P>
<P>
   This won't be the first time Andress, Gebhard and Marriner have
visited companies across the nation.
</P>
<P>
   During their last summer break, Gebhard and Marriner traveled
the western United States, from Los Angeles to Seattle, across to
Montana and on down to Utah, visiting companies such as Boeing Co.
and Nucor Steel's mill in Plymouth, Utah.
</P>
<P>
   And during winter break, Gebhard and Andress visited some
high-tech companies in Northern California.
</P>
<P>
   Each company they visited had its own formula for success. For
example, Nucor Steel had only four layers of management, ``which
translates into: a guy sweeping the floor is only three promotions
away from the CEO,'' Gebhard said.
</P>
<P>
   Also, the employee pay system was based on a combination of
straight hourly pay and productivity, which encouraged employees to
work harder. This, they say, has resulted in a $4.2 billion company
that made No. 374 on the latest Fortune 500 list.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was incredible, we learned a lot of stuff,'' Gebhard said.
``Each company had its own individual lesson.''
</P>
<P>
   They learned so much that they wanted to do it again this
summer, only more extensively. The question, however, was how to
finance the trip, which was ``way too expensive'' for some college
students, said Marriner, 21, a biology and sports medicine double
major.
</P>
<P>
   The answer came to Marriner and Gebhard after a day of surfing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're sitting in the jacuzzi brainstorming . . . and we came
up with the idea to gain sponsorship, to turn the interviews into a
book and place them on a Web site,'' Marriner said.
</P>
<P>
   The Web site -- roadtrip.monster.com -- will serve as a way to
keep the public up to date on the trio's findings, once it's
operational on Friday. It will also allow Web readers to pose their
own queries to the company heads. Those questions will be taken
into the interviews and answers will posted on the site.
</P>
<P>
   ``So basically it's almost a reader-driven project,'' Marriner
said.
</P>
<P>
   The trio is working with several editors on a book deal.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the three plan to use what they learn to start a
business together someday.
</P>
<P>
   ``My goal is to take this whole experience and put the best
company in the world together,'' Gebhard said.
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
