<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-25 20:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0904 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHINA-SPY-BOS &LR;      05-25 1117
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-SPY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPORT DETAILS ALLEGED N-SPYING BY CHINA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANN SCALES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ China has stolen secret information on every
currently deployed warhead in the US ballistic missile arsenal _
and has accumulated details about the neutron bomb, which the
United States has not yet deployed _ according to a congressional
investigation of Chinese espionage.
</P>
<P>
   The three-volume, 700-page report released Tuesday produced
swift and widespread reaction, with Republicans and Democrats
conceding that the allegations were indeed serious, though they
differed over what the long-term consequences would be for
relations between the United States and China.
</P>
<P>
   Representative Christopher Cox, the Republican from California
who headed the House select committee that undertook the
investigation, said the alleged thefts began in the late 1970s,
adding that it is ``exceptionally likely'' that China's spying
``continues to this very day.''
</P>
<P>
   The declassified report detailed what Representative Norman
Dicks, a Washington Democrat on the panel, said was ``no doubt one
of the worst counter-intelligence failures in the nation's
history,'' but the findings were conveyed in a ``worse-case
fashion.''
</P>
<P>
   With US-China relations already frayed by NATO's bombing of the
Chinese Embassy in Belgrade, the panel's conclusions brought fresh
concerns over such issues as whether China should gain entry into
the World Trade Organization.
</P>
<P>
   The findings also increased calls among lawmakers, mostly
Republicans, for the resignation of Attorney General Janet Reno and
national security adviser Samuel R. ``Sandy'' Berger. Republicans
accused the administration of being slow to respond to earlier
reports of Chinese espionage. Democrats shot back that Republicans
should also share the blame since they were briefed on the problem
and also failed to act.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton administration officials emphasized that since the
report was completed earlier this year steps have been taken to
beef up security at the nation's nuclear laboratories. The report
was not released until Tuesday, and about a third of it remains
classified, including some details about the espionage
investigation at the Los Alamos weapons laboratory in New Mexico
where a scientist was fired in March after being under suspicion of
espionage for more than three years.
</P>
<P>
   Energy Secretary Bill Richardson, whose agency oversees the
nuclear labs, warned of ``over-sensationalizing'' the report's
findings. ``There is no evidence of a wholesale loss of
information,'' he said. ``Not every allegation is a proven fact.''
</P>
<P>
   In Beijing, the foreign ministry spokesman Zhu Bangzao
reiterated the Chinese government's earlier denial of the spying
charge, calling the allegations in the report ``groundless.''
</P>
<P>
   Zhu said the report's authors manufactured the allegations to
poison US-China relations in a ``despicable attempt'' to divert
attention from the May 7 bombing of the Chinese Embassy.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton, attending an empowerment zone conference in
Texas, said he agreed with the ``overwhelming majority'' of the
committee's recommendations for tightening security at nuclear
labs. He also said he was ``particularly appreciative'' of the way
the bipartisan panel conducted its work.
</P>
<P>
   He said his administration was ``moving aggressively to tighten
security.'' Clinton noted he increased funding for
counter-intelligence in weapons labs to almost $40 million from
$2.6 million through an executive order signed in Feburary, and his
administration has conducted a major overhaul of security at
nuclear labs.
</P>
<P>
   He added that he strongly believes it was in the country's best
interest to continue its relations with China.
</P>
<P>
   But Senator Richard Lugar of Indiana, a ranking Republican on
the Senate Foreign Relations and Intelligence committees, said
Congress and Clinton should recognize that the ``United States may
now be at signficantly greater risk from a Chinese ballistic
missile attack.''
</P>
<P>
   Senator Bob Smith, a New Hampshire Republican who also is a
candidate for president, said the report was devastating.
``Somebody is going to jail over this,'' he said. ``This is not
going to be accepted.''
</P>
<P>
   According to the report, China ``mounted a widespread effort to
obtain US military technologies by any means _ legal or illegal.''
</P>
<P>
   China's ``insatiable appetite'' for US technology allowed it to
leap ``in a handful of years from 1950s-era strategic nuclear
capabilities'' to a position of having nuclear design information
``on par with our own.''
</P>
<P>
   The stolen information includes classified information on seven
US thermonuclear warheads, the report said. The information was
believed to have been obtained through Chinese espionage activities
that occurred in the 1980s, although the theft was not discovered
until the mid-1990s.
</P>
<P>
   Also stolen was classified design information for the ``neutron
bomb,'' which neither the United States, nor any other nation, has
deployed.
</P>
<P>
   The report singled out as particularly damaging the loss of
design material for the W-88, a miniaturized, tapered warhead
believed to be the most sophisticated nuclear weapon the United
States has ever built.
</P>
<P>
   The report also said that two US satellite manufacturers, Loral
Corp. and Hughes Electronics, ignored legal requirements and
allowed China to obtain information critical to its ballistic
missile program.
</P>
<P>
   The committee concluded that China will exploit elements of that
stolen US thermonuclear weapons information in its future design,
including a weapon that could be deployed as early as 2002.
</P>
<P>
   The panel of five Republicans and four Democrats found that most
thefts had occurred at US nuclear weapon labs at Los Alamos,
Lawrence Livermore, Oak Ridge and Sandia.
</P>
<P>
   Senator John F. Kerry said the report would ``make things
rougher'' between the United States and China. ``It has the
potential to have very damaging consequences, and it will depend on
level heads and leadership to avoid allowing us to dig ourselves a
hole here,'' said Kerry, a member of the Foreign Relations and
Senate Select committees.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to be very careful in how we proceed,'' Kerry
continued. ``China is much too important and the long-term
relationship is much too important to allow short-term politics to
manage this.''
</P>
<P>
   Senate Minority Leader Thomas A. Daschle said ``it was too
early'' to determine whether the committee's conclusions would hurt
China's efforts to join the World Trade Organization. ``Clearly
this is not something that has helped us in the effort to move the
trade legislation along,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
