<SLUG> BC-BUSINESS-TRAVEL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS TRAVEL: DISCOUNTED HOTEL ROOMS DO EXIST IN NEW YORK CITY 
</HEADLINE>
  (Duplication warning: also moving in `t' category) 
(dal) 
 By JANE L. LEVERE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Discounted hotel rates are currently available in New York City,
despite public perception to the contrary.
</P>
<P>
   According to Sean Hennessey, New York-based director of the
hospitality and leisure practice of PricewaterhouseCoopers,
occupancy rates at Manhattan hotels in the first quarter of this
year dropped to the high 70 percent range from 83 percent during
the comparable period a year earlier. This has led approximately
one-fifth of New York hotels _ particularly the larger ones _ to
lower their room rates, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some hotels are making their discounted rooms available longer
than they typically would,'' he said. ``If business travelers check
around, they are more likely to find last-minute bargains than they
would a year ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Another way to get a less expensive rate is to stay at one of
the new or refurbished hotels that have recently opened or will
soon; many offer introductory discounts. Following are some of
these hotels:
</P>
<P>
   The Benjamin, at 125 E. 50th St. between Lexington and Third
Avenues, is the newest of the 10 hotels owned by Manhattan East
Suite Hotels. Formerly the Hotel Beverly, the Benjamin has
undergone a $30 million renovation. It now has 209 rooms, including
98 one- and two-bedroom suites; Larry Forgione's restaurant, An
American Place, will move there next month. The Benjamin offers
special rates, good only on Saturdays and Sundays through the end
of the year, that range from $229 to $549 a night.
</P>
<P>
   The Holiday Inn Wall Street, a boutique hotel owned by RD
Management, a New York real estate developer, is situated at 15
Gold St., three blocks north of Wall Street. The hotel, which will
open next month, has 138 rooms, all with high-speed Internet
connections; 8-foot desks; safes; televisions with separate
Internet access, and CD players. Introductory rates, good through
Labor Day, range from $189 to $240 during the week and from $150 to
$225 on weekends.
</P>
<P>
   The Iroquois, a 114-room hotel at 49 W. 44th St. between Fifth
and Sixth Avenues owned by hotelier Shimmie Horn, is undergoing a
$13-million renovation transforming it from what management calls a
``standard'' hotel to a ``luxury boutique'' hotel in the style of a
private European mansion. A gourmet restaurant, whose chef formerly
worked at Lespinasse, will open in September. Rates through the end
of August are $169 for a deluxe room or $299 for a suite; both
include breakfast.
</P>
<P>
   The Time, a 192-room boutique hotel at 224 W. 49th St. between
Broadway and Eighth Avenue, is owned by New York-based Hampshire
Hotels and Resorts. The hotel was designed by Adam Tihany, whose
other projects include New York restaurants Jean Georges, Le Cirque
2000 and Remi. The Time's restaurant is Palladin, run by chef
Jean-Louis Palladin, formerly of Jean-Louis at the Watergate in
Washington, D.C. Rates through Aug. 31 range from $165 to $245.
</P>
<P>
   Although all of the new or refurbished hotels' discounts are
available through the summer, Hennessey warned that other
discounted rates now offered by more established hotels might not
be around much longer. ``Most hotels are saying their summer
tourist business and fall convention business appear strong again
this year,'' he said. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
