<DOCNO> NYT19990525.0350 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-25 20:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0909 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DIDO-RECORDINGS-2TAKE     05-25 0808
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIDO-RECORDINGS-2TAKES-$ADV30-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RAISING THE STAKES IN A PURCELL OPERA  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MAY 30) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By ALLAN KOZINN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When performers make new recording alliances, they often start
by revisiting favorite works. Ideally, they do so for good reasons:
their ideas have changed, or scholarship has yielded new
perspective on a work. Just as likely, though, the motivation is
more mundane.
</P>
<P>
   The earlier recording may have run its course in sales and been
deleted or reduced to midprice, and the new contract may offer more
favorable royalty provisions.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the terms of the new agreement between the conductor
Andrew Parrott and Sony, Parrott's second reading of Purcell's
``Dido and Aeneas'' (Sony Classical SK 62993; CD) is sufficiently
different from his classic 1981 Chandos recording, for better and
worse, that he cannot be charged with reduplication of the more
cynical kind.
</P>
<P>
   The new ``Dido'' may, in fact, be a move to keep big-label
cynicism at bay. When Parrott signed with Sony, there was less talk
of major repertory than of his crossover potential, so perhaps he
reasoned that a success with a work that had been a springboard for
him in the past might forestall the indignity of recording
``Baroque Tango Appalachia: The Film Score.''
</P>
<P>
   When Parrott and the Taverner Players and Choir made their first
``Dido and Aeneas'' recording (now on a midprice CD from Chandos),
period-instrument Purcell was largely uncharted territory. The only
competing gut-string, low-vibrato ``Dido,'' in fact, was a
vigorous, idiosyncratic 1979 recording by Joel Cohen and the Boston
Camerata on Harmonia Mundi France (never transferred to CD).
</P>
<P>
   Cohen took chances: a minimal string complement (one player to a
part) was augmented by flute, oboe and, briefly, tambourine, and
both the Sorceress and the Sailor were assigned to male voices.
Some of these touches seemed eccentric at the time, yet as
period-instrument ``Dido'' recordings have become commonplace,
other performers have adopted them, and musicological
justifications have sprouted, mostly after the fact.
</P>
<P>
   Parrott's 1981 ``Dido'' was more orthodox in its use of strings
only _ the instrumentation given in the Tenbury manuscript of 1777,
the earliest surviving score of this 1689 opera _ with two or three
players to a part, and harpsichord, theorbo and guitar in the
continuo group.
</P>
<P>
   His advances included a realization of the guitar dance
suggested after Belinda's ``Pursue thy conquest,'' the
interpolation of a hornpipe from ``The Married Beau'' as the finale
of the second act, and the execution of the thunder and ``horrid
music'' (ad libitum orchestral noise) called for at the end of the
Witches' scene.
</P>
<P>
   New as they were to disk, these ideas had been floating around
for some time. The ground bass figure for the guitar dance and the
adaptation of the hornpipe are included in the 1961 Novello edition
of the score, prepared by Margaret Laurie and Thurston Dart. The
demand for a thunderstorm is in the libretto. In modern-instrument
versions, conductors were inconsistent about the hornpipe (most
skipped it) and ignored the guitar piece and the storm completely.
</P>
<P>
   The real charm of Parrott's 1981 recording was its cast,
borrowed wholesale from the Consort of Musicke, then a young
early-music group with a superb Dowland series to its credit.
Breaking from the tradition of regal, almost Victorian portrayals
of the role of Dido, Emma Kirkby sang it with an energy, brightness
and vocal compactness that made the doomed Carthaginian Queen sound
almost girlish.
</P>
<P>
   Judith Nelson's equally clear-toned Belinda abetted that
characterization, and David Thomas showed Aeneas to be thoroughly
spineless, a plaything of the Witches and unable to sustain his
resolve after the rebuke from Dido.
</P>
<P>
   Acting on the assumption then current that ``Dido and Aeneas''
was composed for Josiah Priest's school for girls _ a notion
recently supplanted by the theory that the work may have had a more
professional performance for a royal audience a few weeks before _
Parrott made the Sorceress a mezzo-soprano and gave the other roles
to sopranos.
</P>
<P>
   For his new recording, Parrott has reconsidered everything and
nothing. Orchestral textures, vocal assignments and phrasings are
revised, yet the spirit and the overall shape of the recording
closely match those of the 1981 account.
</P>
<P>
   In several details, Parrott now follows Cohen: he has scaled
back the ensemble to single strings (though no winds), and in the
dance that follows the ``Fear no danger'' chorus, he adds a
tambourine to evoke a livelier, more rustic spirit than one hears
on his Chandos disk. And now, with musicological backing that Cohen
didn't have, Parrott has reassigned male voices to the Sorceress
and the Sailor.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Purely in instrumental terms, the new recording is generally an
improvement. Its most strikingly fresh characteristic is its string
timbre. Gone is the comparatively mellow sound of the earlier disk;
here, the Taverner strings play with a bright edge and acidic bite.
The ornamentation, both vocal and instrumental, is also more
florid, and the continuo players are more overtly pictorial; an
example is the rolling harpsichord arpeggiation that evokes the
unfurling flags, streamers and sails the Sorceress sings about.
</P>
<P>
   Both the guitar dance and the ``Married Beau'' hornpipe are
retained: this despite the assertion in the liner notes that the
interpolation was a decision made ``in the edition prepared for
this recording,'' as if it were something new.
</P>
<P>
   Still, in the way that almost everything has been magnified
here, these dances appear in versions that are livelier and more
fully fleshed out than their 1981 counterparts.
</P>
<P>
   Parrott's casting this time is less felicitous. Emily Van Evera,
one of the Enchantresses in 1981, has been promoted to Dido. She
has in common with Ms. Kirkby a light timbre and a judicious sense
of when to use vibrato, and her Dido is similarly youthful. But
hers is a more mannered portrayal. She is overwrought and
melodramatic both in her opening consultation with Belinda and at
the end, as she heads into her final lament.
</P>
<P>
   She is also given to little slides and dynamic manipulations
that seem interesting at first but quickly grow tiresome,
especially since the recording seems to make her hairpin accents in
the middle of words sound unattractively peaky.
</P>
<P>
   The Aeneas, Ben Parry, has a pleasant, light baritone, but apart
from matching this Dido's exaggerations, he offers little sense of
what Aeneas is about. The rest of the cast sings ably but without
particular distinction, although Hayden Andrews, as the Sorceress,
and Douglas Wooten, as the Sailor, follow the post-Cohen tradition
of characterizing their roles by toying with intonation and
accents.
</P>
<P>
   Where Parrott proves really daring is in his use of sound
effects. Indeed, his innovations here lead one to look back to his
earlier disk, and Cohen's, as the first bids in a curious
musicological poker game.
</P>
<P>
   After Cohen opened with his single strings, winds and male
singers, Parrott raised him a thunderclap and a couple of dances.
Nikolaus Harnoncourt (on Teldec) passed on the thunder but saw
Cohen's winds and raised his colleagues a cast of singers whose
English was nearly impenetrable, evoking memories of the 1951
Kirsten Flagstad recording. William Christie, in the first of his
two ``Dido'' recordings (Harmonia Mundi France), called
Harnoncourt's accented singers and Parrott's storm; in his second
``Dido'' (Erato), he called Cohen's single strings.
</P>
<P>
   Trevor Pinnock (Archiv) passed on Cohen's added flute, but saw
his oboe and his male Sorceress, and raised him a bassoon and an
oboe da caccia as well as a full-fledged string section and an
artistocratic Dido in Anne Sofie von Otter.
</P>
<P>
   Christopher Hogwood (L'Oiseau-Lyre) saw Pinnock's big string
section and got serious with the sound effects, raising everyone
(including Purcell) a thunderstorm that began (italics)before(end
italics) the Witches' scene and returned as late as ``Haste, haste
to town'' at the end of the subsequent scene.
</P>
<P>
   Parrott, who brought the storm to ``Dido'' recordings in the
first place, was not about to stand for such thunder-stealing. On
his remake, he sees Hogwood's early storm as well as the
recurrences up to ``Haste, haste'' and raises him some birds.
</P>
<P>
   That's right, birds. At the start of the grove scene _ just
after the violent thunderstorm conjured by the Witches and called
for by Purcell, and a few moments before the gratuitous one at
``Haste, haste'' _ he sets the idyllic tone of Dido and Aeneas'
country frolic with a few seconds of chirping.
</P>
<P>
   One of Parrott's colleagues is bound to follow this by recording
the ruffling of the unfurling sails and banners at the start of the
last act. When someone hits on the idea of ending the work with the
sound of Dido roasting on an open pyre, it will be time to cash in
the chips.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
