<SLUG> BC-INDIA-GANDHI-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GANDHI RETURNS TO LEAD THE CONGRESS PARTY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds, fixes garble in 4th graf.)  (dal) 
 By CELIA W. DUGGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW DELHI, India _ Sonia Gandhi, the Italian-born heiress to an
Indian dynasty, made a triumphant return Tuesday as leader of the
political party that has ruled the nation for most of the last half
century and is now trying to regain power.
</P>
<P>
   Her followers, who came by bus, train and plane from across
India, cheered and chanted in ecstatic celebration.
</P>
<P>
   A combative, impassioned Mrs. Gandhi, who quit as president of
the Congress Party only a week ago after three party leaders
opposed her prime ministerial candidacy because of her foreign
birth, said an outpouring of support from the party's members had
persuaded her to withdraw her resignation.
</P>
<P>
   In a voice choked with feeling, Mrs. Gandhi, 52, staked her
claim to being an Indian patriot. The country adopted her 31 years
ago when she married Rajiv Gandhi, she said.
</P>
<P>
   She recalled the assassinations of her mother-in-law, Prime
Minister Indira Gandhi, in 1984 and her husband, a former prime
minister who was only 46 when he was slain in 1991. And she
witheringly noted that the same three men who now raised questions
about her Italian origins had only a year earlier asked her to head
the Congress Party, then in a slow dance toward oblivion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I became a wife here, a mother here, a widow here, too, right
before your eyes,'' she said, speaking in Hindi. ``The greatest
daughter of this country, Indiraji, breathed her last in my arms.
Every drop of blood in me says this country is mine. This country
is mine.''
</P>
<P>
   She defiantly said she would not reply to those who have
questioned her patriotism. She was apparently alluding to critics
who have asked why she waited until she had been in India 15 years
before she became a citizen and suggested that she may never have
renounced her Italian citizenship (a charge her friends say is
false).
</P>
<P>
   ``The people will give a resounding reply to that,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   In explaining her resignation, Mrs. Gandhi said she had felt
hurt and betrayed when the three men, who had supported her as
president of the party, publicly opposed having anyone other than a
native Indian serve as prime minister. They sought to sow doubts
about her loyalty to India in her followers' minds, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought that this whole fight is mine alone,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But the people who have flocked to her residence from all over
the country in the last week convinced her she was far from alone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to come to know who my true friends are,'' she said.
``You have again revived my hopes.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I will not let you down.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Gandhi arrived at the packed Talkatora Stadium, where
hundreds of members of the All India Congress Committee, a national
body of Congress members, had been waiting for her for an hour and
a half. Thousands of her supporters milled around outside, and
everyone who entered the stadium was searched.
</P>
<P>
   Security precautions delayed her arrival. Congress Party
officials say the government has warned Mrs. Gandhi recently of
threats on her life. The Hindu, a sober, English-language daily,
reported today that the Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam, a Sri
Lankan rebel group, were suspected of plotting to kill her. The
same group was implicated in her husband's assassination.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Gandhi, whose friends fear for her safety now that she is
in politics, did not renounce the possibility that she will be
prime minister if the Congress Party wins in general elections in
September and October against its archrival, the Hindu nationalist
Bharatiya Janata Party.
</P>
<P>
   The Congress members elected to parliament would chose the prime
minister, she said. She did not need to add that they would surely
pick her.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now nobody will dare go against her because the grass roots
are with her,'' said Ajay Singh, a Congress assemblyman from the
state of Haryana.
</P>
<P>
   The rage of the audience against the three Congressmen who
challenged her was palpable. The three, led by Sharad Pawar, a
powerful politician from the western state of Maharashtra, were
expelled from the party last week and say they will soon form a new
political party.
</P>
<P>
   When a Congress Party official from Maharashtra, Ranjit
Deshmukh, added a respectful ``ji'' to the end of Pawar's name
while delivering his speech, shouts of protest rose from the
audience. No ``ji'' for Pawar, they demanded. Only when Deshmukh
called the three men traitors did the crowd roar its approval.
</P>
<P>
   The stadium, both inside and out, was strung with banners and
decorated with billboards. ``No Soniaji. No Congress,'' said one.
``For the Sake of the Motherland, Soniaji, Please Come Back,'' said
another.
</P>
<P>
   A larger-than-life likeness of Mrs. Gandhi, clad in a sari,
loomed benevolently over the stadium floor, packed with Congress
men and women dressed in khadi, the white homespun cotton that is
their usual garb.
</P>
<P>
   When she finally arrived on the stage, where dozens of
high-ranking Congress officials sat cross-legged on white pillows,
chants of ``Sonia Gandhi, Zinzabad!'' or ``Long Live Sonia
Gandhi!'' rocked the stadium.
</P>
<P>
   From the dais, she waved to the audience, and it waved back to
her.
</P>
<P>
   A parade of speakers then swore their allegiance to her, each
more extravagant than the last.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wherever your sweat falls,'' vowed Subash Chopra, president of
the Delhi Congress Committee, ``we Congressmen will sacrifice our
blood.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
