<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-25 20:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0915 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AULENTI-ARCHITECTURE-     05-25 1133
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AULENTI-ARCHITECTURE-2TAKES-$ADV30-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DESIGNING FOR A WORLD THAT'S ALREADY FILLED  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MAY 30) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By HERBERT MUSCHAMP   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   They say that anyone can nominate candidates for the Pritzker
Architecture Prize. May I propose Gae Aulenti? The great Milanese
architect has just broken ground for her first major project in the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   She already has as distinguished a body of work to her credit as
any Pritzker Prize winner. Not incidentally, she is also the most
important female architect since the beginning of time. Think about
it.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Aulenti's current project, the San Francisco Museum of Asian
Art, is the most recent in a series of older buildings that she has
remodeled into art museums. The series includes two in Paris and
one each in Venice, Barcelona, Istanbul and Milan. These projects,
along with her stage designs, are the works for which she is best
known.
</P>
<P>
   Her work can be crudely termed adaptive reuse. It has also been
described as interior design, a loaded term that may help explain
why Ms. Aulenti has been overlooked by the Pritzker jury.
Traditionally, interior design, like interior decoration, has been
considered a woman's profession. Architecture, meanwhile, is a guy
thing: big, new buildings, designed from top to toe.
</P>
<P>
   But in recent decades, there's been a gradual shift away from
these stereotypes. Interior architecture, as it is sometimes
called, has become a specialty for many talented architects. These
include quite a few male-female partnerships, including Williams &AMP;
Tsien, Smith Miller &AMP; Hawkinson, Hodgetts &AMP; Fung, and Morris &AMP;
Saito. Stage and exhibition design are also fields in which
architects have produced inventive work.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Aulenti can now be seen as a pioneer in these fields. She
has helped gain recognition for the interior as a ground where
architects can explore issues of context, history, perception and
public space. In the process, she has developed new ways of
thinking about designing for a built-up world. For an increasing
number of her colleagues, architecture has become a Gae thing.
</P>
<P>
   The San Francisco Museum of Asian Art will be housed in a
Beaux-Arts edifice in the Civic Center. The museum's collection,
now displayed at the de Young Museum in Golden Gate Park, includes
more than 12,000 artifacts, one of the largest holdings of Asian
art in the western world.
</P>
<P>
   Scheduled for completion in 2002, the new museum does not easily
lend itself to prior appraisal. Ms. Aulenti's work is spare,
enveloping and experiential. It reckons with light and shade,
openness and enclosure, stillness and procession. But it is not too
soon to reflect on the meanings that the San Francisco project may
reveal about Ms. Aulenti's work as a whole.
</P>
<P>
   In an introduction to ``Gae Aulenti,'' a 1993 monograph, Ms.
Aulenti states the three principles that have guided her work:
analysis, synthesis and what she calls the prophetic capacity.
There is nothing startlingly fresh about the first two, but her
idea of prophecy offers an intriguing clue to what makes her work
distinctive.
</P>
<P>
   On the most literal level, it describes an architect's ability
to foresee a place where none exists, or a new kind of place on the
site of an old one. Beyond that, the prophetic capacity refers to
an architect's ability to see herself as part of a cultural
continuum.
</P>
<P>
   ``If cultural tradition is not something that one passively
inherits but something that one builds day by day,'' she writes,
``then this third ability must be an aspiration to create an effect
of cultural continuity, to construct its forms and its figures with
personal, contemporary content.''
</P>
<P>
   I interpret this to mean, in part, that architects face the
Proustian task of exploring the relationship between duration and
time. Calendar time and cultural memory are different, though they
may overlap. Thus, the gigantic clock that faces visitors entering
the Musee d'Orsay may be something more than a fortuitous relic
from the time when the building was a train station.
</P>
<P>
   It's a reminder of what Ms. Aulenti is up to. People go to the
d'Orsay not to catch trains but to catch up with themselves, to
glimpse the present through the medium of time past.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Aulenti's work has, in fact, been prophetic. No architect
has a keener vision of the industrial city's transformation into a
cultural matrix. None has worked more intelligently to bring that
transformation about. This is the great story of the d'Orsay, her
best known work to date.
</P>
<P>
   Itself an industrial artifact (in effect, the largest object in
the museum's collection), the d'Orsay train station had become
obsolete 30 years after its completion in 1900. The platforms were
too short for the longer trains made possible by technological
advance. For years it stood derelict. Perhaps it was always
destined to be the museum Ms. Aulenti made of it, an unforeseen
consequence of the lofty place to which industrial society elevated
cultural achievement.
</P>
<P>
   One sees that loftiness in works exhibited throughout the
museum, but at two points it strikes with comic force. One is the
model of the Paris Opera and the Haussmann boulevards that radiate
outward from it. Set beneath glass on the ground floor, this
display is a Wim Wenders moment. The viewer commands the aerial
view of the angels, deities and muses with which 19th-century
architects furnished the urban skyline as tributes to the life of
the mind. The Opera was their Apollo Space Program. Coming in for a
landing!
</P>
<P>
   Then, ascending to the museum's restaurant, on a staircase that
leads past the gear box of another huge clock, you go higher into
angel territory, and lunch amid the heavenly creatures of Gabriel
Ferrier's murals. With a glass of wine, you can look past Ferrier's
pompier style.
</P>
<P>
   The industrial society gave birth to these angels, but the
machines are long gone, sacrificed by the cult of progress that
once worshiped them. The muses have taken over the building. In
fact, it has been renamed for them.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Aulenti has been prophetic, too, in recognizing that a major
function of the post-industrial city is to hold opposites together
_ to collapse the dualisms permeating modern culture. At the
d'Orsay she neither avoids nor exaggerates the difference between
old and new.
</P>
<P>
   On the ground floor are few signs that we typically read as
modern. There are no white panels to stop the eye, no floating
partitions, no chrome-plated steel. The free-standing walls take
their spatial rhythm from the building's side arches but in no way
mimic their style. The walls are made of stone, a material that
evokes permanence, but their low height and mazelike organization
suggests the flexibility of a temporary exhibition.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In her redesign of the Milan Trienalle galleries at the Palazzo
dell' Arte, Ms. Aulenti renews a truce between neo-classicism and
Rationalism, Italy's warring architectural factions when Giovanni
Muzio designed the building in 1931. Ms. Aulenti's gallery
partitions, aligned with columns and windows in Muzio's building,
take the form of extruded columns. Their silhouette alludes to
Muzio's neo-classicism, but also derive from functional
requirements.
</P>
<P>
   The projecting ``capitals'' house lighting, air-conditioning and
security devices. The partitions stop well short of the ceiling.
This emphasizes that they perform no structural function and also
reveals the industrial esthetic of Muzio's coffered concrete
floors.
</P>
<P>
   In 1993, at the Guggenheim Museum in New York, Ms. Aulenti
staged an interplay between continuity and disruption. Enormous,
cantilevered chevrons plunged into the heart of Wright's sacred
void. On the ramp, the slabs that supported the chevrons
interrupted a coil that Wright had designed to evoke an ``unbroken
wave.''
</P>
<P>
   But Ms. Aulenti's pointed shapes echoed the hair-pin braces in
the skylight of Wright's rotunda. And her composition, like
Wright's, was as much sculpture as architecture.
</P>
<P>
   I've seen only one of Ms. Aulenti's stage designs, for Rossini's
``Viaggio a Reims.'' As staged at the Vienna Staatsoper, where I
saw it performed in 1989, the production oscillated between the
poles of illusion and fact. Ms. Aulenti used the stage more as a
building site than as a framework for pictorial effects.
</P>
<P>
   There was a fixed set of white platforms and stairs, chairs that
one might see in a contemporary board room and screens for
projecting live-action video of the performers. The performers were
in period dress, but in Ms. Aulenti's straightforward setting a
viewer was more than usually conscious that they were opera singers
as well as characters. Her design was less illusionistic than the
theater.
</P>
<P>
   Speculation of the Week: Does Ms. Aulenti consult the ``I
Ching''? The Taoist yin-yang symbol occasionally appears in her
drawings. This symbolism casts her belief in prophecy in an Eastern
light. And it suggests that the San Francisco Museum of Asian Art
will be something special in her work. Here, visitors will confront
that most powerfully global dualism, East and West.
</P>
<P>
   The museum will be housed in the city's former Main Library,
part of the Beaux Arts Civic Center that includes city hall and the
Opera House. This complex is the Western tradition at its most
grandiose: imperial Rome by the bay. The relocation sets the stage
for encounters between the Western container and its Eastern
contents.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the building and its contents were givens. This is
also true of Ms. Aulenti's other museum projects. Should she be
given credit for effects that result from facts over which she had
no control? Including the fact that these remodelings are the kind
of commissions that have come her way? Or that they reflect
curatorial as well as architectural decisions? These are, after
all, accidents, or coincidences, the circumstances that arise in
the course of any professional career.
</P>
<P>
   But if it does its work properly, a museum of Asian art should
invite alternative ways of thinking about concepts like accident,
coincidence, circumstance and causality. Asian art is religious
art. Its esthetic qualities are inseparable from the spiritual and
philosophical outlook it embodies.
</P>
<P>
   A Chinese landscape painting, for example, is a product of
meditation. The painter goes out to a place and may spend the
better part of a lifetime trying to discern the nature beneath
appearances. The painting records the painter's quest for union
with that nature.
</P>
<P>
   Substitute culture for nature, and you gain insight into Ms.
Aulenti's approach. Her career has led her to contemplate
buildings: cultural fragments, pieces of the city in a dense,
contracting world. Then she has re-rendered these places through
contemporary eyes.
</P>
<P>
   There isn't a more urbane sensibility at work in architecture
today. Or as ``The Book of Changes'' might put it: the Receptive,
changing to the Creative. Sublime success. Furthering through
perseverance.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
