   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service will move the following
entertainment/arts articles this week for release Sunday, May 30,
1999. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ENTERTAINMENT &AMP; ARTS (Moved in `e' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FEATURE stories &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   INSTALLATION-ARTIST (Undated) _ Ann Hamilton, the installation
artist who will represent the United States in the 48th Venice
Biennale, which opens on June 13, is a slight woman. Dressed in the
art-world uniform, black pants and jacket, her salt-and-pepper hair
closely cropped, she is a casual, earnest person who occasionally
flashes an impish smile. But if she has the look of a pixie, she
also has a mind as imposing as an Oxford don's _ and much more
imaginative. Among the many honors on her resume is a much-coveted
``genius'' award from the MacArthur Foundation. Her works are known
for being sensory and cerebral at the same time. By Judith H.
Dobrzynski.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FILM AND VIDEO &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SHAKESPEARE-FILMS (Undated) _ The Shakespeare thing. Is it out
of control? Like lemmings, Hollywood's bankable are rushing to
throw themselves into the sea. Right now, Michelle Pfeiffer's
Titania, queen of the fairies, is flitting through Michael
Hoffman's ``Midsummer Night's Dream'' in starlit freefall. Soon to
follow are Jessica Lange's Tamora, vicious Queen of the Goths, in
Julie Taymor's cinematic ``Titus Andronicus,'' and Alicia
Silverstone as the by no means clueless Princess of France in
Kenneth Branagh's updated ``Love's Labour's Lost.'' The industry is
smitten, cranking out Shakespeare as if there were no tomorrow. By
Matthew Gurewitsch.
</P>
<P>
   CANNES-FILM-FEST (Cannes, France) _ The top official accolades
at the Cannes International Film Festival were awarded to two
intense, painful French-language films dealing with hard lives in
lonely surroundings. The Palme d'Or winner, the Belgian film
``Rosetta'' by the brothers Luc and Jean-Pierre Dardenne, offers a
fierce portrait of a young woman trying to eke out a living against
impossible odds. The year's other major winner, Bruno Dumont's
``L'Humanite,'' is self-consciously minimalist. Dumont's would-be
painterly, philosophical film watches a wide-eyed police
investigator respond to stirrings of evil and sexuality in a rural
town, where the filmmaker regards his characters as brutish and
naked in every sense. By Janet Maslin.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DANCE &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ROBERT-LA-FOSSE-DANCE (New York) _ On a recent Sunday, Robert La
Fosse of New York City Ballet prepared to put on the sleek black
wig, orange gloves and cape of the evil sorcerer Von Rothbart for
the final performance of Peter Martins's ``Swan Lake.'' A few days
later, the elaborate wig and makeup of Von Rothbart packed away, La
Fosse looked more like his wholesome, all-American self in
rehearsals for two of the three new ballets, collectively called
``Duke!'' and set to Duke Ellington's music, that have their
premiere on Thursday as part of City Ballet's program celebrating
jazz. By Susan Reiter.
</P>
<P>
   ANATASIA-BALLET (New York) _ Not many story ballets are based on
the lives of real people while they are still living. Yet the
ballerina Lynn Seymour recalls that she wasn't surprised when the
choreographer Kenneth MacMillan asked her to create the role of
Anna Anderson, the woman who for years claimed to be the Grand
Duchess Anastasia, a daughter of Czar Nicholas II of Russia, in a
one-act ballet, ``Anastasia,'' that he choreographed in 1967 for
Berlin's Deutsche Oper Ballet. The story of the mysterious woman
who thought she was Anastasia so captivated MacMillan that in 1971
he expanded the work into a eveninglong ballet for Britain's Royal
Ballet, which performed it in New York the following year. Now, on
Thursday, ``Anastasia'' returns to New York in the first of eight
performances to be presented by American Ballet Theater at the
Metropolitan Opera House. By Terry Trucco.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CLASSICAL MUSIC &LR;
</P>
<P>
   AVERY-FISHER-PRIZE (New York) _ Calliope, Euterpe and Erato
looked out from the pages of the morning newspaper not long ago.
Daughters of Zeus, goddesses of the arts, photographically
rendered. Well, maybe not the three Muses but certainly violinists.
Their particular Zeus has passed on but left behind a patrimony now
called the Avery Fisher Prize. Women, when I was growing up, were
not known for having pockets, but those of Sarah Chang, Pamela
Frank and Nadja Salerno-Sonnenberg are now each jingling with
$50,000. The big news about the prestigious and financially
attractive award is that the present honorees are all female. It
has not happened before. This same-sex recognition serves the
sociological concerns of the music world, though I, for one, can't
hear anything identifiably feminine or masculine in their playing.
They just play, which is, I hope, the reason they won. By Bernard
Holland.
</P>
<P>
   DIDO-RECORDINGS (Undated) _ When performers make new recording
alliances, they often start by revisiting favorite works. Ideally,
they do so for good reasons: their ideas have changed, or
scholarship has yielded new perspective on a work. Whatever the
terms of the new agreement between the conductor Andrew Parrott and
Sony, Parrott's second reading of Purcell's ``Dido and Aeneas''
(Sony Classical SK 62993; CD) is sufficiently different from his
classic 1981 Chandos recording, for better and worse, that he
cannot be charged with reduplication of the more cynical kind. By
Allan Kozinn.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ART &LR;
</P>
<P>
   AULENTI-ARCHITECTURE (Undated) _ They say that anyone can
nominate candidates for the Pritzker Architecture Prize. May I
propose Gae Aulenti? The great Milanese architect has just broken
ground for her first major project in the United States. She
already has as distinguished a body of work to her credit as any
Pritzker Prize winner. Not incidentally, she is also the most
important female architect since the beginning of time. Think about
it. Ms. Aulenti's current project, the San Francisco Museum of
Asian Art, is the most recent in a series of older buildings that
she has remodeled into art museums. By Herbert Muschamp.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TELEVISION &LR;
</P>
<P>
   TV-MARLO-THOMAS (Undated) _ ``That Girl,'' the ABC comedy from
1966 to 1971 ever so judiciously entertained the notion that an
unattached woman in her 20s might have the urge and the right to
lead a life of her own. As is apparent in nine episodes of the show
now on video from Anchor Bay, those were deep waters in 1966. ``If
women were single, they were `Our Miss Brooks,''' Ms. Marlo Thomas
said the other day, referring to the 1950s series in which Eve
Arden played a wisecracking high school English teacher (who rented
a room in an elderly woman's house, rather than really living on
her own). ``That Girl'' was Ms. Thomas's idea. ``I wanted to do a
show about a young woman who lived in her own apartment, trying to
make it, not divorced from her family, but who, like most young
girls at that time and today, still was related to her parents but
not programmed by them.'' By Peter M. Nichols.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ANTIQUES &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BEISTEGUI-ANTIQUES (Undated) _ The contents of the Chateau de
Groussay, the circa-1815 house near Paris that Carlos de Beistegui,
a Spanish dandy, transformed into a temple to grande luxe
romanticism during the Nazi occupation, will be sold on site in a
three-day sale beginning on Friday. Sotheby's is conducting the
sale in partnership with a Paris auctioneer, Poulain et Le Fur. The
2,416 lots are an eclectic procession of splendors: a Victorian
side chair made of crystal (presale estimate, $3,200-$4,900); an
ebony and bronze Louis XVI desk once owned by the
pianist-politician Ignace Jan Paderewski ($243,000-$324,000); a
lurid raspberry-pink-and-turquoise-blue Savonnerie carpet made in
1953 for Beistegui's Venetian palazzo ($13,000-$19,500), even a
pair of copper frying pans bearing the arms of a noble Spanish
family ($650-$800). By Mitchell Owens.
</P>
<P>
   BESTSELLERS (Undated) (Moved.)
</P>
<P>
   PAPERBACKS (Undated) (Moved.)
</P>
