<SLUG> BC-STARR-MCDOUGAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARR WILL NOT SEEK TO RETRY MCDOUGAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: About 350 more words will be filed ASAP.) 
(mk) 
 By DAVID STOUT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Kenneth Starr said Tuesday that he would drop all
charges against two women he had accused of hindering his
investigation of President Clinton but was unable to convict in
trials that ended in bitter setbacks for the independent counsel's
office.
</P>
<P>
   Starr said he would not seek to retry Susan McDougal, a central
character in his long-running investigation of Clinton's Arkansas
real estate ventures, and Julie Hiatt Steele, a more peripheral
figure in the White House sex scandal.
</P>
<P>
   With the McDougal and Steele cases over, Starr is thought to be
near the end of his far-flung investigations, which began with
murky land deals and bank loans in Arkansas and widened to include
Clinton's relationship with a former White House intern, Monica
Lewinsky, that threatened to engulf his presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Starr is still preparing for two trials against another witness
he has accused of being uncooperative: Webster Hubbell, a former
Justice Department official and Clinton friend from Arkansas who
has already served prison time on charges brought by Starr and
faces further counts of tax evasion and giving false testimony.
</P>
<P>
   And Starr's associates have said that the independent counsel's
office may yet consider whether to seek an indictment of Clinton,
either now or after he leaves office, on charges related to the
Lewinsky matter.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. McDougal was acquitted in Arkansas on April 12 of
obstructing justice for refusing to testify before a grand jury
about the financial dealings of Clinton and his wife, Hillary, in
their pre-presidential life. But the jury deadlocked on two charges
of criminal contempt, and Starr's office was thought, until
Tuesday, to be mulling whether to retry Ms. McDougal on those
counts.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Steele's trial on four obstruction of justice charges ended
in a mistrial on May 7, when jurors in Alexandria, Va., pronounced
themselves ``hopelessly deadlocked.'' Starr had accused her of
making false statements that hindered an investigation into
accusations by Kathleen Willey, a onetime White House volunteer,
that the president made an unwelcome sexual advance on her in
November 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Starr's decision brought expressions of relief and vindication
from the defendants and people close to them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm still kind of numb, but I'm absolutely ecstatic,'' Ms.
Steele said. ``I think he finally realized there was no case. I
didn't do anything wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Steele's lawyer, Nancy Luque, said, ``I'm extremely happy
for Julie and pleased that this decision was finally made.'' Ms.
Luque's firm, Reed Smith of Washington, had represented Ms. Steele
without charge.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Luque said the prosecutor notified Judge Claude Hilton of
U.S. District Court in Alexandria of his decision on Tuesday, and
that a formal motion to dismiss the case was expected this week.
</P>
<P>
   In the McDougal case, Starr did file a dismissal motion with
Judge George Howard Jr. of U.S. District Court in Little Rock,
Ark., telling the court it would be very difficult to empanel a new
jury whose views were not contaminated by extensive publicity.
</P>
<P>
   Referring to the April 12 outcome, Starr said in the motion,
``The unwillingness of some jurors to focus on the evidence and
follow the jury instructions weighs heavily in the OIC's decision
that a retrial in this district is not in the public interest.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. McDougal's brother, William Henley, said that pursuing the
case against his sister ``would only have put my family through the
misery of a retrial. I think he did the right thing.''
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
