<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-25 21:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0923 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BEISTEGUI-ANTIQUES-$A     05-25 0938
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEISTEGUI-ANTIQUES-$ADV30-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXTRAVAGANT FANTASIES A COLLECTOR MADE REAL  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MAY 30) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 Mitchell Owens is the senior interior design editor of Traditional
Home magazine.  
 By MITCHELL OWENS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Stories abound of millionaires with surly tempers, put-on airs
and bad taste. Few stories, however, tell of anyone like Carlos de
Beistegui, an international dandy whose character flaws were myriad
but whose esthetic sense caused him to be widely admired as a rich
man who deserved to be rich.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly he was selfish, difficult and snobbish, which can be
said about many successful men and women,'' said Marcus Linell, a
senior director of Sotheby's, which is dispersing the contents of
Chateau de Groussay, the circa-1815 house near Paris that was
Beistegui's home from 1939 until his death in 1970 at 74. ``But
Charlie Beistegui was that rare thing: a rich man whose fantasies
were not only extraordinarily beautiful but who actually realized
them.''
</P>
<P>
   The contents of the house, which Beistegui (pronounced
Bay-ISS-te-gi) transformed into a temple to grande luxe romanticism
during the Nazi occupation, will be sold on site in a three-day
sale beginning on Friday. Sotheby's is conducting the sale in
partnership with a Paris auctioneer, Poulain et Le Fur.
</P>
<P>
   The 2,416 lots are an eclectic procession of splendors: a
Victorian side chair made of crystal (presale estimate,
$3,200-$4,900); an ebony and bronze Louis XVI desk once owned by
the pianist-politician Ignace Jan Paderewski ($243,000-$324,000); a
lurid raspberry-pink-and-turquoise-blue Savonnerie carpet made in
1953 for Beistegui's Venetian palazzo ($13,000-$19,500), even a
pair of copper frying pans bearing the arms of a noble Spanish
family ($650-$800).
</P>
<P>
   Allied to Beistegui's moody palette _ olive, sapphire, slate
gray, mud brown, pale blue _ these relics made Groussay and its
amateur decorator-owner _ a French-born, English-schooled heir to a
Mexican silver-mining fortune _ arguably the single most important
influence on late 20th-century traditional decoration.
</P>
<P>
   The sale's most fascinating souvenirs, however, are not what
Beistegui bought but what Beistegui wrought, often with the help of
his friends and proteges, Alexandre Serebriakoff, a Russian emigre
artist, and Emilio Terry y Dorticos, a Cuban-born architect and
designer.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to a weakness for fantasy and a passion for building _
this talent turned into a certifiable mania in the early 1960s,
after a series of psychologically disabling strokes _ Carlos de
Beistegui littered the grounds of Groussay with a magically bizarre
assortment of exotic follies.
</P>
<P>
   Though the seven follies he built between 1955 and 1966 will
remain part of the estate, albeit stripped of their furnishings,
the drawings and three-dimensional architectural models depicting
them, the chateau and several unbuilt follies will be sold. Made of
handpainted wood and paper by Serebriakoff, the 10 models are
relatively intact, considering their resting place for the past
30-odd years: a damp basement.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would say they are in country-house condition,'' Linell
said, with a laugh. There is a tear in the paper roof of a 1964
model of the scarlet-and-gold chinoiserie pagoda (it was built on
an artificial island in an artificial lake in 1966) and a painted
wood column missing from the model of the Casino Marino (designed
in 1964 after an 18th-century Irish folly but never built at
Groussay).
</P>
<P>
   The models range from a 14{-inch-tall neo-classical arch
intended for the entrance to Groussay's flower garden ($650-$1,000)
to Emilio Terry's 1952 model of the creamy-colored chateau itself,
measuring 5 feet long by 1 foot high ($8,000-$16,000). There is
also a similarly scaled 19th-century architectural model included
in the sale, depicting an unknown public building in England
($3,200-$4,000).
</P>
<P>
   Curiously, though Carlos de Beistegui built for pleasure, the
pleasure was always fleeting. ``Once a project was finished, he
lost interest and moved on to the creation of some new
extravagance,'' said Linell.
</P>
<P>
   Increasingly addled and dangerously close to insolvency by the
mid 1960s, Beistegui continued to dream up additions to his
personal theme park: a gothic pavilion, a round temple in the style
of Robert Adam, a gilded gondola for touring the lake. How many
follies the mad maestro of Groussay had up his Savile Row-tailored
sleeve may never be known.
</P>
<P>
   Linell said that extensive plans for a 75-foot-tall masonry
elephant were discovered two weeks ago, at the back of a cupboard.
</P>
<P>
   Not one of these later grandiosities was built (though Alexandre
Serebriakoff was kept busy translating his patron's daydreams into
exquisitely detailed gouaches). But one of Beistegui's late
architectural fancies nearly was. A series of watercolor and
pen-and-ink renderings, variously dated 1966 and 1968, depicts the
Bel Air pavilion, a three-story cottage wrapped in lacy galleries
like an antebellum steamboat ($2,400-$3,200).
</P>
<P>
   Serebriakoff prepared three alternative facades for Beistegui's
delectation: New England neo-classical, English Palladian and, more
amusingly, Garden District Camp, ornamented with New Orleans-style
urns, pineapples and busts.
</P>
<P>
   What remains of that particular dream, however, is a dispiriting
ruin, half-forgotten in Groussay's verdant park: a three-story
cinderblock carcass veiled by a tangle of towering sycamores. Two
years after its construction was begun and then mysteriously
halted, Carlos de Beistegui was dead. His fortune nearly depleted
but his legend was assured.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
