<SLUG> BC-CAR-INDY-500-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    INDY 500 notebook
 &HT;    By Dave Lance
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ Arie Luyendyk has raced in the Indianapolis 500
14 times, and not coincidently he holds or shares every
Indianapolis Motor Speedway record.
</P>
<P>
   Among his records, the retiring two-time Indy 500 winner has the
fastest race average speed (185.981 mph, 1990) and fastest official
lap (237.498, 1996). And Saturday he tied Greg Ray for the fastest
official lap by a normally aspirated Indy Racing League car
(225.643).
</P>
<P>
   ``What I will really miss is the sheer pleasure of driving here
or any race,'' Luyendyk said. ``I'll miss the competition _ the
race most.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thrill is always there, but (Pole Day) was even more of a
thrill because of the way the fans reacted. When I came around,
everybody was cheering and waving the towels. It was a great
feeling.''
</P>
<P>
   Luyendyk has started the Indy 500 in the front row five times
and is a three-time pole winner.
</P>
<P>
   Seven drivers have won the pole three times, including Mario
Andretti, Johnny Rutherford and Tom Sneva. A.J. Foyt and Rex Mays
won four poles and Rick Mears won a record six.
</P>
<P>
   Luyendyk is the 12th driver to start from the pole in his final
Indy 500 start. Bobby Unser is the only driver to win from the pole
in his final Indy (1981). Beechler bears down:
</P>
<P>
   That Donnie Beechler is in the Indianapolis 500 is a minor
miracle.
</P>
<P>
   Beechler, who drives for Cahill Racing, which is managed by
Dayton, Ohio resident Mack McClellan, was practicing Saturday
before Pole Day when his engine blew. Then he had a couple of
qualifying attempts waved off because his average speed wouldn't
put him in the race.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were out there today and all I could muster is a 218 flat
out,'' Beechler said. ``We pulled out all the stops and stiffened
everything up. We even went to an option tire from Firestone, a
harder compound for speed in the turns. I thought if we could run
four 220s, I'd be happy.''
</P>
<P>
   He did and averaged 221.228 mph to garner the 19th starting
position in Row 7. But will he wear a FUBU shirt?
</P>
<P>
   FUBU's first venture into team sponsorship has been a good one.
</P>
<P>
   The hip-hop clothing company sponsors Eliseo Salazar, who
qualified for Indy in the 18th starting position, Row 6. Though the
company has been one of Salazar's main monetary contributors,
Salazar takes a pass on its oversized clothes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't wear the pants because they won't fit in the car,''
Salazar said, joking. Speedway re-opens:
</P>
<P>
   After being closed for two days, the Indianapolis Motor Speedway
re-opens to the public today from 1 to 7 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Tickets are $5 per person, while children 5 and under get in
free.
</P>
<P>
   Carburetion Day, which will feature the last practice before the
race, is Thursday and the gates open from 9 a.m. to 7 p.m. Tickets
are $10 per person, while children 5 and under get in free.
</P>
<P>
   Dave Lance writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
