<SLUG> BC-AIRLINE-QUIETER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
US AIRWAYS TO BUY QUIETER PLANES AS PART OF SHUTTLE OVERHAUL
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass., N.Y., Va.)   (jw) 
 By LAURENCE ZUCKERMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ As competition heats up to win over the business
executives, politicians and celebrities who regularly fly between
Washington, New York and Boston, US Airways plans to announce
Wednesday that it will retire its fleet of noisy, 30-year-old
Boeing 727s and replace them by the end of the year with roomier
and quieter Airbus A-320s.
</P>
<P>
   The new airplanes, along with an expanded terminal at La Guardia
Airport, are part of a multimillion-dollar overhaul of the shuttle
that the airline is to announce at a Manhattan news conference.
</P>
<P>
   US Airways said the new, 154-seat airplanes were considerably
quieter than the 727s; the airline expects the new Airbus jets to
generate noise audible over an area 19 times smaller. Aircraft
noise has long generated complaints from residents of the densely
populated Queens County neighborhoods that surround La Guardia, and
from residents of Boston, Washington and Northern Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   US Airways' new airplanes will have wider seats and more
overhead storage space, and will feature an electrical outlet for
portable computers at every seat, the company said.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning this summer, US Airways also plans to spend more than
$10 million to renovate its shuttle terminal at La Guardia.
Commuter service that shares space with the shuttle will be moved
to another part of the terminal to make room for an expanded lounge
with fully wired, semiprivate work areas. US Airways also plans to
add jetways, a snack bar and a cocktail lounge.
</P>
<P>
   The investment, which counting new planes amounts to more than
$500 million, comes as US Airways, Delta Air Lines and United
Airlines are expanding their service in the Washington-Boston
corridor.
</P>
<P>
   Next week, the Delta Shuttle, which is the market leader, will
begin offering flights every other hour between Ronald Reagan
National Airport outside Washington and Boston's Logan
International Airport. In response, US Airways plans to fold its
existing hourly service between Logan and National into its shuttle
operation starting July 9. It also said that in the fall it planned
to convert its recently introduced hourly service from both La
Guardia and Logan to Dulles International Airport near Washington
into its shuttle operation.
</P>
<P>
   United, which has a hub at Dulles, responded to the challenge
from US Airways by adding its own hourly flights to La Guardia and
Logan from Dulles.
</P>
<P>
   Eighteen months ago, US Airways bought the part of the shuttle
it did not already own from a consortium of banks that had
repossessed it from Donald Trump.
</P>
<P>
   At that time, Delta flew about 60 percent of the 3.5 million to
4 million annual shuttle passengers.
</P>
<P>
   S. Michael Scheeringa, the vice president in charge of the US
Airways Shuttle, said it had since increased its share to about 44
percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
