<SLUG> BC-IMMIGRATION-REACTION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RIGHTS GROUPS APPLAUD GORE'S STATEMENT ON IMMIGRANT BENEFITS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By STEVE LASH 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Civil rights groups Tuesday praised Vice President
Al Gore's assurance to legal immigrants that they can freely apply
for federal food and health benefits without fear of deportation.
</P>
<P>
   But Rep. Lamar Smith, R-Texas, who heads the House immigration
subcommittee, expressed misgivings with Gore's announcement in
South Texas, saying the vice president has misinterpreted federal
laws designed to help indigent immigrants who do not impose a
severe financial burden on U.S. taxpayers.
</P>
<P>
   Many poor, legal U.S. immigrants have refused to apply for
health and food benefits, fearing their applications will be used
as grounds for deportation, said Hispanic and Asian rights
organizations. But Gore's statement _ asserting that legal
immigrants can apply for benefits without risk _ will alleviate
that concern, said leaders of the National Council of La Raza and
the National Asian Pacific American Legal Consortium.
</P>
<P>
   The immigrants' apprehension is rooted in their confusion
regarding 1996 federal laws designed to reform immigration and
welfare, the groups said. These statutes have led immigrants to
believe that application for any public benefit will cast them as a
``public charge'' under the laws, putting them at risk of
deportation and denial of permanent residency, the organizations
said.
</P>
<P>
   In a prepared statement, Gore sought to clear the confusion by
listing many of the benefits for which immigrants can apply without
jeopardizing their immigration status. These benefits include
Medicaid, Medicare, health insurance for children, immunizations,
testing and treatment of communicable diseases, nutrition programs,
child-care services, housing and energy assistance, emergency
disaster relief, foster care, adoption assistance, transportation
vouchers, education assistance and job training.
</P>
<P>
   NCLR Vice President Cecilia Munoz said Gore has removed ``a
major fear factor'' for immigrants.
</P>
<P>
   ``If immigrants are too scared to use these programs, then
eligibility is meaningless,'' Munoz said.
</P>
<P>
   Karen Narasaki, executive director of the Asian consortium, said
her group is ``very pleased'' with the vice president for removing
the confusion that she said has led elderly immigrants to tell
health facilities to delete their medical records, lest the
documents be used against them.
</P>
<P>
   The praise from immigrant groups was in stark contrast to
Smith's criticism of what he characterized Monday as a misguided
policy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Americans believe that immigration policy should bring people
to our country who will work hard and contribute,'' Smith said,
``but these rules will increase the number of immigrants on welfare
who will be able to bring in more immigrants to go on welfare and
are an insult to all Americans _ native-born and immigrant.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
