<SLUG> BC-SEMINIS-SEEDS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEMINIS TO OFFER SHARES IN JUNE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DEBORAH ADAMSON  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SATICOY, Calif. -- Backed by blue-chip investment bankers,
Seminis Inc. is planning to make a $250 million initial public
offering in June.
</P>
<P>
   The Ventura County-based producer of fruit and vegetable seeds
will be underwritten by J.P. Morgan, Goldman Sachs, Salomon Smith
Barney and Ing Baring Furman Selz.
</P>
<P>
   Seminis will offer 12.5 million common shares at an IPO price
between $20 and $23. After the IPO, total outstanding shares will
stand at 58.6 million. There is an over-allotment of almost 2
million shares, in case of increased demand.
</P>
<P>
   The issue will be listed on the Nasdaq National Market, under
the ticker symbol ``SMNS.''
</P>
<P>
   Seminis hopes to take in between $250 million to $289 million --
based on $21.50 a share, midpoint of the IPO price range, and
depending on demand for the extra 2 million shares.
</P>
<P>
   The IPO market is strong, said Jeff Stacey, chief operating
officer at IPO Monitor, a Calabasas, Calif.-based IPO research and
tracking company.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, six IPOs came to market, ranging from the wildly
successful debut of Santa Monica, Calif.-based eToys to Rubios, the
Carlsbad, Calif.-based restaurant chain. On Tuesday, the IPO for
Barnesandnoble.com rose 27 percent above its offering price.
</P>
<P>
   While Internet stocks continue to attract the most attention,
due to the recent weakness in this sector ``perhaps the market is
looking for alternatives to high-risk Internet stocks,'' Stacey
said.
</P>
<P>
   Seminis will use the IPO proceeds to redeem preferred stock and
pay down some debt. As of March 31, the company carried $443
million of long-term debt. Seminis is negotiating to get an
additional $350 million in loans.
</P>
<P>
   As a comparison, sales for fiscal 1998 were $428.4 million and
earnings from continuing operations were $6.8 million, according to
filings with the Securities and Exchange Commission. Including the
purchase of old Class B redeemable common shares, net loss was
$133.4 million for 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Company officials, citing SEC rules mandating a ``quiet'' period
during which they cannot talk publicly about the offering, declined
to comment.
</P>
<P>
   After the IPO, majority shareholder Savia de CV will own 67
percent of the company and control almost 80 percent of the voting
rights. Savia will effectively control management, according to the
SEC filing.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Savia has used as collateral for its loans 48
percent (before the IPO) of Seminis shares. If Savia defaults on
its loans, the lenders can sell off Seminis stock and drive the
price down, the company warned in the filing.
</P>
<P>
   Seminis was created when several companies merged in 1994. The
core business was created through the acquisition of Asgrow from
the Upjohn Co. Later, it added Petoseed and Royal Sluis. These
three formed the company's full-line brands. With a total of 13
acquisitions in the past five years, Seminis also offers nine
specialty brands.
</P>
<P>
   Seminis holds 20 percent of the global commercial market for
fruit and vegetable seeds. It produces more than 8,000 distinct
varieties covering most species of fruits and vegetables. The
company sells to 120 countries; it has 70 research and development
stations in 19 countries and production sites in 32.
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
