A0934 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OHIO-EARLY-PRIMARY-CO     05-25 0447
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OHIO-EARLY-PRIMARY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    By Mike Wagner
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLUMBUS, Ohio _ Ohio voters will likely be grabbing their
winter coats instead of spring jackets next year when they head to
the polls for the state's primary election.
</P>
<P>
   The Ohio Senate on Tuesday voted to move the 2000 primary up two
weeks to March 7 with the intent of making the Buckeye state a
player in next year's presidential election.
</P>
<P>
   The vote broke along party lines; all 21 Republican senators
voted to change the primary date and all 12 Democratic senators
voted against the move. The bill has already has passed the Ohio
House, but will go back there so legislators can make a technical
change. Once the legislation leaves the house, it will be sent to
Gov. Bob Taft who will sign it into law, said the Republican
governor will sign the legislation into law Scott Milburn,
spokesman for Gov. Bob Taft. , said the Republican governor will
sign the legislation into law.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will become much more of a political player, (presidential)
candidates will come to Ohio early and often,'' said state Sen.
Gene Watts, R-Dublin. ``This legislation will increase voter
turnout and increase the state's status in the national election.''
</P>
<P>
   The 2000 primary is slated for March 21, but many in the General
Assembly said they are tired of Ohio taking a back seat to states
like New York and California in the presidential race. On March 7,
2000, California, New York and eight other states are scheduled to
have primaries.
</P>
<P>
   In nonpresidential years, the Ohio primary is held in May. In
1996, the primary was moved to late March for presidential years,
but Democrats say they want the primary held in May every election
year.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Democrats predict colder weather, a shortage of poll
workers and confusion about the election date will keep more voters
at home next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Voters don't want to go to an election in the middle of the
winter,'' said state Sen. Dan Brady, D-Cleveland, before Tuesday's
vote. ``There is no question there will be less people voting on
March 7 than in May. If we really want to encourage people to
participate in the election, this is certainly the wrong way to
go.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats cited the March 1996 presidential primary that had
300,000 fewer voters than a May primary in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   But Republicans stood by their belief that Ohio's larger role in
the presidential election would draw more people into the election.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it comes too late, you must change the date,'' Watts said.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Wagner writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
