<SLUG> BC-FLA-MOTHER-SLAY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOMAN AVOIDS MURDER CHARGE OVER DAUGHTER 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By RICK BRAGG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ When an Orlando woman chose to end her life last week by
removing herself from a life support system rather than spend her
life paralyzed from the neck down, prosecutors said they would very
likely charge the woman who crippled her, her mother, with murder.
But on Tuesday, the state attorney in Orange County said it would
be ``inappropriate'' to charge Shirley Egan, 68, with the murder of
her daughter, Georgette Smith, 42.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Smith, who was left paralyzed when her mother, Ms. Egan,
fired a bullet into her neck in an argument on March 8, sued her
Orlando hospital last month for the right to be disconnected from
the ventilator machine that was keeping her alive.
</P>
<P>
   She won that lawsuit last week. On Wednesday Ms. Smith was
disconnected from her life support system at the Lucerne Medical
Center in Orlando and died soon after.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors had said they would very likely file murder charges
against Ms. Egan for causing the death, even though it was her
daughter's decision to end her life. A state court judge delayed
Ms. Smith's request to die for more than a day while lawyers
questioned her and gathered evidence in the pending murder trial.
</P>
<P>
   But on Tuesday, the state attorney, Lawson Lamar, said Ms.
Egan's failing health, among other things, had made pursuing the
murder charge inappropriate. Ms. Egan's ``deteriorating health, and
her relationship to the victim, do not provide an appropriate
circumstance'' for a murder charge, Lamar said.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Smith, whose spine was severed at the neck when her mother
fired a bullet into her after hearing that she was going to be
placed in a nursing home, had said she forgave her mother.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Egan's lawyer has said that she did not mean to shoot her
daughter and that it would serve no purpose to pursue a murder
charge against her. Ms. Egan had been charged with attempted
first-degree murder and aggravated battery causing great bodily
harm.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Egan, who also has respiratory problems and gets about
mostly in a wheelchair after a recent automobile accident, saw her
daughter the day before she died. She said she supported her
daughter's decision to end her own life.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
