<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCKESSON-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 McKesson Cautions Investors About Profits  &HT;       
 By Tom Abate 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
Four weeks after it was forced to restate its fiscal 1999 earnings,
McKesson HBOC Inc. yesterday warned investors to expect further
revisions, as auditors continue to probe its troubled software
division.
<P>
   Shares in the giant drug wholesaler and hospital software firm
plunged $4.69 cents to close at $33.50 on the news. The company did
not provide any new figures, or say when it would issue its final
earnings statement.
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco's McKesson first acknowledged problems on April
28, after an audit showed that HBOC, which it had acquired in
January, had prematurely booked $42.2 million in software revenues
for the year ended March 31.
</P>
<P>
   At that time, the company reduced its fiscal 1999 earnings from
84 cents per share to 75 cents.
</P>
<P>
   That news sent the stock plummeting from $65.75 to $34.50,
taking $9 billion of McKesson HBOC's market value.
</P>
<P>
   McKesson HBOC spokesman Larry Kurtz said yesterday that auditors
have now found additional software sales that were recorded before
they should have been. He also said auditors are investigating
possible irregularities in accounting for sales of other HBOC
products and services.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know that there are in fact other contingent (software)
sales improperly recognized,'' Kurtz said, adding that ``other
financial statement items, in addition to simply software sales,
are now under review.''
</P>
<P>
   Kurtz said auditors have also extended their look into HBOC's
revenues back to calendar years 1996 and 1997. He said McKesson
HBOC hopes to complete its audit in time to file its annual report
on June 30. Its annual shareholder meeting is scheduled for July 28
in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Vietor, an analyst with Merrill Lynch, said yesterday's
revelation ``clearly raises the question about whether any number
can be trusted at HBOC.''
</P>
<P>
   The McKesson-HBOC merger was never popular on Wall Street.
Investors didn't see the wisdom of marrying McKesson _ which earns
razor-thin margins on its $20 billion in drug sales _ to HBOC,
which enjoys fat margins on just $1.8 billion in software and
service revenues.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Pulido, who had been chief executive of McKesson before the
merger, retains that position in the new company. Charles McCall,
who had been chief executive of HBOC before the merger, is chairman
of the combined company. Neither executive has discussed the
situation publicly. Pulido works in San Francisco and McCall works
in Atlanta, where HBOC had been based.
</P>
<P>
   Alan Seelenfreund, former chairman and chief executive of
McKesson and currently a board member, is heading the audit
committee that is directing the investigation of HBOC. More than 30
shareholder lawsuits have been filed against the company.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
