<SLUG> BC-GROW-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 How to Give But Not Go Broke  &HT;       
 By Peter Sinton  
 c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
 &UR; Question: &LR;  I have a 2-year-old business that is starting to make
money and would like to start giving back to the community but
don't want to jeopardize the future of my business. Do you have any
suggestions for achieving the right balance.
<P>
   &UR; Answer: &LR;   &LR; Few businesses go broke by giving away too much. But
there are no hard and fast rules on what is appropriate.
</P>
<P>
   Some companies earmark 1 percent or more of pretax profits for
charity. But all the mergers and acquisitions and focus on
cost-cutting in the 1990s have taken a toll on business bounty. The
Conference Board reports that corporate giving has stalled,
dropping to 0.8 percent of pretax income in 1997 from slightly more
than 1 percent in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   One company that might be a role model for you and others is
fittingly named Give Something Back. The Oakland office supply
company has given more than half its net profits to charity since
its start in 1991 and was a finalist in last week's ``Most Generous
Company in America'' contest sponsored by George magazine and
Newman's Own, the company started by actor Paul Newman which gives
all profits to charities.
</P>
<P>
   Give Something Back co-founder Sean Marx, 33, suggests, ``You
should do what you can do without jeopardizing your business and
you should make it part of your mission.''
</P>
<P>
   He and Mike Hannigan, 50, started Give Something Back with the
intention of giving most of their profits to causes they believe
in, principally health and human services organizations. Their
bylaws state that the principals can earn no more than 80 percent
of the ``market wage`` for someone doing a comparable job at a
comparable size company.
</P>
<P>
   With annual revenues approaching $20 million and 75 employees,
Marx figures he and Hannigan could each earn about $160,000 a year,
but the two limit themselves to $72,000. Over the past three years,
Give Something Back has given away $551,342 of its $1.4 million in
profits, paid $479,825 in taxes and reinvested the rest in the
business.
</P>
<P>
   Marx says that Give Something Back is as focused on driving down
costs and improving service as any other company. It reduced
overhead 10 percent to 15 percent by requiring wholesalers to
handle all the warehousing and order packing and labeling.
</P>
<P>
   Marx does not recommend giving away more than you feel
comfortable with. But who knows, you may be able to build your
business by giving money away. Marx said his customers cite Give
Something Back's philosophy as a ``strong secondary reason'' for
buying its products.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Retaining Talent
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR; Q: I run a small travel agency and find it hard competing for
talent in this tight labor market. What are some strategies for
attracting and holding on to employees?
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR; A: Small Business Success, a magazine published by Pacific
Bell Directory in partnership with the U.S. Small Business
Administration, focuses on employees as ``your most valuable
asset,'' in its latest cover story. Phone (800) 848-8000 for a free
copy.
</P>
<P>
   Its low- or no-cost employee retention tips include:
</P>
<P>
   _Offer an open management style with little bureaucracy to give
staff a sense of control over their own destiny.
</P>
<P>
   _After a tough project, give team members some time off.
</P>
<P>
   _Be flexible with work hours, dress, work rules.
</P>
<P>
   _Stop being petty. Rules for the sake of rules only anger and
frustrate people.
</P>
<P>
   _Try to make the work challenging or allow individuals to make
an immediate difference.
</P>
<P>
   _Stop micromanaging. If your employees are really incapable of
being trusted, you need new employees. If they can be trusted, you
need a new attitude.
</P>
<P>
   _Have fun. Throw a pizza party for no particular reason. Give
away family tickets to an amusement park.
</P>
<P>
   _Assign coaches or mentors to help employees not ony with
specific jobs but in developing their careers.
</P>
<P>
   _Consider offering an equity stake in the company to key hires.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Send small-business questions to  &LR; entrepreneurs(at &LR; 
 &LR; sign)sfgate.com &LR;  or to Peter Sinton, Grow a Business column, 901
Mission St., San Francisco, Calif., 94103
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
