<SLUG> BC-PACBELL-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Bill Gives Phone Users `Cooling Off' Period  &HT;       
 By Deborah Solomon 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
California consumers would have five days to change their minds
after ordering telephone services like Caller ID or call waiting
under a bill approved by the state Senate yesterday.
<P>
   Customers who order add-on services would get a five-day
``cooling off'' period in which they would not have to pay any
installation charges or fees incurred from using the service. They
could cancel without any penalty.
</P>
<P>
   The bill, which passed 24 to 13, would also require the state
Public Utilities Commission to create a system so customers can
compare prices between telecommunications companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``This bill should make it easier for customers to compare
telephone services and should give customers specific rights to
refuse services they haven't ordered or felt pressured into
getting,'' said Debra Bowen, D-Redondo Beach, who authored the
bill.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation must still be approved by the state Assembly,
which begins hearing bills in June.
</P>
<P>
   Bowen proposed the legislation after hearing complaints from
customers who said they felt pressured into signing up for
expensive services from Pacific Bell.
</P>
<P>
   Right now, customers who sign up with Pac Bell for services like
call waiting are charged from the day they authorize service. Many
of the services include a one-time activation fee. This bill would
give customers five days in which they could cancel the service
without paying any charges.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have `cooling off' periods for people who sign contracts
with health clubs, weight loss and dating centers,`` Bowen said.
``It makes sense to extend that same protection to telephone users
who are constantly being hit on and pressured to buy services.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials from Pac Bell said they were still talking to Bowen
about the bill and did not believe the legislation was in its final
form.
</P>
<P>
   John Britton, a spokesman for Pac Bell, said the bill's
``cooling off'' period is unnecessary because the phone company
already lets customers cancel new services within a few days after
placing an order.
</P>
<P>
   ``If somebody calls up a couple days after ordering a service
and says `We don't want it,' we'll let them out. We're liberal
about that,'' Britton said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-25-99 2118EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
