<DOCNO> NYT19990525.0377 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-25 21:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0955 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CNN-SFCHRON &LR;      05-25 0483
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CNN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 CNN, IDG's New Venture Shows They're No Dummies  &HT;       
 By Dan Fost  
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
Television for dummies?
<P>
   Cable network CNN and tech publishing powerhouse International
Data Group _ which produces the ``... For Dummies'' series of books
_ will launch a new consumer technology TV show as part of a $50
million partnership announced yesterday in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Although most of the deal involves advertising dollars, CNN also
will make an unspecified minority investment in a new, yet-unnamed
Internet company that IDG is forming.
</P>
<P>
   That new company could end up based in or near San Francisco,
where IDG already employs more than 500 people at a range of
magazines and online ventures, including PC World, InfoWorld,
GamePro and The Industry Standard.
</P>
<P>
   The forthcoming television show does not yet have a name or a
host, but it probably will be produced at CNN's headquarters in
Atlanta. It will compete with shows produced in San Francisco at
the Internet firm Cnet and at ZDTV, the cable network launched last
year by IDG's archrival, New York technology publishing giant
Ziff-Davis.
</P>
<P>
   With the CNN show, IDG of Massachusetts is taking a different
approach to broadcasting than Ziff-Davis. While Ziff created its
own national cable channel, IDG instead is lending its brand name
and expertise to one of the most successful channels on cable
television, CNN.
</P>
<P>
   Kelly Conlin, IDG president and chief executive, didn't mention
ZDTV by name as he noted its limited reach to 11 million homes.
``After a year of operation, the 24-hour television channel is not
at a level where it's rated by the Nielsens,'' he said. ``One
billion people are reached by CNN.''
</P>
<P>
   The 30-minute weekly show is likely to offer some hard news
about developments in the world of technology, as well as features
on Internet executives, stock market news, cool new gadgets,
favorite Web sites, and software and hardware reviews, according to
CNN Senior Vice President Rob Tolleson. It is due to premiere this
fall on CNN.
</P>
<P>
   IDG is a privately held company with annual revenues of $2.35
billion. It publishes more than 290 computer newspapers and
magazines and 700 book titles. Last year, it offered stock for sale
in its book division, IDG Books.
</P>
<P>
   It's also thinking of a possible stock offering for its
forthcoming Internet division. The company, which will run IDG's
240 Web sites, is being formed with the code name of Web IDG
Networks, or Project WIN, Conlin said.
</P>
<P>
   Although CNN's exact equity stake in that venture was not
disclosed, the executives said it represents about one-third of the
$50 million deal announced yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   IDG also will spend a similar amount, about $17 million, to
advertise on CNN's television shows and Web site, and the rest of
the money will come from cross-promotional ads in each company's
media endeavors.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
