<SLUG> BC-MARKET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHARES AGAIN FALL STEEPLY
</HEADLINE>
   (dal) 
 By KENNETH N. GILPIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Stocks slumped for the fourth consecutive session on
Tuesday as a selloff continued in technology and Internet issues.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from a further steep drop in Brazilian stock prices,
traders had little fresh news to influence their decisions. While
the threat of higher interest rates continues to hang over the
stock market, bond prices actually edged up on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The feeling that the Fed has moved toward a tighter stance
doesn't give people much optimism, and Brazil is not in great
shape,'' said Bob Gasser, head of U.S. equity trading at J.P.
Morgan Securities. ``But there is nothing on the horizon that would
have suggested we couldn't have rallied back'' from Monday's steep
slide.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, few analysts were willing to view the recent pullback as
more than a long-awaited correction, particularly in technology and
Internet stocks, which have been riding the crest for some time.
The technology-laden Nasdaq composite index has fallen just under
10 percent since its peak on April 26.
</P>
<P>
   ``This correction is largely a function of declining Internet
stocks,'' said Laszlo Birinyi of the research firm Birinyi &AMP;
Associates. ``The market is fine, but for the time being pressure
from Internet selling, both direct and indirect, and the fact there
is no news lets gravity assert itself.''
</P>
<P>
   Technology and Internet stocks that trade on Nasdaq suffered
most on Tuesday. Led by big declines in market favorites like
Intel, Cisco Systems and Yahoo, the Nasdaq composite index fell
72.76 points, or nearly 3 percent, to 2,380.90.
</P>
<P>
   Internet shares have been harder hit. TheStreet.com's Internet
stock index fell 26.35 points, or 4.6 percent, to 550.33. Since a
peak on April 12, the index has lost 30 percent of its value.
</P>
<P>
   It was a bad day to varying degrees in almost every corner of
the market. On the New York Stock Exchange, losers outnumbered
winners by almost 2 to 1. The Dow Jones industrial average declined
123.58 points, or 1.16 percent, to 10,531.09, while the Standard &AMP;
Poor's 500-stock index dropped 22.25 points, or 1.7 percent, to
1,284.40. The Russell 2000 index of small-company stocks slumped
5.94, or 1.35 percent, to 434.45.
</P>
<P>
   Particularly hard hit were issues like Amazon.com, Ebay and
America Online. Amazon fell 5 15/16, to 111 9/16. Ebay dropped 19
5/16, to 163 15/16. And America Online declined 4{, to 115.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Cook, lead portfolio manager of the Munder NetNet Fund,
which has a little more than $2 billion in assets under management,
said profit taking, the threat of higher interest rates and a
supply of new issues were putting pressure on stocks.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fourth and first quarters were particularly strong'' for
these stocks, he said, ``and 38 new names have come public since
the start of the year. And since these are high-multiple stocks,
they are going to suffer if interest rates move higher.''
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said the weakness in Internet stocks was also a likely
catalyst for a drop in the Dow and the S.&AMP; P. 500 during the final
hour of trading. Investors facing margin calls in Internet stocks
may have been forced to sell Dow stocks to meet them, Birinyi said.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Charles Schwab, Mo Shafroth, said: ``In the last
couple of days, when the Nasdaq takes a dip, it is often the case
that there is an increase in margin calls. I can't quantify how
much margin calls are up, but it is more than a little and less
than a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dow was led down by weakness in cyclical stocks like Alcoa,
which fell 3{, to 56 13/16, and financial shares like J.P. Morgan,
down 3 11/16, to 133 1/16, and Citigroup, which dropped 2], to 62}.
</P>
<P>
   Intel led the Nasdaq and S.&AMP; P. 500 lower, falling 3 1/16, to
52~. Cisco was another big loser, falling 5, to 104].
</P>
<P>
   Bank and financial service stocks, punished on Monday after an
analyst at Credit Suisse First Boston put out a sell signal on
several money-center banks, were losers again on Tuesday. Bank of
America fell 2~, to 62}. First Union, which cut profit estimates
Tuesday for a second time this year, fell 4 5/16, to 45|.
Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette shed 4, to 64|. And Charles Schwab
lost 9}, to 96|.
</P>
<P>
   Utility stocks, often used as a safe haven during times of broad
market weakness, did well again on Tuesday. The Dow Jones utilities
average advanced to a fifth consecutive record, rising 1.05 points,
to 328.48.
</P>
<P>
   Among individual issues, American Electric Power rose |, to 43
11/16. Con Edison gained |, to 49]. And Duke Energy rose }, to
60[. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
