<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-25 21:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0958 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MBAVENTURE-SFCHRON &LR;      05-25 1292
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MBAVENTURE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Venture capital firms investing in student startups  &HT;     By Peter Sinton 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
When Juan Mini and Scott Kucirek graduated from UC Berkeley's Haas
School of Business last Sunday, they had one distinction that
wasn't obvious as they walked to the podium in their caps and
gowns.
<P>
   Mini and Kucirek were the first Berkeley MBAs to get venture
capital financing while they were still in school. They raised $1.7
million for their online business zipRealty.com, including $1.2
million from Palo Alto's Vanguard Venture Partners.
</P>
<P>
   The pair marks the new breed of MBAs.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1980s, only 1 or 2 percent of graduating MBAs wanted to
start out as entrepreneurs. Today, thanks in part to a booming
stock market for high-tech startups, 10 to 20 percent want to be
their own bosses, according to business school officials.
</P>
<P>
   And many aren't waiting until they get a diploma to start. From
Berkeley to Stanford to the Massachusetts Institute of Technology,
dozens of MBAs are already running businesses. And the venture
capitalists are right behind them.
</P>
<P>
   VC firms are flocking to campus to find and finance the next
generation of high-tech hits. Some venture capitalists are even
teaching classes part time _ a great opportunity to scope out
potential talent.
</P>
<P>
   VC firms are also sponsoring and judging competitions where
students with the best business plans can win thousands of dollars
_ and the attention of VCs with millions more to spend.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; ``Business plan competitions are really hot,'' said Mark
Gorenberg, a partner with San Francisco's Hummer Winblad Venture
Partners and a judge for contests at Berkeley, Stanford and MIT.
``I feel like a scout going to the Triple-As and looking for the
next Big League players.''
</P>
<P>
   The contests ``help foster entrepreneurship on campus and
encourage cross-pollination between business and other
departments,'' according to Gorenberg. That is important because
successful businesses are typically collaborations between people
in business, engineering, medicine and other disciplines.
</P>
<P>
   From UC to VC
</P>
<P>
   The first business plan competition at Berkeley's Haas School of
Business this year drew 75 entrants. Winners shared $10,000 in
prize money.
</P>
<P>
   The first-place winner, taking home $8,000, was Timbre
Technologies. Its principals, who met in an entrepreneurship class,
are Nickhil Jakatdar, 35, a Ph.D. candidate in electrical
engineering from India, and two first-year MBA students, Pedro
Abreu, 26, from Portugal and American Nick Sturiale, 35.
</P>
<P>
   The company is developing a cheaper, faster way to spot
semiconductor chip defects in the manufacturing process by
measuring the polarization of light traveling through thin films.
National Semiconductor is testing the technology and Timbre is
discussing its product with other chipmakers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many students are using class projects to build businesses and
get more out of business school,'' said Steve Domenik, a general
partner of Sevin Rosen Funds, which sponsored the Haas School
contest and is hiring Sturiale for the summer.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the classroom, some universities are even setting up
free office incubators where students can turn embryonic ideas into
viable businesses.
</P>
<P>
   ZipRealty co-founders Juan Mini, 31, from Guatemala, and Scott
Kucirek, 33, from Merced, took full advantage of all UC facilities,
including free office space in the basement of the Bancroft Hotel.
</P>
<P>
   Kucirek, who flew helicopters in the U.S. Navy, went to business
school because he wanted to pilot his own business. So did Mini,
who previously was a management consultant and turned around
Vecesa, Guatemala's largest bike company.
</P>
<P>
   The two met and decided to start a company that would let people
buy and sell homes over the Internet with the help of online
agents.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the free office space, Mini and Kucirek got
thousands of dollars of free advice from UC faculty and guest
lecturers such as renowned attorney Mario Rosati, a partner with
Palo Alto's Wilson Sonsini Goodrich &AMP; Rosati.
</P>
<P>
   Mini and Kucirek also enlisted more than a dozen classmates who
helped develop zipRealty marketing strategies as part of a class
project.
</P>
<P>
   At least seven other e-commerce businesses have been started by
graduating Berkeley MBAs. They include BusinessPlace, ClubTivity,
jSpan Corp., netRelevance, NoSilence.com, RedLadder.com and the
Utility Corner. Several hope to raise VC financing in the next few
months.
</P>
<P>
   Stanford Startups
</P>
<P>
   Student entrepreneurs have been around even longer at Stanford
University's Graduate School of Business.
</P>
<P>
   Meg Luttrell, 28, started a furniture e-commerce business as
part of a venture capital course assignment. After studying
economics as an undergraduate and working for an information system
software company, Luttrell sought an MBA to bone up on marketing,
operations and other business skills.
</P>
<P>
   Last Thanksgiving, she and two classmates _ Lillian Ho and
Pratima Rao _ decided what 20- and 30-somethings really needed was
affordable, well-crafted furniture that they could buy online.
</P>
<P>
   They honed the concept in a course taught by Sierra Ventures
General Partner Peter Wendell, and are now discussing VC backing
with several firms.
</P>
<P>
   Luttrell said they intentionally picked a made-up name. ``If the
business model changes a little,'' she explained, ``you don't have
to change the name.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bayla women are not among the 68 teams vying for $25,000 in
prizes to be awarded Thursday in the Stanford Entrepreneur's
Challenge. The business plan contest began three years ago in the
engineering school and now includes students in business, law,
medicine, biology and other departments.
</P>
<P>
   ``This started as a way to foster entrepreneurship among
engineering students who often had no idea how to get something on
the market or make a business of it,'' said Ted Acworth, a manager
of the contest who will receive his Ph.D. in engineering next
month. He figures that about 80 percent of this year's entrants
were multidisciplinary teams and most included MBA candidates.
</P>
<P>
   The finalists include:
</P>
<P>
   _ &UR; ImaGen.  &LR; Rob Batchco, a Ph.D. candidate in physics, teamed up
with three MBA students to develop live, full-motion highway
billboards using low-cost laser image projection systems developed
in the physics lab.
</P>
<P>
   _ &UR; MusiCop.com.  &LR; Chief executive Erin Turner, who is earning a
master's degree in engineering, joined three Ph.D. candidates to
use computer algorithms to spot and stop Web sites that are
broadcasting pirated recordings. MusiCop expects to do this by
quickly comparing the digital signature of the broadcast songs with
original, protected recordings and sending cease-and-desist notices
to host servers that violate the law.
</P>
<P>
   _ &UR; Tosk Inc. &LR;  Biology Ph.D. Patrick Fogarty cut short his
postdoctorate work at Stanford's medical school to pursue a venture
that he named after a mythological Star Trek creature.
</P>
<P>
   Tosk hopes to cut months or years off preclinical drug trials by
using specially engineered fruit flies to test the effectiveness of
new compounds.
</P>
<P>
   Fogarty, 32, has raised some money from friends and private
investors and hopes to tap venture capital firms for $3 million
late next year.
</P>
<P>
   Not every student entrepreneur is high tech. At MIT's Sloan
school, where business plan competitions have been going on for a
decade, this year's runner-up was an all-terrain skates company.
</P>
<P>
   MBA student James Page, 28, won $10,000 for Crosskate, which
looks like skis with wheels and can be used on hillsides without
snow. Each skate features nine-inch-diameter pneumatic tires front
and back, plus mountain bike-style brakes and a mechanism that
prevents rolling backward.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
