<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-25 21:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0963 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TAMOXIFEN-STUDY-COX     05-25 0551
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TAMOXIFEN-STUDY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SCIENCE/HEALTH: Cancer drugs will get test
 &HT;    (EDS: Moving in (a) General news and (l) Lifestyle categories.)
 &HT;    By Kevin Lamb
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ A national study to compare how well two drugs
prevent breast cancer will include about 250 Miami Valley women who
are past menopause and have a high risk for the disease.
</P>
<P>
   The five-year Study of Tamoxifen and Raloxifene (STAR) announced
Tuesday will include 22,000 women and 400 medical centers in the
United States and Canada.
</P>
<P>
   Tamoxifen, long used for treating breast cancer, already has
been shown to reduce the incidence of breast cancer among high-risk
women by about half in research limited to five years and reported
about a year ago. But the women who used tamoxifen also experienced
a doubling of uterine cancer rates, a tripling of potentially fatal
blood clots in the large veins and lungs and smaller increases in
cataracts and possibly strokes.
</P>
<P>
   Raloxifene is a treatment for osteoporosis that also has side
effects, but does not appear to increase uterine cancer rates.
However, it has been on the market only for a year and a half, with
about five years of clinical trials, compared with 20 and 30 years,
respectively, for tamoxifen.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are risks, but in my mind they're very small compared to
what this information will do for all the women out there,'' said
Judy Johnson, who will be part of the clinical trial. She was one
of about 80 women locally and more than 13,000 altogether in the
previous tamoxifen trial.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson's high risk for breast cancer surfaced in 1991, when she
was diagnosed with a precancerous lesion.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was very scary,'' she said. ``You go along, happy-go-lucky,
working and doing all the things you do in life, and it all came to
a screeching halt. I knew I may not be here five or 10 years from
now. You think about your family, what you might be missing, and
you appreciate it all a lot more.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, 50, was disappointed only ``for a fleeting moment''
when she learned she was among half the women in the tamoxifen
trial who received a placebo instead of the drug. ``But I did
contribute,'' she said. ``Without that, they wouldn't have had
anything to compare the tamoxifen to.''
</P>
<P>
   No one in STAR will receive only a placebo. Each participant
will take one of the two drugs for five years and be monitored
during and after that period. Neither the women nor their doctors
will know who is taking which drug.
</P>
<P>
   The Dayton Clinical Oncology Program (DCOP) wants to add about
50 women a year to STAR, which it will coordinate locally through
the eight private adult hospitals in Montgomery, Greene and Miami
counties and the Dayton VA Medical Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's exciting about this trial is it's a means to find out
how to prevent breast cancer in patients with high risk,'' Dr.
Daniel McKellar said at DCOP's announcement of the trial's
availability. ``Most breast cancer trials have been about treating
people who already have it.''
</P>
<P>
   Raloxifene is marketed as Evista by Eli Lilly and Co. Tamoxifen
is marketed as Nolvadex by Zeneca Pharmaceuticals.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Lamb writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
