<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-UPDATE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KOSOVO UPDATE 
</HEADLINE>
  (jw) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DIPLOMACY
</P>
<P>
   NATO approved plans for a heavily armed peacekeeping force of
50,000 soldiers for Kosovo, part of a broad campaign by the
alliance's top commander to increase pressure on President Slobodan
Milosevic of Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   The German foreign minister said his country was counting on a
diplomatic outcome to the Kosovo conflict, with the backing of
Russia, in a few weeks. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   COMBAT
</P>
<P>
   NATO planes attacked Milosevic's villa outside Belgrade and
other targets, including military barracks and fuel depots.
Explosions shook the Kosovo capital of Pristina.
</P>
<P>
   REFUGEES
</P>
<P>
   A new wave of refugees was reported bound for Macedonia, where
officials pushed the Macedonian government to expand tent cities.
</P>
<P>
   ON THE WEB
</P>
<P>
   Continuous coverage of the conflict is available from The New
York Times on the Web: http://www.nytimes.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
