<DOCNO> NYT19990525.0387 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-25 21:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0971 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVAR-REFUGEES-COX     05-25 0782
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVAR-REFUGEES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    First Kosovar Albanians arrive in Georgia
 &HT;    By Christy Oglesby and Rebecca McCarthy
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Just a few weeks ago, the Hoxha family fled the terror
of war, murder, and ethnic expulsion in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Today they will awaken in the tranquility of a Christian refuge
in north Georgia. Tomorrow, the schedule calls for English lessons
and grocery shopping.
</P>
<P>
   The humanitarian in Yugoslavia reached Georgia in a tangible way
Tuesday afternoon. Hundreds of thousands of ethnic Albanians have
fled the province of Kosovo. The Hoxhas _ two parents and three
children _ arrived at Hartsfield International Airport, becoming
the first refugees from the conflict to reach this area.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds more are expected to arrive in the coming months.
</P>
<P>
   The Hoxhas stepped off the 737 from Newark into Atlanta _ and a
frenzy of media attention. But they seemed at ease answering
reporters' questions. The exception was 20-year-old Arben, who
nervously tapped his heel on the floor.
</P>
<P>
   The trip _ from Kosovo to Macedonia to New Jersey to Georgia _
was ``long and very, very difficult,'' said Ilir Hoxha, the father.
``We would like to thank the American people.''
</P>
<P>
   Georgia, in terms, has opened its arms.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're getting more offers of help than we can use,'' said Don
Mosley of Jubilee Partners, an intentional Christian community in
Comer, Ga., where the refugees will live for the next two months.
``We really don't have any place to store any more help.''
</P>
<P>
   The family lived in Pristina, the capital of Kosovo, where Ilir
Hoxha musical producer for a television station before being booted
out of his job.
</P>
<P>
   `` It was a very hard life there,'' he said through a Albanian
translator. ``They forced us to leave our house. Every moment we
waited, our lives were in danger.''
</P>
<P>
   Also with them were two daughters _ Teuta, who is 15, and
Arbreshe, who is 17.
</P>
<P>
   After collecting their luggage _ new clothes given them at Fort
Dix, New Jersey, because they fled only with what they were wearing
_ the Hoxhas climbed in a van and were driven to Comer.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a healing place,'' said Jennifer Drago, Jubilee's refugee
program coordinator who waited at the airport with a sign that read
``welcome'' in Albanian.
</P>
<P>
   The people of Jubilee had been preparing for this day. A
traditional home-cooked Kosovar meal of meats and dough was waiting
for the refugees, and staff at Jubilee had stocked their house with
familiar kinds of food.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a 50-pound bag of flour waiting for them,'' Drago
said. ``They do lots of bread. And there's yeast, fruit and
chicken. And vegeta _ it's like bouillon cubes. They use that to
season meats.''
</P>
<P>
   When the red van carrying the Hoxhas topped the hill near the
Jubilee driveway, Mosley began waving and smiling.
</P>
<P>
   Staff members and their families waved at the van and held aloft
a large sign saying ``Mire es na vini,'' the Albanian equivalent of
``welcome.'' The Hoxhas and their children shook hands with most of
the 25 or so people who live year-round at Jubilee.
</P>
<P>
   Ilir Hoxha, in an atmosphere less pressured than at the airport,
told of being pushed out of his home by Serbian paramilitary
members early last March. The three-mile route that his family and
he were forced to walk to the train station was lined with masked,
armed soldiers, but Hoxha didn't look at them. The family kept
their eyes focused on the ground the entire way.
</P>
<P>
   When the boarded the train, Hoxha said, they didn't know where
they were going of what would happen to them _they only knew they
would be killed if they stayed. They were dumped off the train
right inside the Macedonian border, where they slept on the ground,
in the rain, for seven days, with no shelter or provisions, before
moving into a refugee camps.
</P>
<P>
   Their frightening exit from Kosovo capped 10 years of oppression
and mistreatment by Serbians, Hoxha said. Fired from her clerical
job with a branch of the Kosovar government, his wife, Hyshije,
didn't work for five years, until she landed a job in the
University of Prishtna.
</P>
<P>
   By then, it was almost 7:30 p.m., and the Hoxha family seemed
tired, having been in transit most of the day. The meaty aroma of
the Albanian dinner prepared by the translator's wife wafted into
the parking lot as the Jubilee staff unloaded it from the van. The
family looked at the clear blue sky, the rustling trees and the
smiling faces of their hosts, then boarded the van to go to supper.
</P>
<P>
   Christy Oglesby and Rebecca McCarthy write for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
