<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-25 21:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0975 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MATTHEWS-STUDIO-LADN     05-25 0516
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MATTHEWS-STUDIO-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WALL STREET STAR-STRUCK OVER HOLLYWOOD OUTFITTER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DAVE MCNARY  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BURBANK, Calif. -- Wall Street is starting to fall in love with
Hollywood rental-equipment specialist Matthews Studio Group.
</P>
<P>
   The Burbank-based company, which has taken advantage of Internet
fever this year by announcing plans for a comprehensive Web site,
saw its stock close at three consecutive all-time highs last week
in a breathtaking 38 percent sprint from $7 to $9.6975. It jumped
to $10.875 Monday after announcing a long-term outsourcing
agreement with Raleigh Studios before profit-taking led to a
25-cent decline. On Tuesday, it gained 12.5 cents to $9.5625.
</P>
<P>
   Those figures are stratospheric compared with stock prices from
last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Matthews had been one of those hidden little gems that's been
discovered,'' said Peter Cardillo, chief investment strategist at
New York-based Westfalia Investments. ``We still have a long-term
`strong buy' rating. It could go all the way to $18 a share.''
</P>
<P>
   The run-up began in late December when Matthews announced strong
quarterly results and accelerated in January when it rolled out
plans for ShowbizMart.com as a one-stop Web site for producers,
suppliers, crews and equipment. The company, which will formally
launch the site next week, has signed partnership deals with
Amazon.com, Reel.com and Sabre Group's Travelocity.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, the stock is on a roll and the Internet site is the
sizzle behind it,'' Cardillo said. ``There's a tremendous potential
for revenue growth. Things are still a little soft in the
rental-supply business but when that turns around, it's going to be
incredible.''
</P>
<P>
   Matthews began buying up rivals in 1995 to become the rental
industry's leader and to diversify beyond the volatile feature film
business. It sold off its manufacturing subsidiary late last year
and operates in 14 locations with 400 employees.
</P>
<P>
   Although Matthews reported last week a loss of $3.5 million in
its six months ended March 31, investors focused on a 22 percent
gain in cash flow to $5.4 million.
</P>
<P>
   Carlos De Mattos, chairman and chief executive officer, said
broadening Matthews into supplying equipment to special events,
Broadway shows, Las Vegas casino shows and TV specials has made the
company less susceptible to Hollywood's tightened feature film
spending.
</P>
<P>
   ``The diversification has made us more predictable for Wall
Street,'' he said. ``We think features will stay soft for a while
but we are prepared to cope.''
</P>
<P>
   De Mattos said the Web site will enable Matthews to capitalize
on its fundamental strengths along with moving into the consumer
market by selling memorabilia through deals with studios and TV
shows. It also plans to use the site to auction off used equipment.
</P>
<P>
   Bret Weeks, director of marketing, said ShowbizMart.com has
provoked strong positive reaction within the industry. ``We're
seeing more response from majors and indies in our core business,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
