<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CASINO-VOTE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Commissioners vote down West Georgia Indian casino
 &HT;    By Jennifer Brett and Ralph Ellis
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The Carroll County Board of Commissioners on Tuesday
voted unanimously to turn down an Indian tribe's proposal to build
a Las Vegas-style casino off I-20 near the Alabama state line.
</P>
<P>
   The vote came before a crowd of about 250, with another 350
vocal opponents outside, in the courthouse parking lot chanting,
``No casinos! No Casinos!''
</P>
<P>
   Marc Curlee, pastor of Kansas Baptist Church, led a prayer of
thanks after the vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a conviction that gambling is wrong. Legitimate
business is win-win: gambling is a win-lose situation,'' Curlee
said.
</P>
<P>
   County Commsiionion Chairman Jack Bell said early support from
some area representatives, based on the potential economic gain to
the county, was withdrawn in recent days.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will go somewhere else. Someone will accept this, and it
will be a boon to that county,'' Bell said after the vote.
</P>
<P>
   The Oklahoma businessman who wants to help the Kialegee Indians
develop the casino resort, said the tribe, which was forcibly
relocated from Georgia to Oklahoma in the 1830s, is willing to give
state and local government 25 percent of its game machine winnings
from the first 10 years of operation.
</P>
<P>
   Kenneth Baldwin of the Baldwin Investment Group, the sole
proponent to speak in favor of the casino complex, said that
amounts to about $1 billion, with Carroll County receiving about
$275 million over the 10 years. Baldwin said he wanted to try to
raise the money to build the casino.
</P>
<P>
   The casino and its 350-room hotel, golf course and other
attractions could provide about 11,000 jobs and pump $62 million
into the economy during the two-year construction phase alone. He
predicted the economic benefits would continue for decades.
</P>
<P>
   Baldwin's pitch to the Rotary Club of Carrollton on Tuesday
didn't appear to sway many members. Ward Pafford, president
emeritus of State University of West Georgia, said he is
``viscerally opposed'' to the casino.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all economics,'' he said. ``There are values other than
economics we must think about.''
</P>
<P>
   Federal law requires the tribe or its developers to discuss the
project with state and local authorities. Gov. Roy Barnes on
Tuesday reiterated his opposition to the casino.
</P>
<P>
   ``Casino gambling is not a productive addition to the economy,
long term,'' Barnes said. ``We think it has more negatives than it
has positives.''
</P>
<P>
   Baldwin and his Atlanta-based spokesman, Winston Leavell, said
they want local and state cooperation, but don't necessarily have
to have it. Baldwin said they can appeal local and state opposition
through a lawsuit, get approval from the Bureau of Indian Affairs
and end up building the casino anyway.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have the legal right to proceed with this project whether
the governor likes it or not,'' Baldwin said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a deal killer in the true sense of the word,''
Leavell said.
</P>
<P>
   Baldwin said the tribe, along with most other Georgia Indians,
were forcibly relocated to Oklahoma in the 1830s. The tribe doesn't
have its own reservation, but has a ``tribal town'' on a Creek
Indian reservation.
</P>
<P>
   Federal law allows the tribe to set up a reservation if it can
buy land in its ancestral homeland. That area covers most of
Georgia and the east part of Alabama, Baldwin said.
</P>
<P>
   Jennifer Brett and Ralph Ellis write for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
