<SLUG> BC-STARR-MCDOUGAL-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 WASHINGTON: right thing.''   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The McDougal and Steele cases presented public relations
problems, as well as courtroom ones, for the prosecution.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. McDougal became a familiar and unsettling sight as she was
led in shackles from jail to courthouse while serving 18 months for
contempt of court for refusing to cooperate with Starr, who she
said was punishing her for refusing to give testimony that
dovetailed with his theory of the case. Ms. McDougal was convicted
on earlier charges related to the Arkansas deals, as was her late
husband, James McDougal.
</P>
<P>
   Starr told the court Tuesday that a juror who talked to his
office said several members of the panel had simply refused to
follow the judge's instructions during deliberations, and that
``years of extensive press coverage'' may have swayed their views
in any event.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Steele, a single mother with an adopted son, seemed to some
observers an unimportant and unwilling participant in the
sex-scandal investigation. Had she been convicted, she could have
faced 35 years in prison and $1 million in fines.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecution maintained that Ms. Steele undercut the
investigation of Ms. Willey's accusations by offering varying
accounts of what Ms. Willey, a longtime friend, told her of her
supposed encounter with the president. The differing accounts
discouraged Starr from including the Willey matter in the material
he sent to the House of Representatives as part of his impeachment
case against the president.
</P>
