<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALLEN-DEAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CABLE DEAL FOR $3.6 BILLION IN THE WORKS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Wash., Calif., Mo., Ore.)   (jw) 
 By LAURA M. HOLSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Charter Communications Inc., the cable-television
operator owned by Paul Allen, a co-founder of Microsoft Corp., is
expected to announce as early as Wednesday that it is buying the
cable assets of Falcon Cable Holdings of Los Angeles in a stock
swap valued at more than $3.6 billion, according to people close to
the talks.
</P>
<P>
   Executives at both companies have been in talks for only a few
weeks, these people said. Allen is also negotiating to acquire the
assets of two other smaller cable companies.
</P>
<P>
   The acquisition of Falcon's cable assets would be the latest in
a springtime spree of deal-making by Allen. Charter has committed
itself to $3.7 billion in cable purchases this year alone,
including last week's announcement that it would agree to buy
Avalon Cable Television for $845 million.
</P>
<P>
   In buying the assets of closely held Falcon, Charter, the
nation's seventh-largest cable operator, based in St. Louis, would
own systems with about 1.2 million subscribers in several small and
medium-sized markets in several states, including Oregon, Missouri
and California, particularly Los Angeles. Some analysts suggested
that Charter would be willing to swap assets with other cable
operators to gain market share in urban Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for Charter would not comment on the possible
acquisition.
</P>
<P>
   Allen's recent acquisitions may put him in a position to
challenge AT&AMP;T or other major telecommunications concerns that have
been vying for cable assets this year as a way to expand Internet
capabilities into every home.
</P>
<P>
   But any deal with Falcon is sure to be complicated. Last year
Falcon joined with Tele-Communications Inc. to restructure itself
and refinance its heavy debt load, leaving TCI with a 47 percent
stake in Falcon. At that time, the chairman and chief executive of
Falcon, Marc Nathanson, said he was considering taking Falcon
public or remaining an independent company.
</P>
<P>
   But AT&AMP;T has been on its own $90 billion cable buying binge,
first agreeing to buy TCI last year and, more recently, MediaOne.
</P>
<P>
   The deal between Falcon and Charter is expected to be a stock
swap of privately held shares. And one banker suggested that AT&AMP;T
would consider selling its stake _ which it will acquire in the TCI
transaction _ once the privately held Charter begins selling shares
to the public.
</P>
<P>
   That could come as soon as this year. Charter is expected to go
public in the second half of this year as long as the market
remains receptive, and could sell for as much as $2 billion to $3
billion in stock. If successful, the public offering would be the
largest ever in the cable-television industry.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
