<HEADER>
A0981 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AIRTRAN-ACCUSATIONS-D     05-25 0481
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIRTRAN-ACCUSATIONS-DELTA-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    American suit trailed by AirTran complaint
 &HT;    By Scott Thurston
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ On the heels of a government lawsuit against American
Airlines for predatory pricing against smaller rivals, AirTran is
lodging fresh complaints of similar behavior by Atlanta rival Delta
Air Lines.
</P>
<P>
   In a brief sent to the Justice and Transportation departments,
AirTran said Delta uses matching fares and extra flights to soak up
low-fare demand on key routes. The carrier said the goal is to
force AirTran to retreat so Delta can raise fares.
</P>
<P>
   ``Delta's competitive response to AirTran over the years, and
increasingly in recent days, has only one objective _ drive a
small-but-growing, successful low-fare carrier out of its
markets,'' the brief said.
</P>
<P>
   AirTran executives, who insisted they were working on the brief
before the May 13 American suit, said they aren't seeking a lawsuit
or specific remedy.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we've done is reviewed the competitive practices,''
AirTran President Robert Fornaro said. ``We want the DOJ and DOT to
pass judgment on them however they see fit.''
</P>
<P>
   Delta spokesman Bill Berry called the charges an ``insulting and
untrue'' rehash of old allegations.
</P>
<P>
   ``AirTran, formerly ValuJet, has used such charges for years to
divert attention from its own problems,'' Berry said. ``No
government agency has ever found Delta to be in the wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's time for AirTran, which is one of the largest discount
carriers in the country, to accept responsibility for its past
marketing failures and stop blaming the competition,'' Berry added.
</P>
<P>
   ValuJet and AirTran have periodically complained of Delta's
tactics, but Fornaro said the AirTran brief contains new details of
intensified activity.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, according to the brief:
</P>
<P>
   _ Delta has raised walk-up fares 52 percent on the
Atlanta-Richmond, Va., route since AirTran withdrew last winter in
the face of intensive fare-matching.
</P>
<P>
   _ Delta last fall began flights to Chicago-Midway Airport, which
it had never before served, and undercut AirTran's average fares by
8 percent. AirTran said it may be forced to withdraw from that
route, too.
</P>
<P>
   _ Delta responded to a recent AirTran sale by not only matching
fares but also dropping round-trip and weekend stay requirements.
The response, which AirTran claims was unprecedented, came after it
announced a first-quarter profit _ only its second in the past two
years.
</P>
<P>
   In the American case, the DOJ charges the carrier drove low-fare
carriers out of its Dallas-Fort Worth hub by flooding routes with
cheap fares. While the suit signals a more protective government
stance toward small airlines, legal experts say the case will be
tough to win because of prior court decisions.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
