<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: SIAMESE SENATORS
</HEADLINE>
   (Dal) 
 By MAUREEN DOWD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ There is no other conversation here.
</P>
<P>
   New York is consumed with watching the renowned gladiators
warily circle one another, two tough cookies ready to rumble.
</P>
<P>
   Surely these A-plus students are already studying oppo-research,
getting ready to exploit every mistake, every gaffe, every weakness
until one or the other is utterly destroyed. You can picture the
first lady and the mayor hunched over their neat desks late at
night, a single light burning, as they peruse briefing papers on
each other.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine Rudy's briefing book on Hillary:
</P>
<P>
   She envisions how things should be and assumes she can make it
so.
</P>
<P>
   Her world is black and white.
</P>
<P>
   She's most sure she's right when she's most wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Her smile is not connected to her face.
</P>
<P>
   She despises the press.
</P>
<P>
   She quickly gets paranoid.
</P>
<P>
   Her marriage is troubled, mysterious to the outside world.
</P>
<P>
   She has a nun's lofty air of sacrifice.
</P>
<P>
   She's polarizing. People who like her really like her and people
who don't really don't.
</P>
<P>
   Her spouse is probably hoping she becomes a senator and moves
away.
</P>
<P>
   You might admire her but you wouldn't want to hang out with her.
</P>
<P>
   Her aides comport themselves like members of a cult, their faces
a jittery mix of adoration and fear.
</P>
<P>
   She supported Mario Cuomo.
</P>
<P>
   She disdains Al D'Amato.
</P>
<P>
   She has a temper.
</P>
<P>
   She favors the death penalty.
</P>
<P>
   She favors welfare reform.
</P>
<P>
   Her nickname is Saint Hillary.
</P>
<P>
   She runs a secretive ship.
</P>
<P>
   She has a very long memory for political enemies.
</P>
<P>
   She's unwilling to compromise.
</P>
<P>
   She puts ambition ahead of her personal life.
</P>
<P>
   She sometimes mistakes herself for a messianic figure.
</P>
<P>
   She does not get distracted by pleasure. She is superhumanly
single-minded.
</P>
<P>
   She sees the world like a litigator, a take-no-prisoners
attitude that casts things in extreme terms, even when the ideas
are moderate.
</P>
<P>
   She has a conviction that anything she does is the right thing.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes she tries to project a softer image, Ms.
Have-a-Nice-Day, but nobody buys it.
</P>
<P>
   She sees the Senate as a stepping stone to the White House.
</P>
<P>
   She has serious hair issues.
</P>
<P>
   Now imagine Hillary's briefing book on Rudy:
</P>
<P>
   He envisions how things should be and assumes he can make it so.
</P>
<P>
   His world is black and white.
</P>
<P>
   He's most sure he's right when he's most wrong.
</P>
<P>
   His smile is not connected to his face.
</P>
<P>
   He despises the press.
</P>
<P>
   He quickly gets paranoid.
</P>
<P>
   His marriage is troubled, mysterious to the outside world.
</P>
<P>
   He has a priest's lofty air of sacrifice.
</P>
<P>
   He's polarizing. People who like him really like him and people
who don't really don't.
</P>
<P>
   His spouse is probably hoping he becomes a Senator and moves
away.
</P>
<P>
   You might admire him but you wouldn't want to hang out with him.
</P>
<P>
   His aides comport themselves like members of a cult, their faces
a jittery mix of adoration and fear.
</P>
<P>
   He supported Mario Cuomo.
</P>
<P>
   He disdains Al D'Amato.
</P>
<P>
   He has a temper.
</P>
<P>
   He favors the death penalty.
</P>
<P>
   He favors welfare reform.
</P>
<P>
   His nickname is Saint Rudy.
</P>
<P>
   He runs a secretive ship.
</P>
<P>
   He has a very long memory for political enemies.
</P>
<P>
   He's unwilling to compromise.
</P>
<P>
   He puts ambition ahead of his personal life.
</P>
<P>
   He sometimes mistakes himself for a messianic figure.
</P>
<P>
   He does not get distracted by pleasure. He is superhumanly
single-minded.
</P>
<P>
   He sees the world like a litigator, a take-no-prisoners attitude
that casts things in extreme terms even when the ideas are
moderate.
</P>
<P>
   He has a conviction that anything he does is the right thing.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes he tries to project a softer image, Mr.
Have-a-Nice-Day, but nobody buys it.
</P>
<P>
   He sees the Senate as a stepping stone to the White House.
</P>
<P>
   He has serious hair issues.
</P>
