<SLUG> BC-TRUCK-SAFETY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADMINISTRATION PLEDGES ACTION ON IMPROVED SAFETY FOR TRUCKERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (dal) 
 By MATTHEW L. WALD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Clinton administration on Tuesday set a goal of
reducing fatalities from truck crashes by 50 percent over 10 years,
and promised quick action on safety questions that have stymied it
for years, including revising the 62-year-old rules on how many
hours a day a driver can work.
</P>
<P>
   ``Up to this point, very little focus has been placed on the
needs of the drivers,'' said Transportation Secretary Rodney
Slater, announcing the new goal. ``It's always been, for the most
part, the bottom line.''
</P>
<P>
   The current rules, written long before the age of
transcontinental truck routes, call for drivers to have 8 hours off
after 10 hours of driving or 15 hours of work, which can include
loading and unloading or other duties. The rest hours can be split
into two parts, the shorter as little as 2 hours, and can be taken
in a cab's sleeper berth.
</P>
<P>
   The National Transportation Safety Board, which estimates that
750 to 1,500 deaths annually occur in crashes in which trucker
fatigue is a factor, has put new rules on hours on its ``most
wanted'' list of safety improvements since 1990. The Transportation
Department proposed new rules in 1995, but, unable to win consensus
among labor, business and safety groups, has not moved forward.
Slater said on Tuesday that unless the pace was increased, no new
rule would be written before President Clinton's term ends.
</P>
<P>
   And the existing rule is widely disobeyed, Transportation
Department officials say.
</P>
<P>
   Kenneth Mead, the inspector general of the department, said the
industry's economic structure, with drivers widely paid by the mile
instead of the hour, would have to change to make the system safer.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't drive till they're exhausted because they want
to,'' Mead said.
</P>
<P>
   He has detailed a series of problems with the department's
Office of Motor Carriers recently. In 1998, he said, more than
20,000 violations were cited by investigators, but only 11 percent
resulted in fines, and of those, fines paid were only 46 percent of
the dollar amounts initially assessed. The average final payment
was $1,500, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Slater and Kenneth Wykle, the federal highway administrator,
said one step would be bigger fines.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will take a more aggressive posture,'' Wykle said.
</P>
<P>
   Under legislation that took effect this year, fines for serious
violations of trucking rules, formerly limited to $1,000 each and
$10,000 per accident or incident, are now set at $10,000 each, with
no ceiling. And fines for record-keeping violations, formerly $500
each with a cap of $2,500, are now $5,000 each, with no ceiling.
</P>
<P>
   Federal statistics show that the number of accidents per million
miles traveled has fallen steadily, but the number of deaths is
stubbornly high, because the industry is booming. Slater said on
Tuesday that the number of miles traveled by trucks was up 25
percent in the last four years.
</P>
<P>
   According to the National Highway Traffic Safety Administration,
5,398 people died in crashes involving heavy trucks in 1997, nearly
all of them in a car, van, pickup or other light vehicle, not the
heavy truck. The preliminary number for 1998 is 5,302.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
