<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-APPOINT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIAN PREMIER NAMES POINT MAN ON ECONOMIC POLICY 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By CELESTINE BOHLEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Finance Minister Mikhail Zadornov, an advocate of tough
fiscal policies, will take charge of Russia's economic policy, said
Prime Minister Sergei Stepashin on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Zadornov's promotion to the rank of first deputy prime minister
was one of the few surprises in a series of Cabinet appointments
announced Tuesday by the new prime minister as he returned to
Moscow after meeting with President Boris Yeltsin at the Black Sea
resort of Sochi.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier reports had the job going to Alexander Zhukov, the
moderate chairman of the Parliament's budget committee, whose views
on economic policy are similar to Zadornov's.
</P>
<P>
   By giving broader responsibilities to Zadornov, a 36-year-old
economist well regarded by Russia's Western financial partners,
Stepashin succeeded in convincing the Yeltsin administration that
an experienced finance manager should be put in overall charge of
Russia's debt-ridden economy.
</P>
<P>
   Stepashin already has one first deputy prime minister, Nikolai
Aksyonenko, a former railways minister who had also been a
candidate to head the government after the firing of Prime Minister
Yevgeny Primakov two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   Aksyonenko, reportedly a favorite of Yeltsin's inner circle, was
a surprise guest at Tuesday's talks in Sochi, where Yeltsin has
gone for a two-week vacation. After the talks, Stepashin said that
his deputy's appearance had been planned, and said that his new
government would make a ``good team.''
</P>
<P>
   Stepashin confirmed that Zhukov had also been considered to run
the economy, but he said his support was more important in the
Parliament's lower house, the Duma. ``The Zadornov-Zhukov
combination will be very useful,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Except for a few changes in minor ministries, the Stepashin
government _ now 80 percent complete _ looks remarkably like the
one headed by Primakov. The former head of the Tax Service, Georgi
Boos, was replaced by Alexander Pochinok, who previously had held
the post. Mikhail Kasyonov, a deputy finance minister, was promoted
to succeed Zadornov. Yeltsin last week reconfirmed a series of
ministers, including Gen. Igor Sergeyev as defense minister and
Igor Ivanov as foreign minister.
</P>
<P>
   ``If all the changes that will take place in the Cabinet in the
future are like this, one cannot say that this will be a government
that is new to any serious extent,'' Grigory Yavlinsky, leader of
Parliament's largest liberal party, told reporters Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The Communist speaker of the lower house, Gennady Seleznyov,
welcomed the appointment of Zadornov, whom he described as ``a
professional who knows his job.'' But, he warned that Zadornov
would be successful only ``if he listens to the opinion of
parliamentarians.''
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said Tuesday that Zadornov, a former Parliament budget
chairman and veteran of three previous governments, has the
credentials and the experience needed for the job. The main
question, they said, is whether he _ and the Stepashin government
generally _ will get the political support they need from a
Parliament that is already getting ready for elections in December.
</P>
<P>
   ``Zadornov knows what needs to be done,'' said David Riley,
director of emerging European market for Fitch IBCA, a New
York-based credit rating company. ``The question mark is whether he
has enough political support to deliver.''
</P>
<P>
   The Parliament is soon due to consider a legislative package _
part of which was already introduced by the Primakov government _
intended to meet the fiscal requirements set by the International
Monetary Fund for a critical $4.5 billion debt relief program for
Russia.
</P>
<P>
   Russia's ability to meet these conditions is also crucial for a
restructuring of $90 billion of Soviet-era debts to Western
governments and commercial banks, on which Russia has already
missed several payments this year. Analysts this week were already
predicting that Russia will not pay $216 million in interest due
the London club of commercial creditors on June 2.
</P>
</TEXT>
