</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) OVER FITCHBURG, Mass. -- May 25, 1999 --
AUTHOR-BLUME-BOS, 5-25 --- Randy Bloom at the controls during a
recent flight out of Hanscom Field in Bedford. Ms. Blume, 38, is a
confessed teenage bookworm and the daughter of author Judy Blume.
That she wrote a novel - even a novel about a woman who chooses
flying over law - should come as no big surprise. But that she was
the young woman who chose flight school over law school takes some
explaining. ``I knew it was totally alien to the way I was brought
up,'' she says. (Pam Berry/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) PLAINVILLE, Mass. -- May 25, 1999 -- RAC-HARNESS-BOS,
5-25 --- Harness drivers heading out to the track at the new
Plainridge Race Course. The track is still in its trial stage.
Racing cards are small and limited and there is live racing on
Monday, Tuesday and Saturday. (Tom Herde/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) NEW YORK -- May 25, 1999 -- PERU-CUISINE-3, 5-25 -- In
New York, the pisco cocktail, a Peruvian specialty at Pio Pio. Peru
has one of the great cuisines of the world. It is the original
fusion food, having absorbed influences from almost every continent
over the last 500 years and melded them with ingredients and dishes
that provide a direct link to the Incas. (Norman Y. Lono/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) NEW YORK -- May 25, 1999 -- PERU-CUISINE-2, 5-25 -- In
New York, a Peruvian dish, tiradito, is served at Nobu. The Nobu
menu includes several Peruvian specialties, such as tiradito, a
cross between ceviche and sashimi in which raw white fish is gently
flavored with citrus and enlivened with chili, then served
exquisitely unadorned, the thin slices fanned out like the delicate
petals of a flower. ``My food is Japanese technique and Peruvian
influence,'' says Nobu Matsuhisa, chef and co-owner of the
restaurant. (Kiyoshi Togashi/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) MIAMI -- May 25, 1999 -- PERU-CUISINE-1, 5-25 -- In
Miami, markets cater to Peruvians' quest for fresh ingredients.
Peru's food is remarkable for the diversity of its ingredients,
from wonderful fresh fish to astounding varieties of potatoes, corn
and chilies, and for preparations that encompass the world, from
stir-fried beef to pasta with shrimp. (Susan Greenwood/New York
Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) NEW YORK -- May 25, 1999 -- WINE-TALK, 5-25 -- Americans'
