<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-25 21:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0995 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SMOKING-TOURISM-LADN     05-25 0500
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SMOKING-TOURISM-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOBACCO INDUSTRY'S TOURISM WARNINGS UNFOUNDED, STUDY SAYS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY PHILLIP W. BROWNE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Even though smokers are banished to restaurant
patios and sidewalks in California, the statewide smoking ban has
not harmed tourism as the tobacco industry predicted, according to
a study released Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Smoking bans in three states and six cities were established at
a time when tourism was on a significant upswing, and those numbers
have risen, according to the University of California, San
Francisco, study.
</P>
<P>
   ``The tobacco industry is full of hot air when they say the
world will come to an end with smoking bans,'' said Stanton A.
Glantz, author of the report that appears today &UR;  &LR; in the Journal of
the American Medical Association.
</P>
<P>
   ``Local governments can institute bans without fear of economic
impact,'' said Glantz, a medical researcher who became a tobacco
industry critic when the smoking debate shifted from health to
economic issues.
</P>
<P>
   In Los Angeles since 1994, hotel revenues have jumped from $450
million that year to almost $600 million in 1998, the study says.
California's restaurant smoking ban became law in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Tobacco industry advocates say the latest study is another one
of Glantz's ``scams.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just another advocacy piece masquerading as research,''
said Tom Humber, president of the National Smokers Alliance, an
Arlington, Va.-based group that advocates smokers rights.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any economist with any knowledge of the hospitality industry
would laugh this research out of the country,'' Humber said.
</P>
<P>
   In Los Angeles, the tourism industry's greatest challenge has
been overcoming the 1992 riots and the 1994 Northridge Earthquake
-- not the smoking ban, said Michael Collins, executive vice
president of the Los Angeles Convention and Visitors Bureau.
</P>
<P>
   Local tourism continues to climb even with the ban in place.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every single tourism indicator has marched upward with huge
increases,'' Collins said. ``I'm sure the bans have had some effect
on individual businesses somewhere, but tourism and visitor
spending has jumped.''
</P>
<P>
   Humber said all recent smoking ban studies are flawed because
researchers focus on industry revenue data without taking into
account compliance with the ban and other factors.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Los Angeles there's only about a 50 percent compliance to
the ban, so people spend the same money, they just spend it at
places where they can smoke,'' Humber said. ``The businesses that
comply are severely impacted.''
</P>
<P>
   The states included in the study were California, Utah and
Vermont. Cities studied included Los Angeles; San Francisco; New
York; Mesa, Ariz.; Boulder, Colo. and Flagstaff, Ariz.
</P>
<P>
   In every case, the data showed that hotel occupancy has
increased dramatically in those cities since the bans became the
vogue in the mid-1990s, the report says.
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
