<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-25 21:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0997 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HATIAN-SMUGGLE-VERDIC     05-25 0424
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HATIAN-SMUGGLE-VERDICT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Man found guilty in fatal Haitian smuggling trip
 &HT;    By Clay Lambert
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT LAUDERDALE, Fla. _ Addison Joseph Hepburn piloted a rickety
boatload of Haitians to the Palm Beach County coastline last August
and forced them out of his boat about a mile offshore, causing the
death of one woman, a federal jury decided Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Court Judge William Dimitrouleas set sentencing
for Aug. 13 after a Broward County jury rendered its decision.
Hepburn faces a mandatory 3-year sentence for profiting from his
smuggling plan. Witnesses said they paid as much as $1,500 to be
ferried to the United States from the Bahamas. Attorneys for both
sides said guidelines likely will limit his sentence to little more
than the 3 mandatory years.
</P>
<P>
   The jury found Hepburn guilty of eight counts of smuggling,
eight counts of smuggling for financial gain and one count of
smuggling that resulted in death. While federal prosecutors believe
33 Haitian immigrants were on the 23-foot motor boat piloted by
Hepburn the night of Aug. 10, they could identify only eight
passengers. The jury considered charges related to smuggling those
eight people.
</P>
<P>
   Hepburn, a 45-year-old Bahamian fisherman, dumped his human
cargo on a sandbar about 100 yards from land. Some swam ashore,
where they were picked up by Palm Beach County sheriff's deputies.
Others were rescued from the sandbar. Two Haitians died struggling
between the sandbar and the beach.
</P>
<P>
   Hepburn, who was later nabbed as he slept on his broken-down
boat, was held responsible for the drowning death of Benette
Dorsonne. But the jury found Hepburn not guilty of causing the
death of another drowning victim _ Richard Presendieu. Witnesses
provided conflicting evidence of whether Presendieu was a passenger
on Hepburn's boat.
</P>
<P>
   Before presenting its findings, the jury of seven men and five
women asked Dimitrouleas to define ``resulting'' in the charge of
smuggling resulting in death. He offered little help, sending a
handwritten note imploring them to ``rely on their collective
understanding of what the word 'resulting' means.''
</P>
<P>
   One juror said that was the only point of contention.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we were all tied up about was whether he was responsible
for the death,'' Janice Freiert said after the verdict. ``He didn't
commit murder.''
</P>
<P>
   Clay Lambert writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
