from communist outpost to a member of the European community of
nations has not been easy for Albania. It remains Europe's poorest
country and has suffered through one crisis after another. (Tyler
Hicks/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT28) WASHINGTON -- May 25, 1999 -- CHINA-COX-REPORT-5, 5-25
-- At the presentation on Tuesday of the House panel's survey of
security, military and commercial concerns with China were the
Republican chairman, Rep. Christoper Cox, left, and four other
Representatives, Bobby Scott, Lucille Roybal-Allard, Norm Dicks,
the ranking Democrat on the committee, and Doug Bereuter. (Stephen
Crowley/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT27) SOWETO, South Africa-- May 25, 1999 --
SAFRICA-ELECTIONS-COX-2, 5-25 -- Outgoing South African President
Nelson Mandla, left, joins Deputy President Thabo Mbeki during a
campaign rally earlier this month. Mbeki is strongly favored to win
the presidency in elections on June 2. Five years after South
Africa's first all-race elections propelled the country's first
black-led government to power, relations between whites and blacks
are more relaxed and less fractious than almost anyone could have
predicted. (W. A. Bridges/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT26) JOHANNESBURG -- May 25, 1999 -- SAFRICA-ELECTIONS-COX-1,
5-25 --Marian Kareden, 22, a store manager in a mall, says she will
cast her vote in upcoming elections for the Inkatha Freedom Party.
Five years after South Africa's first all-race elections propelled
the country's first black-led government to power and ended the
official policy of apartheid relations between whites and blacks
are more relaxed and less fractious than almost anyone could have
predicted. (W. A. Bridges/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT25) NEW YORK -- May 25, 1999 -- NY-LOUIMA-TRIAL-2, 5-25 --
Howard Safir, the New York City police commissioner, is asked to
comment about the guilty plea made by police officer Justin Volpe
on Tuesday. Volpe admitted Tuesday that he rammed a stick into
Abner Louima's rectum and then thrust it in his face, an act, Volpe
acknowledged, which was intended to humiliate and intimidate the
handcuffed Haitian immigrant. (Ozier Muhammad/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT24) FORSYTH, Ga. -- May 25, 1999 -- SOCTUS-HARASS, 5-24 --
Aurelia Davis, left, with her daughter LaShonda, at their home on
Monday. In a 5-4 decision, the Supreme Court ruled on Monday that
teachers and school administrators who fail to stop
student-to-student sexual harassment may be violating a federal
anti-bias law known as Title IX. (Alan S. Weiner/New York Times
Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT23) OSUBI, Nigeria -- May 25, 1999 -- NIGERIA-AIRPORT, 5-25
-- J.R. Udodia, Shell Oil's general manager in the western part of
the Niger Delta, near the tarmac of a newly constructed air strip.
Years of experience has taught Udodia that the impossible in
Nigeria, like building an airport, is often possible, so long as
certain illusions are maintained. So this facility is officially
known as an air strip, eliminating the red tape and corruption that
would have come with the Nigerian government's involvement should
they have been involved in its construction. (Norimitsu Onishi/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT22) JAZINCE, Macedonia -- May 25, 1999 --
KOSOVO-MACEDONIA-3, 5-25 -- Ethnic Albanian refugees from Kosovo on
a bus bound for refugee camps after crossing the border in to
Macedonia on Tuesday. About 3,000 Kosovar refugees crossed into
Macedonia on Tuesday, after spending 24 hours in the no-man's land
separating Serbia and Macedonia, the UN refugee agency said.
(Andrew Testa/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) JAZINCE, Macedonia -- May 25, 1999 --
KOSOVO-MACEDONIA-2, 5-25 -- Ethnic Albanian refugees from Kosovo
after crossing the border in to Macedonia on Tuesday. About 3,000
Kosovar refugees crossed into Macedonia on Tuesday, after spending
24 hours in the no-man's land separating Serbia and Macedonia, the
UN refugee agency said. (Andrew Testa/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) CEGRANE, Macedonia -- May 25, 1999 --
KOSOVO-MACEDONIA-1, 5-25 -- A young man pulls back the blanket
covering the body of his father, an ethnic Albanian refugee from
Kosovo, who died of a heart attack on Tuesday. The son had returned
from Germany and was in the process of taking his family back with
him when his father died. (Andrew Testa/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) BOSTON -- May 25, 1999 -- TRAVEL-LIGHTHOUSES-BOS, 5-25
--- With Boston as a backdrop, the nation's oldest lighthouse,
Boston Light, catches a sunset. Colonial history buffs can take day
cruises this summer out to the lighthouse, which was built in 1716
on Little Brewster Island in the Boston Harbor. The 103-foot
granite tower was blown up by the British in 1776 and rebuilt in
1873. It is the last operating lighthouse in the nation that is
staffed around the clock. (David L. Ryan/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) NEW YORK -- May 25, 1999 -- EAST-THEATER-REVIEW, 5-25 --
From left, Purva Bedi, portraying a daughter, with Jenny Sterlin,
as the mother, and Dariush Kashani, as a brother, in the play
``East Is East.'' Ayub Khan-Din's lively production is an awkward
but affectionate tale of domestic and cultural combat among the
Pakistani owner of a chips (as in fish and chips) shop in
northwestern England, his British wife and their many children.
(Sara Krulwich/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) SOWETO, South Africa -- May 25, 1999 --
SAFRICA-POLITICS, 5-25 -- South African President Nelson Mandela,
second from right, and Thabo Mbeki, center, South Africa's deputy
president and the man who will almost certainly inherit Mandela's
job after elections on June 2, salute the crowd during a rally
kicking off the campaign earlier this month. Over the last few
years Mbeki has been the behind-the-scenes administrator as Mandela
greeted dignitaries and traveled the globe to woo foreign
investors. (W.A. Bridges/Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) WASHINGTON -- May 25, 1999 -- CHINA-COX-REPORT-4, 5-25
-- Attorney General Janet Reno arrives for an event on missing
children on Tuesday. Reno made it clear Monday that she isn't
resigning even though a Clinton administration loyalist in the
Senate suggested she consider stepping down over the handling of
allegations of Chinese nuclear espionage. (Justin Lane/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) NEW YORK -- May 25, 1999 -- NY-LOUIMA-TRIAL, 5-25 --
Justin Volpe, right, enters Brooklyn Federal Court on Tuesday.
Volpe admitted for the first time on Tuesday that he tortured Abner
Louima in the bathroom of a Brooklyn police station in a fit of
rage. (Ruby Washington/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) NEW YORK -- May 25, 1999 -- CHEF-GEOMANCY, 5-25 -- Eric
Ripert, one of at least a dozen chefs, including Daniel Boulud,
Francois Payard and Jean-Louis Palladin, who look to a 42-year-old
Frenchman named Jerome Brasset for career advice. Brasset claims he
can divine the future through an obscure occult practice known as
geomancy. (Rebecca Cooney/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) OVER FITCHBURG, Mass. -- May 25, 1999 --
AUTHOR-BLUME-BOS, 5-25 --- Randy Bloom at the controls during a
recent flight out of Hanscom Field in Bedford. Ms. Blume, 38, is a
confessed teenage bookworm and the daughter of author Judy Blume.
That she wrote a novel - even a novel about a woman who chooses
flying over law - should come as no big surprise. But that she was
the young woman who chose flight school over law school takes some
explaining. ``I knew it was totally alien to the way I was brought
up,'' she says. (Pam Berry/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) PLAINVILLE, Mass. -- May 25, 1999 -- RAC-HARNESS-BOS,
5-25 --- Harness drivers heading out to the track at the new
Plainridge Race Course. The track is still in its trial stage.
Racing cards are small and limited and there is live racing on
Monday, Tuesday and Saturday. (Tom Herde/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) NEW YORK -- May 25, 1999 -- PERU-CUISINE-3, 5-25 -- In
New York, the pisco cocktail, a Peruvian specialty at Pio Pio. Peru
has one of the great cuisines of the world. It is the original
fusion food, having absorbed influences from almost every continent
over the last 500 years and melded them with ingredients and dishes
that provide a direct link to the Incas. (Norman Y. Lono/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) NEW YORK -- May 25, 1999 -- PERU-CUISINE-2, 5-25 -- In
New York, a Peruvian dish, tiradito, is served at Nobu. The Nobu
menu includes several Peruvian specialties, such as tiradito, a
cross between ceviche and sashimi in which raw white fish is gently
flavored with citrus and enlivened with chili, then served
exquisitely unadorned, the thin slices fanned out like the delicate
petals of a flower. ``My food is Japanese technique and Peruvian
influence,'' says Nobu Matsuhisa, chef and co-owner of the
restaurant. (Kiyoshi Togashi/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) MIAMI -- May 25, 1999 -- PERU-CUISINE-1, 5-25 -- In
Miami, markets cater to Peruvians' quest for fresh ingredients.
Peru's food is remarkable for the diversity of its ingredients,
from wonderful fresh fish to astounding varieties of potatoes, corn
and chilies, and for preparations that encompass the world, from
stir-fried beef to pasta with shrimp. (Susan Greenwood/New York
Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) NEW YORK -- May 25, 1999 -- WINE-TALK, 5-25 -- Americans'
tastes in wines have moved toward varietals. Shown are cases at
Gotham Wine and Liquor on the Upper West Side. (Barbara Alper/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) NEW YORK -- May 25, 1999 -- CILANTRO, 5-25 -- At March,
Wayne Nish sprinkles baby cilantro onto a lobster dish. The herb is
the latest entrant in the great New York restaurant race to
distinguish one chef's cooking from another's with esoteric
ingredients like micro greens. Such minuscule leaves are already
becoming old hat, as chefs seek out the unusual micro herb no one
has seen before. And right now, it's this baby, also known as
coriander or Chinese parsley. (Michael Rogol/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) YOUNTVILLE, Calif. -- May 25, 1999 -- MASTER-CHEF, 5-25
-- Thomas Keller, chef of the French Laundry, with cornets - small
cones filled with salmon tartare and creme fraiche. ``I like to
present a series of five to nine intensely focused courses,'' he
writes. ``I want my customers to experience the jolt, the new
sensation on the palate, and then to move on to another one.''
(Thor Swift/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) FAIRFIELD, Conn. -- May 25, 1999 -- AMTRAK-FATALITY, 5-25
-- Police investigate the scene where a woman and three of her four
sons were struck and killed by an Amtrak train as they walked along
the tracks early Tuesday morning. The fourth child was in critical
condition. The 209 people on board the train, which was traveling
from Boston to Virginia, were uninjured, but the engineer was
hospitalized for shock. Knapsacks and what looked like school
papers were scattered about the tracks, investigators said.
(Richard L. Harbus/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) WASHINGTON -- May 25, 1999 -- CHINA-COX-REPORT-3, 5-25 --
Reps. Norman Dicks, left, and Christopher Cox talk to reporters
after their committee's report on alleged Chinese espionage at U.S.
nuclear laboratories was released, Wednesday on Capitol Hill. The
report issued by the committee, which was headed by Cox, concludes
that China has stolen design secrets for all seven nuclear warheads
currently deployed on American missiles. Dicks is the ranking
Democrat on the committee. (Stephen Crowley/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) WASHINGTON -- May 25, 1999 -- CHINA-COX-REPORT-2, 5-25 --
House staffers distribute copies of the report issued by a special
House committee which looked into alleged spying of U.S. nuclear
installations by China, Wednesday on Capitol Hill. The report
concludes that China has stolen design secrets for all seven
nuclear warheads currently deployed on American missiles, enabling
Beijing to leap years ahead and modernize its nuclear weapons.
(Stephen Crowley/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) HOGANSVILLE, Ga. -- May 25, 1999 --
MASTERPIECE-RECREATIONS-COX, 5-25 -- Jacques Harvey, who has spent
a lifetime aping the masters, with a copy of the Mona Lisa. The
reproduction and 64 other ``masterpieces,'' are here in a place
that celebrates artifice, the International Art Museum of
Re-Creations. If you think the notion of a museum with a collection
of faux art is strange, it's no less odd than how it came to be
located in Hogansville, 55 miles southwest of downtown Atlanta.
(Phil Skinner/Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) WASHINGTON-- May 25, 1999 -- CHINA-COX-REPORT-1, 5-25 --
Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, left, meets with Chris Williams,
Lott's foreign policy adviser, in his Capitol Hill office after
meeting with Senate Republican leaders about the release of the Cox
Report on Wednesday. The report claims that China has stolen
classified information about every currently deployed nuclear
weapon in the U.S. arsenal. (Paul Hosefros/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
</P>
