House committee which looked into alleged spying of U.S. nuclear
installations by China, Wednesday on Capitol Hill. The report
concludes that China has stolen design secrets for all seven
nuclear warheads currently deployed on American missiles, enabling
Beijing to leap years ahead and modernize its nuclear weapons.
(Stephen Crowley/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) HOGANSVILLE, Ga. -- May 25, 1999 --
MASTERPIECE-RECREATIONS-COX, 5-25 -- Jacques Harvey, who has spent
a lifetime aping the masters, with a copy of the Mona Lisa. The
reproduction and 64 other ``masterpieces,'' are here in a place
that celebrates artifice, the International Art Museum of
Re-Creations. If you think the notion of a museum with a collection
of faux art is strange, it's no less odd than how it came to be
located in Hogansville, 55 miles southwest of downtown Atlanta.
(Phil Skinner/Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) WASHINGTON-- May 25, 1999 -- CHINA-COX-REPORT-1, 5-25 --
Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, left, meets with Chris Williams,
Lott's foreign policy adviser, in his Capitol Hill office after
meeting with Senate Republican leaders about the release of the Cox
Report on Wednesday. The report claims that China has stolen
classified information about every currently deployed nuclear
weapon in the U.S. arsenal. (Paul Hosefros/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
