<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-25 21:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1000 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHINA-SPYING-HNS &LR;      05-25 1524
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-SPYING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON VOWS CHANGES IN WAKE OF CHINESE SPYING 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN C. HENRY 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Faced with a bipartisan congressional report
indicating that China's theft of U.S. nuclear secrets continues
``to this very day,'' President Clinton pledged Tuesday to
implement many of the committee's recommendations for safeguarding
strategic technology.
</P>
<P>
   In an appearance in Edinburg, Texas, Clinton said his
administration already is ``moving aggressively'' to strengthen
security at nuclear laboratories and said he would work with
Congress to safeguard U.S. nuclear secrets. At the same time, the
president said there should be no change in U.S. policy toward
China.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will work very hard with the Congress to protect our
national security, to implement the recommendations, and to
continue our policy of engagement (with China) because both of them
are in our national interests,'' the president said.
</P>
<P>
   In the long-awaited report, the congressional committee headed
by Rep. Christopher Cox, R-Calif., catalogs Chinese espionage since
the late 1970s. Investigators say the nuclear information stolen
probably gives China the ability to develop weapons ``on a par with
our own.''
</P>
<P>
   The committee's top-ranking Democrat, Rep. Norman Dicks of
Washington, called the security breeches that aided the Chinese as
``a major counterintelligence failure ... one of the worst failures
in the nation's history.''
</P>
<P>
   The report, published in three volumes covering more than 700
pages, brought fresh Republican demands for top Clinton
administration officials to resign for their lax security measures
and slowness to respond to the espionage. It also drew sharp
responses from a variety of GOP presidential aspirants, including
Texas Gov. George W. Bush whose father was vice president and then
president for 12 years while the espionage was occurring.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton ``calls China a strategic partner,'' said
Bush. ``China is not America's strategic partner. China is a
competitor, a competitor which does not share our values but now,
unfortunately, shares many of our nuclear secrets.''
</P>
<P>
   Approved unanimously by the five Republican and four Democratic
members of the committee, the report was released after months of
wrangling among the committee, the White House and intelligence
agencies about how much information, much of it classified, could
be published. About 30 percent of the report remains classified.
</P>
<P>
   It outlines a multilayered espionage effort by China that
yielded crucial data on such items as the highly secret W-88
warhead, as well as secrets on the as-yet undeployed neutron bomb.
The report also listed submarine-detection, space-weapon
information and special nuclear codes among the compromised data.
</P>
<P>
   ``The People's Republic of China has stolen classified
information on every currently deployed warhead in the U.S.
ballistic missile arsenal,'' Cox said. ``It is exceptionally likely
that penetration of our U.S. national weapons laboratories
continues to this very day.''
</P>
<P>
   Chinese officials denounced the report as a ploy to demonize the
Beijing government and divert attention from the bombing of China's
Embassy in Belgrade during the NATO air attacks against Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   ``The report is full of groundless allegations,'' said Liu
Xiaoming, chief of China's mission to the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The report details a web of tactics, including using U.S.
businesses to lobby for looser export standards, exploiting
information available publicly, scientific exchange programs, joint
ventures with U.S. corporations, and old-fashioned espionage at the
nation's nuclear research facilities, primarily at Los Alamos in
New Mexico and Lawrence Livermore in California.
</P>
<P>
   The report says U.S. scientists visiting China often would be
praised for their expertise, feted at elaborate banquets, and
peppered with technical questions, often after ``substantial
amounts of alcohol have been consumed.'' At other times, the report
says, scientists would be taken on sightseeing tours while their
hotel rooms were burglarized.
</P>
<P>
   Cox said international scientific cooperation is laudable, but
everyone must play by the same rule. While U.S. agencies must be
willing to take the blame for lax security and shoddy
counter-intelligence efforts, ``we are not willing to forgive
people engaged in espionage,'' Cox said. ``And if we catch them,
they should be executed.''
</P>
<P>
   Security at the labs ``will not meet even minimal standards
until sometime next year,'' said Cox, whose committee made 38
recommendations for safeguarding U.S. nuclear secrets.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to tighter lab security, the committee's
recommendations include:
</P>
<P>
   _ Tighter export controls, especially for the sale of high-power
computers and in helping China's satellite launches.
</P>
<P>
   _ Reports by the president to congressional leaders at least
every six months on actions being taken to respond to espionage by
China.
</P>
<P>
   _ A damage assessment by appropriate agencies of the
implications of the security breaches.
</P>
<P>
   _ Consideration by congressional committees of whether the
Department of Energy should continue to maintain U.S. nuclear
weapons responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   While lauding the Cox committee for its ``good, solid report,''
the Clinton administration and some congressional Democrats,
including members of the Cox panel, dismissed claims about how much
China's nuclear-weapons program was aided by access to U.S.
technology.
</P>
<P>
   Energy Secretary Bill Richardson said 30 of the committee's
recommendations already have been accepted and many of them are
being implemented. He said there is ``no evidence of wholesale loss
of information,'' or that the U.S. is losing its nuclear edge to
China.
</P>
<P>
   ``China is not up to par with the United States on nuclear
development. It is far behind us,'' Richardson said, adding that he
will announce disciplinary action next week against government
workers responsible for lax security at the agency's Los Alamos
facility.
</P>
<P>
   Dicks, the ranking Democrat on the Cox committee, agreed with
Richardson's assessment of China's nuclear capability. ``As of
today, (China) has not deployed a single new nuclear weapon based
on the information they have obtained,'' he said, urging his
congressional colleagues and the media to keep the report in
perspective.
</P>
<P>
   ``The United States still possesses overwhelming nuclear
superiority over China with more than 6,000 strategic nuclear
warheads currently in our inventory, compared to China's total of
about two dozen,'' Dicks said. ``It remains to be seen what use
(China) can make of the information it has acquired.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the committee's report prompted renewed calls for the
resignation or investigation of Attorney General Janet Reno and
National Security Adviser Sandy Berger for failure to respond
quickly to reports of spying.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sandy Berger has failed in his duty to the administration and
the American people and I think he ought to accept his
responsibility,'' said House Majority Leader Richard Armey,
R-Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Armey said Berger first learned that China had stolen missile
warhead technology in April 1996 and was briefed again in July
1997. Berger has testified that he notified Clinton of the security
breach later that month. Two months ago, the president said: ``To
the best of my knowledge, no one has said anything to me about any
espionage, which occurred by the Chinese against the labs, during
my presidency.''
</P>
<P>
   Armey said, ``I just think Sandy Berger should resign.''
</P>
<P>
   White House spokesman Jim Kennedy said the president ``has full
confidence in Sandy Berger, and we would take strong objection to
anything to the contrary.''
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, Sen. Richard Shelby, R-Ala., had urged Reno to resign
because of the FBI and Justice Department handling of the
espionage.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president has full confidence in the attorney general and
she is secure in her position,'' White House press secretary Joe
Lockhart said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Asked Tuesday about Shelby's call for her resignation, Reno
said, ``We just respectfully disagree.'' The attorney general
called the Cox report ``very constructive'' and said it offers
``some very important suggestions about what to do about
espionage.''
</P>
<P>
   House Majority Whip Tom DeLay, a frequent critic of the
president, said for six years the Clinton administration ``turned a
blind eye while Communist China stole our most classified national
security secrets.'' The Texas Republican questioned whether Clinton
and Vice President Al Gore ``deliberately ignored the reality of
Chinese spying and theft because they had ulterior economic and
political motives'' _ a reference to 1996 campaign contributions
from Chinese interests to the Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
   The committee was organized a year ago after then-House Speaker
Newt Gingrich, R-Ga., initiated an investigation into whether
Chinese contributions to the Democrats, which have since been
returned, influenced the administration's decisions regarding
exports of sensitive technology to China. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
