u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEN-NCAA-UGA-CHAMPION     05-25 0415
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-NCAA-UGA-CHAMPIONS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Georgia captures NCAA tennis championship
 &HT;    By Norman Arey
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATHENS, Ga. _ Disproving the old theorem that the whole is equal
to the sum of its parts, top-seeded UCLA's parts were much more
efficient, smoother, stronger, faster and individually better than
those of Georgia, but nobody put a measure on the Bulldogs' heart.
</P>
<P>
   The scrappy Bulldogs, who were underdogs in talent in as many as
five of the six singles in the finals of the men's NCAA Tennis
Championships Tuesday, proved that sometimes a team effort can
overcome a talent deficiency and Georgia stormed back from behind
to take their third national championship, stopping the No. 1
Bruins 4-3.
</P>
<P>
   Spotting the Bulldogs a point by uncharacteristically losing the
doubles point to start the match, the Bruins rocketed out to a
quick start in the singles action, winning straight-sets matches at
No. 2 and No. 5 to take a 2-1 lead. On court No. 2, UCLA freshman
Zack Fleishman stopped Georgia's Talito Corrales 6-3, 6-3, and
Brandon Kramer defeated UGA's Adam Seri 6-2, 7-5 to give the Bruins
a 2-1 lead.
</P>
<P>
   The Bulldogs rally began with Chad Carlson when the sophomore
from Mableton ousted Jason Cook in straight sets, 6-4, 7-6, at No.
3 singles to hand the Bulldogs a 2-2 tie with three singles matches
still to finish.
</P>
<P>
   On the No. 1 court, UCLA's Jean-Noel Grinda, ranked seventh
nationally, needed three sets but disposed of Georgia's
eighth-ranked Hisham Hemeda 6-4, 6-7 (7-4), 6-4, and UCLA led 3-2.
</P>
<P>
   The deciding points were then relegated to the unlikely
territory on No. 4 and No. 6 courts, where Georgia's Joey Pitts had
come back from a first-set loss to tie UCLA's Jong Min-Lee at No. 4
and on No. 6 where Michael Lang dropped the first set to UCLA's
Marcin Rozpedski, but came back to take the second.
</P>
<P>
   Both Georgia players took early services break in the deciding
third sets knowing that the Bulldogs needed both points to take
their third national title.
</P>
<P>
   Lang was the first to finish, breaking Rozpedski's 17-match win
streak, taking a 2-6, 7-6 (7-4), 6-2 and the score was tied at 3
with Pitts and Min-Lee still playing. But not for long. Pitts broke
Min-Lee in the final game and pulled out a 5-7, 6-3, 6-2 win to
give Georgia its third national title.
</P>
<P>
   Norman Arey writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
