<SLUG> BC-MAFIA-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING COLUMN: OVERTONES OF THE UNDERWORLD
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., N.J., Calif.)   (jw) 
 BY STUART ELLIOTT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Madison Avenue is getting mobbed up, as gangster and
Mafia imagery and language become increasingly common in
advertising.
</P>
<P>
   A growing number of campaigns are centered on godfathers,
goodfellas and wiseguys, toughs who talk in patois heavily accented
in the dese-dem-dose tones of the Northeast and dress in sleeveless
undershirts and pinstriped suits. The cornucopia of Corleone
wannabes appears in commercials and print ads and on World Wide Web
sites pitching a variety of products and services in addition to
promoting films and television series with organized-crime themes.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're borrowing a recognizability,'' said Dawn Hudson, senior
vice president for strategy and marketing at the Pepsi-Cola Co &UR; . &LR; 
unit of Pepsico Inc. in Purchase, N.Y. ``People get it because they
bring a history to it.''
</P>
<P>
   For the company's flagship soda, a commercial by the BBDO New
York unit of Omnicom Group features the voice of Marlon Brando
emanating from a girl angered that the owner of a pizzeria served
her Coca-Cola instead of Pepsi-Cola.
</P>
<P>
   ``You insulted me and my entire family by offering me this,''
the Brando voice complains as music evocative of gangster movies
plays in the background.
</P>
<P>
   The campaigns are indicative of a widespread belief among agency
executives that stereotyped characters and situations are useful
devices because familiarity breeds contentment among consumers.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are visual symbols that have become part of the cultural
vernacular,'' said Dean Stefanides, partner and creative director
at Hampel/Stefanides in New York, ``so all you have to do is see
the image and you get what we're trying to communicate.''
</P>
<P>
   For Monzu, a restaurant in the SoHo neighborhood of Manhattan
that serves Italian-French cuisine, Hampel/Stefanides created a
print ad showing a dead mobster sprawled on the floor of a barber
shop, a baguette clutched in his hand. The caption reads
``Sicilian, with a French twist.''
</P>
<P>
   As that example attests, crime-themed campaigns are almost
always meant to be humorous.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Mafia is getting into advertising because the carting
industry is downsizing,'' said Michael Dweck, chairman and creative
director at Dweck Inc. in New York.
</P>
<P>
   For Top Driver, a driving school, Dweck created a series of
spots intended to mock the instructors employed by competitors. In
one commercial, a thug-like instructor clad all in black asks his
young student for help in disposing of a bulky wrapped object _
resembling a body bag _ in the trunk of the car being used for the
driving lessons.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really 'preciate this,'' the instructor says as he and the
student toss the object into an oversized trash receptacle. ``I
consider you a friend, you hear?''
</P>
<P>
   That use of ``friend,'' mimicking the term uttered by mob
members identifying each other in films like ``Donnie Brasco,'' is
typical in campaigns like these. There are innumerable invocations
of such gangster catch phrases from movies, TV shows and books as
``sleep with the fishes'' and ``it's only business.''
</P>
<P>
   For instance, newspaper ads for ``Analyze This,'' the comic film
about a mobster undergoing therapy, used this headline to promote
sneak previews: ``Consider this an offer you can't refuse.''
</P>
<P>
   ```The Godfather' proved there's interest in the subject
matter,'' said Brad Ball, president for domestic theatrical
marketing at Warner Brothers in Burbank, Calif., the unit of Time
Warner Inc. that distributed ``Analyze This.''
</P>
<P>
   Even so, he added, the studio sought to avoid being ``cliche
driven'' in the campaign because ``as with any good marketing
effort, we wanted to show what's different about this picture, so
people see it as fresh instead of corny.'' As a result, subsequent
ads played down the mob lingo and carried headlines like ``What's
everybody laughing at?''
</P>
<P>
   The developers of an interactive campaign tied to ``The
Sopranos'' _ the series about a New Jersey mobster and his
families, presented by the HBO cable TV unit of Time Warner _ also
sought to serve up their gangsters in an original way.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to make sure the show was seen in its own right and
not as an echo of something else,'' said Kevin Dowdell, vice
president for interactive ventures at HBO in New York, who worked
on a series Web site (www.hbo.com/sopranos) with Diane Jakacki,
executive producer at HBO.com.
</P>
<P>
   A contest offering prizes like ``Sopranos'' posters, hats and
T-shirts (``If anybody asks, they fell off a truck'') ends on June
9, when HBO starts reruns of the series.
</P>
<P>
   Are there any deterrents to the trend that can stop it the way
the Untouchables stopped Chicago bootleggers? One potential problem
is negative reaction from consumers who perceive gangland sendups
as slurs on Italian-Americans.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Bruno Brugnatelli, president at Brugnatelli &AMP;
Partners Advertising in Elmsford, N.Y., sent a reporter a copy of a
letter to Pepsico complaining that the Brando Pepsi-Cola commercial
amounted to ``character assassination that is used to promote
commercial products.''
</P>
<P>
   Another possible difficulty is the association of gangsters,
even comic stereotyped gangsters, with violence. That could hurt if
protests against violent content in entertainment mount in the wake
of school shootings. Already, CBS has shelved a drama series for
the 1999-2000 season, ``Falcone,'' that was to be a TV version of
``Donnie Brasco.''
</P>
<P>
   If those problems don't derail the mob bang wagon, what could be
next? Peter Drakoulias, partner and business development director
at Deutsch Inc. in New York, has long promoted the idea of a cable
TV network devoted to gangster- and crime-related programming,
which could of course also feature compatible commercials.
</P>
<P>
   Drakoulias has even named the network: the Wiseguy Channel.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
