<HEADLINE>
ALASKA AIR, MECHANICS AGREE ON NEW BARGAINING PROCESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PAUL NYHAN  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Alaska Airlines Inc. has created a bargaining process
with its mechanics that both sides say could help the airline avoid
the lengthy disputes that forced it to cancel hundreds of flights
in the past few months.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday night, Alaska Airlines struck a tentative deal with more
than 1,000 mechanics and technicians that would create a binding
arbitration process for future negotiations. During the next round
of talks, if the two sides can't settle their differences after 120
days they will be forced to submit to arbitration by an impartial
party on a set of issues, such as pay rates .
</P>
<P>
   The idea, known as interest arbitration, holds the promise of
shortening labor negotiations that can drag on for several years.
So far this year, Alaska Airlines has struggled to negotiate four
contracts and the disputes have disrupted services. In fact, Alaska
Airlines claimed that many of the more than 600 flights it has
canceled since April 26 were the result of a alleged slowdown by
mechanics.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at the International Association of Machinists and
Aerospace Workers, who are locked in separate and contentious talks
with Alaska Airline on behalf of baggage, freight handlers and
stock clerks, have already expressed interest in the idea.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they offered (the proposal) it would help on the next go
around of negotiations,'' said Stephen Stanczyk,
secretary-treasurer of the International Association of Machinists
and Aerospace Workers' Local 2202. The talks would be ``over and
done by a specific date.''
</P>
<P>
   Stanczyk, however, said the approach will not jumpstart the
effort to renegotiate its current contract. The talks have stalled,
in part, because of disagreements over wage increases and other
benefits changes, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Some union officials may also be wary of the new approach,
because they could lose one of their most powerful tools, the
ability to strike, according to Glenn Engel, an airline analyst for
Goldman Sachs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think management seems much more willing to move to this
model than labor,'' Engel said. ``Labor feels they get more by
using the strike threat.''
</P>
<P>
   Overall, U.S. investors welcomed the news that Alaska Airlines,
the 10th-largest U.S. carrier, had settled its longest running
labor dispute. The stock of Alaska Air Group Inc., which owns
Alaska Airlines, surged to 39 11/16, up 1 9/16, during a day when
the Dow Jones Industrial Average fell 123.58.
</P>
<P>
   ``The mechanics have been slowing the airline down. It is
probably the reason why the stock has underperformed,'' Engel said.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the Aircraft Mechanics Fraternal Association must
still ratify their contract, and a vote is expected in the next
three weeks. The union's local airline representative, Louie Key,
however, has already said he will recommend that members endorse
the $30 million package, which contains an across-the-board wage
increase, and other benefits increases.
</P>
<P>
   While Alaska's negotiations with its ramp service and stock
clerks have run aground, the company is making progress on the
other two contracts with its flight attendants and clerical
workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The mood at our table is really quite good,'' said Thomas
Lent, a representative at the National Association of Flight
Attendants. Lent added that he is confident the two sides could
strike a tentative deal by July 30.
</P>
<P>
   Alaska Airlines president and chief executive officer John Kelly
has also said the company will likely settle its contract with
representatives of the clerical workers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
