<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-CHINA-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH CRITICAL OF CLINTON ADMINISTRATION'S RESPONSE TO CHINESE
SPYING 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By R.G. RATCLIFFE 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Gov. George W. Bush switched gears from governor
to presidential candidate Tuesday, sharply criticizing the Clinton
administration for what he called a slow, insufficient response to
reports of Chinese theft of U.S. nuclear secrets.
</P>
<P>
   ``The balance of power is going to shift as a result of this,
and it is going to accelerate China's emergence as a nuclear
power,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's quick reaction to a congressional report outlining
Chinese spying was a marked contrast to the slow and public
deliberations he undertook in taking a stand on NATO's intervention
in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The attack on Clinton also occurred as Clinton and Vice
President Al Gore were in South Texas promoting Gore's bid for the
Democratic presidential nomination. Clinton had made attacks on a
China policy a major element of his 1992 defeat of Bush's father,
former President George Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Bush, so far the front-runner for the 2000 Republican
presidential nomination, acknowledged the report's note that
Chinese spying has been going on since the late 1970s, including
the 12 years his father was vice president and president.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's unfortunate that China has been stealing secrets during
Carter, Reagan, Bush and Clinton (administrations). But there has
only been one administration that has been given the news, only one
administration knew. And that is the Clinton administration,'' Bush
said.
</P>
<P>
   The governor noted the evidence that Clinton's national security
staff has known about Chinese spying for several years without
acting on the information.
</P>
<P>
   ``Should I run and should be the president, I can assure you
that (if) my national security adviser knew that secrets were being
stolen, I would want to know about it, and I would do something
about it immediately,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   One of Bush's GOP opponents, Elizabeth Dole, echoed Bush's
criticism of inaction by the Clinton administration. But Dole also
said ``previous administrations must share in the blame.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush said the United States needs to ``reassess our relationship
with China'' and that future presidents must be ``firm and
consistent'' in dealing with the Chinese.
</P>
<P>
   But Bush, whose father also was U.S. ambassador to China and CIA
director, continued to support the admission of the People's
Republican of China into the World Trade Organization and opening
China up to U.S. producers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The two are not inconsistent. We can have trade with China, so
long as we have firm export controls to make sure we're not trading
technology that will become part of a Chinese nuclear arsenal,''
Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   Another of Bush's GOP rivals, Steve Forbes, demanded an
immediate halt to efforts to get China into the World Trade
Organization. Forbes said the lost secrets show a need to
immediately renew research of missile defense systems.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Clinton-Gore administrations's national security policy of
hear no evil, see no evil and speak no evil has deeply wounded the
U.S.'s ability to defend itself,'' Forbes said.
</P>
<P>
   Republican presidential hopefuls Gary Bauer and Lamar Alexander
also criticized the current administration.
</P>
<P>
   But Democratic presidential candidate Bill Bradley, who hopes to
wrest the party nomination from Vice President Al Gore, chose not
to join in the criticism of the administration during a
fund-raising visit Tuesday to Houston.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no reason to turn China into an enemy,'' said the
former U.S. senator from New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley had not yet read the congressional report, but said
safeguards to protect nuclear secrets should be improved and that
those involved should be punished swiftly.
</P>
<P>
   In criticizing the administration, Bush self-consciously
admitted that he was breaking his self-imposed vow to concentrate
on Texas until the Legislature ends next Monday.
</P>
<P>
   But he said a congressional report on Chinese espionage was so
significant that as a potential presidential candidate ``I thought
it was important to make a clear statement of my view.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush has been trying to rapidly establish his foreign policy
credentials, meeting several times with policy advisers.
</P>
<P>
   But the difficulty of a governor campaigning on foreign policy
issues was illustrated in 1992 when Bush's father likened Clinton's
foreign policy experience to that of the Bush family dog.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clinton-Gore, they've got about as much foreign policy
experience as Millie,'' President Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton attacked Bush's open trade policies, saying the
president was not doing enough to force the Chinese government to
protect human rights.
</P>
<P>
   But since Clinton has been in office, there have been questions
of possible trade security lapses that have allowed U.S. technology
to leak to China as a result of financial contributions to
Clinton's re-election campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the nuclear secrets leaks are believed to have occurred
at U.S. research laboratories.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Chronicle reporter Edward Hegstrom in Houston contributed to this
story.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
