<HEADER>
A1026 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-USCHINA-BUSH-COX     05-25 0815
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-USCHINA-BUSH-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bush blames Clinton administration for leaks to ChineseBy Ken
Herman
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Sounding more like a presidential candidate than
ever, Gov. George W. Bush on Tuesday moved quickly to stake out a
position on the congressional report on Chinese espionage.
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks, on other issues, Bush has taken some heat for
being cautiously evasive on presidential campaign issues. On
Tuesday, armed with a prepared statement, Bush jumped in shortly
after U.S. Rep. Christopher Cox issued a 700-page report detailing
Chinese theft of U.S. nuclear weapon technology.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, who plans to formally announce his candidacy later this
summer, placed the blame squarely on ``the current
administration,'' a phrase targeted to include Vice President Al
Gore, his potential 2000 opponent.
</P>
<P>
   Bush also allowed room for some blame of previous
administrations, including his father's. But, without mentioning
President Clinton by name during his statement, the candidate-to-be
came down hardest on the current White House resident.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today's report also shines a glaring light on the current
administration's failed policies toward China,'' said Bush.
``Presented with detailed information about China's espionage, the
administration apparently did not take it seriously, did not react
promptly and is still trying to minimize the scope and extent of
the damage done.''
</P>
<P>
   His quick and decisive comments stood in sharp contrast to the
way he handled his position on another recent foreign policy
question: U.S. troops in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   In March, after Clinton committed troops to the United
Nations-led effort in the Balkans, Bush took heavy criticism for
not weighing in on the decision right away and for being vague in
his comments when he did finally take a stand.
</P>
<P>
   The governor said Tuesday he chose to speak out on the Cox
report because ``I thought it was important to make a clear
statement of my views.'' Bush made his comments after a ceremony in
which he signed into a law a bill prohibiting juveniles who commit
crimes with guns from being released until they appear before a
judge.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of waiting for questions from reporters, Bush took a
proactive stance, announcing at the outset of the ceremony that he
wanted to remark afterward on a Washington issue of importance to
the country.
</P>
<P>
   Bush spokeswoman Karen Hughes said later that the governor was
more circumspect about Kosovo because the United States had troops
at risk. She also said Bush has been following the Chinese spying
situation closely and felt obligated to speak out.
``Increasingly,'' she said, ``he will be speaking out more on
issues that have implications for America.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush noted that the report ``makes it clear that for the past 20
years, including the last few years, China has systematically
stolen American nuclear secrets and is after other military
technologies as well.'' The result, according to Bush, has been
thefts that ``have dramatically accelerated China's emergence as a
major nuclear power.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The implications are huge for the balance of power in Asia and
for the balance of power in the world,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if blame must be shared by other presidents during that
20-year period, Bush said, ``It's unfortunate that China has been
stealing secrets during Carter, Reagan, Bush and Clinton.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There was only but one administration that has been given the
news,'' he said. ``Only one administration knew, and that's the
Clinton administration. . . I readily concede previous
administrations did not know what was going on. And that is a
problem with U.S. security. Step one is to make sure our security
is tightened at all facilities at which there are sensitive
technologies.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush said if he runs and wins ``I can assure you that if my
national security adviser knew that secrets were being stolen that
I would want to know about it and I would do something about it
immediately.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the decades of espionage, Bush does not favor economic
punishment of China to through trade embargoes. He remains a
free-trade proponent who believes commerce can change nations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it is also important for us to realize that the
development of an entrepreneurial class in China will enhance
freedom in that part of the world,'' said Bush, who believes China
should be admitted to the World Trade Organization.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said the Clinton administration has it all wrong when it
refers to China as a ``strategic partner.''
</P>
<P>
   ``China is not America's strategic partner,'' said Bush. ``China
is a competitor, a competitor which does not share our values but
now, unfortunately, shares many of our nuclear secrets.''
</P>
<P>
   Ken Herman writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
