<HEADLINE>
MOTHER, THREE SONS KILLED BY TRAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CINDY RODRIGUEZ AND RICHARD WEIZEL  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FAIRFIELD, Conn _ In total darkness, an Ecuadorian immigrant
followed the railroad tracks, her four young sons by her side.
Carrying children's books, a Bible, and toys stuffed in knapsacks,
the family trudged toward the local commuter station early Tuesday
morning.
</P>
<P>
   But looming behind them was an Amtrak train, one that moved
stealthily under electric power. The family could not hear the
muffled rumblings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Her last act was an attempt to save her child, that much we
know,'' Metropolitan Transit Authority Police Chief James O'Donnell
said later.
</P>
<P>
   By the time the conductor spotted the human shadows, it was too
late.
</P>
<P>
   The horn blared as the mother rushed to scoop up her children.
She grabbed three, but the fourth darted to the other side of the
tracks. In the seconds before the train sped through, the boy raced
across, to get to his family's side, said O'Donnell. The mother
reached out to pull him. But they ran out of time.
</P>
<P>
   The train slammed into them at more than 70 miles per hour,
police said.
</P>
<P>
   The mother and three of the sons died instantly. One of the
boys, 6-year-old Angel Gabriel Urgiles Toledo, is on life support
at nearby Bridgeport Hospital, suffering from major head trauma.
</P>
<P>
   Police said the mother was in her mid-40s, had immigrated from
Ecuador and had been living in East Bridgeport for about two years.
She was a resident alien, meaning she had a ``green card'' which
permitted her to work in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The children were enrolled in Luis Munoz Marin Elementary School
in a predominantly Latino neighborhood. Her husband was back in
Ecuador; police had not reached him by Tuesday evening.
</P>
<P>
   Many neighbors, along with police, could only speculate as to
why the mother was walking alone with her children on the railroad
tracks at night. Some people speculated that the woman must have
been running away from some form of threat or abuse, but police and
other officials said they didn't know if that was the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no evidence that has been uncovered yet,'' said
Fairfield First Selectman Ken Flatto. ``But there may have been a
housing problem.'' Flatto stopped short of saying the family was
homeless.
</P>
<P>
   The accident happened at 2:20 a.m., a few hundred yards from the
Fairfield commuter rail station, the place the family seemed to be
heading, authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   The station is near the middle of downtown Fairfield, a
picturesque and affluent waterfront suburb of 53,000, just an hour
from New York City. The town borders Bridgeport, the state's
largest, and one of its poorest, cities.
</P>
<P>
   Kenneth J. Gambardella, rail safety coordinator for the
Connecticut Department of Transportation, said the accident scene
was ``the most horrific, horrifying I have witnessed in the 15
years I have been on the job.''
</P>
<P>
   Gambardella agreed with O'Donnell that there was no way the
engineer could have stopped the train in time to avoid the
accident.
</P>
<P>
   ``At 75 miles per hour, which is the speed limit for that track,
it would take a mile or more to stop,'' said Gambardella.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday afternoon, yellow police tape trailed along
finely-manicured shrubs surrounding the outer perimeter of the
tracks. The train, carrying 210 passengers, remained near the
station for at least two hours. The front of the train was covered
in blood.
</P>
<P>
   When paramedics found Angel unconscious, they took him to
Bridgeport Hospital. The train had severed his left leg, up to the
knee, and inflicted a wound to his skull.
</P>
<P>
   Surgeons opened a three-inch hole in the front right side of his
skull to relieve brain swelling, said Dr. Nabil Atweh, who operated
on Angel for more than three hours as neurosurgeons worked on his
leg.
</P>
<P>
   Atweh said that while Angel remained in life-threatening
condition, he was doing somewhat better than expected. His blood
pressure had improved and he responds to pain stimulus, but the
brain pressure remains very high.
</P>
<P>
   An uncle and two aunts watch over the boy, on monitoring devices
in a pediatric intensive care unit, as medical staff stand by to
keep him alive.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
