</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-GUN-SUIT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOSTON HIRES LAWYERS TO PREPARE SUIT AGAINST GUN MAKERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEPHANIE EBBERT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Riding the nation's wave of antigun sentiment, the
city of Boston intends to hire three heavy-hitting law firms to
file a $100 million lawsuit against gun manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
   Boston could file as early as this week, becoming the 19th
municipality in the country to sue gun manufacturers and
distributors, after six California cities and two counties joined
the mounting battle Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Straddling the legal theories put forth in claims first filed in
Chicago and New Orleans, Boston will argue that the gun industry
has been negligent in the marketing and distribution of unsafe
products. It also argues that the loose distribution _ particularly
trafficking from states where guns are more readily accessible _
creates a public nuisance, costing the city not only in police,
hospital, and emergency services, but also in dwindling quality of
life and property values in crime-ridden neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   Proponents of such litigation hope the rising pressure on the
industry and the costs of legal defense will force gunmakers to
bend to broader safety measures and a clampdown on slipshod
distribution.
</P>
<P>
   At a moment of widening schisms within the industry, the school
shooting in Littleton, Colo., and Congress' grappling with the
slippery issue of gun control, officials in Boston think their case
is particularly ripe.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems that this is a good time in the country in that there
really has been a shift in both public opinion and the perspective
of policymakers that something is seriously wrong with the
availabilty of guns, and we need to try some new approaches,'' said
John Auerbach, director of the Boston Public Health Commission,
which is spearheading the legal challenge.
</P>
<P>
   Industry representatives, however, maintain the suits are
politically motivated measures that don't recognize the compromises
already made by manufacturers _ including voluntary safety locks,
background checks at gun shows, and a permanent ban on gun
ownership for juveniles with violent records.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our response is, get in line,'' said Jack Adkins, director of
operations for the American Sports Shooting Council, an industry
trade group. ``What's new? It's old news now.''
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Thomas M. Menino, he said, ``is not going to get any more
out of this industry than the first mayor that filed the lawsuit as
far as financial gain.''
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, manufacturers argue that cities like Boston have
demonstrated success in reducing crime without antigun measures,
rendering their arguments useless.
</P>
<P>
   Boston's homicide rate has plummeted to 35 last year from 152 in
1990, and 12 in the first five months of 1999. The homicide rate
since 1997 has been lower than any time since 1961.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got these states that already have severe restrictions
on firearms ownership,'' Adkins said. ``Crime doesn't really seem
to be an issue anymore . . . but it's the feeding frenzy as a
result of the tobacco legislation which has now opened the door up
to the next politically correct industry, which happens to be
firearms.''
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, Los Angeles and San Francisco announced they would sue
the gun industry, in conjunction with four other California cities
and two counties. Gun litigation also has been lodged by New
Orleans; Chicago; Miami-Dade County, Fla.; Bridgeport, Conn.;
Cleveland; Atlanta; Cincinnati; Detroit and Wayne County, Mich.;
and St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   After Menino threatened the gun industry with the suit last
fall, the city tread water for a time, due to corporation counsel
Merita Hopkins' concern that the massive undertaking would drain
city resources and staff time, sources said.
</P>
<P>
   City attorneys then embarked on a long search for cocounsel
willing to take on the costly project. Brown Rudnick Freed &AMP;
Geesmer, which led the state's suit against tobacco companies, have
agreed to take on the case, after retreating from talks for a time.
</P>
<P>
   Partner Tom Sobol said the legal team includes Sullivan,
Weinstein &AMP; McQuay of Boston; Lieff, Cabraser, Heimann &AMP; Bernstein
of San Francisco and New York, a leader in diet-pill and
breast-implant suits and partner in the national tobacco
settlement; and Cohen, Milstein, Hausfeld &AMP; Toll of Washington. The
Legal Action Project of the Center to Prevent Handgun Violence
Center is also cooperating with the city.
</P>
<P>
   The firms would receive a percentage of proceeds from any
settlement, which would pale in comparison to the sums available
through deep-pocketed tobacco companies. Sobol said the partnership
can absorb the expense of filing the suit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that when a laudable public health goal is the reward
of the litigation, one's got to be willing to accept and take the
risks,'' said Sobol.
</P>
<P>
   The city's deliberative effort has included an exhaustive probe
of every shooting injury reported in the city over six years. The
suit will target 25 manufacturers and distributors, including Smith
&AMP; Wesson, Glock, Colt, Bryco, Sundance, Kel-Tec, Mossberg, Taurus,
and Interarms.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't intend to lose. We're entering this to win,'' said
Peter Welsh, the mayor's director of policy and planning. ``By
waiting and hopefully signing a deal with some of the top law firms
in the country, we're increasing our chances dramatically.''
</P>
</TEXT>
