<SLUG> BC-TIPPER-GORE-VISIT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mrs. Gore speaks of husband's accomplishments in Bush's
backyardBy Ken Herman
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ In a preseason preview of what could be the 2000
presidential showdown, Gov. George W. Bush's top political aide and
Vice President Al Gore's wife are offering wildly different views
on what the last eight years could mean to the election.
</P>
<P>
   Karl Rove, Bush's longtime strategist, says Gore could pay for
the sins of his president.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are at the end of eight years of a party dominating the
White House. ... We are at the end of a presidency where people
really want to see it in the rear-view mirror,'' Rove said in a
recent interview. ``Whether they want to admit it or not, they want
it in the rear-view mirror. There is a desire for change.''
</P>
<P>
   Not so, said Tipper Gore, who raised money Tuesday for the Gore
campaign while her husband toured South Texas to tout
administration programs that have promoted economic growth in the
poverty-ridden Rio Grande Valley.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm looking forward, and I know that my husband is,'' Mrs.
Gore told the Austin American-Statesman. ``He's talking about a
bold vision for the future of the country and how we need to
prepare to move into the 21st century.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think if we take a look at what's been accomplished by the
administration in these eight years we are very proud of the
economic prosperity people are enjoying.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Gore's comments came between Austin fund-raising events and
after she toured Lifeworks, a South Austin-based program that
offers youth and family services. She also attended a midday
fund-raiser at a downtown hotel and spoke at a dinner at the home
of Austin attorney Bill Whitehurst. The evening event raised about
$60,000. Overall, the Gore campaign hoped to raise about $900,000
during five Texas events Tuesday and today.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Gore made no mention of Bush during her two speeches here.
But Bush was targeted by people who introduced her. Jane Hickie, a
former aide to Bush's predecessor, Gov. Ann Richards, told Mrs.
Gore to report that there are Austinites ``who are going to be very
happy that we are going to have our candidate for president who is
qualified to become the commander-in-chief on day one, and who has
travelled places other than to Mexico and to Israel to apologize
for the suggestion that only some people get to go to heaven.''
</P>
<P>
   Her comment referred to Bush's recounting of a discussion he,
his mother and The Rev. Billy Graham once had about whether heaven
is open to people who do not accept Jesus Christ. Bush has said he
makes no judgments on the topic. The Anti-Defamation League has
said Bush's comments were not offensive to Jews.
</P>
<P>
   In South Texas, Gore presided over a White House conference
reviewing ``empowerment zones'' launched as part of a 1993 economic
recovery that was opposed by congressional Republicans. The program
provides grants, tax incentives and bonding authority to
economically distressed areas. Clinton was on hand to introduce
Gore.
</P>
<P>
   As Gore campaigned in South Texas, his only apparent competition
for the Democratic nomination, former New Jersey Sen. Bill Bradley,
visited El Paso and Houston. He campaigned with former Texas state
Comptroller John Sharp, who once worked on Gore's ``reinventing
government'' program to cut bureaucracy, will be his Texas campaign
chairman.Ken Herman writes for the Austin American-Statesman,
Austin, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
