<HEADER>
A1036 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MORGANSTANLEY-INQUIRY     05-25 1013
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MORGANSTANLEY-INQUIRY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MYSTERY GROWS OVER PAYMENT BY MORGAN STANLEY 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JOSEPH KAHN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Many people on Wall Street are scratching their heads
as to why Morgan Stanley Dean Witter, America's largest securities
firm, would pay $10,000 to a middleman who helped secure the arrest
of a former employee. Now, it turns out, even the middleman had
doubts.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Joseph Luethke, the middleman, early this year asked
Morgan Stanley for instructions on how to return $10,000 paid to
him by the firm within days of the employee's arrest, a
confidential document shows. Luethke says that he decided in the
weeks after last August's sting operation against the former
employee that he wanted to sever his financial ties to Morgan
Stanley and distance himself from the cash payment.
</P>
<P>
   That claim is supported in a letter sent by certified mail to
Luethke by John Cooney Jr., a Morgan Stanley lawyer at Davis, Polk,
Wardwell, a Manhattan law firm. The letter, dated Jan. 11, 1999,
stated that Luethke has ``mentioned his interest in repaying the
$10,000 which was given to you by Morgan Stanley.'' It includes the
number of a Morgan Stanley account at Citibank. The letter was made
available to The New York Times.
</P>
<P>
   The letter appears to be part of a dialogue between Morgan
Stanley and Luethke, 29, whose murky role in the complex affair is
at the center of an investigation by the Manhattan district
attorney. That investigation had been focused on Christian Curry,
the former employee. But last week, the district attorney's office
said it was dropping all charges against Curry and instead was
making both Morgan Stanley and Luethke subjects of the
investigation. So far, no criminal charges have been brought.
</P>
<P>
   The relationship between Luethke and Morgan Stanley is full of
innuendo, accusations and denials, but it is the linchpin in a huge
discrimination suit filed last week against the firm by Curry. The
lawsuit contends that high-level employees at Morgan Stanley,
including the chairman and chief executive, Philip Purcell, worked
closely with Luethke to plan a sting operation against Curry. Curry
had been fired shortly before and was contemplating a racial
discrimination suit against the firm.
</P>
<P>
   The letter to Luethke is the first tangible evidence that Morgan
Stanley paid $10,000 to Luethke, who acknowledges a role in
brokering the sting operation. It also supports Luethke's
contention that he has held an ongoing dialogue with Morgan Stanley
lawyers that continued many months after that $10,000 payment was
made. He maintains that to this day lawyers working for Morgan
Stanley are seeking to pressure or cajole him to keep silent in the
matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are very eager to work out some kind of arrangement with
me,'' Luethke said Tuesday. ``They have also told me that if I
don't stay silent, they will crush me like a bug. On numerous
occasions they said that: `Crush me like a bug.'''
</P>
<P>
   Morgan Stanley, which says it is cooperating with law
enforcement officials, has repeatedly declined to explain the
$10,000 payment publicly. On Tuesday, Martin London, a lawyer for
Davis Polk &AMP; Wardwell who also represents Morgan Stanley,
reiterated that stance. But he added that Luethke was not to be
trusted, and that Luethke's accounts of communications with Morgan
Stanley ``should not be accepted as accurate.''
</P>
<P>
   Morgan Stanley's contention is echoed by other parties involved
in the case, including lawyers involved in the district attorney's
investigation and Curry, a college acquaintance of Luethke. All say
that Luethke has misled them on more than one occasion.
</P>
<P>
   Even the authorities have had some trouble detecting fact from
fiction. Last September, the district attorney arrested Luethke and
charged him with two crimes. One was a misdemeanor charge of
harassing Curry's girlfriend, Marissa Wheeler. Another was a felony
count of possessing a false identification card that showed him
holding the rank of lieutenant colonel in the U.S. Army.
</P>
<P>
   Both charges are still outstanding. On Tuesday, Ms. Wheeler,
Curry's girlfriend, was interviewed by officials in the district
attorney's office who were seeking to get to the bottom of
harassment charges against Luethke.
</P>
<P>
   Even pinning down Luethke's school record proves difficult. He
says he was a full-time student at Columbia. But records at the
school show he was enrolled as a part-time student in general
studies for one semester in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Luethke insists he has told the truth all along and says he is
innocent of all charges.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever his credibility, the prevailing mystery in the story is
why Morgan Stanley nursed a relationship of any kind with Luethke,
who has never been an employee of the firm and has no financial
training. Lawyers involved in the investigation say they suspect
that Morgan Stanley was so desperate to avoid being hit with a
racial discrimination suit by Curry, who comes from a
well-connected black family in New York, that it agreed to work
with Luethke to discredit Curry.
</P>
<P>
   Morgan Stanley has said that Curry was fired for abusing his
expense account. But his dismissal came several days after photos
of him appeared in a gay pornographic magazine. Curry insists that
he is not a homosexual, and that the photos were taken two years
earlier and showed up in the magazine without his consent. He says
that his dismissal is evidence of discrimination on the basis of
perceived sexual orientation. He has also alleged racial
discrimination at Morgan Stanley.
</P>
<P>
   Understanding the nature and chronology of Luethke's
relationship with Morgan Stanley is difficult, in part because
Luethke himself often speaks abstractly, even referring to
``Luethke'' and the ``confidential informant'' in the third person.
The district attorney's office has had no direct contact with
Luethke in months and considers him unreliable, lawyers involved in
the matter said. But the lawyers said that to their knowledge, the
district attorney's office never saw the Jan. 11 letter to Luethke.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
