<HEADER>
A1038 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVAR-REFUGEE-1STWR     05-25 0777
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVAR-REFUGEE-1STWRITETHRU-C </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Kosovar family exchanges war for North Georgia tranquillity
 &HT;    (EDS: CORRECTED VERSION.)
 &HT;    By Christy Oglesby and Rebecca McCarthy
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Just a few weeks ago, the Hoxha family fled the terror
of war, murder and ethnic expulsion in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Today they will awaken to the tranquillity of a Christian refuge
in North Georgia. Tomorrow, the schedule calls for English lessons
and grocery shopping.
</P>
<P>
   The humanitarian crisis in Yugoslavia reached Georgia in a
tangible way Tuesday afternoon. Hundreds of thousands of ethnic
Albanians have fled the province of Kosovo. The Hoxhas _ two
parents and three children _ arrived at Hartsfield International
Airport, becoming the first refugees from the Balkans conflict to
reach this area.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds more are expected to arrive in the coming months.
</P>
<P>
   The Hoxhas stepped off the 737 from Newark into Atlanta _ and a
frenzy of media attention. They seemed at ease answering reporters'
questions. The exception was 20-year-old Arben, who nervously
tapped his heel on the floor.
</P>
<P>
   The trip _ from Kosovo to Macedonia to New Jersey to Georgia _
was ``long and very, very difficult,'' said Ilir Hoxha, the father.
``We would like to thank the American people.''
</P>
<P>
   Georgia, in turn, has opened its arms.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're getting more offers of help than we can use,'' said Don
Mosley of Jubilee Partners, a Christian community in Comer, Ga.
where the refugees will live for the next two months. ``We really
don't have any place to store any more help.''
</P>
<P>
   The family lived in Pristina, the capital of Kosovo, where Ilir
Hoxha was a musical producer for a television station before being
booted out of his job.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a very hard life there,'' he said through an Albanian
translator. ``They forced us to leave our house. Every moment we
waited, our lives were in danger.''
</P>
<P>
   The family includes two daughters _ Teuta, who is 15, and
Arbreshe, 17.
</P>
<P>
   After collecting their luggage _ new clothes given them at Fort
Dix, N.J., because they fled with only what they were wearing _ the
Hoxhas climbed into a van and were driven to Jubilee.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a healing place,'' said Jennifer Drago, Jubilee's refugee
program coordinator. She was waiting at the airport with a sign
that read ``welcome'' in Albanian.
</P>
<P>
   The people of Jubilee had been preparing for this day. A
traditional home-cooked Kosovar meal of meats and dough was waiting
for the refugees, and staff at Jubilee had stocked their house with
familiar kinds of food.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a 50-pound bag of flour waiting for them,'' Drago
said. ``They do lots of bread. And there's yeast, fruit and
chicken. And vegeta _ it's like bouillon cubes. They use that to
season meats.''
</P>
<P>
   When the red van carrying the Hoxhas topped the hill near the
Jubilee driveway, Mosley began waving and smiling.
</P>
<P>
   Staff members and their families waved and held aloft a large
sign saying ``Mire es na vini,'' the Albanian equivalent of
``welcome.'' The Hoxhas and their children shook hands with most of
the 25 or so people who live year-round at Jubilee.
</P>
<P>
   Ilir Hoxha, in an atmosphere less pressured than at the airport,
told of being pushed out of his home by Serbian paramilitary
members in March. The three-mile route that his family was forced
to walk to the train station was lined with masked, armed soldiers,
but Hoxha didn't look at them. The family kept their eyes focused
on the ground the entire way.
</P>
<P>
   When they boarded the train, Hoxha said, they didn't know where
they were going or what would happen to them _ they only knew they
would be killed if they stayed. They were dumped off the train just
inside the Macedonian border, where they slept on the ground, in
the rain, for seven days, with no shelter or provisions, before
moving into a refugee camp.
</P>
<P>
   Their harrowing exit from Kosovo capped 10 years of oppression
and mistreatment by Serbians, Hoxha said.
</P>
<P>
   Fired from her clerical job with a branch of the Kosovar
government, his wife, Hyshije, didn't work for five years, until
she landed a job in the University of Pristina.
</P>
<P>
   By 7:30 Tuesday night, the Hoxhas were showing their fatigue,
having been traveling most of the day. The meaty aroma of the
Albanian dinner prepared by the translator's wife wafted into the
parking lot.
</P>
<P>
   The family looked at the clear blue sky, the rustling trees and
the smiling faces of their hosts, then headed off to supper.
</P>
<P>
   Christy Oglesby and Rebecca McCarthy write for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
