<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-LOUIMA-DEFENSE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IMPACT OF SUDDEN GUILTY PLEA UNCLEAR FOR OTHER DEFENDANTS
</HEADLINE>
   (jw) 
 By JOSEPH P. FRIED   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Until now, the spotlight in the Abner Louima trial
has largely been on the actions of Officer Justin Volpe. But with
Volpe's guilty plea Tuesday, the focus of the explosive case shifts
immediately to the three other officers and a sergeant still on
trial.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the evidence presented against them ranges from
relatively substantial to seemingly flimsy. And people close to the
case say the prosecution has largely presented the heart of its
evidence against three of the four.
</P>
<P>
   But now the remaining defendants have one more thing to contend
with: Volpe's guilty plea. Although it is common for jurors not to
be told that a defendant's disappearance from a trial was the
result of a guilty plea, it appeared Tuesday that the Louima jurors
might be told of Volpe's plea when the trial resumed Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   John Patten, the lawyer for Sgt. Michael Bellomo, one of the
remaining defendants, said he believed that the plea could be so
harmful to his client that he planned to ask the judge Wednesday
morning to declare a mistrial in his client's case so that he might
be tried anew.
</P>
<P>
   Yet one of the defense lawyers and some legal experts said that
Volpe's guilty plea cut both ways.
</P>
<P>
   On the one hand, they said, the jurors may subconsciously
believe that if he pleaded guilty, the other defendants must also
be guilty, and the evidence presented against him may linger beyond
his presence to taint the remaining defendants.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, they say, with the most notorious defendant _
the man whom the prosecution has portrayed as Louima's chief
brutalizer _ standing convicted, the jurors may resolve any doubts
about the evidence against the remaining defendants in favor of
those defendants, believing that justice has been done.
</P>
<P>
   One thing seems clear: Volpe is highly unlikely to appear as a
witness for either side. His guilty plea does not involve a deal
with the prosecution, which last week rebuffed his overture for a
plea bargain.
</P>
<P>
   Although Volpe made statements while pleading guilty Tuesday
that seemed helpful to two of the remaining defendants, Officer
Charles Schwarz and Sgt. Michael Bellomo, lawyers for both of these
men swiftly made clear that they considered Volpe poison.
</P>
<P>
   Schwarz is charged with holding Louima down in the restroom
while Volpe tortured him with the stick. But in giving his account
of the restroom attack to Judge Eugene Nickerson of U.S. District
Court in Brooklyn, Volpe said the other officer in there _ whom
Volpe did not name _ merely ``saw what was going on'' and ``did
nothing to stop it.''
</P>
<P>
   While this ascribes a far lesser role to the other officer _ and
while people familiar with Volpe's full account say the other
officer is not Schwarz _ Schwarz's lawyer said emphatically that he
had no plans to call Volpe as a witness for Schwarz, despite his
seemingly helpful account. ``Justin Volpe _ the man who has
admitted torturing an individual?'' the lawyer, Stephen Worth
declared, making clear his belief that Volpe's testimony would be
damaging, even if his words would seem to help Schwarz.
</P>
<P>
   Bellomo is charged with trying to cover up another assault
against Louima _ what prosecutors have described as a beating in a
police car _ and Volpe's assault of a second man, Patrick Antoine,
by arresting him on false charges. But Volpe told the judge on
Tuesday that he had ``no understanding with Sgt. Bellomo'' about a
cover-up.
</P>
<P>
   The sergeant's lawyer, John Patten, said that while he would
``love to have'' Volpe's testimony on that point, ``at the same
time I think he's damaged goods.''
</P>
<P>
   Patten, in saying that he planned to ask the judge to declare a
mistrial Wednesday for Bellomo, added that with Volpe's having
pleaded guilty, the jurors would think that ``everything Louima
ever said is true.''
</P>
<P>
   While the jurors were not in court Tuesday to see Volpe plead
guilty, the prosecution and the defense were seeking to work out an
agreement Tuesday under which Nickerson would tell the jurors of
Volpe's plea, but not of the charges he pleaded guilty to or what
he said in court Tuesday. The judge would further instruct the
jurors that they were not to consider his plea as evidence of the
remaining defendants' guilt.
</P>
</TEXT>
