<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-25 22:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1053 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OHIO-BUDGETSHORTFALL-     05-25 1175
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OHIO-BUDGETSHORTFALL-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    State officials dismayed over size of budget shortfall
 &HT;    By Lynn Hulsey
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ The first strong sign of financial trouble at
Dayton City Schools came a year ago when administrators canceled
purchase orders in order to balance the budget, Assistant
Superintendent Carol Hauser said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   But district officials failed to make budget cuts needed to head
off a June 30 deficit estimated at $19 million, Hauser said, and
only now are canceling all non-essential purchases and looking to
borrow money, transfer funds and put off some financial obligations
to make it through the end of the school year.
</P>
<P>
   Officials are also considering long-term cuts and may close five
school buildings, outsource busing and cut staff.
</P>
<P>
   School officials are still trying to determine how they ended up
spending $213 million instead of the $181 million budgeted in June
1998.
</P>
<P>
   Carryover funds from last year and unexpected revenue kept the
deficit from growing even larger when the district failed to cut
staff in response to declining enrollment, Hauser said.
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of a damning state audit of the district's finances
and performance, a local legislator said he may propose a law to
allow the Dayton City Commission to take temporary control of the
city's public school system.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those are just terrible, terrible figures,'' said State Rep.
Robert Corbin (R-Washington Twp.), citing auditors' conclusions
that Dayton's deficit could rise to $40 million by 2003 unless
officials take corrective measures.
</P>
<P>
   State Auditor Jim Petro issued the first state-mandated
performance audit of Dayton schools on Monday. The audit showed
that although the school board had approved a budget surplus for
fiscal year 1999, the district actually faces a $14 million
deficit. Updated projections by the district's new budget director,
Jan Schultz, put that figure at $19 million. She discovered the
shortfall after she took over from former budget director Judy Peck
in February. Schultz said she does not know how the looming deficit
escaped school officials' notice.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can only speculate. I cannot provide an answer for that,''
said Schultz. ``I look at things differently than the past budget
director.''
</P>
<P>
   Petro slammed the district's financial planning, record keeping
and business practices. The audit also found Dayton teachers
instructing far below the maximum levels of instructional time
allowed by their contracts. Auditors noted high levels of
absenteeism by drivers, teachers and non-teaching staff.
</P>
<P>
   The audit prompted County Auditor A.J. Wagner to question the
district's official certificate of estimated resources, approved by
the three-member County Budget Commission in March. Wagner,
Montgomery County Prosecutor Mathias H. Heck and Montgomery County
Treasurer Hugh Quill make up the commission. They will ask district
treasurer Kennon Goff to clarify documents that seem to conflict
with Petro's findings. Wagner said it is the first time the
commission has had to make that kind of request.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've never encountered a surprise like this,'' said Wagner,
expressing disbelief that Dayton schools did not have a better
system of checks and balances to catch budget mistakes.
</P>
<P>
   ``As fiscal officer of the county, all kinds of bells and
whistles would be going on, actually years before now, that we were
approaching trouble,'' Wagner said.
</P>
<P>
   School board members are dismayed at the size of the deficit.
They say Superintendent James A. Williams had been assuring them
since January that financial problems were under control.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were being given wrong answers or no answers,'' said Ricky
Boyd, board vice president.
</P>
<P>
   Board member Nancy Brown said she did not trust Williams'
assurances.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got hesitant answers from (Treasurer) Ken (Goff) so I
suspected that everything was not right,'' Brown said.
</P>
<P>
   She said she is not ready to see Goff leave the district but
``would not be unhappy'' if Williams were to find another job.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he owes us some explanations but I don't think we're
going to get them,'' said Brown. ``I think he doesn't think he owes
us any.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams said Monday he is not to blame for the budget shortfall
because his staff gave him inaccurate information.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not taking this beating,'' Williams said.
</P>
<P>
   Williams and Goff did not return calls on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Board members said both Williams and Goff will answer to them
during their evaluations in June. Goff has a year left on his
contract and Williams has a contract through July 31, 2000.
Williams gets an automatic two-year extension unless the board
issues written notice of unsatisfactory performance by Aug. 16.
</P>
<P>
   Board member Clayton Luckie said firing both men is an option.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fourteen million dollars in debt right now is very serious and
I'm not ruling out anything,'' Luckie said.
</P>
<P>
   In Columbus, Corbin said he has discussed with House Republicans
introducing legislation to allow city government to take control of
a struggling or unresponsive school district, hire and fire
employees, close schools and freeze salaries for a year.
</P>
<P>
   GOP leadership in the House did not embrace Corbin's idea,
deeming it ``too controversial,'' Corbin said.
</P>
<P>
   State Rep. J. Donald Mottley, R-West Carrollton, said such
legislation would likely face constitutional challenges if it
became law. Mottley said current state law allows for outside
takeover of a school district with chronic financial problems.
</P>
<P>
   State Sen. Charles Horn, R-Centerville, said Corbin's idea ``is
worth discussion,'' but added that he would ``have to think twice''
before turning districts over to some city commissions or councils
in Ohio, because of the potential for the problems to become even
more politicized.
</P>
<P>
   Mottley called the audit projections ``a great surprise.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The reason it was such a shock is that there is a perception
of Dayton as one of the better-run districts,'' Mottley said. ``I
personally have a certain degree of confidence that at the
administrative level, they'll get on top of this.''
</P>
<P>
   Mottley, Horn and Corbin all said the revelations in the Dayton
audit illustrate the wisdom of legislators' insistence on the
state's 21 largest districts undergoing performance audits.
</P>
<P>
   In response to claims by Dayton school officials that they are
losing enrollment to charter schools, Gov. Bob Taft said Dayton
schools must do a better job if they want to keep students.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it is a challenge of Dayton schools to improve the
product they're offering and attract students,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   If the schools face budget cuts, Taft said, they should not
emphasize protecting jobs or school buildings over classroom
education.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not providing education just to perpetuate certain
schools,'' he said. ``It is to educate children.''
</P>
<P>
   Lynn Hulsey writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
