<SLUG> BC-TEN-FRENCH-OPEN-880&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAMPRAS, CHASING HISTORY, REFUSES TO FADE AWAY 
</HEADLINE>
  (dal) 
 By ROBIN FINN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ On his first match point on Tuesday, Pete Sampras soared
like Superman to hit a forehand stretch volley that would have
ended his first-round ordeal at the French Open. But Sampras wound
up on his belly in the red dirt as his shot, and his noble
intentions, buried themselves in the net.
</P>
<P>
   So he soldiered on.
</P>
<P>
   On his second match point, Sampras, covered with clay,
double-faulted on the 18th point of the fourth-set tie breaker. He
then glared in disgust as his dogged opponent, 88th-ranked Juan
Antonio Marin of Costa Rica, sent their standoff into a fifth set
by converting his eighth set point with a forehand that glanced off
the corner tape.
</P>
<P>
   So Sampras, very much against his will, soldiered on a little
longer and eventually won the war.
</P>
<P>
   Another French Open, another torturous outing for Sampras, the
man who would love to become a king of clay but continues to fumble
around like a court jester on the stuff of his Grand Slam
nightmares. A title here at Roland Garros, the only Grand Slam
tournament to confound him, would bring the 27-year-old Californian
a 12th Grand Slam crown and tie him with Roy Emerson's career
record. But Sampras knows better than to focus on that finish line.
Now, in his 10th year here, he has advanced no closer than the 1996
semifinals, and merely surviving the opening round has required
something close to an act of God.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday it took him forever, or 4 hours 18 minutes _ which
felt like one and the same thing to Sampras _ to escape from Round
1 with a 6-7 (10-12), 6-4, 7-5, 6-7 (9-11), 6-4 victory. Sampras
and Marin began in stark sunshine and concluded with center court
shrouded by evening shadows.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it's the fifth set, it comes down to the heart, and
obviously I wanted to win this match, want to do well here,'' said
Sampras, now 23-9 at Roland Garros and 27-10 in career
five-setters. ``It's a tough way to open, but I got through it,
that's the bottom line. It's welcome to Paris, I guess.
</P>
<P>
   ``How did I survive it? Grace of God, I guess,'' said Sampras,
who also gave thanks for his serve, with the exception of a few
ill-timed double faults. ``At match point is not recommended,'' he
joked. ``Losing that fourth-set tie breaker kind of killed me a
little bit, but the fact that I hung in there, it pleases me. It's
never good to play four and a half hours in the first round, but
I'm still alive.''
</P>
<P>
   In the final set, Sampras and Marin traded early breaks, then
Sampras, after holding for 5-4, hunkered down and ambushed his
intrepid challenger in the 10th game. Though his hangdog body
language and frequent knee bends hinted at physical distress,
Sampras had closure on his mind. He brought the game to deuce with
a forehand pass, pelted a buoyant forehand winner into the corner
for his third match point and ended the marathon with another bold
forehand that provoked a halfhearted backhand into the net from
Marin.
</P>
<P>
   ``That last game he played well; any mistake you make, and it's
the match,'' said Marin, who dismissed the notion that Sampras
performs on clay with all the ease of a fish in a frying pan.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I play indoors or on grass, I'm not gonna
serve-and-volley,'' said Marin, a tried and true baseliner. ``Maybe
on this surface he's not as good as on other surfaces, but he
knows. He's been six years No. 1; he knows what to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Sampras littered the match with 74 unforced errors, including 14
double faults, the most consequential of them the angry double
fault that spoiled his first match point and the double fault, his
fourth of the match, that gave Marin possession of the tie breaker
in their 52-minute opening set.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guy can play some really good tennis, came out and made me
work extremely hard and probably should have beaten me,'' said
Sampras, who faces Andrei Medvedev next. ``If I'm going to lose,
I'm going to lose playing my way. I just told myself this year I'm
going to come in, be aggressive. Today I just kind of hung in there
and scrapped it out.''
</P>
<P>
   Compared with Sampras, the other top seeded players in action on
this sunny afternoon advanced without much scrapping or trauma:
Gustavo Kuerten, the eighth-seeded Brazilian who won his first
career title here in 1997 and is heralded as this year's favorite,
put on a clay court clinic and annihilated Galo Blanco of Spain,
6-4, 6-4, 6-3. Patrick Rafter, the runner-up to Kuerten last week
at the Italian Open and the third-seeded man here, topped Roger
Federer of Switzerland, 5-7, 6-3, 6-0, 6-2.
</P>
<P>
   In the opening act on the center court program, the five-time
champion Steffi Graf thrashed Magdalena Maleeva of Bulgaria, 6-2,
6-0. Lindsay Davenport, seeded second, disposed of 67th-ranked Jane
Chi, 6-3, 6-1, and last year's runner-up, Monica Seles, seeded
third, overwhelmed Fang Li of China, 6-2, 6-4. Mary Pierce, seeded
eighth, gave Joannette Kruger of South Africa a 6-4, 6-3 pounding
and then acknowledged that part of her power comes with the help of
creatine, the controversial training supplement favored by weight
lifters and baseball players.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not a science person, but it just helps you recover
quicker and build lean muscle mass, just gives you a little bit of
extra energy,'' she said. ``It's been a very small part of my
supplementation and training, probably 3 percent.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   MATCH POINTS
</P>
<P>
   The short list of seeded players who lost was headed by
10th-seeded Mark Philippoussis, last year's U.S. Open runner-up,
who continues to sputter on clay. As his paltry trio of aces
testified, the big-serving Australian lacked his necessary
artillery and fell to his countryman Jason Stoltenberg, 7-6 (7-4),
6-4, 6-1. The loser's 63 unforced errors included 16 double faults.
The other seeded man to depart was 11th-seeded Karol Kucera of
Slovakia, who made his fifth first-round exit in seven visits.
Kucera was ousted, 6-2, 6-3, 6-2, by Magnus Larsson of Sweden. On
the women's side, 14th-seeded Amanda Coetzer was dispatched by Ai
Sugiyama, 7-5, 6-1. ... Jennifer Capriati, who won her first title
in six and a half years at Strasbourg on Saturday, defeated
Virginia Ruano-Pascual of Spain, 6-2, 6-3.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
