<HEADER>
A1055 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OBIT-RIOS-NYT &LR;      05-25 0357
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-RIOS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANTHONY P. RIOS, 84, AN ORGANIZER IN POLITICS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: California)   (dal) 
 By WOLFGANG SAXON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Anthony P. Rios, a veteran political organizer among Hispanic
Californians, died on May 19 at Kaiser Permanente Hospital in
Baldwin Park, a suburb of Los Angeles. He was 84 and lived in Los
Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Rios joined Saul Alinsky, the Chicago sociologist and organizer,
in founding the Community Service Organization in California in
1947. Their purpose was to marshal Hispanic Californians and turn
them into a political and social force to reckon with.
</P>
<P>
   He was a mentor to former Rep. Edward R. Roybal, a social worker
and public-health educator whose political career the group
championed. Roybal won election to the Los Angeles City Council in
1949 and went on to Washington in 1963, where he stayed until 1992,
serving in important committee posts and as chairman of the
Congressional Hispanic Caucus.
</P>
<P>
   Rios, a native of Calexico, Calif., and a former labor organizer
himself, was also an early supporter of Cesar Chavez and his
campaign to organize farm workers in California. Rios started
organizing as a teen-ager in the 1930s when he and his fellow lemon
pickers were left without jobs in the winters. He became involved
in organizing steelworkers in Los Angeles and, in 1947, helped to
form the a group that rallied people to register and vote.
</P>
<P>
   Over the next decades the organization inspired chapters across
California, especially in rural areas. Chavez, a migrant worker,
became active in the movement in 1952 and was serving as its
general director in 1962, when he left to form the United Farm
Workers union.
</P>
<P>
   As the Community Service Organization grew, Rios' long-term goal
remained what it had been at the start, involving Hispanic
residents in the political process.
</P>
<P>
   He is survived by his wife, Rosie Vasquez; three daughters,
Geraldine, of Montebello, Calif., Senda, of Hayward, and Donna, of
San Luis Obispo; two sons, Fernando, of Whittier, and Tony Jr., of
Los Angeles; a brother, Armando; 10 grandchildren; and six
great-grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
