<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCKESSON-OUTLOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MCKESSON EARNINGS REVISION SENDS STOCK PLUNGING
</HEADLINE>
   (jw) 
 By DAVID J. MORROW   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In what is becoming a serial calamity, McKesson HBOC
Inc. announced Tuesday that it would make further revisions to its
fiscal and quarterly earnings because of improperly recorded sales
at HBO &AMP; Co., a software maker it acquired in January.
</P>
<P>
   The news frightened investors, who quickly sold the stock.
Shares of McKesson dropped 12.3 percent, or $4.6875, Tuesday to
close at $33.50, barely above its 52-week low. McKesson's stock
plunged nearly 48 percent last month when it first announced
accounting irregularities.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's announcement, released early in the morning in a terse
statement, raised the ire of investors and analysts alike.
McKesson, the nation's largest drug wholesaler, said last month
that it had found $42.2 million in sales transactions that had not
been fully completed.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, the company insisted that the audit should go back
only one year. But Tuesday, McKesson said that additional instances
of improper revenue recognition had been discovered and that
results for prior years at HBO might have to be restated.
</P>
<P>
   As with many dealings with McKesson in the last year, this one
comes with its share of complexities. Analysts, for example, openly
pondered the future of Charles McCall, McKesson's chairman, and
Mark Pulido, the chief executive, after neither man was quoted in
Tuesday's announcement.
</P>
<P>
   ``The board of directors at McKesson has clearly taken control
of the company,'' said Mike Krensavage, an analyst with Brown
Brothers Harriman. ``The company's management has no credibility.
Heads will roll at McKesson.''
</P>
<P>
   Larry Kurtz, a company spokesman, said, ``The process is still
ongoing, and I don't have a comment at this time.''
</P>
<P>
   The release did not provide any dollar amounts to the new
improper sales or say what negative effect the recalculation would
have on earnings.
</P>
<P>
   A series of large options trades has preceded each of the
McKesson announcements about its accounting woes, raising
additional questions. Around noon on Monday, 1,285 options were
traded in three transactions at prices of 62 cents to 75 cents
each. With McKesson's stock droop, those options were trading
Tuesday at $2.25, a gain of 200 percent. A week before McKesson's
first announcement last month, some 1,400 options were traded.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said that McKesson executives must have feared that
information was leaking into the financial markets and rushed out a
statement about the progress of the audit.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts and investors were puzzled as to why the company was
just discovering the irregularities. When McKesson first announced
the troubles, the company said that many of the questioned sales
transactions occurred when HBO recorded the sale before the
contract for it was signed.
</P>
<P>
   Many analysts accepted this explanation. McKesson even reassured
investors that many of the sales would be recorded later, once the
contingencies to these contracts had been met. But with Tuesday's
announcement, some analysts are no longer comfortable with
McKesson's explanation and have begun to suspect that the company
may have been duped by HBO.
</P>
<P>
   As recently as last summer, when McKesson first began its
acquisition talks, questions about HBO's accounting practices had
begun to surface. In two reports, one in April 1997 and another in
August 1998, the Center for Financial Research and Analysis, an
institutional research company in Rockville, Md., warned investors
that HBO was booking revenue too fast.
</P>
<P>
   Among the center's concerns was how aggressively HBO booked
sales from its long-term contracts. For example, in a 10-year
contract for $10,000, HBO could decide that it had completed
one-quarter of the contract's obligations and book $2,500 in
revenues the first year.
</P>
<P>
   The only problem, the center said, was that HBO could collect
only $1,000 that year, according to terms in the contract. While
this practice is common among software makers, the center worried
that HBO used it too often.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts and investors are riled that McKesson did not catch
these accounting problems before it bought HBO. Angry investors,
many of whom have joined several class-action lawsuits against
McKesson over the battered stock price.
</P>
<P>
   With Tuesday's news, McKesson will have plenty to explain beyond
the findings in the audit. Analysts question whether the company
did its due diligence when buying HBO. With the selloff in
McKesson's stock, the market has valued HBO at nothing, making many
wonder whether the purchase was more trouble than it was worth.
</P>
<P>
   ``McKesson should have realized what was going on at HBO,'' said
Christopher Teeters, an analyst at the Center for Financial
Research and Analysis. ``Drug delivery is a cash-and-carry
business. Software doesn't work that way. When McKesson's
executives reviewed how HBO's sales work, they didn't understand
what they were looking at.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
