<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-REDSKINS-SALE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NFL APPROVES $800-MILLION PURCHASE OF REDSKINS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By RICHARD SANDOMIR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The tortuous, sometimes bitter, process of selling the
Washington Redskins concluded Tuesday when the National Football
League unanimously blessed the $800 million acquisition by Daniel
Snyder, a 34-year-old communications entrepreneur.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been an incredible journey,'' said Snyder, whose company,
Snyder Communications, is in Bethesda, Md. ``I woke up this morning
and I felt strange and wonderful. I'm a fan. A huge fan. It's that
simple.''
</P>
<P>
   Snyder and his partners, Mortimer Zuckerman and Fred Drasner,
the owners of The New York Daily News, paid more for the Redskins
than anyone before for a sports franchise, ending a process that
began last September when Jack Kent Cooke's estate put the team up
for sale.
</P>
<P>
   The league's 31 owners approved the bid in the only action taken
on the first of two days of meetings.
</P>
<P>
   Snyder was originally a partner in a bid by Howard Milstein, the
New York real estate developer. Milstein withdrew his bid last
month and subsequently sued two Redskins officials, saying they
lobbied NFL owners against his $800 million offer, which was deemed
too debt-heavy by the league.
</P>
<P>
   Snyder brought in Zuckerman and Drasner, who have helped finance
his past business ventures, soon after Milstein unhappily backed
out. ``It came together in about a week,'' Snyder said.
</P>
<P>
   He had no comment on Milstein's suit against John Kent Cooke,
the Redskins' president and son of the late owner, who bid $680
million to buy the Redskins, which his father refused to will to
him, and general manager Charley Casserly. Both denied the
allegations.
</P>
<P>
   NFL commissioner Paul Tagliabue said that in a conversation with
Milstein two or three weeks ago, ``I told him I thought the
understanding is there would be peace and no lawsuits, but he said
he felt Cooke acted improperly and I said I felt he was
misguided.''
</P>
<P>
   As the Redskins, a bedrock NFL franchise, proceed under new
ownership, the prospective owners of an expansion Los Angeles team
brought their competing plans for redeveloping the Los Angeles
Memorial Coliseum to the meeting. But the deciding factor between
plans from Michael Ovitz, the entertainment deal maker, and Eli
Broad, an insurance services billionaire, may not be luxury suites,
fountains, reflecting pools or lavish landscaping. It won't be
which man can name the members of the Fearsome Foursome fastest.
</P>
<P>
   It may all come down to parking.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our mission here is, how do you do parking?'' said John
Semcken, executive vice president of New Coliseum Partners, the
group formed by Broad and Ed Roski Jr., a real estate developer.
``It's boring, but it's what they asked us to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Parking is crucial because of its importance to the so-called
fan experience at the often-maligned Coliseum site, which the Rams
and the Raiders have abandoned.
</P>
<P>
   Ovitz's plan calls for building 60 acres of grassy parkland
above a series of two- to five-story parking garages. There would
be 16 garage entrances, and each game ticket would designate which
one to enter. The garages would cost an estimated $225 million.
``The NFL asked us for 25,000 spots, and we've suggested 27,000,''
Ovitz said.
</P>
<P>
   Broad offered four parking options, one as expensive as $240
million to build 24,150 underground spaces, but he recommended a
modest $67 million garage with 7,500 spaces that would be added to
10,000 spaces now in place or to be built.
</P>
<P>
   ``We presented certainty,'' Semcken said. ``We feel we can get
public funding for $67 million, with all the parking revenues
dedicated to paying off the bond.''
</P>
<P>
   Tagliabue all but endorsed the scope of Ovitz's stadium
redevelopment plan, which is more elaborate and grandiose than
Broad's.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is exactly the kind of vision we feel is necessary to
transform the venue that is in the best interests of fans and the
city of Los Angeles,'' Tagliabue said.
</P>
<P>
   Tagliabue and several owners said the league hoped that Ovitz
and Broad merge. ``That would be in the best interests of the
league and the people of Los Angeles,'' said Wayne Weaver, the
owner of the Jacksonville Jaguars. ``Together they'd have a lot of
leverage.''
</P>
<P>
   Wellington Mara, the Giants' co-owner, said: ``Certainly, it
would be desirable. Each is a strong group.''
</P>
<P>
   The ultimate pessimist is Al Davis, the Raiders' chief who left
the Coliseum for Oakland. He says he believes that the Los Angeles
market is his, and that he wants to build a stadium at Hollywood
Park.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if they know where they're going here,'' he said.
``We're a professional football league and we're talking about
parking lots.''
</P>
<P>
   Even as Ovitz pursues ownership in Los Angeles, he said he was
not certain that local fans would flock to football after losing
two teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not 100 percent convinced they'll embrace football,'' he
said. ``There's a lot of apathy. They're up with football. If you
want to see a game, you can turn on the TV or go to San Diego. We
have to give them an appropriate facility and an appropriate
experience.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
