<SLUG> BC-NY-LOUIMA-VOLPE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN UNREMARKABLE OFFICER, AN UNSPEAKABLE ACTION 
</HEADLINE>
  (dal) 
 By AMY WALDMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ What Justin Volpe did to Abner Louima in the bathroom
of the 70th Precinct station house on Aug. 9, 1997, is now as plain
as the words Volpe spoke in court on Tuesday. Why he did it,
however, remains painfully, perhaps permanently, inscrutable.
</P>
<P>
   Other officers, and young men on the streets of the Brooklyn
neighborhood he patrolled, intimated after Volpe's arrest in 1997
that he had a short temper and an occasionally bullying demeanor.
Some acquaintances called him arrogant, an adjective consistent
with testimony that the officer boasted of his brutality.
</P>
<P>
   But the picture painted by most of those who know him was of an
unremarkable man who led an unremarkable life. He was, they say, a
dutiful teen-ager, an average cop who was by turns quiet and
sociable, who lifted weights and rode his Harley-Davidson through
the city at night.
</P>
<P>
   Justin A. Volpe was born in March 1972 in Bay Ridge, Brooklyn,
the youngest of three brothers. Shortly after his birth, the family
moved to Eltingville, on Staten Island, living in a stylishly
landscaped, two-story white wood-and-brick house _ the same one
where Volpe spent Monday night under house arrest before his plea
on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Both of his parents are artists. His mother, Grace, paints and
teaches art at St. Joseph by the Sea High School on Staten Island.
His father, Robert, became a police officer _ a career move he has
often described as illogical for an artist _ but he fused his
interests by becoming a one-man unit specializing in art theft. He
retired from the force 12 years ago, after making a name for
himself by cracking a number of high-profile cases of stolen art.
</P>
<P>
   He has spent his retirement writing screenplays, painting,
lecturing _ and, for the last year and a half, maintaining his
son's innocence. As recently as a month ago, he asserted that his
youngest son was the victim of a ``modern-day lynching.''
</P>
<P>
   Both Justin and his older brother Damian followed their father
on the force. At the time of the Louima incident, Damian was also
assigned to the 70th Precinct, where he was a delegate of the
Patrolmen's Benevolent Association. He has since been transferred.
The oldest brother, Robert, who is in his 30s, also toyed with
becoming a police officer, but instead became an English teacher.
</P>
<P>
   Justin Volpe attended St. Joseph by the Sea, and, like his two
brothers, enrolled at the Staten Island campus of St. John's
University. He joined the force in August 1993, and received his
degree in criminal justice in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   After graduating from the academy, he was assigned to the
midnight shift at the 70th Precinct, where Damian worked on the day
shift. Police officials have described Justin Volpe's police record
as unexceptional. He was decorated with six medals for good police
work, mainly for arresting suspects with guns. On one occasion, in
September 1995, he was the subject of an unsubstantiated complaint
to the Civilian Complaint Review Board that he ``pinched, kicked
and cursed'' a man. Several officers familiar with him have said he
tended to be hot-tempered and arrogant.
</P>
<P>
   ``They say he's arrogant,'' Robert Volpe said after his son's
arrest. ``I say proud.''
</P>
<P>
   While the Louima incident appeared to have undercurrents of
racial bigotry, Justin Volpe was not overtly prejudiced, friends
and acquaintances said. For several years, he has dated Susan
Lawson, a black woman who was working as a clerk at the 70th
Precinct, and the two became engaged.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-25-99 2225EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
