<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOYS-SETTLEMENT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
2 TOY MAKERS, ONE RETAILER SETTLE ANTITRUST CHARGES 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By DANA CANEDY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Several leading players in the toy industry agreed
Tuesday to pay 44 states $50 million in cash and merchandise to
settle antitrust charges.
</P>
<P>
   Toys R Us, which was accused of orchestrating the conspiracy to
restrict competition, agreed to pay the heftiest amount _ toys with
a retail value of $27 million and $13.5 million in cash to be used
for toys, books and other educational material.
</P>
<P>
   Toys R Us, which is based in Paramus, N.J., and is one of the
largest toy retailers in the world, agreed to make the donations
and cash payment to settle a lawsuit in which attorneys general in
44 states accused the company of using its power to persuade toy
makers to limit the amount of some popular items, including Barbie
Dream House and Fisher Price Nursery Monitors, distributed to
warehouses and price clubs.
</P>
<P>
   Two manufacturers also agreed Tuesday to donate toys to settle
similar charges in the suit, filed in federal court in 1997 by the
New York attorney general's office. Mattel Inc., in El Segundo,
Calif., agreed Tuesday to pay $8.2 million in cash and toys and
Little Tikes Co. agreed to pay $1.3 million in cash and toys.
Little Tikes, a unit of Newell Rubbermaid Inc., is based in Hudson,
Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   The toys will be distributed to needy children by the Marine
Corps `Toys for Tots' program over three holiday seasons beginning
this year.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the $50 million combined value of Tuesday's
settlement, Hasbro Inc., Pawtucket, R.I., agreed last December to
pay $6 million in cash and toys to resolve its portion of the case.
None of the companies admitted wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   The donations and cash payments are intended to penalize the toy
makers and retailer for what the attorneys general say was a
far-reaching conspiracy to limit distribution and restrict
consumers' ability to compare prices. The companies are expected to
claim tax deductions to reflect their costs.
</P>
<P>
   The settlement, which is subject to court approval, is
nonetheless a victory for consumers, according to the New York
state attorney general, Eliot Spitzer, who took over the case
brought in federal court by his predecessor, Dennis Vacco.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although toy makers and sellers like to view themselves as
Santa's helpers, in this case these companies were nothing more
than modern-day Scrooges,'' Spitzer said.
</P>
<P>
   Toys R Us said it settled the suit to avoid protracted
litigation. As part of the agreement, New York will receive $2.2
million in toys and $850,000 in cash, which will be used to provide
books and other educational material to needy youngsters. Overall,
the toys will go to children in all 50 states, Washington and
Puerto Rico.
</P>
<P>
   The product mix is at the discretion of the companies within
certain guidelines. ``The bottom line is they wanted as much leeway
as possible to decide which toys went and the states tried to rein
them in on that,'' said Linda Gargiulo, an assistant attorney
general in New York who was involved in the negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, the donated goods must include toys for girls as
well as boys, and items for children of all ages. The goods must be
among items currently for sale at Toys R Us and cannot include
recalled items or products that depict violence.
</P>
<P>
   The price of individual items was left largely to the discretion
of the companies. Only 10 percent, however, can be of a value
greater than $30 so that the donation will generate enough toys to
distribute to a large number of children.
</P>
<P>
   Toys R Us said it had not decided what toys to donate but ``I
think we will try to put together a broad selection of toys,'' said
Rebecca Caruso, a company spokeswoman.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-25-99 2225EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
