<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-RHODEN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: WIN OR LOSE, VAN GUNDY IS ON THE HOT SEAT 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By WILLIAM C. RHODEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ What a fine time for pro basketball fans here. The
Knicks, after a five-year wait, are playing for a conference
championship beginning Sunday. The team has taken on a sleek,
fast-moving style of play and the franchise, which has seen dark
days, is enjoying a triumphant moment.
</P>
<P>
   But at a time when the organization, the city and the fans
should be dancing in the aisles, the franchise is ensnarled in a
bizarre drama involving the head coach, the team's top executive,
the players and even the news media. The joy of what the team has
accomplished shares the stage with this never-ending drama, and
it's too bad.
</P>
<P>
   Hours before the Knicks completed an impressive sweep of the
Atlanta Hawks on Monday, the Madison Square Garden crowd, instead
of being gripped by pre-game electricity, was digesting the news
that Garden president Dave Checketts admitted that he had indeed
met with Phil Jackson and that he had lied about it, not simply to
the news media but also to his head coach, Jeff Van Gundy.
</P>
<P>
   Fans reacted a number of ways. For some, the idea of being lied
to by the boss or lying to an employee was not such a big deal. For
others, the idea of Phil Jackson in New York was not revolting. For
many in attendance Monday night, the news seem to demand a
response. In the waning moments of the Knicks' victory, fans began
to chant _ instead of chanting for the team or the players, they
chanted for the coach, in sing-song style: ``Jeff Van GUN-dy, Jeff
Van GUN-dy.''
</P>
<P>
   In their minds the fans were giving Van Gundy the vote of
confidence that Checketts refused to give.
</P>
<P>
   But this Knicks franchise has become so fragmented and so
polarized in this lockout-shortened season, there could easily have
been at least two more groups of fans chanting their support at the
Garden. One group could have chanted ``Ernie GRUN-feld'' to pay
homage to Grunfeld's role in bringing Marcus Camby and and Latrell
Sprewell to the Knicks. Another group, considerably smaller, could
have chanted David CHECK-etts.''
</P>
<P>
   There have been no hue and cry for Van Gundy to stay on as head
coach; rather, there have been pockets of support. The greater
sense is one of wait-and-see curiosity: what direction does the
Garden want to take _ Grunfeld's big-name approach or a more
grass-roots approach to rebuilding.
</P>
<P>
   Van Gundy is a fine basketball coach, but there's more to
coaching than staying up all night watching film or diagramming
plays. There's more to it than being loyal, so loyal to your
``guys'' that you nearly let the ship sink. Van Gundy's unearned
good fortune _ and I'm not sure he understands this _is that
Sprewell is an outstanding basketball player, and the versatile
Camby has been gracious in ignoring the coach's early-season
innuendos about his lack of work ethic. Camby has held his tongue
and played outstanding basketball.
</P>
<P>
   In victory after victory, the coach has seemed reluctant to
praise the two players. On Monday he said in response to a question
about Sprewell: ``He helped us win. That's all I care about.''
</P>
<P>
   But Van Gundy also cares about his job, and Sprewell and Camby
have played as crucial a role in helping him keep it as Oakley and
Ewing and Starks played in helping him get it.
</P>
<P>
   Van Gundy proved he can win in the first round and that he can
beat a Hawks team depleted by injuries in Round 2. Indiana
represents a major challenge for Van Gundy's career. This series
will be his best audition yet.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks have the talent to beat Indiana. But to do so, Van
Gundy will have to deploy personnel and use a wide-open style to a
greater extent than he has to this point. In this series, Sprewell
will not be the automatic genie in the bottle; the Pacers have
their own genie in Jalen Rose.
</P>
<P>
   The 6-foot-11-inch Camby is the wild card. How will Van Gundy
use him? Will he break from rigid substitution patterns? Will he
turn the offensive players completely loose?
</P>
<P>
   For the Knicks, it's all part of a vicious and unfortunate
cycle. Van Gundy is reluctant to praise Sprewell or Camby;
Checketts is reluctant to praise Van Gundy.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone talks about this playoff series and ties it to the
Knicks' future. But this season is not about the future. It's about
the here and now. The wheels are about to fall off this wagon, and
no one is sure who is going to be around to put them back on. The
Knicks are playing for now.
</P>
<P>
   Let's make it clear and simple: if the Knicks win the Eastern
Conference championship _ or lose valiantly in seven games _ Van
Gundy crosses the burning sands. He stays. If the Knicks lose, we
keep our options open. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
