<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Braves notebook: Smoltz encouraged by pitching session
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Milwaukee _ The news couldn't have been much better for John
Smoltz _ and the struggling Braves starting rotation _ Tuesday
after he spent 30 minutes throwing from a mound for the first time
since going on the disabled list May 17.
</P>
<P>
   He threw about 75 pitches in the bullpen at what he estimated
was 80-85 percent and reported afterward he was feeling good and
was still on track to return when he comes off the disabled list to
start either June 1 or 2.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a lot more pleasant than I expected,'' said Smoltz,
whose pain level was his biggest concern. ``That's all I care about
right now. I feel more rusty (than anything).''
</P>
<P>
   Smoltz said he was just glad to be back out there pitching. ``I
couldn't wait any longer. I've been thinking about it for three or
four days. `What am I going to do?' and `How am I going to do
it?'''
</P>
<P>
   Next is another throwing session Friday or Saturday in Atlanta,
and this time he'll face hitters in some sort of simulated game.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was just a small hurdle,'' Smoltz said. ``Next thing is
to throw to hitters when they don't know what's coming, more like a
game, refamiliarize myself with the strike zone.''
</P>
<P>
   Nomo's back
</P>
<P>
   The Braves are curious what they'll see tonight when they face
pitcher Hideo Nomo, who has apparently returned to form with the
Brewers after being released by the Mets and Cubs earlier this
season.
</P>
<P>
   Nomo, 1-1 for Milwaukee with a staff-best 2.21 ERA, is 2-0 with
a 1.94 ERA in seven career starts against the Braves.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves hit him hard in spring training before he was
released by the Mets. After winning the NL Rookie of the Year award
in 1995, Nomo started to struggle with his control.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once the league adjusted to him, he started having problems,''
said Chipper Jones, who's 0-for-19 against Nomo. ``You're a little
bit apprehensive because obviously something changed. We'll find
out pretty early what it is.''
</P>
<P>
   At his best, Nomo mixes a fastball and a split-finger fastball,
while hiding the ball in a strange delivery.
</P>
<P>
   Etc.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Hunter replaced Ryan Klesko in the lineup Tuesday against
Brewers left-hander Jim Abbott. Klesko has not started against a
left-hander since the Padres' Sterling Hitchcock on May 9. Klesko
is hitting .158 (3-for-19) with one home run against left-handers
and .303 (27-for-89) with five home runs against right-handers. . .
. Jones' 455-foot home run off Horatio Estrada Monday night tied
Greg Vaughn and Cecil Fielder for the fourth-longest homer hit at
County Stadium since stadium officials began recording distances in
1987. The homer was the longest the switch-hitter remembers hitting
from the right side and it brought his season total from the right
to five, along with five homers from the left. His career high in
home runs from the right side in a season is six, in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
