<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPREWELL KEEPS APPEARING OUT OF NOWHERE FOR KNICKS 
</HEADLINE>
  (dal) 
 By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ On the cover of the Knicks' playoff guide is a figure
that looks like a life-sized cardboard cutout from a supermarket
display standing between a stoic Jeff Van Gundy and the
broad-shouldered Chris Dudley.
</P>
<P>
   Latrell Sprewell's image in the team photo is a little flatter
and stiffer than the rest of his teammates. He was late to practice
a month ago, so a computer superimposed a photo of Sprewell into
the space that was left for him.
</P>
<P>
   In a sense, what was captured on film April 22 was another
moment in the evolution of the once disjointed Knicks. At his own
speed, Sprewell began to blend into a team that has closed their
gaps, smoothed over their seams and formed a unit at the right time
to face the Indiana Pacers in the Eastern Conference finals.
</P>
<P>
   It is a playoff distance never traveled by an eighth-seeded
team, and the first time the Knicks have gone this far since 1994.
Their path has not always been blissful, not even during their
crushing four-game sweep of the Atlanta Hawks.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, the day before Game 3 of that series, a shouting
match erupted at practice between two players, according to a
person who requested anonymity. One player was upset over how hard
Van Gundy was pushing them, and the other was trying to stop the
complaining to get through the workout.
</P>
<P>
   ``Up, 2-0, against Atlanta, and this is what's going on?'' the
person said. ``They almost came to blows.''
</P>
<P>
   Teetering on self-destruction has become a way of life for the
Knicks. They have grown accustomed to their dysfunction and thrived
in spite of it. Through it all, Van Gundy has been able to focus on
the game despite the cloak-and-dagger operations at Madison Square
Garden.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has been a struggle this year,'' Larry Johnson said. ``We
could have been done and folded in this tent and not focused in on
our goal last month.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Jeff, he is the toughness one on this team because of
everything that he has to cope with and the criticism he had to put
up with. He not only kept himself together but made sure he kept
his team together and made sure we were prepared every night. I
think his focus was always on us.''
</P>
<P>
   Van Gundy's vision has not been shared by everyone, but his
strategies have paid off in the playoffs. Sprewell may never
embrace his sixth-man role, but he played it to perfection as he
turned up the pace on the slow dance the Hawks had in mind.
</P>
<P>
   Marcus Camby may want steadier minutes, but he pounced on each
chance like a cat on yarn and was not shy about challenging Dikembe
Mutombo.
</P>
<P>
   Together, Camby and Sprewell have formed a dynamic second team
that routinely beats the Knicks' first team in practice.
</P>
<P>
   Almost in the shadow of the bench's play, Allan Houston has not
always responded as aggressively as he should, but he has shown he
can coexist with Sprewell and still be a star (34 points in Game
1). Patrick Ewing has groaned a time or two when he has been lifted
from a playoff game, but with his injury situation, Van Gundy's use
of him as a spot-up shooter pulled Mutombo away from the basket.
</P>
<P>
   The injury-plagued Hawks were hardly a good measure for the
Knicks' turnaround. Meet the Pacers. They possess a counter to each
Knick impact player: Jalen Rose, Antonio Davis, Reggie Miller and
Rik Smits.
</P>
<P>
   But Indiana will face a team different from the one that clawed
its way into the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything works so much better when we're looking for each
other,'' Camby said. ``When we're swinging the ball around, trying
to get open looks, cutting to the basket, we're at our best.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we had more patience within our team,'' Van Gundy
said. ``We played very well the last three weeks of the regular
season, and we have played well to date in the playoffs. Hopefully,
we can continue.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
