<HEADLINE>
STRAWBERRY TO BE ARRAIGNED ON DRUG AND PROSTITUTION CHARGES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla.)   (bl)  
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Darryl Strawberry is scheduled to be arraigned on charges of
possession of cocaine and solicitation of prostitution Wednesday
morning in Tampa, Fla., with his immediate baseball future hanging
in the balance.
</P>
<P>
   Strawberry has maintained he is not guilty and if he pleads that
way, it may be two months before his jury trial begins. If he
pleads guilty or no contest, he almost certainly will prompt Major
League Baseball to suspend him as a multiple offender of its drug
aftercare program.
</P>
<P>
   No matter what happens Wednesday, however, the calendar
continues to present a formidable threat to Strawberry's baseball
career. After Strawberry, 37, was charged in April, the New York
Yankees ended his workouts at their minor league facility in Tampa,
and he was later placed on administrative leave by Major League
Baseball.
</P>
<P>
   Even if Strawberry was allowed to play immediately after his
case was resolved, it could be weeks before he was ready to play
again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't given any thought on the Strawberry thing
whatsoever, given the fact that he's out of our control and he's
not under our guidance,'' said Yankees general manager Brian
Cashman. ``If you asked me today who are the left-handed options
for the Yankees in the future, I would say Tony Tarasco and Ricky
Ledee, because Strawberry is not an option right now.''
</P>
<P>
   And there remains the matter of how George Steinbrenner, the
team's principal owner, will react to any resolution other than a
verdict of not guilty. When Strawberry was charged, the Yankees
believed language in his $2.5 million contract gave them the right
to void what is left on his deal. If Strawberry is suspended again
by Major League Baseball, his contract will be voided and he will
be left without a job.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
