<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-BUDGET-BATTLE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BATTLE GROWS OVER BUDGET AS SPEAKER THREATENS THE GOVERNOR'S PAY 
</HEADLINE>
  (dal) 
 By RICHARD PEREZ-PENA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Because the state budget is late, legislators
have gone almost two months without pay, and some angry and
frustrated Democrats want to make Gov. George Pataki do without,
too.
</P>
<P>
   Assembly Speaker Sheldon Silver is considering blocking an
emergency spending bill that contains the salaries of the governor
and other statewide elected officials for the next two weeks,
Silver's aides said on Tuesday. If the Assembly does not pass the
spending bill, it could further inflame a budget stalemate that has
already turned bitter and personal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We laid the bill aside, and he's weighing his options and
talking to the members of his conference about how to proceed,''
said Patricia Lynch, a spokeswoman for Silver, D-Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki, a Republican, said, ``I would hope that they would just
concentrate on and pass the budget and not look at petty things.''
</P>
<P>
   Some Republican officials said it might be illegal to withhold
the officials' pay.
</P>
<P>
   In December, lawmakers approved a 38 percent salary increase for
the state's elected officials, their first increase in 10 years.
But as a condition of approving the raise, Pataki and Joseph Bruno,
the Senate's Republican majority leader, insisted on a law
providing that if the budget was late, pay would be withheld for
the 211 members of the Legislature until the budget was passed.
</P>
<P>
   Legislators received their last paychecks on March 31, the last
day of the old fiscal year. For the 15th year in a row, New York
did not have a budget in place on time.
</P>
<P>
   The government has been kept running through a series of
two-week emergency bills, including one in each cycle providing the
salaries of Pataki, Lt. Gov. Mary Donohue, Comptroller H. Carl
McCall and Attorney General Eliot Spitzer.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate passed the latest such bill on Monday. The officials
are scheduled to be paid Wednesday, so if the Assembly passed the
bill Wednesday, checks would not be interrupted. But if not, the
Legislature is not scheduled to convene again until Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's disruptive, it's not helpful, it's not productive,''
Bruno said of Silver's threat. ``We ought to be focused on passing
a budget.''
</P>
<P>
   Since March, Bruno, Silver and Pataki have traded accusations
over the budget, but there have been few talks and no progress. The
legislative leaders have blamed each other for their failure to
agree on an overall spending cap, and for the fact that conference
committees on the budget have not yet been convened.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
