<HEADLINE>
AWARDS FOR BUSINESS REPORTING ANNOUNCED
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ohio, Minn., N.Y., Calif., Fla., Wash., Ill.)   (jw) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Cleveland Plain Dealer, Minnesota Public Radio and ``60
Minutes'' were among the news organizations honored by the 1999
Gerald Loeb Awards for Distinguished Business and Financial
Journalism. The awards, which are administered by the Anderson
School at the University of California at Los Angeles and honor
both print and broadcast media, were announced on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The staff of The New York Times won the award for beat reporting
on a deadline for the newspaper's coverage of the near-collapse of
Long-Term Capital Management in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   The award for commentary was given to Walter Mossberg of The
Wall Street Journal, for a series of ``Personal Technology''
columns. In the network and large-market television category, Mike
Wallace and Walt Bogdanich of the CBS program ``60 Minutes'' won
for their investigative piece on the international pharmaceutical
industry.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Shepard, editor in chief of Business Week magazine, was
awarded the Lifetime Achievement Award, which is given annually.
Sue Johnson, president of the G. and R. Loeb Foundation Inc., said
in a statement that Shepard had ``earned a reputation for editorial
integrity and independence.''
</P>
<P>
   Gerald Loeb established the awards in 1957; the Anderson School
has administered them since 1973.
</P>
<P>
   The awards included:
</P>
<P>
   Large newspaper category: Joel Rutchick for a series of articles
about the Cuyahoga Metropolitan Housing Authority in The Cleveland
Plain Dealer.
</P>
<P>
   Medium-sized newspaper category: Fred Schulte and Jenni Bergal
for ``Cosmetic Surgery: The Hidden Dangers'' in The Sun-Sentinel in
Fort Lauderdale, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Small newspaper category: Jennifer Hieger and Bill Heisel Jr.
for ``The Dairy Boom: Growth, Trouble and Transition'' in The
Yakima Herald-Republic in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Magazines: Shane Tritsch for ``Bull Marketing'' in Chicago
Magazine.
</P>
<P>
   Radio: Karen Tofte and team for ``The World Turned Upside Down''
on Minnesota Public Radio.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
