<SLUG> BC-MISSOURI-RIVERBOATS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GAMBLING PACE UNABATED AT RIVERBOAT CASINOS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICK ALM  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Kansas City's torrid gambling pace continued
for a second consecutive month in April, as gamblers set a record
for dollars left behind in riverboat casinos.
</P>
<P>
   The $42.8 million record probably won't stand for long, with the
approach of the summer tourist season. In addition, pending changes
in casino regulations later this year would make gambling in
Missouri easier and quicker.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Missouri Gaming Commission, combined April
gambling revenue at the four Kansas City area casinos edged past
the $42.4 million mark set in March. Revenue statewide topped $80
million in April.
</P>
<P>
   Harrah's North Kansas City Casino &AMP; Hotel led all Missouri
casinos with an April tally of $15.4 million, stretching its local
market lead over Station Casino Kansas City to almost 2.5
percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   Harrah's 1 percentage point increase in market share in April,
to 35.95 percent, came almost entirely at the expense of Station,
which fell back to 33.52 percent. Last fall, Station seized the top
spot for 30 days but couldn't keep up the pace in an expanding
market.
</P>
<P>
   Argosy Riverside Casino in April continued its reign as home of
the market's ``loosest slots.''
</P>
<P>
   Argosy's average jackpot payback rates to players have been
Kansas City's most generous for months in the most popular 5 cent,
25 cent and $1 denomination machines.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Gaming Commission meets today in Maryland
Heights, Mo., to consider abolishing the state's rules on two-hour
cruises and restricted boarding times.
</P>
<P>
   It also is expected to revisit whether to legalize blackjack
card-counting.
</P>
<P>
   If approved, those changes will not go into effect until this
fall, unless the commission acted under its emergency rule-making
procedure, which is not expected.
</P>
<P>
   The commission today also is scheduled to discuss an amendment
to the state's gambling law approved in the waning hours of the
1999 Missouri General Assembly.
</P>
<P>
   That three-word change could significantly speed up slot machine
play and, thus, players' average rate of loss.
</P>
<P>
   If signed by the governor, the change will allow players to
receive ``physical or electronic'' tokens when they first buy in to
play. Under current law, when cash is inserted into a slot machine,
the device discharges metal tokens that must be played by hand, one
at a time.
</P>
<P>
   Gambling experts routinely advise slot players to feed coins by
hand to slow down their play, and thus their rate of loss.
</P>
<P>
   Under the change, players' buy-in automatically would be
converted to electronic credits, which are the same as the jackpot
credits paid to players when they win. Electronic wagers can be
made as fast as players can punch the machines' keyboard buttons.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Ryan, executive director of the Missouri Riverboat Gaming
Association, disputes the notion that electronic tokens will hasten
play.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's strictly a customer-convenience factor as far as we're
concerned,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Ryan said the open-boarding issue was more acute in St. Louis.
Illinois lawmakers this week are taking steps toward abolishing
river-cruising requirements for floating casinos in that state,
including two on the Mississippi River near St. Louis. The change
would result in open boarding on the Illinois boats.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Taylor, executive director of the Missouri anti-gambling
group Casino Watch, said his organization had taken no position on
electronic tokens but had urged the commission to allow the General
Assembly next year to debate the open-boarding issue.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor suggested that lawmakers next year might challenge any
easing of boarding times allowed by the commission.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Mel Carnahan has until July 14 to sign or veto the gambling
bill.
</P>
<P>
   That legislation, House Bill 793, also:
</P>
<P>
   Stiffens penalties for underage gambling, including misdemeanor
convictions for those under 21.
</P>
<P>
   Extends riverboat gambling licenses from two to three years
between renewal hearings.
</P>
<P>
   Establishes regulatory guidelines for sweepstakes and raffle
gambling legalized by voters last fall.
</P>
<P>
   Clarifies that arcade games and other amusement devices that
award points and prizes valued under $250 shall not be regarded as
gambling.  &LR; brk:Open boarding  &LR; tx:The commission heard testimony in
Kansas City and St. Louis last month from casino executives,
security officers, players and others urging that gamblers be
permitted to enter casinos at any time. Only a handful opposed the
change.
</P>
<P>
   Most said open boarding would be more convenient to players and
make it easier for casino workers to check for underage, inebriated
or compulsive gamblers.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor and others argued that the change represented one more
step in a continuing campaign by casino operators to remove
restrictions placed on the industry when voters approved riverboat
gambling in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Electronic scanner cards, already in use statewide, would
continue to monitor adherence to the state's $500 loss-limit rule.
 &LR; brk:Counting cards  &LR; tx:Blackjack card-counters have sought for
three years to legally ply their trade in Missouri.
</P>
<P>
   Casino operators routinely bar known or suspected card-counters
from their tables, saying their systems for mentally keeping tabs
of high and low cards played gives them an unfair advantage. Kansas
Citian Robert Cherry filed a formal objection to the practice in
1996 after he was barred from the tables at Harrah's North Kansas
City Casino &AMP; Hotel.
</P>
<P>
   The commission late in 1997 voted 2-1 to legalize counting, but
three votes were needed for passage. Two commissioners were absent
that day, and the window for making rules closed shortly
thereafter.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
