<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-25 22:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1087 &Cx1f; kan-z
r p &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GORE-VALUES-KAN &LR;      05-25 0956
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-VALUES-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE PREACHES VALUES _ AND ASHCROFT'S FOE CRINGES DURING SERMON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID GOLDSTEIN  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Vice President Al Gore certainly hoped that the
speech he gave Monday about values would boost his presidential
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   But whatever good he did for himself, he also tossed a political
bouquet to Missouri's Sen. John Ashcroft, who faces a battle for
re-election against a Gore ally, Missouri Gov. Mel Carnahan.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking to the Salvation Army in Atlanta, the vice president
trumpeted the use of faith-based groups to help the government
solve social problems.
</P>
<P>
   He endorsed a ``little-known provision'' in the 1996
welfare-reform law signed by President Clinton, known as
``charitable choice.''
</P>
<P>
   The provision allows religious organizations to use government
money to provide social services as long as they do not proselytize
and a secular alternative is available. Many see that as a
violating the separation of church and state.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whether they are religious or not, most Americans are hungry
for a deeper connection between politics and moral values; many
would say `spiritual values,' '' Gore said.
</P>
<P>
   The author of charitable choice, however, was Ashcroft, a
Republican. And he was quick Tuesday to seize the political
opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   Noting the ``growing bipartisan support,'' Ashcroft proposed
legislation that would extend charitable choice to federally funded
social services across the board.
</P>
<P>
   The political fallout from Gore's speech for Carnahan, however,
may not be so inviting. Gore's blessing of a major Ashcroft
initiative could muddy the governor's ability to continue to paint
the senator as too conservative for Missouri.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's having the mantle of the vice president and a Democratic
administration given to John Ashcroft in what promises to be a very
difficult and tough re-election effort,'' said Ralph Reed, a
Republican strategist and occasional Ashcroft adviser.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're certainly not doing any favors for Governor Carnahan
by doing this, or at least by not giving him an opportunity to
share in it, or maybe get ahead of it a little.''
</P>
<P>
   Roy Temple, a political adviser to Carnahan, downplayed the
significance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not necessarily shocked,'' he said. ``Of all the ideas
Ashcroft has proposed, he had one good idea from Gore's
perspective.''
</P>
<P>
   Temple added, however, that it would have been nice to have been
warned. he said.
</P>
<P>
   Carnahan's office apparently called the White House on Tuesday
to discuss the vice president's speech. And the Gore campaign tried
to point up the differences it had with Ashcroft, one of the early
critics of the president in the Monica Lewinsky scandal.
</P>
<P>
   Inside political circles, the view among both Democrats and
Republicans was that the Gore campaign, which had been preparing
the values speech for several weeks, had slipped up by not giving
Carnahan an early warning.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the governor's record as a strong, longtime supporter of
the Clinton administration, Missouri is often a key battleground
state in presidential politics.
</P>
<P>
   The episode adds to the impression that the Gore campaign, which
has been traveling a much smoother road lately after a rocky patch,
is still not yet a finely tuned political machine. But it also
foreshadows the kind of tensions in the Democratic Party that lie
in wait when the 2000 campaign is fully engaged.
</P>
<P>
   Many Democrats still resent the Clinton White House for
embracing welfare reform and a balanced budget before the 1996
presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   While no Democrat would publicly express that view, Reed, who is
advising Texas Gov. George W. Bush's GOP presidential campaign,
summed it up when he said: ``It's the prototypical Clinton-Gore
tactic _ whatever they have to do to advance their message without
regard to how it might impact the rest of the party.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore's speech to the Salvation Army was an attempt to take the
lead in the political debate over violence and culture. Amid the
national soul-searching after two recent high school shootings,
presidential hopefuls are all trying to give voice to the public
mood.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, a Baptist who spent a year in divinity school, has been
outspoken since the murders of 14 students in Littleton, Colo., on
stricter access to guns, the need for more character education and
parental involvement. But the Atlanta speech, in which he talked
about his own religious convictions, was an attempt to weave the
threads of faith, family and government into a common strand.
</P>
<P>
   By saying, ``our severest challenges are spiritual, not
material,'' Gore waded into uncharted territory as far as Democrats
are concerned. Religion and politics has long been a province
inhabited largely by Republicans. Democrats stayed away because any
discussion of ``values'' evoked connections to the religious right
wing.
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of Littleton, however, values and their place in
society are emerging as a political issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``What Gore has done is try and say values are critical to him
personally,'' said Mark Mellman, a Democratic pollster and Gore
adviser.
</P>
<P>
   Aides said Gore's support of faith-based programs is not new. He
dealt with them in 1997 when he worked with welfare-to-work groups.
Other presidential contenders, including Democrat Bill Bradley and
Bush embrace them, also.
</P>
<P>
   And now the issue of religion's role in social policy could be
felt in the Missouri Senate contest, which, apart from a possible
race in New York by first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton, is
considered one of the hottest in the country. As for Ashcroft's
reaction to Gore's speech?
</P>
<P>
   Said spokesman Steve Hilton: ``He was just delighted.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
