<SLUG> BC-JESSE-JAMES-GUNS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO GUNS AT JESSE JAMES MUSEUM TOO NEW TO HAVE BEEN OUTLAW'S 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY BERRIOS  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ There's been a goof involving America's most
famous gunslinger.
</P>
<P>
   Two guns that have been touted by the Jesse James Farm and
Museum for 11 years as the legendary outlaw's weapons _ including a
Colt .45 revolver James was supposedly wore right before he was
killed _ are not the real things.
</P>
<P>
   The two guns actually were made /{after/} James was shot in the
back of the head by Robert Ford in St. Joseph in 1882.
</P>
<P>
   The archival error was discovered after a tourist from England
asked an innocuous question about the rifle. That question prompted
Elizabeth Gilliam Beckett, the director of the Kearney museum, to
review acquisition records.
</P>
<P>
   She noticed the revolver and the Winchester rifle, which the
museum /{thought/} James used in a train robbery, did not have
authenticity documents.
</P>
<P>
   Using serial numbers to research the guns' lineage, Gilliam
Beckett discovered the revolver was made in 1883 and the rifle was
made in 1890.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was shocked and surprised,'' she said Tuesday. ``The public
needed to know these weren't Jesse's guns.''
</P>
<P>
   The two guns were donated to the museum in 1988 by Ethel Rose
Owens, a deceased granddaughter of James, and James R. Ross, James'
great-grandson.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am utterly mystified,'' Ross said Tuesday. Ross said he
remembers James' son, Jesse Jr., shooting the weapons and reveling
about their heritage.
</P>
<P>
   John Hartman, Clay County's director of parks, recreation and
historic sites, said an archival search should have been done when
the guns were donated. But, he added, it's not unusual for a museum
to accept items on good faith based on oral history.
</P>
<P>
   Gilliam Beckett said according to the James family history, both
guns were used in ``Under the Black Flag,'' a 1921 film about a
James robbery that starred Jesse Jr.
</P>
<P>
   Ross said he thinks the only time the guns were out of the
family's possession was during that filming.
</P>
<P>
   When asked whether he thought the guns might have been switched,
Ross said, ``I don't know of any other explanation.''
</P>
<P>
   Hartman said the museum is researching other artifacts. So far,
no other discrepancies have been found.
</P>
<P>
   There are five weapons at the museum, including the revolver and
rifle, which have remained on display.
</P>
<P>
   Gilliam Beckett said two guns belonged to the James gang.
</P>
<P>
   The only gun the museum now believes was Jesse James' is a
shotgun, made by a London company that was in business between 1876
and 1879, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Gilliam Beckett said most guns used by Jesse James are now owned
by collectors. The museum does not buy its artifacts; it relies on
donations.
</P>
<P>
   Hartman said these historical errors are rare.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it is a real demonstration of their professionalism
that they caught this one,'' Hartman said. ``You try to be accurate
to the best of your ability.''
</P>
<P>
   This isn't the first time a gun linked to the notorious bank
robber has been questioned.
</P>
<P>
   In 1993, Jesse James scholars and enthusiasts debated whether a
.44-caliber Smith &AMP; Wesson sold at an auction in England was indeed
the weapon Bob Ford used to murder James.
</P>
<P>
   But perhaps the ultimate debate over authenticity involved Jesse
James himself.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, a team of scientists conducted DNA testing on remains
exhumed from James' Kearney grave.
</P>
<P>
   Their conclusion? It was Jesse James.
</P>
</TEXT>
