u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-POLICE-BRUTALITY-N     05-25 1058
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-POLICE-BRUTALITY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. TO HEAR COMPLAINTS ABOUT POLICE 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By KEVIN FLYNN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The U.S. Civil Rights Commission on Wednesday will
focus a national spotlight on police practices here by holding a
public hearing on police treatment of minority groups in a city
still reeling from a white officer's admission that he tortured a
black man in a station house restroom.
</P>
<P>
   The panel is preparing to stay late into the night to allow what
it expects might be hundreds of black and Hispanic people to
describe their own encounters with the police, said commission
chairwoman Mary Frances Berry.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will stay there as long as there are people who want to be
heard from,'' Ms. Berry said. ``Part of our responsibility is to be
a safety valve for people who have not been heard from.''
</P>
<P>
   The daylong hearing at a Manhattan hotel, at which Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani and Police Commissioner Howard Safir are also scheduled to
testify, was prompted by the police shooting of Amadou Diallo and
by longstanding complaints that the city's largely white police
force often ignores the civil rights of citizens, especially
members of minority groups.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to try to get attention for cases where the police
officers have done things and they get away with it and no one is
held accountable,'' said Iris Baez, who fought until she secured a
federal civil rights conviction against a police officer who killed
her son, Anthony, in 1994. ``I want the commission to take this
very seriously because no one is doing their job,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Commission officials said that in addition to hearing sworn
testimony from witnesses, the panel would review thousands of
police documents for evidence that disproportionate numbers of
black and Hispanic people are searched, and for signs of lapses in
police sensitivity training, discrimination in hiring and promotion
as well as gaps in the current oversight of officers who abuse
their powers.
</P>
<P>
   The commission is a fact-finding, not a prosecuting agency, and
by the fall, Ms. Berry said, it hopes to have prepared a report for
the president and Congress that will include recommendations on how
the New York police might repair their strained relations with
members of minorities.
</P>
<P>
   The hearing, at the Doubletree Guest Suites, on Broadway near
West 47th Street, could not come at a more contentious time. Only
yesterday, Officer Justin A. Volpe pleaded guilty to federal
charges that he violated the civil rights of a Haitian immigrant,
Abner Louima, by sodomizing him with a stick in a station house
restroom. Just weeks ago, four white officers were charged with
second-degree murder in the death of Diallo, an unarmed black man
who was fired upon 41 times.
</P>
<P>
   Those incidents and others have led to investigations of police
conduct by state Attorney General Eliot Spitzer, the City Council
and federal prosecutors in Manhattan and Brooklyn. Giuliani, who is
scheduled to be the lead witness in an hour's appearance, has
argued that so much scrutiny is far out of proportion with what he
describes as isolated problems within the police force.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have the most restrained Police Department of any in the
United States,'' the mayor said Wednesday, adding nonetheless that
he welcomed the chance to testify. ``This is an opportunity for
both the commissioner and for me to make a much more complete and
full picture, rather than the sometimes abbreviated picture that is
presented.''
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani's position as he approaches his appearance resembles
that of one of his predecessors, Ed Koch, who testified 16 years
ago before a congressional committee investigating possible police
abuses in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Among those also scheduled to testify are the Rev. Al Sharpton;
the executive director of the New York Civil Liberties Union,
Norman Siegel; the Rev. Calvin Butts, pastor of the Abyssinian
Baptist Church in Harlem, and Public Advocate Mark Green.
</P>
<P>
   Safir will testify late in the morning, in a group with the
chairman of the Civilian Complaint Review Board, the state's
criminal justice coordinator and the president of the Patrolmen's
Benevolent Association. The decision to hear Safir with other
witnesses disappointed police officials, who had hoped to make a
full presentation on the department's enhanced recruiting efforts
and other innovations.
</P>
<P>
   Marilyn Mode, a police spokeswoman, said: ``Certainly the
commissioner would have preferred to spend more time and would have
preferred to have an opportunity to discuss what we at the Police
Department have been doing, and to do it one on one with the
commission. But he understands their time constraints.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Berry said she had been surprised by how much jockeying for
exposure there had been. ``Usually people will argue that they
can't be on at a time because they have other things to do,'' she
said, ``not because they are worried about what kind of stage they
are going to be on.'' She warned that witnesses should not try ``to
make speeches about how great they are,'' adding, ``We will bring
them up short if anyone tries to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Members of the general public are to begin testifying at 6 p.m.
after the officials have left the hearing, which will be held in
the hotel's sixth-floor ballroom.
</P>
<P>
   The scope of the commission's inquiry in New York is evident in
the broad nature of its subpoenas, which have requested hiring
statistics, training materials and all disciplinary proceedings,
complaints of abuse and discrimination, and civil suits filed
against officers since 1993.
</P>
<P>
   The eight-member commission, an independent, bipartisan panel
established by the Civil Rights Act of 1957, voted 3-2 in March to
investigate the police practices in New York. Earlier this month,
the commission released its review of police operations in Los
Angeles, where it began a long-term review in 1993, two years after
the police beating of Rodney King.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Berry said the commission would likely study a second city,
possibly Washington, where there is considerable concern about the
frequency of police gunfire. She also said the panel had hoped
that, by scheduling its New York hearing in the late spring well
after the Diallo shooting, the controversy over police conduct
might have died down a bit. ``But I guess not,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
