<SLUG> BC-DRESSCODE-FLAP-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCHOOL'S GRADUATION DRESS CODE CHAFES SOME PARENTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATT STEARNS and DONALD BRADLEY  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Kevin Cerveny looked pretty spiffy. Just not
spiffy enough to get into his big sister Patricia's graduation from
Raytown High School on Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Cerveny's short-sleeve plaid dress shirt, pressed and pleated
navy-blue shorts and brown bucks didn't meet the newly imposed
graduation dress code in the Raytown School District.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what he wears to school,'' said his exasperated mother,
Geralyn Cerveny. ``He's 12 years old. He looks fine.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, clearly printed on the back of the graduation ticket were
the rules. Among them, no shorts. So Cerveny was hustled home
before the ceremony to put on some pants. About 10 others found
themselves in the same predicament.
</P>
<P>
   District officials said the dress code was not meant to torture
12-year-olds. They wanted to restore some decorum to graduation
ceremonies, which in recent years had become more rowdy at Raytown
schools and elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   The code was agreed to months ago by a special graduation
committee of seniors, parents and staff.
</P>
<P>
   Few people at the First Baptist Church of Raytown, where
graduation ceremonies were held Monday and Tuesday night, seemed to
mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``There needs to be a little dignity and honor injected into the
ceremony,'' said Randy Frymire, whose son Nathan was among the 266
graduates Tuesday night. ``If they're not dressed appropriately,
they feel they can act inappropriately.''
</P>
<P>
   Graduating senior Mike Shaw hoped the dress code would curb bad
behavior.
</P>
<P>
   ``In past years, they've had people bring in beach balls and air
horns,'' he said. ``That's just not showing respect to the people
who are graduating.''
</P>
<P>
   Geralyn Cerveny said she understood respect. But, she said, the
invitation spelled out rules for men and women _ not for kids.
</P>
<P>
   She was especially upset that a couple of toddlers had been
allowed in wearing shorts and sandals while Kevin was turned away.
Cerveny said she would write a letter to district officials
complaining about the code's enforcement.
</P>
<P>
   School district spokeswoman Shirley Wurth conceded that the new
system wasn't perfect, and would be evaluated before next year.
Still, she said those who were turned away Tuesday seemed to
understand and simply went home to change.
</P>
<P>
   That staid response differed mightily from Monday night's drama
during Raytown South High School's graduation ceremony, when an
incident helped ignite public controversy over the new dress code.
</P>
<P>
   A man in blue jeans didn't like being told he couldn't get in
because his outfit didn't fit the rules. He complained. He cursed _
loudly, according to witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   Officials escorted him out the door. A handful of other guests
also were turned away because their T-shirts, shorts or athletic
shoes didn't comply. Some returned after changing clothes.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday morning, phones were ringing at the district's
central office when employees arrived at work.
</P>
<P>
   /{How in the world,/} some callers wondered, /{could the
district prevent parents from attending graduation just because of
the clothes they wore?/}
</P>
<P>
   The answer: To cut down on hooting, outbursts and the
aforementioned noisemakers and beach balls.
</P>
<P>
   Other districts have dealt with the issue, too _ just not in the
same manner as Raytown.
</P>
<P>
   In the mid-1990s, graduations in the Kansas City School District
were marred by raucous crowds and over-zealous family members.
Student speeches and instrumental performances were drowned out,
and one relative of a graduate was even arrested.
</P>
<P>
   So in 1996, the Kansas City district took some steps to make
sure such chaos would never happen again.
</P>
<P>
   To control disruptions, the district opted to hold smaller
ceremonies on school grounds, issued admission tickets to some
celebrations and provided more security.
</P>
<P>
   But the district does not impose a dress code on the family
members and well-wishers of its high school graduates.
</P>
<P>
   Administrators do, however, expect proper decorum.
</P>
<P>
   ``We communicate to the guests that they should act and dress in
a dignified manner that would be respectful of all the graduates,''
said district spokeswoman Roxane Johnson. ``Because they've worked
really hard for this honor and this day.''
</P>
<P>
   Several districts require seniors to wear something nice under
those caps and gowns, but Raytown may be the first to go to a dress
code for those attending the ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   The Olathe, Shawnee Mission, Lee's Summit, Park Hill, North
Kansas City, Hickman Mills and Kansas City, Kan., districts have no
dress codes for graduation guests.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it's my place to tell adults how to dress,''
said Hickman Mills High School Principal Charles Greene.
</P>
<P>
   At Oak Park High School in the North Kansas City School
District, commencements have a history of seniors bouncing beach
balls through the air during the reading of students' names.
</P>
<P>
   ``I try to express to them it's both a celebration and a
ceremony,'' Principal Benny Cain said. ``After all the names are
read, then it's time to celebrate.''
</P>
<P>
   As far as noisy disruptions, Shawnee Mission principals ask
parents before graduation each year to treat the occasion with
dignity, spokesperson Shelley Bartkoski.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a really special ceremony,'' Bartkoski said. ``They want
to make it special for the graduates.''
</P>
<P>
   That is the real purpose behind Raytown's dress code, Watkins
said. When discussing how to calm down graduations, a senior on the
committee said: ``We act better when we dress up.''
</P>
<P>
   The 30-member graduation committee also limited the number of
guests per graduate.
</P>
<P>
   Watkins said three letters had been sent home with graduates
explaining the new rules. The dress code was clearly spelled out on
the ticket to the ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unless you were blind, you knew what was expected,'' said
Sharon Logue, a parent who attended the Raytown South's ceremony
Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   Dick Kurtenbach, executive director of the American Civil
Liberties Union of Kansas and Western Missouri, thought officials
may have overreacted to those who didn't meet the school district's
dress code.
</P>
<P>
   ``They should have expected that some folks wouldn't abide by
it, and try to make some accommodation,'' he said. ``Their sons and
daughters only graduate once, and to bar them from the ceremony
seems pretty drastic.''
</P>
<P>
   But guests who made a scene at the door objecting to the dress
requirement disturbed Logue.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it was a defiance of rules and they set a very poor
example for our children,'' Logue said.
</P>
<P>
   Logue, a 1966 graduate of Raytown South, remembers another age _
when people dressed up for graduation because it was a special
night and deserved respect.
</P>
<P>
   Then came the years of shorts, tank tops and ball caps. Along
with the casual dress came noise and rowdiness.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, we're trying to get back to where we should have been all
along,'' Logue said.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Schmiedeler, father of a graduate, took an opposing
view.
</P>
<P>
   ``How can that school district dictate what adults should wear
to a public event?'' Schmiedeler asked. ``What if someone can't
afford nice dress clothes?
</P>
<P>
   ``People wait their kid's whole life to go to graduation and I
don't think it's fair to be turned away because of the clothes they
wear.''
</P>
<P>
   Watkins sees the man's point. He points out, though, that these
days blue jeans and other casual clothes often cost more than dress
wear.
</P>
<P>
   He also emphasized that the man escorted from the Raytown South
ceremony wasn't ushered out because of his clothes. The man was
hostile and verbally abusive, Watkins said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't the way he was dressed. It was the way he acted.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
