<SLUG> BC-AMTRAK-FATALITY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOMAN AND 3 CHILDREN ARE KILLED BY AN AMTRAK TRAIN 
</HEADLINE>
  (dal) 
 By PAUL ZIELBAUER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   FAIRFIELD, Conn. _ A woman and three of her four young sons were
killed early Tuesday morning when they were hit by an Amtrak train
as the woman crossed the tracks in a last-second attempt to rescue
one of the children from the locomotive's path, the State Police
said.
</P>
<P>
   One of the boys who was struck survived, but remained
unconscious and was in gravely critical condition at Bridgeport
Hospital Tuesday night after surgery to repair a deep head wound
and several bone fractures, hospital officials said. The boy, whom
police identified as Angel Gabriel Urgiles Toledo, 6, also
underwent emergency surgery to amputate what remained of his left
leg.
</P>
<P>
   Late Tuesday, police investigators were still trying to
determine why the woman, an Ecuadorean immigrant in in her 40s, was
walking with her four sons along a series of four parallel train
tracks about 2:20 a.m. The woman and the boys, ages 3, 6, 10 and
12, had been living for the past week at Families-In-Transition, an
emergency shelter operated by the YMCA in Bridgeport, police said.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference, Chief James O'Donnell of the Connecticut
State Police said investigators would not be able to identify the
victims until the bodies are examined by state's medical rxaminer's
office.
</P>
<P>
   The woman's husband, identified by the Ecuadorean Consulate in
New York City as Carlos Urgiles, had returned to Ecuador more than
a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   O'Donnell offered a rough explanation of how the woman and her
four sons were struck by the electrically powered train, an Amtrak
Twilight Shoreliner carrying 210 people between Boston and Newport
News, Va.
</P>
<P>
   He said the woman and three of her four sons were walking on one
side of Track 3, the northernmost of the four tracks just west of
Fairfield's rail station. A fourth boy was apparently walking on
the other side of Track 3, the police said, when the train
approached and the locomotive's engineer pulled on the horn and
engaged the emergency brake.
</P>
<P>
   According to police interviews with the engineer, a 20-year
veteran operator for Amtrak and Conrail, the woman heard the
train's horn and, her three other children in tow, tried to run
over Track 3 to retrieve her fourth child. The child ran toward her
onto Track 3. The train struck all five family members as they
huddled on the track, O'Donnell said.
</P>
<P>
   Amtrak officials did not know how fast the train was moving at
the time of the crash, but said locomotives are allowed a top speed
of 70 miles per hour. At that speed, a train takes from one to two
miles to grind to a halt, even with the emergency brake employed.
``There was nothing, absolutely nothing, the engineer could have
done,'' said Kenneth J. Gambardella, an investigator with the
Connecticut Department of Transportation.
</P>
<P>
   The engineer was so distraught after the accident that
paramedics took him to Bridgeport Hospital, along with the train's
conductor, to be treated for shock. Both men were later released,
police said.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
