<SLUG> BC-WRESTLER-FALL-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAMILY OF WRESTLER KILLED IN FALL CRITICIZES STUNT ORGANIZERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RUTH E. IGOE  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Days after their youngest son plunged to his
death in Kemper Arena, Canada's first family of professional
wrestling assailed a sport they think is relying on
ever-more-dangerous stunts for increased TV ratings and revenues.
</P>
<P>
   Family members said what was once a small-time regional show
circuit has become dominated by two national organizations, the
World Wrestling Federation and World Championship Wrestling, which
emphasize over-the-top theatrics that put wrestlers at risk.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a campaign to out-do each other,'' said Smith Hart,
50, said Tuesday from the family home in Calgary, Alberta. ``There
is no respect for the sport anymore. There used to be (wrestling)
heroes for children. I don't see any heroes.''
</P>
<P>
   During a Sunday WWF show dubbed ``Over the Edge,'' Hart's
brother, Owen Hart, fell from a 90-foot-high catwalk preparing for
a aerial descent into the ring.
</P>
<P>
   All seven Hart boys followed their father Stu, a former Olympic
wrestler, into the sport as amateurs and professionals. Owen Hart,
34, was the youngest member of the prominent family. On Sunday,
Owen Hart _ a WWF wrestler known as the ``Blue Blazer'' _ bled to
death internally from blunt chest trauma after he plunged into the
ring.
</P>
<P>
   His brother Bret Hart is a star known as ``The Hitman'' on the
rival World Championship Wrestling circuit.
</P>
<P>
   Officials from both the WWF and the WCW declined to respond to
the family's criticism.
</P>
<P>
   Stu Hart, 84, who promoted the sport for years after his own
wrestling career ended, also thinks his son was exposed to
unnecessary risks. He said his youngest son had harbored doubts
about being lowered by a cable into the ring during Sunday's show.
But, Stu Hart said, someone persuaded him to do it, anyway.
</P>
<P>
   ``They put you into compromising positions where they let you
know you have no choice,'' he said. ``They should make sure
everything is safe and that they have good equipment.''
</P>
<P>
   In recent days, WWF President Vince McMahon has been quoted as
saying that federation wrestlers would stop performing the aerial
move that killed Owen Hart. But on Tuesday, WWF Publicity Vice
President Jim Byrne said he was not sure exactly which stunts would
be prohibited.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's being evaluated right now,'' he said. McMahon was
unavailable for further comment.
</P>
<P>
   At World Championship Wrestling, a team of professional stunt
coordinators carefully choreographs each move, said spokesman Alan
Sharp. An aerial descent, like the one Owen Hart was attempting
Sunday, is the signature entrance for a WCW wrestler dubbed
``Sting.''
</P>
<P>
   Kansas City police are investigating what might have gone wrong
Sunday night. A leading theory, police have said, is that Owen Hart
lost his balance while preparing for his drop and somehow activated
a quick-release that detached his harness from the cable. Police
plan to perform strength testing on the equipment he was wearing,
said Capt. Jerry Gallagher.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at the Occupational Safety and Health Administration
also are investigating whether they might have jurisdiction in the
case.
</P>
<P>
   It is only in recent years, the Harts said, that professional
wrestling has grown into the often-outlandish sport that it is
today.
</P>
<P>
   A few years ago, most everyone had a background in either
wrestling or other sports, Smith Hart said. Today, he said, that
isn't always the case.
</P>
<P>
   WWF and WCW ``are starting to train some of their own guys
now,'' Smith Hart said. ``There is a lot lacking there. They are
not very good wrestlers. They do more crazy things and there are
more injuries.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith Hart remembers when professional wrestling was more like
old silent movies: melodramatic expressions, wide-sweeping
movements, creative plots involving heroes and villains. Today, he
said, the outfits are wilder, the plots more violent, the
characters brasher.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's far-fetched, ludicrous storytelling,'' he said. ``I don't
watch it anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, there are now some Kansas Citians who have abandoned
the sport after Sunday's incident. Kevin Brice of Blue Springs used
to watch what he thought were ``lighthearted'' shows with his
10-year-old daughter, Kelly. But after attending Sunday's WWF
event, which continued after Owen Hart was taken from the ring,
Brice has vowed never to watch professional wresting again.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was human sacrifice,'' he said about Owen Hart's death.
``It turned out to be all about the bucks.''
 &LR; tag1:To reach Ruth E. Igoe, call {(816) 234-4376} or send e-mail
to {rigoe &LR; kcstar.com} &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
