<SLUG> BC-FORD-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORD TO BUILD LUXURY PICKUP AT PLANT IN KANSAS CITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RANDOLPH HEASTER  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ The Ford Motor Co. today is expected to
announce today that a new ``luxury pickup'' will be built at its
Claycomo plant, marking the third new product planned for the
facility.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said Ford planned to unveil the Lincoln Blackwood,
being billed as a hybrid of a luxury sport-utility vehicle and a
pickup truck that could sell for more than $40,000.
</P>
<P>
   Ford has scheduled a news conference at the Westin Crown Center
hotel for this afternoon. Missouri Gov. Mel Carnahan is expected to
attend.
</P>
<P>
   This would be Ford's third announcement within a year regarding
a new vehicle to be built at Claycomo. The plant employs nearly
5,000 hourly and salaried workers, making it Ford's biggest
factory, in terms of workers, in North America.
</P>
<P>
   Local union officials said several hundred jobs could be added
at Claycomo as a result of the new products.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the changes and new products coming up are definitely good
for us,'' said Jerry Kline, president of United Auto Workers Local
249.
</P>
<P>
   But Ford spokesman Mike Vaughn disputed the jobs claim.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any net gain (in jobs) would be minimal,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the automaker said it would begin building a compact
sport-utility vehicle there to replace the Ford Contour and Mercury
Mystique cars. Production of the SUV is expected to begin next
year. In addition, Ford will add to Claycomo's F-series truck line
the F-150 SuperCrew, a four-door pickup with a bigger back seat.
</P>
<P>
   The Claycomo plant is undergoing extensive renovations and an
expansion that will add at least 122,000 square feet to produce the
sport-utility vehicle. Some construction also is being done to
accommodate the F-150 SuperCrew and apparently the Blackwood.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Blackwood will be built on the same basic platform as the
SuperCrew,'' said Michael Robinet, director of forecast services
for CSM Worldwide, an automotive consulting firm in Farmington
Hills, Mich. ``So we think it'll be built in Kansas City.''
</P>
<P>
   Ford unveiled a concept Blackwood in December at the Los Angeles
International Auto Show. The four-door, four-passenger vehicle is
based on the design of the Lincoln Navigator luxury sport-utility
vehicle but adds an enclosed, wood-paneled box similar to a truck
bed.
</P>
<P>
   The truck would come only in black. The exterior trunk area
would be covered with more than 20 square feet of wood sealed in a
clear epoxy, recalling the ``woody'' look of the 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   The hard top of the enclosed trunk would open hydraulically to a
45-degree angle, exposing an aluminum-finished interior. A global
positioning system is integrated into the center console. The four
bucket seats will be trimmed in leather.
</P>
<P>
   ``It'll be the ultimate luxury pickup available on the market,''
Robinet said. He expects the Blackwood to sell for more than
$40,000.
</P>
<P>
   Wes Brown, an analyst with Nextrend, a marketing research firm
in Thousand Oaks, Calif., estimates that Ford's Lincoln Mercury
division will sell about 5,500 Blackwoods in 2000 and as many as
8,500 in 2003.
</P>
<P>
   Ford's Vaughn declined to comment on speculation about today's
product announcement.
</P>
<P>
   Reports last year indicated that Ford was spending up to $750
million on construction at Claycomo in preparation for the new
vehicles. A state enterprise zone was expanded to extend a variety
of tax incentives for the project.
</P>
<P>
   Union officials said more construction could keep the plant
closed longer than the traditional two weeks this summer for model
changeovers.
Bloomberg News contributed to this report
</P>
</TEXT>
