A1244 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-REDS-D0DGERS-COX     05-25 0533
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-REDS-D0DGERS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Reds down Dodgers 3-2
 &HT;    By Marc Katz
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CINCINNATI _ Kevin Brown wore a commemorative Sandy Koufax patch
on the left sleeve of his Los Angeles Dodgers uniform and pitched
like Koufax most of the game.
</P>
<P>
   That wasn't quite good enough, especially since Steve Parris of
the Cincinnati Reds was also pitching like Koufax. And the Dodgers
defense let Brown down.
</P>
<P>
   It all led to a 3-2 Reds' win in front of 18,203 at Cinergy
Field on Tuesday night, extending Cincinnati's winning streak to
three games. The Reds have won eight of their last nine.
</P>
<P>
   None of it could have happened without some faulty Los Angeles
fielding plays, despite the fact Brown struck out a career-high 12.
</P>
<P>
   When Barry Larkin struck out to seemingly end the fourth, he
made it to first on catcher Todd Hundley's passed ball. Hundley
magnified the mistake by throwing the ball away trying to get
Larkin at first. Dmitri Young, who had walked, took third on the
error.
</P>
<P>
   Larkin then stole second without a throw, and would have been
out there had first baseman Eric Karros come up with Michael
Tucker's grounder that sliced under his glove. It was ruled a hit
as two runs scored, giving the Reds a 2-1 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Thus Brown _ the costliest player in baseball with a 7-year,
$105 million contract that pays him more per game than Parris makes
this season _ trailed despite striking out six, walking one and
allowing only a third-inning double by Larkin prior to Tucker's
hit.
</P>
<P>
   The Reds tacked on another run when Mark Lewis and Eddie
Taubensee led the fifth with back-to-back doubles.
</P>
<P>
   Brown is not used to such abuse, especially against the Reds. He
entered the game 6-0 with a 1.58 ERA against Cincinnati. He was 5-2
with a 2.54 ERA this season, and his ERA was not hurt in this game.
The two runs allowed in the fourth were both unearned.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile Parris _ who is playing for $275,000 this season _ was
more than a match for Brown. Although Devon White led off the game
with a single and Gary Sheffield led the fourth with his 10th
homer, Parris made a nearly spotless appearance in only his third
start of the season. He allowed a second hit in the fourth _ a
single _ and another single in the fifth. In the sixth, he walked
Sheffield.
</P>
<P>
   In the seventh, Parris gave up an infield hit to Adrian Beltre.
</P>
<P>
   Offensively, that was it for the Dodgers, and it for Parris, who
completed seven innings with nine strikeouts and five hits. He
walked just one. Danny Graves came on to start the eighth.
</P>
<P>
   Graves was greeted by a Sheffield single, but got Raul Mondesi
and Hundley to fly to center before he caught a line drive to the
mound by Eric Karros.
</P>
<P>
   Graves was not so lucky in the ninth. Beltre was out on a
sensational play by second baseman Pokey Reese, who flagged a
bouncer into the hole and threw to Graves for an out.
</P>
<P>
   Then Tripp Cromer homered, his second of the season.
</P>
<P>
   The next two Dodgers were retired in order as Graves registered
his team-leading sixth save.
</P>
<P>
   Marc Katz writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
