<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-KEISSER-COLUMN-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NFL PUTS STING ON L.A.
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB KEISSER   
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   This is a setup, a sting worthy of Redford and Newman, a superb
example of the long con. The NFL is starring in a remake of ``The
Grifters,'' and Los Angeles is its mark.
</P>
<P>
   League owners are meeting in Atlanta and receiving an update on
stadium designs and business plans from the two groups seeking an
expansion franchise in Los Angeles, Michael Ovitz and the Eli
Broad/Ed Roski team.
</P>
<P>
   Befitting his background in entertainment, Ovitz arranged a
sneak preview of his Coliseum vision for several owners before the
meetings began, and it elicited more ohhs and ahhs than the new
Star Wars film. Carolina owner Jerry Richardson, head of the
expansion committee, called it ``extraordinary.''
</P>
<P>
   Other words also apply.
</P>
<P>
   What the NFL ostensibly is doing is putting Los Angeles and its
political leaders against the wall in search of the league's
favorite kind of money, public money.
</P>
<P>
   If the league leaves Atlanta with a mandate or leaning in favor
of the Ovitz plan, and every indication is it will, state and city
officials will have to deal with a plan that calls for $225 million
in public money to build several parking garages in Exposition
Park.
</P>
<P>
   This is a classic scam. For three years, L.A. City Councilman
Mark Ridley-Thomas and Kings owner Ed Roski carried the Coliseum's
flag and worked diligently on a proposal that could bring football
back to L.A. at a reasonable cost. Roski and Broad were prepared to
pay for most everything, with a minimal $40 million public
investment of new money via the sale of bonds.
</P>
<P>
   But after signing off on the Coliseum, seemingly giving the
councilman his victory, the NFL retained the right to select a
developer and owner rather than accept the Roski/Broad proposal
that had hard financial commitments with government.
</P>
<P>
   That day, Ovitz was asked when he would meet with city and state
officials about his Coliseum plans. ``That's a good question,'' he
said. ``I haven't really thought about it yet.''
</P>
<P>
   He still hasn't. There hasn't been any discussion, much less an
agreement, between Ovitz and any of the groups involved. They
include: the Coliseum Commission, which has a lease for the stadium
through 2005; the state, which owns the land; civic groups involved
in the overall downtown makeover; several conservancies, including
one that protects the Coliseum; the federal Department of the
Interior; the museums in Exposition Park; and USC.
</P>
<P>
   One presumes this is the way the NFL wanted it. Richardson,
talking about the Ovitz proposal earlier this week, said he expects
L.A. to make whatever adjustments it needs to consider Ovitz's
plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``My assumption is they will be given a fair hearing to whatever
the ruling bodies are, particularly if it enhances that park in a
significant way,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   So clearly, if the deal falls apart, it will do so on the head
of civic leaders who couldn't make it work to the league's
satisfaction.
</P>
<P>
   It certainly won't fall on the league, which can say it gave
L.A. a conditional franchise and six months to make it happen. The
league can point to other cities and their investments in new
stadia Pittsburgh ($147 million), Cleveland ($166 million), Detroit
($180 million), Nashville ($292 million), Seattle ($300 million),
Cincinnati ($404 million) and say L.A. is getting off cheap for
parking garages that will also benefit its museums.
</P>
<P>
   It certainly won't fall on owner Ovitz, who came up with a
genius stadium and park vision and has, since the beginning, said
``I will do whatever they want.'' This is especially so considering
the league has asked Broad to join Ovitz's team.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine how Mayor Richard Riordan, councilman Ridley-Thomas and
governor Gray Davis will look if they can't strike a deal. Ovitz's
plan, planted in the downtown newspaper Sunday before anyone in
City Hall or Sacramento could respond, incorporates the park way
beyond the mere renovation of a football stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Even if the masses understand the finances, Riordan, Davis and
company will be left a somewhat empty and dreary park, and
remembered as the latest L.A. team to fumble away the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   Ridley-Thomas listened to these scenarios calmly and tried to
pick it apart. He said it ``wouldn't be very smart'' for the league
to pick the Ovitz plan and then tell L.A. to make it work. To be
blunt, he said ``They can forget that.''
</P>
<P>
   To date, said Ridley-Thomas, they have met every request by the
league. When the league asked for a new stadium design, they
produced one. When it said Roski needed a partner, Broad showed up.
Per the league's request, its most recent business plan has four
different parking solutions, although none of them as
all-encompassing as Ovitz's.
</P>
<P>
   ``The number of parking sports just popped up on us,'' said
Ridley-Thomas. ``Every time we satisfy one request, another pops
up. But our track record has been that we keep satisfying (their
requests).''
</P>
<P>
   That said, Ridley-Thomas tried to speak reasonably and
positively about being able to make things work should Ovitz's plan
get the bid.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's difficult to know what this request is, not having seen
it,'' said the councilman. ``It's hard to be supportive when you
don't know what it entails. And the clock is ticking. It's pretty
late for us to be talking about things like this.
</P>
<P>
   ``But there are a number of funding sources that could be found.
We first have to see how it would benefit (the area). We (meaning
all of the agencies) would be looking for some revenue streams.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, so might Ovitz and the NFL.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-25-99 2312EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
