<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-LOUIMA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: A BLUE WALL OF WITNESSES 
</HEADLINE>
  (dal) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It is too soon to suggest that the Abner Louima case has finally
brought down the ``blue wall of silence'' that has long prevented
New York City police officers from testifying against their
colleagues. But a crack of potentially seismic proportions began to
open when the sickening testimony of a series of his colleagues
forced Officer Justin Volpe to plead guilty on Tuesday to charges
that he tortured Louima two years ago in a Brooklyn police station
bathroom.
</P>
<P>
   The police witnesses, whose appearance clearly surprised defense
attorneys, pointed to Volpe as the one who had sodomized Louima in
August 1997 with a stick and then bragged about it to colleagues.
In court on Tuesday Volpe admitted the attack and said he had also
threatened to kill Louima if he told anybody about it. After Louima
was hospitalized for a torn rectum, a nurse persisted in demanding
answers about his unusual injuries. As the Louima case became
public, it forced New Yorkers to demand answers about how anyone
charged with protecting the public could commit such a sadistic
act.
</P>
<P>
   The police witnesses emerged more slowly than necessary, and
there are those who suggest that they were talking only because
they were afraid of being implicated themselves in this
high-profile case. But those officers who testified deserve credit
for speaking out in court. Once back in the station house, they
will undoubtedly encounter colleagues from the old school who will
label them unfairly as ``rats'' or persecute them in other
unsanctioned ways.
</P>
<P>
   One of the first officers to talk to investigators, Eric
Turetzky, found himself quickly transferred from the 70th Precinct
in Brooklyn, where the incident took place, to the Internal Affairs
Division, which investigates police misconduct. Joseph Armao, chief
counsel to the Mollen commission that investigated police
corruption in the early 1990s, said this transfer signaled to the
police force that Turetzky was no longer fit for any duty except
investigating his colleagues. ``You have to spread the culture of
integrity throughout the department,'' Armao correctly pointed out.
</P>
<P>
   Some have raised the hope that with better-educated officers,
New York's Police Department is not the closed society it once was.
Mayor Rudolph Giuliani and Police Commissioner Howard Safir prefer
the idea that the blue wall of silence is a media-driven myth that
the Volpe plea has destroyed. But Volpe's attack did not trigger
the usual closing of ranks from fellow officers because it was so
barbaric. The real test of whether the blue wall is finally
breached must await less dramatic cases of corruption or police
abuse.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-25-99 2316EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990525.0458 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-25 23:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1256 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SAFRICA-POLITICS-ART-     05-25 0871
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAFRICA-POLITICS-ART-800(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEAR AND LOATHING ARE LITERAL ON SOUTH AFRICA'S CAMPAIGN TRAIL 
</HEADLINE>
  
(ART ADV: Map is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036.) (jw) 
 By SUZANNE DALEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JOHANNESBURG, South Africa _ The campaign procession for
President Nelson Mandela's African National Congress began in the
rural town of Nongoma on Friday with an armored vehicle leading the
convoy and ended with a truckload of soldiers in bulletproof vests.
</P>
<P>
   As it wove through the streets, women smacked their thighs and
thrust their buttocks at it insultingly. Men walked through crowds
slapping stickers for the rival Inkatha Freedom Party on people's
chests without even asking permission.
</P>
<P>
   From the back of a pickup truck festooned with ANC posters,
Senzo Mchunu spoke to the crowds over a megaphone. He did not tout
the party's accomplishments. He merely assured voters that they
could vote for the party on June 2. Their ballot would really be
secret. They would be safe, he said.
</P>
<P>
   But he himself was surrounded by bodyguards _ their Uzis just
visible under their jackets, the bright sun glinting off their dark
glasses.
</P>
<P>
   In some parts of South Africa, political freedom is still more
of an ideal than a reality. As the country nears its second
post-apartheid national elections, there is far less tension than
there was in 1994, when thousands died in bloody clashes.
</P>
<P>
   But political violence and intimidation are not gone. Nowhere
was that clearer than in Nongoma last week. For the first time, the
African National Congress took its campaign to this Inkatha Freedom
Party stronghold deep in the heart of the lush province of
KwaZulu/Natal on the country's east coast. It was eventually forced
to leave in a hurry by a fierce mob shouting abuse and stomping out
the rhythmic war dance of a Zulu battalion.
</P>
<P>
   In April two ANC organizers were killed in this town _ one in
broad daylight on a crowded street, though no witnesses have come
forward. Within hours of the campaigning on Friday, the party's
posters had been ripped down and the house of another supporter, a
Zulu prince, had been firebombed.
</P>
<P>
   Still, party officials called the excursion a success. In 1994
they would not have dared to come at all. ``We achieved the purpose
we came for,'' boasted Mchunu, the party's deputy secretary in the
region, once he was safely out of town. ``The ANC made clear they
were going to fight to take their campaign everywhere, even
Nongoma.''
</P>
<P>
   Some South Africans will experience this year's elections as
voters in any Western country would. They will go to meetings,
listen to radio ads (television ones are banned), talk to friends
and make up their minds. But for many others _ particularly in
rural areas and in the squatter camps in black townships _
violence, intimidation and a lack of information will hobble their
freedom of choice.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the long-standing conflict between the governing
African National Congress and the Inkatha Freedom Party, there has
been tension between the governing party and the upstart biracial
United Democratic Party, led by a former ANC official, Bantu
Holomisa.
</P>
<P>
   That has been especially true in the Cape Town area and the
Eastern Cape, where even a rally featuring Mandela was disrupted by
United Democratic Party supporters in April.
</P>
<P>
   Human rights organizations say that officials from both parties
have been shot at near Cape Town while putting up election posters,
and that there has been a resurgence of paramilitary training.
There have been deaths as well, including four in March within 48
hours that appeared to be tit-for-tat killings of officials of both
parties.
</P>
<P>
   In the same areas, gang violence _ and Muslim vigilante groups
crusading against it _ may also be factor in the elections. A
conservative Muslim group has called on its followers to boycott
the voting because no party deserves its support. That could make
it hard for some Muslims to go to the polls.
</P>
<P>
   Then, over the weekend, the seven Muslim members of the
country's election commission from the Cape area resigned, saying
they had been threatened with death if they continued their work.
</P>
<P>
   But it is KwaZulu/Natal _ where the ANC and the Zulu-based
Inkatha party have clashed for years _ that still appears to be the
most volatile. Peace negotiations have been under way since 1997,
and rumor has it that the ANC, which is expected to win the
elections in a landslide, will give Inkatha a place in its
government when the elections are over.
</P>
<P>
   Yet suspicions abound between the two groups, and local
officials are not necessarily as enamored of peace as their
national leaders. The police uncovered a seven-ton arms cache
belonging to Inkatha two weeks ago, but said it hardly made a dent
in the arsenals believed to be kept by both sides. Most experts say
an explosion of violence is still possible.
</P>
<P>
   But so far, killings are down. The human rights groups say at
least 120 people have died in political violence in the last few
months, compared with more than 300 in 1994.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Some say the number of bodies may not reflect the true level of
fear. Even without hundreds of deaths, the voting population can be
intimidated. ``You can maintain pressure without stepping up the
violence,'' said Mary de Haas, a social anthropologist at the
University of Natal who publishes a newsletter on political
violence. ``A killing here and a killing there, and it sends a
message that most people will listen to. Just an odd death or two
is enough to get anybody scared.''
</P>
<P>
   In some villages, Ms. de Haas said, people sleep in the grass at
night for fear of being attacked in their homes. Many will vote
exactly as their local chiefs tell them to. In fact, privacy in the
voting booth becomes something of a joke in the rural areas, where
illiteracy is high and many people rely on others to show them
where to make their mark.
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks, Inkatha campaigners have felt their share of
intimidation as well. When Inkatha's leader, Chief Mangosuthu
Buthelezi, tried to hold a rally in the governing party's territory
along KwaZulu's south coast last week, he met up with its
supporters, who shouted abuse and padlocked the stadium to keep out
his luxury campaign bus.
</P>
<P>
   Around Durban, KwaZulu's largest city, there have also been
several incidents of violence during the campaign, including the
shooting of an African National Congress organizer in the Umlazi
district last Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   At his funeral on Sunday, the police had to rescue an Inkatha
supporter who was being beaten by a mob.
</P>
<P>
   But the oratory between the longtime enemies is not nearly as
heated as it was in 1994. Buthelezi, 71 and suffering from
diabetes, has been wooed by the ANC over the last five years _ and
allowed to be ating resident when Mandela and his heir apparent,
Deputy President Thabo Mbeki, were both out of the country.
</P>
<P>
   Buthelezi is coy about whether he will accept a role in a
coalition government, but it is clear that he is not campaigning
with the ardor of 1994. At a recent rally near Johannesburg, he
even included a cheer for Mandela and the ANC And the two parties
signed a pact saying they would allow each other to campaign freely
throughout the province.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the arms cache has raised tensions, and Buthelezi and
Mbeki backed out of a joint appearance at a prayer meeting
scheduled for last weekend.
</P>
<P>
   But on Sunday, a kind of history was made when the ANC went
campaigning without incident in Lindelani township, a former ``no
go'' area. Pius Mkhize, 24, accepted a flier but tucked it quickly
into his jacket.
</P>
<P>
   He said he could take the flier only because he did not actually
live in Lindelani. He was visiting his girlfriend.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here, if they catch you with this, they shoot you,'' he said.
``It is very dangerous.''
</P>
<P>
   But David Shabalala, the township's fierce self-proclaimed
Inkatha ``warlord,'' was certainly not in a fighting mood. At one
point he surprised the campaigners by arriving in their midst. From
the trunk of his car, he pulled out handfuls of his own party's
fliers and threw them in the air in what appeared to be friendly
competition.
</P>
<P>
   Shabalala said he would be campaigning in ANC territory soon.
``They can come here,'' he said of the governing party's workers.
``But I will beat them on election day.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-25-99 2317EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
