<DOCNO> NYT19990525.0460 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-25 23:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1260 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FRAUD-PLEA-NYT &LR;      05-25 1103
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRAUD-PLEA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A TURF BATTLE OVER HANDLING OF FRAUD CASE 
</HEADLINE>
  (dal) 
 By GRETCHEN MORGENSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A purloined prisoner in an important state securities
fraud case has put two powerful prosecutors on a collision course.
</P>
<P>
   At one end of the tarmac is Robert M. Morgenthau, the Manhattan
district attorney, and at the other is Zachary W. Carter, the U.S.
attorney in Brooklyn.
</P>
<P>
   In the middle sits Victor Wang, the former chairman of Duke &AMP;
Co., a defunct New York brokerage firm. On May 5, Wang, along with
Duke and 17 former colleagues, was indicted for securities fraud by
Morgenthau's office. He was unable to raise the $1.25 million cash
bail set by Justice William Wetzel of State Supreme Court and thus
resided in prison.
</P>
<P>
   But on Monday, apparently with no notice to Morgenthau, federal
marshals spirited Wang from his cell on Riker's Island at the
request of Carter's office. Michele Adelman, an assistant attorney
in that office, declined to comment on Wang's whereabouts or what
federal prosecutors might be discussing with him.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly upset over the twist in a case that reflects nearly two
years of work by his office, Morgenthau said, ``We were surprised
that they would remove from state custody a prisoner under state
indictment for any reason, but particularly without notifying the
district attorney or getting our consent.''
</P>
<P>
   In the indictment of Duke and its employees, Morgenthau said
Wang oversaw the manipulation of six stocks underwritten by Duke
between 1995 and 1998. If found guilty, Wang faces up to 30 years
in state prison.
</P>
<P>
   Now that case could be threatened. Under New York's double
jeopardy law, someone pleading guilty to a federal crime _ and Wang
may be discussing such a prospect with Carter's office _ cannot be
prosecuted for a similar crime by the state.
</P>
<P>
   Federal prosecutors are not barred from securing a guilty plea
following a state prosecution, but the Petit Rule says that they
should generally not prosecute where a state prosecution already
exists. To do so, a federal prosecutor usually must get approval
from the Department of Justice. The U.S. attorney declined to
comment on that matter on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Wang's exit from Riker's Island _ under a writ requested by
Carter's office _ may signal that the former broker is trying to
reach a plea agreement with federal prosecutors that would trump
Morgenthau's indictment. In their writ, the federal prosecutors did
not state whether they sought Wang as a witness in a case or as a
defendant.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Wang's lawyer, Lawrence V. Carra of Mineola, N.Y.,
said, ``It is not in my client's best interests to discuss his
transfer.''
</P>
<P>
   If a plea is being discussed, it indicates that cooperation
between the U.S. attorney's and the district attorney's staffs,
which have previously worked together, is near a low. The
maneuvering for control of high-profile cases is usually conducted
by prosecutors behind the scenes, not in the spotlight.
</P>
<P>
   Jack S. Hoffinger, a criminal defense lawyer at Hoffinger,
Friedland, Dobrish &AMP; Stern, called the apparent squabble
unfortunate. ``It's irregular to writ out a state prisoner without
notifying the district attorney who put him away. Especially when
the DA is Bob Morgenthau, whose competence and integrity are models
for the rest of the country,'' he said. ``Is this a grab for
publicity?''
</P>
<P>
   Since Morgenthau began investigating Duke &AMP; Co. almost two years
ago, four former employees of the firm have pleaded guilty to
securities violations. Earlier this month, a grand jury returned
indictments against the firm and 18 individuals for enterprise
corruption, grand larceny, antitrust violations and evidence
tampering.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors contend that Duke employees colluded with at least
two other brokerage firms to maintain artificially high prices of
six stocks underwritten by Duke between 1995 and 1998. About 34,000
clients invested $171 million with Duke, according to Morgenthau.
The firm was the subject of 26 regulatory actions before it closed
in March 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Because Duke had offices in Manhattan and on Long Island, the
case could fall within the domain of either Morgenthau or Carter.
But Carter's intervention in a case under a state grand jury's
review for more than 18 months is unusual.
</P>
<P>
   This is not the first time a federal prosecutor has interfered
with a case brought by Morgenthau. In December 1997, he brought
securities fraud charges against Marisa Baridis, a former
compliance officer in the legal department at Morgan Stanley Dean
Witter ho had fed confidential information about companies to
acquaintances. About a month later, Mary Jo White, the U.S.
attorney in Manhattan, took control of the case, arguing that
serious federal securities crime was her territory, not the
state's. Morgenthau's office had to dismiss its case against Ms.
Baridis, but prosecuted 10 others in the matter.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Baridis pleaded guilty to federal conspiracy and securities
fraud charges; she has yet to be sentenced.
</P>
<P>
   Defendants caught in a turf battle between state and federal
prosecutors can benefit by essentially choosing to be prosecuted by
the office providing the best deal. Federal prisons are generally
considered more appealing than state jails. In Wang's case, the
dispute may also result in a lesser sentence even if he admits to
having swindled investors.
</P>
<P>
   Securities lawyers say that as more investors jump into stocks,
opportunities rise for securities swindlers. Prosecutors well
understand the publicity that accrues from success in fraud cases,
and the battle to mount them is hotter than ever.
</P>
<P>
   Federal prosecutors often say that they are better equipped than
their state counterparts to prosecute complex securities cases and
that prosecuting such crimes under state law diminishes their
seriousness.
</P>
<P>
   But Morgenthau's office has pursued white-collar crime and
securities fraud cases in recent years. In the last 18 months
alone, his office has brought 8 securities fraud cases against 61
individuals. The Duke case is one of the largest, but others
include the case against A.R. Baron, a brokerage firm, now defunct,
whose employees, prosecutors said, swindled investors out of $75
million.
</P>
<P>
   Carter's office is also investigating Stratton Oakmont, a
brokerage firm that attracted several regulatory actions before
being shut in 1996. Stratton's principals, Jordan Belfort and
Daniel Porush, were indicted on federal securities fraud and
money-laundering charges in September. Before starting Duke &AMP; Co.,
Wang was an executive at Stratton Oakmont.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
