<SLUG> BC-ABC-PANASONIC-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ABC AND PANASONIC ANNOUNCE HIGH DEFINITION TV BROADCAST DEAL
</HEADLINE>
   (dal) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The ABC television network and the Panasonic Corp.
said on Tuesday that Panasonic would lend the network millions of
dollars worth of new equipment so that ABC can broadcast its Monday
night football games and the Super Bowl in high definition starting
this fall.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement, expected to cost Panasonic about $10 million, is
the second cooperative arrangement between a network and an
equipment manufacturer announced this month. On May 9, the
Mitsubishi Electric Corp., a large maker of television sets, agreed
to underwrite CBS's costs to broadcast most of its prime-time
schedule in high definition beginning this fall.
</P>
<P>
   In late April, NBC began broadcasting ``The Tonight Show'' in
high definition with help from the Sony Corp. All of the
manufacturers hope the deals will help them sell more
high-definition television sets and broadcast equipment.
</P>
<P>
   Panasonic, a unit of the Matsushita Electric Industrial Corp.,
will build and equip a new mobile production truck used to televise
football games and equip it with high-definition cameras, switchers
and related equipment.
</P>
<P>
   ABC will use the gear to broadcast 17 Monday night football
games in high definition from Sept. 13 through Jan. 3, plus a
wildcard playoff game on Jan. 8 and the Super Bowl on Jan. 30.
</P>
<P>
   ABC agreed to give Panasonic free advertising in exchange for
the equipment. At the beginning of each game, said Preston Davis,
president of broadcast operations for ABC, the network will mention
Panasonic in an on-screen message. And Panasonic will get free
advertising time during the high-definition programming. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
