<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-25 23:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1267 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-READING-TEST-ART-N     05-25 0794
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-READING-TEST-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MORE THAN HALF IN 4TH GRADE FAILED NEW STATE ENGLISH TEST 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By ANEMONA HARTOCOLLIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   More than half of all fourth-graders across New York state
failed the new English test given last January, which replaced an
old-fashioned multiple choice test with a three-day marathon that
required children to read long passages and write essays.
</P>
<P>
   The test _ a model being watched by educators across the country
_ was designed to set new, higher standards for reading and writing
that will help prepare children for high school graduation
requirements being phased in during the next five years.
</P>
<P>
   But the results left even some leaders of elite districts
smarting from results that showed only a small fraction of
students, 5 percent statewide, achieving advanced levels. In New
York City, two out of three students failed to meet the state
standards, and in a great many schools, the results were abysmal.
</P>
<P>
   The state education commissioner, Richard Mills, who imposed the
new test with the approval of the state Board of Regents, suggested
that the low statewide passing rate confirmed his prediction that
the new test would expose weaknesses in many schools that had been
papered over by the test it replaced. On that test, which measured
minimum competency, affluent suburban districts were accustomed to
seeing more than 90 percent of their students pass. On the new
test, many of those districts saw the percentages plunge into the
60s and 70s.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an exercise in truth telling,'' Mills said. ``Where do
we go from here? We have to go up, obviously.''
</P>
<P>
   The test was preceded by months of worry and feverish cramming.
Some teachers warned that it was too abstract for 9-year-olds.
Schools virtually suspended their normal curriculums to brush up on
concepts like ``the main idea,'' and some parents invested in
private tutoring.
</P>
<P>
   The results confirmed some of their worst fears.
</P>
<P>
   The test was scored in four levels, with students in levels 3
and 4 performing at or above the state standards for reading,
writing and listening and those in levels 1 and 2 failing to meet
the standards. The standards, developed by a panel of fourth-grade
teachers last fall, require students to read long passages of
literature and nonfiction, then answer questions and write essays
about them. Children must also listen to a passage read out loud,
take notes and then recall what they have heard. They are also
evaluated on spelling, grammar and punctuation.
</P>
<P>
   The new fourth-grade test replaces a multiple-choice test that
was given in third grade. The old test simply required children to
read short passages and fill in missing words. Statewide, 84
percent of third-graders passed the old test, which measured a
minimum level of competency; in New York City, 65 percent passed.
</P>
<P>
   On the new test, 48 percent of the state's 210,000 public-school
fourth- graders, including special education students, scored at or
above the standards, while 11 percent scored in the worst category,
meaning that they showed ``no evidence'' of performing at the
standards.
</P>
<P>
   The picture was even bleaker in New York City, which has always
lagged behind the rest of the state. Only 33 percent of the city's
65,000 fourth- graders passed the test, while 21 percent fell into
the worst category, compared with 6 percent in the rest of the
state.
</P>
<P>
   Mills recommended Tuesday that all students in the bottom level
be sent to summer school this year.
</P>
<P>
   In an indication of the how hard the test was, only 3 percent of
New York City's fourth-graders and 6 percent in the rest of the
state fell into the highest category.
</P>
<P>
   The scores include special education students, because, state
officials said, they wanted to make sure that no students were
excluded as a way of improving results.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Elmore, a professor of education at Harvard University,
said the test was one of the most challenging in the country, and
that New York students had done better on it than students in other
states, like Kentucky and Texas, that have aggressively used
testing to measure schools and students.
</P>
<P>
   ``What worries me is it brings out the anti-testing people,'' he
said. ``At this stage of the game, I think we have no option to
choose not to test. This test is much better than tests they've
been using in the past.''
</P>
<P>
   New York City's schools chancellor, Rudy Crew, contended that
the city had some cause to celebrate, because it had scored
slightly higher than the state's other big cities, Buffalo,
Rochester, Syracuse and Yonkers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
