<DOCNO> NYT19990525.0464 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-25 23:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1274 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-JUDGE-PROFILE-NYT &LR;      05-25 0932
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-JUDGE-PROFILE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MATCHED SET: 2 JUDGES, 2 WEDDINGS, 2 SHOWS
</HEADLINE>
   (jw) 
 By JAN HOFFMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ O joy, O wretched excess: five bathrooms for two
people!
</P>
<P>
   Gerald Sheindlin, who schlepped to the Bronx criminal courts for
16 years, twinkles through a tour of his Sutton Place duplex on
Manhattan's East Side, delighted and dazed. He and his wife had
been public servants. But this? This is the house that TV bought.
</P>
<P>
   ``The white tornado decorated the whole place just like that,''
he whispers, snapping his fingers, referring to the woman he has
wed twice, known to millions as Judge Judy.
</P>
<P>
   Her Judgeship pads by, in tights and a sweater set, chasing a
yapping powder puff, ``Baby, baay-bee.''
</P>
<P>
   He: ``And this is our kitchen!'' Glares at her back. ``Too bad
you can't cook.''
</P>
<P>
   No response. He repeats the jab.
</P>
<P>
   Not bothering to look over, Judy waves her wrist and zings, ``I
ignore him; he's retired.''
</P>
<P>
   Sheindlin gazes heavenward. ``It's not easy being me,'' he
sighs.
</P>
<P>
   They crack up laughing, because the joke is too, too good. On
May 15, Gerald Sheindlin, 65, did retire as an acting justice of
New York's state Supreme Court. And like his wife, the former Judge
Judith Sheindlin of Manhattan Family Court, he has begun a TV
career. In September, he will make his debut as Judge Jerry of
``The People's Court,'' replacing Edward Koch, who named both
Sheindlins to the bench. Taping has started.
</P>
<P>
   But Jerry was a serious jurist! A man who published 65 opinions,
presided over 86 murder trials and thinks big thoughts about the
admissibility of DNA evidence! From this to small-claims silliness
on daytime TV and inevitable comparisons with his tempestuous soul
mate, star of the top syndicated daytime show?
</P>
<P>
   He settles into an armchair in a living room tastefully
appointed save for a 53-inch TV screen (his) and limns a life with
a trajectory from the heavy to the helium:
</P>
<P>
   Savage Bronx childhood. Immigrant parents. Father painted
houses, mother toiled in a tie factory, both punished their
ne'er-do-well son with fists, ropes, hangers, wooden spoons. Jerry
fell into petty crime and started a gang. Having reached his full
scrapper's height of 5 feet 6, he restricted membership to tough
guys no taller than 5 feet 7. They called themselves the
Kingsbridge Munchkins, and they said it with a swagger. He finished
school with a 68 average and joined the Navy.
</P>
<P>
   A Navy doctor became his mentor, imploring him to lose the Bronx
accent and find his brain, which he did. Long Island University
accepted him on probation. He got straight A's, graduated in 21/2
years, president of his class, and flew through Brooklyn Law
School.
</P>
<P>
   For someone bright and smoldering, criminal defense trials are a
fine outlet. Over the next 22 years, he built a booming practice
with Herbert Adlerberg, a law school buddy who is now also a judge.
``We had a feeling for the disadvantaged,'' Jerry recalls. He was
aggressive, meticulous and immodest.
</P>
<P>
   There was a first marriage, 12 years, two sons and a daughter,
and then a divorce. He rode motorcycles, was single for five years,
and his warm brown eyes still glow with memory.
</P>
<P>
   In 1976 at a bench-and-bar tavern, he met Judy, a hellacious
Family Court prosecutor, recently separated with two children. The
repartee began upon introduction and they married the following
year. His judgeship was approved in 1983. In the Bronx, he was
known as a strict, productive, impatient judge, but a sweetheart
when he took off the robes.
</P>
<P>
   Her Judgeship pads into the room and curls up with Lulu the
Baby.
</P>
<P>
   Judy: ``Is he nicer than me? No. He gives a nicer impression. I
am easier to live with.''
</P>
<P>
   Jerry shakes his head softly. An entire nation has watched his
wife on television, and he knows he has an entire nation's
condolences.
</P>
<P>
   Judy: ``Who made the bed this morning?''
</P>
<P>
   Jerry: ``Whose dog peed on it? And you're supposed to be the
nicer person just because you made the bed?''
</P>
<P>
   They giggle. Weep not for Judge Jerry, who gives as good as he
gets. She's more confident and constant, middle-class, a Brooklyn
daddy's girl. He's moodier, sensitive, still scarred by childhood.
In 1991 they divorced, and in 1992 they remarried. She likes to
say, ``I have a lot of patience for him.'' Then, ``I need
interesting and Jerry's interesting.''
</P>
<P>
   So why did Sheindlin retire early and take the TV gig, which in
New York will be the lead-in show to his wife's? He used to love
being a judge, he says, but the passion dimmed. For starters, the
infamous acquitting Bronx jury does exist:
</P>
<P>
   ``Open-and-shut apartment burglary case,'' he says.
``Overwhelming evidence. Jury acquits. Afterward I said: `The
defendant has indicated he would like to thank you for your
verdict, and he asked me to give him your home addresses so he can
visit each of you and express his appreciation. So I did.' '' (He
didn't.)
</P>
<P>
   The nadir was the 1996 nonjury trial of Officer Francis Livoti
in the choking death of a Bronx man. Sheindlin was widely
criticized for acquitting the officer and for speaking to the
press.
</P>
<P>
   Repeating his explanation _ the prosecution's evidence was
conflicting _ Sheindlin looks mournful. ``I ruled in favor of
someone I couldn't stand and devastated the family that already had
a loss. It was the most difficult, disturbing, devastating case,
and it took its toll.''
</P>
<P>
   So this year, a TV producer appears: neither the cases nor the
verdicts are about life and death, and the salary jumps from
$135,000 a year to over a million. You have to ask?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-25-99 2337EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
