<HEADLINE>
GUILTY SOUL RETURNS CASH LOST IN TURNPIKE MISHAP
</HEADLINE>
   (dal) 
 By ANDREW JACOBS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Here's one for the faith-in-humanity file.
</P>
<P>
   A suspicious-looking package that arrived Monday at the office
of the Port Authority of New York and New Jersey contained more
than $14,000, toll proceeds that fell off the back of an armored
truck last week on the New Jersey Turnpike.
</P>
<P>
   The money, in small bills and coins, was determined to be a part
of the $30,000 to $100,000 that authorities say spilled across the
southbound lanes on May 17, sparking a frenzied grabfest involving
dozens of drivers who ran from their cars as cash fluttered through
the air.
</P>
<P>
   State troopers gathered $2,236, and another $743 was later
turned in by people who said they had second thoughts about keeping
it.
</P>
<P>
   The money was from three days of tolls at the Holland Tunnel,
which is run by the Port Authority, and was headed to a
Philadelphia bank, said Sgt. Al Della Fave, a spokesman for the New
Jersey State Police.
</P>
<P>
   The armored car was owned by Coin Depot Corp. of Elizabeth,
N.J., whose drivers told officials that the back doors just swung
open without warning. Its executives did not return calls for
comment.
</P>
<P>
   When the cardboard box arrived at the Port Authority's offices
at the World Trade Center, workers were suspicious because the
parcel listed no name and the police initially said that the return
address was false. Bam Bam, a bomb-sniffing dog, was called in. The
dog expressed no interest, and the box was opened.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a pleasant surprise,'' said Greg Trevor, a Port
Authority spokesman, who added that the loss was insured.
Investigators are trying to track down those less forthcoming
through license numbers and videotape by cameras in police cars.
</P>
<P>
   Whoever sent the box had no interest in glory. A simple note
said, ``This money was found on the shoulder of the NJTP in very
torn bags.'' There was the return address of an Orthodox Catholic
church in Little Italy, St. Anthony of Padua.
</P>
<P>
   As it turns out, St. Anthony is the patron saint of lost things.
The Rev. Michael Verra, the pastor, said he knew nothing about the
cash, but that people do approach him: ``They give me things and
say: `I took this and I'm feeling very guilty about it. Would you
return it for me?'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
