<SLUG> BC-FUNDRAISING-HUANG-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FUND-RAISER WHO BROUGHT ASIAN MONEY TO DEMOCRATS TO PLEAD GUILTY TO
CONSPIRACY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS to add sentence in 4th graf, clarifying the guilty plea.)  (rm) 
 By DAVID JOHNSTON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ John Huang, the prolific fund-raiser at the center
of the furor over Democratic Party financing of President Clinton's
re-election, will plead guilty in federal court to a single felony
count of conspiring to make illegal contributions, the Justice
Department and Huang's lawyer said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   A frequent White House visitor and prominent figure behind
Democratic efforts to solicit millions of dollars in political
contributions from Asian-Americans, Huang was part of a
fund-raising operation later found to be tainted by questionable or
illegal contributions. In at least one case, the money was funneled
through a top Chinese intelligence official.
</P>
<P>
   Huang refused to testify at congressional investigations, and
thus became an absent star at Capitol Hill hearings. Republicans
vilified him as a symbol of abuse. They accused him of using his
fund-raising prowess to launder contributions to the Democrats and
burrow his way deep into the Clinton administration through a job
at the Commerce Department on behalf of his financial patrons, the
Riady family of Indonesia and its Asian-based conglomerate, the
Lippo Group.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly half of the $3.4 million Huang raised during the 1996
election campaign was returned as potentially improper. The
specific charge to which he is expected to plead guilty, however,
relates to contributions raised earlier for campaigns in
California.
</P>
<P>
   Huang has for years seemed like a pivotal witness who could jump
start the Justice Department's criminal investigation of political
fund-raising.
</P>
<P>
   But on Tuesday, law-enforcement officials downplayed Huang's
significance, offering a mixed assessment of his cooperation.
Several officials suggested that he had provided no explosive
revelations and emerged as a lesser figure than he seemed after
congressional hearings.
</P>
<P>
   Still, other officials said they wanted to question Huang more
extensively about his relationship with the Riady family and his
dealings with presidential aides like Harold Ickes, a former White
House deputy chief of staff who helped manage fund-raising when
Huang was brought in as a fund-raiser for the Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed plea agreement, which Huang is expected to formally
accept in a week or two, is unusual. Under one of its terms,
Justice Department officials said they will acknowledge that
investigators have unearthed no evidence that Huang engaged in any
espionage or violated national security laws, Justice Department
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   That finding would directly rebut and, in effect, dismiss an
important conclusion by the Senate Governmental Affairs Committee,
which investigated how the Democrats financed Clinton's
re-election. In its March 1998 report, the panel found that China
wanted to influence political campaigns and policies in Washington
and that Huang ``may possibly'' have had a direct financial
relationship with Beijing.
</P>
<P>
   Another provision in the deal would grant Huang sentencing
leniency in exchange for his cooperation, which has been underway
for the last six months, Justice Department officials said. Under
the arrangement, he would be spared jail and placed on one-year's
probation. Under the law, he could be sentenced to a maximum of
five years in prison.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am greatly relieved for John and his family that his ordeal
is almost over,'' said Ty Cobb, Huang's attorney, who confirmed
that Huang would plead guilty under the terms of the deal outlined
by the Justice Department. ``I also commend the Justice Department
for stepping up to the plate and acknowledging that John is not and
never was a spy.''
</P>
<P>
   Some Republicans scoffed at the deal, accusing the Justice
Department of allowing Huang to escape punishment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what information they're getting, but it
certainly appears to be a sweetheart deal,'' said Michael Madigan,
the former Republican chief counsel for the Senate investigating
committee. ``It certainly looks like they've got the rug pulled up
and the broom in the other hand. I hope that isn't the case.''
</P>
<P>
   But Justice Department officials said that, in the end, the case
against Huang was weaker and narrower than they initially believed.
The conspiracy charge against Huang dates back to a period between
1992 and 1994 and focuses on two contributions totaling $7,500, one
to a mayoralty candidate in Los Angeles, the other to a California
Democratic fund. He was not charged with any specific act related
to his fund raising for Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Cobb would not discuss the nature or extent of Huang's
cooperation, but law enforcement officials said that Huang had been
meeting extensively with investigators from the Justice
Department's campaign finance unit and from the offices of several
independent counsels, including the Whitewater prosecutor, Kenneth
Starr.
</P>
<P>
   Huang did not make an appearance Tuesday. Justice Department
officials, who filed the one-count criminal information in federal
court in Los Angeles, said he would acknowledge wrongdoing in
exchange for a deal in which he will be placed on a year of
probation without a jail sentence.
</P>
<P>
   The deal suggested that prosecutors are re-energizing the nearly
3-year-old campaign finance inquiry. Last Friday, Yah Lin Trie, a
Democratic fund-raiser and longtime Arkansas friend of Clinton,
pleaded guilty in Little Rock to political fund-raising charges and
agreed to cooperate with the Justice Department's campaign finance
inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   But with Trie said by some officials to be unlikely to provide
revelations and with Huang shedding little new light on the issue,
it is unclear whether the Justice Department is preparing for a new
prosecutorial assault or is, as some officials predict, nearing the
end of the long inquiry.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
