<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-PACERS-ROSE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A TALE OF TWO JALEN ROSES: WHICH ONE WILL SHOW UP? 
</HEADLINE>
  (dal) 
 By IRA BERKOW   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Two coaches named Larry observed at different times two players
named Jalen Rose. The two coaches were separate entities, while
Jalen Rose was solely the party of the third part.
</P>
<P>
   ``He shouldn't be in the league,'' Larry Brown, his former coach
with the Indiana Pacers, had said at one point about Rose, a
talented, 6-foot-8-inch player.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a lot of confidence in Jalen,'' said Larry Bird, his
present coach. ``He's a very good player and he could become one of
the better players in the league.''
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, and for several days following, the Knicks will get a
good opportunity to view Rose as they open the Eastern Conference
finals against the Indiana Pacers in Market Square Arena.
</P>
<P>
   Rose got into a scrape with Patrick Ewing in the Knicks' lone
victory over the Pacers in three games. But he will not be Ewing's
problem, though he may well be Latrell Sprewell's. Rose is the
Pacer who may likely take advantage of Sprewell's periodic lapses
on defense.
</P>
<P>
   But which Rose will appear? Will it be the one who blooms into a
slasher and scorer, who can also flower as an outside scorer? And
on defense, will it be the one demonstrating his prowess by nipping
the speedy Sprewell in the bud? Or will this particular Rose fade
into the floorboards?
</P>
<P>
   A pair of Jalen Roses were apparent in the Pacers' sweep of the
Philadelphia 76ers, the team now coached by Larry Brown. In Game 1
on May 17, Rose _ who has the speed, strength and versatility to
play point guard, shooting guard or small forward, and does all
three when called upon by Bird _ led his team in scoring with 27
points on 9 baskets on 16 attempts after coming off the bench and
playing 30 minutes. In the fourth and final game on Sunday, he
scored 5 points on 1 basket in 11 tries.
</P>
<P>
   ``I rode him too long,'' said Bird, who had played Rose for 21
minutes. ``Usually, with Jalen, if he doesn't start quickly, he
doesn't have it the whole game. It was probably one of his worst
games all year. He really got nothing accomplished.''
</P>
<P>
   After the game, Bird said nothing to Rose. He didn't have to.
``Larry believes that you're a professional and he treats you like
one,'' Rose said. ``You're supposed to know what's expected of you,
and when you screw up, he knows you know. What's there to be
said?''
</P>
<P>
   There were times when Brown didn't have much to say about Rose,
either. And there was a period during Brown's tenure with the
Pacers when he didn't allow Rose to play for 14 straight games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had said to Larry, `You've got to work with this kid and
help him,''' recalled Donnie Walsh, the Pacers' general manager.
``But they got off on the wrong foot. And I think that Larry
learned something having to coach Allen Iverson. Some of these
younger kids have a sing-songy little act. You have to get to
understand it. And I have seen Jalen grow and mature.''
</P>
<P>
   This season, Brown admitted a mistake with the Pacers. ``I
mishandled Jalen,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Pacers had traded Mark Jackson to the Denver Nuggets for
Rose after the 1996 season. Rose had entered the NBA as one of the
cocky Fab Five crew from the University of Michigan, and in his two
years with Denver did little to dispel a reputation as a spoiled
brat, arguing at times with Dan Issel, his coach there.
</P>
<P>
   When Walsh traded for Rose, it was anticipated that he would be
the Pacers' point guard. But that didn't work to Brown's
satisfaction. The Pacers traded again with the Nuggets, bringing
back Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rose never talked back to Larry,'' Walsh said, referring to
Brown, ``but he pouted. It wasn't so much what he said that
bothered Larry, it was the body language. That kind of thing.''
</P>
<P>
   When Brown left Indiana to take the job in Philadelphia two
seasons ago, and Bird arrived on the scene, Rose believed that he
would get another chance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was eager and ready for a fresh start,'' he said. ``I
embraced the idea of learning from the best. I remember that when
Larry played he had ice water in his veins. And he's the same as a
coach. He's the same person regardless of the score, the situation
or the environment. It seems impossible to do, but he succeeds.''
</P>
<P>
   Rose still doesn't start, nor does Sprewell. In contrast to
Sprewell, who still bridles about not starting, Rose has acquiesced
to the situation. His attitude, according to Bird, is highly
professional, and he has led the Pacers' bench in scoring with 11
points a game, the highest average of his five-year career.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know Jalen wants to be a point guard, and wants to lead a
team,'' Bird said. ``And one day I think he will. He's still only
26 years old. But right now Mark Jackson is doing a great job for
us there, and I've told Jalen that he is most valuable to us in his
versatility. And he's accepted that. He's our best player on the
wing, because he's a better dribbler than Reggie Miller, and when
Jalen penetrates he can pass better than Reggie, rather than having
to force a shot.''
</P>
<P>
   Bird was asked how he keeps Rose happy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I give him minutes,'' he said, with a smile.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Rose is usually off the bench and into the game before
the end of the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
   But what happens when Rose has a game like the last one against
Philadelphia?
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems he sometimes loses focus,'' Walsh said. ``You can see
it on his face. When he's into it, his shot selection is sharper,
his passes are sharper, and so is his defense. In the conference
finals last year against the Bulls, when we took them to seven
games, I thought Jalen did a very good job on Michael Jordan. I
thought he kept him from driving to the basket. But then in
Philadelphia Sunday, the first thing Jalen did when he came into
the game was throw the ball away. I said, `Oh, oh, this doesn't
look good.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``But we need him focused for the Knicks. He makes a big
difference for us.''  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
