u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-KNICKS-NYT &LR;      05-25 0356
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-KNICKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE KNICKS' AMAZING RUN 
</HEADLINE>
  (dal) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Wednesday, May 26:
</P>
<P>
   The dreaded Indiana Pacers come next, so now is the time to
savor the advance of the New York Knickerbockers, who seemed dead
in April, to the Eastern Conference finals. The Knicks first beat
the heavily favored Miami Heat, exacting delightful revenge against
former coach Pat Riley, then swept the Atlanta Hawks in four games.
They did it with their crippled superstar, Patrick Ewing, playing
at half speed; with a creative second unit that has outplayed
everyone else's first team, and with Latrell Sprewell, a talented
player and erratic personality best known for choking his former
coach before the Knicks brought him to New York.
</P>
<P>
   They also did it despite some off-court distractions that simply
make the on-court heroics more delicious. Back when the Knicks were
21-21 and in danger of not making the playoffs, Dave Checketts, the
president of Madison Square Garden, demoted the team's general
manager, Ernie Grunfeld, who had assembled this team, and met with
Phil Jackson, who before retiring had coached the Chicago Bulls to
six league championships. This was not a dumb thing to do, since
Checketts is paid to think about the organization's future. What
was dumb was that he lied about the meeting after The New York
Times revealed it. Checketts has since apologized to all concerned,
including Jeff Van Gundy, the present coach, but he still looks
bad.
</P>
<P>
   Van Gundy, though, is looking good, at least for now. Checketts
may not believe in him, but the fans are behind him. When Ewing
tires, Van Gundy puts in Chris Dudley, a plodder whose role is to
do a Jesse Ventura number on the other team's big man while the
rest of the Knicks' second unit, chiefly Sprewell and Marcus Camby,
run like crazy and find open shots. Beginning Sunday we will learn
whether this works against Indiana, a team with a good second unit
of its own and, of course, Reggie Miller, who seems put on earth to
torment Spike Lee and the rest of the Madison Square Garden
faithful.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-25-99 2349EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
