<HEADER>
A1290 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAR-UNION-NYT &LR;      05-25 0705
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-UNION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STRUGGLING RACING BODIES MAY DECIDE TO REUNITE 
</HEADLINE>
  (dal) 
 By TARIK EL-BASHIR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Four years after Championship Auto Racing Teams and the Indy
Racing League split up, damaging the appeal of open-wheel racing in
the United States, the two rival series may be secretly planning a
reconciliation.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Craig, CART's chairman, and Tony George, the IRL
president, have had face-to-face meetings as recently as last week,
according to a high-ranking motorsports executive. Bill France, the
president of Nascar and the new owner of four tracks where CART has
races, was also present.
</P>
<P>
   The most recent meeting was in Indianapolis, and the sides
discussed the parameters of a reunification, which could happen by
the end of this year, the executive said, speaking on condition of
anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   Both CART and the IRL have suffered since they parted company in
1995, when conflicting egos and differing ideals led CART to leave
the Indianapolis Motor Speedway, home of the Indianapolis 500. The
series differed over the engines used and the cost of operating the
teams.
</P>
<P>
   But it has become clear to both sides that to thrive, the two
series must be unified.
</P>
<P>
   Fans are not filling seats at the tracks for either series'
races, and television ratings are also poor. A prime example of fan
apathy was the abundance of hotel rooms available in downtown
Indianapolis on Tuesday, four days before the Indianapolis 500,
which is supposed to be open-wheel racing's premier event. The
500's luster has been dulled by the rift, and the reason is simple:
CART won't be there. The cars are different, and the drivers'
contracts keep them from racing in each other's series.
</P>
<P>
   CART's drivers will be racing Saturday in the Motorola 300 at
Gateway International Raceway in St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   While fans want all of the best open-wheel drivers competing in
the same race, that won't happen Sunday when the green flag is
waved at the Indianapolis Motor Speedway. But if the talk in
Gasoline Alley is true, there is that possibility for 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Here is what has been fueling the speculation.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, Roger Penske, one of CART's founders and
ardent supporters, sold four tracks to the International Speedway
Corp., which is owned by France. So now International Speedway is
the promoter of four CART races (in Brooklyn, Mich., Nazareth, Pa.,
Fontana, Calif., and Homestead, Fla.) and one IRL race (in
Phoenix).
</P>
<P>
   France has kept his intentions quiet, but he now has a vested
interest in open-wheel racing's success. France may try to broker a
deal between CART and the IRL.
</P>
<P>
   ``Promoting open-wheel racing is not going to hurt Nascar,'' a
Nascar official said. ``In Bill France's eyes, strengthening
motorsports in America helps everyone, including Nascar.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week, ABC secured the rights to the Indianapolis 500 and
the IRL for five years, even as television ratings have continued
to slump. ABC already owns the rights to CART. ABC's executives
might expect something drastic to reverse the trend of low ratings
for both series.
</P>
<P>
   And there are other less significant hints that something is in
the works. CART has not released its plans for an engine formula
for next season, meaning any plans could be changed with relative
ease. Also, the most successful chassis builder in CART, Reynard,
recently acquired Riley &AMP; Scott, which builds IRL chassis.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there are many obstacles that stand between a CART-IRL
merger, thus making it expensive and complicated. The biggest
potential snag concerns the engine manufacturers: CART engine
suppliers lease the engines to teams, while IRL engine builders
sell them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody wants to make a $20 million commitment on an engine
program if we're never going to make it,'' said a motorsports
executive who is affiliated with CART. ``But even if the CART and
the IRL were to reach a compromise, it's probably too late for
engine suppliers to have something ready for 2000.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``There are signs all around that something is in the
works. After all this time, I don't want to get my hopes up. But
you would have to be blind or an idiot not to realize that these
guys need each other.''  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-25-99 2350EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
