u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RAC-SILVERBULLETDAY-N     05-25 0725
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-SILVERBULLETDAY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAFFERT'S FILLY RUNS 6 FURLONGS IN 1:10 4/5 
</HEADLINE>
  (dal) 
 By JOSEPH DURSO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Silverbulletday, the best 3-year-old filly in racing, worked a
sizzling six furlongs at Churchill Downs on Tuesday. But her
trainer, Bob Baffert, would still not say that she would try to
thwart Charismatic's bid to sweep the Triple Crown in the Belmont
Stakes one week from Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're out of it till we say we're in it,'' Baffert said in the
cryptic style he used before the Kentucky Derby and the Preakness.
``But right now, it's looking better. I want to see how she came
out of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Baffert watched his star filly fly six furlongs in 1:10 4/5 at
Churchill Downs, but then declined to commit her to the Belmont
although he seemed to be holding the door open. He played a similar
guessing game before the Derby, then ran her the day before in the
Kentucky Oaks, which she won. Two weeks later, he entered her in
the Preakness, then scratched her after she drew a bad post
position. Instead, he ran her in the Black-Eyed Susan, which she
also won.
</P>
<P>
   Silverbulletday now has won 11 of her 12 starts, but has not yet
tested colts.
</P>
<P>
   ``She just did her work,'' Baffert said, describing Tuesday's
workout. Then, sounding ambivalent again, he added: ``It was an
amazing work. A little too fast for me. Look, there were too many
horses in the Derby, and she drew a bad post position for the
Preakness. The Belmont may suit her.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, the down side is the distance, a mile and a half. But if
you're going to take a shot, now's the time. If I think she can do
it, we'll take the shot.''
</P>
<P>
   Mike Pegram, Silverbulletday's owner, was on hand for her
workout on Tuesday and afterward seemed to be tilting toward the
Belmont.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's pretty fast, huh?'' he said of his star horse. ``If we
go to New York, we want to win the race.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, said Pegram, if Silverbulletday ships to New York, it
will be for only one reason _ to run in the Belmont, even though
the Acorn, a marquee race for 3-year-old fillies, will be run the
day before.
</P>
<P>
   ``We aren't going to cross-enter her in anything,'' Pegram said.
``If she goes to New York, she's going to run the Belmont, nothing
else. I guarantee that.''
</P>
<P>
   The Churchill Downs track took on an all-star tone yesterday
when Charismatic also worked out, but he did it without great
expectations or great speed, just an easy six furlongs in
1:16 &LR; gffraction &LR; 3 5 . His trainer, D. Wayne Lukas, said his colt
would work once more before shipping to Belmont next Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was more to give him a mental or energy edge,'' Lukas
said of the workout. ``When this whole thing started, I had hoped
he'd move forward from the Derby to the Preakness, then I just
wanted him in condition for the Belmont. But I think we're going to
move forward again.''
</P>
<P>
   The horse's owner, Bob Lewis, said from Los Angeles that the
slow time of the workout did not concern him, either.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we need to put a strong workout into him at this
point,'' Lewis said.
</P>
<P>
   Then he punctuated the point by saying: ``Charismatic dropped
from 31-1 in the Kentucky Derby to 8-1 in the Preakness. So, I
guess he's moving in the right direction.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewis was asked whether he thought Baffert was waffling on
entering his filly in the Belmont, and he noted that Baffert had
trained many horses for him, including Silver Charm, who won the
Kentucky Derby and the Preakness in 1997 before losing the Belmont.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd been with Bob as a trainer for nine years, and with Wayne
for seven,'' he replied. ``People can change their minds. If they
feel confident, I hope they'll be there. I would like to see
Silverbulletday in the race. But I know Mike Pegram will make the
right decision.''
</P>
<P>
   The Belmont Stakes presented a strange twist of fate for
Baffert. Twice in the last two years, he won the Kentucky Derby and
the Preakness but both times lost the Belmont in the final strides
and also the chance to sweep the Triple Crown. Now, he was watching
Lukas standing on the doorstep of the Triple Crown with
Charismatic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Silver Charm was beaten by Touch Gold, who was fresher and ran
a great race,'' Baffert recalled. ``Last year, Real Quiet lost with
an unlucky bob of the head. Charismatic is just a race horse. He
gets there and grinds it out.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
