<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-25 23:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1296 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LA-FOOTBALL-FRANCHISE     05-25 1016
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LA-FOOTBALL-FRANCHISE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NFL URGES COMPETITING GROUPS TO TEAM UP FOR L.A. FRANCHISE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Editors: With budgeted story BC-ELWAY-FOOTBALL-LADN) 
BY STEVE DILBECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -- In the belabored soap opera that has become the NFL
granting an expansion franchise to Los Angeles, league owners came
up with yet another twist Tuesday when they suggested the two
competing ownership groups get together at the eleventh hour.
</P>
<P>
   Again impressed by the glitz and scope of Michael Ovitz's new
Coliseum plan presented Monday, but apparently recognizing all the
site know-how belonged to the two-year effort of the Eli Broad-Ed
Roski Jr. group, NFL Commissioner Paul Tagliabue said at the owners
meetings that he had urged the two rivals to make happy and merge.
</P>
<P>
   Although the idea has been floated before -- and rejected by
Ovitz -- this was the first time the NFL had directly pushed for a
joint effort.
</P>
<P>
   Broad, who flew back to Los Angeles on Tuesday, said he had yet
to speak with Tagliabue or anyone else from the NFL about the
proposed merger.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ovitz brought a very nice model, which some of them liked very
much,'' Broad said. ``The problem is really very simple. They
realized during our presentation that it couldn't be built. Plus,
there's no way the state is going to fund their $225 million for
parking structures.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they thought, although we like the Ovitz plan, Roski
and Broad know all the rules of engagement. . . . Our door is open
if he wants to suggest some things. I have always said our main
priority is to get a first-rate stadium and an NFL team, and we'll
do whatever it takes to get there.''
</P>
<P>
   Few, however, have been able to visualize the two strong-willed
men coming together. Ovitz, the Hollywood super agent, is renowned
for wanting to be in control and has shown no interest in taking a
subordinate role in team ownership.
</P>
<P>
   And Broad made it clear that although he was still open to Ovitz
joining his group, it would be in a minority ownership role.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to remain the principal owner,'' Broad said. ``Mike has
a lot of talent. I have always had great respect for his abilities.
But I think my business and financial accomplishments are second to
none. He could have a very significant role, possibly in marketing
and promotions, something he is very good at.''
</P>
<P>
   The NFL requires that a team's principal owner have at least 30
percent of the team. Broad said he and Roski can provide 100
percent of the franchise cost, but are willing to take the 30
percent minimum each, leaving 40 percent of team ownership
available to others.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've already been talking to some people in the entertainment
industry and (former Broncos quarterback) John Elway about being
part owners,'' Broad said. ``If Ovitz wants to join us, there is 10
to 20 percent available to each.''
</P>
<P>
   Ovitz was flying back to Los Angeles on Tuesday night and could
not be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Tagliabue all but endorsed Ovitz's splashy plans for renovating
the Coliseum in a press conference at the Ritz-Carlton Hotel.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the plan offered by Michael Ovitz presents exactly the
kind of vision that we feel is necessary to transform the venue in
the best interest of the fans and the city of Los Angeles, which
would also be in the best interest of the National Football
League,'' Tagliabue said.
</P>
<P>
   But when the two competing groups presented an update of their
Coliseum plans to the expansion committee Monday night, Broad
stressed that his group had been working with the multiple agencies
involved in redesigning the Coliseum for more than two years and
was the only plan that could get built.
</P>
<P>
   Ovitz originally planned a new stadium in Carson, and had only
six weeks to formulate a new design for the Coliseum after it was
selected as the franchise site last month.
</P>
<P>
   Ovitz has yet to meet with any of the agencies that have control
over the Exposition Park area. And his optimum plan calls for seven
parking garages at an estimated $225 million that would require
state funding.
</P>
<P>
   But Tagliabue said the two groups had come together on the
general stadium size and the need for at least one parking garage
and said it was time they examined combining forces.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've talked to both groups coming together and unifying their
efforts,'' Tagliabue said. ``We think whether it's a merger,
whether it's a consolidation, whether it's working together in the
next phase, that's what has to be worked out.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the site development plans, everybody can work together and
come out with THE plan, then we think we'd be better off than going
on two different tracks, which involve two different plans.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have any specific thinking about what form their
working together would take on. What we're trying to do is move
ahead in a constructive way, rather than having a competition which
can be both time-consuming and counterproductive.''
</P>
<P>
   The day had not begun well for Broad. Both groups were invited
to make a shortened version of the plans they presented Monday
night to the expansion committee to all team owners Tuesday
morning.
</P>
<P>
   Ovitz was told to return Monday night, but the league did not
inform Broad of its plans until Tuesday morning, by which time he
was already flying home.
</P>
<P>
   John Semcken, the group's executive vice president, and John
McKay, its director of football operations, were forced to step in
for Broad.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Raiders owner Al Davis -- who moved his team from the
Coliseum to Oakland four years ago -- continued to bemoan the
league turning down his plans for a privately financed stadium at
Hollywood Park and to maintain a claim on the Los Angeles area.
</P>
<P>
   ``The L.A. opportunity does belong to us,'' Davis said. ``That
doesn't mean some other team can't move there, but they certainly
owe us the difference in the L.A. opportunity and the Oakland
opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can speculate on the amount. If you speculated $700
million, you wouldn't be wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
